[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and welcome to Keep it Simple: 1.e4 - 2.0!  This course provides a complete repertoire for the white pieces, based on the most popular and 'best by test' opening move 1.e4.  Before we discuss the contents, some words about me. My name is Christof Sielecki; I am an International Master and professional chess teacher and content creator. I started this profession in 2014 when my focus was teaching chess. I offered lessons to individual students and groups online and over the board.  This focus has changed, mostly due to the first edition of Keep It Simple: 1.e4, released in 2018, a groundbreaking course for Chessable and me. It was the first course to feature video, the first to be converted to a print book, and the reason why I am a full-time course creator now. The reception of the course was outstanding. Even after almost five years since the release, students play the suggested lines and use the course to build and improve their opening repertoire.  Since 2018, I have created a dozen courses for Chessable, including two more Keep It Simple @@StartBracket@@KIS@@EndBracket@@ courses. One about 1.d4 for White, one to handle the black pieces. Keep It Simple for Black was released on Christmas 2021 and thus a late entry for the Chessable Awards. It won 'Course of the Year' and 'Opening Course of the Year', which felt like a late Christmas present to me! 😀 The students loved the key changes I had made compared to earlier courses. The most common request I received was: 'Make a new version of KIS 1.e4, in the style of KIS for Black'. Well, here it is!  Let's talk about the concept of 'Keep It Simple' and this course.  The chosen lines are simple to learn and practical. I want to follow simple recipes, if possible. In some cases, I suggest more ambitious lines or moves that pose more problems for our opponent. Some of the lines are sharp and tactical. Simple does not mean 'boring'!  It must be possible to find your way even if you forgot your lines. The course provides guidelines and rules of thumb to understand the concepts better. This makes it easier to find your way, even if you have forgotten your move-by-move preparation.  All chosen opening lines are fully sound and playable for a wide range of players. All the lines are well-founded on sound principles and not 'refutable', even by very strong opponents that prepare for the game. I suggest mainstream openings that you can play on all levels: from your local town championships to online speed chess to classical time control games against titled opponents.  We have about the same amount of trainable lines as in KIS for Black, but even more explanations and guidance. I focus on lines that strike a balance between best play/master-level, and lines that regularly occur in amateur games. The course does include high-level theory but also keeps an eye on typical early mistakes or wrong concepts that amateur players employ.   Let's talk about the course contents. Each chapter includes up to a maximum of about twenty trainable lines. This makes learning a portion of the course easier in one go. Most of the videos are about one hour to 90 minutes, depending on the complexity of the chapter.  A further split sometimes makes no sense - some topics are best presented together. To better grasp a large number of chapters, the course is grouped into sections with an Introduction/Overview chapter. These chapters explain how the chapters tie together and why I chose the selected lines. Here is the list of the sections and a brief overview of the repertoire choices:   A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  Open Games - 10 chapters.  I suggest playing the Ruy Lopez @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , a major change from the first edition. The Ruy Lopez is a great opening that will lead to exciting games. It is a very versatile opening that teaches you a lot about Chess, in general. It's not a 'simple' opening, but I selected lines that make it accessible.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  Sicilian - 8 chapters.  We fight the Sicilian with a combination of Bb5 lines and a delayed version of the c3-Sicilian @@StartBracket@@Alapin@@EndBracket@@. The key lines are the Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , the Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  . This approach avoids the 'Open Sicilian', while still challenging Black. The first edition was based on the same concept, and there was no reason to change it. All the chapters are fully updated and improved, though. There are several changes and much more instruction and strategy pointers.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  French - 3 chapters.  I suggest fighting the French Defense with the Tarrasch @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  , a change from the first edition, which featured the Exchange Variation. The Tarrasch exerts more pressure while keeping our theoretical workload reasonable. The resulting positions also harmonize well with our choices against the Sicilian and Caro-Kann, as we frequently play against the Isolated Queen's Pawn.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  Caro-Kann - 2 chapters.  I suggest playing the Exchange Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  against the Caro-Kann, a new addition to the repertoire. I got interested in this line while writing my KIS for Black course, which featured the Caro-Kann from Black's perspective. I noticed that Black's job is not easy and felt the Exchange is an excellent weapon for White in the KIS context.  E. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  Scandinavian - 3 chapters.  The theory of the Scandinavian has not changed much in the last years. My basic recommendations have not changed, as the ways to an advantage for White are well-known. There are several improvements and simplifications compared to the first edition, though.  F. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  Defenses - 3 chapters.  This section features various lines based on ...d6 and ...g6, like the Pirc and Modern. I suggest playing an aggressive system based on an early f4.   G. 1.e4 Other Defenses - 2 chapters.  This section covers Black's rare lines, from Alekhine's Defense @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  . It's also important to note that it is possible only to employ single sections of the course. You can, for example, easily combine your favourite lines from the first edition with new ones presented here.   In addition to the chapters, four Quickstarter Guides include the most important lines and concepts you should know to start playing the repertoire. I suggest studying the Quickstarters first, then continuing with the dedicated chapters of your choice.  A popular approach is learning the Quickstarter and trying the repertoire in faster time control games. After the games, look up the theoretical details in the dedicated chapters. This way, you'll learn it step by step, focusing on the lines you get on the board.  Chessable offers a variety of study options, and each student is different: some prefer to watch videos, some learn best by reading, and some use the MoveTrainer. There are many options for studying the course - it's your call.   Enjoy the course and your games with 1.e4! }
