[White "Quickstarter Guide – Open Games 1.e4 e5"]
[Black "The Petroff (2...Nf6) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical reply.  It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.  In the Quickstarter Guide, I will focus on the most important lines and ideas to get you started with the opening. After studying the Quickstarter, you can test the suggestions in your games and deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@The Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines. Amongst the rare lines, the only serious option is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. These three moves account for about 95% of the games and are our focus in the Quickstarter. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting move of the Petroff or Russian Defense. I will stick to Petroff, as it is more commonly known in English, I think. }
3. Nxe5
{ I suggest taking the pawn and steering for the classical main line of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.d4  d5  6.Bd3  , which aims to play for a small pull from a position of complete safety. }
3... d6
{ The most normal move ever, but I need to mention the Stafford Gambit  3...Nc6?  . There are various ways to refute it - here's the one I suggest:  4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.Nc3  Bc5  6.h3  , which covers the g4-square. We'll develop with d3 and g3, later developing the bishops to e3 and g2. Black has no compensation for the pawn. }
4. Nf3
{ I also looked at  4.Nd3  , but if Black knows  4...Nxe4  5.Qe2  Qe7  6.Nf4  Nc6  7.Nd5  Nd4!  , we'd have absolutely nothing. Black has some alternatives to this forcing line, so it's not like we'd be winning otherwise.  The main move 4.Nf3 remains the critical test, so let's stick to it. }
4... Nxe4
{ After 4...Nxe4 White has a key choice. I am recommending the classical main line 5.d4 now, but I checked White's alternatives, too. In the full chapter, I provide an overview with my takes on them. }
5. d4
{ Very natural play. We want to develop our bishop to d3 next and castle kingside. }
5... d5
{ Black plays this logical move almost all the time. I found games with  5...Be7  6.Bd3  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  would transpose to the main line, still@@EndBracket@@, when White is better with playing natural moves. A good move to play early on is h3, stopping ...Bg4. You can do that immediately with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  to make it as simple as possible. Next, we'd castle, play Re1, c4, centralise, and enjoy a nice advantage in space.   Back to  5...d5  ,  when we reach a symmetrical pawn formation, typical of the Petroff. It's fascinating to see that while the pawns are symmetrical, Black is more actively placed on the surface. They have the centralised knight while our knight is still on f3.Our job is to prove that Black's knight is more of a liability than an asset. This is accomplished by exerting pressure on the knight and the supporting pawn d5. We'll discuss this topic more concretely after our next move. We need to develop our f1-bishop and castle for all these plans. }
6. Bd3
{ White's play in the whole 5.d4 line is all about fighting against Black's e4-knight. We want to increase the pressure on the knight and force some concessions. If Black, for example, would be forced to retreat the knight, we'd consider the opening phase successful.Other forms of concessions could be structural. If Black needs to play ...f5 and weaken the e5-square, we'd usually be happy too. This depends a bit more on the concrete position, though.So how do we put pressure on the knight? There are two basic methods:   Attacking the knight with moves like Re1 and Nbd2,Attacking the supporting pawn of the knight by playing our pawn to c4.What is best? That mostly depends on Black's piece configuration. Their setup will not only be defined by the next move but rather by the next two moves; we are going to castle next in all cases. Let's see the overview and have a brief assessment for them.   A.  6...Bd6  is the main line and most popular on all levels. Black develops the bishop to its most active square and focuses on kingside development first. After  7.O-O  Black castles, not yet committing a queenside piece. In this line, we'll play a quick c4 to attack Black's d-pawn.   B. Black can play a more conservative setup based on ...Be7. There are various versions of it, as Black can start with  6...Be7  , or play a move like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  first, and continue with  7.O-O Be7 to reach the same positions. I'll cover the various ...Be7 ideas via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  and point out our possible transpositions from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  .  This sounds a bit complicated at first, but you'll see that our approach against all ...Be7 versions is essentially the same, so it's not too difficult to master. Against these setups, challenging the knight with piece pressure @@StartBracket@@Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ is the most promising. We'll discuss in the notes to the lines why this approach is better than ideas based on pawn to c4, as in A. }
6... Be7
{ Black decides on a ...Be7-based setup. We'll talk more about Black's intentions after our natural reply when they have a choice. }
7. O-O
{ Let's discuss the strategy against the ...Be7-based setup. As discussed, there are two basic strategies against the e4-knight: Piece pressure with Re1 and Nbd2 or playing a pawn to c4 to attack the knight's support pawn on d5. What's best here?  White has tried both approaches, but the current state of theory is that going for piece pressure against the knight is the most promising. This assessment is based on concrete lines, but there is a certain logic as to why c4-based play is not as effective. With the bishop on e7, Black supports the d-pawn with the queen. If the bishop is on d6, the pawn moves to c4 and threatens to take the d-pawn.   We play this way after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  9.c4!  , when Black needs to protect the pawn immediately. Now compare to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  , when  9.c4  can be answered with  9...Nc6!  , as d5 is covered by the queen.  Alright, so we focus on piece pressure against the knight by playing moves like Re1 and Nbd2 - how does that translate to concrete lines? Black has various move orders, like  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bf5  , but I'll focus on @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  in the Quickstarter, as it is the most popular. Our general strategy is the same as against the others, too. They are covered in more detail in the full chapter. }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight first before castling or committing the c8-bishop. It's important to understand that the knight's position on c6 is double-edged for Black. It can be well-placed if Black has pressure on d4 @@StartBracket@@this applies mostly when White wants to play c4@@EndBracket@@, but it will often be in bad shape if White plays a pawn to c3. This will be a common pattern later.We need to play the correct move order now. Otherwise, Black can benefit from their early knight jump. }
8. Nbd2
{ It's important to get this move order right. After  8.Re1  Black may go for  8...Bg4  when their chances are considered to be OK. This is different from @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4?!  8.c4!  , when we hit Black's center much faster. It's crucial to remember to play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1bppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nbd2!  here.   I want to add that  8.c4  is answered by  8...Nb4  , demonstrating a key point of the knight move. It makes a lot more sense to preserve the option of c2-c3 when the knight is placed poorly on c6. The current state of theory is quite clear here - the alternatives to 8.Nbd2 don't promise much.   Now we'll check some options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1bppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nxd2  9.Bxd2  is the main move. Black acknowledges that they can't keep the knight on e4 under reasonable conditions. A small victory for White, leading to a nagging pull.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1bppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bf5  9.Re1  Nxd2  10.Qxd2  is a similar story. We keep annoying pressure, as Black has to trade their best piece.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1bppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nf6  9.c3  is a worse option than A or B. Retreating the knight is a large concession.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1bppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...f5?  is far too ambitious and immediately punished by  9.c4!  when the position opens while Black is still not well organised. }
8... Nxd2
{ Black's most popular move, but certainly a concession. They didn't manage to keep the knight on e4. }
9. Bxd2 Bg4
{ Going for this pin is a logical choice. They can play it here or after  9...O-O  10.c3  Bg4  , which leads to the same positions. }
10. c3 { We need to cover d4 first. } 10... O-O 11. h3
{ This move is the start of a cunning idea. We are annoyed by the pin, and this is the way to solve the issue. The real point comes on the next move. }
11... Bh5 12. g3
{ Very strong! We want to play Kg2 and Qc2 to leave the pin. It is crucial to remember this idea. It is by far the best to fight the pin and gives us a comfortable advantage. }
12... Qd7 13. Kg2
{ We are now ready for Qc2, leaving the pin and attacking the h7-pawn. Black now usually plays 13...Bg6 or after we attacked h7 first. Here are two possible lines:   A.  13...Bg6  14.Bf4  Bxd3  15.Qxd3  leads to a position that is quite similar to the line @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1bppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bf5  9.Re1  Nxd2  10.Qxd2  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  - White has a nagging edge.   B.  13...Rfe8  14.Qc2  Bg6  can be answered in two ways. We can take on g6 and claim that the doubled pawn is a weakness. After  15.Bxg6  hxg6  16.h4  the idea h4-h5 gains strength. It's also fine to let Black take on d3 when we reach a similar game as in A. White is pushing a risk-free advantage in both cases. }
