{ Very natural play. We want to develop our bishop to d3 next and castle kingside. }
5... d5
{ Black plays this logical move almost all the time. I found games with  5...Be7  6.Bd3  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  would transpose to the main line, still@@EndBracket@@, when White is better with playing natural moves. A good move to play early on is h3, stopping ...Bg4. You can do that immediately with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  to make it as simple as possible. Next, we'd castle, play Re1, c4, centralise, and enjoy a nice advantage in space.   Back to  5...d5  ,  when we reach a symmetrical pawn formation, typical of the Petroff. It's fascinating to see that while the pawns are symmetrical, Black is more actively placed on the surface. They have the centralised knight while our knight is still on f3.Our job is to prove that Black's knight is more of a liability than an asset. This is accomplished by exerting pressure on the knight and the supporting pawn d5. We'll discuss this topic more concretely after our next move. We need to develop our f1-bishop and castle for all these plans. }
6. Bd3
{ White's play in the whole 5.d4 line is all about fighting against Black's e4-knight. We want to increase the pressure on the knight and force some concessions. If Black, for example, would be forced to retreat the knight, we'd consider the opening phase successful.Other forms of concessions could be structural. If Black needs to play ...f5 and weaken the e5-square, we'd usually be happy too. This depends a bit more on the concrete position, though.So how do we put pressure on the knight? There are two basic methods:   Attacking the knight with moves like Re1 and Nbd2,Attacking the supporting pawn of the knight by playing our pawn to c4.What is best? That mostly depends on Black's piece configuration. Their setup will not only be defined by the next move but rather by the next two moves; we are going to castle next in all cases. Let's see the overview and have a brief assessment for them.   A.  6...Bd6  is the main line and most popular on all levels. Black develops the bishop to its most active square and focuses on kingside development first. After  7.O-O  Black castles, not yet committing a queenside piece. In this line, we'll play a quick c4 to attack Black's d-pawn.   B. Black can play a more conservative setup based on ...Be7. There are various versions of it, as Black can start with  6...Be7  , or play a move like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  first, and continue with  7.O-O Be7 to reach the same positions. I'll cover the various ...Be7 ideas via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  and point out our possible transpositions from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  .  This sounds a bit complicated at first, but you'll see that our approach against all ...Be7 versions is essentially the same, so it's not too difficult to master. Against these setups, challenging the knight with piece pressure @@StartBracket@@Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ is the most promising. We'll discuss in the notes to the lines why this approach is better than ideas based on pawn to c4, as in A. }
6... Bd6
{ Black develops their bishop to the most active square. A natural move and the most popular on all levels of play. }
7. O-O
{ Both sides castle first, then we discuss our strategy against the ...Bd6 system. }
7... O-O
{ Let's talk about how to play against Black's setup. We want to fight against the e4-knight and the d5-pawn - what's the best way to do it? We can exert piece pressure on the knight @@StartBracket@@Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ or attack the d-pawn with c4.It turns out that we must fight ...Be7 and ...Bd6 setups differently. Against ...Be7, going for piece pressure is best, while against ...Bd6, we need the c4-move to make progress. Let's illustrate this point by comparison.   A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  9.Nbd2  is one possible line for the ...Be7-systems. Black has no way to reinforce the knight further and needs to play  9...Nd6  ,  which gives us a small advantage.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  9.Nbd2  Re8!  is a big difference. The bishop does not block the e-file, which allows Black to keep the knight on e4. White has already put maximum pressure on e4 and there is no way to remove the intruder on e4. White's strategy has failed.   The consequence is simple: After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  , White needs to play  9.c4!  which is the main line of the dedicated chapter. }
8. Re1
{ I suggest starting with this move, but it is possible to play  8.c4  first. After  8...c6  9.Re1  we'll transpose to lines that are part of the suggested repertoire, as Black has nothing better than  9...Bf5  or  9...Re8  to transpose.   After  8.Re1  , we will consider  8...Bf5  and  8...Re8  , protecting the knight. Black has no good alternatives to these moves. Here are two less effective options.   A.  8...f5?  is awful for Black after  9.c4  c6  10.Nc3  Be6  11.Qb3  ,  when Black's weakened position is very shaky. The early ...f5 never works properly, creating too many weaknesses.   B.  8...Nf6?!  gives up on the idea of the Petroff and accepts playing a French exchange a tempo down. We also see this scenario sometimes in the ...Be7 lines, but not as much here, as Black's job of keeping the knight on e4 is a bit easier. It makes little sense to return when 8...Re8 or 8...Bf5 are obvious alternatives.In any case, I'd suggest meeting  8...Nf6  with  9.Bg5  ,  establishing an annoying pin. The general strategy is playing Nbd2, c3 and Qc2, preparing a later Ne5, if possible. }
8... Bf5
{ The bishop move is Black's most fashionable choice and employed by the Petroff gurus, Ian Nepomniachtchi being the most prominent.   The main alternative is  8...Re8  , when we play in the same way as against the bishop move:  9.c4  c6  10.Qb3  , putting pressure on the queenside and the d-pawn. }
9. c4
{ We get nowhere with  9.Nbd2?!  Re8  ,  when Black keeps the knight on e4, while we can't increase the pressure on it. The only way to go in the ...Bd6 lines is by playing the c-pawn. }
9... c6 10. Qb3
{ White's main line and the same idea we play in the 8...Re8 line. We increase the pressure on b7 and d5. Black has two good moves now, but only 10...Qd7 is a challenge and our main topic now. }
10... Qd7
{ Black's most popular and likely best move. It leads to the currently most topical line of the Petroff.White can try many moves now, which is a clear upside, as Black must be prepared for them all. It's not easy for Black, as they can't get by with 'general considerations; the lines are very concrete and tactical in most cases. I suggest a slower approach that Black probably won't have that high on their list of moves to prepare. }
11. Be3
{ A rare move, but it contains a fair amount of poison. As mentioned, White has plenty of more explored alternatives, like  11.Nc3  and @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/pp1q1ppp/2pb4/3p1b2/2PPn3/1Q1B1N2/PP3PPP/RNB1R1K1 w - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.c5  , all leading to interesting play. It might be very drawish for Nepo & Co, but this is less relevant for other levels of play.   I went for  11.Be3  , as even a well-versed theory buff might not know the move. It is not as forced as some other continuations and based on a simple concept: our pieces are more active. We often get a small edge with little risk. In the full chapter, I have continued the analysis from here. For the Quickstarter, I decided only to mention some key lines.  Let's consider Black's options.  A. @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/pp1q1ppp/2pb4/3p1b2/2PPn3/1Q1BBN2/PP3PPP/RN2R1K1 b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Na6  was Arjun Erigaisi's choice against Levon Aronian, the first high-level game that featured our move. I suggest  12.cxd5  cxd5  13.a3  , a prophylactic move that stops ...Nb4. Black is very close to equality, but I think White's job is easier and without risk.   B. @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/pp1q1ppp/2pb4/3p1b2/2PPn3/1Q1BBN2/PP3PPP/RN2R1K1 b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...dxc4  is a different concept. This move was tested in the game Maxime Vachier Lagrave - Bogdan-Daniel Deac, played in 2022. After  12.Bxc4  Na6  13.Ne5  looks better for White.  C. @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/pp1q1ppp/2pb4/3p1b2/2PPn3/1Q1BBN2/PP3PPP/RN2R1K1 b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Re8  also looks very natural to me and is worth a check.  12.Nc3  dxc4  13.Bxc4  Na6  14.Ne5  gives White an edge, though. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Open Games 1.e4 e5"]
[Black "Philidor Defense (2...d6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical reply.  It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.  In the Quickstarter Guide, I will focus on the most important lines and ideas to get you started with the opening. After studying the Quickstarter, you can test the suggestions in your games and deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@The Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines. Amongst the rare lines, the only serious option is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. These three moves account for about 95% of the games and are our focus in the Quickstarter. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The starting move of the Philidor Defense. Black covers their central pawn but restricts the f8-bishop.   After our natural reply  3.d4  , Black has a wide choice of moves, of which only  3...exd4  is somewhat respectable and the one we'll cover in the Quickstarter. }
3. d4
{ We immediately attack the e5-pawn again, trying to force the capture on d4. This approach is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  d6  4.d4  , where ...d6 is answered similarly.   It's instructive to compare these scenarios with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  , when  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  Bb4  highlights the difference: Black can develop their bishop actively. After the early ...d6, the bishop remains passive, and our immediate d4-push gets stronger.   After  3.d4  , Black's best move is  3...exd4  , but they have a long list of bad options to check. Here's an overview of them:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  is best for Black, as mentioned.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd7?!  4.Bc4!  is excellent for White.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg4?  4.dxe5  is known from the famous Morphy Opera game and is much better for White. We'll examine these with trainables. There are some more moves, but they don't warrant closer study.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5?  is a reckless move that can be refuted in many ways, the best being  4.Bc4  , but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp3pp/3p4/4pp2/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exf5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp3pp/3p4/4pp2/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  will lead to a large advantage, too.  E. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  is best answered by  4.Bb5  , transposing to the Ruy Lopez Steinitz, which is excellent for White. }
3... exd4
{ This is the only good move for Black if they continue with the following setup: ...Nf6/...Be7/...O-O. We'll see that White retains an advantage, but it's a game. }
4. Nxd4
{ The natural recapture.   We don't want to allow  4.Qxd4  Nc6  with a tempo gain on our queen. }
4... Nf6
{ The natural move, attacking the e-pawn. Other moves have no independent significance:   A.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  Bd7  leads to a favourable Ruy Lopez Steinitz.  6.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@intending Bf4, Qd2 and O-O-O@@EndBracket@@ is strong.   B.  4...g6  5.Nc3  will likely transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  , which gives us a dangerous attack. }
5. Nc3
{ We cover our pawn and wait for Black to decide on a defensive setup. We'll examine  5...Be7  , which seems best, and the more ambitious but dubious  5...g6  , an idea of the Great Dane, Bent Larsen.   A third rarely-played move is  5...Nc6  , when  6.Bb5  again transposes to a good line of the Ruy Lopez Steinitz. }
5... Be7
{ Black's best bet in the Philidor. The plan is castling quickly, then exerting pressure on e4 with ...Re8 and ...Bf8. If White is not careful, Black may manage the move ...d5, freeing the position completely.   The alternative  5...g6  is risky and dubious, as the simple plan Be3, Qd2, O-O-O, and a quick attack on the kingside is very effective. }
6. g3
{ It looks like White has two good options against 5...Be7 and they are fundamentally different.   A.  6.Bf4  , preparing Qd2 and O-O-O, is strong. There are, however, some crazy complications ahead that require detailed study. Some of those lines are nice for White, but one misstep may lead to problems. It's worth checking out if you like to analyze sharp complications, but I felt it is unwarranted for our repertoire approach.   B. The strategically minded move  6.g3  is just as promising but entirely different. White immediately tries to increase control over d5 - this is logical as Black's play is based on a quick ...d6-d5 in most cases. The quick ...d5 break solves Black's problems in many lines, for example, after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  O-O  7.Qd2  d5!  - our fianchetto serves as a prophylaxis against this concept.   After  6.g3  , we focus on  6...O-O  now, Black's best move. They can play @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  , but it is dubious after  7.e5  Ng4  8.Bg2  , as Black loses too much time with their knight. }
6... O-O
{ This solid line is best for Black, but natural moves give us a slight pull. }
7. Bg2
{ Now it's going to be very tough for Black to engineer ...d5. They are more or less limited to a sit-and-wait strategy. }
7... Re8 { Black completes their ...Re8/...Bf8 is regrouping first. } 8. O-O
Bf8 { Black's setup is compact and solid but rather passive. } 9. h3
{ Our setup controls d5 reliably, so this freeing advance is not available to Black without due preparation. 9.h3 is a fine move that controls g4 and prepares to expand on the kingside. }
9... c6 10. g4
{ This may be the start of an attack with g5 and f4 to come, but it is versatile. Giving the bishop on c1 a good post on g3 makes sense, too. This is the option I prefer if Black continues to wait. }
10... d5
{ Otherwise, Bf4/Qd2/Rad1 are easy moves to follow up with, putting more pressure on the center. }
11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Bf4
{ With a very comfortable edge. Black has a huge development disadvantage, and Nb5 is a threat. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Open Games 1.e4 e5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical reply.  It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.  In the Quickstarter Guide, I will focus on the most important lines and ideas to get you started with the opening. After studying the Quickstarter, you can test the suggestions in your games and deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@The Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines. Amongst the rare lines, the only serious option is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. These three moves account for about 95% of the games and are our focus in the Quickstarter. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ I recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. This might come as a surprise, as the Ruy Lopez does not have the reputation as a 'simple' opening. I agree that it is more complex than others, but it depends greatly on the choices afterwards.  Learning a repertoire based on the Ruy Lopez is worth the effort for numerous reasons:It leads to interesting and fighting positions. In most lines, there are no early trades and simplifications.It's versatile. Against some defenses, we can play more aggressively in the center @@StartBracket@@c3&d4@@EndBracket@@. In other cases, the position will be more closed, and we can drum up an attack on the kingside after shifting pieces to this side of the board. The Ruy is a great opening to learn a variety of middlegame structures.It's easy to modify later. Based on the framework you learn in this course, you can easily expand and change parts of it later. These points are key considerations for me.  'Keep it Simple' does not mean: 'Make it Boring'! Learning the Ruy Lopez is time well invested - you'll get interesting positions, challenge your opponent and teach yourself a lot about chess.   Let's get an overview of the Ruy Lopez. Black has many options against the Ruy. The best way to understand the various options is to view them on a conceptual basis.@@HeaderStart@@Black's Best Defensive Approach:@@HeaderEnd@@The best defenses for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  . In both cases, Black attacks our unprotected e-pawn. This approach looks very natural and logical. The knight is developed to its best square, and White has to worry about the e-pawn. In both cases, I recommend covering the e-pawn by play playing d3. The lines  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  are closely related and share multiple ideas.  In the first version, Black gains the additional option ...b5, which changes the position considerably. This leads us to the four most important branches of the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@A-D@@EndBracket@@:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  is a popular line for Black. They use their options to play ...b5 and then continue their kingside development most actively, playing the bishop on c5.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  is the more modest-looking version of A. Black opts for ...Be7, avoiding possible pins @@StartBracket@@Bg5 is a key idea in A@@EndBracket@@.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  . Black may react to 5.d3 differently. After we have reliably covered e4 with d3, the threat of Bxc6 and Nxe5 is serious. This leads to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  , which cover the pawn - the bishop move is based on  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5??  Qd4  , when Black wins.  D. In the Berlin Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  , Black's situation is similar to C. They have to do something about their e-pawn. Therefore,  4...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bc5  are the moves. We handle C and D in the same style. There are plenty of parallels and transpositions. These lines are less dependent on concrete move orders but more based on concepts and understanding. We save a lot of learning effort, as we have a framework of ideas that work against two important defenses by Black.  @@HeaderStart@@Black's Old-Fashioned Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  is called the Classical Defense. Black fails to put any pressure on e4, with allows us the aggressive reply  4.c3  , intending d4 next. It's important to understand that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  is a much better version of ...Bc5, as we have already played d2-d3. In the Classical, we manage d2-d4 with a tempo on Black's bishop. White can count on advantage in the Classical, based on this concept.   F. The Steinitz Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  and the Steinitz Deferred @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  . The early ...d6 does not put any pressure on our e4-pawn and blocks Black's f8-bishop. This allows us to open the position favourably with a quick d4. The Original Steinitz is a bad defense for Black, while the Deferred is a bit trickier to handle. We need the correct move orders to open the game favourably.  @@HeaderStart@@Risky/Odd Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@G. Black can play in Gambit style with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  . The second version is known to be bad for Black, while 3...f5 has the reputation of being risky but playable. I suggest a reply that is easy to handle and looks good for White.   H. Other Defenses. We have a chapter for the Odds end Ends, including defenses like the Bird @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  , Cozio @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  or Smyslov @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  .  The Bird is dubious, as it weakens the pawn structure and loses time. The Cozio and Smyslov don't put any pressure on our center and give us some leeway. I suggest a pragmatic solution based on a quick d2-d4, a similar concept as against the Steinitz.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on the replies you are most likely to encounter. Therefore, I decided to cover A-G above and skip the rarest lines. }
3... d6
{ The Steinitz Defense is one of the oldest Defenses to the Ruy Lopez - sometimes the name of an opening line already tells you a bit about its background in Chess history. It was played frequently by the first World Champions, like Steinitz, Lasker, Capablanca and Alekhine.  Over time, better defenses against the Ruy Lopez were developed, and the attention switched away from the Steinitz. It is now extinct on the master level but still frequently met in online/amateur games. It is, therefore, necessary to know how to exploit its defects. }
4. d4
{ Awarding this move an exclamation mark is a bit strong, but I want to draw attention to this move. There are two main reasons, except the simple fact that it is the best move:  1. It is the only occasion in our Ruy Lopez repertoire of an early d2-d4 that was not prepared by c2-c3. We usually play for the c3&d4 central occupation, but here we don't need the move c3 to prepare the central advance. After ...d6 is already played, we welcome the pawn structure after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  , as Black's f8-bishop, remains passive.  This can be compared to the Scotch Opening after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  , when  4...Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  Bb4  are the best defenses. Black's bishop is deployed actively, which is impossible in the Steinitz Variation.  2. It is important to understand the difference between the Steinitz Defense Deferred/Improved Steinitz Defense. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  , the move  5.d4?!  is NOT the best and has to be avoided because Black can play  5...b5  6.Bb3  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  , which is fine for Black. Here  8.Qxd4??  c5  9.Qd5  Be6  10.Qc6+  Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  is the famous 'Ark Noah' trap when White loses the bishop. White can avoid that fate by not taking on d4, but it's already too late to play for an advantage.   I suggest @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  , delaying the idea d2-d4, against the Steinitz Deferred - more on that in the dedicated chapter.  Let's return to the Steinitz. After 4.d4, Black's choice is limited, as we threaten both d4-d5 and dxe5. }
4... exd4
{ Black gives up the center.   They can try to hold the tension, but after  4...Bd7  5.Nc3  Nf6  , we have  6.Bxc6!  Bxc6  7.Qe2  , when  7....exd4  8.Nxd4  leads to the capture anyway. }
5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3
{ Developing the knight is the most flexible move. We want to preserve the option of queenside castling, most importantly. }
6... Nf6
{ Black's main move by a mile. This position is frequently reached by other move orders that started with 4...Bd7 or entirely different ones like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Bb5  exd4  6.Nxd4  Bd7  , which is a fun transposition. }
7. Bxc6
{ Capturing on c6 is a strong move, but not an obvious choice, in my mind. The reasoning is, as it often happens, very concrete: both recaptures lead to much better positions for White. }
7... bxc6
{ After  7...Bxc6  8.Qe2  , we prepare queenside castling @@StartBracket@@f3, Be3, O-O-O@@EndBracket@@ and are much better.  Taking this way @@StartBracket@@7...bxc6@@EndBracket@@ is more common and stronger than the bishop capture, but still very favourable for White. The next move is important, though. }
8. Qf3
{ An important move with two ideas: we support a possible knight jump to f5 and prepare the move e4-e5, eyeing the c6-pawn. This point is the reason why the natural move 8...Be7? fails. }
8... Be7
{ A natural-looking move and very common in online play. It leads to immediate disaster, though.   Better is  8...c5  , but  9.Nf5  Bxf5  10.exf5  is much better for White, too. We have much more space and can go for O-O-O and g4 ideas. }
9. e5 Nd5
{ A tougher defense than  9...dxe5  , when  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.Qxc6+  gives White an overwhelming advantage. Black has to move their king or play  11...Nd7  , when  12.Be3  and O-O-O will kill Black on the d-file. }
10. Nxc6
{ Much better than  10.Nxd5  cxd5  11.Qxd5  O-O  , when White is a pawn up, but Black manages to castle. }
10... Bxc6 11. Nxd5
{ We have won a pawn under better circumstances than 10.Nxd5, as Black can't castle due to  11...O-O  12.Nxe7+  , winning a piece. Currently, we are threatening Nf6+, too... which explains Black's next move. }
11... Qd7
{ Covering the bishop and avoiding  11...dxe5??  12.Nf6+  Bxf6  13.Qxc6+  Kf8  14.Be3  , with a deadly attack. }
12. Be3 { We are getting ready for queenside castling. } 12... dxe5 13. O-O-O
{ Black is in huge trouble. They can't castle and have to defend carefully. A good idea for White is to support the d5-knight to increase our queen's mobility. You can accomplish that by doubling on the d-file or playing the move c4, covering the knight with our pawn.  Black struggles in the Steinitz Defense, but knowing some ideas helps maximize the results. }
*

