[White "Quickstarter Guide – Open Games 1.e4 e5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical reply.  It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.  In the Quickstarter Guide, I will focus on the most important lines and ideas to get you started with the opening. After studying the Quickstarter, you can test the suggestions in your games and deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@The Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines. Amongst the rare lines, the only serious option is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. These three moves account for about 95% of the games and are our focus in the Quickstarter. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ I recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. This might come as a surprise, as the Ruy Lopez does not have the reputation as a 'simple' opening. I agree that it is more complex than others, but it depends greatly on the choices afterwards.  Learning a repertoire based on the Ruy Lopez is worth the effort for numerous reasons:It leads to interesting and fighting positions. In most lines, there are no early trades and simplifications.It's versatile. Against some defenses, we can play more aggressively in the center @@StartBracket@@c3&d4@@EndBracket@@. In other cases, the position will be more closed, and we can drum up an attack on the kingside after shifting pieces to this side of the board. The Ruy is a great opening to learn a variety of middlegame structures.It's easy to modify later. Based on the framework you learn in this course, you can easily expand and change parts of it later. These points are key considerations for me.  'Keep it Simple' does not mean: 'Make it Boring'! Learning the Ruy Lopez is time well invested - you'll get interesting positions, challenge your opponent and teach yourself a lot about chess.   Let's get an overview of the Ruy Lopez. Black has many options against the Ruy. The best way to understand the various options is to view them on a conceptual basis.@@HeaderStart@@Black's Best Defensive Approach:@@HeaderEnd@@The best defenses for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  . In both cases, Black attacks our unprotected e-pawn. This approach looks very natural and logical. The knight is developed to its best square, and White has to worry about the e-pawn. In both cases, I recommend covering the e-pawn by play playing d3. The lines  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  are closely related and share multiple ideas.  In the first version, Black gains the additional option ...b5, which changes the position considerably. This leads us to the four most important branches of the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@A-D@@EndBracket@@:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  is a popular line for Black. They use their options to play ...b5 and then continue their kingside development most actively, playing the bishop on c5.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  is the more modest-looking version of A. Black opts for ...Be7, avoiding possible pins @@StartBracket@@Bg5 is a key idea in A@@EndBracket@@.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  . Black may react to 5.d3 differently. After we have reliably covered e4 with d3, the threat of Bxc6 and Nxe5 is serious. This leads to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  , which cover the pawn - the bishop move is based on  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5??  Qd4  , when Black wins.  D. In the Berlin Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  , Black's situation is similar to C. They have to do something about their e-pawn. Therefore,  4...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bc5  are the moves. We handle C and D in the same style. There are plenty of parallels and transpositions. These lines are less dependent on concrete move orders but more based on concepts and understanding. We save a lot of learning effort, as we have a framework of ideas that work against two important defenses by Black.  @@HeaderStart@@Black's Old-Fashioned Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  is called the Classical Defense. Black fails to put any pressure on e4, with allows us the aggressive reply  4.c3  , intending d4 next. It's important to understand that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  is a much better version of ...Bc5, as we have already played d2-d3. In the Classical, we manage d2-d4 with a tempo on Black's bishop. White can count on advantage in the Classical, based on this concept.   F. The Steinitz Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  and the Steinitz Deferred @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  . The early ...d6 does not put any pressure on our e4-pawn and blocks Black's f8-bishop. This allows us to open the position favourably with a quick d4. The Original Steinitz is a bad defense for Black, while the Deferred is a bit trickier to handle. We need the correct move orders to open the game favourably.  @@HeaderStart@@Risky/Odd Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@G. Black can play in Gambit style with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  . The second version is known to be bad for Black, while 3...f5 has the reputation of being risky but playable. I suggest a reply that is easy to handle and looks good for White.   H. Other Defenses. We have a chapter for the Odds end Ends, including defenses like the Bird @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  , Cozio @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  or Smyslov @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  .  The Bird is dubious, as it weakens the pawn structure and loses time. The Cozio and Smyslov don't put any pressure on our center and give us some leeway. I suggest a pragmatic solution based on a quick d2-d4, a similar concept as against the Steinitz.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on the replies you are most likely to encounter. Therefore, I decided to cover A-G above and skip the rarest lines. }
3... Nf6
{ The starting move of the Berlin Defense. It is no coincidence that Black's most reliable defenses to the Ruy are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  - both lines feature an early attack on e4. We need to worry about our e-pawn immediately. This turns our ambition to build a full pawn center, with the perfect pawn duo e4 and d4, into a difficult task.   My choice against the Berlin is  4.d3  , covering the important e-pawn. Before we continue, here is a brief overview of the alternatives and how I assess them:  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  is the other serious option when  4...Nxe4  leads to a split.  5.d4  leads to the Berlin endgame. I am not a fan of playing this endgame. White has no theoretical advantage, and Black plays the Berlin to reach this endgame; it's their home ground.  I like @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4n3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  more, and it was a serious candidate that I considered. My main objection: the forced continuation  5...Nd6  6.Nxe5  Be7  7.Bf1  Nxe5  8.Rxe5  O-O  leads to a completely symmetrical pawn structure, which I try to avoid in the second edition of the repertoire.  I replaced the French Exchange from the first edition with the Tarrasch @@StartBracket@@3.Nd2@@EndBracket@@, for instance. You can't avoid it completely @@StartBracket@@Petroff@@EndBracket@@, but here we have a good alternative. It is strategically richer than playing for a nibble in a symmetrical structure. }
4. d3
{ We keep our important e-pawn. I want to add that I considered  4.Nc3  , as well - also via the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bb5  move order, of course. However, I think it is too simple for Black to equalise in the Spanish Four Knights. Both  4...Nd4  and  4...Bb4  are fine and don't require much effort for Black to master.   Let's discuss Black's options after  4.d3  -  their choice is rather limited, as our move involves a simple threat: capturing on c6 and winning the e-pawn next. For example, Black can't play  4...Be7?  as  5.Bxc6  dxc6  6.Nxe5  wins the e-pawn. It's not a flank pawn, but the most important pawn on the board!That leaves the following moves:   A.  4...Bc5  is by far the main move. Black develops the bishop and tactically covers the e-pawn. After  5.Bxc6  dxc6  6.Nxe5??  Qd4  White's greed is punished.   B.  4...d6  is the second most popular option. Our coverage of this line will be brief, as it is similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  ,  which we cover in detail. We'll often transpose to said line, as Black frequently inserts ...a6 at a later stage.   C.  4...Ne7  is a crazy-looking move that we need to examine. Black sets a cunning trap, as  5.Nxe5??  c6  6.Bc4  Qa5+  is a sad end of the knight! We should play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/5n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  , avoiding this disaster.  We'll now examine 4...Bc5, Black's most important reply. }
4... Bc5
{ Black goes for the most active defense and develops the bishop to a natural square. It's important to understand the difference to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  , when we can go for  4.c3  and want to play d2-d4 next. Black has already provoked the 'small' d-pawn move, taking a quick central expansion out of the equation.   What to play against  4...Bc5?  I started my investigation with the move  5.c3  , a typical move in the Ruy. White wants to still play for the full pawn center at a later stage. We employ this strategy in several lines, for instance, after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.c3  in the current chapter.   I would have liked to suggest @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  ,  as it would fit well to these lines from a conceptual point of view. There are concrete problems, though. I found that Black can get equal chances with more than one defense, and mastering the move orders looked difficult to me.In the end, I have discarded  5.c3  and suggest an option we rarely play in the Ruy: exchanging our bishop for the knight. I will discuss the ideas once the trade is on the board; hang on. }
5. Bxc6
{ Black has to take with the d-pawn now, enabling the defense of the e-pawn. After  5...dxc6  , we can't play  6.Nxe5??  due to  6...Qd4  , when Black wins.   If somehow Black decides to try  5...bxc6?  we can take the e-pawn unpunished. }
5... dxc6
{ Let's discuss this position. Why did we capture the knight and give up our bishop pair? Let's make a list of key points to consider.   The bishop pair is an asset for Black, but the pawn structure is not ideally suited for bishops. They would like open, long diagonals, and Black has difficulty creating them here.  We need to consider the pawn structure. The doubled pawn is a key factor. It is not a weakness we could attack, but it is still a strategic handicap for Black. The problem is that the doubled pawn reduces Black's options for pawn breaks. Currently, there are no open files. To a large extent, closed positions are about both sides trying to open them under favourable circumstances. Due to the doubled pawn, Black's options to change the pawn structure have been reduced. Black can't gain much by advancing pawns on the queenside. The pawn push ...c6-c5-c4 is tough to realise.Black could try to open the position by playing ...f5, attacking our central pawn. This option is also difficult to engineer. Black has no d-pawn, which means that ...f5 would lead the e-pawn unprotected.Let's compare these points with our position. We are much better equipped to alter the pawn structure. We have two basic ideas to change the pawn structure: breaking in the center with d4 and attacking e5 with f4. Our attempts to play f4 are more promising than Black's ...f5 possibilities because we still have a d-pawn to protect e4. It is easier to prepare and involves less risk.  It is important to consider castling options. It's very relevant, as the closed center makes it easier to start flank operations. If Black castles to the kingside, we might launch an attack based on g2-g4, for instance.  What about piece placement? We have discussed pawns; how do the pieces relate to the structure? Black's pieces are not ideally placed at the moment. The knight mostly looks at a well-protected pawn, while the bishop is developed but not doing much, either. Quite often, Black quickly starts a knight tour to improve this piece. Moving the knight has an additional benefit: the option of ...f6, which would reliably cover e5.   Black's sub-optimal piece placement is an important factor. It is the crucial difference to the Ruy Exchange Variation. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  ,  the same pawn structure arises, but Black would never voluntarily play their pieces to f6 or c5. It is much more common for Black to go for an early ...f6 and delay the development of the knight. }
6. Nbd2
{ White has two major options here. My recommendation and  6.O-O  , which I dislike for a simple reason. Black can play  6...Bg4  and pin our knight. It looks like the only way to answer this move is  7.h3  Bh5  8.g4  , when Black can play  8...Nxg4!  9.hxg4  Bxg4  and destroy our pawn cover. This line looks theoretically sound for Black, and there is no way I would want to play this position unless it is REALLY good for me and I see a way to secure my king.   Well, we have a good alternative to castling. By playing  6.Nbd2  ,  we defuse ...Bg4, as our king is not yet committed to the kingside. Once you scratch  6.O-O  off your list,  6.Nbd2  quickly emerges as the main alternative to examine. The knight has no bright future on c3, so developing it to d2 makes much more sense. We often place it on c4 to increase the pressure on e5 or transfer it to the kingside via f1. In some cases, playing Nb3 is motivated by concrete lines, gaining a tempo on the c5-bishop.Black has a fundamental choice now that heavily influences the course of the game. We currently still don't threaten e5, so Black has some flexibility. The main choice is about castling.Black can go for kingside castling:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  commits the king right away.   B.  6...Nd7  7.Nc4  O-O  is a different path to kingside castling.Black can prepare queenside castling:   C.  6...Be6  is probably the best move to get closer to O-O-O.   D.  6...Bg4  looks like a less reliable option with the same intention.  Black's most popular plan is based on kingside casting. We'll check this concept in the Quickstarter. }
6... O-O
{ Black commits to kingside castling. This concept is the most popular, but White's job is easier than against other concepts. We know the address of Black's king, which helps. We want to play on the kingside against Black's king; a key question is where to castle. I think kingside castling is a safer and better option. Let's see how it continues. }
7. Nc4
{ A good move to start with. We attack e5 a second time and activate the knight.   I already mentioned that we want to castle kingside. Playing  7.O-O  first is not a mistake and will likely transpose. I prefer  7.Nc4  , because we start with this move in various other lines @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qe7  7.Nc4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd7  7.Nc4  @@EndBracket@@.Black has to cover the e-pawn now. The most popular move is  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/2N1P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nd7  .  It looks odd to see Black blocking their c8-bishop, but the knight is not well-placed on f6, and the c8-bishop has no great development perspective.An alternative for Black is  7...Re8  - it will often transpose to 7...Nd7, if Black plays the knight soon. }
7... Nd7
{ The most logical move, in my mind. The e-pawn needs protection, and the knight wants to improve its position. }
8. O-O
{ After castling, we attack the e5-pawn 'for real'. Black has to cover it. Most of the time, Black plays  8...Re8  now, but 8...f6 also makes some sense. Black often wants to play both moves because they want to cover e5 reliably with a pawn to make the knight mobile again. It can't stay on d7 forever and often wants to improve via f8 to e6 when it is connected to the squares d4 and f4.   We'll examine  8...Re8  9.Kh1  f6  , which follows this concept. }
8... Re8
{ Black covers the e-pawn and clears f8 for a piece. We'll see that they can use it for a knight or a bishop.After 8...Re8 White has a wide choice. We have a closed position that requires good manoeuvring. In the general discussion about the pawn structure, I mentioned that it is easier for us to make progress. I think it's a good plan for White to start some action on the kingside. The center is closed, and Black has no quick counterplay on the queenside, so playing on the flanks is possible without undue risks. The next move serves to prepare our play. }
9. Kh1
{ I suggest starting with the king move, but White has many options here. You can also play a move like  9.a4  first or  9.Bd2  - it's not so much about concrete lines in such a slow position. White often plays one of the other moves, then still resorts to the kingside play that Kh1 is needed for.What does the king move accomplish?   - We allow the f-pawn to move. This is relevant for plans like Nh4 @@StartBracket@@in case of ...f6@@EndBracket@@ or Ng1 when we are ready to advance our f-pawn.   - The second idea is playing the move g4, often connected to Rg1 and Ne3-f5 ideas. We want to transfer more pieces to the kingside and start an attack.Black's position is solid, though. It will not be a simple attacking win by any means. But we can be sure about some action later in the game, as it remains complicated. The position's closed nature ensures that most pieces stay on the board.I will examine some moves now to show relevant ideas in this position. As mentioned before: it's less about concrete moves but using manoeuvres that you know and employ, adjusted to the specific position on the board.  I'll check the move 9...f6 now, which is a logical idea for Black. }
9... f6
{ Black will often play this move to allow the knight to move. A good target square is e6, looking at the important squares d4 and f4. The drawback of ...f6 is allowing the following manoeuvre. }
10. Nh4 { Black has given up control of h4, so this move is possible. } 10...
Nf8
{ Black improves the knight, as planned. We have some options now. It's premature to play  11.Nf5?  because  11...Bxf5  12.exf5  e4  is great for Black. They open the position favourably because we have no control over the e4-square. Our main choice is between  @@StartFEN@@r1bqrnk1/ppp3pp/2p2p2/2b1p3/2N1P2N/3P4/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1R1K w - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Ne3  and  11.Be3  , I think. }
11. Be3
{ A tough choice, as both moves look interesting. After  11.Ne3  g6  12.g3  ,  we can play for f2-f4 next.   The move  11.Be3  feels a bit better to me because it looks like two pieces are competing for squares, and trading one of them could help. The engine is no help; it always evaluates these positions between 0.00 and a marginal advantage for White. }
11... Bd6
{ This move was played in a 2022 GM game at the Chennai Olympiad. Probably Black should play  11...Bxe3  12.Nxe3  ,  when I would still prefer White a bit. Our idea of playing g3&f4 remains a factor. The same plan was realised under worse circumstances for Black in the game. }
12. g3
{ According to plan. Black's move was a mistake, but it was not easy to play... }
12... Bh3
{ That's a serious mistake. The comp points out  12...Ng6  13.Nf5  a5  is a better defense, with about equal chances. Well, it might be equal for the engine, but it's not boring for human players. }
13. Rg1
{ Black has provoked a move we don't mind playing anyway. They also need to worry about g3-g4 now, trapping the bishop! }
13... Be6 14. Nxd6
{ The simplest move. We want to play f4 next, and don't worry about a potential capture of the knight. }
14... cxd6 15. f4
{ White was much better in the mentioned GM game. White has realised the desired play on the kingside and can be happy about the opening result.In general, the positions after both sides have castled kingside look about equal, but offer chances for conflict by trying to open the kingside. This usually leads to complications later in the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Open Games 1.e4 e5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical reply.  It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.  In the Quickstarter Guide, I will focus on the most important lines and ideas to get you started with the opening. After studying the Quickstarter, you can test the suggestions in your games and deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@The Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines. Amongst the rare lines, the only serious option is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. These three moves account for about 95% of the games and are our focus in the Quickstarter. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ I recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. This might come as a surprise, as the Ruy Lopez does not have the reputation as a 'simple' opening. I agree that it is more complex than others, but it depends greatly on the choices afterwards.  Learning a repertoire based on the Ruy Lopez is worth the effort for numerous reasons:It leads to interesting and fighting positions. In most lines, there are no early trades and simplifications.It's versatile. Against some defenses, we can play more aggressively in the center @@StartBracket@@c3&d4@@EndBracket@@. In other cases, the position will be more closed, and we can drum up an attack on the kingside after shifting pieces to this side of the board. The Ruy is a great opening to learn a variety of middlegame structures.It's easy to modify later. Based on the framework you learn in this course, you can easily expand and change parts of it later. These points are key considerations for me.  'Keep it Simple' does not mean: 'Make it Boring'! Learning the Ruy Lopez is time well invested - you'll get interesting positions, challenge your opponent and teach yourself a lot about chess.   Let's get an overview of the Ruy Lopez. Black has many options against the Ruy. The best way to understand the various options is to view them on a conceptual basis.@@HeaderStart@@Black's Best Defensive Approach:@@HeaderEnd@@The best defenses for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  . In both cases, Black attacks our unprotected e-pawn. This approach looks very natural and logical. The knight is developed to its best square, and White has to worry about the e-pawn. In both cases, I recommend covering the e-pawn by play playing d3. The lines  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  are closely related and share multiple ideas.  In the first version, Black gains the additional option ...b5, which changes the position considerably. This leads us to the four most important branches of the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@A-D@@EndBracket@@:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  is a popular line for Black. They use their options to play ...b5 and then continue their kingside development most actively, playing the bishop on c5.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  is the more modest-looking version of A. Black opts for ...Be7, avoiding possible pins @@StartBracket@@Bg5 is a key idea in A@@EndBracket@@.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  . Black may react to 5.d3 differently. After we have reliably covered e4 with d3, the threat of Bxc6 and Nxe5 is serious. This leads to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  , which cover the pawn - the bishop move is based on  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5??  Qd4  , when Black wins.  D. In the Berlin Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  , Black's situation is similar to C. They have to do something about their e-pawn. Therefore,  4...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bc5  are the moves. We handle C and D in the same style. There are plenty of parallels and transpositions. These lines are less dependent on concrete move orders but more based on concepts and understanding. We save a lot of learning effort, as we have a framework of ideas that work against two important defenses by Black.  @@HeaderStart@@Black's Old-Fashioned Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  is called the Classical Defense. Black fails to put any pressure on e4, with allows us the aggressive reply  4.c3  , intending d4 next. It's important to understand that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  is a much better version of ...Bc5, as we have already played d2-d3. In the Classical, we manage d2-d4 with a tempo on Black's bishop. White can count on advantage in the Classical, based on this concept.   F. The Steinitz Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  and the Steinitz Deferred @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  . The early ...d6 does not put any pressure on our e4-pawn and blocks Black's f8-bishop. This allows us to open the position favourably with a quick d4. The Original Steinitz is a bad defense for Black, while the Deferred is a bit trickier to handle. We need the correct move orders to open the game favourably.  @@HeaderStart@@Risky/Odd Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@G. Black can play in Gambit style with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  . The second version is known to be bad for Black, while 3...f5 has the reputation of being risky but playable. I suggest a reply that is easy to handle and looks good for White.   H. Other Defenses. We have a chapter for the Odds end Ends, including defenses like the Bird @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  , Cozio @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  or Smyslov @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  .  The Bird is dubious, as it weakens the pawn structure and loses time. The Cozio and Smyslov don't put any pressure on our center and give us some leeway. I suggest a pragmatic solution based on a quick d2-d4, a similar concept as against the Steinitz.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on the replies you are most likely to encounter. Therefore, I decided to cover A-G above and skip the rarest lines. }
3... Bc5
{ Black goes for the Classical Defense. As the intro to this chapter mentioned, ...Bc5 in the Ruy Lopez is a common sight. Black has many ways to employ the move, and 3...Bc5 is the earliest one.  Nowadays, the Classical is regarded as slightly imprecise, as White manages to expand in the center with c3&d4 quickly, our standard idea in the Ruy Lopez. }
4. c3
{ White has a basic choice between  4.c3  and  4.O-O  here.   The main difference between the two is  4.O-O  Nd4!  5.Nxd4  Bxd4  , which helps Black a bit. White still has chances for a small advantage, but @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c3  prevents the idea.   Playing c3 first is in sync with other choices in this chapter. Now we need to check some options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4....Nf6  is by far the most popular and logical move. A key line is  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  when we attack Black's knight.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4....Nge7  is an alternative way for Black to develop the kingside. It avoids the line mentioned in A but puts less pressure on our center. After  5.d4  exd4  6.cxd4  Bb4+  7.Bd2  , we keep a small advantage, as examined in the full chapter.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5?!  is a rarely played gambit and not 100% sound. After  5.d4  , we are much better.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6?  is even worse than it looks and loses on the spot after  5.d4  exd4  6.cxd4  Bb4+  7.Kf1!  , when the combined threats of d4-d5 and Qa4 win material!   E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6?  is played a lot in online games, but just a blunder, as we will see. We can take on c6 and e5 in this particular case.  Other moves shouldn't worry us, as we are ready to play d4 and castle. }
4... Nf6 { The most natural and popular move. } 5. d4
{ No surprises here - we played c3 for a reason. } 5... exd4
{ Black captures and hopes for  6.cxd4  Bb4+!  , but we have a much better option. }
6. e5
{ We don't want to play  6.cxd4?  Bb4  , which is fine for Black. Attacking the knight with e4-e5 is much better for us and leads us to an instructive point.   Have you wondered why @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  is considered super sound for Black, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Bc5  is a slightly dodgy defense? One reason becomes apparent here.  In the Italian, there is the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  , when  6...d5!  7.Bb5  Ne4  8.cxd4  Bb6  is the best defense for Black. Note that Black hits White's bishop. It has to move to b5 using two tempi. In the Ruy, we already have the bishop on b5! Black does not have the ...d5! reply with a tempo and has to move their knight now.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ne4  likely leads to the Italian line mentioned above with a full extra tempo, giving us a nice pull.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd5  is the alternative for Black, but tough to handle after  7.O-O  , when we have the threat of cxd4 with tempo, followed by Bc4 or Qb3 to attack the unstable knight. }
6... Ne4
{ Jumping to e4 is Black's best defense. We still have better chances if we play well. }
7. O-O
{ This is better than  7.cxd4  Bb4+  , when Black manages to trade some material. We want to take it under better conditions.   Note that @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd5  is also answered by  7.O-O  , which makes it easier to remember. }
7... d5
{ Black's best defense here.   It's mandatory to put a pawn in the center and stop us from a further advance. A line to show the problem is  7...O-O?  , when  8.cxd4  Bb6  9.d5  gives us a central steamroller that Black should not survive.   Another dubious move is  7...dxc3?  , when  8.Qd5  is a strong reply, attacking both minor pieces. }
8. cxd4
{ I think this is the most promising move, but White has some good lines available, like  8.exd6  and  8.b4  , which is a yet untested engine suggestion. It's always nice to have options, but let's see how my choice unfolds. }
8... Bb6
{ The bishop is best placed on b6, keeping some pressure on our center. } 9. h3
{ I'd like to stop a possible pin first. Let's discuss the strategy of this position after the next pair of moves. }
9... O-O 10. Nc3
{ This position is not easy for Black to play. We have some fairly simple ideas that can prove very effective:  Put pressure on the e4-knight and try to provoke a capture on c3. This would be huge for us, as we managed to trade Black's best piece and support our d4-pawn. We have a space advantage on the kingside anyway, based on the e5-pawn.The capture on c6 can be an idea if we prevent Black's b6-bishop from becoming active.Black often attacks our pawn chain with ...f6. In this case, we often get control of the e5-square, ideal for a knight.  Let's explore some lines to illustrate these concepts. }
10... Bf5
{ Black develops their last minor piece, a logical move. There are some worse alternatives:   A.  10...Nxc3?  11.bxc3  gives us a dream position. Our Ruy bishop will find a fantastic spot on d3, looking at the kingside. Black's queenside pieces are just spectators, not defenders.   B.  10...f6  11.exf6  Rxf6  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.Be3  Qe8  14.Ne5  is nice for White, too. Our e5-knight is a monster, but Black has some active pieces on the kingside. }
11. Be3 { We support our d-pawn first, completing our development. } 11... Ne7
{ Black wants to stop worrying about Bxc6 and removes the knight. } 12. Bd3
{ We increase the pressure on e4. Our bishop had no job on b5 after Black's last move. I want to stop the trainable line now and close with some more ideas and sample lines.   A.  12...Qd7  is nicely met with  13.Nh4  , when Blach has problems with their knight support, and the same applies to @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp1nppp/1b6/3pPb2/3Pn3/2NBBN1P/PP3PP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 6 12@@EndFEN@@  12...c6  13.Nh4  .   B.  12...Rc8  13.Qb1!  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/ppp1nppp/1b6/3pPb2/3Pn3/2NBBN1P/PP3PP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 7 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qc2  c5!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/ppp1nppp/1b6/3pPb2/3Pn3/2NBBN1P/PP3PP1/RQ3RK1 b - - 8 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nxc3  14.bxc3  Bxd3  15.Qxd3  h6  16.Rfb1  , planning a4-a5, is excellent for White.   C.  12...f6  13.Qc2  fxe5  14.Nxe5  Nd6  15.Bg5  Bxd3  16.Qxd3  gives White some pressure. The move ...f6 is understandable from Black's perspective, but it creates weaknesses, and our pieces are actively placed. Black's bishop on b6 is missing as a kingside defender, too. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Open Games 1.e4 e5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical reply.  It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.  In the Quickstarter Guide, I will focus on the most important lines and ideas to get you started with the opening. After studying the Quickstarter, you can test the suggestions in your games and deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@The Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines. Amongst the rare lines, the only serious option is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. These three moves account for about 95% of the games and are our focus in the Quickstarter. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ I recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. This might come as a surprise, as the Ruy Lopez does not have the reputation as a 'simple' opening. I agree that it is more complex than others, but it depends greatly on the choices afterwards.  Learning a repertoire based on the Ruy Lopez is worth the effort for numerous reasons:It leads to interesting and fighting positions. In most lines, there are no early trades and simplifications.It's versatile. Against some defenses, we can play more aggressively in the center @@StartBracket@@c3&d4@@EndBracket@@. In other cases, the position will be more closed, and we can drum up an attack on the kingside after shifting pieces to this side of the board. The Ruy is a great opening to learn a variety of middlegame structures.It's easy to modify later. Based on the framework you learn in this course, you can easily expand and change parts of it later. These points are key considerations for me.  'Keep it Simple' does not mean: 'Make it Boring'! Learning the Ruy Lopez is time well invested - you'll get interesting positions, challenge your opponent and teach yourself a lot about chess.   Let's get an overview of the Ruy Lopez. Black has many options against the Ruy. The best way to understand the various options is to view them on a conceptual basis.@@HeaderStart@@Black's Best Defensive Approach:@@HeaderEnd@@The best defenses for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  . In both cases, Black attacks our unprotected e-pawn. This approach looks very natural and logical. The knight is developed to its best square, and White has to worry about the e-pawn. In both cases, I recommend covering the e-pawn by play playing d3. The lines  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  are closely related and share multiple ideas.  In the first version, Black gains the additional option ...b5, which changes the position considerably. This leads us to the four most important branches of the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@A-D@@EndBracket@@:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  is a popular line for Black. They use their options to play ...b5 and then continue their kingside development most actively, playing the bishop on c5.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  is the more modest-looking version of A. Black opts for ...Be7, avoiding possible pins @@StartBracket@@Bg5 is a key idea in A@@EndBracket@@.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  . Black may react to 5.d3 differently. After we have reliably covered e4 with d3, the threat of Bxc6 and Nxe5 is serious. This leads to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  , which cover the pawn - the bishop move is based on  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5??  Qd4  , when Black wins.  D. In the Berlin Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  , Black's situation is similar to C. They have to do something about their e-pawn. Therefore,  4...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bc5  are the moves. We handle C and D in the same style. There are plenty of parallels and transpositions. These lines are less dependent on concrete move orders but more based on concepts and understanding. We save a lot of learning effort, as we have a framework of ideas that work against two important defenses by Black.  @@HeaderStart@@Black's Old-Fashioned Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  is called the Classical Defense. Black fails to put any pressure on e4, with allows us the aggressive reply  4.c3  , intending d4 next. It's important to understand that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  is a much better version of ...Bc5, as we have already played d2-d3. In the Classical, we manage d2-d4 with a tempo on Black's bishop. White can count on advantage in the Classical, based on this concept.   F. The Steinitz Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  and the Steinitz Deferred @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  . The early ...d6 does not put any pressure on our e4-pawn and blocks Black's f8-bishop. This allows us to open the position favourably with a quick d4. The Original Steinitz is a bad defense for Black, while the Deferred is a bit trickier to handle. We need the correct move orders to open the game favourably.  @@HeaderStart@@Risky/Odd Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@G. Black can play in Gambit style with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  . The second version is known to be bad for Black, while 3...f5 has the reputation of being risky but playable. I suggest a reply that is easy to handle and looks good for White.   H. Other Defenses. We have a chapter for the Odds end Ends, including defenses like the Bird @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  , Cozio @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  or Smyslov @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  .  The Bird is dubious, as it weakens the pawn structure and loses time. The Cozio and Smyslov don't put any pressure on our center and give us some leeway. I suggest a pragmatic solution based on a quick d2-d4, a similar concept as against the Steinitz.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on the replies you are most likely to encounter. Therefore, I decided to cover A-G above and skip the rarest lines. }
3... f5
{ This is Black's most aggressive move against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit. It looks a bit outrageous that this move should be possible, and indeed we'll see that it is a risky choice for Black - if White knows what they are doing!  We need to study a good reply to 3...f5, as common sense play is not enough. Ultimately, it is not that much effort to gain an advantage, but it would be tough to figure out without any preparation. Let's get to work. }
4. d3
{ We simply cover our e-pawn, which I consider to be the best choice. Let's check some alternatives to understand Black's opening points.   A.  4.exf5?  e4!  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp2pp/2n5/1B2pp2/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.exf5  e4  should be avoided.   B.  4.d4?  looks logical, but Black has  4...fxe4  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  c6!  7.Bc4  Qa5+  , when the e-pawn drops. This is the key difference to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  , when  5.d4!  is the best move. With the bishop a4, the move ...c6 does not hit White's bishop.  Another fun comparison is the Vienna Game @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.f4  d5!  , when Black is fine - having the bishop at home is better than b5 in this concrete line.   C.  4.Nc3  is the only good alternative to our choice, but requires more memorization work and is not objectively better. }
4... fxe4
{ Very natural and almost exclusively played.   After a sloppy move like  4...Nf6?!  we are ready to play  5.exf5  , as ...e4 is no reply anymore. }
5. dxe4 Nf6
{ Black develops and attacks our e-pawn. We reach the first crucial point. } 6.
O-O
{ This is White's best move and important to remember. We don't need to cover our e-pawn and can play O-O first, a move that we'll need anyway.   A common mistake is  6.Nc3?  Bb4!  , which is surprisingly comfortable for Black.   After our move, Black has a fundamental choice. They can play the most ambitious move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc5  , a pawn sacrifice, or cover their e-pawn with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  , which keeps material equality.  Black has no good alternatives to these moves. We are threatening Bxc6, followed by Nxe5, to win a pawn.  The greedy @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nxe4?  is far too risky due to  7.Qe2  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n5/1B2p3/4n3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  , eyeing Black's king on e8. }
6... Bc5
{ Certainly the move Black wants to play. They develop the bishop to its most active square and want to castle next. There is an obvious drawback, though: it loses a pawn.   Black can keep the pawn with  6...d6  , but at the price of having a passive bishop. It's good to know that  7.Bc4!  is best for White, stopping kingside castling. We examine this line more in the dedicated chapter. }
7. Bxc6
{ White has tried some other ideas here, but I like to grab the pawn. I am generally reluctant to accept gambits, but here we take a central pawn, which is far more important than a pawn on the edge of the board. }
7... bxc6 8. Nxe5 O-O
{ Black needs to get castled, there is no alternative.   A.  8...Nxe4??  9.Qh5+  is easy.   B.  8...Qe7?  9.Nd3  Nxe4  leads to a disaster on the e-file after  10.Nd2  Nxd2  11.Re1!  Ne4  12.Nxc5  , and it's over. }
9. Nc3
{ We cover the e-pawn and ask Black to prove compensation. Black has the bishop pair and open files, but the current theoretical evaluation is favourable for White.  In the current position, Black has tried many moves, particularly if you check games played online or below master level. However, many of these moves can be dismissed rather quickly, as they don't address an idea we have prepared with our last move. The idea is to play Nd3 @@StartBracket@@tempo on the bishop@@EndBracket@@, followed by e4-e5, attacking Black's knight. This simple idea refutes some of Black's attempts convincingly. }
9... d6
{ Attacking our knight is Black's main move.   Now we have to avoid being too greedy by playing  10.Nxc6?!  Qe8  11.Nd4  Nxe4  12.Nxe4  Qxe4  , when the wide open position gives Black's bishop pair the right stage to shine on.  Instead, we have a much stronger but less intuitive move. }
10. Na4
{ A tough move to remember, but it is White's best claim for an advantage.   The other move you can play here is  10.Nd3  , which has been tested in some games. After  10...Bd4  11.Ne2  Bb6  12.Bg5  Qe8  13.Bxf6  Rxf6  14.Ng3  White remains a pawn up, but Black has two bishops against our two knights. The computer likes White in this position, but I am not sure how easy it is to play. I have a lot of respect for the bishop when it competes with two knights, so my judgement may be off here. Maybe you like White here more than I do - then this line is a good alternative to my suggestion.   The point of  10.Na4  is to trade off Black's best piece, the c5-bishop. Black has tried various moves, but they don't solve their problems. I will examine  10...Nxe4  and  10...Qe8  in more detail now and want to mention two worse and rather easy-to-handle alternatives.   A.  10...Bxf2+  leads to a forced simplification.  11.Rxf2  dxe5  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.Bg5  Rd4  14.Bxf6  Rxa4  15.Bxe5  Rxe4  16.Bxc7  is a much better endgame for White. Black has drawing chances, but it's no fun to play. We should be careful with rook trades here, as it would help Black a lot.   B.  10...Bb6  11.Nxb6  axb6  12.Nxc6  Qe8  13.Nd4  Qxe4  14.f3  Qg6  15.a4  keeps the extra pawn, and Black has no compensation.   C.  10...Qe8  is possible when  11.Nd3  Bg4  12.Qe1  Bd4  13.c3  Bb6  14.Nxb6  axb6  .  15.f3  is a similar story. }
10... Nxe4 { Black grabs the e-pawn, which prompts the following sequence. }
11. Nxc5 Nxc5 12. Nxc6 Qe8
{ Black is looking for a play on the light squares, so this feels like the best try.   12...Qf6  13.Qd5+  Be6  14.Qg5  Qf7  15.Be3  is a different line that also leads to a position with an extra pawn and insufficient compensation for Black. }
13. Nd4 Bb7 14. f3
{ This move is a key point to remember about this position or similar positions. Our extra pawn is the f-pawn. The advantage of having this pawn is twofold. It has a material value but, more importantly, a strategic one. By placing it on f3, we also blunt Black's bishop and take away the e4-square. Black has been missing their f-pawn since move three, which weakens the kingside permanently.  If we build up pressure with something like Qd2, b3 and Bb2, they have to face a much stronger bishop on the long diagonal, as they can't limit its scope with a pawn. We have attacking chances on the dark squares here - the opposite-coloured bishops are not a drawing factor.  Finally, I want to point out that playing a4 and Ra3 is an interesting idea, too. Getting our rook active via a3 to e3 is a creative way to play this position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Open Games 1.e4 e5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical reply.  It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.  In the Quickstarter Guide, I will focus on the most important lines and ideas to get you started with the opening. After studying the Quickstarter, you can test the suggestions in your games and deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@The Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines. Amongst the rare lines, the only serious option is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. These three moves account for about 95% of the games and are our focus in the Quickstarter. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ I recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. This might come as a surprise, as the Ruy Lopez does not have the reputation as a 'simple' opening. I agree that it is more complex than others, but it depends greatly on the choices afterwards.  Learning a repertoire based on the Ruy Lopez is worth the effort for numerous reasons:It leads to interesting and fighting positions. In most lines, there are no early trades and simplifications.It's versatile. Against some defenses, we can play more aggressively in the center @@StartBracket@@c3&d4@@EndBracket@@. In other cases, the position will be more closed, and we can drum up an attack on the kingside after shifting pieces to this side of the board. The Ruy is a great opening to learn a variety of middlegame structures.It's easy to modify later. Based on the framework you learn in this course, you can easily expand and change parts of it later. These points are key considerations for me.  'Keep it Simple' does not mean: 'Make it Boring'! Learning the Ruy Lopez is time well invested - you'll get interesting positions, challenge your opponent and teach yourself a lot about chess.   Let's get an overview of the Ruy Lopez. Black has many options against the Ruy. The best way to understand the various options is to view them on a conceptual basis.@@HeaderStart@@Black's Best Defensive Approach:@@HeaderEnd@@The best defenses for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  . In both cases, Black attacks our unprotected e-pawn. This approach looks very natural and logical. The knight is developed to its best square, and White has to worry about the e-pawn. In both cases, I recommend covering the e-pawn by play playing d3. The lines  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  are closely related and share multiple ideas.  In the first version, Black gains the additional option ...b5, which changes the position considerably. This leads us to the four most important branches of the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@A-D@@EndBracket@@:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  is a popular line for Black. They use their options to play ...b5 and then continue their kingside development most actively, playing the bishop on c5.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  is the more modest-looking version of A. Black opts for ...Be7, avoiding possible pins @@StartBracket@@Bg5 is a key idea in A@@EndBracket@@.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  . Black may react to 5.d3 differently. After we have reliably covered e4 with d3, the threat of Bxc6 and Nxe5 is serious. This leads to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  , which cover the pawn - the bishop move is based on  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5??  Qd4  , when Black wins.  D. In the Berlin Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  , Black's situation is similar to C. They have to do something about their e-pawn. Therefore,  4...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bc5  are the moves. We handle C and D in the same style. There are plenty of parallels and transpositions. These lines are less dependent on concrete move orders but more based on concepts and understanding. We save a lot of learning effort, as we have a framework of ideas that work against two important defenses by Black.  @@HeaderStart@@Black's Old-Fashioned Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  is called the Classical Defense. Black fails to put any pressure on e4, with allows us the aggressive reply  4.c3  , intending d4 next. It's important to understand that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  is a much better version of ...Bc5, as we have already played d2-d3. In the Classical, we manage d2-d4 with a tempo on Black's bishop. White can count on advantage in the Classical, based on this concept.   F. The Steinitz Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  and the Steinitz Deferred @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  . The early ...d6 does not put any pressure on our e4-pawn and blocks Black's f8-bishop. This allows us to open the position favourably with a quick d4. The Original Steinitz is a bad defense for Black, while the Deferred is a bit trickier to handle. We need the correct move orders to open the game favourably.  @@HeaderStart@@Risky/Odd Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@G. Black can play in Gambit style with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  . The second version is known to be bad for Black, while 3...f5 has the reputation of being risky but playable. I suggest a reply that is easy to handle and looks good for White.   H. Other Defenses. We have a chapter for the Odds end Ends, including defenses like the Bird @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  , Cozio @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  or Smyslov @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  .  The Bird is dubious, as it weakens the pawn structure and loses time. The Cozio and Smyslov don't put any pressure on our center and give us some leeway. I suggest a pragmatic solution based on a quick d2-d4, a similar concept as against the Steinitz.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on the replies you are most likely to encounter. Therefore, I decided to cover A-G above and skip the rarest lines. }
3... a6
{ Black attacks our bishop and forces a decision: to take or not to take? } 4.
Ba4
{ We keep our bishop on the board.   White has a reasonable alternative, the Exchange Variation 4.Bxc6, but I like to keep the game more complicated. It's important to see that  4.Bxc6  dxc6!  5.Nxe5?  fails to  5...Qd4!  , when Black regains the pawn with a good position. We don't threaten to win the e-pawn at the moment, but this idea will become serious once we have secured our e-pawn.   In the Quickstarter, I will only cover @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  now, as it is the main move by a mile.  I want to mention the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  , though. After  5.Bb3  , you will often transpose to lines that I cover via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  , the simplest example being @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.d3  , when you reach the same position.  Black also has @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  , the Steinitz Deferred. I briefly discussed it in the notes to 3...d6, as the ideas are similar. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's most logical and best move. They develop and attack our center pawn. }
5. d3
{ The start of the Anderssen Variation. We cover the e-pawn, which limits Black's options.  They need to be aware that now we threaten to capture e5 and snatch the e5-pawn. Black can't play  5...Be7?  as  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  wins the most important pawn on the board. It may sound silly, but I found thousands@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ of online games that featured this pawn blunder - and White often didn't even take the pawn!  What are the serious options for Black?  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  is the most popular move by a mile. Black kicks our bishop to b3 and then continues development.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  is a good move for Black but has little independent value in our repertoire. I suggest  6.Bxc6  , which cuts our workload tremendously. We'll reach a position that is almost identical to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  , but with an irrelevant extra move for Black.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  covers the e-pawn and leads to a slower, strategic game. We will discuss piece placement and ideas in these lines more than actual move sequences. }
5... d6
{ Black covers their e-pawn but forfeits the option to play ...Bc5. It looks more natural to play  5...Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  , but there are reasons why Black might want to play differently:  They possibly intended to play a line like @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  d6  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6...b5  7.Bb3  d6  , and want to reach a familiar setup.They might want to develop with ...g6, an interesting concept. This type of position can also arise from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  d6  , a line that is also part of our repertoire. Knowing and understanding these lines' typical manoeuvres and ideas will help immensely, as there are many similar variations in the Ruy and even the Italian game.  If you want to expand your repertoire at a later stage, you have a solid foundation after studying these lines.   The move 5...d6 also involves a threat! We need to get the move order correct now. }
6. c3
{ It's crucial to start with  6.c3  and avoid @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O?  b5  7.Bb3  Na5!  ,  when our Ruy bishop will be traded off. Losing the bishop pair is one bad aspect, but it also hurts that Black manages to get rid of their c6-knight so easily. The slightly misplaced knight on c6 is a key strategic issue in these slow Ruy structures. Why misplaced? We have a pawn on c3, which limits the scope of the knight. It mostly looks at protected squares, like b4 and d4.An additional issue for Black is the blocked c-pawn. We can favourably use our c-pawn to support a later d3-d4, building a well-supported pawn center. This is not as easy for Black to accomplish.Before we look at Black's options on move six, a word about our plans and setup. We have a fairly straightforward concept that works well, more or less, regardless of Black's choice:  Castle kingside,Play Re1,Start the knight tour Nb1-d2-f1-g3,If Black plays ...b5, we retreat the bishop to c2.  This is the 'default setup' that we play. If Black plays an unexpected move and you see no clear refutation, resort to the described setup. This configuration is harmonious and provides excellent support to play d3-d4 and finally build the full pawn center.   Black has a fundamental choice now: developing the bishop to e7 or going for a kingside fianchetto. In most cases, they play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  or  6...g6  now and commit to one of the setups.   In the Quickstarter, I will demonstrate our 'default setup' based on the most popular choice, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  . The full chapter also covers the fianchetto  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , of course. }
6... Be7
{ Black chooses to castle kingside as fast as possible. This setup is often the choice of players who intend to play a more traditional line of the Ruy, like @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  b5  7.Bb3  d6  , for instance. }
7. O-O { We continue with our standard move. } 7... O-O
{ Now Black almost always castles, but they could play  7...b5  8.Bc2  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4  8.Re1  first. These options have no independent value, though. Black can hardly play without castling, so they usually start with this move. We will examine Black's various plans on the next move. }
8. Re1
{ Here we go, the next move to get closer to our desired setup. Black has a ton of possible moves now. As both sides manoeuvre inside their camp, there are many options.  I will focus on the two most popular moves now and give you some brief info on others. We are always fine and preserve at least a small advantage by completing the knight tour to get and prepare d3-d4. In some cases, playing d3-d4 earlier is also possible.  Black has a ton of moves now, but @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...b5  is the most popular one. Black may also play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Re8  , @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bd7  , @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...h6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bg4  , there any many alternatives.  A general remark: the move orders can be irritating at first. If you keep in mind that we play the knight tour to g3 to ultimately prepare d3-d4, White's position will always be good. No one tries to memorize all the different permutations of ...h6, ...Re8, ...b5 and so on. There is no need to do that, which is a compelling aspect. We'll get a game full of pieces and possibilities without having to memorize a maze of irritating theory. }
8... b5 { Black's main move, sending our bishop to c2. } 9. Bc2
{ OK, job done. Now it's Black's turn to decide how to develop. I'll check 9...Bb7 now. Black has alternatives, but remembering our knight tour to g3 and d2-d4 as the general plan is enough for now. }
9... Bb7 { Black completes the extended fianchetto. } 10. Nbd2
{ Our normal move, starting the knight tour. We need to prepare d3-d4 thoroughly.   After  10.d4?!  exd4  11.cxd4  Nb4  Black gets good activity for their pieces. }
10... Nb8
{ Black invests some time to direct the knight to d7. We often see that the knight is not well-placed on c6. It looks at controlled squares @@StartBracket@@d4/b4@@EndBracket@@ and blocks the c-pawn. Black wants to place it on d7, often followed by ...c5, to involve the c-pawn. This regrouping is known from the Breyer Variation @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  b5  7.Bb3  d6  8.c3  O-O  9.h3  Nb8  @@EndBracket@@, but frequently seen in slower Ruy structure, too. }
11. Nf1
{ After 10...Nb8, there is less pressure on our center. Therefore, playing  11.d4  is possible, too. We still need the knight tour, so it will likely lead to the same positions at the end. One example is @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p2p1n2/1p2p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PPBN1PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11.d4  Nbd7  12.Nf1  Re8  13.Ng3  . }
11... Nbd7 { Both sides improve their knights. } 12. Ng3
{ Alright, we completed our knight tour. Now Black usually goes for ...Re8 and ...Bf8. It makes sense, as Black may play a fianchetto later. It combines defense against Nf5 with possible active ideas on the long diagonal. The bishop has little to hope for on e7, in any case. }
12... Re8 13. d4
{ The eagle has landed! Finally, we get our perfect pawn center. It's well-supported and stable. }
13... Bf8
{ Black is done with their regrouping, too. Now, what's our plan? I like to attack the b5-pawn and see if we can get Black to make some concessions on the queenside. }
14. a4
{ A common idea. We attack the pawn and can add more pressure on it with Bd3 later. In most cases, Black will play ...c5 pretty soon when we reach the following position type. }
14... c5
{ After a slower move like  14...g6  ,  15.Bd3  is a good way to put more pressure on b5. }
15. d5
{ Closing the center is best. We gain lots of space and make sure that Black's b7-bishop has no scope. }
15... c4
{ Black must play this advance to get the c5-square for their knight. After something like  15...g6  16.b3!  we are ready to answer ...c4 with b4, when this opportunity is gone. }
16. h3
{ It's not strictly necessary to play exactly this move, but it helps us in many ways. It prepares Be3 in the short term and may help later for kingside play.   I want to close with a key idea you should know: after  16...Nc5  17.Be3  Qc7  the move  18.Ra3!  is a strong resource. We want to play Qe2 next, then Rea1, when we have doubled behind the a-pawn and want to open the file soon under optimal circumstances. White is always slightly better here, as we have more active ideas.  The a-file idea is one, but in the long run, often, some action on the kingside takes place. It is also easier for us to generate play on this side of the board. Think of Nh2 and ideas like f2-f4. Piece-based play with Nh2-g4 is also possible. Black's situation is solid, but at the same time, quite passive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Open Games 1.e4 e5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical reply.  It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.  In the Quickstarter Guide, I will focus on the most important lines and ideas to get you started with the opening. After studying the Quickstarter, you can test the suggestions in your games and deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@The Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines. Amongst the rare lines, the only serious option is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. These three moves account for about 95% of the games and are our focus in the Quickstarter. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ I recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. This might come as a surprise, as the Ruy Lopez does not have the reputation as a 'simple' opening. I agree that it is more complex than others, but it depends greatly on the choices afterwards.  Learning a repertoire based on the Ruy Lopez is worth the effort for numerous reasons:It leads to interesting and fighting positions. In most lines, there are no early trades and simplifications.It's versatile. Against some defenses, we can play more aggressively in the center @@StartBracket@@c3&d4@@EndBracket@@. In other cases, the position will be more closed, and we can drum up an attack on the kingside after shifting pieces to this side of the board. The Ruy is a great opening to learn a variety of middlegame structures.It's easy to modify later. Based on the framework you learn in this course, you can easily expand and change parts of it later. These points are key considerations for me.  'Keep it Simple' does not mean: 'Make it Boring'! Learning the Ruy Lopez is time well invested - you'll get interesting positions, challenge your opponent and teach yourself a lot about chess.   Let's get an overview of the Ruy Lopez. Black has many options against the Ruy. The best way to understand the various options is to view them on a conceptual basis.@@HeaderStart@@Black's Best Defensive Approach:@@HeaderEnd@@The best defenses for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  . In both cases, Black attacks our unprotected e-pawn. This approach looks very natural and logical. The knight is developed to its best square, and White has to worry about the e-pawn. In both cases, I recommend covering the e-pawn by play playing d3. The lines  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  are closely related and share multiple ideas.  In the first version, Black gains the additional option ...b5, which changes the position considerably. This leads us to the four most important branches of the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@A-D@@EndBracket@@:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  is a popular line for Black. They use their options to play ...b5 and then continue their kingside development most actively, playing the bishop on c5.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  is the more modest-looking version of A. Black opts for ...Be7, avoiding possible pins @@StartBracket@@Bg5 is a key idea in A@@EndBracket@@.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  . Black may react to 5.d3 differently. After we have reliably covered e4 with d3, the threat of Bxc6 and Nxe5 is serious. This leads to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  , which cover the pawn - the bishop move is based on  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5??  Qd4  , when Black wins.  D. In the Berlin Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  , Black's situation is similar to C. They have to do something about their e-pawn. Therefore,  4...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bc5  are the moves. We handle C and D in the same style. There are plenty of parallels and transpositions. These lines are less dependent on concrete move orders but more based on concepts and understanding. We save a lot of learning effort, as we have a framework of ideas that work against two important defenses by Black.  @@HeaderStart@@Black's Old-Fashioned Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  is called the Classical Defense. Black fails to put any pressure on e4, with allows us the aggressive reply  4.c3  , intending d4 next. It's important to understand that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  is a much better version of ...Bc5, as we have already played d2-d3. In the Classical, we manage d2-d4 with a tempo on Black's bishop. White can count on advantage in the Classical, based on this concept.   F. The Steinitz Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  and the Steinitz Deferred @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  . The early ...d6 does not put any pressure on our e4-pawn and blocks Black's f8-bishop. This allows us to open the position favourably with a quick d4. The Original Steinitz is a bad defense for Black, while the Deferred is a bit trickier to handle. We need the correct move orders to open the game favourably.  @@HeaderStart@@Risky/Odd Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@G. Black can play in Gambit style with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  . The second version is known to be bad for Black, while 3...f5 has the reputation of being risky but playable. I suggest a reply that is easy to handle and looks good for White.   H. Other Defenses. We have a chapter for the Odds end Ends, including defenses like the Bird @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  , Cozio @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  or Smyslov @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  .  The Bird is dubious, as it weakens the pawn structure and loses time. The Cozio and Smyslov don't put any pressure on our center and give us some leeway. I suggest a pragmatic solution based on a quick d2-d4, a similar concept as against the Steinitz.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on the replies you are most likely to encounter. Therefore, I decided to cover A-G above and skip the rarest lines. }
3... a6
{ Black attacks our bishop and forces a decision: to take or not to take? } 4.
Ba4
{ We keep our bishop on the board.   White has a reasonable alternative, the Exchange Variation 4.Bxc6, but I like to keep the game more complicated. It's important to see that  4.Bxc6  dxc6!  5.Nxe5?  fails to  5...Qd4!  , when Black regains the pawn with a good position. We don't threaten to win the e-pawn at the moment, but this idea will become serious once we have secured our e-pawn.   In the Quickstarter, I will only cover @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  now, as it is the main move by a mile.  I want to mention the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  , though. After  5.Bb3  , you will often transpose to lines that I cover via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  , the simplest example being @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.d3  , when you reach the same position.  Black also has @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  , the Steinitz Deferred. I briefly discussed it in the notes to 3...d6, as the ideas are similar. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's most logical and best move. They develop and attack our center pawn. }
5. d3
{ The start of the Anderssen Variation. We cover the e-pawn, which limits Black's options.  They need to be aware that now we threaten to capture e5 and snatch the e5-pawn. Black can't play  5...Be7?  as  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  wins the most important pawn on the board. It may sound silly, but I found thousands@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ of online games that featured this pawn blunder - and White often didn't even take the pawn!  What are the serious options for Black?  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  is the most popular move by a mile. Black kicks our bishop to b3 and then continues development.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  is a good move for Black but has little independent value in our repertoire. I suggest  6.Bxc6  , which cuts our workload tremendously. We'll reach a position that is almost identical to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  , but with an irrelevant extra move for Black.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  covers the e-pawn and leads to a slower, strategic game. We will discuss piece placement and ideas in these lines more than actual move sequences. }
5... b5 { If you get the next move wrong, we need to talk. } 6. Bb3
{ Now Black's best moves are 6...Be7 and 6...Bc5, which are examined in the Quickstarter.  Black has some alternatives, but they usually transpose to worse versions of the above lines. Black can hardly play without developing the kingside soon, and e7 or c5 are the only good squares for the bishop. }
6... Be7
{ Black's main path after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  is  5...b5  6.Bb3  and then either  6...Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  .  Let's examine 6...Be7, the more modest-looking of the two. This is not a clear-cut assessment, though. Black's motivation behind 6...Be7 is not yet clear. They might want to play conservatively, based on ...d6, or aim at ...d7-d5 to open the center. One important difference to 6...Bc5 is that our idea of pinning the knight with Bg5 is exclusive to the ...Bc5-setups.   We fight @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc5  with  7.Nc3  and hope to manage something like  7...d6  8.Nd5  O-O?  9.Bg5  , when Black collapses. A very naive sequence, but it shows our basic plan.   When Black develops the bishop to e7, it makes little sense to play for this idea, as Bg5 is no pin. Therefore, we need a different approach to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  , as the same patterns don't work. The way to go is playing  7.a4!  , attacking Black's queenside. We will still frequently employ the move Nc3, but with different ideas in mind. }
7. a4
{ It's important to remember that we start attacking Black's b-pawn immediately. We will castle kingside soon, but it's more accurate to start with  7.a4  instead of casting.  What's the difference? After our move, we threaten to capture the b-pawn. Black has three replies to save it:  7...Bb7  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq a3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Rb8  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq a3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...b4  - all three moves have certain, small drawbacks; more on that in a moment.  Let's compare to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  now. Black's b-pawn is not threatened, and they have the main choice between  7...O-O  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  .  If they play  7...O-O  and we go  8.a4  , the situation is the same as after 7.a4 - Black has the three options I mentioned.  However, if Black chooses @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  , they gain the additional option to answer  8.a4  with  8...Bd7  - a better bishop placement than b7 @@StartBracket@@more on this topic in a moment@@EndBracket@@. Of course, 7.O-O is not a bad move. It transposes to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  Be7  6.d3  b5  7.Bb3  , one of White's main Anti-Marshall weapons nowadays. But we can take advantage of our move order by playing 7.a4 to reduce Black's options.  After our move, Black has three answers. They all lead to distinctly different positions and have their individual, small concession that Black needs to make.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq a3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Rb8  gives us the a-file after  8.axb5  and a small advantage.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq a3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...b4  changes the queenside pawn structure. Black gains space and controls c3 @@StartBracket@@no Nc3-d5 ideas@@EndBracket@@ but creates some weaknesses, like the c4-square.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq a3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb7  is the most popular move. One general objection against the move is that Black directs their bishop against a well-protected pawn on e4. It can be misplaced on its post - Black needs to be precise to prevent this scenario.  Interestingly, Black often gets close to equal chances regarding engine evaluation, but White scores heavily against all three moves. In my mind, White's play is a lot easier to conduct. I have played the black side of these lines frequently and never put in any serious study. The consequence was lots of suffering due to inaccurate play. Black needs to know some key points. Otherwise, they'll often struggle. }
7... Bb7
{ In the Quickstarter, we'll focus on this move, Black's most popular choice. Black develop their bishop to a less-than-ideal square. It stares at a well-protected e4-pawn, for starters. A second drawback might be the absence from the kingside, which can make a difference. Think of a knight jumping to f5, for instance.  A key decision for us is how to develop our knight. I think both Nc3 and Nbd2 setups are fine, but I prefer Nc3-based play. We use this idea frequently in the 5...b5 lines, and I like to use similar ideas, if possible.  I have checked if there is any point in starting with 8.Nc3, but it seems better to play it one move later and castle first. }
8. O-O O-O { A flexible move. Black does not yet commit their d-pawn. } 9. Nc3
{ I stick to Nc3 solutions whenever possible. It's not the only good setup, though.   You can also play  9.Re1  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nbd2  , these lines are good alternatives and should give White some advantage, too.  Our choice @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc3  is a more direct way. We attack b5, so Black's choice is limited.  9...b4  is the most popular move, leading to a long, forced line that is slightly better for White. }
9... b4
{ Black's most natural and popular move. Where to go now? After @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d6  9.Nc3  b4  , we play  10.Ne2  , aiming for the g3-square. Here, the situation is different, as Black has not moved their d-pawn yet. This allows a more powerful answer based on ...d7-d5. The way to go is jumping to d5. }
10. Nd5
{ It's crucial to play this move.   After  10.Ne2  Na5  11.Ba2  d5!  Black has tricked us and accomplished their desired central break.  What's best for Black now? They have a narrow path but many spots to go wrong. The best is the dynamic option @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/3Np3/Pp2P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Na5!  11.Nxe7+  Qxe7  12.Ba2  d5!  , breaking in the center. Black will often be a pawn down, though. This is not an easy option to go for.  In practice, Black often plays differently and is worse. It will often come down to knowledge, as this concept is not easily devised over the board. In the Quickstarter, I will check  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/3Np3/Pp2P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...d6  now, as it is the most played move. }
10... d6
{ Black covers the e-pawn, a slow and non-committal move. We have various ways to keep an advantage against it, but I suggest a concrete solution: capturing the bishop looks strong. }
11. Nxe7+
{ Simple but strong. We grab the bishop pair.   There are many good alternatives, though. Playing @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np1n2/3Np3/Pp2P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd2  , @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np1n2/3Np3/Pp2P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.c3  is no mistake, either. You should be aware that @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np1n2/3Np3/Pp2P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.a5  Nxd5  12.Bxd5?  fails to  12...Nxa5!  13.Rxa5  c6  , when Black has tricked us.  In my mind, taking on e7 is the easiest way to prove that we are better after 10...d6 - it's the bishop pair in a position that will eventually open up. }
11... Nxe7
{ After  11...Qxe7  I suggest  12.c3  , starting to open the position. Taking with the knight looks more logical for Black, as they want to use the c-pawn and have ...Ng6 in mind. We have a good reply, though. }
12. Bg5
{ Very annoying for Black. The important point is: this move is more about the pinning effect than about taking on f6.   If Black plays something slow like  12...Kh8  , I suggest  13.Nh4  to prepare f4 ideas. It's far more likely that Black wants to do something about the pin, though. }
12... Ng6
{ An alternative is  12...Nd7  , when  13.Nh4  looks good, too. We have ideas involving f4 or Qh5.    Black's move 12...Ng6 leads to an instructive moment. Black's idea is to play...h6 to break the pin. Our reply is a standard idea worth knowing. }
13. Nh4
{ Very nice! Now Black can't play  13...h6??  due to  14.Nxg6  , when we win material. Our Ruy Bishop is strong!   After  13.Nh4!  Black is under pressure. It's easy to fall off the cliff quickly, as the following line shows:  13...Nxh4  14.Bxh4  h6  - Black wants to play ...g5 to finally get rid of the pin, but the dreams are smashed by  15.f4!  exf4  16.Rxf4  g5  17.Qf3!  gxf4  18.Qxf4  ,  with a winning attack for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Open Games 1.e4 e5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical reply.  It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.  In the Quickstarter Guide, I will focus on the most important lines and ideas to get you started with the opening. After studying the Quickstarter, you can test the suggestions in your games and deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@The Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines. Amongst the rare lines, the only serious option is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. These three moves account for about 95% of the games and are our focus in the Quickstarter. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ I recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. This might come as a surprise, as the Ruy Lopez does not have the reputation as a 'simple' opening. I agree that it is more complex than others, but it depends greatly on the choices afterwards.  Learning a repertoire based on the Ruy Lopez is worth the effort for numerous reasons:It leads to interesting and fighting positions. In most lines, there are no early trades and simplifications.It's versatile. Against some defenses, we can play more aggressively in the center @@StartBracket@@c3&d4@@EndBracket@@. In other cases, the position will be more closed, and we can drum up an attack on the kingside after shifting pieces to this side of the board. The Ruy is a great opening to learn a variety of middlegame structures.It's easy to modify later. Based on the framework you learn in this course, you can easily expand and change parts of it later. These points are key considerations for me.  'Keep it Simple' does not mean: 'Make it Boring'! Learning the Ruy Lopez is time well invested - you'll get interesting positions, challenge your opponent and teach yourself a lot about chess.   Let's get an overview of the Ruy Lopez. Black has many options against the Ruy. The best way to understand the various options is to view them on a conceptual basis.@@HeaderStart@@Black's Best Defensive Approach:@@HeaderEnd@@The best defenses for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  . In both cases, Black attacks our unprotected e-pawn. This approach looks very natural and logical. The knight is developed to its best square, and White has to worry about the e-pawn. In both cases, I recommend covering the e-pawn by play playing d3. The lines  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  are closely related and share multiple ideas.  In the first version, Black gains the additional option ...b5, which changes the position considerably. This leads us to the four most important branches of the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@A-D@@EndBracket@@:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  is a popular line for Black. They use their options to play ...b5 and then continue their kingside development most actively, playing the bishop on c5.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  is the more modest-looking version of A. Black opts for ...Be7, avoiding possible pins @@StartBracket@@Bg5 is a key idea in A@@EndBracket@@.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  . Black may react to 5.d3 differently. After we have reliably covered e4 with d3, the threat of Bxc6 and Nxe5 is serious. This leads to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  , which cover the pawn - the bishop move is based on  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5??  Qd4  , when Black wins.  D. In the Berlin Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  , Black's situation is similar to C. They have to do something about their e-pawn. Therefore,  4...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bc5  are the moves. We handle C and D in the same style. There are plenty of parallels and transpositions. These lines are less dependent on concrete move orders but more based on concepts and understanding. We save a lot of learning effort, as we have a framework of ideas that work against two important defenses by Black.  @@HeaderStart@@Black's Old-Fashioned Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  is called the Classical Defense. Black fails to put any pressure on e4, with allows us the aggressive reply  4.c3  , intending d4 next. It's important to understand that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  is a much better version of ...Bc5, as we have already played d2-d3. In the Classical, we manage d2-d4 with a tempo on Black's bishop. White can count on advantage in the Classical, based on this concept.   F. The Steinitz Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  and the Steinitz Deferred @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  . The early ...d6 does not put any pressure on our e4-pawn and blocks Black's f8-bishop. This allows us to open the position favourably with a quick d4. The Original Steinitz is a bad defense for Black, while the Deferred is a bit trickier to handle. We need the correct move orders to open the game favourably.  @@HeaderStart@@Risky/Odd Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@G. Black can play in Gambit style with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  . The second version is known to be bad for Black, while 3...f5 has the reputation of being risky but playable. I suggest a reply that is easy to handle and looks good for White.   H. Other Defenses. We have a chapter for the Odds end Ends, including defenses like the Bird @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  , Cozio @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  or Smyslov @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  .  The Bird is dubious, as it weakens the pawn structure and loses time. The Cozio and Smyslov don't put any pressure on our center and give us some leeway. I suggest a pragmatic solution based on a quick d2-d4, a similar concept as against the Steinitz.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on the replies you are most likely to encounter. Therefore, I decided to cover A-G above and skip the rarest lines. }
3... a6
{ Black attacks our bishop and forces a decision: to take or not to take? } 4.
Ba4
{ We keep our bishop on the board.   White has a reasonable alternative, the Exchange Variation 4.Bxc6, but I like to keep the game more complicated. It's important to see that  4.Bxc6  dxc6!  5.Nxe5?  fails to  5...Qd4!  , when Black regains the pawn with a good position. We don't threaten to win the e-pawn at the moment, but this idea will become serious once we have secured our e-pawn.   In the Quickstarter, I will only cover @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  now, as it is the main move by a mile.  I want to mention the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  , though. After  5.Bb3  , you will often transpose to lines that I cover via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  , the simplest example being @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.d3  , when you reach the same position.  Black also has @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  , the Steinitz Deferred. I briefly discussed it in the notes to 3...d6, as the ideas are similar. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's most logical and best move. They develop and attack our center pawn. }
5. d3
{ The start of the Anderssen Variation. We cover the e-pawn, which limits Black's options.  They need to be aware that now we threaten to capture e5 and snatch the e5-pawn. Black can't play  5...Be7?  as  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  wins the most important pawn on the board. It may sound silly, but I found thousands@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ of online games that featured this pawn blunder - and White often didn't even take the pawn!  What are the serious options for Black?  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  is the most popular move by a mile. Black kicks our bishop to b3 and then continues development.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  is a good move for Black but has little independent value in our repertoire. I suggest  6.Bxc6  , which cuts our workload tremendously. We'll reach a position that is almost identical to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  , but with an irrelevant extra move for Black.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  covers the e-pawn and leads to a slower, strategic game. We will discuss piece placement and ideas in these lines more than actual move sequences. }
5... b5 { If you get the next move wrong, we need to talk. } 6. Bb3
{ Now Black's best moves are 6...Be7 and 6...Bc5, which are examined in the Quickstarter.  Black has some alternatives, but they usually transpose to worse versions of the above lines. Black can hardly play without developing the kingside soon, and e7 or c5 are the only good squares for the bishop. }
6... Bc5
{ Compared to 6...Be7, Black elects to develop their bishop to a more active square. This changes the position considerably, compared to 6...Be7, which is less ambitious. One change is the option of Bg5, which establishes a pin now. We will use this motive in some lines, but our starting move is different and somewhat surprising at first sight. We will start with   7.Nc3  .  It looks strange, given the plan of playing c3&d4, which should still be on our agenda.The point of  7.Nc3  is first to play Nc3-d5 and then continue with c3&d4, depending on Black's response. I like this idea much, compared to the more familiar concept of playing c3 and continuing with the knight tour Nb1-d2-f1-g3. In the line  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  we need to play  6.c3  and go for this plan. This type of play wouldn't be terrible here, but we can be more cunning by playing 7.Nc3. You'll see that Black has many pitfalls to navigate. }
7. Nc3
{ Here we go,  7.Nc3  is our choice in this line. How should Black react to our move? They must consider our ideas Nd5 and Bg5 - allowing both moves can easily spell trouble. The knight jump to d5 is annoying in itself, as Black would like to capture it, but both exd5 and Bxd5 can be problematic. Our bishop is not badly placed on d5 and usually will recapture.Conceptually speaking, Black has three moves that look reasonable - right now or on the next move. They can think of ...d6, ...h6 and ...O-O, but combining them correctly is tricky. Black has to navigate several pitfalls.  Let's check some possible options. Our job is easy, as we want to play Nd5 next in all cases.   A. Black has to be careful with castling early. In the Quickstarter, I will examine an attractive line that illustrates the dangers.  B. Black can delay castling. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1pb1p3/4P3/1BNP1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  8.Nd5  h6  9.c3  Rb8  is a sophisticated way for Black to do that. I suggest playing  10.d4  against it, starting the central action. I analyse this line in the full chapter, of course. }
7... O-O
{ Castling can't be a bad move, but we'll see that Black's job is not easy after committing the king that early. I decided to organise the move orders in a way that all early O-O positions are shown here, but Black may also play a different seventh move. Then they castle on move 8 or 9 when we reach the lines discussed here. }
8. Nd5
{ We always start with the knight jump, setting up the Bg5 and c3 ideas. Black now has to worry about Bg5; what are the options?   A.  8...d6?  ignores our idea and runs into  9.Bg5  , when Black's kingside is torn apart.   B. Black's most popular move is  8...h6  now, stopping the pin. We'll see that Black is in danger of losing a miniature - look forward to some fun lines.   C.  8...Nxd5  is rarely played but looks better than the alternatives. We'll get a small and comfortable advantage, but Black won't get checkmated quickly - that might happen in A or B! }
8... h6
{ By far the most popular move, but Black is walking a tightrope after weakening the kingside. }
9. c3
{ Playing  9.c3!  is a standard idea in this chapter. We'll usually play 7.Nc3, 8.Nd5 and 9.c3, but the exclam is set as a reminder that we don't castle kingside for a reason.We'll now focus on  9...d6  , which is almost exclusively played now. I found some games with  9...Rb8  or  9...Re8  , when you can play any 'normal' move, like castling. I suggest something else, though. Play  9...Rb8  10.h3  , intending  10...d6  11.Nxf6+  Qxf6  12.g4  , which is dangerous for Black. It's not as powerful as the lines we'll see in a minute, but still a good option. }
9... d6
{ The most common move by a mile, but it probably loses the game! That sounds harsh, but I don't think Black should survive our attack. The position after  9...d6  is very important, as it may occur via different orders. Black often starts with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1pb1p3/4P3/1BNP1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  8.Nd5  h6  9.c3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1pb1p3/4P3/1BNP1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h6  8.Nd5  d6  9.c3  and then  9...O-O  ,  when we reach the same position.So... why is it all so grim for Black? }
10. Nxf6+
{ It's all about the position we reach in a moment. First, we capture on f6 and play our bishop to d5 to pin the knight. }
10... Qxf6 11. Bd5
{ An important move. We force Black's bishop to d7 when it's difficult for our opponent to untangle. They can't move the bishop or knight, so our attack will work well. }
11... Bd7
{ Here  11...Bb7  is even worse, as then we wouldn't even need the next move and could play  12.g4!  immediately. }
12. Rg1
{ Boom! Yes, we'll go g4-g5 and go for the checkmate! This move has caught dozens of strong players off guard, including many GMs. It is one of those moves that fly under the radar, but once you see it, it makes perfect sense. The center is stable, Black can't move c6 or d7, and ...h6 weakens their kingside. What to check now?  In the Quickstarter, I look at Black's most frequently seen idea, moving the a8-rook. In the full chapter, I also analyse some other defensive attempts - Black is in bad shape in all of them. }
12... Rae8
{ Black moves the rook to unpin the knight, but it's too late already. } 13. g4
Qg6
{ Here's a funny alternative line:  13...Ne7  14.g5  Qg6  15.Nh4  Qh7  16.g6  will likely lead to resignation unless you play Jonathan Corbblah! 😀 }
14. g5 hxg5
{ We have already seen that  14...Ne7  15.Nh4  Qh7  16.g6  wins quickly. The alternative @@StartFEN@@4rrk1/2pb1pp1/p1np2qp/1pbBp1P1/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3P1P/R1BQK1R1 b Q - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qh5  15.gxh6  g6  16.Rg5  Qxh6  17.Rg4  Qg7  18.Rh4  is also crushing. }
15. Bxg5
{ Our immediate threat is Nh4, followed by Bf6. There is no way Black is surviving our attack. It's particularly nice that we didn't need to sacrifice any material. It's all for free! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Sicilian"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... e6
{ Against  2...e6  , I suggest playing  3.c3  , a delayed Alapin. I like playing c3 on the third move, as Black's move ...e6 has limited their choice of defense. The delayed Alapin is also a good weapon against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  , which we cover in the Sicilian Sidelines chapter. }
3. c3
{ After our move 3.c3, Black has two main continuations and some minor alternatives that we will check.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  is the most popular move @@StartBracket@@50% of games@@EndBracket@@.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  is possible, but it either transposes into A or leads to problems for Black. The transposition is  4.d4  d5!  5.exd5  , when both captures lead to 3...d5 lines. The worse alternative is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4?!  5.cxd4  d5  , when  6.e5!  is strong. We reach a nice French-type position with a premature trade on d4, which allows the active move Nc3 soon.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  is a similar story as  4.d4  d5!  5.exd5  can still transpose to A territory, but sometimes Black trades on d4 and allows the favourable advance.   D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is the main alternative, played in about 25% of games. }
3... Nf6
{ Black's most popular reply is 3...d5, but 3...Nf6 is an important alternative that leads to different positions. Black attacks our e-pawn and forces the advance. In my mind, 3...Nf6 is more promising for Black than 3...d5, but these early decisions are often a matter of taste.  Against  3...Nf6  , I decided to keep my suggestion from the first edition:  4.e5  Nd5  5.g3  , which has proven to be very effective in practice. In online games, it scores much better than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bc4  , showing that these more popular lines are not easy for White to play.  One problem in these lines is: White tries to keep the pawn on e5, which is double-edged. The pawn can be strong but may also be a weakness. We go for the simple approach of always taking a pawn coming to d6, avoiding this strategic complexity. }
4. e5 Nd5
{ After 4...Nd5, White usually goes for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bc4  , with d4 to follow. They are the most popular lines but difficult to handle in practice. In the first edition, I recommended the setup starting with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.g3  , which is simpler to play and scores well in practice. }
5. g3
{ We follow a simple, yet effective idea: our bishop will be well-placed on the long diagonal, while Black's c8-bishop takes a while to develop. Black will attack our e5-pawn sooner rather than later. If they play ...d6, we take this pawn and avoid a possible target on e5.  How does Black continue now?  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2NP1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  is our main line. Black attacks our advanced pawn immediately and forces a decision. As mentioned: we take on d6.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2NP1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  will often lead to A, as ...d6 next is very natural. }
5... d6 6. exd6
{ Our concept does not involve keeping this pawn.  In the 5.d4 variation, White's aim is different. They try to keep the pawn on e5 and establish a space advance. The practical problem often turns out to be that the advanced pawn can be a weakness, too.  We play a simpler strategy. After taking on d6, we want to complete kingside castling and open the center with d4. }
6... Bxd6 7. Bg2 Nc6
{ This position may also arise via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2NP1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Bg2  d6  7.exd6  Bxd6  , a common alternative move order. }
8. O-O
{ Starting with  8.d4  is also fine and should lead to a transposition. } 8...
O-O 9. d4
{ Our idea is to use the superior bishop position on g2, compared to the counterpart on c8. We will also try to use the queenside pawn majority, which is often nicely supported by our fianchettoed bishop.  After 9.d4, Black's most natural move is taking d4 to clarify the central situation.  If they want to keep the tension, @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbp3/2pn4/3P4/2P2NP1/PP3PBP/RNBQ1RK1 b - d3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...b6  is a sensible choice. After  10.c4  Nde7  11.Nc3  , we can develop our knight to a more active square, though. }
9... cxd4
{ Taking d4 is by far the most popular move. Black clarifies the central structure and then organises their pieces accordingly. }
10. Nxd4
{ We open the bishop diagonal and avoid any structural weakness.  Black usually trades knights on d4, but a quick look at  10...Bd7  is warranted. }
10... Nxd4
{ Black has less space; trading is a logical step.   They can play  10...Bd7  , when  11.c4  Nf6  12.Nb3  is interesting. We keep more pieces on the board, which makes it harder for Black to activate the d7-bishop. }
11. Qxd4
{ We always want to take with a piece to avoid an IQP.  Now we get to an important crossroads, as Black needs to be precise to avoid getting under serious pressure. The first point to understand for both sides: White is not threatening to win a pawn by capturing twice on d5. We can't give up our best piece, activate Black's position and weaken our kingside for a stupid pawn.  Black's best move is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/3bp3/3n4/3Q4/2P3P1/PP3PBP/RNB2RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qc7  , which correctly ignores the possibility of Bxd5. Master-level players usually play this move, but there are plenty of alternatives that more materialistic or inexperienced players may go for. I will take a look at @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/3bp3/3n4/3Q4/2P3P1/PP3PBP/RNB2RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/3bp3/3n4/3Q4/2P3P1/PP3PBP/RNB2RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb6  , as these look quite logical, but give White an excellent position. }
11... Qc7
{ Black's best defense. They are not worried about the capture on d5 and prepare the moves ...Rd8 and ...Bd7.   Much worse is  11...Nf6?  12.Rd1  Be7  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Rxd8+  Bxd8  15.a4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/3bp3/3n4/3Q4/2P3P1/PP3PBP/RNB2RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb6?!  12.Qxb6  Nxb6  13.Rd1  Be7  14.a4  , when we have a huge initiative on the queenside. Our bishop is a monster, compared to its counterpart on c8. }
12. c4
{ I already suggested this move in the first edition and still think it is better than 12.Nd2, which was more popular at the time.   Now it looks like 12...Nf6 is best, but 12...Nb4? is a tempting but bad alternative. I'll check @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2ppp/3bp3/3n4/2PQ4/6P1/PP3PBP/RNB2RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nb4  now, as it is much trickier to meet than @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2ppp/3bp3/3n4/2PQ4/6P1/PP3PBP/RNB2RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nf6  , when  13.Nc3  Bd7  14.Nb5  Bxb5  15.cxb5  leads to a position that is easier to play for White. Our g2-bishop remains a strong piece. }
12... Nb4
{ Black is tempted by the fork, but we can ignore this idea and get our threats on the road. }
13. Nc3
{ A super strong move!   It turns out that Black can't play  13...Nc2?  because  14.Qd3  Nxa1  15.Nb5  Qd8  16.Nxd6  wins for White. Our knight and g2-bishop are monsters, and we'll pick up the guy on a1 along the way. Black is in some trouble now. What to do against our Nb5 idea? }
13... a6
{ Black can't get a good game anymore. This won't work, but the alternatives are grim, too:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2ppp/3bp3/8/1nPQ4/2N3P1/PP3PBP/R1B2RK1 b - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Bd7??  14.Rd1  is curtains.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2ppp/3bp3/8/1nPQ4/2N3P1/PP3PBP/R1B2RK1 b - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nc6  13.Qe4  a6  14.Rd1  puts lots of pressure on Black. Stockfish says White is winning, but that's too much.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2ppp/3bp3/8/1nPQ4/2N3P1/PP3PBP/R1B2RK1 b - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Be5  14.Nb5  Qb8  15.Qe4  is a similar story. }
14. Rd1 Be5 { We have a cool move now to put Black out of business. } 15. Bf4
{ Very nice! After @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1pq2ppp/p3p3/4b3/1nPQ1B2/2N3P1/PP3PBP/R2R2K1 b - - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bxf4  16.Qxf4  Qxf4  17.gxf4  we are winning, as Black can't ever move the queenside. We have Rd6 and Rad1 next - chess is fun! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Sicilian"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... e6
{ Against  2...e6  , I suggest playing  3.c3  , a delayed Alapin. I like playing c3 on the third move, as Black's move ...e6 has limited their choice of defense. The delayed Alapin is also a good weapon against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  , which we cover in the Sicilian Sidelines chapter. }
3. c3
{ After our move 3.c3, Black has two main continuations and some minor alternatives that we will check.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  is the most popular move @@StartBracket@@50% of games@@EndBracket@@.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  is possible, but it either transposes into A or leads to problems for Black. The transposition is  4.d4  d5!  5.exd5  , when both captures lead to 3...d5 lines. The worse alternative is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4?!  5.cxd4  d5  , when  6.e5!  is strong. We reach a nice French-type position with a premature trade on d4, which allows the active move Nc3 soon.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  is a similar story as  4.d4  d5!  5.exd5  can still transpose to A territory, but sometimes Black trades on d4 and allows the favourable advance.   D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is the main alternative, played in about 25% of games. }
3... d5
{ Probably Black's most natural and popular move. After our capture on d5, we'll have a further split. }
4. exd5
{ Now, we often reach an IQP position. After 4...exd5, Black often goes for the IQP - after 4...Qxd5, we will play with the isolated pawn in many cases.  I decided only to cover @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5  in the Quickstarter, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  5.d4  is very similar to the French Tarrasch @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  c5  4.Ngf3  Nc6  6.exd5  exd5  , which I cover in the Quickstarter on the French. It is even possible to transpose to the same positions, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  5.d4  Nc6  6.Bb5  Bd6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.O-O  Nge7  9.Nbd2  O-O  10.Nb3  demonstrates. }
4... Qxd5
{ Black avoids the IQP with this move, in fact, White could soon be the one with a @@StartBracket@@favourable@@EndBracket@@ IQP. Most of the time, however, we play with an early Na3, intending to harass the Queen with Nb5, leading to an open center without an isolated pawn. }
5. d4
{ After our move 5.d4, it is a good moment to talk about various scenarios that may arise now:  A. Black captures on d4 now, and after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4  6.cxd4  , we will play with an IQP. We are happy about their choice, as it is a favourable version of the isolated pawn. The key reason is that we will play Nc3, gaining a tempo on the queen. A typical sequence is  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4  6.cxd4  Nf6  7.Nc3  Qd8  8.Bd3  Be7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Re1  Nc6  11.a3  , when we plan to play Bg5 and the attacking idea Bc2&Qd3 next.   B.  Our opponent realises that taking on d4 is premature and keeps the tension by playing  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  . Often, Black will play both knights to their natural squares, and it does not matter what move they started with. We will examine 5...Nf6, the far more popular of the two, as the main move. }
5... Nf6
{ This is the main line by a mile. This follows the logic that this knight will be best on f6 with almost 100% certainty, while the optimal position of the other knight is not as obvious. }
6. Na3
{ We immediately get our knight in the game, intending to activate it via b5 or c4. }
6... Nc6 { With this move, Black keeps the queen on d5 as long as possible. }
7. Be3
{ Very natural play, but it is important to note that instead,  7.Nb5  Qd8  8.dxc5  is less promising than it looks due to  8...Bxc5  9.Qxd8  Kxd8  , and this endgame does not lead to much. It is, of course, an option if you like a quiet game, but I think 7.Be3  is objectively more promising. }
7... cxd4
{ With Be3, we had increased the pressure on c5. We'll see the typical knight jump to ensure we take on d4 with a piece. }
8. Nb5 Qd8 9. Nbxd4
{ We manage to capture on d4 with a piece and establish a strong centralisation. }
9... Nd5
{ This looks best for Black.   The continuation  9...Nxd4  10.Bxd4  Be7  11.Bd3  looks excellent for White. Depending on your preferences, we can choose between playing for kingside or queenside castling. }
10. Nxc6 { Damaging Black's pawn structure is desirable. } 10... bxc6 11. Bd2
{ 11.Bd4  is also interesting, but plans involving ...f6 are a bit murky. Our move is simple but also good for a slight pull. }
11... Qb6
{ Black may also develop the f8-bishop, of course, but this move is the only one that requires a concrete reaction. After a slow alternative like  11...Bc5  12.Bd3  O-O  13.O-O  , we enjoy a small but distinct advantage due to the better pawn structure. }
12. Bd3 { We happily offer the b2-pawn as we are much better developed. } 12...
Qxb2 13. Rb1
{ This move is much better than  13.O-O  , which I suggested in the first edition. It is dangerous for Black, but there seems to be no immediate win. Some years later, the computer shows @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p4ppp/2p1p3/3n4/8/2PB1N2/Pq1B1PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Rb1!  is leading to an attack that is already winning by engine standards. }
13... Qa3
{ A bit better than  13...Qxa2  14.c4  Nf6  15.O-O  , when our attack is devastating. Moves like Bc3, Ne5, and Qf3 have a very natural flow, while Black has no development and a precarious situation with their queen. }
14. O-O
{ We can castle now, making sure that  14...Nxc3??  14.Qc2  wins on the spot. We'll play ideas like Re1 and Ne5 next, with a fantastic attack for just a single pawn. }
*

