[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... Nc6
{ Black develops their knight, the starting point of many famous Open Sicilian lines.  Nowadays, the focus has shifted from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  to the Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  , the move I recommend. White can pose problems in positions that work perfectly in the context of this course. We want to exert some pressure while following classical and easy-to-understand principles. }
3. Bb5
{ The starting move of the Rossolimo. We develop and prepare kingside castling and keep our pawn structure flexible. We'll focus on Black's most popular moves now:  3...g6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  .   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  is Black's most popular reply. We play  4.O-O  and want to build a full center with c3&d4 later.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  signals Black's intention to play ...Nge7 next and then challenge our bishop with ...a6.  Again, we play  4.O-O  and intend to occupy the center later.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  follows a similar idea as B. Black usually continues with ...Bd7 and ...a6 to attack our bishop. We react like in B: castle and prepare to play in the center later. }
3... e6
{ This move is Black's second most popular against Rossolimo. Its basic idea is to cover the c6-knight with ...Nge7 and then chase our bishop with ...a6. They want to only play ...a6 after ensuring that a piece can recapture on c6. }
4. O-O
{ Here, White's main alternative is  4.Bxc6  , immediately creating an imbalance in the position. White gives up the pair of bishops but creates weaknesses in Black's camp.   I prefer  4.O-O  for our repertoire because it is easier to learn and understand. We castle and prepare Re1, which allows us to keep our bishop - more on this subject in a moment. }
4... Nge7
{ The consistent move after 3...e6. Black is now ready for ...a6, attacking our bishop without worrying about doubled pawns. They also prepare the move ...d5, a common feature of our main line. Alternatives don't require deeper study:  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  provokes the capture when  5.Bxc6  will transpose to position types we examine via the move order 3...a6 featured in the Rossolimo sidelines chapter.  Sometimes you meet @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  when many natural replies are good. You can play  5.e5  Nd5  6.Nc3  , as I suggested in the first edition, or prefer @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/2n1pn2/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  , planning c3&d4 later. Both options @@StartBracket@@and some more@@EndBracket@@ look convincing and comfortable to play. All these options delay Black's development too much. }
5. Re1
{ We have to decide how to retreat our b5-bishop after the expected move ...a6.   We could play  5.c3  , signalling our intention to drop it to b3/c2 later. This is similar to the Ruy Lopez, which would fit our choice in the 1.e4 e5 universe.  However, a closer look has led me to conclude that clearing f1 for our bishop is a better choice. This is certainly a matter of taste to some degree, but I like that we play in the same way after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  when we face a similar choice. }
5... a6
{ Black almost always plays this move first and only after our bishop retreat decides their further setup.  Black's main choices are  5...a6  6.Bf1  d5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng6  , which are of about equal strength. I am presenting this overview here because Black could omit the move 5...a6 and start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ng6  , when  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  is a transposition to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Ng6  7.c3  , which we examine in a minute. }
6. Bf1
{ Preserving our bishop, according to plan. Now Black has to commit in some way to a development scheme. Here's an overview of the options that we will examine.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  is Black's most popular move. After  7.exd5  Nxd5  8.d4  , the position opens, and we retain a small advantage.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng6  leads to a more complex game, often reminiscent of the French Defense. It continues  7.c3  Be7  8.d4  cxd4  9.cxd4  d5  10.e5  , when the space advantage gives us an edge.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6?!  is dubious for Black, as they weaken the dark squares too much. We can exploit it with  7.d4  , opening the position.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...b5?!  gains space on the queenside but presents targets to attack this side of the board.  7.c3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3pnppp/p1n1p3/1pp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 w kq b6 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4  are strong replies giving White an advantage. }
6... d5
{ Black expands in the center, a very logical decision. This line was played in a well-known game between Magnus Carlsen and Boris Gelfand in 2013. Based on this game, it has earned the reputation of being slightly better for White. Modern analysis confirms this assessment - we can be happy with our chances. }
7. exd5
{ After this capture, the most common and logical move is  7...Nxd5  , as played in the mentioned Carlsen-Gelfand game. }
7... Nxd5
{ The natural recapture. By taking with the knight, Black prepares ...Be7 and kingside castling. }
8. d4
{ We open the center as fast as possible. We are much better developed and have already castled, after all. Now we'll check three lines of defense for Black.  A. The main move, the prophylactic retreat @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/2pn4/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nf6  .   B. Developing with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/2pn4/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  , which looks better for White after  9.dxc5  , followed by a queenside expansion with a3 and b4.   C. The capture on d4. This move is not bad, but it needs to be followed by precise play - otherwise, Black can easily get into trouble. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/2pn4/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  Ndb4  10.Nxc6  Qxd1  11.Rxd1  Nxc6  12.c3  White has the idea Nd2-c4, which is not easy for Black to handle. }
8... Nf6
{ This is the best move. Remarkably, Black can afford to delay development further, but concrete analysis shows that it works. }
9. Be3 cxd4
{ Black can also delay the capture for a moment. After  9...Be7  I suggested  10.dxc5  in the first edition, but @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2bppp/p1n1pn2/2p5/3P4/4BN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QRBK1 w kq - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c4  is a much simpler approach that will transpose to our main line after  10...cxd4  11.Nxd4  Bd7  12.Nc3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2bppp/p1n1pn2/2p5/2PP4/4BN2/PP3PPP/RN1QRBK1 b kq c3 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...O-O  11.Nc3  cxd4  12.Nxd4  , which are both common sequences.  In the first edition, I expressed concerns about @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2bppp/p1n1pn2/2p5/3P4/4BN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QRBK1 w kq - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c4  Ng4  , but after  11.d5  Nxe3  12.fxe3  exd5  14.cxd5  Na5  15.e4  White is in good shape, as the a5-knight looks terrible. }
10. Nxd4 Bd7
{ Here  10...Nxd4  11.Bxd4  Be7  is an alternative move order for Black. We can play  12.c4  , transposing to our main line, or try @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2bppp/p3pn2/8/3B4/8/PPP2PPP/RN1QRBK1 w kq - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.a4  instead. This is an interesting idea, trying to use the c4-square for a knight later. }
11. c4
{ An important part of our concept. We have not yet played Nc3 and blocked our c-pawn. Now we see a benefit of the delayed queenside development. By playing c4, we gain more control of the center, particularly the square d5.  An additional aspect is our pawn majority on the queenside. We have three pawns against two pawns of our opponent, which is a good starting point for space gains on this side of the board. }
11... Nxd4
{ Black needs some space for their pieces. The c6-square is better suited for the bishop, so trading on d4 makes perfect sense. }
12. Bxd4 Bc6 13. Nc3
{ We managed to develop our knight behind our pawn chain and pawn majority, which is strategically very desirable. }
13... Be7 14. a3
{ We start to set our majority in motion. Black has a fundamental choice now: allowing b2-b4 or stopping it.  A. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1p2bppp/p1b1pn2/8/2PB4/P1N5/1P3PPP/R2QRBK1 b kq - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...a5  was played in the game Carlsen-Gelfand I mentioned before. After  15.Qd3  O-O  16.Rad1  Carlsen enjoyed a comfortable advantage and managed to win a fine game.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1p2bppp/p1b1pn2/8/2PB4/P1N5/1P3PPP/R2QRBK1 b kq - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...O-O  15.b4  looks even better for us. Here's an instructive idea worth knowing: after  15...Qd7  , there is the attractive move  16.Ra2!  , going for the rook lift to d2.  All in all, I am happy with White's chances in this line. We enjoy a comfortable position without taking risks, and Black's game is more difficult to conduct. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Sicilian"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... Nc6
{ Black develops their knight, the starting point of many famous Open Sicilian lines.  Nowadays, the focus has shifted from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  to the Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  , the move I recommend. White can pose problems in positions that work perfectly in the context of this course. We want to exert some pressure while following classical and easy-to-understand principles. }
3. Bb5
{ The starting move of the Rossolimo. We develop and prepare kingside castling and keep our pawn structure flexible. We'll focus on Black's most popular moves now:  3...g6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  .   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  is Black's most popular reply. We play  4.O-O  and want to build a full center with c3&d4 later.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  signals Black's intention to play ...Nge7 next and then challenge our bishop with ...a6.  Again, we play  4.O-O  and intend to occupy the center later.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  follows a similar idea as B. Black usually continues with ...Bd7 and ...a6 to attack our bishop. We react like in B: castle and prepare to play in the center later. }
3... d6
{ Black opts for 3...d6, reaching a position that could also arise via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  Nc6  , as a less common sequence. Black's basic idea is to play ...Bd7 and ...a6, kicking our bishop back without accepting doubled pawns. }
4. O-O
{ Just as after 3...g6 or 3...e6, we castle first. It's a move we need anyway, and being ready for Re1 to protect e4 is useful.  Now Black's only fully satisfactory move is 4...Bd7, breaking the pin and preparing ...a6 to attack our bishop. }
4... Bd7
{ This is by far the most popular and best move. Others delay the development even more and are quite risky. }
5. Re1
{ There is nothing fundamentally wrong about  5.c3  here, but I prefer the rook move. The reasoning is similar to the situation after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.O-O  Nge7  , when Black is ready to answer Bxc6 with a piece recapture and avoids the doubled pawn. This makes the capture unattractive for White, and we need to decide if we want to retreat the bishop via a4-c2 or f1. In both cases going to f1 is a better choice, as it doesn't allow Black's queenside expansion with tempo.   Now, after @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  , Black's best setup is  5...Nf6  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  Bg4  , pinning our knight. We can also reach this position via the move order @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Nf6  7.c3  Bg4  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Bg4  7.c3  Nf6  all lead to the same position.   Our job is quite simple here: if they play ...a6, we retreat to f1. Otherwise, we continue with the logical move c3 to prepare our central expansion. I will examine 5...Nf6 as the path to the main position on move 7.   A bad alternative for Black is @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  , because  6.c3  Bg7  7.d4  gives us a great center. }
5... Nf6
{ Heading for the main line, in most cases. As mentioned before, they could also start with  5...a6  to reach this main position we are about to examine. }
6. c3
{ According to plan. We are now ready to play d4, which Black should fight. }
6... a6 7. Bf1
{ We prepared this retreat with the early Re1.  Now Black has two continuations: the main move 7...Bg4 and 7...e5, gaining some ground in the center. We'll focus on the bishop move, which is much more popular. After @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1bpppp/p1np1n2/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  I suggest  8.h3  , preparing d4 next. This is covered in the full chapter in more detail. }
7... Bg4
{ By far the most common move. In many cases, Black will take on f3, giving us the Bishop pair. In return, Black gains some time to develop, as shown in the main line.  If Black tries to keep the bishop by retreating to h5, White has excellent chances to get an early attack. }
8. h3
{ White has two main options here. You may also play  8.d4  , but this move is considerably sharper. The reason is the capture  8...Bxf3  , when we need to damage our pawn structure with  9.gxf3  - d4 is under pressure, and we need to keep it covered. The arising lines are still interesting, but I prefer the move  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p2pppp/p1np1n2/2p5/4P1b1/2P2N1P/PP1P1PP1/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h3  as a safer option.  We either get the bishop pair without structural damage, or Black allows the attractive lines after  8...Bh5?!  9.g4!  , giving us a strong attack. The point is that  9...Bg6  10.d4!  is possible. Black can't take on e4 due to tactics based on Qa4. One sample line is  10...Nxe4  11.d5  Ne5  12.Nxe5  dxe5  13.Rxe4!  Bxe4  14.Qa4+  , when White wins material. }
8... Bxf3
{ This is best. Black keeps control over d4 for a while, and White will lose some time by moving the queen. }
9. Qxf3
{ We have gained the bishop pair but lost some influence over the center. It will take a moment to finally get our d-pawn to d4, as we will see.  Black now has two basic options: developing with ...e6 or ...g6. Our concept will be similar in both cases. We must play our pawn to d3, retreat our queen to d1, develop the bishop to  e3  , and then play Nb1-d2-f3. This setup optimally supports the central pawn push d4.  We'll check 9...g6 now. As mentioned, @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p2pppp/p1np1n2/2p5/4P3/2P2Q1P/PP1P1PP1/RNB1RBK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...e6  10.d3  Be7  11.Nd2  O-O  12.Qd1  d5  13.e5  Nd7  14.Nf3  follows a similar concept. }
9... g6
{ Black goes for the kingside fianchetto. This makes a lot of sense strategically, as they connect their bishop to the d4-square. However, they can't stop our central pawn push forever. }
10. d3 Bg7 11. Be3
{ Lending even more support to d3-d4. This bishop development is less precise in the 9...e6 formation but works well here. }
11... Nd7 { Black has good control over d4, but we need to be persistent. } 12.
Nd2 { Playing  12.Qd1  first also works. } 12... O-O 13. Qd1 b5 14. Nf3
{ And we are finally ready to build our dream center. We have a comfortable advantage due to our space advantage and the bishop pair. Black's queenside may also prove vulnerable. }
*

[Event "?"]
