[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Sicilian"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... Nc6
{ Black develops their knight, the starting point of many famous Open Sicilian lines.  Nowadays, the focus has shifted from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  to the Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  , the move I recommend. White can pose problems in positions that work perfectly in the context of this course. We want to exert some pressure while following classical and easy-to-understand principles. }
3. Bb5
{ The starting move of the Rossolimo. We develop and prepare kingside castling and keep our pawn structure flexible. We'll focus on Black's most popular moves now:  3...g6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  .   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  is Black's most popular reply. We play  4.O-O  and want to build a full center with c3&d4 later.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  signals Black's intention to play ...Nge7 next and then challenge our bishop with ...a6.  Again, we play  4.O-O  and intend to occupy the center later.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  follows a similar idea as B. Black usually continues with ...Bd7 and ...a6 to attack our bishop. We react like in B: castle and prepare to play in the center later. }
3... g6
{ This chapter covers Black's most popular reply to the Rossolimo: 3...g6, preparing the kingside fianchetto. It is played in roughly 50% of all Rossolimo games and is a cornerstone of our Sicilian repertoire. }
4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1
{ I suggest playing  5.Re1  , just as I did in the first edition. There is an important difference, though. After Black's main reply,  5...Nf6  , I am now recommending  6.c3  , aiming for a full pawn center. This continuation is more in line with the general spirit of our repertoire, which emphasises building a pawn duo e4&d4. The Ruy Lopez is the perfect example of this strategy, of course.  Now, seeing that we'll answer @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  with  6.c3  , what about playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  instead? This is indeed an excellent alternative, which I seriously considered. Let's briefly discuss the difference between the two.  The simple part is that @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  Nf6  6.Re1  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  Nf6  6.c3  lead to the same position. However, @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  e5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  e5  differ considerably. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  e5  , we have the strategically complex but promising option  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.d3  , with a later queenside initiative in mind.  The capture on c6 is not as promising after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  e5  , as the move c3 is less useful and weakens our central structure. White's best @@StartBracket@@and more or less only@@EndBracket@@ way forward is  6.d4!?  , an interesting pawn sacrifice. It usually continues with  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  exd4  8.Bf4  , when White has active pieces for the pawn and enough compensation.  The conclusion is 5.c3 involves a commitment to this gambit play, while 5.Re1 is more geared towards a strategic battle. It's a tough call between these concepts, but I decided to stick with 5.Re1 for consistency reasons. We play  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  5.Re1  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.O-O  Nge7  5.Re1  , which makes the rook move look very consistent.  There is one conceptual difference, though. In the mentioned lines, we play Re1 to prepare Bf1 in reply to ...a6, as the capture on c6 had become unattractive. Here, in the  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.O-O  Bg7  5.Re1  line, we will take on c6 frequently, as it creates doubled pawns that we can exploit.  Here is an overview of Black's options. A and B are the most important by a mile, played in about 75-80% of the games. We'll also check some minor moves, as their study has enormous instructional value.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is very popular and logical.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  aims to block the center. It's Black's second most popular move.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6?  is bad due to c3&d4 - we get the full center, and Black has no counterplay  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6?  is met by  6.e5!  , which is surprisingly strong. Black's development is lagging, and we open the game quickly.  We'll check the most important options A and B now. }
5... e5
{ The only fully respectable alternative to  5...Nf6  . Black clamps down on d4 and intends to develop with Nge7 next. }
6. Bxc6
{ One of the few cases where I recommend taking on c6 when still relatively unprovoked. Why is the capture a good choice? There is no one-sentence answer because Black has two possible recaptures, and we need different plans against each. Let's discuss the two moves and see why White should keep a pull. }
6... dxc6
{ This is more reliable than  6...bxc6  . Black opens a path for the c8-bishop and increases control over the d4-square, which leads to an entirely different game than  6...bxc6  ,  when c3&d4 opens the center favourably.  We won't play in the center. Our target in the ...dxc6 pawn structure is the queenside. Depending on Black's setup, we have multiple ways of attacking this side of the board, but our main device will be a pawn break: a3&b4. We'll start with a universally useful move that we need anyway. }
7. d3
{ Now we need to consider three moves by Black. Our strategy against them is quite similar, but there are enough differences to make a split worthwhile. We want to open the queenside with a3&b4, attacking Black's weakened pawn structure.   A.  7...Ne7  is the most popular move below master level. it looks normal to develop the knight and prepare to castle, but the move has a serious drawback: the knight is passively placed on e7 and does not connect to the dark squares that will be crucial in the coming battle on the queenside.   B.  7...Qe7  covers the e-pawn and prepares ...Nf6-d7 to help cover the queenside. This move is likely the best choice for Black and the most popular on the GM level.   C.  7...Qc7  follows a similar idea, but the different queen position changes some details, compared to B.  We'll have a closer look at B now, Black's best defense. }
7... Qe7
{ This is played to cover e5 and thus prepare Nf6. Nf6 is the first step for a possible later Nd7-f8-e6-d4. }
8. a3
{ White has a wide choice here, but I still like my suggestion from the first edition. Trying to open the queenside quickly makes a logical impression. Black now usually continues development with 8...Nf6, but they may also try 8...a5 to close the queenside. After a later Bd2, we'd still be able to play for the opening on the queenside, though. }
8... Nf6
{ Black's main move by far. They prepare castling and don't try to stop our b-pawn. }
9. b4
{ Here we go. White immediately opens up the queenside. Of course, a slower course of action is also possible. }
9... O-O
{ Taking the b-pawn would be a serious concession. Black can't play  9...cxb4  10.axb4  Qxb4?  , as  11.Ba3  gives White a fantastic attack. Playing 10...Qxb4? is naive, of course. It would be better to play a sensible move like castling, but we have clearly benefited from the opening of the queenside. }
10. bxc5 Qxc5
{ Black can also play  10...Nd7  when  11.a4  Nxc5  12.Ba3  leads to the same structure. The queen capture has been the recent preference on the GM level, but White still retains a pull. }
11. a4
{ A simple threat to win the exchange, but it's not about a simple trick. Gaining space on the queenside is useful, and Ba3 may be attractive even without immediately winning material. }
11... Re8 12. Ba3
{ This looks very natural and was played successfully in 2022 by Anish Giri vs Wang Hao, but it's not clear if it is best. Stockfish also likes a setup with h3 and Be3, which looks good, too.   The mentioned game continued  12...Qa5  13.Nbd2  Be6  14.Qb1  Qc7  and now  15.Ng5  would be a small engine improvement on Giri's  15.a5  . I think that White has a nagging pull in this type of position, as Black has to defend the weakened squares, and their bishop pair doesn't count for much. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Sicilian"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... Nc6
{ Black develops their knight, the starting point of many famous Open Sicilian lines.  Nowadays, the focus has shifted from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  to the Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  , the move I recommend. White can pose problems in positions that work perfectly in the context of this course. We want to exert some pressure while following classical and easy-to-understand principles. }
3. Bb5
{ The starting move of the Rossolimo. We develop and prepare kingside castling and keep our pawn structure flexible. We'll focus on Black's most popular moves now:  3...g6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  .   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  is Black's most popular reply. We play  4.O-O  and want to build a full center with c3&d4 later.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  signals Black's intention to play ...Nge7 next and then challenge our bishop with ...a6.  Again, we play  4.O-O  and intend to occupy the center later.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  follows a similar idea as B. Black usually continues with ...Bd7 and ...a6 to attack our bishop. We react like in B: castle and prepare to play in the center later. }
3... g6
{ This chapter covers Black's most popular reply to the Rossolimo: 3...g6, preparing the kingside fianchetto. It is played in roughly 50% of all Rossolimo games and is a cornerstone of our Sicilian repertoire. }
4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1
{ I suggest playing  5.Re1  , just as I did in the first edition. There is an important difference, though. After Black's main reply,  5...Nf6  , I am now recommending  6.c3  , aiming for a full pawn center. This continuation is more in line with the general spirit of our repertoire, which emphasises building a pawn duo e4&d4. The Ruy Lopez is the perfect example of this strategy, of course.  Now, seeing that we'll answer @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  with  6.c3  , what about playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  instead? This is indeed an excellent alternative, which I seriously considered. Let's briefly discuss the difference between the two.  The simple part is that @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  Nf6  6.Re1  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  Nf6  6.c3  lead to the same position. However, @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  e5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  e5  differ considerably. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  e5  , we have the strategically complex but promising option  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.d3  , with a later queenside initiative in mind.  The capture on c6 is not as promising after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  e5  , as the move c3 is less useful and weakens our central structure. White's best @@StartBracket@@and more or less only@@EndBracket@@ way forward is  6.d4!?  , an interesting pawn sacrifice. It usually continues with  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  exd4  8.Bf4  , when White has active pieces for the pawn and enough compensation.  The conclusion is 5.c3 involves a commitment to this gambit play, while 5.Re1 is more geared towards a strategic battle. It's a tough call between these concepts, but I decided to stick with 5.Re1 for consistency reasons. We play  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  5.Re1  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.O-O  Nge7  5.Re1  , which makes the rook move look very consistent.  There is one conceptual difference, though. In the mentioned lines, we play Re1 to prepare Bf1 in reply to ...a6, as the capture on c6 had become unattractive. Here, in the  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.O-O  Bg7  5.Re1  line, we will take on c6 frequently, as it creates doubled pawns that we can exploit.  Here is an overview of Black's options. A and B are the most important by a mile, played in about 75-80% of the games. We'll also check some minor moves, as their study has enormous instructional value.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is very popular and logical.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  aims to block the center. It's Black's second most popular move.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6?  is bad due to c3&d4 - we get the full center, and Black has no counterplay  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6?  is met by  6.e5!  , which is surprisingly strong. Black's development is lagging, and we open the game quickly.  We'll check the most important options A and B now. }
5... Nf6
{ Black develops the kingside and prepares to castle. It's a very natural move and the most popular one. }
6. c3
{ In the first edition of the course I recommended  6.e5  , which remains a good option.  My main incentive to switch to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  is the conceptual consistency with the Ruy Lopez. Building a pawn center by playing c3&d4 is a logical concept here is a challenging approach for Black.  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  , Black almost always castles. The other rare idea is  6...a6  to attack our bishop. I suggest  7.Bxc6  dxc6  8.h3  O-O  9.d4  , building a solid pawn center. }
6... O-O
{ Black's almost universal choice. Castling is the most natural move in the world. We played c3 to prepare the central pawn push, so our choice is easy now. }
7. d4
{ Now we need to consider some options for Black.   A.  7...d5  is the main line and probably the best move. Black is correctly concerned about our center rolling forward, so they fight for central space.   B.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  d5  is a worse version of A, as we are happy about the trade on d4. It only helps White, as far as I can see.   C.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  and other tries than 8... d5.   D.  7...a6  8.Bxc6  dxc6  9.h3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  7.Bxc6  dxc6  8.h3  O-O  9.d4  , which is slightly better for White. Black can't deviate with  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1pppbp/p1B2np1/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...bxc6?  , as  9.e5  Nd5  10.dxc5  wins a pawn with a large advantage. }
7... d5
{ Black's main reply to consider. Black wants a foothold in the center and avoids the early trade on d4. }
8. e5
{ An important feature of our concept is the strong central pawn chain, limiting Black's bishop on g7. }
8... Ne4 9. Be3
{ We develop and attack the c-pawn, limiting Black's choice. They can take on d4 or play ...Qb6 to address our threat. An important motive to consider: Black's central knight does not have any possible retreat squares. It is not in danger of getting trapped at the moment, but the lack of retreats affects how to evaluate other moves. For instance,  9...Bg4?  makes no sense at all, as  10.h3  Bxf3??  11.gxf3!  wins the knight. }
9... Qb6
{ Black attacks our bishop. We are happy to take on c6, as both recaptures lead to favourable outcomes.  Black's alternative is  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  Qb6  , when  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.Qc1!  leads to the line we will examine in a moment. Black will probably prefer  11...Qxc6  , when  12.Nfd2  Be6  13.f3  Nxd2  14.Qxd2  Rfc8  15.Nc3  leads to a position that is slightly better for White, as Black's bishop on e6 will probably never turn into a good piece. }
10. Bxc6
{ Capturing c6 is strong and secures White some advantage. A key point to remember is our answer to  10...bxc6  , which is not an obvious move. }
10... bxc6
{ Black may also play  10...Qxc6  , but  11.dxc5  looks better for White. We gain control of the d4-square.  After the pawn capture on c6, we arrive at an important moment. We have to do something about the hanging b-pawn. }
11. Qc1
{ This is a strong move and a good moment to discuss our strategy. We have traded on c6 and given up our bishop pair. In return, we have weakened Black's queenside structure. An additional consequence is emphasised control of the dark squares. We have three minor pieces that can fight for the dark squares; Black only has two.  This concept becomes the most apparent if Black captures on d4. After @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p3ppbp/1qp3p1/2ppP3/3Pn3/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RNQ1R1K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  , the c5-square  is weak, and we can connect all minor pieces with it, while the Black's c8-bishop has no target to attack. This is a key concept. We try to prove that this bishop is operating on empty diagonals. A dream scenario after the trade on d4 would be to play with a knight on c5 against the lights-squared bishop. Let's see how our strategy unfolds.  Black's options are @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p3ppbp/1qp3p1/2ppP3/3Pn3/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RNQ1R1K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...cxd4  , @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p3ppbp/1qp3p1/2ppP3/3Pn3/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RNQ1R1K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...c4  , and @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p3ppbp/1qp3p1/2ppP3/3Pn3/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RNQ1R1K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rb8  now. It's tough to say what Black's best defense is, as they suffer a bit in all of them.  I'll look at @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p3ppbp/1qp3p1/2ppP3/3Pn3/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RNQ1R1K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...cxd4  in the Quickstarter, as these positions may also arise by different move orders @@StartBracket@@Black trading earlier on d4@@EndBracket@@. }
11... cxd4
{ Ahh, thank you! Well, you shouldn't really say 'thanks!' to your opponent in an OTB game, but they usually help us with trading on d4 - this one is no exception. }
12. cxd4
{ Black has some choice of moves, but they are nowhere near equality. It's difficult to determine what the best try is, as they all involve a bit of grovelling. The c-pawn and c5-square will not go away easily! }
12... Rb8
{ Black plays this move most of the time, particularly below master level. A closer look shows that provoking b3 might even help White, as we get control of a4 @@StartBracket@@...a5-a4 is a plan for Black@@EndBracket@@ and get the Qa3 idea for free.   An alternative is  12...a5  , but White is in good shape after  13.Nc3  Nxc3  14.Qxc3  , as the weaknesses remain on the board. }
13. b3
{ Forced, but it is a good move. I want to check the move 13...f6 now, as it leads to more direct play. }
13... f6
{ Black attacks our center and wants to find some use for the bishop.   As usual,  13...Bg4?  14.h3  is bad, while @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/p3ppbp/1qp3p1/3pP3/3Pn3/1P2BN2/P4PPP/RNQ1R1K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...a5  14.Nc3  Nxc3  15.Qxc3  is the comfortable edge we want. }
14. Nc3
{ Finally, the knight joins it to either trade Black's best piece or jump to a4. }
14... Bf5
{ Black keeps it complicated. After  14...Nxc3  15.Qxc3  Bg4  16.exf6  exf6  17.Bf4  ,  we are better in a one-sided position. Black has weaknesses, and we have the potential to invade. The idea Bd6-c5 comes to mind. }
15. Na4
{ This looks best, aiming at the c5-square. After  15...Qa5  I suggest  16.exf6  exf6  17.Nd2  ,  trading Black's best piece and clearing the way to c5. Our central control is more than enough to offset Black's bishop pair. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Sicilian"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Nd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... d6
{ Black's most popular move is 2...d6, hoping for a Najdorf or Dragon... no such luck, we won't comply! }
3. Bb5+
{ We go for the Moscow Variation, White's most interesting option, if you want to avoid the Open Sicilian and still reach a complex middlegame.  Black has three possible answers, but we'll cover  3...Nc6  via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  d6  , which is the more common one. The answers @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bd7  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd7  lead to different middlegame types. We'll discuss the strategies once the moves are on the board. }
3... Nd7
{ I am keeping my repertoire suggestion from the first edition of Keep It Simple: 1.e4 because it fits perfectly with the new choice of the Ruy Lopez. The move 4.c3 strives to build the perfect pawn center with d4 next, very much in the spirit of our Ruy Lopez repertoire. }
4. c3
{ Against 3...Nd7, White has a wide range of options. I looked at them in-depth, trying to determine if I should change my current recommendation. There are some interesting ideas, but I preferred the strategic clarity of 4.c3 in the end.  Black has two main options now that will often lead to the same lines. They can start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ngf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  , immediately attacking our e-pawn or our bishop. These moves are the most logical, for sure. At some point, Black needs to decide how to develop the kingside: ...e6, ...e5 or ...g6 come to mind.  We'll examine these options at various moments on the next moves, and there are some possible transpositions. Our job is quite easy, though. We play natural moves and can get by with some general principles. Let's continue. }
4... Nf6
{ 'Knights out first' is one of the general rules you should always take with a grain of salt. However, there often is a strong logic to it. Here it's fairly clear that Black's knight is best on f6, so it makes sense to place it there first with a tempo on our e-pawn.   Black has the alternative  4...a6  , when  5.Ba4  b5  6.Bc2  is likely to transpose to our main lines later. }
5. Qe2
{ Black attacked the pawn, and we cover it.  How does it continue now? Black has to decide on the kingside development. The three options are ...g6, ...e6 and ...e5. The main question is when to decide on one of them.  Black could play one of them right now, after 5.Qe2. This is rarely played and is imprecise. We play d4 quickly and can retreat our bishop to d3, which saves a bit of time compared to the more common b5-a4-c2 route. A sample line is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  6.d4  when we are ready to play Bd3 in response to ...a6.  Most of the time, Black expands on the queenside first. }
5... a6
{ Black gains time for their queenside expansion, a logical move and Black's most popular choice. }
6. Ba4
{ After this automatic move, Black's most obvious and popular move is  6...b5  , expanding with a tempo gain.   It is not the only move, though. Black can delay ...b5, but often will play the move soon enough and will transpose to lines that we'll examine via 6...b5 in a moment. }
6... b5 { Black hits our bishop and prepares ...Bb7, very natural play. } 7.
Bc2
{ Now Black most of the time plays  7...Bb7  , which certainly looks very logical.  There is an important alternative in @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  , though. It's important to note that Black should play ...e5 now and not delay it with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb7  8.d4  e5  , because  9.d5!  is great for White.  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  8.d4  , we'll reach a position similar to a Ruy Lopez. We'll castle next and play a4 soon, trying to provoke a weakness on the queenside. }
7... Bb7
{ Black emphasises the queenside development and only wants to commit to a central pawn formation on the next move. }
8. d4
{ We have arrived at an important crossroads. Black needs to decide how to develop the kingside. We'll consider the following options now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6  is a popular and sound way for Black to play. It's the line I will examine here in the Quickstarter.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...g6  is seen less often but was recommended by Anish Giri in his Najdorf course. It can lead to sharp play, but it's our call to tackle this line - sharp or more strategically focused. I suggest  9.O-O  Bg7  10.Rd1  , a solid approach.  C. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  is frequently seen but has little independent value, as often Black will play ...e6 or ...g6 soon to get to positions similar to A or B.   D. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e5?!  is dubious due to  9.d5!  , when we transpose to a favourable line that we examine via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  8.d4  Bb7  9.d5  , an alternative move order. }
8... e6
{ Black goes for 8...e6, which would probably be the move I'd play with the black pieces. They keep the tension and avoid possible problems related to e4-e5-e6, which is a factor in the ...g6-based system.  While I appreciate Black's approach, I don't think White has anything to complain about. We'll reach an interesting middlegame with all pieces and pawns on the board. }
9. O-O { We'll castle first and then decide how to proceed. } 9... Be7
{ Black prepares castling, too. Now we are at an important crossroads, as White has to decide on further plans. It looks to me that White has a range of options roughly of the same quality, so taste plays a role, for sure. }
10. Re1
{ I suggest this move, which is still not too committal. The main idea is twofold: we lend some additional protection to e4 and clear f1 for the knight tour Nd2-f1-g3 later. Our queenside is not developed, and the knight transfer to g3 is a standard idea, well-known from the Ruy Lopez.   As mentioned, White has some possible alternatives here. Some notes:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Rd1  is less precise than @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Re1  , I think. There is little chance the rook is doing anything useful on this file. On e1, it protects e4. If you like to prepare for the knight tour,  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Re1  looks better to me.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.a4  is a different idea that I like more. If you want to investigate an alternative to 10. Re1, this is the one I'd go for. }
10... O-O
{ Or Black plays  10...Qc7  here, when you need to be aware of the threat ...cxd4 - we want to recapture with our c-pawn, so  11.Bd3!  must be played. We'll see the same idea again in a moment. }
11. Nbd2 Qc7
{ Attention: Black now wants to take on d4 - we need to ensure that we can recapture with our pawn. }
12. Bd3
{ We remove the bishop from the c-file. This ensures that we'll always be able to keep the center intact.   The move  12.Nf1  is possible, but we'll likely need to move the bishop at some point.   After  12.Bd3  , there are loads of possibilities for both sides. You can't analyze it like a position dependent on concrete tactics. I want to show some ideas to give you a better idea of what's going on.  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqnbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2PB1N2/PP1NQPPP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12...e5  can be answered by  13.d5  c4  14.Bc2  , with a slow, manoeuvring fight. This is not a great version of this structure, though. We have lost a lot of time with our bishop, which helps Black. I prefer a different idea.  After @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqnbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2PB1N2/PP1NQPPP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12...e5  I suggest  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.c4!  , which leads to a pawn structure change. Now  14...b4  15.Nf1  is the idea, transferring the knight to d5 via e3. This leads to an interesting strategic struggle, as we are quicker to use the d5-square.   B. Black can play @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqnbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2PB1N2/PP1NQPPP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12...cxd4  13.cxd4  e5  when we have the choice between advancing the d-pawn and keeping the tension. I'd suggest  14.b3  exd4  15.Bb2  , when we regain the pawn quickly.  C. Black can keep the tension and don't change the pawn structure. There are many possible moves to do that, of course. An idea that I like is @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqnbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2PB1N2/PP1NQPPP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfc8  and now  13.a3!?  , which has the idea to play b4 at the right moment. A sample line for this point is  13...cxd4  14.cxd4  e5  15.b4  , which looks interesting. We fix the black queenside pawns on light squares and gain the b3-square for our knight. This line leads to equal chances and interesting positions to play.   The key point is that the slow nature of the game, often in the style of the Ruy Lopez, might not be the forte of many Sicilian players. This makes our choice a good practical weapon, in my mind. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Sicilian"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Bd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... d6
{ Black's most popular move is 2...d6, hoping for a Najdorf or Dragon... no such luck, we won't comply! }
3. Bb5+
{ We go for the Moscow Variation, White's most interesting option, if you want to avoid the Open Sicilian and still reach a complex middlegame.  Black has three possible answers, but we'll cover  3...Nc6  via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  d6  , which is the more common one. The answers @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bd7  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd7  lead to different middlegame types. We'll discuss the strategies once the moves are on the board. }
3... Bd7 { Black interposes with the bishop, their most popular move. } 4.
Bxd7+
{ This is the main move and is still my recommendation.  For the second edition, I also considered switching to  4.c4  , but ultimately decided to stick with my old move. My main issue about  4.c4  is that some of the arising positions are difficult to understand. I also felt that the theoretical state of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1bpppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxd7+  is fine, and I found some interesting, new ideas to present. Let's get to work.  Black has two moves after our capture, leading to different scenarios:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd7  is the main line and answered by  5.c4  when we play for the Maroczy Bind after a later d2-d4. After the queen's capture, we immediately know what pawn formation we reach.   B. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd7  is a different story. In this line, being more flexible is best. My recommendations after the knight capture differ significantly from the first edition, much more than in line A. }
4... Nxd7
{ Black takes with the knight, which leads to different positions than the queen recapture. The key point is that we shouldn't commit to a pawn formation quickly - more on this topic after our next move. }
5. O-O
{ We start with kingside castling, a move we'll need anyway. Castling early is often imprecise in the 4...Qxd7 complex because White needs any tempo available to build a well-protected center.  Here, after the knight capture, it is clear that Black will have less immediate pressure on our center, as the knight on d7 is not as active at the moment.   Would it be possible to start with  5.c4  here, though? That would be consistent with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd7  5.c4  , but there is a drawback. I'm not too fond of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd7  5.c4  Ne5  , or @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ngf6  6.Nc3  Ne5  - looks odd but seems fine for Black.  There is an additional incentive for castling first: we might have better options than the Maroczy Bind setup in some cases. Let's have a look. }
5... Ngf6
{ Black plays this move almost all the time, and only on the next move decides if they want to play with ...e6 or ...g6. It's possible to start with one of the pawn moves and play ...Ngf6 later, of course.   A key point to remember is that we want to answer ...g6-based setups with c3&d4, building a perfect pawn center. That would happen after @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  6.c3!  Bg7  7.d4  , when White has a comfortable game, based on the strong center. }
6. Qe2
{ This looks like the most promising setup. Our e-pawn needed protection, which limited our choice.  We don't want to commit our d-pawn with  6.d3  or block the c-pawn by going  6.Nc3  .  This leaves  6.Re1  or our choice, the queen move.  6.Re1  is not bad, but I prefer the queen move because it gives us more flexibility regarding the later rook placement. We will also see that pushing the e-pawn is better supported by the queen, if Black opts for ...g6.   Now we'll examine the two most popular moves in detail:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  is Black's most popular move. Compared to the first edition, I have a new and interesting suggestion against it.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  is also frequently played but makes our task easier. After  7.c3!  we manage to build a strong center, and Black needs to be careful to avoid serious trouble.  Some words about other options:  C. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e5?!  is a bad idea. We are better after  7.c3  , intending d4,  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1n1ppp/3p1n2/2p1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq e6 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c4  , when we reach a much better version of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd7  5.c4  e5  - Black's knight is misplaced on d7. We'll examine a similar scenario in line A when Black can opt for ...e5 some moves later.   D. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Rc8  is a good waiting move. Black does not yet commit to a central pawn formation but mostly aims for a ...g6 setup under better circumstances than option B. One example would be  7.c4  , when  7...g6  is better than on move 6, as c3&d4 is out of the window. Now it is interesting to see that  8.Nc3  Bg7  9.d4?!  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Qa5  gives Black good counterplay against White's queenside. I think a good and easy-to-play solution is @@StartFEN@@2rqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1PQPPP/R1B2RK1 w k - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.d3  when we aim for the plan Bd2, Rb1 and b4 to open the queenside. We also play a setup based on c4 and d3 in line A. This is a similar idea. }
6... e6
{ This setup, based on ...e6, is Black's most popular one. Black aims for flexible development and waits for our decision on how to play in the center.Against an early d4, they want to capture the pawn and start counterplay on the c-file, the standard Sicilian Defense idea.If White prepares d4 with c3, aiming for the full pawn center, Black is ready to play a well-timed ...d5 break. This changes the pawn structure and gives it a French flavour. Black has already traded their c8-bishop, though, which helps a lot. I am not a fan of playing c3&d4 if Black has this option.  How do we continue? }
7. b3
{ I have changed my recommendation from the first edition. My original suggestion was  7.d4  , but I see a practical problem with this move. After  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  we intend to play a quick c4, establishing a Maroczy Bind. This is possible, but Black has many move orders to choose from and may start a direct counterplay against c4. A sample line is  8...Be7  9.c4  and now  9...Qa5  ,  which I didn't consider in the first edition. Black wants to play ...Rc8/...Qb4/...Ne5 in various combinations. I don't think White is in trouble here, but playing this setup is more difficult than I previously thought.   I wondered if White has any alternatives and noticed that @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1n1ppp/3ppn2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.b3  is a popular option which is much easier to handle, in my mind. We actively develop the bishop to b2 and still retain the option to play for a Maroczy-style center with a later c4&d4. We'll see that we have more ideas, though - hang on. }
7... Be7
{ Black prepares to castle, and we complete our fianchetto, very natural play. }
8. Bb2 O-O
{ Now we need to commit to a central pawn structure, at least partially. } 9.
c4
{ This looks best to me. We gain some influence in the center and keep the option to play d2-d4 to play for a Maroczy Bind.  This general concept, however, can be difficult to realise against a cunning opponent. It's Black to move now, and they have a wide choice. In SOME cases, not all of them, they can meet our d4 break with ...d5!, a strong counterpunch. Two examples are @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Rc8  10.d4  d5!  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Re8  10.d4  d5!  , when Black gets equal chances and manages to trade lots of material.  I'm not too fond of these lines - we need a different idea against these moves. Black does not play the rook moves all of the time, though. They regularly go for @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...a6  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  , for example. Quite shockingly, even after @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  10.d4  d5!?  is possible, as  11.exd5  exd5  12.Qxe7??  Rfe8  traps our queen! I think you already suspect what I am getting at.   Black has many moves, and the various versions of White's d4 being met with ...d5 are confusing! After studying the lines more, I realised that White has a fundamentally different approach in this position: you don't need to play the move d2-d4 but can opt for a slow setup involving the moves Nc3 and d3. The later plan is moving the f3-knight and going for f2-f4. The charm of this setup is that it works well, regardless of Black's move order!   I will examine two moves now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Rc8  to demonstrate the Nc3/d3 plan - it also works against other, non-committal moves like  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...a6  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Re8  - more on that in the notes.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...e5  is an entirely different approach that I want to check. Black sometimes goes for this central block to stop d2-d4 completely. We didn't intend this move @@StartBracket@@line A@@EndBracket@@, but Black might still want to avoid it. I suggest playing the knight tour Nf3-e1-c2-e3 against it, focusing on the d5-square. The pawn break f2-f4 is part of our plan, too. }
9... Rc8
{ The slow plan I am suggesting works against this move. But it is also possible against the other 'small moves, like  9...a6  or  9...Re8  . Black will often combine them in various orders. }
10. d3
{ We go for the slow setup I described earlier. The idea is to complete development with Nc3 next and then aim for Ne1/d2 and f4. }
10... a6 11. Nc3
{ I think that playing  11.Nbd2  here also looks fine. There is room for creativity here, as there is no direct contact between both sides' forces.  One important point to mention is that Black can't do much to change the pawn structure, which gives us the time to play in a relatively slow fashion. For example, they can't easily play ...d5, as we have the strong reply e4-e5. }
11... Qa5
{ This move was recently played @@StartBracket@@2022@@EndBracket@@ by top Indian GM Vidit in an online game against GM Swiercz. Black prepares ...b5 this way.   There are many alternatives for Black, of course. An interesting one is  11...Ne5  , when  12.Nxe5  dxe5  13.f4  exf4  14.Rxf4  Nd7  15.e5!  @@StartBracket@@stopping ...Bf6@@EndBracket@@ looks best and slightly better for White. We have a large space advantage and easy improvements like Ne4 and Raf1 to pile up on the f-file. Black likely needs to play ...f6, which creates some weaknesses. If Black plays further waiting moves, going for the Nd2&f4 plan looks promising. }
12. Nd2
{ We prepare f4, which gains lots of space. Now Black needs to be quite careful. }
12... b5
{ This is - surprisingly - a mistake.   Black should play  12...Ne5  13.f4  Nc6  14.Nf3  , when I prefer White, but Black's chances are not significantly worse. One idea for White is playing e4-e5 to clear the e4-square for our knight. This may quickly turn into a dangerous attack, as most of our pieces point to Black's kingside. }
13. f4
{ It turns out that playing ...b5 didn't help Black much to get counterplay. Taking on c4 nets nothing and advancing the pawn further closes the queenside.   The game Swiercz-Vidit continued with  13...b4  14.Nd1  Qc7  15.Ne3  a5  16.g4  , when White had a strong and probably winning attack. He later spoiled the game @@StartBracket@@it was blitz@@EndBracket@@ but had his strong opponent on the ropes. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Sicilian"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Bd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... d6
{ Black's most popular move is 2...d6, hoping for a Najdorf or Dragon... no such luck, we won't comply! }
3. Bb5+
{ We go for the Moscow Variation, White's most interesting option, if you want to avoid the Open Sicilian and still reach a complex middlegame.  Black has three possible answers, but we'll cover  3...Nc6  via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  d6  , which is the more common one. The answers @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bd7  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd7  lead to different middlegame types. We'll discuss the strategies once the moves are on the board. }
3... Bd7 { Black interposes with the bishop, their most popular move. } 4.
Bxd7+
{ This is the main move and is still my recommendation.  For the second edition, I also considered switching to  4.c4  , but ultimately decided to stick with my old move. My main issue about  4.c4  is that some of the arising positions are difficult to understand. I also felt that the theoretical state of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1bpppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxd7+  is fine, and I found some interesting, new ideas to present. Let's get to work.  Black has two moves after our capture, leading to different scenarios:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd7  is the main line and answered by  5.c4  when we play for the Maroczy Bind after a later d2-d4. After the queen's capture, we immediately know what pawn formation we reach.   B. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd7  is a different story. In this line, being more flexible is best. My recommendations after the knight capture differ significantly from the first edition, much more than in line A. }
4... Qxd7
{ This move signals that Black will play ...Nc6 most of the time to emphasise control over d4. This is most often combined with a kingside fianchetto. }
5. c4
{ A strategically very sound choice. White places his pawns on light squares after this bishop has been traded off. We are aiming for a Maroczy Bind structure, giving White comfortable control.  What options and moves does Black have now? A key decision is about the future of the f8-bishop.  Plan A: Black can aim for a kingside fianchetto and play ...g6 soon. A typical sequence could be @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  g6  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  , both occur frequently.   Plan B:  Our opponent can develop the bishop to e7 after playing ...e6. A sample line for this approach would be  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  e6  , but they may also start with  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  e6  .   Plan C:  Black may keep the center closed by playing a quick ...e5. This could happen after  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  , when we reach this structure.  These are the three basic concepts that Black usually chooses from. I have ranked them in order of popularity; Plan A is the most popular, followed by B and C. The distribution is roughly 60%, 20% and 10%.  What is the remaining 10%? Besides downright strange moves, there are some more concrete ideas that Black can try. In the Quickstarter, I will look closely at A and B, as these are most likely to appear in your games. I'll mention an example when we look at move orders. Let's discuss concrete move orders and what happens now on move 5.  The first point to realise is that for Plan A and B, Black will develop their g8-knight to f6. No scenario in which playing the knight elsewhere would make any sense. On the other hand, it is not clear if Black always wants to play ...Nc6 soon. It's certainly a natural square for the knight, but there is less urgency to decide the knight's fate. Black can easily delay this decision and complete the kingside formation first. We'll see that this is a viable and interesting strategy for Black.  This leads to the conclusion that the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the most flexible for Black, as they start with the knight move that has to be played anyway. This is also the reason why @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is my choice as the main move order in the following lines. With this starting move, we can examine all lines that combine ...Nf6 and ...Nc6, but also the move orders that omit or delay ...Nc6 for a while.  In practice, the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  is even considerably more popular than @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , but Black will almost always play ...Nf6 quickly afterwards to transpose. This leads to the following moves and structure:  1. The move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is our main move to consider when Black goes for Plan A or B.  2. I will check @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  to demonstrate the transpositions to other lines. There are no good independent options that Black has.  3. Black can play @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  @@EndBracket@@ to employ Plan C.  4. Black may play the dubious @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qg4?!  , when  6.O-O  Qxe4  7.d4  gives us fantastic compensation for the pawn. }
5... Nf6
{ This is the most popular move on the top level nowadays. There are some concrete lines where delaying ...Nc6 is relevant, as an early ...Rf8-c8 will attack the c4-pawn. More about that later. }
6. Nc3
{ We need to cover our pawn, of course. What next? We'll now check the following moves:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , which commits to plan A as described in the notes to move  5.  B. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@6...e6  , deciding for plan B.  Black can also play @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  , when  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  or @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/8/2PNP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6  would transpose to A or B.  In the full chapter, we also check rare options for Black, like @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/2p5/2PPP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qg4  8.d5!  and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/2p5/2PPP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Qg4  9.Qxg4  Nxg4  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Ke2  , which are slightly better for White. }
6... e6
{ Black chooses to develop the bishop to e7, setting up a pawn formation with both d6 and e6 being played, very typical of many open Sicilian lines like the Scheveningen Variation. }
7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ Note that ...e6 and ...Be7 look more passive than ....g6 and ...Bg7, but there is a very significant upside: Black controls d5, so the white knight is not coming to d5. In g6 formations, this is always an idea. Black can't easily kick it away with a later ....e6 as this weakens d6 considerably. }
8... Nc6
{ Black usually develops the knight to c6, but they can aim for ...Nbd7, too. This takes a few moves @@StartBracket@@...a6, ...Qc7@@EndBracket@@ to implement, though. You can wonder why they started with 4...Qxd7 if this type of setup was their intention.  It makes no difference to us, as our setup is the same as against ...Nc6-based formations. Here's a sample sequence: @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1q1ppp/3ppn2/8/2PNP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Qe2  a6  11.Be3  Qc7  12.Rad1  , with the same formation we apply against an early ...Nc6. }
9. O-O Be7 10. Be3
{ 10.b3  is a good alternative, but I prefer to cover d4 with Be3. This allows a setup with Qe2 and Rad1, which looks harmonious. }
10... O-O 11. Qe2 a6 12. Rad1
{ Very natural play. Black will lose some time with the queen, leaving the d-file. }
12... Qc7 13. f4
{ A good move to control more space, but it also prevents a possible ...Ne5 idea to attack our c-pawn. White is slightly better here, but Black's position is quite solid.   It is not helpful to analyse this type of position deeply, as it is more about knowing some ideas. Here are some lines to illustrate them.  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1bppp/p1nppn2/8/2PNPP2/2N1B3/PP2Q1PP/3R1RK1 b - f3 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Na5?  is bad, as  14.b3  b5  runs into  15.f5!  , a typical idea. We push the f-pawn forward to put pressure on e6. If Black moves the e-pawn, we gain control of d5.  Here  15...e5  16.Nc2  bxc4  17.Nb4  is fantastic for White.  B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1bppp/p1nppn2/8/2PNPP2/2N1B3/PP2Q1PP/3R1RK1 b - f3 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rac8  14.b3  Nxd4  15.Bxd4  e5  16.fxe5  dxe5  17.Be3  b5  18.Nd5  Nxd5  19.cxd5  is slightly better for White due to the strong d5-pawn. You must be aware of Black's ...b5 idea and need a good reply. Here Nd5 works well.   C. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1bppp/p1nppn2/8/2PNPP2/2N1B3/PP2Q1PP/3R1RK1 b - f3 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rac8  14.b3  Qa5  15.Nxc6  Rxc6  16.Bd4  e5  17.Nd5!  is another noteworthy idea. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Sicilian"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Bd7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter for the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played.  I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  What do we cover in the Quickstarter? I focus on the most important lines and ideas you need to know. Therefore, I decided to skip minor options for Black on the second move and focus on Black's most popular replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  -  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , played in about 90% of the games.  Black lesser options are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's check how to fight the Sicilian main lines now. }
2. Nf3
{ After 2.Nf3 Black has a long list of moves, but  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  are the main options and the focus of our Quickstarter. }
2... d6
{ Black's most popular move is 2...d6, hoping for a Najdorf or Dragon... no such luck, we won't comply! }
3. Bb5+
{ We go for the Moscow Variation, White's most interesting option, if you want to avoid the Open Sicilian and still reach a complex middlegame.  Black has three possible answers, but we'll cover  3...Nc6  via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  d6  , which is the more common one. The answers @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bd7  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd7  lead to different middlegame types. We'll discuss the strategies once the moves are on the board. }
3... Bd7 { Black interposes with the bishop, their most popular move. } 4.
Bxd7+
{ This is the main move and is still my recommendation.  For the second edition, I also considered switching to  4.c4  , but ultimately decided to stick with my old move. My main issue about  4.c4  is that some of the arising positions are difficult to understand. I also felt that the theoretical state of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1bpppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxd7+  is fine, and I found some interesting, new ideas to present. Let's get to work.  Black has two moves after our capture, leading to different scenarios:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd7  is the main line and answered by  5.c4  when we play for the Maroczy Bind after a later d2-d4. After the queen's capture, we immediately know what pawn formation we reach.   B. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd7  is a different story. In this line, being more flexible is best. My recommendations after the knight capture differ significantly from the first edition, much more than in line A. }
4... Qxd7
{ This move signals that Black will play ...Nc6 most of the time to emphasise control over d4. This is most often combined with a kingside fianchetto. }
5. c4
{ A strategically very sound choice. White places his pawns on light squares after this bishop has been traded off. We are aiming for a Maroczy Bind structure, giving White comfortable control.  What options and moves does Black have now? A key decision is about the future of the f8-bishop.  Plan A: Black can aim for a kingside fianchetto and play ...g6 soon. A typical sequence could be @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  g6  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  , both occur frequently.   Plan B:  Our opponent can develop the bishop to e7 after playing ...e6. A sample line for this approach would be  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  e6  , but they may also start with  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  e6  .   Plan C:  Black may keep the center closed by playing a quick ...e5. This could happen after  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  , when we reach this structure.  These are the three basic concepts that Black usually chooses from. I have ranked them in order of popularity; Plan A is the most popular, followed by B and C. The distribution is roughly 60%, 20% and 10%.  What is the remaining 10%? Besides downright strange moves, there are some more concrete ideas that Black can try. In the Quickstarter, I will look closely at A and B, as these are most likely to appear in your games. I'll mention an example when we look at move orders. Let's discuss concrete move orders and what happens now on move 5.  The first point to realise is that for Plan A and B, Black will develop their g8-knight to f6. No scenario in which playing the knight elsewhere would make any sense. On the other hand, it is not clear if Black always wants to play ...Nc6 soon. It's certainly a natural square for the knight, but there is less urgency to decide the knight's fate. Black can easily delay this decision and complete the kingside formation first. We'll see that this is a viable and interesting strategy for Black.  This leads to the conclusion that the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the most flexible for Black, as they start with the knight move that has to be played anyway. This is also the reason why @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is my choice as the main move order in the following lines. With this starting move, we can examine all lines that combine ...Nf6 and ...Nc6, but also the move orders that omit or delay ...Nc6 for a while.  In practice, the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  is even considerably more popular than @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , but Black will almost always play ...Nf6 quickly afterwards to transpose. This leads to the following moves and structure:  1. The move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is our main move to consider when Black goes for Plan A or B.  2. I will check @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  to demonstrate the transpositions to other lines. There are no good independent options that Black has.  3. Black can play @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  @@EndBracket@@ to employ Plan C.  4. Black may play the dubious @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qg4?!  , when  6.O-O  Qxe4  7.d4  gives us fantastic compensation for the pawn. }
5... Nf6
{ This is the most popular move on the top level nowadays. There are some concrete lines where delaying ...Nc6 is relevant, as an early ...Rf8-c8 will attack the c4-pawn. More about that later. }
6. Nc3
{ We need to cover our pawn, of course. What next? We'll now check the following moves:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , which commits to plan A as described in the notes to move  5.  B. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@6...e6  , deciding for plan B.  Black can also play @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  , when  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  or @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/8/2PNP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6  would transpose to A or B.  In the full chapter, we also check rare options for Black, like @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/2p5/2PPP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qg4  8.d5!  and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/2p5/2PPP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Qg4  9.Qxg4  Nxg4  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Ke2  , which are slightly better for White. }
6... g6 { The kingside fianchetto is by far Black's most popular option. } 7.
d4
{ It is crucial to play this move right away before castling.   After  7.O-O  Nc6  8.d4  cxd4  9.Nxd4  Bg7  Black's pressure on White's center more or less forces the move  10.Nde2  , retreating the knight.   By playing the immediate  7.d4  , we will be ready to support our center in time to avoid the retreat and keep our knight on d4. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ Now Black has the choice between delaying the move ...Nc6 or for a while or playing it now.   The position after  8...Nc6  frequently arises, as it may easily occur via other move orders. The sequences @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  and @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  , all lead to the same position.  These various move orders don't make things complicated, by the way. We always play 6.Nc3 and 7.d4  , unless Black stops us with ...e5 first. }
8... Nc6
{ Black can start with  8...Bg7  , when the right move order for us is  9.f3!  O-O  10.Be3  , when we'll often transpose to 8...Nc6 later. One example is  10...Rc8  11.b3  a6  12.Qd3  Nc6  13.O-O  , which we will check in a moment.   It is crucial to understand that we must start with f3 and Be3 and delay kingside castling. The same applies to @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpp1p/3p1np1/8/2PNP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nc6  9.f3!  , which we'll discuss now. }
9. f3
{ This is an important move order detail! We want to play Be3 and f3 to support the center anyway, but it is important to start with this immediately and not waste a tempo on castling.   After  9.O-O?!  Bg7  Black threatens ...Nxe4! and it is too late to play f3. }
9... Bg7
{ Black is increasing the pressure on d4 and now threatens ...Nxe4!, which prompts our prepared reply. }
10. Be3
{ We need to lend some protection to the knight and develop the bishop to the most natural square. Both sides have prioritised the fight for central control - now it's time to castle. }
10... O-O 11. O-O
{ It isn't easy to analyse these positions on a move-by-move basis. Black has different rook setups @@StartBracket@@...Rfc8, ...Rac8+...Rad8@@EndBracket@@ and moves like ...a6 and ...Qd8-a5, which they can play in various move orders.  White is happy to consolidate the space advantage and prevent the pawn breaks like ...b7-b5 or be ready for ...e7-e6 and ...d6-d5 by Black. We will centralise and often base our play on the knight coming to d5. This will be a key idea for changing the pawn structure.  The Maroczy center is generally regarded as slightly favourable for White, but it requires patience, building up slowly. It is important to note that the play is quite strategic and slow.  It is a type of position that, in many cases, the Black player did not intend to reach when he learned his main line Open Sicilian theory. Defending the black side of the Maroczy is quite different to a Dragon or Najdorf main line.   Black has many possible moves now, as there are various ways to place the rooks. Against  11...Rac8  or @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rfc8  , we play b3 and Qd2 next, supporting our center. The rook moves are popular, but  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a6  looks like Black's best bet. They don't commit a rook but play the preparation move for the pawn break ...b5 first. We'll focus on this move, as we need to be more cunning against it. }
11... a6
{ Against this move, we need to be precise. Black has the simple idea of taking on d4 and then going ...b7-b5 immediately. }
12. Qd3
{ This is not a very common square for the queen, but it is most important to keep an eye on b5, thus preventing the b-pawn push.   Note that  12.Qe2?  fails to  12...Nxe4  , when everything falls apart.   After  12.Qd3  Black has some options that we need to check:  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Ne5  looks logical, but is better for White based on a timely knight jump to  d5  . We will check this important idea in a moment.  B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfc8  looks like the best line for Black, going for a quick ...b5 push. After  13.b3  Ne5  14.Qe2  b5  15.Nd5  , we might transpose to A, but @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 w - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.b3  b5  is interesting for Black.  14.cxb5  Ne5  15.Qd2  d5  is the tactical point. After  16.Nc6  Nxc6  17.bxc6  Rxc6  18.e5  , we reach an interesting position with about equal chances.  In the full chapter, I also examine  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rac8  and @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rab8  to demonstrate more concepts and ideas of the Maroczy Bind. }
12... Ne5
{ A very natural move, hitting our queen. A closer look shows, however, that White retains a nice advantage. }
13. Qe2
{ A forced retreat - we need to keep c4 covered.   Now Black can try both rook moves to c8, attacking our pawn again. I'll cover @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p2p1np1/4n3/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP2Q1PP/R4RK1 b - - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rfc8  because the positions after it could also arise via @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfc8  13.b3  Ne5  14.Qe2  , leading to the same position.  Of course, @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p2p1np1/4n3/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP2Q1PP/R4RK1 b - - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rac8  is also possible, but the key idea  14.b3  b5  15.Nd5!  is the same as after the other rook move. }
13... Rfc8 14. b3 b5 15. Nd5
{ An important resource. The knight jumps to d5, threatening Nb6. White retains a pull now, as the following lines show:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/3qppbp/p2p1np1/1p1Nn3/2PNP3/1P2BP2/P3Q1PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Nxd5  16.cxd5  is very nice for White. Black always has to watch out for our knight jumping to c6. They can play ...e6 to get rid of the d5-pawn, which creates pawn weaknesses in the center.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/3qppbp/p2p1np1/1p1Nn3/2PNP3/1P2BP2/P3Q1PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Rab8  16.cxb5  axb5  17.Rac1  Rc5  18.Nb4  also exerts lots of pressure on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide to the French Defense and the Caro-Kann.  The French Defense 1.e4 e6 and the Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 are frequently played on all levels and rank third and fourth in popularity charts - usually, the French is slightly ahead. Still, on the master level, the Caro-Kann is a more popular opening. Let's examine how we approach these defenses. }
1... c6
{ The Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 is a popular defense on all levels of play, from amateur to GM. Depending on the parameters, it ranks in third or fourth place and should appear in 10% of your games, a bit more if you play higher-level opposition.  How to battle the Caro-Kann? In the first edition of the course, I suggested the Two Knights variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  d5  3.Nf3  - a choice that I still like from a theoretical point of view.  However, for this course, I suggest a different line. Why the change? In December 2021, I released Keep It Simple for Black. My suggestion for Black is the Caro-Kann. For this course, I needed to check all White's tries and find antidotes for them. This drew my attention to the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann, which proved far more difficult to handle for Black than I expected. In addition, White's concepts are easy to learn and employ. These aspects make it an ideal weapon for a KIS repertoire with White.  The Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann leads to a non-symmetrical pawn structure. This is an important difference to openings like the French Exchange or Slav Exchange, which have a drawish reputation. The open files can be a chopping block for the pieces, leading to simplifications and less exciting games.  In the Caro-Kann Exchange, there is no open file. The pawn structure, which we determine from the very start, features some key elements.  We have no problems developing our pieces on active squares and can usually play a similar setup. We play Bd3, c3, Nf3, h3, O-O and Re1 in the majority of the lines.Black's development is not that simple: by playing Bd3 and h3 early, we stop any ...Bg4 ideas.Black often decides to play ...g6, preparing ...Bf5. This makes sense, as ...Bg4 is impossible. The move ...g6 has significant drawbacks, though.  We will discuss these strategies in more detail once these positional features are on the board. }
2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ We develop our bishop to its most active square and stop ...Bf5 simultaneously. In most games, the next moves are  4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  when I suggest playing  6.h3  , again preventing Black's bishop development.  It is difficult to devise something entirely different, as developing the two knights to their natural squares makes a lot of sense. In many cases, Black might start a bit differently on the first moves but then plays both knight moves after all. }
4... Nc6
{ In most cases, Black starts with this knight move. It looks like a natural choice, as you can hardly imagine a scenario where developing it to d7, let alone a6, would make any sense. }
5. c3
{ It's important to play this move and avoid  5.Nf3  Bg4!  , when Black solves a key issue immediately. Black should work harder to get their bishop developed!  Now we have to consider different options for Black.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the main line by a mile. We play  6.h3  against it and stop Black's idea ...Bg4 in its tracks. The main line is discussed in a dedicated chapter. Black has some alternatives with independent value. Some might still transpose to the main line because a later ...Nf6 is a natural move.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  looks a bit passive but has some points if Black plays correctly afterwards.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qc7  is Black's most important alternative. They prevent Bf4 and hope to develop the c8-bishop later. After  6.h3  , Black will usually play  6...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , when we'll end up in the main line, after all.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  prepares the fianchetto and the move ...Bf5, a common idea in the Exchange Caro-Kann. This move will often transpose to the main line after a later ...Nf6.  We will check 5...e6 and 5...Nf6 now. }
5... e6
{ Black locks in the c8-bishop, which is not in the spirit of the Caro-Kann, you might think.  However, in recent years this move has received some attention, as the setup involving ...Bd6 and ...Nge7 looks reasonable for Black. They have some control of the e5-square and might even play ...f6 at some point, stopping any ideas we may have about playing our knight to the attractive square e5.  Let's examine how to play against this approach. }
6. Nf3
{ I suggest continuing with our kingside development. The setup Nf3, O-O and Re1 is a common sight in our line. If in doubt, go for this setup. }
6... Bd6 7. O-O Nge7
{ This setup is the most interesting for Black and the reason why 5...e6 has recently become more popular.  Black could also play  7...Nf6  here, but we are happy to see this move: Black has less control over the e5-square, which allows a later Ne5, a strong knight outpost. }
8. Re1 O-O
{ After Black's kingside castling, it's a good time to consider further plans. Here are some points to look at:  Playing our knight to e5 does not lead to much. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2nbp3/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne5  f6  works fine for Black, as  10.Qh5  Nf5  defends h7. At a later stage, Black might play ...Qc7 and stop the move Ne5 completely, as Black has too much control of the square.  We have one pawn break available, the move c4. This move should always be strongly considered if Black plays the move ...f6, which frequently happens. It is much more attractive in this case, as we open the position to attack the weakened soft spot e6. Conclusion: we want to be ready to play c4 at a favourable moment but shouldn't play it prematurely.  We need to organise our pieces. Our forces are directed towards the kingside, but there is nothing concrete yet. Have you thought about @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2nbp3/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxh7+?  It doesn't work due to  9...Kxh7  10.Ng5+  Kg6!  , when Black's king is safe. I want more forces on this side of the board, trying to create weaknesses. I like the knight tour Nbd2-f1 as a first step. The knight may hop to g3 or e3 later.  Black frequently plays the move ...Qc7 on the next moves. It is a good idea to invest a tempo on the move h3 to mobilize the knight@@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nbd2
{ We start the knight tour to f1. Starting with  9.h3  is also fine and will lead to the same positions.   We'll now have a look at  9...f6  , but Black may also try to play without this pawn move. They could try @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2nbp3/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  , @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2nbp3/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bd7  or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2nbp3/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ng6  and focus on development.   I'd suggest playing the same setup: Nf1 and h3. One idea for White is playing on the kingside. Ng5 comes to mind, trying to create weaknesses in Black's camp. }
9... f6
{ Black goes for ...f6 and hopes to create a full pawn center with ...e5 later. Our standard reply to ...f6 is the pawn break c4, so here we go. }
10. c4
{ An almost automatic response - if they play ...f6, go for c4!  Black could take on c4 now, but the resulting IQP position is better for White. The move ...f6 does not help at all, as it created a potentially weak pawn on e6 and made Black's king less secure.  Black should probably hold the tension now. }
10... Kh8
{ A slow move like this looks best. The king move can be useful in many scenarios to prevent a later Qc2 hitting h7 with a tempo.   As mentioned, Black should avoid  10...dxc4  11.Nxc4  , when our pieces get more active, and e6 is a more severe weakness than d4. }
11. a3
{ The final move and idea I want to point out. In some cases, I want to prepare the move b4 but also take away ...Nb4 ideas by Black.  One important point is that we want to keep the tension in the center and not play the move c4-c5 unless it nets some immediate gain. Let's assume Black plays a small waiting move now, like @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r1k/pp2n1pp/2nbpp2/3p4/2PP4/P2B1N2/1P1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bc7  .  Now  12.c5??  e5!  is a disaster!  Instead, we should play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r1k/ppb1n1pp/2n1pp2/3p4/2PP4/P2B1N2/1P1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.b4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r1k/ppb1n1pp/2n1pp2/3p4/2PP4/P2B1N2/1P1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nf1  , improving our position slowly and trying to provoke the move ...dxc4 to open the position. It's an interesting and complicated position for both sides, which is why the early 5...e6 line has attracted some players recently. }
