1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide to the French Defense and the Caro-Kann.  The French Defense 1.e4 e6 and the Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 are frequently played on all levels and rank third and fourth in popularity charts - usually, the French is slightly ahead. Still, on the master level, the Caro-Kann is a more popular opening. Let's examine how we approach these defenses. }
1... c6
{ The Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 is a popular defense on all levels of play, from amateur to GM. Depending on the parameters, it ranks in third or fourth place and should appear in 10% of your games, a bit more if you play higher-level opposition.  How to battle the Caro-Kann? In the first edition of the course, I suggested the Two Knights variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  d5  3.Nf3  - a choice that I still like from a theoretical point of view.  However, for this course, I suggest a different line. Why the change? In December 2021, I released Keep It Simple for Black. My suggestion for Black is the Caro-Kann. For this course, I needed to check all White's tries and find antidotes for them. This drew my attention to the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann, which proved far more difficult to handle for Black than I expected. In addition, White's concepts are easy to learn and employ. These aspects make it an ideal weapon for a KIS repertoire with White.  The Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann leads to a non-symmetrical pawn structure. This is an important difference to openings like the French Exchange or Slav Exchange, which have a drawish reputation. The open files can be a chopping block for the pieces, leading to simplifications and less exciting games.  In the Caro-Kann Exchange, there is no open file. The pawn structure, which we determine from the very start, features some key elements.  We have no problems developing our pieces on active squares and can usually play a similar setup. We play Bd3, c3, Nf3, h3, O-O and Re1 in the majority of the lines.Black's development is not that simple: by playing Bd3 and h3 early, we stop any ...Bg4 ideas.Black often decides to play ...g6, preparing ...Bf5. This makes sense, as ...Bg4 is impossible. The move ...g6 has significant drawbacks, though.  We will discuss these strategies in more detail once these positional features are on the board. }
2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ We develop our bishop to its most active square and stop ...Bf5 simultaneously. In most games, the next moves are  4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  when I suggest playing  6.h3  , again preventing Black's bishop development.  It is difficult to devise something entirely different, as developing the two knights to their natural squares makes a lot of sense. In many cases, Black might start a bit differently on the first moves but then plays both knight moves after all. }
4... Nc6
{ In most cases, Black starts with this knight move. It looks like a natural choice, as you can hardly imagine a scenario where developing it to d7, let alone a6, would make any sense. }
5. c3
{ It's important to play this move and avoid  5.Nf3  Bg4!  , when Black solves a key issue immediately. Black should work harder to get their bishop developed!  Now we have to consider different options for Black.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the main line by a mile. We play  6.h3  against it and stop Black's idea ...Bg4 in its tracks. The main line is discussed in a dedicated chapter. Black has some alternatives with independent value. Some might still transpose to the main line because a later ...Nf6 is a natural move.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  looks a bit passive but has some points if Black plays correctly afterwards.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qc7  is Black's most important alternative. They prevent Bf4 and hope to develop the c8-bishop later. After  6.h3  , Black will usually play  6...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , when we'll end up in the main line, after all.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  prepares the fianchetto and the move ...Bf5, a common idea in the Exchange Caro-Kann. This move will often transpose to the main line after a later ...Nf6.  We will check 5...e6 and 5...Nf6 now. }
5... Nf6 { Black main move by a mile. They want to play ...Bg4 next. } 6. h3
{ White has a choice between  6.Bf4  and  6.h3  , the latter of which I suggest playing. I think both moves are of equal strength, but I feel that  6.h3  is simpler to handle and likely not as well prepared by Black. An additional benefit becomes more obvious once you examine Black's possible replies. I did this when I wrote Keep It Simple for Black, which made me aware of the  6.h3  line. Let's have an overview.   A.  6...e5  is the best move, in my opinion. I recommended it in KIS Black and still think Black should equalise with the best play. Still, this move is not the most popular in practice. Why? After  7.dxe5  Nxe5  Black needs to play an IQP position, which is a rare sight for Black in the Caro. Many opponents won't feel comfortable defending the IQP and avoid 6...e5 for this reason. I was also reluctant to recommend the move in KIS Black with the same reasoning, but I think it is objectively the best solution.So, you won't get 6...e5 that often in your games. I like it from White's point of view: it is easy to play and involves minimal risk, as you will see. The positions are similar to those in our repertoire, like the French Tarrasch with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  c5  Ngf3  Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  ,  also leading to an IQP.   B.  6...g6  is Black's most popular move. It serves two purposes: preparing Bg7 and, more importantly ...Bf5. Our move 6.h3 stopped the bishop's development, and Black insists on developing it to f5. I examined this option for KIS Black and concluded that I'd rather be White in this line, which now comes in handy for this course! }
6... g6
{ More often than not, Black opts for 6...g6 in the main line. I think that many Caro-Kann players do not like playing with an IQP after 6...e5 and prefer this alternative. Black's setup has two ideas:  Playing ...Bf5 to trade the bishop. How should we answer ...Bf5? We can take the bishop and create a doubled pawn or allow Black to trade on d3.I suggest a clear guideline: We don't take on f5, unless it is motivated by a concrete tactic or we reach a particularly favourable scenario. This is rare, but we'll see two cases that apply. I will analyse the motivation behind my advice when ...Bf5 is on the board after 7.Nf3 Bf5, when I suggest to castle kingside.    Complete the fianchetto and castle kingside. Understanding that the fianchetto is NOT an ideal setup for Black is crucial. The bishop is not well-placed on g7, as it bites on the c3+d4 pawn chain. It is also missing as a participant in a possible queenside play for Black. Black would definitely prefer a setup with ...e6 and ...Bd6 or ...Be7.A further drawback of ...g6 is weakening the kingside dark squares. I understand that this sounds far-fetched, but you'll agree once you have studied this chapter till the end.  Let's continue with our next, very natural move. }
7. Nf3
{ We continue with the most natural move and prepare kingside castling. It's also possible to play  7.Bf4  here, but there is no particular benefit in playing the bishop to f4 early. We are not concerned about Black playing ...Qc7, for example. With the more natural  7.Nf3  ,  we intend to complete a piece setup that we use a standard in the Caro-Kann Exchange: Bd3, Nf3, h3, O-O and Re1 is a common sight across many lines.What now for Black? They have two points on the agenda: completing castling and playing ...Bf5. You meet all kinds of move orders that combine the two. It will usually lead to the same positions, as our moves are the same in all cases. We castle and play Re1 next. I decided to organise the lines as follows:   A.  7...Bf5  is our main line and covers all situations that feature the move ...Bf5.   B.  7...Bg7  is just as popular but will usually include a later ...Bf5, too.   C.  7...Qc7  is a third option that will also likely transpose to A, but it has some interesting move-order subtleties worth seeing.  In all cases, our next moves are O-O and Re1. }
7... Bf5
{ The main purpose of ...g6, in my mind, is preparing this move. Black wants to trade the bishop. }
8. O-O
{ I already mentioned that I advise not to capture on f5. The question 'to take or not to take' can occur in various versions. We have the very early situation here @@StartBracket@@Black has not even played ...Bg7 yet@@EndBracket@@ or at the later stages of the kingside development. The capture is the most unattractive option right here when Black might even play a quick ...Rg8 ...e6, and ...Bd6 to take over the initiative. At a later stage, the capture gets a bit more compelling, but I still advise against it to make our job easier unless there is a concrete idea.   We'll now consider two scenarios: Black takes on d3, or Black keeps the tension with  8...Bg7  .  I also found some online games that featured the move @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p1b2/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6?!  , when  9.Bb5!  is a good reply. Black's f5-bishop is running low on squares, and Ne5/Qa4 ideas are dangerous. }
8... Bg7 { Black avoids the capture and continues their kingside development. }
9. Re1
{ Completing our standard setup. Now Black again decides between taking on d3 and keeping the tension. If they take, we'll transpose to lines that I cover via 8...Bxd3, the earlier capture. }
9... O-O
{ The alternatives are  9...Bxd3  ,  leading to 8...Bxd3 lines, or  9...Qc7?  , a blunder that we can punish with  10.Bxf5!  gxf5  11.Nh4!  ,  as covered via the move order  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7  8.O-O  Bg7  9.Re1  Bf5?  10.Bxf5!  , leading to the same disaster.   After  9...O-O  ,  we reach an interesting position which allows a wide range of moves. My choice is not the most obvious but will pose a likely unexpected challenge. In practice, Black usually does not react properly to the next move. }
10. Bf1
{ I like this surprising move. We argue that Black missed their chance to trade bishops, so we take away this option.  Before I continue, a word about alternatives. The main one I see is  10.Bf4  , which is a more obvious move. I was not too fond of the reply  10...Bxd3  11.Qxd3  Qb6  , when defending the b-pawn, is a bit awkward. This is still viable for White, but I found the bishop retreat to f1 more challenging for Black to handle.   In practice, Black often goes wrong quickly. So, what's the idea of our move?  If Black continues with a slow move  @@StartBracket@@  10...Rc8  , @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n2np1/3p1b2/3P4/2P2N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQRBK1 b - - 7 10@@EndFEN@@  10...a6  @@EndBracket@@, we play Bf4 and Nbd2 to complete our development most actively. This type of position is comfortable for White. In such a scenario, Black often starts an ill-advised attack on the queenside. We are perfectly placed to answer ...b5 with a4. Our knight may also use the weak c5-square.Black's most popular reply in practice is @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n2np1/3p1b2/3P4/2P2N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQRBK1 b - - 7 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Ne4?!  , which is surprisingly difficult for Black to handle. We get a nice advantage against it, as the knight is ultimately unstable on e4.It looks like Black's best is @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n2np1/3p1b2/3P4/2P2N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQRBK1 b - - 7 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qc7  , as the engines point out. This is rarely played, though, and I still have an interesting suggestion against the move. We can try  11.Be3  , followed by Qc1 to prepare Bf4.It's fascinating that we currently have most pieces on the first rank. The key point is that Black has developed the pieces, but most are not effectively placed. The g7-bishop is biting on d4, and the other one of f5 is pointing into thin air. The c6-knight is looking at protected squares.  We'll check 10...Ne4 now, Black's most popular move. }
10... Ne4
{ Black opts for the knight jump most of the time. It looks attractive to centralise the knight, but it turns out it is unstable in the center. }
11. Nbd2
{ We immediately challenge the intruder. Playing  11.Bf4  is also possible, with Nbd2 next. The knight move is more direct, though. }
11... Qb6
{ After  11...Nxd2  12.Bxd2  ,  Black's concept has failed. We have a nice choice of ideas, like Bf4/g5 and Qd2, to go for a kingside initiative or focus on the queenside @@StartBracket@@Qb3, a4-a5 ideas, for instance@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Nd2 { We get the knight to the queenside with tempo. } 13...
Bf5 14. Nb3
{ The knight is well-placed on b3 in this situation. We want to play Bf4, a4-a5 and jump to c5 later. It is amazing to see how ineffective Black's pieces are. Our opponent has no active idea, which makes it very tough to play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide to the French Defense and the Caro-Kann.  The French Defense 1.e4 e6 and the Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 are frequently played on all levels and rank third and fourth in popularity charts - usually, the French is slightly ahead. Still, on the master level, the Caro-Kann is a more popular opening. Let's examine how we approach these defenses. }
1... c6
{ The Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 is a popular defense on all levels of play, from amateur to GM. Depending on the parameters, it ranks in third or fourth place and should appear in 10% of your games, a bit more if you play higher-level opposition.  How to battle the Caro-Kann? In the first edition of the course, I suggested the Two Knights variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  d5  3.Nf3  - a choice that I still like from a theoretical point of view.  However, for this course, I suggest a different line. Why the change? In December 2021, I released Keep It Simple for Black. My suggestion for Black is the Caro-Kann. For this course, I needed to check all White's tries and find antidotes for them. This drew my attention to the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann, which proved far more difficult to handle for Black than I expected. In addition, White's concepts are easy to learn and employ. These aspects make it an ideal weapon for a KIS repertoire with White.  The Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann leads to a non-symmetrical pawn structure. This is an important difference to openings like the French Exchange or Slav Exchange, which have a drawish reputation. The open files can be a chopping block for the pieces, leading to simplifications and less exciting games.  In the Caro-Kann Exchange, there is no open file. The pawn structure, which we determine from the very start, features some key elements.  We have no problems developing our pieces on active squares and can usually play a similar setup. We play Bd3, c3, Nf3, h3, O-O and Re1 in the majority of the lines.Black's development is not that simple: by playing Bd3 and h3 early, we stop any ...Bg4 ideas.Black often decides to play ...g6, preparing ...Bf5. This makes sense, as ...Bg4 is impossible. The move ...g6 has significant drawbacks, though.  We will discuss these strategies in more detail once these positional features are on the board. }
2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ We develop our bishop to its most active square and stop ...Bf5 simultaneously. In most games, the next moves are  4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  when I suggest playing  6.h3  , again preventing Black's bishop development.  It is difficult to devise something entirely different, as developing the two knights to their natural squares makes a lot of sense. In many cases, Black might start a bit differently on the first moves but then plays both knight moves after all. }
4... Nc6
{ In most cases, Black starts with this knight move. It looks like a natural choice, as you can hardly imagine a scenario where developing it to d7, let alone a6, would make any sense. }
5. c3
{ It's important to play this move and avoid  5.Nf3  Bg4!  , when Black solves a key issue immediately. Black should work harder to get their bishop developed!  Now we have to consider different options for Black.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the main line by a mile. We play  6.h3  against it and stop Black's idea ...Bg4 in its tracks. The main line is discussed in a dedicated chapter. Black has some alternatives with independent value. Some might still transpose to the main line because a later ...Nf6 is a natural move.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  looks a bit passive but has some points if Black plays correctly afterwards.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qc7  is Black's most important alternative. They prevent Bf4 and hope to develop the c8-bishop later. After  6.h3  , Black will usually play  6...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , when we'll end up in the main line, after all.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  prepares the fianchetto and the move ...Bf5, a common idea in the Exchange Caro-Kann. This move will often transpose to the main line after a later ...Nf6.  We will check 5...e6 and 5...Nf6 now. }
5... Nf6 { Black main move by a mile. They want to play ...Bg4 next. } 6. h3
{ White has a choice between  6.Bf4  and  6.h3  , the latter of which I suggest playing. I think both moves are of equal strength, but I feel that  6.h3  is simpler to handle and likely not as well prepared by Black. An additional benefit becomes more obvious once you examine Black's possible replies. I did this when I wrote Keep It Simple for Black, which made me aware of the  6.h3  line. Let's have an overview.   A.  6...e5  is the best move, in my opinion. I recommended it in KIS Black and still think Black should equalise with the best play. Still, this move is not the most popular in practice. Why? After  7.dxe5  Nxe5  Black needs to play an IQP position, which is a rare sight for Black in the Caro. Many opponents won't feel comfortable defending the IQP and avoid 6...e5 for this reason. I was also reluctant to recommend the move in KIS Black with the same reasoning, but I think it is objectively the best solution.So, you won't get 6...e5 that often in your games. I like it from White's point of view: it is easy to play and involves minimal risk, as you will see. The positions are similar to those in our repertoire, like the French Tarrasch with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  c5  Ngf3  Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  ,  also leading to an IQP.   B.  6...g6  is Black's most popular move. It serves two purposes: preparing Bg7 and, more importantly ...Bf5. Our move 6.h3 stopped the bishop's development, and Black insists on developing it to f5. I examined this option for KIS Black and concluded that I'd rather be White in this line, which now comes in handy for this course! }
6... g6
{ More often than not, Black opts for 6...g6 in the main line. I think that many Caro-Kann players do not like playing with an IQP after 6...e5 and prefer this alternative. Black's setup has two ideas:  Playing ...Bf5 to trade the bishop. How should we answer ...Bf5? We can take the bishop and create a doubled pawn or allow Black to trade on d3.I suggest a clear guideline: We don't take on f5, unless it is motivated by a concrete tactic or we reach a particularly favourable scenario. This is rare, but we'll see two cases that apply. I will analyse the motivation behind my advice when ...Bf5 is on the board after 7.Nf3 Bf5, when I suggest to castle kingside.    Complete the fianchetto and castle kingside. Understanding that the fianchetto is NOT an ideal setup for Black is crucial. The bishop is not well-placed on g7, as it bites on the c3+d4 pawn chain. It is also missing as a participant in a possible queenside play for Black. Black would definitely prefer a setup with ...e6 and ...Bd6 or ...Be7.A further drawback of ...g6 is weakening the kingside dark squares. I understand that this sounds far-fetched, but you'll agree once you have studied this chapter till the end.  Let's continue with our next, very natural move. }
7. Nf3
{ We continue with the most natural move and prepare kingside castling. It's also possible to play  7.Bf4  here, but there is no particular benefit in playing the bishop to f4 early. We are not concerned about Black playing ...Qc7, for example. With the more natural  7.Nf3  ,  we intend to complete a piece setup that we use a standard in the Caro-Kann Exchange: Bd3, Nf3, h3, O-O and Re1 is a common sight across many lines.What now for Black? They have two points on the agenda: completing castling and playing ...Bf5. You meet all kinds of move orders that combine the two. It will usually lead to the same positions, as our moves are the same in all cases. We castle and play Re1 next. I decided to organise the lines as follows:   A.  7...Bf5  is our main line and covers all situations that feature the move ...Bf5.   B.  7...Bg7  is just as popular but will usually include a later ...Bf5, too.   C.  7...Qc7  is a third option that will also likely transpose to A, but it has some interesting move-order subtleties worth seeing.  In all cases, our next moves are O-O and Re1. }
7... Bf5
{ The main purpose of ...g6, in my mind, is preparing this move. Black wants to trade the bishop. }
8. O-O
{ I already mentioned that I advise not to capture on f5. The question 'to take or not to take' can occur in various versions. We have the very early situation here @@StartBracket@@Black has not even played ...Bg7 yet@@EndBracket@@ or at the later stages of the kingside development. The capture is the most unattractive option right here when Black might even play a quick ...Rg8 ...e6, and ...Bd6 to take over the initiative. At a later stage, the capture gets a bit more compelling, but I still advise against it to make our job easier unless there is a concrete idea.   We'll now consider two scenarios: Black takes on d3, or Black keeps the tension with  8...Bg7  .  I also found some online games that featured the move @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p1b2/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6?!  , when  9.Bb5!  is a good reply. Black's f5-bishop is running low on squares, and Ne5/Qa4 ideas are dangerous. }
8... Bxd3 { Black goes for the trade of bishops. } 9. Qxd3
{ Now Black's almost automatic move is  9...Bg7  ,  when we develop our bishop to f4. Black may also play  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PQ1N1P/PP3PP1/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  ,  which requires a different way to develop our bishop, as the more active f4-square is not available.I will focus on 9...Qc7 now, as it makes our job a bit harder, and the arising position and strategy are the same as after the bishop move. }
9... Qc7
{ Black stops our development option Bf4. This move is fairly rare at this point, but you can always reach these positions if Black plays Qc7 earlier and then opts for ...Bf5. A possible sequence covered in the current chapter is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7  8.O-O  Bf5  9.Re1  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  ,  which leads to the same scenario.How do we play now? A good way to go is to play a setup with Re1, Be3, and Nbd2. Let's put these moves on the board and discuss the strategy once these initial steps are completed. }
10. Re1
{ It's no mistake to start with  10.Be3  ,  of course. I go for Re1 first, as we usually play this move first in other lines. }
10... Bg7 11. Be3
{ It looks more active to play  11.Bg5  , but  11...Ne4  is a good reply. }
11... O-O 12. Nbd2
{ We have developed the minor pieces and connected rooks, a good moment to take stock. What is the strategy here? Here are some points to consider.It is crucial to understand that Black has no clear active idea. There are two possible ways for our opponent to change the pawn structure: Playing for ...e5. This is tough to realise and not that attractive, to begin with. Black would create an IQP that is likely going to be weak. The minority attack, based on ...b5. This is a far more common and popular idea but usually quite dubious in this particular version of the Carlsbad pawn structure.The key issue is Black's bishop on g7, which does not support the queenside play and fails to cover the c5-square. If you would modify the current position, put Black's pawn back on g7 and set up ...e6 and ...Bd6, Black would be in excellent shape. Black controls e5 and c5 and has the bishop ideally placed to support b5-b4 and cover c5.In the current configuration, the move ...b5 gives us an excellent square for our knight @@StartBracket@@Nb3-c5@@EndBracket@@. You also commonly see that b4 answers Black's ...b5 if White installs the knight on c5. In such a case, the technically backward pawn on c3 would not matter compared to the monster knight on c5.Black's lack of clear ideas is key; it allows us to make small, incremental progress in the center and on the kingside.Some steps we can take:  Playing g3&Bf4 to activate our bishop and strengthen control of e5.  We can consider h4-h5 at a later stage. This attack could become dangerous quickly if the f6-knight had to leave its post.  It would be excellent to manoeuvre our d2-knight to d3, its ideal square. On d3, it would look at all crucial squares: e5, c5, b4 and b2. It is active and defending simultaneously.  Doubling on the e-file is an idea. One rook is often well-placed on e2 to cover b2.  Trading bishops can be a good idea. This could happen in a sequence like g3, Be3-f4 first, later Ne5/ ...Nxe5/ Bxe5, when our bishop arrives on e5. With more minor pieces traded, an attack based on h4-h5 becomes more likely and dangerous.This position and overall type of position is not something to learn on a move-by-move basis. Therefore I think it is best to continue with some possible lines to see the points above in action.   A.  12...a6  signals the intention to play for ...b5. This often backfires, as mentioned.  13.Nb3  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1ppbp/p1n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PQBN1P/PP1N1PP1/R3R1K1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.g3  , but I like to connect the knight to the sensitive c5-square@@EndBracket@@. Now let's look at some options.   A1. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1ppbp/p1n2np1/3p4/3P4/1NPQBN1P/PP3PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...b5?  is a mistake due to  14.Nc5  Nd7  15.b4  , when our knight is great on c5 and can hardly be taken.   A2. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1ppbp/p1n2np1/3p4/3P4/1NPQBN1P/PP3PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nd7  covers c5 but allows  14.Qd2  Rfe8  15.Bf4  Qd8  16.Re2  a5  17.Rae1  , when we are ready for Nc1-d3 for a dream formation. We have a grip on the dark squares and may play h4-h5 soon. If Black moves the knight back to f6, we may jump to c5.   A3. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1ppbp/p1n2np1/3p4/3P4/1NPQBN1P/PP3PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Ne4  14.Ng5  Nxg5  15.Bxg5  Rfe8  16.Re2  also looks good. Black is getting nowhere on the queenside, and we shift forces to the center and kingside. h4-h5 is the idea. I am generally happy to see Black playing for a minority attack here, as it often creates weaknesses. The move ...a6 is no problem for Black, but it rarely serves to prepare ...b5 in a good way.   B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/ppq1ppbp/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PQBN1P/PP1N1PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 6 12@@EndFEN@@  12...e6  is more of a waiting move. Black should probably play such a strategy.  13.g3  Rfe8  14.Bf4  Qb6  15.a3  Rac8  is an example of such an approach. It could continue with  16.Kg2  a6  17.g4  Nd7  18.Bg3  , when we have gained some ground on the kingside. I feel that this type of position is easier to play for White. I see chances on the kingside in the long term, while Black can easily go wrong with misguided queenside initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide to the French Defense and the Caro-Kann.  The French Defense 1.e4 e6 and the Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 are frequently played on all levels and rank third and fourth in popularity charts - usually, the French is slightly ahead. Still, on the master level, the Caro-Kann is a more popular opening. Let's examine how we approach these defenses. }
1... e6
{ The French Defense 1...e6 is popular for Black, particularly below the master level. Depending on the data, the French ranks third or fourth in popularity rankings and occurs about 10-15% of the time.  I recommend the Tarrasch Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , the favourite move of many players who prefer to exert pressure from a position of safety.  A key difference to the Exchange Variation is that we keep the central tension and do not determine the pawn structure. The move 3.Nd2 looks more passive than 3.Nc3, but has two advantages over 3.Nc3 -  we prevent the ...Bb4 pin and still have c2-c3 supporting our center.   Let's discuss our coverage in the Quickstarter. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  , it is split as follows.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.e5  leads to a typical French pawn center and a space advantage for White. In my mind, White reaches an advantage in many ways. I recommend a setup based on f4, which is very difficult for Black to handle.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  is Black's second main line. I suggest  4.Ngf3  , when Black frequently accepts an Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. A sample line is  4...Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  . White has good chances for a comfortable pull here. A better alternative for Black is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  , which currently looks like Black's best line against the Tarrasch. Black should get equal chances with perfect play.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ We also look at  3...dxe4  , the solid Rubinstein Variation Black has rarer moves, which are discussed in the sidelines chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nd2
{ Against the Tarrasch, Black's most popular replies are 3...Nf6 and 3...c5. We will check these two main options and 3...dxe4, which enjoys considerable popularity below the master level. }
3... c5
{ After 3...c5, White has an important choice to make. Two good moves CAN lead to the same positions, but there are important differences. Let's compare and understand the nuances.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  leads to an immediate split between two answers:  A1. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/3P4/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  leads to the IQP lines after  5.Ngf3  Nc6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  - all three options are welcome and lead to this pawn structure. I am happy to play against the IQP, a common strategy in our repertoire.  A2. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/3P4/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5!  is a much more serious challenge. Black avoids the IQP in this line and currently has excellent chances to equalise the game. I checked it in detail and felt it was best avoided, if possible. That gets us to option B.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  is my choice when we have a split, too.  B1. Black can play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  when we trade on d5 and reach the lines mentioned under A1 above. In these cases, capturing on d5 with the queen is worse. We more or less force the transposition to the IQP structures, as Black can't sensibly deviate.  B2. The main alternative and likely best is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  , when Black hopes for  5.exd5  Qxd5  , which would transpose to A2 above. But we played the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  for a reason. After  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  we reach the main lines of this chapter.  To summarise: we play the slightly more sophisticated move order B to avoid the ...Qxd5 lines. White chooses to fight Black in this line or opt for  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  cxd4  5.Nxd4  , as I suggest. My reasons are twofold: I think we can pose more problems, and it is simpler to play. }
4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line. These two continuations are the focus of the Quickstarter.  A quick word about other moves:  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  6.exd5  exd5  6.Bb5+  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure when the Bb5 themes are out. After  6.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Nb3  Ba7  9.Qe2+  , we have some advantage, as we either trade queens or manage Be3 to trade Black's strong bishop.   E. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxe4?  is a mistake, as  5.Nxe4  cxd4  6.Qxd4  gives us a huge lead in development. }
4... Nc6
{ Black puts more pressure on d4 and, more or less, accepts to enter an IQP structure after our reply. }
5. exd5
{ Now Black's best move is  5...exd5  when we reach the common line that features the IQP structure.   Black must avoid  5...Qxd5?!  , as  6.Bc4  Qd8  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Qe2  Nf6  9.Ne4  is favourable for White. We'll manage to castle queenside and have good attacking chances. }
5... exd5
{ Black captures with the pawn, signalling the intention to play with the Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. We don't have an IQP on the board yet, but a trade of our d-pawn for Black's pawn is more or less unavoidable. These IQP structures have the reputation of being solid for Black but slightly passive and tough to win. White can create a nagging pull and pressure Black without running any undue risks.Our general strategic outline is quite simple:  Create the IQP,Keep it blockaded/place a piece on d4,Trade minor pieces and pressurise the pawn,Endgames are generally favourable for us. }
6. Bb5
{ 'Pin and win' - well, we are not winning, but I am still happy with this move. Bb5 not only creates a pin but prepares to castle next. Black must be careful about a rook coming to e1 while their king is still in the center. We'll have three options now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  is the traditional main line for Black. They usually want to combine ...Bd6 and ...Nge7, which shields against the early attack on the e-file.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6?  is a bad idea, as we quickly expose Black's problems on the e-file. Black would like to develop their knight to f6 but does not manage to do it in this simple way. After  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Re1+  Be6  10.Nb3  Bb6  11.Nbd4  we see the problem: there is too much pressure on e6 and c6.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qe7+  is a clever move and probably Black's best bet nowadays. After White's best reply  7.Be2  it usually continues  7...Qc7  8.O-O  Nf6  9.Re1  Be6  10.Bb5  , when I prefer White. While this line might be Black's best option, White still retains a small advantage. We examine this line in more detail in the full chapter. }
6... Bd6
{ Black's traditional main line. They develop the bishop and prepare ...Nge7, ensuring no accidents on the e-file. }
7. dxc5
{ A good moment to take, but  7.O-O  Nge7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  is a common and equally good sequence, too. }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O
{ Ready for Re1+, which usually prompts Black to block the e-file with  8...Nge7  ,  the point of the 6...Bd6 line. }
8... Ne7
{ Black can still go wrong with  8...Nf6?  , when  9.Re1+  transposes to the line  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Re1+  , with a large advantage for White. }
9. Nb3
{ After this natural move, Black needs to decide between retreating to d6 or b6. }
9... Bd6
{ We'll check this move in the Quickstarter.   Black's alternative  9...Bb6  is slightly different, as we can operate with Be3 ideas. One possible line is  10.c3  O-O  11.Re1  Bg4  12.Be3  , when we trade Black's strong bishop.  From d6, the bishop is not looking at the blockade square d4 but instead pointing towards our kingside. Our strategy is slightly different than after ...Bb6, as this bishop retreat invited the Be3 plan. We need a different approach here, but we'll that many ideas are shared, between the two lines. }
10. c3
{ Taking more control of d4 makes a lot of sense. It's also an efficient choice, as it will become clearer on the next move. }
10... O-O
{ We have reached a position that we might also play in the Sicilian. It is the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  exd5  5.d4  Nc6  6.Bb5  Bd6  7.O-O  Nge7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Nbd2  O-O  10.Nb3  Bd6  , when we reach the position currently on the board. }
11. Bd3
{ This retreat is, in fact, the most active move. It prevents ...Bg4 due to Bxh7+ and prepares the battery with Bc2+Qd3 to provoke weaknesses. This concept is also used in the 9...Bb6 line. }
11... h6
{ After  11...Bg4??  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Ng5+  and Qxg4, White wins an important pawn and hopefully the game later on.  The move 11...h6 prevents this tactic and prepares the bishop for development. }
12. h3 { No pin, please, an important move. } 12... Nf5
{ A good move that prevents our bishop development to e3.   I also found many games with  12...Bf5  , when  13.Re1  Qd7  14.Bxf5  Nxf5  15.Qd3  Rae8  16.Rxe8  Rxe8  17.Bd2  is a sample line to demonstrate how this could develop further. We plan Rd1 next and maybe Bc1 to put more pressure on d5. Black's d5-pawn will remain a target. }
13. Bc2 { Going for the battery idea. } 13... Re8 14. Qd3
{ Quite inconvenient for Black to meet. Black has to decide how to defend against the g4 idea. It is important to realise that g4 is not a deadly threat, as there is no checkmate on h7. }
14... Qf6
{ Black could also try  14...g6  , making sure the queen is not invading at all. After  15.Bd2  Be6  16.Nbd4  we manage to trade some minor pieces, which is a substantial accomplishment when fighting the IQP. Without any minor pieces, our heavy pieces can exert more pressure on the weak pawn. }
15. Bd2
{ Grabbing the pawn on d5 does not lose immediately but gives Black substantial compensation. We should rather focus on development.   Note that  15.g4?  Nh4  leads to nothing, as we only have a harmless check on h7. Here, the battery is a constant worry for Black, but we need to be cautious about executing the 'threat', especially if we have to weaken our position like 15.g4? does here. Instead, we should focus on small improvements, like playing a rook on the e-file and potentially double rooks there. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 c5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide to the French Defense and the Caro-Kann.  The French Defense 1.e4 e6 and the Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 are frequently played on all levels and rank third and fourth in popularity charts - usually, the French is slightly ahead. Still, on the master level, the Caro-Kann is a more popular opening. Let's examine how we approach these defenses. }
1... e6
{ The French Defense 1...e6 is popular for Black, particularly below the master level. Depending on the data, the French ranks third or fourth in popularity rankings and occurs about 10-15% of the time.  I recommend the Tarrasch Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , the favourite move of many players who prefer to exert pressure from a position of safety.  A key difference to the Exchange Variation is that we keep the central tension and do not determine the pawn structure. The move 3.Nd2 looks more passive than 3.Nc3, but has two advantages over 3.Nc3 -  we prevent the ...Bb4 pin and still have c2-c3 supporting our center.   Let's discuss our coverage in the Quickstarter. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  , it is split as follows.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.e5  leads to a typical French pawn center and a space advantage for White. In my mind, White reaches an advantage in many ways. I recommend a setup based on f4, which is very difficult for Black to handle.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  is Black's second main line. I suggest  4.Ngf3  , when Black frequently accepts an Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. A sample line is  4...Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  . White has good chances for a comfortable pull here. A better alternative for Black is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  , which currently looks like Black's best line against the Tarrasch. Black should get equal chances with perfect play.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ We also look at  3...dxe4  , the solid Rubinstein Variation Black has rarer moves, which are discussed in the sidelines chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nd2
{ Against the Tarrasch, Black's most popular replies are 3...Nf6 and 3...c5. We will check these two main options and 3...dxe4, which enjoys considerable popularity below the master level. }
3... c5
{ After 3...c5, White has an important choice to make. Two good moves CAN lead to the same positions, but there are important differences. Let's compare and understand the nuances.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  leads to an immediate split between two answers:  A1. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/3P4/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  leads to the IQP lines after  5.Ngf3  Nc6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  - all three options are welcome and lead to this pawn structure. I am happy to play against the IQP, a common strategy in our repertoire.  A2. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/3P4/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5!  is a much more serious challenge. Black avoids the IQP in this line and currently has excellent chances to equalise the game. I checked it in detail and felt it was best avoided, if possible. That gets us to option B.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  is my choice when we have a split, too.  B1. Black can play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  when we trade on d5 and reach the lines mentioned under A1 above. In these cases, capturing on d5 with the queen is worse. We more or less force the transposition to the IQP structures, as Black can't sensibly deviate.  B2. The main alternative and likely best is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  , when Black hopes for  5.exd5  Qxd5  , which would transpose to A2 above. But we played the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  for a reason. After  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  we reach the main lines of this chapter.  To summarise: we play the slightly more sophisticated move order B to avoid the ...Qxd5 lines. White chooses to fight Black in this line or opt for  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  cxd4  5.Nxd4  , as I suggest. My reasons are twofold: I think we can pose more problems, and it is simpler to play. }
4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line. These two continuations are the focus of the Quickstarter.  A quick word about other moves:  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  6.exd5  exd5  6.Bb5+  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure when the Bb5 themes are out. After  6.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Nb3  Ba7  9.Qe2+  , we have some advantage, as we either trade queens or manage Be3 to trade Black's strong bishop.   E. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxe4?  is a mistake, as  5.Nxe4  cxd4  6.Qxd4  gives us a huge lead in development. }
4... cxd4
{ Black captures on d4, which signals their intention to play  5.exd5  Qxd5  , transposing to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.Ngf3  cxd4  ,  which has a good reputation nowadays. We specifically played 4.Ngf3 to avoid this line, though. The way to do it is recapturing on d4. }
5. Nxd4
{ Black is quite far behind in development and needs to catch up. Therefore, they now usually play either 5...Nf6 or 5...Nc6, the more popular and combative move and our focus in the Quickstarter.  I want to mention two interesting points about 5...Nf6, though.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3p4/3NP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.exd5  Qxd5  is rarely played because  7.Nb5  forces Black's knight to a6.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3p4/3NP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.exd5  Nxd5  is more common when  7.N2f3  Bb4+  is the most important moment to see about 5...Nf6, because  8.c3??  Nxc3!  is a common blunder. We must play @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/4p3/3n4/1b1N4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bd2  , retaining a small advantage. These lines are examined more closely in the dedicated chapter. }
5... Nc6
{ Black attacks our knight and hopes for the capture on c6, which strengthens Black's center. The knight jump to c6 is Black's main move by far and leads to interesting play. First, we must see that we can't avoid capturing on c6. It is, however, imperative to remember the next move and the attached idea. }
6. Bb5
{ It's much more challenging for Black first to pin the knight, and only after  6...Bd7  capture on c6. Let's compare:   A.  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3   B.  6.Bb5  Bd7  7.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3    We prefer the version in B as the extra move ...Bd7 is not helpful for Black, quite the opposite. The bishop is better placed on c8, as it leaves d7 free for the knight @@StartBracket@@think of a later e4-e5 attack on the f6-knight@@EndBracket@@ and may get to b7 later.So don't forget to play 6. Bb5, an important subtlety. }
6... Bd7 7. Nxc6
{ After provoking ...Bd7, we are better positioned to capture. Now Black captures with the pawn most of the time, as  7...Bxc6  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.c4  leads to a rather unattractive position. Black's pawns are slightly weak, and Qa4 next increases the pressure. }
7... bxc6 { Better and more combative than taking with the bishop. } 8. Bd3
{ Mission accomplished! Our bishop returns after fulfilling their job to lure Black's bishop to d7. We need to consider two moves now. Black can't play  8...Nf6?  now, as  9.e5  sends the knight home immediately. This is why the d7-bishop is misplaced.What are Black's best options? It makes sense to take control of e5, trying to develop the knight soon.   A.  8...Bd6  is Black's most popular move. They develop the bishop to a good square first and then decide how to continue with the problematic knight on g8.   B.  8...Qc7  is Black's main alternative to A. The queen move also connects to the e5-square and fights against a possible e4-e5 by White. The queen move is usually connected with the idea ...Ne7-g6, which aims to strengthen control of e5 and f4.  I suggest  9.Qe2  Ne7  10.Nf3  Ng6  11.O-O  Be7  12.c4  , attacking Black's center. It leads to interesting play that is examined in more detail in the full chapter.  I will examine option A now, as it is by far the most popular. }
8... Bd6
{ The bishop move is the most popular move and was recommended by Anish Giri in his Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. }
9. Qe2
{ This looks like the most dangerous move. The main idea is preparing e4-e5, gaining space while hitting the bishop. Now we come to an important split.   A. @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/p2b1ppp/2pbp3/3p4/4P3/3B4/PPPNQPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...e5  is the latest trend and was recommended by Anish Giri in his LTR French. I will check this move as the main one, as it also requires the most effort to fight.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/p2b1ppp/2pbp3/3p4/4P3/3B4/PPPNQPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ne7  is the former main line that we'll check, too. Black allows the pawn to push to e5, which we are happy about:  10.e5  Bc7  11.O-O  Ng6  12.f4  gives White an advantage in space and slightly better chances in a complicated position.  C. @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/p2b1ppp/2pbp3/3p4/4P3/3B4/PPPNQPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  stops e4-e5, but  10.Nf3  is better for White. We either manage e4-e5 under better conditions than in B, or Black goes for ...dxe4, compromising their pawn structure. }
9... e5
{ This move looks incredibly risky, but nowadays, engines show that it is a valid option. Anish Giri suggested this move in his Chessable repertoire, and I understand his reasoning: in the other lines, Black is usually forced to allow e4-e5 at some point, which the ultra-principled 9...e5 stops in its tracks. You won't be surprised to learn that you can't refute 9...e5, but I think we'll be able to get an interesting game against it. }
10. c4
{ The start of a rather forcing line. We attack the d5-pawn and lure it forward. }
10... d4
{ We follow Giri's recommendation. This is best, as  10...Ne7?!  11.cxd5  cxd5  12.O-O  opens the position too quickly for Black's taste. The game could continue  12...O-O  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Ne4  Be7  15.Rd1  , when Black is poorly coordinated. }
11. c5
{ This is the real point of the previous move. We sacrifice a pawn to activate our knight and weaken Black's dark squares. }
11... Bxc5 12. Nc4
{ A fantastic square for our knight. Now Black has only one good continuation. They have to play the bishop check; otherwise, our pawn push to f4 would become even more effective. A sample line would be @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/p2b1ppp/2p5/2b1p3/2NpP3/3B4/PP2QPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qc7  13.f4!  Bb4+  14.Bd2  Bxd2+  15.Qxd2  exf4  16.e5!  , when we reach a better version of the main line. The move Nd6+ is looming.  Now Black's best is  @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/p2b1ppp/2p5/2b1p3/2NpP3/3B4/PP2QPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bb4+  13.Bd2  Qe7  , when  14.O-O  Bxd2  15.Qxd2  Nh6  16.f4  leads to an interesting position that looks equal after further complications. This line is analysed in much more detail in the dedicated chapter. This coverage is very high-level, but comparing it to Giri's analysis makes sense. I cut the trainable for the Quickstarter here - you can study more in the full chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 dxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide to the French Defense and the Caro-Kann.  The French Defense 1.e4 e6 and the Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 are frequently played on all levels and rank third and fourth in popularity charts - usually, the French is slightly ahead. Still, on the master level, the Caro-Kann is a more popular opening. Let's examine how we approach these defenses. }
1... e6
{ The French Defense 1...e6 is popular for Black, particularly below the master level. Depending on the data, the French ranks third or fourth in popularity rankings and occurs about 10-15% of the time.  I recommend the Tarrasch Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , the favourite move of many players who prefer to exert pressure from a position of safety.  A key difference to the Exchange Variation is that we keep the central tension and do not determine the pawn structure. The move 3.Nd2 looks more passive than 3.Nc3, but has two advantages over 3.Nc3 -  we prevent the ...Bb4 pin and still have c2-c3 supporting our center.   Let's discuss our coverage in the Quickstarter. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  , it is split as follows.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.e5  leads to a typical French pawn center and a space advantage for White. In my mind, White reaches an advantage in many ways. I recommend a setup based on f4, which is very difficult for Black to handle.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  is Black's second main line. I suggest  4.Ngf3  , when Black frequently accepts an Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. A sample line is  4...Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  . White has good chances for a comfortable pull here. A better alternative for Black is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  , which currently looks like Black's best line against the Tarrasch. Black should get equal chances with perfect play.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ We also look at  3...dxe4  , the solid Rubinstein Variation Black has rarer moves, which are discussed in the sidelines chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nd2
{ Against the Tarrasch, Black's most popular replies are 3...Nf6 and 3...c5. We will check these two main options and 3...dxe4, which enjoys considerable popularity below the master level. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has a choice of lines that lead to different scenarios.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nd7  is the main continuation. Black prepares ...Ngf6 next and aims for a later ...c5 break. We can count on a small advantage in this line and examine it in the Quickstarter.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bd7  leads to the so-called Fort Knox Variation. Black wants to activate the bishop via c6 but often ends up trading the bishop for one of our knights. The Fort Know has its name for a reason: it has the reputation of being a solid, albeit passive defense. We continue with  5.Nf3  Bc6  6.Bd3  Nd7  7.c3  , which sets a nice trap. After  7...Ngf6  8.Nxf6+  Qxf6??  9.Bg5  Bxf3  10.Qd2!  we win the queen! Black must play @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/2b1pN2/8/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nxf6  , when  9.O-O  Bxf3  leads to long-term edge due to the bishop pair.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  is imprecise but regularly played in online and amateur games. White is better after  5.Nxf6  gxf6  6.Be3  @@StartBracket@@preparing O-O-O@@EndBracket@@ or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pN2/8/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qxf6  6.Nf3  , when a setup based on Bd3 and c3 is good for White. We often get a dangerous attack based on a quick h4 - more on that in the dedicated chapter. }
4... Nd7
{ The knight move was Rubinstein's original intention, and it remains Black's main choice on all levels. Black wants to play ...Ngf6 next and challenge our centralised knight. }
5. Nf3
{ As standard as it gets. A crucial point arises on move seven, so let's fast forward to this crossroads. }
5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+
{ This looks like White's best. There is a wide range of options on the next move, though. }
6... Nxf6 7. Be3
{ White has a wide range of options here. It is tough to decide, as  7.c3  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.g3  all seem to give White a small pull, but not more.  I ultimately decided to recommend @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be3  ,  as I felt it is the easiest to play. The idea is twofold: we stop Black's pawn push ...c5 for the moment and get one move closer to queenside castling. If Black continues their kingside development and castles, we'll play Bd3, followed by Qe2 and O-O-O.  We'll focus on 7...Bd6 now, when we apply this idea. }
7... Bd6
{ Black can also prepare kingside castling with  7...Be7  ,  when our reaction would be the same: Bd3, Qe2 and O-O-O. In a few moves, I'll show a position where the difference between the two bishop positions is relevant.   An entirely different idea is  7...Nd5  , when  8.Bd2  c5  9.Bb5+  Bd7  10.Bxd7+  Qxd7  11.c4  is better for White. Black can't play  11...Nf6?  12.Ne5  @@StartBracket@@followed by Qa4+@@EndBracket@@ and must play the knight to the bad b6-square. }
8. Bd3 { According to plan. We want to go Bd3, Qe2 and castle queenside. } 8...
O-O
{ Black usually castles kingside here.  They can play for queenside castling, but it takes a while to accomplish and feels passive. After  8...Bd7  9.Qe2  Qe7  10.O-O-O  O-O-O  11.c4  we are better due to our space advantage. A good alternative is @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/pppbqppp/3bpn2/8/3P4/3BBN2/PPP1QPPP/2KR3R w - - 8 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd2  Nd5  12.g3  - it stops further exchanges and makes the space advantage more pronounced. }
9. Qe2 { The next step. } 9... b6
{ The only active way for Black to develop their bishop. } 10. O-O-O Bb7 11.
Bg5 { Pinning the knight looks like the most powerful move. } 11... h6
{ Black's game is not easy to play.   Here  11...c5?  loses on the spot to  12.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.Qd3+  , a nice tactic. }
12. Bh4
{ Black is under some pressure, and it isn't easy to defend. In some GM games, the move  12...Be7  was tested now. I like  13.Ne5  , when Black's most obvious ideas are the knight moves.   A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pbp1bpp1/1p2pn1p/4N3/3P3B/3B4/PPP1QPPP/2KR3R b - - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nd7?  14.Bg3  is great for White. After  14...Nxe5  15.Bxe5  our bishops are hitting Black's kingside, with Qg4 ideas to come.   B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pbp1bpp1/1p2pn1p/4N3/3P3B/3B4/PPP1QPPP/2KR3R b - - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nd5  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  15.Qe4!  f5  16.Qf3  also looks good for White. We have provoked ...f5 and Black's counterplay idea  16...c5  17.dxc5  Rfc8  18.c6!  Bxc6  19.Nxc6  Rxc6  gives White a choice between  20.Bxf5  and @@StartFEN@@r5k1/p3q1p1/1pr1p2p/3n1p2/8/3B1Q2/PPP2PPP/2KR3R w - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Rhe1  ,  which looks even more promising.My overall conclusion is that the plan based on 7.Be3 and queenside castling looks like a good try to keep an advantage. Black has to play a sharper position than they likely aimed for. }
