[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – French & Caro-Kann"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide to the French Defense and the Caro-Kann.  The French Defense 1.e4 e6 and the Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 are frequently played on all levels and rank third and fourth in popularity charts - usually, the French is slightly ahead. Still, on the master level, the Caro-Kann is a more popular opening. Let's examine how we approach these defenses. }
1... e6
{ The French Defense 1...e6 is popular for Black, particularly below the master level. Depending on the data, the French ranks third or fourth in popularity rankings and occurs about 10-15% of the time.  I recommend the Tarrasch Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , the favourite move of many players who prefer to exert pressure from a position of safety.  A key difference to the Exchange Variation is that we keep the central tension and do not determine the pawn structure. The move 3.Nd2 looks more passive than 3.Nc3, but has two advantages over 3.Nc3 -  we prevent the ...Bb4 pin and still have c2-c3 supporting our center.   Let's discuss our coverage in the Quickstarter. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  , it is split as follows.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.e5  leads to a typical French pawn center and a space advantage for White. In my mind, White reaches an advantage in many ways. I recommend a setup based on f4, which is very difficult for Black to handle.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  is Black's second main line. I suggest  4.Ngf3  , when Black frequently accepts an Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. A sample line is  4...Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  . White has good chances for a comfortable pull here. A better alternative for Black is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  , which currently looks like Black's best line against the Tarrasch. Black should get equal chances with perfect play.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ We also look at  3...dxe4  , the solid Rubinstein Variation Black has rarer moves, which are discussed in the sidelines chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nd2
{ Against the Tarrasch, Black's most popular replies are 3...Nf6 and 3...c5. We will check these two main options and 3...dxe4, which enjoys considerable popularity below the master level. }
3... Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn and tells us they want to play a true French-style position. We are happy to advance our pawn and gain space. }
4. e5
{ We advance the e-pawn and establish the typical 'French' pawn center. The next moves are more or less mandatory, so I'll explain why I think this particular version of the French center is favourable for us. }
4... Nfd7 5. c3
{ I want to play the moves c3 and f4 to support our center.   The order of these moves does not matter, it is just as good to start with  5.f4  and after  5...c5  6.c3  reach the same position. }
5... c5 { Black needs to attack our center quickly. } 6. f4
{ White has a wide choice of variations. The main alternatives for White are  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ne2  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP1N1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ngf3  ,  which also gives White good chances to keep a small advantage. However, I have always thought that the ambitious f4 line must be a critical test of Black's game, as White tries to grab as much space as possible and challenges Black to find any counterplay. In my mind, Black is worse and needs to be precise to avoid being hopelessly passive.  What's the difference to other, similar lines in the French? This is best explained after the next moves are on the board. }
6... Nc6
{ Black almost always plays this logical move first.   They could start with  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  , and then play  7...Nc6  8.Ndf3  , which leads to a similar position. }
7. Ndf3
{ This is much better than  7.Ngf3  ,  when our knights step on each other's toes. We better keep the knight on g1 for the moment and later decide if e2 or h3 are the best squares to get it into the game.Now let's see why I think White is in good shape here. We have a nice version of the French pawn center, which becomes clearer if we compare it to two other lines.   A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nf3  - Advance Variation.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.f4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.Be3  - Classical Steinitz.In A, Black has not yet developed the g8-knight. This is helpful, as the knight quickly reaches the good square f5. The knight is well-placed there, putting pressure on d4. In the Tarrasch, the knight is on d7, a much worse square. The knight might support ...f6 at some point, but it mostly clogs up the queenside development. In the Advance, Black's pieces are not standing on each other's toes that much.In B, the Classical Steinitz, Black's setup is identical to the one we have here. Therefore this comparison is the most instructive. In the Steinitz, White has a knight on c3. Thus they don't manage to keep a pawn on d4 by covering it with c3. A key element for Black is the capture on d4, followed by piece pressure.The current main line of the Steinitz is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.f4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.Be3  cxd4  8.Nxd4  Qb6  ,  when Black starts a direct counterplay against d4 and b2. In the Tarrasch, Black also frequently plays the move ...Qb6, but we always keep a pawn on d4, maintaining our space advantage.So is Black just much worse here, and it's all fun and an easy win for us? No, it is not that simple. I think our position is good and advantageous, but there is a drawback. We have neglected development a bit, and we need to be careful not to overextend and run into a counterblow. We'll often push more pawns on the kingside to attack. This can backfire if executed carelessly. We must examine Black's possible replies.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qb6  is the main reply. Black puts pressure on our d-pawn and prevents our natural development move Bd3.  B. Black can make a slower move that does not put pressure on d4. They can't afford this slow type of play, in my mind. If Black plays something strange, we continue with Bd3 and Ne2, supporting our center and preparing to castle. There is a reason why Black usually goes for a quick ...Qb6: to prevent this natural development. If we finish our development undisturbed, Black is in trouble - they have too little space and counterplay. We'll examine 7...Be7 in the Quickstarter to illustrate the passive setups. }
7... Qb6
{ Black increases the pressure on our center and makes it more difficult for us to develop our pieces. We currently can't play  8.Bd3?  ,  as it blunders our d-pawn. Playing Be3 also won't work, as the queen attacks b2. These are the key reasons why 7...Qb6 is the main line and Black's most popular move. How to react? }
8. a3
{ I award an exclamation mark to the move because I am fascinated by the idea. This move always annoyed me when I still played the French Defense with Black. I wanted to play this line with Black but never found a good solution against it. This all dates back to the pre-engine era. At the time, I didn't even properly understand the idea of the move. Now I got the chance to analyze it with modern technology and am happy to show you what it is all about.   What does  8.a3  do? We need to consider some points.◉ Black exerts pressure on d4 and b2. The most problematic point is that we can't play Bd3, as d4 is under attack.◉ How do we develop the kingside if Bd3 is impossible? It is unattractive to play 8. Ne2,  as it takes Bd3 completely out of the picture. And where is the knight going next? What about developing the knight to h3? After  8.Nh3  , Black has  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Bb4+  when we need to play  10.Kf2  f6!  ,  leading to a slightly uncomfortable situation. We have seen that moving the king to f2 is an option, but it is awkward with a knight on h3.◉ This leads to the conclusion that there is no promising piece development. That leaves the moves  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.g3  and  8.h4  , which have been tested numerous times. The move  8.h4  is the more interesting of the two, as it grabs a lot of space on the kingside. It turned out that the best reply to  8.h4  is the surprising move  8...a5!  ,  when Black intends to push the pawn to a4 and possibly a3 to create weaknesses on the queenside.◉ So Black has the idea to push the a-pawn up the board. This is where  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.a3!  comes into play. Its purpose is not to play b2-b4, which you might think at first. We want to be ready to meet  8...a5  with  9.b3!  ,  stopping Black's queenside play. Once this counterplay is stopped, our job gets a lot easier. We can still play h4 to start the kingside expansion - it will frequently be our next move.It is fascinating to analyze this line, as you frequently get the impression that Black is running out of constructive moves. Many normal-looking moves turn out to be mistaken. Let's consider Black's options now.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a5  is the most popular move, claiming some queenside space. It also stops b2-b4, but the pawn advance was not our main intention. We answer with  9.b3!  , when Black's queenside campaign is stopped.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  develops and aims at kingside castling. It is important to see that we don't play  9.b4  against it, but  9.h4  , which is significantly stronger and similar to @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a5  9.b3  Be7  10.h4  , the main path.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  is frequently played but has little independent value. It leads to worse versions of other lines that don't convince.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...f6?!  is questionable and rare at this point. as we have the strong move  9.Bd3  - our d-pawn is tactically covered now.  E. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...c4?!  shuts down the queenside and gives us a free hand to play on the kingside. We can immediately expand with  9.h4  or go for a slower approach with  9.Qc2  to prepare Be3 and develop pieces. We have a large space advantage on the kingside, so there is no rush. }
8... a5
{ Black stops a possible b2-b4 and grabs some space on the queenside. This move is the most popular and the current chapter's main line. An important point of Black's pawn push is the idea to play ...a5-a4, fixing our pawns and allowing a later invasion on b3. Our reply takes care of this plan immediately. }
9. b3
{ 'No ...a4 for you!' I think it is the best choice to play this prophylactic move. Now there is no clear way for Black to proceed on the queenside. Another benefit of playing b3 is developing our bishop to e3, which was impossible before. The timing of this move is very sensitive, though - more about that in a minute. }
9... Be7
{ Black usually delays the capture on d4 for a moment and starts with ...Be7. This might prepare to castle, but it is unclear if Black should commit their king to the kingside. What's our best reply now? }
10. h4
{ It's funny to see that we play yet another pawn move instead of developing a piece. However, there is a method to the madness.   Currently, we don't have a good move for a minor piece. We'd love to play Bd3, but it blunders d4. The move would be possible if Black plays ...O-O or ...f6 soon, though. After  10.h4  f6?!  11.Bd3  works well, as we will see.   This is also why it makes little sense to play  10.Ne2?  now - we still want the Bd3 option, if possible. Finally, there is  10.Be3?  , but it is badly timed due to  10...f6!  ,  when Black threatens to use the unprotected bishop.  11.Bd3  cxd4  12.cxd4  fxe5  13.fxe5  Ndxe5!  shows the core of the problem.This leads to the conclusion that 10.h4 is a flexible move. We gain some space and additional options, like h4-h5 or Rh3. Now it's Black's turn, and there are plenty of options to go wrong. }
10... O-O
{ Black castles and allows our perfect piece setup!   The same type of mistake is  10...f6?!  , when  11.Bd3  is also possible.   This move will usually lead to the same positions as  10...O-O  , as after  10...f6  11.Bd3  Black will likely castle soon.   Black's best try seems to be  10...f5  , shutting the kingside down. I suggest playing  11.h5  , when Black is limited to passive defense, but it's a long way from falling apart.  The key to our success is patience. We have a clear long-term plan: playing g4 to open the kingside. This can and should be prepared thoroughly. Black can't do anything, so we have lots of time. }
11. Bd3
{ Exactly! Now they can't grab the d-pawn, as  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  Nxd4??  13.Nxd4  Qxd4  14.Bxh7+  wins the queen. Black also needs to worry about a possible greek gift sacrifice. }
11... cxd4
{ A much better move than  11...f6?  , which already allows  12.Bxh7+  with a winning attack. These lines are fun to study, but I don't want to explore them deeper in the Quickstarter. }
12. cxd4
{ I checked  12.Bxh7+  here, but it only leads to a draw after  12...Kxh7  13.Ng5  Kh6  , when we don't have a win. It's a close call for Black, but they can hold with only moves after  14.Qd3  f5  15.exf6  Nxf6  16.h5  Ne4  17.Nxe4  dxe4  18.Qxe4  Rf5  19.g4  dxc3  ... And it even continues from here. Long story short: just recapture on d4. }
12... f6
{ Black's best try is probably still  12...f5  ,  but we need to check why we can't smash on h7 now. }
13. Ne2
{ This is best, completing our desired piece setup. It's tempting to go for the Greek gift, but it does not work here. I examine the details in the dedicated chapter, of course.   The good news is: after our simple move  13.Ne2  , we are much better. I want to check one typical idea now that you need to be aware of.   Black could play @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p1nb1pp/1qn1pp2/p2pP3/3P1P1P/PP1B1N2/4N1P1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...fxe5  14.fxe5  Ndxe5?  to open the position with a sacrifice. It fails to  15.dxe5  Rxf3  16.gxf3  Nxe5  17.Nf4  , when Black has no dangerous attacking pieces. The sacrificial idea fails quite badly here, but you should always consider it an option for Black.   Black's best after  13.Ne2  is  13...f5  , or a setup with ...Rf7 and ...Nf8 to go full defensive mode. We definitely can't complain in such a scenario. }
*

