[White "Quickstarter Guide – Other Defenses"]
[Black "Philidor Defense "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter on Black's second-tier defenses. There is no commonly used name for this group of openings, but 1...e5, 1...c5, 1...e6 and 1...c6 are usually viewed as Black's main and first-tier replies. These four moves are played in about 75-85% of the games.  Black has many other options, though. These defenses are not as popular for a reason, as Black quite frequently goes for risky strategies. My recommendations in this Quickstarter and the full chapters are more aggressive than my lines against Black's main defenses. We should use the opportunity to play more aggressively here, given a chance.  Openings like 1...d6 or 1...g6 give White a wide range of options, and having some sharper lines in the repertoire makes it more versatile and fun.   What do we cover in the Quickstarter:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  The Scandinavian,  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  may lead to the Pirc after  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  , but we'll also check different options, including the Philidor with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  .   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  is the Modern Defense.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  , the Alekhine's Defense.  I decided to skip even rarer moves in the Quickstarter. In the Odds and Ends chapter, I also examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nc6  , but for the moment, you'll be doing fine without studying them. }
1... d6
{ Black starts with 1...d6, a modern-looking move. Their intentions are not yet clear, though. We'll know more on move three when they have a crucial decision. }
2. d4 Nf6
{ We'll focus on this move, as others either transpose elsewhere  @@StartBracket@@  2...g6  would lead to 1...g6 territory@@EndBracket@@ or are too obscure to warrant detailed coverage. }
3. Nc3
{ We have reached an important moment now. Black has a choice between various moves:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  is the most popular and leads to the Pirc, which we examine in the Quickstarter. Our weapon is the move  4.f4  , our general approach against early ...d6/...g6 systems like the Pirc and Modern.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  leads to the Neo-Philidor. I suggest the fascinating reply  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Rg1  . I cover this fun line in the Quickstarter, too.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  has a serious drawback for Black: we can play  4.f4!  , which gives White a comfortable advantage.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6  is the Czech Defense. It's a rare line best answered by  4.f4!  , when Black has trouble getting any counterplay against our strong center.   We answer 3...g6, 3...c6 and 4...Nbd7 with f4!, forming a consistent approach. The exception is 3...e5, which puts a pawn in the center and requires a different antidote. }
3... e5
{ This is Black's best move after 3...g6  .   Black's idea is a transposition to a Closed Philidor formation after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  , an invitation I am happy to accept. }
4. Nf3
{ A natural development move and the most challenging, I think. Taking on e5 and trading queens is not a bad alternative, but I want to play more aggressively. }
4... Nbd7
{ That's Black's main idea, but there are two possible transpositions to other chapters.   A.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  leads to the Ruy Lopez Steinitz, a welcome line for us.   B.  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  leads to the old Philidor move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  , which looks @@StartBracket@@at least@@EndBracket@@ slightly better for White. }
5. Rg1
{ Wait... what? Yes, I recommend playing this quirky move! I know it looks completely crazy at first, but hear me out. It makes a lot of sense once you have looked a bit deeper.   Before we do that, I want to reflect on my old recommendation from the first edition, the classical continuation of  5.Bc4  ,  followed by O-O. Is there anything wrong with it? Not from a quality perspective, as the move still promises an opening advantage. I noticed, however, that students had problems with the myriad of possible move orders that may happen. Black has various pawn formations, and things can get rather sophisticated sometimes.When I discovered the  5.Rg1  variation in 2018/2019, while studying Richard Rapport's games, I knew I had a cool alternative on my hands. Some years later, the idea has caught on but is still not well-known to players on the Black side.Let's discuss what we accomplish with the early rook move. The immediate intention is clear: we want to play g2-g4 next, gaining ground on the kingside. The move g4 has more than one point. The first one is the position of Black's knights. Our opponent must worry about g4-g5, as the f6-knight has no natural flight square. They certainly don't want to retreat to g8, and jumping to the edge of the board to h5 does not look ideal. The current theoretical status suggests that Black should play a quick ...h6 to secure the knight for the moment. This is not an easy decision for Black: once the pawn is on h6, Black can't ever castle kingside.Let's discuss a secondary and less obvious idea of playing g4. Once the pawn is on g4, protected by the rook, we can comfortably develop our bishop to e3, without getting annoyed by ...Ng4. This often allows a quick queenside castling.I want to add one important point: we have a good grip on the center. The famous 'rule' is that action on the flank should be met with a central counterblow. Black has no good way of doing that. Taking on d4 rather helps us, as you will see.Let's have a look at Black's options. Our choice is a fresh idea and often will hit Black by surprise. If you look at online games or games below master level, Black is usually much worse quickly, and they don't know or find the best defenses. Surprise value goes a long way!   A.  5...h5?!  is a dubious move but still frequently seen. Black stops our g4 idea but weakens the g5-square too much.   B.  5...Be7?  is very popular online and below master level. After  6.g4  , White is much better, as we will see. The bishop move is a bit too slow.   C.  5...exd4?!  6.Nxd4  is excellent for White, as the d7-knight is passive in this structure.   D.  5...g6  is a popular move. Black prepares ...Bg7 and covers the h5-square, which becomes relevant after  6.g4  Bg7  7.g5  Nh5  when the knight is protected. Still, we are better due to the offside piece.   E.  5...c6  6.g4  h6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ currently seems to be Black's best bet. This position may also arise via  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBR1 b Qkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...h6  6.g4  c6  ,  a less common move order. We play  7.Be3  b5  8.a3  and will castle queenside later.  Currently, the move 5...g6 is still the most popular and, therefore, the one I examine in the Quickstarter. }
5... g6
{ Black prepares the fianchetto and makes the h5-square a safer spot for their knight. }
6. g4
{ According to our plan, of course.   Here White has an interesting alternative worth mentioning. It is possible to delay g4 and start with  6.Be3  , which may lead to slightly different positions after  6...Bg7  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.g4  , followed by Qd2 and O-O-O.  I prefer playing 6.g4 immediately, as it is easier to remember and just as good. }
6... Bg7 7. g5 { 'Off to the rim, please!' } 7... Nh5
{ Now it's easy to describe the nature of White's advantage: the knight on the rim is dim. Our next step is completing queenside castling. }
8. Be3 { Playing Be3, Qd2 and O-O-O is very natural and strong. } 8... O-O 9.
Qd2 c6
{ Black needs some hope for counterplay and usually tries this idea, preparing ...b5. The timing of this move is difficult for Black, though. More about that in a moment. }
10. O-O-O
{ We have completed the next step and castled queenside. Black's defensive task is not easy now. In practice, they often go wrong quickly. Here are some examples of how the game could continue.   A.  10...b5??  is very common, particularly in online games.  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Qd6  wins on the spot, as Black loses c6, and everything falls apart.   B.  10...Qa5?!  11.Kb1  b5  12.a3  shows a good setup for us. We are safe on the queenside, and Black has difficulty developing a plan.  12...a6  13.dxe5  dxe5?  14.Nd5!  shows an important tactical point of playing Kb1 - we avoid the capture on d2 with a check.   C.  10...Re8  A quieter move like this might be best. We have a choice between maintaining the tension, for instance, with  11.Kb1  , or  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Bh3  , which illustrates an additional idea at our disposal. After  12...Qe7  13.Qd6  we keep some advantage in the endgame, as our pieces are more active. They also have to watch out for the e5-pawn, which will often need protection by a piece, as ...f6 is more difficult to play with a pawn on g5. }
