[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Other Defenses"]
[Black "Pirc Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter on Black's second-tier defenses. There is no commonly used name for this group of openings, but 1...e5, 1...c5, 1...e6 and 1...c6 are usually viewed as Black's main and first-tier replies. These four moves are played in about 75-85% of the games.  Black has many other options, though. These defenses are not as popular for a reason, as Black quite frequently goes for risky strategies. My recommendations in this Quickstarter and the full chapters are more aggressive than my lines against Black's main defenses. We should use the opportunity to play more aggressively here, given a chance.  Openings like 1...d6 or 1...g6 give White a wide range of options, and having some sharper lines in the repertoire makes it more versatile and fun.   What do we cover in the Quickstarter:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  The Scandinavian,  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  may lead to the Pirc after  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  , but we'll also check different options, including the Philidor with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  .   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  is the Modern Defense.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  , the Alekhine's Defense.  I decided to skip even rarer moves in the Quickstarter. In the Odds and Ends chapter, I also examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nc6  , but for the moment, you'll be doing fine without studying them. }
1... d6
{ Black starts with 1...d6, a modern-looking move. Their intentions are not yet clear, though. We'll know more on move three when they have a crucial decision. }
2. d4 Nf6
{ We'll focus on this move, as others either transpose elsewhere  @@StartBracket@@  2...g6  would lead to 1...g6 territory@@EndBracket@@ or are too obscure to warrant detailed coverage. }
3. Nc3
{ We have reached an important moment now. Black has a choice between various moves:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  is the most popular and leads to the Pirc, which we examine in the Quickstarter. Our weapon is the move  4.f4  , our general approach against early ...d6/...g6 systems like the Pirc and Modern.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  leads to the Neo-Philidor. I suggest the fascinating reply  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Rg1  . I cover this fun line in the Quickstarter, too.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  has a serious drawback for Black: we can play  4.f4!  , which gives White a comfortable advantage.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6  is the Czech Defense. It's a rare line best answered by  4.f4!  , when Black has trouble getting any counterplay against our strong center.   We answer 3...g6, 3...c6 and 4...Nbd7 with f4!, forming a consistent approach. The exception is 3...e5, which puts a pawn in the center and requires a different antidote. }
3... g6
{ Black prepares the kingside fianchetto and delays the immediate fight for central control.  They allow us to build a strong center but are confident to attack it later. Black has multiple ways to strike at our center, most importantly the moves ...c5 and ...e5.   After  3...g6  , White has a wide choice of possible systems against the Pirc. In the first edition, I recommended  4.Be3  , which remains a strong option. One drawback of my suggestion was that it allows a wide range of replies, often leading to rather sophisticated move order issues.   For this course, I decided to switch to a different reply that is considerably simpler to master: the Austrian Attack  4.f4  , White's most aggressive option. Let's discuss this further once the move is on the board. }
4. f4
{ We push the f-pawn and increase our pawn control of the center, showing our aggressive intentions. The label 'aggressive' often suggests that tactical complications lead to an additional workload. Fortunately, this is not the case here. On the contrary: our maximalist approach reduces Black's choice, as only a small set of replies are even playable. I'll present an overview after the natural continuation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg7  5.Nf3  , hang on. }
4... Bg7 { The logical follow-up to Black's third move. } 5. Nf3
{ We develop the knight to the natural square and get one move closer to kingside castling. I promised to present an overview of Black's possible replies... here it is.   A. Black immediately attacks our center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  , leading to complications that are favourable for White and tricky for Black to handle. I suggest  6.dxc5  Qa5  7.Qd3  , when  7...Qxc5  8.Be3  Qa5  9.Qb5+  gives White a substantial lead in development.   B. Black plays the flexible move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  and only after our reply  6.Bd3  decides how to fight our imposing center. }
5... O-O
{ This is Black's most popular move by far. They delay the decision about the central counterplay for a move. }
6. Bd3
{ Our concept against 5...O-O is based on kingside castling. Playing 6.Bd3 is the best way to prepare it, as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bc4?  is a mistake due to the instructive tactic  6...Nxe4!  7.Nxe4  d5  , when our central phalanx is destroyed.   After our move  6.Bd3  Black has a wide choice, but I think that only  6...Nc6  gets Black close to equal chances. This move is my recommendation in my Lifetime Repertoires: Pirc Defense. My work on this course made me appreciate the 'Austrian Attack' more.  Black's path to a good game is narrow! Let's make an overview of Black's options:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  is the best line for Black. Black plans to strike at our center with ...e5. I suggest  7.O-O  e5  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qe1  against it, a less explored option that will likely surprise Black.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Na6  prepares the move ...c5. This seems to be Black's second-best option. White often gets a dangerous attack after  7.O-O  c5  8.d5  , but Black has some counter chances.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5?  is amazingly popular, but  7.dxc5  dxc5  8.e5  gives White a large advantage.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4?  is known to be bad since Fischer's days, but still played in lower-level games. After  7.h3  , we gain the bishop pair on top of everything.  E. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6?  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6?  is far too slow. We castle kingside and play e4-e5, starting our kingside attack.  In the Quickstarter, I will take a look at 6...c5. It is not Black's best move, but a common mistake and seeing the way to exploit it helps to understand the basic idea of our setup. }
6... c5
{ This move is amazingly popular, but a mistake, I think Black sometimes confuses the move order and thinks that @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  6.Bd3  c5  are the same thing - they are not! }
7. dxc5
{ We take the pawn, the best response and just the same as after 5...c5, which is a far better moment for the pawn push. }
7... dxc5
{ Here  7...Qa5?  doesn't work due to the simple  8.cxd6  , winning a pawn. Compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.dxc5  Qa5  , our e-pawn is safely protected. }
8. e5
{ Our strategic goal in the Austrian Attack is to establish a well-protected pawn on e5 that blunts the g7-bishop. The position on the board is a perfect example of a successful realization of this strategy. }
8... Nd5
{ Black centralises the knight. We are happy to trade it and later gain time on the queen. }
9. Nxd5
{ Simple and good. After the sequence  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Qe2  , we are ready to gain time on Black's queen. }
9... Qxd5 10. Qe2
{ A strong move. We want to play Be4 next, placing the bishop in a commanding position. This is one huge asset of our f4/e5 pawn wedge: control of the e4-square.  In this case, having the pawn on c5 is a huge problem for Black. It weakens key squares, like b5 and d5, makes the bishop even stronger on e4, and serves as a target after a later Be3. }
10... Nc6
{ We'll have a look at this move to demonstrate White's setup.  The alternatives are similar or no improvement:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/pp2ppbp/6p1/2pqP3/5P2/3B1N2/PPP1Q1PP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bg4  11.Be4  Qd7  12.Be3  is much better for White, similar to our examined move.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/pp2ppbp/6p1/2pqP3/5P2/3B1N2/PPP1Q1PP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bf5  stops our idea, but  11.Bxf5  gxf5  is not a happy sight for Black, either. After  12.Be3  @@StartBracket@@or similar moves@@EndBracket@@ Black's pawn structure is a long-term problem. We are also much faster on the d-file, and c5 is vulnerable, as usual in the 6...c5 line. }
11. Be4 Qd8 12. Be3
{ You may also start with  12.c3  here and play the bishop on the next move.   White has a large advantage now, based on the strong pressure on the queenside and Black's passive g7-bishop. I don't see a good way for Black to continue. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/2p1P3/4BP2/4BN2/PPP1Q1PP/R3K2R b KQ - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nd4  13.Bxd4  cxd4  14.O-O-O  wins the d-pawn and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/2p1P3/4BP2/4BN2/PPP1Q1PP/R3K2R b KQ - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qa5+  13.c3  Bg4  14.O-O  Rad8  15.Qc4  is just one possible line to show that Black cannot hold the queenside together. }
