[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Other Defenses"]
[Black "Modern Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter on Black's second-tier defenses. There is no commonly used name for this group of openings, but 1...e5, 1...c5, 1...e6 and 1...c6 are usually viewed as Black's main and first-tier replies. These four moves are played in about 75-85% of the games.  Black has many other options, though. These defenses are not as popular for a reason, as Black quite frequently goes for risky strategies. My recommendations in this Quickstarter and the full chapters are more aggressive than my lines against Black's main defenses. We should use the opportunity to play more aggressively here, given a chance.  Openings like 1...d6 or 1...g6 give White a wide range of options, and having some sharper lines in the repertoire makes it more versatile and fun.   What do we cover in the Quickstarter:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  The Scandinavian,  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  may lead to the Pirc after  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  , but we'll also check different options, including the Philidor with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  .   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  is the Modern Defense.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  , the Alekhine's Defense.  I decided to skip even rarer moves in the Quickstarter. In the Odds and Ends chapter, I also examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nc6  , but for the moment, you'll be doing fine without studying them. }
1... g6
{ The Modern Defense starts with the moves 1.e4 g6 and incorporates various lines with a common theme. Black neglects central control for the moment and allows White to build a broad center. They plan to attack the pawn center later, often based on playing on the queenside @@StartBracket@@...a6 and ...b5@@EndBracket@@.   The Modern has an opening relative: the Pirc Defense @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  , which we examine in this Quickstarter, too.  Black frequently starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Bg7  but quickly plays the moves ...d6 and ...Nf6 to transpose into the Pirc. A sample variation for this transposition is  3.Nc3  d6  4.f4  , when  4...Nf6  gets the game into Pirc territory and might be Black's best move.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Bg7  3.Nc3  , Black has a major choice:  A.  3...d6  is the main line by a mile. We'll play  4.f4  in 'Austrian Attack' style - our approach vs the Pirc.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6  aims for a setup with ...d5. We'll also play  4.f4  and build a broad center. Black suffers from a severe lack of space and counterplay in this system.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  attacks our center with the c-pawn and aims for transposition into a Sicilian. After  4.Nf3  cxd4  , we'd reach a line that is not part of our repertoire. This is no problem, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp1pppbp/6p1/2p5/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5!  more or less refutes the whole idea. }
2. d4 Bg7 { Almost a 'premove' in Online Chess terminology. } 3. Nc3
{ As mentioned earlier, Black now mostly plays  3...d6  .  In the full chapter, we'll also examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  .  A quick briefing on how they continue:   A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5?  is dubious due to  4.dxc5  Qa5  5.Bd2!  Qxc5  6.Nd5  , when we get a strong initiative. A key idea is  6...d6?  7.Bb4  Qc6  8.Bb5!  , winning the queen.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6  is answered by  4.f4  , as usual. After  4...d5  5.e5  , we have a substantial space advantage, and Black's g7-bishop is passive. }
3... d6
{ Black's main move at this point, leading to the main lines of the Modern Defense. }
4. f4
{ Not a surprise. We always play for this formation against the ...g6-defenses. Now we'll look at some moves; here's an overview.   A.  4...Nf6  is probably the best move, but it transposes to the Pirc Defense, covered in the previous chapter.   B.  4...a6  is Black's main alternative, going for a quick queenside expansion.   C. Black could go for a Hippo setup with various moves  @@StartBracket@@  4...e6  or  4...Nd7  @@EndBracket@@  . We develop with Nf3 and Bd3 and should consider queenside castling, as Black's setup is passive.   D.  4...Nc6  is an option, but  5.Be3  @@StartBracket@@avoiding @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/2np2p1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  Bg4!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/2np2p1/8/3PPP2/2N1B3/PPP3PP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nf3  O-O  7.e5  is better for White.   We'll check 4...a6 now, Black's most important option. }
4... a6 5. Nf3
{ We continue, as usual, aiming for the setup with Nf3, Bd3 and O-O. We argue that Black's slow play on the flanks should be answered by centralisation and therefore don't stop the ...b5 idea. }
5... b5 6. Bd3
{ No surprise here. We complete our usual piece formation. Now Black has two moves that lead to similar positions, and we'll answer both with the same concept.   A.  6...Bb7  7.a4!  b4  8.Ne2  is the slightly less popular version of the same structure, as Black is a bit slower to start their counterplay.   B.  6...Nd7  7.a4!  b4  8.Ne2  is the main path.   Even worse is  6...c5?  , when  7.dxc5!  dxc5  8.e5!  is a textbook refutation in Austrian Attack style. White gets the strong, supported e5-pawn, and Black has weaknesses on the queenside. We get to use the e4-square, too. }
6... Nd7
{ Black may also start with  6...Bb7  , when we'll usually reach the same positions. }
7. a4
{ We attack Black's pawn and force it forward. The main idea is that after  7...b4  8.Ne2  White is always ready to answer ...c5 with c3, maintaining the perfect pawn center. In many other lines that look more aggressive at first, Black trades their c-pawn for White's d-pawn because White never got the chance to support d4 with the c-pawn. }
7... b4 8. Ne2
{ Now we are always ready to support our d-pawn with c3 - very comfortable. A large benefit of the 7.a4 line is that the resulting positions are relatively easy to play and not much dependent on deeper, concrete theoretical knowledge. }
8... Bb7 { Balck goes for the fianchetto. } 9. c3
{ We have two move orders that should lead to the same positions. I suggest  9.c3  c5  10.O-O  , but @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/1bpnppbp/p2p2p1/8/Pp1PPP2/3B1N2/1PP1N1PP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.O-O  c5  10.c3  will lead to the same. Black can't play without ...c5, regardless. }
9... c5
{ Black covers their b-pawn and starts attacking our center. It's bad to open the b-file with ...bxc3, as Black's bishop will be vulnerable on the open file. }
10. O-O
{ Black has tried some moves here, but there is no fully effective solution. Here's an overview:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/1b1nppbp/p2p2p1/2p5/Pp1PPP2/2PB1N2/1P2N1PP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Ngf6  is played frequently but allows  11.e5  Nd5  12.Ng5  , a dangerous attack.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/1b1nppbp/p2p2p1/2p5/Pp1PPP2/2PB1N2/1P2N1PP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...cxd4  11.cxd4  is not popular but may be best. One idea of the capture is that after a later ...Ngf6, our reply e4-e5 is less effective, as ...Nd5 places the knight on a stable square. After  11...a5  12.Ng3  Qb6  13.Be3  Ngf6  14.h3  White is undoubtedly better, but Black won't get checkmated quickly. }
10... Ngf6 { Black's most common move, but it invites a strong attack. } 11. e5
{ I suggest going for the throat immediately. It is, however, no mistake at all to play  11.Ng3  and try to play e4-e5 under even better circumstances later. Black is in serious trouble in both cases. }
11... Nd5 12. Ng5
{ White has some good alternatives, but this move is the most forceful. } 12...
h6
{ Not the best move, but I want to show the key attacking idea in a trainable. What else is there for Black?   A.  12...e6?  13.Ne4  wins on the spot, fork time on d6.   B.  12...Nc7?  13.f5  dxe5  14.fxg6  fxg6  also loses. White has multiple wins here, like  15.Bc4  ,  15.Qb3  or  15.Qc2  still crush Black.   C.  12...dxe5!  is the only move when both recaptures are excellent for White. I like  13.dxe5  more, as  13...e6  14.c4  Ne7  15.Be4  looks dominating. We have the great central squares, and Black's g7-bishop is awful. }
13. Ne6
{ Smashing on f7 should also win, but this move is cleaner and more attractive, in my mind. }
13... fxe6 14. Bxg6+ Kf8 15. f5
{ And Black is wiped out on the f-file. With perfect play, Black can still avoid a quick mate, but they will need to return the piece with something like  15...dxe5  16.fxe6+  N7f6  17.dxe5  , when we aren't even material down. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide – Other Defenses"]
[Black "Alekhine's Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter on Black's second-tier defenses. There is no commonly used name for this group of openings, but 1...e5, 1...c5, 1...e6 and 1...c6 are usually viewed as Black's main and first-tier replies. These four moves are played in about 75-85% of the games.  Black has many other options, though. These defenses are not as popular for a reason, as Black quite frequently goes for risky strategies. My recommendations in this Quickstarter and the full chapters are more aggressive than my lines against Black's main defenses. We should use the opportunity to play more aggressively here, given a chance.  Openings like 1...d6 or 1...g6 give White a wide range of options, and having some sharper lines in the repertoire makes it more versatile and fun.   What do we cover in the Quickstarter:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  The Scandinavian,  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  may lead to the Pirc after  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  , but we'll also check different options, including the Philidor with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  .   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  is the Modern Defense.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  , the Alekhine's Defense.  I decided to skip even rarer moves in the Quickstarter. In the Odds and Ends chapter, I also examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nc6  , but for the moment, you'll be doing fine without studying them. }
1... Nf6
{ Black opts for the Alekhine's Defense, a provocative opening. They attack our pawn and want us to expand in the center. Black hopes that we overextend and our center will be the subject to a counterattack. }
2. e5
{ We don't mind being provoked. Gaining space with tempo is something we are happy to do. }
2... Nd5 3. d4 d6
{ Black starts their counterattack against our center. They have no good alternative to this move. }
4. c4
{ Here  4.Nf3  is a different main line, but I am sticking with my recommendation from the first edition. }
4... Nb6
{ After 4...Nb6 White has the choice between my recommendation, 5.exd6, and the sharp Four Pawns Attack 5.f4, which is nowadays considered a critical try against the Alekhine. The Four Pawns looks like a good line, but it is tough to simplify for the context of this course.  What's more, my recommendation 5.exd6 looks in excellent shape, too. White has pressure in all lines without taking any risks. }
5. exd6
{ The Exchange Variation of the Alekhine is our repertoire choice. It still puts considerable pressure on Black without being overly theoretical. Now Black has a fundamental choice between recapturing with either c- or e-pawn. The consensus is that taking with the e-pawn is solid for Black but relatively passive. The other option is sharper but was always considered a riskier choice.  Now, while I am sticking with the choice of 5.exd6, I am changing my recommendation against both recaptures. The reason is pretty compelling: there is a much simpler approach/setup that works well in both cases and is far less prone to possible move order mishaps. The setup I am suggesting consists of Nf3, Be2, O-O and Nc3, a very natural formation.  In the 5...cxd6 line, you need to play a quick h3, while after 5...exd6, this move is not strictly necessary but still useful and should be included. Does the order of the moves matter? You are not in danger if you play a somewhat imprecise order, but my conclusion is that the following order works well after BOTH recaptures:  Play Nf3 @@StartBracket@@we are not worried about ...Bg4 early on@@EndBracket@@,Play h3 @@StartBracket@@we need this move exactly now in the 5...cxd6 line, more on that later@@EndBracket@@,Play Be2,Play Nc3,Play O-O.  You can switch Be2 and Nc3; it won't make a difference.  I'll focus on the more combative move 5...cxd6 now. If they play 5...exd6, the same setup will work fine. }
5... cxd6
{ Black goes for the non-symmetrical, more enterprising capture. Black now enjoys two center pawns; their dream scenario is mobilising the e- and f-pawns in the long run. This is usually prepared with the kingside fianchetto, followed by ...Nc6 and ...e5. As mentioned: that is Black's dream. With precise play, this won't materialise in an acceptable form for Black, if at all. }
6. Nf3
{ After  6.Nf3  , Black's most popular reply is  6...g6  , which fits well with their intention to play a later ...e5 pawn push.   We don't have to worry about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/1n1p4/8/2PP4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , as  7.h3  is good for White. After  7...Bh5  8.Nc3  e6  9.d5!  we have a large space advantage, and Black's bishop is offside. }
6... g6 7. h3
{ A crucial move order finesse!   We want to prepare kingside castling with  7.Be2  , but now  7...Bg4  comes at a better moment for Black than on the previous move.  It looks more powerful to stop ...Bg4 and ask Black about a good square for the c8-bishop. }
7... Bg7 { Black continues as planned: complete the fianchetto and castle. } 8.
Be2 { You may also play  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Be2  , leading to the same position. }
8... O-O
{ Now, Black is closer to achieving the ...e5 break after having castled. We need to show some precision with the move order now. }
9. Nc3
{ This move is a bit more precise than  9.O-O  , because after  9...e5  , we would like to play  10.Bg5  f6  11.Be3  , which can be met with  11...e4  now!   This is the reason why 9.Nc3 is more precise: we cover e4, so the pawn advance is stopped.   After  9.Nc3  , we'll examine the mentioned  9...e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/8/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  , delaying a possible central strike. }
9... Nc6
{ Black does not commit the e-pawn yet and focuses on development.   The move  9...Bf5  follows a similar idea, and after  10.O-O  Nc6  might easily lead to the same line we will examine now.   It's bad for Black to play  9...e5?!  , as  10.Bg5  f6  11.Be3  looks great for White. A key idea for White is c4-c5-opening the diagonal a2-g8. }
10. O-O
{ Completing our setup. Now Black's best move is 10...Bf5, it seems. The alternatives don't convince me at all:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/1nnp2p1/8/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 6 10@@EndFEN@@  10...e5?  is met with the typical  10...e5  11.Bg5  f6  12.Be3  , when Black has tons of weaknesses. After  12...f5  13.dxe5  dxe5  the move  14.Qb3  is nice, threatening c4-c5+ and clearing d1 for a rook. Black can't play this ambitiously and create so many weaknesses.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/1nnp2p1/8/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 6 10@@EndFEN@@  10...d5?  is met by  11.c5  Nc4  12.b3  , when the knight only has the sad square a5 available. White is much better here, of course. }
10... Bf5
{ A healthy development move, but we still have excellent chances after it.  White has tried many moves with some success, but I want to suggest the top engine recommendation, which is strong and extremely tough for Black to play against. }
11. d5 Na5
{ That is the critical move.   After  11...Ne5  12.Nxe5  Bxe5  13.Bd2  Rc8  14.b3  we stabilize the pawn chain and have a large strategic advantage. Next, we aim to exchange dark-squared bishops with Be3/Qd2 and then Bd4. Then we can double rooks on the e-file to pile up on Black's backward e7-pawn.  Now, after 11...Na5, the issue is simple: Black attacks the c-pawn twice, and we have no way to save it. The big point is that we can sacrifice it for excellent play. }
12. Nd4
{ We force Black to take the pawn now. Otherwise, we'd play b3 and secure the chain. After  12...Bd7  13.b3  , for example, the a5-knight is stranded, and Black is in awful shape. They have to grab the c-pawn. }
12... Naxc4 { Black needs to take the pawn. } 13. a4
{ The threat is a4-a5 now, winning one of the unlucky knights.   Now Black's best is probably  13...a5  , as the alternatives look even worse:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/3P1b2/P1nN4/2N4P/1P2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - a3 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rc8  15.a5  Nd7  16.a6  opens up the c6-square for our knight.   B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/3P1b2/P1nN4/2N4P/1P2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - a3 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Na5  14.Nxf5  gxf5  15.Bd3  e6  16.Re1  gives White great play, too. We have excellent attacking chances on the kingside, with Qh5 ideas on the agenda.  After  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/3P1b2/P1nN4/2N4P/1P2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - a3 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...a5  , I suggest  14.Nxf5  gxf5  15.Bd3  , which gives White more than enough compensation for the pawn. The dedicated chapter on the Alekhine provides more information about possible alternatives. Black's problems are the multiple weaknesses and poor coordination. }
