[White "Quickstarter Guide – Other Defenses"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 3...Qd8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter on Black's second-tier defenses. There is no commonly used name for this group of openings, but 1...e5, 1...c5, 1...e6 and 1...c6 are usually viewed as Black's main and first-tier replies. These four moves are played in about 75-85% of the games.  Black has many other options, though. These defenses are not as popular for a reason, as Black quite frequently goes for risky strategies. My recommendations in this Quickstarter and the full chapters are more aggressive than my lines against Black's main defenses. We should use the opportunity to play more aggressively here, given a chance.  Openings like 1...d6 or 1...g6 give White a wide range of options, and having some sharper lines in the repertoire makes it more versatile and fun.   What do we cover in the Quickstarter:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  The Scandinavian,  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  may lead to the Pirc after  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  , but we'll also check different options, including the Philidor with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  .   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  is the Modern Defense.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  , the Alekhine's Defense.  I decided to skip even rarer moves in the Quickstarter. In the Odds and Ends chapter, I also examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nc6  , but for the moment, you'll be doing fine without studying them. }
1... d5
{ The Scandinavian enjoys considerable popularity, particularly if you examine stats for the amateur level or for online play. Therefore, we must devote some effort to studying how to fight the various branches of the Scandi.  What do we examine in the Quickstarter?  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Qa5  . The most popular and important line of the Scandi features the queen move to a5. White has no problem gaining an advantage, but we need to be precise and play aggressively. We play a setup based on Ne5 and Bc4, often connected with an attack on the kingside.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Qd8  . Black may retreat the queen on the d-file to d6 or d8. I devoted one chapter to these options and will check the main branch of the 3...Qd8 line in the Quickstarter. The retreat to d6 is covered in the full chapter.   Black can also avoid @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Qxd5  and play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  to regain the pawn. I suggest not holding the d-pawn but playing a disturbing check  3.Bb5+  . This line is covered in the Scandi Sidelines chapter. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Black has a choice of queen moves. The main line  3...Qa5  is played in about 50% of the games, while the queen retreats to d8 and d6 share the other half.  In the Quickstarter, I skip the coverage of  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qd6  . Black is under pressure in this line, as discussed in the full chapter. }
3... Qd8
{ Black retreats the queen on the safest square - on d8, it is certainly not getting into trouble soon. Still, moving the queen twice in the opening, only to return it to its initial square, can't be ideal.How do we play against 3...Qd8 then? The first step is easy. }
4. d4
{ Our natural reply against all the sensible queen moves. Now Black has two popular setups that we need to check in detail. They usually play a combination of the moves ...Nf6, ...c6 and bishop development to f5 or g4. This may happen in various move orders.   We'll examine  4...Nf6  as the main move order, but  4...c6  is possible, too. After  5.Nf3  Bg4  we can play  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  , as  7...Qxd4?  8.Bf4  is far too risky for Black. We analyse this in detail in the full chapter. An alternative without a pawn sac is  6.Be3  , which is fine as well. }
4... Nf6 { The most natural and flexible move for Black. } 5. Nf3
{ The most natural move, for sure. Now Black must decide if they want to develop the bishop to f5 or g4. If ...Bg4 is the intention, they need to start with  5...Bg4  right away. After  5...c6  , we play  6.Bc4!  , when  6...Bg4??  7.Bxf7+!  is a common tactic.Black has to resort to  6...Bf5  , when after  7.Ne5  we transpose to a position that we may also reach via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  6.Ne5  c6  7.Bc4  ,  giving White excellent chances after  7...e6  8.g4!  .  We will see that Black gets into trouble in the ...Bf5-setups. Our play is very similar to the lines we examine with the queen on a5, but Black's queen is more passive on d8. }
5... Bg4
{ This pinning move is Black's main continuation. The lines involving ...Bf5 look excellent for White, so this is no surprise. }
6. h3
{ Our usual reaction to early ...Bg4 moves in this chapter: attack the bishop immediately. Black is now more or less forced to capture our knight and give up the bishop pair. After  6...Bh5?  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  , we reach a scenario quite similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  6.Ne5  e6  7.g4  Bg6  - Sometimes, we might even get to the same positions.   One of those, and likely to occur, is  6...Bh5?  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  e6  9.Bg2  c6  10.h4  , when  10...Bb4  11.O-O  leads to a winning advantage for White. Black can try @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5nb1/4N3/3P2P1/2N4P/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nbd7  instead, but both  9.Qe2  or  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.g5  Nh5  11.d5  are awful for Black. }
6... Bxf3
{ This is forced, as  6...Bh5?  7.g4  leads to a disaster. White now gets the usual type of edge against the Scandinavian with the bishop pair and a space advantage. Black is content with a solid structure, as we will see. }
7. Qxf3 c6 { Black has to cover b7 and now attacks d4 for real. } 8. Be3
{ We develop the bishop and cover the attacked d-pawn. This move was my recommendation in the first edition, intending to castle queenside. I still like the move, but want to adjust the intended plan. I see no objective problem in castling queenside, but I think that playing with O-O is much easier to handle in practice. White's king on c1/b1 is often a potential target for ideas like ...b5, followed by ...Nd7-b6-c4, to name just one plan. }
8... e6 9. Bd3 { We develop and prepare kingside castling. } 9... Nbd7
{ We aren't worried about  9...Bb4  10.O-O  Bxc3?  11.bxc3  O-O  12.c4  ,  as our pawns do an excellent job of controlling key central squares. We have two bishops against two knights in an open position, which is a huge asset. }
10. O-O
{ Castling queenside was my recommendation in the first edition. While I still think White retains an edge, castling kingside is simpler to handle in practice and better for White. }
10... Bd6
{ Blach has also tried the bishop development to e7, but it doesn't change the evaluation and plans much. We'll discuss the strategy in a moment. }
11. Rfe1 { We'll centralise our rooks and then decide how to proceed. } 11...
O-O 12. Rad1
{ We have completed our development, reaching a position that could be in a textbook under the section 'Centralisation'. How do we continue from here, though?   The type of position is a frequent guest in several openings. In our repertoire, we could reach a similar scenario in the French Rubinstein, Fort-Knox Variation @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  dxe4  4.Nxe4  Bd7  5.Nf3  Bc6  ,  with a later ...Bxe4 or ...Bxf3 to follow@@EndBracket@@. Let's make a list of strategy pointers:  We have the bishop pair, a long-term asset. We should keep both bishops on the board, as the bishop pair will prove useful deep into the endgame.  The position is not easy to open for our bishops. As a long-term idea, playing c2-c4 and d4-d5 comes to mind, breaking the center wide open. This is a long way to materialise, though. In addition, playing the pawn to c4 has the drawback of weakening our d-pawn - We can't protect it with c2-c3 anymore. Therefore, I advise carefully considering if playing the pawn to c4 is a good idea. Often, stabilising the center with a pawn to c3 is a better idea - you can still go for c3-c4 later, anyway.  Black can't do much in terms of active play. They have the pawn breaks ...c5 and ...e5, but these might backfire as our bishops get more scope. Quite often, Black will resort to a sit-and-wait strategy. Patience is key for us. We don't need to rush anything and can try small things to progress.   I want to illustrate these points with moves taken from an online Blitz game I found, played in 2022 between K.Mekhitarian and O. Yurovskich.  12....Re8  13.Bc1  Not strictly necessary, but White is in no hurry  13...Qc7  14.g3  Rad8  15.Kg2  Continuing to make small improvements. This kingside setup makes it a bit easier to advance the h-pawn, and to have a pawn on g3 stops a possible ...Bf4 idea by Black, forever.  15...Nb6  16.Ne4!  Now we get to an interesting moment. The knight on c3 is not well placed, as it attacks nothing and blocks the c-pawn. We want the option to play the pawn to c3 to support the d-pawn. White doesn't mind the trade, so Ne4 is a good way to proceed.  16...Nxe4  17.Qxe4  g6   Now White played the move  18.c4?!  ,  which I don't like that much. It helps to restrict Black's knight but creates a target on d4. With ...Bf8-g7, Black gets something to attack.  If White plays  18.c3  instead, the center remains perfectly safe. We could continue with h4-h5 ideas and still have many options to improve our pieces. Our bishop could be well-placed on b3, for instance. This would more or less rule out any ...e6-e5 option by Black due to the pressure on f7. If Black decides to stop h4-h5 by playing ...h5, we can prepare g3-g4, of course. }
*

