1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter on Black's second-tier defenses. There is no commonly used name for this group of openings, but 1...e5, 1...c5, 1...e6 and 1...c6 are usually viewed as Black's main and first-tier replies. These four moves are played in about 75-85% of the games.  Black has many other options, though. These defenses are not as popular for a reason, as Black quite frequently goes for risky strategies. My recommendations in this Quickstarter and the full chapters are more aggressive than my lines against Black's main defenses. We should use the opportunity to play more aggressively here, given a chance.  Openings like 1...d6 or 1...g6 give White a wide range of options, and having some sharper lines in the repertoire makes it more versatile and fun.   What do we cover in the Quickstarter:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  The Scandinavian,  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  may lead to the Pirc after  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  , but we'll also check different options, including the Philidor with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  .   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  is the Modern Defense.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  , the Alekhine's Defense.  I decided to skip even rarer moves in the Quickstarter. In the Odds and Ends chapter, I also examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nc6  , but for the moment, you'll be doing fine without studying them. }
1... d5
{ The Scandinavian enjoys considerable popularity, particularly if you examine stats for the amateur level or for online play. Therefore, we must devote some effort to studying how to fight the various branches of the Scandi.  What do we examine in the Quickstarter?  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Qa5  . The most popular and important line of the Scandi features the queen move to a5. White has no problem gaining an advantage, but we need to be precise and play aggressively. We play a setup based on Ne5 and Bc4, often connected with an attack on the kingside.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Qd8  . Black may retreat the queen on the d-file to d6 or d8. I devoted one chapter to these options and will check the main branch of the 3...Qd8 line in the Quickstarter. The retreat to d6 is covered in the full chapter.   Black can also avoid @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Qxd5  and play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  to regain the pawn. I suggest not holding the d-pawn but playing a disturbing check  3.Bb5+  . This line is covered in the Scandi Sidelines chapter. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Black has a choice of queen moves. The main line  3...Qa5  is played in about 50% of the games, while the queen retreats to d8 and d6 share the other half.  In the Quickstarter, I skip the coverage of  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qd6  . Black is under pressure in this line, as discussed in the full chapter. }
3... Qa5
{ This is the traditional main line, but it is not as popular anymore, as Black players began to appreciate that the queen is a bit safer on d8 and that there is little tangible benefit in having the queen on a5. }
4. d4
{ A natural and strong move. We are now ready to develop all minor pieces and control the center well.  Sounds excellent - what does Black have? And what is our opponent's idea? In almost all cases, Black has one particular setup in mind: Develop the knight to f6, Develop the bishop to f5 or g4, if possible, Play the pawn to c6, which gives the queen some other retreat squares.   Black has various move orders that may lead to the same positions. The most popular move to start with is @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , which will be the move order we focus on.  Instead, @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  will often transpose to lines we'll examine via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  , which is more common. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's most popular and natural move.   They can also start with  4...c6  5.Nf3  , but it will often lead to the same lines:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Bc4  is a direct transposition to our main line.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  6.Ne5  Nf6  7.Bc4  also transposes to the main line.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  6.h3  will also likely transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  , as examined later. }
5. Nf3
{ 'Develop the knights before the bishops' is an old rule, often taught to players that make their first steps in learning opening play. Here it applies, too. Our knight is developed to its most active square, while we do not commit our bishops just yet. We often combine the moves Nf3 and Bc4 in the current chapter but never start with the bishop move.   Now we need to consider different options for Black:  A. They can play @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6  , staying flexible about the development of the c8-bishop. This move is the most popular on the master level.   B. Develop the bishop immediately with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  .  After  6.Ne5  c6  7.Bc4  we transpose to lines examined via A.  C. Black pins our knight with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  . This move is prevalent in online chess and at the club/amateur level. White is much better after  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  , starting an immediate attack.  D. While lines A-C are somewhat similar and sometimes transpose to one another, the fourth option @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6?  is entirely different. The move is a mistake and should be answered with  6.Bd2!  , when we operate with the idea Nb5. This line is analysed in more detail in the dedicated chapter. }
5... Bg4
{ This early bishop sortie is tremendously popular but very dubious. Let's see how to exploit this premature pin. As always, we need to play aggressively to punish Black. }
6. h3
{ 'Give me the bishop pair or allow a kingside attack... what's your choice?' }
6... Bh5
{ Black's most interesting continuation to check.   What are the alternatives?  A.  6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  is excellent for White. We have the bishop pair without having made any concessions. The way to go is Bd2, O-O-O and advancing on the kingside - what does Black have?   B.  6...Qh5??  looks fun for Black, but...  7.hxg4!  Qxh1  8.Ne2!  is a great concept. Black has no way to stop 9.Ng3, winning the queen! }
7. g4 { As usual, White needs to act quickly to exploit Black's play. } 7...
Bg6 8. Ne5
{ This is already very critical for Black. One misstep might now lead to a quick defeat, as the bishop is threatened due to h3-h4-h5. Our secondary idea is Nc4, attacking Black's queen. }
8... Nbd7
{ This move is played most often, challenging our knight.   Black can only choose between bad and worse, as the alternatives give White some leeway about how to exploit the deficits of Black's position.  A.  8...c6  9.h4  Be4  10.Nc4  Qd8  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.Qd3  Nf6  13.g5  is terrible for Black.   B.  8...e6  9.h4  Bb4  10.Bd2  Nbd7  11.Nxd7  Kxd7  12.h5  is a disaster, too.   As mentioned, these are two sample lines to illustrate Black's trouble. White also has some alternatives against these two moves that are strong. }
9. Nc4 { Black's queen is dangerously low on squares. } 9... Qa6
{ The only move, as  9...Qb4  is answered by  10.a3  and it's curtains. } 10.
Bf4
{ Probably the most powerful move, threatening Nd6+ to win the queen.   White has strong alternatives in  10.Qf3  and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pppnpppp/q4nb1/8/2NP2P1/2N4P/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne3  , though. }
10... Qe6+
{ There is no other defense against our threat, but 10... Qe6+ doesn't save Black either. }
11. Ne3
{ The best reply, because  11.Be2  Nd5  helps Black a bit.   After @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pppnpppp/4qnb1/8/2NP1BP1/2N4P/PPP2P2/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 7 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Ne3  I don't see a good defense for Black. We threaten d4-d5, followed by Nc4. This idea materialises after  11...O-O-O  12.d5  Qb6  13.Nc4  Qc5  14.Be3  Qb4  15.a3  , when we trap the unlucky queen.   A better try is @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pppnpppp/4qnb1/8/3P1BP1/2N1N2P/PPP2P2/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 8 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb6  , but  12.Nb5  Rc8  13.g5  already looks fantastic. We win material after  13...c6  14.Nc7+  Rxc7  15.Nc4!  Qb5  16.Bxc7  , and likely the game.   It's clear that @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  is a dubious move for Black. Make sure to play as aggressively as possible to exploit it. }
*

