2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Black has a choice of queen moves. The main line  3...Qa5  is played in about 50% of the games, while the queen retreats to d8 and d6 share the other half.  In the Quickstarter, I skip the coverage of  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qd6  . Black is under pressure in this line, as discussed in the full chapter. }
3... Qa5
{ This is the traditional main line, but it is not as popular anymore, as Black players began to appreciate that the queen is a bit safer on d8 and that there is little tangible benefit in having the queen on a5. }
4. d4
{ A natural and strong move. We are now ready to develop all minor pieces and control the center well.  Sounds excellent - what does Black have? And what is our opponent's idea? In almost all cases, Black has one particular setup in mind: Develop the knight to f6, Develop the bishop to f5 or g4, if possible, Play the pawn to c6, which gives the queen some other retreat squares.   Black has various move orders that may lead to the same positions. The most popular move to start with is @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , which will be the move order we focus on.  Instead, @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  will often transpose to lines we'll examine via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  , which is more common. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's most popular and natural move.   They can also start with  4...c6  5.Nf3  , but it will often lead to the same lines:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Bc4  is a direct transposition to our main line.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  6.Ne5  Nf6  7.Bc4  also transposes to the main line.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  6.h3  will also likely transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  , as examined later. }
5. Nf3
{ 'Develop the knights before the bishops' is an old rule, often taught to players that make their first steps in learning opening play. Here it applies, too. Our knight is developed to its most active square, while we do not commit our bishops just yet. We often combine the moves Nf3 and Bc4 in the current chapter but never start with the bishop move.   Now we need to consider different options for Black:  A. They can play @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6  , staying flexible about the development of the c8-bishop. This move is the most popular on the master level.   B. Develop the bishop immediately with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  .  After  6.Ne5  c6  7.Bc4  we transpose to lines examined via A.  C. Black pins our knight with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  . This move is prevalent in online chess and at the club/amateur level. White is much better after  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  , starting an immediate attack.  D. While lines A-C are somewhat similar and sometimes transpose to one another, the fourth option @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6?  is entirely different. The move is a mistake and should be answered with  6.Bd2!  , when we operate with the idea Nb5. This line is analysed in more detail in the dedicated chapter. }
5... c6
{ This is the most common move, giving the queen retreat squares. Often, this position is reached via the @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  5.Nf3  Nf6  move order. By playing ...c7-c6, Black is not yet committing where the c8-bishop will be developed. }
6. Bc4
{ We develop our bishop to the most active square. It's a simple development move but has some finer points.  We anticipate the move @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/2BP4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  and intend to answer it  7.Ne5  @@StartBracket@@tempo on f7@@EndBracket@@  7...e6  8.g4!  , starting our initiative on the kingside.  It's better to start with the bishop move and avoid @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ne5  Be6!  , which deprives us of the more active post for the bishop on c4. Black has much better chances in this line, compared to our choice.   There are cases of playing Ne5 before Bc4. These sequences are @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Ne5  and the similar @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Ne5  , which both feature early ...Bf5 moves.  A good rule of thumb is: 'We develop our bishop first, instead of Ne5, when Black develops their bishop last'. A different way to put it is: 'Our response to ...Bf5 is always Ne5. If Black delays the move, we play Bc4.'   Alright, what happens after  6.Bc4?  As usual in this chapter, Black has the choice between the bishop's moves to f5 and g4. Black does not obtain equal chances in either case, but it looks like  6...Bf5  is better than @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/2BP4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , when Black is walking on a tightrope. After  7.h3  Bh5  8.g4  Bg6  9.Bd2  Qc7  10.Qe2  Nbd7  11.Ne5  we have a substantial advantage. Black's bishop is in danger due to h4-h5, and our knight enjoys a fantastic post. }
6... Bf5
{ Developing the bishop to f5 is Black's main and more reliable option. } 7.
Ne5 { Not only attacking f7 but preparing g4 simultaneously. } 7... e6 8. g4
{ As usual, we need to play forcefully to put pressure on Black. Now they most often play  8...Bg6  , but we check @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/q3Nb2/2BP2P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQK2R b KQkq g3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be4  in the dedicated chapter, too. White has multiple ways to be much better/winning:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/q3Nb2/2BP2P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQK2R b KQkq g3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be4  9.O-O  Bd5  10.Bd3  Nbd7  11.f4  is my suggestion from the first edition, giving White a large plus.  B. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/q3Nb2/2BP2P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQK2R b KQkq g3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be4  9.O-O  Bd5  10.g5  Nfd7  11.Bxd5  cxd5  12.Nxf7!  is even better, as White gets a crushing attack after  12...Kxf7  13.Qf3+  Kg8  14.Qg4  Qb6  15.Re1  - this line is analysed in more detail in the dedicated chapter. }
8... Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7
{ Black challenges our knight, the most frequently played move.   Note that Black could play  9...Be4  , similar to 8...Be4. The only difference between the two positions is that we have the additional move h4. }
10. Nxd7
{ We trade on d7 and continue with h5 next. For Black, both recaptures are possible and lead to similar structures, but 10...Nxd7 looks more natural and better. Black can still castle queenside. }
10... Nxd7
{ By far the most popular move, still keeping the option of queenside casting. After   10...Kxd7  11.h5  Be4  12.O-O  Bd5  13.Nxd5  cxd5  14.Bd3  we reach a better version of 10...Nxd7 - Black likely needs to castle 'by hand', losing time. }
11. h5 Be4 12. O-O
{ Similar to @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1N1ppp/2p1pnb1/q7/2BP2PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Kxd7  11.h5  Be4  12.O-O!  , we castle kingside after pushing our pawns. }
12... Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3
{ An excellent moment to take stock. I prefer White here, but it is quite clearly a complicated position.  Don't be afraid of the seemingly open king position. Black does not have any attacking pieces to threaten us directly, so it is not particularly risky - that being said, it's not like being completely safe as in a typical castling scenario.  An interesting plan for Black is trying to trade the dark-squared bishop through ...Qc7 and ...Bd6.   They could continue with @@StartFEN@@@@EndFEN@@  14...Bd6  15.Bd2  Qc7  , when  16.Qf3  stops the intended plan of ...Bf4, going for the trade. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A1) Open Games – Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "1.e4 e5 – Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ Hello and welcome to the Introduction to and Overview of 1.e4 e5, the Open Games.  We start the course with 1.e4 e5, Black's symmetrical answer. It is often called 'Open Games', but whether the game opens up soon depends a lot on both players' choices. You will meet 1.e4 e5 frequently - 30% of the games sounds about right.   White has many options against 1.e4 e5 - what to play? I suggest  2.Nf3  , when we have a split between  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@by far the most popular@@EndBracket@@,  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@the Petroff@@EndBracket@@ and rare lines.  Against 2...Nc6, I suggest a different approach than in the first edition, which featured the Scotch Four Knights @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  @@EndBracket@@  .   I recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez. This might come as a surprise, as the Ruy Lopez does not have the reputation as a 'simple' opening. I agree that it is more complex than others, but it depends greatly on the choices afterward.  Learning a repertoire based on the Ruy Lopez is worth the effort for numerous reasons:It leads to interesting and fighting positions. In most lines, there are no early trades and simplifications.It's versatile. Against some defenses, we can play more aggressively in the center @@StartBracket@@c3 & d4@@EndBracket@@. In other cases, the position will be more closed, and we can drum up an attack on the kingside after shifting pieces to this side of the board. The Ruy is a great opening to learn a variety of middlegame structures.It's easy to modify later. Based on the framework you learn in this course, you can easily expand and change parts of it later. These points are key considerations for me.  'Keep it Simple' does not mean: 'Make it Boring'! Learning the Ruy Lopez is time well invested - you'll get interesting positions, challenge your opponent and teach yourself a lot about chess.   Let's get an overview of the Ruy Lopez. Black has many options against the Ruy. The best way to understand the various options is to view them on a conceptual basis.@@HeaderStart@@Black's Best Defensive Approach:@@HeaderEnd@@The best defenses for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  . In both cases, Black attacks our unprotected e-pawn. This approach looks very natural and logical. The knight is developed to its best square, and White has to worry about the e-pawn. In both cases, I recommend covering the e-pawn by play playing d3. The lines  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  are closely related and share multiple ideas.  In the first version, Black gains the additional option ...b5, which changes the position considerably. This leads us to the four most important branches of the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@A-D@@EndBracket@@:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  is a popular line for Black. They use their options to play ...b5 and then continue their kingside development most actively, playing the bishop on c5.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  is the more modest-looking version of A. Black opts for ...Be7, avoiding possible pins @@StartBracket@@Bg5 is a key idea in A@@EndBracket@@.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  . Black may react to 5.d3 differently. After we have reliably covered e4 with d3, the threat of Bxc6 and Nxe5 is serious. This leads to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bc5  , which cover the pawn - the bishop move is based on  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5??  Qd4  , when Black wins.  D. In the Berlin Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  , Black's situation is similar to C. They have to do something about their e-pawn. Therefore,  4...d6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bc5  are the moves. We handle C and D in the same style. There are plenty of parallels and transpositions. These lines are less dependent on concrete move orders but more based on concepts and understanding. We save a lot of learning effort, as we have a framework of ideas that work against two important defenses by Black.  @@HeaderStart@@Black's Old-Fashioned Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  is called the Classical Defense. Black fails to put any pressure on e4, with allows us the aggressive reply  4.c3  , intending d4 next. It's important to understand that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  is a much better version of ...Bc5, as we have already played d2-d3. In the Classical, we manage d2-d4 with a tempo on Black's bishop. White can count on advantage in the Classical, based on this concept.   F. The Steinitz Defense @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  and the Steinitz Deferred @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  . The early ...d6 does not put any pressure on our e4-pawn and blocks Black's f8-bishop. This allows us to open the position favourably with a quick d4. The Original Steinitz is a bad defense for Black, while the Deferred is a bit trickier to handle. We need the correct move orders to open the game favourably.  @@HeaderStart@@Risky/Odd Defenses@@HeaderEnd@@G. Black can play in Gambit style with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  . The second version is known to be bad for Black, while 3...f5 has the reputation of being risky but playable. I suggest a reply that is easy to handle and looks good for White.   H. Other Defenses. We have a chapter for the Odds end Ends, including defenses like the Bird @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  , Cozio @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  or Smyslov @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  .  The Bird is dubious, as it weakens the pawn structure and loses time. The Cozio and Smyslov don't put any pressure on our center and give us some leeway. I suggest a pragmatic solution based on a quick d2-d4, a similar concept as against the Steinitz.  This makes it eight chapters on the Ruy Lopez.   Let's now turn to other options for Black on move two:  • @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  . The Petroff has the reputation of being a super-solid opening for a reason. Black responds to our attack on e5 with a counter-attack on e4 and does not mind playing a symmetrical position. I suggest fighting the Petroff with  3.Nxe5  and opt for the Classical main line. It allows us to play for an advantage without taking unduly risks.   • @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Others. Well, the only good move in this chapter is  2...d6  , the Philidor Defense. We'll have an advantage, but it is still better than Black's shady gambits that I will cover, too. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A2) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ In the Open Games, Black often elects to develop their bishop to c5. In the case of the Ruy Lopez, there are several versions of this idea. This doesn't sound very easy at first, but once you categorise them, things become much simpler.  The first and most important distinction is the following: Black can play ...Bc5 after they have provoked the move d3 or without doing this first. Those two scenarios differ considerably, as provoking d3 slows White's central pawn expansion. Here is a list of these cases and where they are covered:   1. The Berlin @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  ,   2. The Anderssen @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  Bc5  ,   3. The Anderssen main line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  .  Let's turn to the content of the current chapter, where we cover the other versions. The common feature of these lines is that we manage to play a quick c3 & d4 push, expanding in the center and attacking Black's bishop. We will cover the following lines:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  is called the Classical Defense and the main subject of the current chapter. We answer with  4.c3  and can advance the d-pawn to d4 in one go next. The Classical Variation is out of fashion on the master level, as White has good chances for an advantage.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Bc5  is a rarely played, slightly improved version of the Classical. We play the same way, going for a quick c3&d4 play in the center. It's very similar to the Classical, but I will highlight two key differences you should know.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  b5  5.Bb3  Bc5  is the third version covered here. Again, we go for a quick c3 & d4 to expand in the center. This line is imprecise and leads to a nice advantage for us.  We'll examine the lines in the given order, as it is best to see the Classical first and then learn the differences from the other versions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A2) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...Bc5 4.c3 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ Black goes for the Classical Defense. As the intro to this chapter mentioned, ...Bc5 in the Ruy Lopez is a common sight. Black has many ways to employ the move, and 3...Bc5 is the earliest one.  Nowadays, the Classical is regarded as slightly imprecise, as White manages to expand in the center with c3&d4 quickly, our standard idea in the Ruy Lopez. }
4. c3
{ White has a basic choice between  4.c3  and  4.O-O  here.   The main difference between the two is  4.O-O  Nd4!  5.Nxd4  Bxd4  , which helps Black a bit. White still has chances for a small advantage, but @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c3  prevents the idea.   Playing c3 first is in sync with other choices in this chapter. Now we need to check some options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  is by far the most popular and logical move. A key line is  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  when we attack Black's knight.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  is an alternative way for Black to develop the kingside. It avoids the line mentioned in A. but puts less pressure on our center.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5?!  is a rarely played gambit and not 100% sound. We need to study it for a moment to avoid being surprised.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6?  is even worse than it looks and loses on the spot!  E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6?  is played a lot in online games, but is just a blunder, as we will see. We can take on c6 and e5 in this particular case.  Other moves shouldn't worry us, as we are ready to play d4 and castle. }
4... a6 { A mistake, but it is played incredibly often in blitz games. } 5.
Bxc6 { We go for the e-pawn. } 5... dxc6 6. Nxe5
{ With c3 on the board, Black can't regain the pawn with ...Qd4-based ideas. They need to act quickly; otherwise, we'd play d4 with tempo and protect the knight. }
6... Qg5
{ Black has set their hopes on this double attack on our knight and the g-pawn. We have an excellent reply, though.   Note that  6...Qe7  is also possible and met with the same reply. }
7. O-O
{ That's the crucial point. Black can take our knight, but we immediately get the material back. }
7... Qxe5 8. d4
{ We have a large advantage now, as Black only has a choice between bad scenarios:   A.  8...Qe7  9.dxc5  Qxc5  10.Bf4  leaves Black with a bad pawn structure and bad development,   B.  8...Bxd4  9.cxd4  is a different structure, but the same problem.  In both cases, the weak c7-pawn can become an issue, too. It does not look that important, but losing the pawn would also mean massive weaknesses on the dark squares. The moves Bf4 and maybe Qf3-g3 put a lot of pressure on it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A2) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...Bc5 4.c3 d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ Black goes for the Classical Defense. As the intro to this chapter mentioned, ...Bc5 in the Ruy Lopez is a common sight. Black has many ways to employ the move, and 3...Bc5 is the earliest one.  Nowadays, the Classical is regarded as slightly imprecise, as White manages to expand in the center with c3&d4 quickly, our standard idea in the Ruy Lopez. }
4. c3
{ White has a basic choice between  4.c3  and  4.O-O  here.   The main difference between the two is  4.O-O  Nd4!  5.Nxd4  Bxd4  , which helps Black a bit. White still has chances for a small advantage, but @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c3  prevents the idea.   Playing c3 first is in sync with other choices in this chapter. Now we need to check some options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  is by far the most popular and logical move. A key line is  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  when we attack Black's knight.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  is an alternative way for Black to develop the kingside. It avoids the line mentioned in A but puts less pressure on our center.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5?!  is a rarely played gambit and not 100% sound. We need to study it for a moment to avoid being surprised.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6?  is even worse than it looks and loses on the spot!  E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6?  is played a lot in online games, but just a blunder, as we will see. We can take on c6 and e5 in this particular case.  Other moves shouldn't worry us, as we are ready to play d4 and castle. }
4... d6
{ Not a good idea! Black creates a pin, which makes our intended d4-advance even more powerful. }
5. d4 exd4 { No choice, as  5...Bb6?  6.d5  is a sad end for Black's knight. }
6. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Again no choice, as  6...Bb6?  7.d5  is an easy win.  We should also win after 6...Bb4+, but at least we need to know/find a crucial move. }
7. Kf1
{ It looks odd to move the king, but it wins on the spot! We still threaten d4-d5, winning the knight. At the same time, Black's b4-bishop is short of squares. Black can't save both pieces! }
7... Bd7
{ The toughest defense. After other moves, it is easier.   A.  7...a6  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.Qa4  a5  10.a3  traps the bishop. Black can still play for a trick with  10...Bb7  , but  11.Qc2  will finally win the piece!   B.  7...d5  8.Qb3!  dxe4  9.Ne5  and Black loses the house. }
8. Qa4
{ The winning move. Black has no defense against the various threats, like d4-d5, Bxc6 and a3. }
