[White "A2) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...Bc5 4.c3 f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ Black goes for the Classical Defense. As the intro to this chapter mentioned, ...Bc5 in the Ruy Lopez is a common sight. Black has many ways to employ the move, and 3...Bc5 is the earliest one.  Nowadays, the Classical is regarded as slightly imprecise, as White manages to expand in the center with c3&d4 quickly, our standard idea in the Ruy Lopez. }
4. c3
{ White has a basic choice between  4.c3  and  4.O-O  here.   The main difference between the two is  4.O-O  Nd4!  5.Nxd4  Bxd4  , which helps Black a bit. White still has chances for a small advantage, but @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c3  prevents the idea.   Playing c3 first is in sync with other choices in this chapter. Now we need to check some options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  is by far the most popular and logical move. A key line is  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  when we attack Black's knight.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  is an alternative way for Black to develop the kingside. It avoids the line mentioned in A but puts less pressure on our center.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5?!  is a rarely played gambit and not 100% sound. We need to study it for a moment to avoid being surprised.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6?  is even worse than it looks and loses on the spot!  E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6?  is played a lot in online games, but just a blunder, as we will see. We can take on c6 and e5 in this particular case.  Other moves shouldn't worry us, as we are ready to play d4 and castle. }
4... f5
{ Black goes for a dubious gambit. It is rarely played, but worth a quick look so that you are not surprised by it and get confused. You only need to know one line to get a nice advantage - let's check. }
5. d4
{ Well, that was the plan. Occupying the center works well here, as the following lines show.   It's important not to confuse this situation with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  , when  4.d3  is best. Here, we can fully use the insertion of c3 and ...Bc5. }
5... fxe4
{ The only good move for Black.   The other capture  5...exd4?  is opening the position far too much and is refuted by multiple moves, like  6.e5  or  6.exf5  , both great for White. }
6. Bxc6
{ This is the cleanest solution. We take on c6 to play Nxe5 next and establish a great, centralised piece. }
6... dxc6 7. Nxe5
{ That's some strong knight! At first glance, you'd think that Black is already busted. We attack their bishop and threaten Qh5+, but things are trickier than they appear. }
7... Bd6 8. Qh5+ { Check! } 8... g6 9. Qe2
{ This move is why 4...f5 needs coverage. Here you can easily fall into Black's trap: after  9.Nxg6?  Nf6  10.Qh4  Rg8  11.Ne5  Bxe5  12.dxe5  Qd3!  13.exf6  Bg4  Black is winning!  The conclusion: we only checked on h5 to provoke the move ...g6, which permanently weakens Black's dark squares. }
9... Bf5 10. Bf4
{ We support our knight and want to complete development with Nd2 and O-O. Let's put these on the board and then look again. }
10... Nf6 11. Nd2 { Castling first also works, of course. } 11... Qe7 12. O-O
{ We have a definite advantage here, as Black's position is too weak on the dark squares, and our knight is too strong. A key idea is the move f3, which opens the f-file.   After  12...O-O  13.f3  exf3  14.Ndxf3  ideas like Bg5 and Bh6 look very annoying for Black. In fact, the engine already assesses Black's situation as hopeless.  It looks better to castle queenside for Black, but the general assessment stands: the beast on e5 is too strong. }
