[White "A2) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...Bc5 4.c3 Nge7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ Black goes for the Classical Defense. As the intro to this chapter mentioned, ...Bc5 in the Ruy Lopez is a common sight. Black has many ways to employ the move, and 3...Bc5 is the earliest one.  Nowadays, the Classical is regarded as slightly imprecise, as White manages to expand in the center with c3&d4 quickly, our standard idea in the Ruy Lopez. }
4. c3
{ White has a basic choice between  4.c3  and  4.O-O  here.   The main difference between the two is  4.O-O  Nd4!  5.Nxd4  Bxd4  , which helps Black a bit. White still has chances for a small advantage, but @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c3  prevents the idea.   Playing c3 first is in sync with other choices in this chapter. Now we need to check some options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  is by far the most popular and logical move. A key line is  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  when we attack Black's knight.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  is an alternative way for Black to develop the kingside. It avoids the line mentioned in A but puts less pressure on our center.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5?!  is a rarely played gambit and not 100% sound. We need to study it for a moment to avoid being surprised.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6?  is even worse than it looks and loses on the spot!  E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6?  is played a lot in online games, but just a blunder, as we will see. We can take on c6 and e5 in this particular case.  Other moves shouldn't worry us, as we are ready to play d4 and castle. }
4... Nge7
{ This knight development is designed to avoid the idea of  4...Nf6  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  when we attack the knight. On e7, it is more safely placed but certainly less active, too. }
5. d4
{ White has a good choice here.  The move  5.O-O  is similarly promising for White but leads to different position types. The idea is still to play d4, but castle first to prevent the idea @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppppnppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4  exd4  6.cxd4  Bb4+  , a line that I recommend allowing.   After  5.O-O  Black has the option  5...d5!?  , which leads to a completely different structure.  My main argument in favour of 5.d4  is that it is simpler to play and remember while still leading to an advantage. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Black has to give the check, as  6...Bb6  7.d5  is great for White. Our strong center pushed forward with tempo. }
7. Bd2
{ It's also perfectly possible to play  7.Nc3  here, when  7...d5  8.e5  Bg4  leads to a situation similar to the line @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  Ne4  7.O-O  d5  8.cxd4  , which is part of our repertoire.   I think Black's setup with ...Nge7 and ...Bg4 is better suited for this pawn formation, but it could be a matter of taste. Stockfish assesses it as better for White, regardless.  In any case, I think that 7.Bd2 is a good solution, as the following line shows. }
7... Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2
{ I want to use the knight on c3 later and, therefore, capture with the queen. Now Black has little choice: they need to push the pawn to d5, stopping our threat of advancing in the center. }
8... d5
{ Black can insert  8...a6  9.Ba4  d5  , which is a fun transposition to the line  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Bc5  , also covered in this chapter. }
9. exd5
{ We go for a concrete solution. After our capture, Black is worse after both possible replies. }
9... Qxd5
{ The more interesting move to check.   After  9...Nxd5  10.Bxc6+  we are better due to Black's wrecked pawn structure. }
10. Nc3 Qd8
{ Here  10...Qe6+  11.Kf1  is no improvement. A quick Re1 will be dangerous for Black. }
11. d5 a6 { Black is just about saving the piece. } 12. Ba4 b5 13. Bc2
{ We have a pleasant advantage here. Black's knight has to settle for a bad spot now, and we have excellent central control and more active pieces. }
