[White "A2) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...Bc5 4.c3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ Black goes for the Classical Defense. As the intro to this chapter mentioned, ...Bc5 in the Ruy Lopez is a common sight. Black has many ways to employ the move, and 3...Bc5 is the earliest one.  Nowadays, the Classical is regarded as slightly imprecise, as White manages to expand in the center with c3&d4 quickly, our standard idea in the Ruy Lopez. }
4. c3
{ White has a basic choice between  4.c3  and  4.O-O  here.   The main difference between the two is  4.O-O  Nd4!  5.Nxd4  Bxd4  , which helps Black a bit. White still has chances for a small advantage, but @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c3  prevents the idea.   Playing c3 first is in sync with other choices in this chapter. Now we need to check some options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  is by far the most popular and logical move. A key line is  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  when we attack Black's knight.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  is an alternative way for Black to develop the kingside. It avoids the line mentioned in A but puts less pressure on our center.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5?!  is a rarely played gambit and not 100% sound. We need to study it for a moment to avoid being surprised.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6?  is even worse than it looks and loses on the spot!  E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6?  is played a lot in online games, but just a blunder, as we will see. We can take on c6 and e5 in this particular case.  Other moves shouldn't worry us, as we are ready to play d4 and castle. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ No surprises here - we played c3 for a reason.   Black's only good move is the capture, but we need to check why  5...Bb6?  fails. The refutation is convincing, but it is pretty wild. }
5... Bb6
{ This move more or less loses against perfect play, but the resulting positions are messy. Let's see how we refute it. }
6. Nxe5
{ We grab the pawn, and Black only can get it back with the following line. }
6... Nxe5
{ Taking e4 immediately fails to  6...Nxe4  7.Qg4  , which is even more powerful than after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/1bn2n2/1B2N3/3PP3/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nxe5  7.dxe5  Nxe4  8.Qg4  , which we will examine shortly.   A different way to disaster is  6...Qe7  7.Bxc6  dxc6  8.O-O  Nxe4  9.Re1  , when Black loses on the e-file. }
7. dxe5 Nxe4 { Black has two pieces on our f2-pawn, what to do? } 8. Qg4
{ Well, we don't defend... but rather attack! Now our queen attacks both the knight and the g7-pawn. Black has only one fighting reply: taking f2 with a check. }
8... Bxf2+
{ The only interesting move. Black is lost anyway but needs to put up the best fight.   There is not much of that in  8...Nxf2  10.Qxg7  Rf8  11.Bg5  and 'Resigns', probably. }
9. Ke2
{ In a purely tactical position, it is often difficult to talk about general considerations or logic. Here, however, the king move to e2 looks logical, as we still keep the bishop attacked and leave f1 free for our rook at a later stage. Now Black only has one move, not to lose a piece by simple means. }
9... Qh4
{ Only move for Black. We need to continue a bit more, and the moves are completely forced for a while. }
10. Qxg7 { We take g7 and attack the rook. } 10... Rf8
{ Again, the only move. } 11. Bh6
{ A development move with a tempo, forcing Black's reply. } 11... Bc5
{ This sequence is more or less forced after 5...Bb6?, which is why we need to go that deep. White has one move that wins; all the others lose! }
12. Nd2
{ Admittedly, the move 12.Nd2 looks logical here, but it is strictly the only one that avoids defeat and should win!  The problem for White is that our king is somewhat exposed, but Black is only attacking with three pieces. If we manage to trade the knight, our king position will be much safer. Black can't involve the queenside in the attack while we are ready to use our rooks. }
12... Qf2+
{ This pushes back our king to d1, at least.   Alternatives like  12...Qh5+  13.g4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/1bn2n2/1B2N3/3PP3/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  12...Nxd2  13.Kxd2  Qf2+  14.Be2  are even easier for us to convert. }
13. Kd1 Nxd2 { Again, no choice for Black, as we attacked the knight. } 14.
Bxd2
{ Here, we can conclude that White is much better or winning if we want to quote the engine. I think it is understandable in human terms, too. Our king will find a safe spot on c2, and Rf1 is coming with a tempo. Black's queenside is still not involved in the game.   While this is convincing, I want to mention that Stockfish does not think the normal  14.Bxd2  is the best move!   It wants to play the crazy  14.Re1  and claims it wins even faster. I don't want to go there, as the human move is perfect enough, and we are already deep down the rabbit hole. I usually avoid these long lines for an early deviation, but 5...Bb6? is a huge mistake, and the refutation runs this deep. Learn this line and win! Even GMs have sometimes allowed all this and lost quickly! }
