4... Nf6 5. d4
{ No surprises here - we played c3 for a reason.   Black's only good move is the capture, but we need to check why  5...Bb6?  fails. The refutation is convincing, but it is pretty wild. }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ We don't want to play  6.cxd4?  Bb4  , which is fine for Black. Attacking the knight with e4-e5 is much better for us and leads us to an instructive point.   Have you wondered why @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  is considered super sound for Black, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Bc5  is a slightly dodgy defense? One reason becomes apparent here.  In the Italian, there is the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  , when  6...d5!  7.Bb5  Ne4  8.cxd4  Bb6  is the best defense for Black. Note that Black hits White's bishop. It has to move to b5 using two tempi. In the Ruy, we already have the bishop on b5! Black does not have the ...d5! reply with a tempo and has to move their knight now.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ne4  likely leads to the Italian line mentioned above with a full extra tempo, giving us a nice pull.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd5  is the alternative for Black.  C. Black can't play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qe7??  , as  7.O-O  Nxe5  8.Nxe5  Qxe5  9.Re1  looks like a bad day at the palace for Her Majesty. }
6... Nd5
{ This move is playable, but most opponents won't know or find the key idea on the next move. }
7. O-O
{ It's super important to play this move first and not allow  7.cxd4?  Bb4+  giving Black a good game.  Now we threaten cxd4 under much better circumstances. We have reached a fascinating moment, as now Black only has one good move, but it is almost never played!   After  7.O-O  , the most popular move is  7...O-O?  , but we easily reach an overwhelming position against it.   The only good move for Black is the strange retreat  7...Be7!  , but this move is played in less than 5% of the games. It is tough to find and unlikely to be prepared.   I will take a closer look at main move  7....O-O  now, as it is far more relevant in practice.   What should you do after  7...Be7  , then? Fortunately, we still have an advantage against the move by simple means. I suggest  8.cxd4  d6  9.exd6  Qxd6  10.Re1  O-O  11.Nc3  , when we have the much better coordinated and active pieces in this wide-open position.   Still, this is not close to lost for Black by any means, while after  7...O-O  , we are getting there. }
7... O-O
{ Black is in terrible shape now. We will take on d4, followed by an attack on the unprotected d5-knight. }
8. cxd4 Bb6
{ They can also try  8...Be7  9.Qb3  Nb6  10.d5  Nb8  11.Nc3  , but this is no fun, either. }
9. Bc4 { Much better than  9.Qb3  Nde7  , when Black is still alive. } 9...
Nce7
{ Or  9...Nde7  10.d5  Na5  11.Bd3  , which looks even worse. Tough to tell; all these lines look a bit like games that Morphy played against some business tycoon who thought that chess was a rather simple game and issued an ill-advised challenge. }
10. Bg5 { Developing with tempo is fun. } 10... Qe8
{ Or  10...c6  11.Bxd5  cxd5  12.Nc3  , when Black should probably resign. }
11. Nc3
{ I think we can stop this trainable line here before it gets too bloody on the board. We have an overwhelming position and will probably win a miniature. }
