{ Black goes for the Classical Defense. As the intro to this chapter mentioned, ...Bc5 in the Ruy Lopez is a common sight. Black has many ways to employ the move, and 3...Bc5 is the earliest one.  Nowadays, the Classical is regarded as slightly imprecise, as White manages to expand in the center with c3&d4 quickly, our standard idea in the Ruy Lopez. }
4. c3
{ White has a basic choice between  4.c3  and  4.O-O  here.   The main difference between the two is  4.O-O  Nd4!  5.Nxd4  Bxd4  , which helps Black a bit. White still has chances for a small advantage, but @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c3  prevents the idea.   Playing c3 first is in sync with other choices in this chapter. Now we need to check some options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  is by far the most popular and logical move. A key line is  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  when we attack Black's knight.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  is an alternative way for Black to develop the kingside. It avoids the line mentioned in A but puts less pressure on our center.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5?!  is a rarely played gambit and not 100% sound. We need to study it for a moment to avoid being surprised.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6?  is even worse than it looks and loses on the spot!  E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1Bb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6?  is played a lot in online games, but just a blunder, as we will see. We can take on c6 and e5 in this particular case.  Other moves shouldn't worry us, as we are ready to play d4 and castle. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ No surprises here - we played c3 for a reason.   Black's only good move is the capture, but we need to check why  5...Bb6?  fails. The refutation is convincing, but it is pretty wild. }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ We don't want to play  6.cxd4?  Bb4  , which is fine for Black. Attacking the knight with e4-e5 is much better for us and leads us to an instructive point.   Have you wondered why @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  is considered super sound for Black, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Bc5  is a slightly dodgy defense? One reason becomes apparent here.  In the Italian, there is the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  , when  6...d5!  7.Bb5  Ne4  8.cxd4  Bb6  is the best defense for Black. Note that Black hits White's bishop. It has to move to b5 using two tempi. In the Ruy, we already have the bishop on b5! Black does not have the ...d5! reply with a tempo and has to move their knight now.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ne4  likely leads to the Italian line mentioned above with a full extra tempo, giving us a nice pull.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd5  is the alternative for Black.  C. Black can't play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qe7??  , as  7.O-O  Nxe5  8.Nxe5  Qxe5  9.Re1  looks like a bad day at the palace for Her Majesty. }
6... Ne4
{ Jumping to e4 is Black's best defense. We still have better chances if we play well. }
7. O-O
{ This is better than  7.cxd4  Bb4+  , when Black manages to trade some material. We want to take it under better conditions.   Note that @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd5  is also answered by  7.O-O  , which makes it easier to remember. }
7... dxc3
{ A mistake, but the refutation is not as trivial as you might think at first. }
8. Qd5
{ That's a typical tactic, attacking the loose pieces on e4 and c5. Black has no way to save both by simple means. }
8... Bxf2+
{ The only challenging move.   After  8...f5  9.exf6  White wins on the spot, while @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1BbQP3/4n3/2p2N2/PP3PPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...c2  9.Qxe4  cxb1=Q  10.Rxb1  gives us a dominating position. This one is fun to explore a bit deeper, as White almost seems to win by force, but it's not necessary to prove that for our purposes. }
9. Rxf2 Nxf2 { Now is why we need to check this line at all. } 10. Nxc3
{ This is a much better move than  10.Kxf2?  cxb2  11.Bxb2  , when matters are not that clear. We want to take the knight under more favourable circumstances on the next move; thus, Black's only real try is to try to escape with it. }
10... Ng4 11. h3
{ White has more than one good move here.   Alternatively,  11.Qe4  is also strong, but  11...d5!  12.exd6+  Kf8  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.h3  Nf6  15.Qxc6  Bd7  16.Qxc7  is still not an easy win.  I think @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B1QP3/6n1/2N2N2/PP4PP/R1B3K1 w kq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.h3  is a more practical solution, but it's a tough call. Now Black needs to give the piece as  11...Nh6??  12.Bxh6  gxh6  13.Ne4  is killing. The best is probably @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B1QP3/6n1/2N2N1P/PP4P1/R1B3K1 b kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ngxe5  12.Nxe5  O-O  13.Nf3  , when we have a strong attack with Qh5 coming next. }
