5... exd4 6. e5
{ We don't want to play  6.cxd4?  Bb4  , which is fine for Black. Attacking the knight with e4-e5 is much better for us and leads us to an instructive point.   Have you wondered why @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  is considered super sound for Black, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Bc5  is a slightly dodgy defense? One reason becomes apparent here.  In the Italian, there is the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4  exd4  6.e5  , when  6...d5!  7.Bb5  Ne4  8.cxd4  Bb6  is the best defense for Black. Note that Black hits White's bishop. It has to move to b5 using two tempi. In the Ruy, we already have the bishop on b5! Black does not have the ...d5! reply with a tempo and has to move their knight now.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ne4  likely leads to the Italian line mentioned above with a full extra tempo, giving us a nice pull.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd5  is the alternative for Black.  C. Black can't play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qe7??  , as  7.O-O  Nxe5  8.Nxe5  Qxe5  9.Re1  looks like a bad day at the palace for Her Majesty. }
6... Ne4
{ Jumping to e4 is Black's best defense. We still have better chances if we play well. }
7. O-O
{ This is better than  7.cxd4  Bb4+  , when Black manages to trade some material. We want to take it under better conditions.   Note that @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1P3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd5  is also answered by  7.O-O  , which makes it easier to remember. }
7... d5
{ Black's best defense here.   It's mandatory to put a pawn in the center and stop us from a further advance. A line to show the problem is  7...O-O?  , when  8.cxd4  Bb6  9.d5  gives us a central steamroller that Black should not survive. }
8. cxd4
{ I think this is the most promising move, but White has some good lines available, like  8.exd6  and  8.b4  , which is a yet untested engine suggestion. It's always nice to have options, but let's see how my choice unfolds. }
8... Bb6
{ The bishop is best placed on b6, keeping some pressure on our center. } 9. h3
{ I'd like to stop a possible pin first. Let's discuss the strategy of this position after the next pair of moves. }
9... O-O 10. Nc3
{ This position is not easy for Black to play. We have some fairly simple ideas that can prove very effective:  Put pressure on the e4-knight and try to provoke a capture on c3. This would be huge for us, as we managed to trade Black's best piece and support our d4-pawn. We have a space advantage on the kingside anyway, based on the e5-pawn.The capture on c6 can be an idea if we prevent Black's b6-bishop from becoming active.Black often attacks our pawn chain with ...f6. In this case, we often get control of the e5-square, ideal for a knight.  Let's explore some lines to illustrate these concepts. }
10... Bf5
{ Black develops their last minor piece, a logical move. There are some worse alternatives:   A.  10...Nxc3?  11.bxc3  gives us a dream position. Our Ruy bishop will find a fantastic spot on d3, looking at the kingside. Black's queenside pieces are just spectators, not defenders.   B.  10...f6  11.exf6  Rxf6  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.Be3  Qe8  14.Ne5  is nice for White, too. Our e5-knight is a monster, but Black has some active pieces on the kingside. }
11. Be3 { We support our d-pawn first, completing our development. } 11... Ne7
{ Black wants to stop worrying about Bxc6 and removes the knight. } 12. Bd3
{ We increase the pressure on e4. Our bishop had no job on b5 after Black's last move. I want to stop the trainable line now and close with some more ideas and sample lines.   A.  12...Qd7  is nicely met with  13.Nh4  , when Blach has problems with their knight support, and the same applies to @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp1nppp/1b6/3pPb2/3Pn3/2NBBN1P/PP3PP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 6 12@@EndFEN@@  12...c6  13.Nh4  .   B.  12...Rc8  13.Qb1!  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/ppp1nppp/1b6/3pPb2/3Pn3/2NBBN1P/PP3PP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 7 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qc2  c5!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/ppp1nppp/1b6/3pPb2/3Pn3/2NBBN1P/PP3PP1/RQ3RK1 b - - 8 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nxc3  14.bxc3  Bxd3  15.Qxd3  h6  16.Rfb1  , planning a4-a5, is excellent for White.   C.  12...f6  13.Qc2  fxe5  14.Nxe5  Nd6  15.Bg5  Bxd3  16.Qxd3  gives White some pressure. The move ...f6 is understandable from Black's perspective, but it creates weaknesses, and our pieces are actively placed. Black's bishop on b6 is missing as a kingside defender, too. }
