[White "A2) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ Now we have two more versions of any early ...Bc5 to check. Black can play it right away or after inserting the move ...b5. }
4... Bc5
{ One of Black's early ...Bc5 lines, and a scarce one. I considered not covering it, but I noticed some strong players recently employed it.  It is a slightly better version of 3...Bc5, but the differences are subtle. In some cases, Black gets to play ...Ba7, for example, or the move ...b5 can still be played in some lines, which changes the situation.  So what do we play against it? It is rather simple: the same concept that we play against 3...Bc5 works well. I'll go through this quickly and highlight two differences between the two lines. }
5. c3
{ Going for a quick c3&d4, as we always do against these early ...Bc5 lines. Now we'll check Black's knight moves to f6 and e7.   The move  5...b5?!  6.Bb3  is great for White and covered in the current chapter via  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  5.Bb3  Bc5?!  6.c3  , leading to the same position. }
5... Nf6
{ This looks more natural and active, but the concrete lines work out well for White. Compared to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.c3  Nf6  , there is one crucial difference, though. }
6. d4 Ba7
{ In this line, there is a huge difference to 3...Bc5. It is a very rare position to occur, but if you'd play in the same way as you'd do after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4  Bb6  , you are in trouble!   Before we check the difference, a word about @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/2b1p3/B2PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...exd4  , which is a slightly worse version for Black, compared to 3...Bc5. The key lines  7.e5  Ne4  8.O-O!  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/2b5/B2pP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e5  Nd5  8.O-O  work even better for White, as a timely Bb3 can sometimes be an improvement.  A deeper study of the difference is not warranted, as you don't have to find anything special here. Now back to 6...Ba7, when you need to know something special! }
7. Nxe5
{ This capture is fantastic for White in the 3...Bc5 line, while here it is just leading to an advantage. We'll see a crucial tactical difference after the next forced moves. I'll give them without deeper annotation, as the start is identical. }
7... Nxe5 8. dxe5 Nxe4 9. Qg4 { Double attacking the knight and g7-pawn. } 9...
Bxf2+ 10. Ke2 Qh4 11. Qxg7 Rf8
{ A somewhat crazy sequence, but forced after we captured on e5. Here comes the crucial difference to the other line - let's see this sequence in full: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4  Bb6  6.Nxe5  Nxe5  7.dxe5  Nxe4  8.Qg4  Bxf2+  9.Ke2  Qh4  10.Qxg7  Rf8  is a similar position. In this line  11.Bh6  Bc5  12.Nd2!  more or less wins the game, as we get to trade Black's best piece.  The same idea would not work here, as our bishop is on a4! If we'd play @@StartFEN@@r1b1kr2/1ppp1pQp/p7/4P3/B3n2q/2P5/PP2KbPP/RNB4R w q - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bh6??  Bc5  , we are already lost, as  13.Nd2  Nxd2  14.Kxd2  Qxa4  drops a piece.  Alright, if not 12.Bh6, then what do we play? }
12. b4
{ The only move that works! I have to admit I like the logic: we secure our bishop on the fourth rank and remove the c5-square from Black so that ...Bc5 is stopped. This way, the move Bh6 becomes a deadly threat again.  The position is very messy, of course. You could analyse this in great detail and with plenty of trainables, but the whole 4...Bc5 line is rarely seen. The main danger for you is not knowing this 12.b4! move and thinking that it is just the same as after 3...Bc5.  Still, I can't just stop here but need to make an assessment. Black only has one playable line now.   A.  12...Qh5?  13.g4  Qg6  14.Qxg6  fxg6  15.Bh6  is much better for White/winning, as Black's pieces are too loose.  15...Rf7  16.Kd3!  is a funny sight, with Black's knight having no square.   B.  12...f6!  13.e6  Qh5+  14.g4  Qd5  is Black's only defense. Now White has two ways to retain an advantage. One is the insanely complicated 15.Bb3; the more straightforward way is  15.Bh6  Qc4+  16.Kd1  Qd3+  17.Kc1  Be3+  18.Kb2  Bxh6  19.Qxh6  Qe2+  20.Bc2  , when Black is running out of checks and White is better. Our king is safer here, now protected by the bishop. }
