[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Bc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ Now we have two more versions of any early ...Bc5 to check. Black can play it right away or after inserting the move ...b5. }
4... Bc5
{ One of Black's early ...Bc5 lines, and a scarce one. I considered not covering it, but I noticed some strong players recently employed it.  It is a slightly better version of 3...Bc5, but the differences are subtle. In some cases, Black gets to play ...Ba7, for example, or the move ...b5 can still be played in some lines, which changes the situation.  So what do we play against it? It is rather simple: the same concept that we play against 3...Bc5 works well. I'll go through this quickly and highlight two differences between the two lines. }
5. c3
{ Going for a quick c3&d4, as we always do against these early ...Bc5 lines. Now we'll check Black's knight moves to f6 and e7.   The move  5...b5?!  6.Bb3  is great for White and covered in the current chapter via  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  5.Bb3  Bc5?!  6.c3  , leading to the same position. }
5... Nge7
{ This is the move played in the recent games I mentioned. It looks like Black's best bet here. }
6. d4 { We play the same way in the 3...Bc5 line. } 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Black has to give the check, as otherwise, d4-d5 starts a central steamroller. I talk about this a bit more in the notes to 3...Bc5 - here I want to show one crucial difference. }
8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 d5 10. exd5 Qxd5
{ After  10...Nxd5  , we play  11.Bxc6+  and destroy Black's pawn structure. }
11. Nc3
{ Now we get to an important difference between this position and the one without the insertion of the moves ...a6 and Ba4. }
11... Qe6+
{ This check would be a substantial mistake in the other line, while here it is playable for Black. The difference is that after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.c3  Nge7  5.d4  exd4  6.cxd4  Bb4+  7.Bd2  Bxd2+  8.Qxd2  d5  9.exd5  Qxd5  10.Nc3  Qe6+?  we can play  11.Kf1!  , enabling Re1 next.   Now compare to the situation here. If we played @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pp1nppp/p1n1q3/8/B2P4/2N2N2/PP1Q1PPP/R3K2R w KQkq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Kf1?  , Black has the annoying  12...Qc4+!  . Therefore, we need a different answer to Black's queen check. }
12. Qe3
{ As mentioned, you need to avoid  12.Kf1?  Qc4+  , when  13.Kg1  Be6  looks good for Black. Instead, the queen move to e3 preserves a small advantage.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pp1nppp/p1n1q3/8/B2P4/2N1QN2/PP3PPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qxe3  13.fxe3  is nice for White due to the strong center.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pp1nppp/p1n1q3/8/B2P4/2N1QN2/PP3PPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12...O-O  13.O-O  is a better try for Black. They still do not want to capture on e3, though. After castling, we are ready for Qd2 and Rfe1 with a tempo. White has a small advantage here, as Black has to be careful due to their slightly worse piece coordination. They always have to watch out for moves like d4-d5, for example.  The main point to know in the 5...Nge7 line is the difference on move 12. Other than this detail, we can handle it just as the 3...Bc5 4.c3 Nge7 line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A2) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 b5 5.Bb3 Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ Now we have two more versions of any early ...Bc5 to check. Black can play it right away or after inserting the move ...b5. }
4... b5 5. Bb3
{ After  5.Bb3  Black has many options, but the current chapter only examines  5...Bc5  to compare with the other versions of the bishop development. Please see the Ruy Lopez Odds and Ends chapter for Black's other moves. }
5... Bc5
{ Black goes for a bad version of an early ...Bc5 setup. Why is it bad? Early ...Bc5 lines work best for Black after they have already provoked the move d3. The best example is the Berlin after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  , when Black has excellent chances to equalise.  If Black plays ...Bc5 before d3 is played, we are happy to go for a quick c3&d4 plan, hitting the bishop. Examples are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.c3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Bc5  5.c3  , both slightly better for White and examined in the current chapter.  Finally, we get to the version here: we are also ready to go for c3&d4 under even better circumstances. Our bishop is well-placed on b3, and Black's queenside is weakened. Let's see how this plays out. }
6. c3
{ We play for c3&d4, of course. This is our approach against all early versions of ...Bc5. Black now has some problems developing naturally. I will only have a look at the move 6...Nf6, which is played most frequently. }
6... Nf6
{ This move is frequently played but accelerates Black's demise. Black has better moves, but I still want to check it as the main move, as it is most likely to happen in a practical game.  Here are some alternatives:   A.  6...d6  is also frequently seen but bad. After  7.d4  exd4  8.cxd4  , we get a dream center, while @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/2p2ppp/p1np4/1pb1p3/3PP3/1BP2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb6  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8+  already wins a pawn.   B. Stockfish gives lines like @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/2pp1ppp/p1n5/1pb1p3/4P3/1BP2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bb6  7.d4  exd4  8.cxd4  Nge7  as relatively best. We get a huge center and are much better, of course. This is still better than 6...Nf6, which looks close to lost for Black. }
7. d4 exd4 8. e5 { Here we go! Black's knight has no good move now. } 8... Ng4
{ The most interesting move to look at.   The line  8...Ne4  9.Bd5!  f5  10.cxd4  is too sad for Black. }
9. cxd4
{ A pretty obvious-looking move, but still important.   You have to avoid a tempting move here:  9.Bxf7+?  is bad because  9...Kxf7  10.Ng5+  Ke8  11.Qxg4  d5  is not clear at all.   9.O-O  is a good alternative that I want to mention. It's just as good as the more natural  9.cxd4  , which I suggest.  Now Black is more or less lost. We have a huge center, and the knight on g4 is stranded.  I once got this position in a classical time control game and was initially concerned about @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2pp1ppp/p1n5/1pb1P3/3P2n1/1B3N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qh4  , but the simple  11.g3  defends with ease.  All in all, Black's @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  looks very dubious and is a welcome sight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A3) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...d6"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ In this chapter, we will examine two defenses to the Ruy Lopez that involve the early move ...d6, the Steinitz Defense and the Steinitz Deferred.  @@HeaderStart@@The Steinitz Defense 3...d6@@HeaderEnd@@The Steinitz Defense is one of the oldest Defenses to the Ruy Lopez - sometimes the name of an opening line already tells you a bit about its background in Chess history. It was played frequently by the first World Champions, like Steinitz, Lasker, Capablanca and Alekhine.  Over time, better defenses against the Ruy Lopez were developed, and the attention switched away from the Steinitz. It is now extinct on the master level but still frequently met in online/amateur games. It is, therefore, necessary to know how to exploit its defects.  @@HeaderStart@@The Steinitz Defense Deferred 3...a6 4.Ba4 d6@@HeaderEnd@@The Steinitz Deferred or Improved Steinitz Defense plays a different role in modern Chess theory. While the original Steinitz is considered too passive, the Steinitz Deferred has a decent reputation and is played from time to time on the master level, mostly as a surprise weapon.  Some of Black's ideas can turn the game into an intense battle, completely different from the more passive strategy of the Steinitz. Let's get into the details now. It's best first to study the Steinitz, then the  Deferred. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A3) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...d6"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ Let's start our examination with the original Steinitz Defense 3...d6, the predecessor of the Steinitz Deferred. }
4. d4
{ Awarding this move an exclamation mark is a bit strong, but I want to draw attention to this move. There are two main reasons, except the simple fact that it is the best move:  1. It is the only occasion in our Ruy Lopez repertoire of an early d2-d4 that was not prepared by c2-c3. We usually play for the c3&d4 central occupation, but here we don't need the move c3 to prepare the central advance. After ...d6 is already played, we welcome the pawn structure after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  , as Black's f8-bishop, remains passive.  This can be compared to the Scotch Opening after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  , when  4...Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  Bb4  are the best defenses. Black's bishop is deployed actively, which is impossible in the Steinitz Variation.  2. It is important to understand the difference between the Steinitz Defense Deferred/Improved Steinitz Defense. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  , the move  5.d4?!  is NOT the best and has to be avoided because Black can play  5...b5  6.Bb3  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  , which is fine for Black. Here  8.Qxd4??  c5  9.Qd5  Be6  10.Qc6+  Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  is the famous 'Ark Noah' trap when White loses the bishop. The term 'Ark Noah' is used, as the trap is supposedly as old as the 'Ark Noah' - in any case, no place to be in!  White can avoid that fate by not taking on d4, but it's already too late to play for an advantage.  In the Deferred Steinitz, White needs an entirely different approach, which we examine in the second part of this chapter. After 4.d4, Black's choice is limited, as we threaten both d4-d5 and dxe5. The two moves are:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd4  , immediately giving up the center.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bd7  , holding the center for the moment. We'll see, however, that Black often needs to take on d4 later, transposing to option A. }
4... Bd7
{ Black breaks the pin and avoids the capture on d4 for the moment. It still will be difficult for Black to avoid it altogether, as we will see. }
5. Nc3
{ We continue with our development.   A good alternative that will usually lead to the same positions is  5.Bxc6  Bxc6  6.Nc3  , when  6...exd4  7.Nxd4  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/2bp4/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  8.Qe2  transposes to lines we'll reach via a different move order. }
5... Nf6
{ Black keeps the central tension as long as possible.   They could play  5...exd4  6.Nxd4  , transposing to the line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Bd7  6.Nc3  , which is the main line of the Steinitz. }
6. Bxc6
{ It took a while to establish that this capture is the strongest move here. Why is it best? The reason is the following, rather forced variation. }
6... Bxc6
{ Black needs to take with the bishop. Otherwise, their e-pawn would fall. Now they have created a counterattack against our e4-pawn. }
7. Qe2
{ We cover our e-pawn, which again poses the question to Black: how do you hold your e-pawn?   By the way, the similar move  7.Qd3  is of about equal strength and leads to the same scenario as 7.Qe2 does: Black needs to take on d4. }
7... exd4
{ There is no good way to defend e5, as  7...Nd7??  8.d5  is rather embarrassing. }
8. Nxd4
{ We have finally transposed to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Bd7  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.Bxc6  Bxc6  8.Qe2  , giving White excellent chances. }
*

