[White "A3) Ruy Lopez – Defenses With an Early ...d6"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ Let's start our examination with the original Steinitz Defense 3...d6, the predecessor of the Steinitz Deferred. }
4. d4
{ Awarding this move an exclamation mark is a bit strong, but I want to draw attention to this move. There are two main reasons, except the simple fact that it is the best move:  1. It is the only occasion in our Ruy Lopez repertoire of an early d2-d4 that was not prepared by c2-c3. We usually play for the c3&d4 central occupation, but here we don't need the move c3 to prepare the central advance. After ...d6 is already played, we welcome the pawn structure after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  , as Black's f8-bishop, remains passive.  This can be compared to the Scotch Opening after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  , when  4...Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  Bb4  are the best defenses. Black's bishop is deployed actively, which is impossible in the Steinitz Variation.  2. It is important to understand the difference between the Steinitz Defense Deferred/Improved Steinitz Defense. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  d6  , the move  5.d4?!  is NOT the best and has to be avoided because Black can play  5...b5  6.Bb3  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  , which is fine for Black. Here  8.Qxd4??  c5  9.Qd5  Be6  10.Qc6+  Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  is the famous 'Ark Noah' trap when White loses the bishop. The term 'Ark Noah' is used, as the trap is supposedly as old as the 'Ark Noah' - in any case, no place to be in!  White can avoid that fate by not taking on d4, but it's already too late to play for an advantage.  In the Deferred Steinitz, White needs an entirely different approach, which we examine in the second part of this chapter. After 4.d4, Black's choice is limited, as we threaten both d4-d5 and dxe5. The two moves are:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd4  , immediately giving up the center.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bd7  , holding the center for the moment. We'll see, however, that Black often needs to take on d4 later, transposing to option A. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3
{ Developing the knight is the most flexible move. We want to preserve the option of queenside castling, most importantly.  Now we'll consider two options for Black: 6...Nxd4 and 6...Nf6, which is played most often. }
6... Nxd4
{ Black suffers from a lack of space and therefore resorts to trading pieces. This move is Black's second most popular move, but they have tried many other moves that don't require any deeper knowledge.  One such example is  6...g6  when  7.Be3  , aiming for Qd2 and queenside castling, is strong. White's space advantage and comfortable development make our job quite easy. }
7. Bxd7+
{ After  7.Qxd4  Bxb5  8.Nxb5  , it's unclear what our knight is doing on b5 - taking on d7 first is a simpler option. }
7... Qxd7 8. Qxd4
{ Our queen has a dominating position in the center of the board. Black has no prospects of any counterplay, and our further development is easy. We can play for queenside castling and attack on the kingside. The following line looks very natural. }
8... Nf6 9. Bg5
{ A development scheme like  9.f3  , followed by Be3 and O-O-O is just as good. }
9... Be7 10. O-O-O
{ Or  10.f3  first and then O-O-O. The move order is not relevant here. } 10...
O-O 11. f3
{ A good move, not only protecting our pawn but also preparing the pawn storm with g4, h4. Based on our superior central control, we can start this dangerous attack. Black has no counterplay and is on the defensive - a very unattractive prospect. }
