PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd4  , immediately giving up the center.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bd7  , holding the center for the moment. We'll see, however, that Black often needs to take on d4 later, transposing to option A. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3
{ Developing the knight is the most flexible move. We want to preserve the option of queenside castling, most importantly.  Now we'll consider two options for Black: 6...Nxd4 and 6...Nf6, which is played most often. }
6... Nf6
{ Black's main move by a mile. This position is frequently reached by other move orders that started with 4...Bd7 or entirely different ones like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Bb5  exd4  6.Nxd4  Bd7  , which is a fun transposition. }
7. Bxc6
{ Capturing on c6 is a strong move, but not an obvious choice, in my mind. The reasoning is, as it often happens, very concrete. Both recaptures lead to much better positions for White, as we'll examine now. }
7... bxc6
{ Taking this way @@StartBracket@@7...bxc6@@EndBracket@@ is more common and stronger than the bishop capture, but still very favourable for White. The next move is important, though. }
8. Qf3
{ An important move with two ideas: we support a possible knight jump to f5 and prepare the move e4-e5, eyeing the c6-pawn. This point is the reason why the natural move 8...Be7? fails.  We'll now examine the details of this move and 8...c5, which at least prevents this immediate disaster. }
8... Be7
{ A natural-looking move and very common in online play. It leads to immediate disaster, though. }
9. e5 Nd5
{ A tougher defense than  9...dxe5  , when  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.Qxc6+  gives White an overwhelming advantage. Black has to move their king or play  11...Nd7  , when  12.Be3  and O-O-O will kill Black on the d-file. }
10. Nxc6
{ Much better than  10.Nxd5  cxd5  11.Qxd5  O-O  , when White is a pawn up, but Black manages to castle. }
10... Bxc6 11. Nxd5
{ We have won a pawn under better circumstances than 10.Nxd5, as Black can't castle due to  11...O-O  12.Nxe7+  , winning a piece. Currently, we are threatening Nf6+, too... which explains Black's next move. }
11... Qd7
{ Covering the bishop and avoiding  11...dxe5??  12.Nf6+  Bxf6  13.Qxc6+  Kf8  14.Be3  , with a deadly attack. }
12. Be3 { We are getting ready for queenside castling. } 12... dxe5 13. O-O-O
{ Black is in huge trouble. They can't castle and have to defend carefully. A good idea for White is to support the d5-knight to increase our queen's mobility. You can accomplish that by doubling on the d-file or playing the move c4, covering the knight with our pawn.  Black struggles in the Steinitz Defense, but knowing some ideas helps maximize the results. }
