5. Nc3
{ I am delighted with my solution 5.Nc3 against the Steinitz Deferred. It is a rarely played line, but I don't see how Black can equalize, and we save a ton of workload compared to more mainstream answers. What are Black's options against it?  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bd7  and 5...Nf6 are frequently played and can both be met with  6.Bxc6+!  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Bxc6!  @@EndBracket@@, when reaching positions almost identical to the original Steinitz. I like White's chances here.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  leads to interesting and, in many cases, unexplored play, but White is in good shape.  C. The ambitious move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  is premature here, as we have not castled yet.  D. Speaking of 'ambitious', @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...f5?  is flat-out refuted by  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.d4  when Black's position is falling apart already.  As I said, the theory of 5.Nc3 is not yet well-established. In practice, mostly in online games, White is doing very well, as Black needs to be precise and usually will need to figure it out without any preparation. }
5... b5 { Black is breaking the pin but weakens the queenside in the process. }
6. Bb3
{ This position is rather unexplored and rather difficult for Black to handle. In practice, many moves fall short quite quickly.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p1np4/1p2p3/4P3/1BN2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6?  7.Ng5  is bad for Black, but not as simple as it may seem.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p1np4/1p2p3/4P3/1BN2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4?!  7.h3  is also bad, but I must include it for 'reasons' - hang on!  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p1np4/1p2p3/4P3/1BN2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Na5  7.d4  is a surprising transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  b5  5.Bb3  Na5  6.Nc3  d6  7.d4  - White is better here, and Black is likely not prepared for this line.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p1np4/1p2p3/4P3/1BN2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  is rarely played, but one of the better options. After  7.a4  b4  8.Nd5  , we reach a position that looks like a better version of some lines in the Anderssen Variation @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  7.a4  @@EndBracket@@. We still have the idea of d2-d4 in one move, which is great! }
6... Bg4
{ As usual, this pinning move early on is dubious. I have to include it in this particular case because of the following line. }
7. h3
{ Now Black should return to d7 or take on f3 and accept to be worse considerably... but what about keeping the pin? }
7... Bh5 8. Nxe5
{ I am excited to include one of my favourite opening traps in the course, Legal's Mate! }
8... Bxd1
{ That allows the mate and has to be in the course! 😀 Black can still avoid it, of course, but would be lost after  8...dxe5  9.Qxh5  , for example. }
9. Bxf7+ Ke7 10. Nd5# { Ahhh, mate! } *

