1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ And we have reached the Steinitz Deferred. Selecting a good weapon against this line proved to be surprisingly challenging.  The problems I encountered were not purely theoretical but more of practical nature. The Steinitz Deferred is a sideline, almost more so below master level. I should not cover such a rare opening with many lines but with a pragmatic solution. This proved to be tricky.  Here's an overview of what I discarded to understand my final choice:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4?!  is dubious due to the 'Ark Noah' Trap, as already mentioned in the notes to 3...d6. After  5...b5  6.Bb3  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4??  c5  White loses the bishop.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d3?!  b5  6.Bb3  Na5  allows Black to trade our bishop under favourable circumstances.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  is one of the two main lines. The problem with this line is that Black has a choice of defenses against it, most importantly the move  5...f5!?  , which looks risky but is sound. White is struggling to prove anything here, and it's a huge load of complicated theory.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  is the second main line. Here Black has a choice of defenses again. One of them is  5...Bg4  , which has  6.h3  h5!?  in mind. Against this somewhat crazy idea, White can 'probably' @@StartBracket@@it's not easy!@@EndBracket@@ get an advantage, but it is shockingly complicated and tough to play.  E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  6.d4  is another try, but  6...exd4!  looks fine for Black, too.  Finally, after checking rarer continuations, I found a solution that I liked and that will likely hit your opponent by surprise. I suggest playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  , which looks like an excellent practical weapon. Let's discuss the move's merits once it is on the board. }
5. Nc3
{ I am delighted with my solution 5.Nc3 against the Steinitz Deferred. It is a rarely played line, but I don't see how Black can equalize, and we save a ton of workload compared to more mainstream answers. What are Black's options against it?  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bd7  and 5...Nf6 are frequently played and can both be met with  6.Bxc6+!  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Bxc6!  @@EndBracket@@, when reaching positions almost identical to the original Steinitz. I like White's chances here.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  leads to interesting and, in many cases, unexplored play, but White is in good shape.  C. The ambitious move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  is premature here, as we have not castled yet.  D. Speaking of 'ambitious', @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...f5?  is flat-out refuted by  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.d4  when Black's position is falling apart already.  As I said, the theory of 5.Nc3 is not yet well-established. In practice, mostly in online games, White is doing very well, as Black needs to be precise and usually will need to figure it out without any preparation. }
5... b5 { Black is breaking the pin but weakens the queenside in the process. }
6. Bb3
{ This position is rather unexplored and rather difficult for Black to handle. In practice, many moves fall short quite quickly.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p1np4/1p2p3/4P3/1BN2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6?  7.Ng5  is bad for Black, but not as simple as it may seem.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p1np4/1p2p3/4P3/1BN2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4?!  7.h3  is also bad, but I must include it for 'reasons' - hang on!  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p1np4/1p2p3/4P3/1BN2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Na5  7.d4  is a surprising transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  b5  5.Bb3  Na5  6.Nc3  d6  7.d4  - White is better here, and Black is likely not prepared for this line.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p1np4/1p2p3/4P3/1BN2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  is rarely played, but one of the better options. After  7.a4  b4  8.Nd5  , we reach a position that looks like a better version of some lines in the Anderssen variation @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  b5  6.Bb3  Be7  7.a4  @@EndBracket@@. We still have the idea of d2-d4 in one move, which is great! }
6... Nf6 { Bad, but It's not as easy as it looks for White. } 7. Ng5
{ At first, you think Black is just collapsing, but they can still defend quite tenaciously. }
7... d5 8. Nxd5 Nd4
{ This move still puts up a fight.   After  8...Nxd5??  9.Nxf7  is over immediately.  White has many possible moves, and it is hard to determine which is best. The following line looks convincing and forced. }
9. Nc3 { We retreat and attack f7 again, forcing Black's reply. } 9... Nxb3 10.
axb3
{ Now, Black needs to be quick to regain the pawn. If we'd manage d2-d3, we keep the material, and Black has nothing to show. }
10... h6
{ The sequence  10...b4  11.Ne2  h6  12.Nf3  Nxe4  13.O-O  leads to the same outcome. }
11. Nf3 b4 { Black regains the pawn. } 12. Ne2 Nxe4 13. O-O
{ That's the important move to remember.   We can't play  13.Nxe5  Qg5!  , but simply castling is strong.   We'll open the center with d4 next, exploiting our large lead in development. After  13.O-O  Bd6  14.d4  exd4  15.Qxd4  Nf6  16.Bf4  , Black's position has too many weaknesses to hold in the long run, probably. }
