StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  , which looks like an excellent practical weapon. Let's discuss the move's merits once it is on the board. }
5. Nc3
{ I am delighted with my solution 5.Nc3 against the Steinitz Deferred. It is a rarely played line, but I don't see how Black can equalize, and we save a ton of workload compared to more mainstream answers. What are Black's options against it?  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bd7  and 5...Nf6 are frequently played and can both be met with  6.Bxc6+!  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Bxc6!  @@EndBracket@@, when reaching positions almost identical to the original Steinitz. I like White's chances here.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  leads to interesting and, in many cases, unexplored play, but White is in good shape.  C. The ambitious move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  is premature here, as we have not castled yet.  D. Speaking of 'ambitious', @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...f5?  is flat-out refuted by  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.d4  when Black's position is falling apart already.  As I said, the theory of 5.Nc3 is not yet well-established. In practice, mostly in online games, White is doing very well, as Black needs to be precise and usually will need to figure it out without any preparation. }
5... Nf6
{ Against this move, we employ a similar approach as against 5...Bd7 - we take the knight and play the d4-advance. }
6. Bxc6+
{ Note that need to take first on c6, as  6.d4?  is still bad due to the 'Ark Noah' trap. }
6... bxc6 7. d4 exd4
{ A lot more natural than  7...Nd7  , when we can maintain the central tension with  8.Be3  , when it's unclear how Black generates activity. }
8. Nxd4
{ Taking with the queen is not bad, either. I prefer the knight capture, though. It is slightly stronger, as now Black has a difficult decision. Cover the c-pawn or advance it?   Here we arrive at another 'almost-transposition' to the Steinitz because  8...Bd7  9.Qf3  is about the same as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  Bd7  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.Bxc6  bxc6  8.Qf3  , which is very nice for White. The extra move ...a6 makes no substantial difference.   Therefore, we need to focus on 8...c5, which has a more independent value. }
8... c5 9. Nc6
{ This is a crucial move to play. We must use this opportunity to drive the black queen to a bad square. In this particular situation, we observe a key difference to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  6.d4  exd4!  7.Nxd4  c5  , when  8.Nc6?  Qd7  9.Na5  Qa4  is awful for White. The added moves Nc3 and ...Nf6 make the knight jump to c6 possible. }
9... Qd7
{ Her Majesty only had this square available - the same applies to our knight now. }
10. Na5
{ It's scarce to see a white knight on a5 early on in the game. It is surprisingly stable on this square and quite annoying for Black. They can't play ...Bb7 and always have to think about a possible invasion on c6.  This is one reason why Black has a hard time coordinating their forces. It seems that only one move does the trick now, and I don't think it is a self-evident choice. }
10... Qg4
{ This seems to be Black's best defense, but it doesn't equalize. What else is there?   A more normal-looking move would be  10...Be7  , but normal development and centralization pose serious problems for Black. Consider  11.O-O  O-O  12.Bf4  Rb8  13.b3  Re8  14.Qf3  as a sample line. Once a rook appears on d1, Black's queen position will be more than uncomfortable. Here  14...Qg4  15.Qxg4  Bxg4  16.Nc6  Rb7  17.Nxe7+  Rxe7  18.Bg5  shows how annoying the knight jump to c6 can be. }
11. O-O
{ The best way to cover g2. Now Black needs to trade on d1; otherwise, the move f3 sends Black's queen back. }
11... Qxd1 12. Rxd1
{ This endgame is difficult for Black to play. They always need to watch out for the central push e4-e5 and tactics based on our knight jumps. The move Nd5 can often be a problem if Black decides to move the f6-knight or we manage to take it at the right moment. Here are some sample lines to illustrate these ideas.   A.  12...Be6  13.Bg5  Be7  14.Re1  @@StartBracket@@ready for e4-e5 now@@EndBracket@@  14...h6  15.Bf4  Nd7  16.Nd5  and Black is under pressure.   B.  12...g6  13.Bg5  Bg7  14.Re1  O-O  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Nd5  wins a pawn or leaves Black tied up in knots after  16...Bxb2  17.Rab1  Bg7  18.Nxc7  Ra7  19.Nd5  .   C.  12...Be7  13.Bf4  Nd7  14.Nd5  looks grim for Black, too.  Amongst these, line A is relatively best for Black, but it's a bit of a grovel. An engine might hold, but White has all the fun in a game between human players. }
