5. Nc3
{ I am delighted with my solution 5.Nc3 against the Steinitz Deferred. It is a rarely played line, but I don't see how Black can equalize, and we save a ton of workload compared to more mainstream answers. What are Black's options against it?  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bd7  and 5...Nf6 are frequently played and can both be met with  6.Bxc6+!  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Bxc6!  @@EndBracket@@, when reaching positions almost identical to the original Steinitz. I like White's chances here.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  leads to interesting and, in many cases, unexplored play, but White is in good shape.  C. The ambitious move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  is premature here, as we have not castled yet.  D. Speaking of 'ambitious', @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...f5?  is flat-out refuted by  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.d4  when Black's position is falling apart already.  As I said, the theory of 5.Nc3 is not yet well-established. In practice, mostly in online games, White is doing very well, as Black needs to be precise and usually will need to figure it out without any preparation. }
5... Bd7
{ Black breaks the pin and avoids a doubled pawn after the capture on c6.   This move is often played here, as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  Bd7  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  Bd7  are frequently seen variations that Black may have in their repertoire. }
6. Bxc6
{ Not the most intuitive solution at first sight, but we have seen similar ideas in the traditional Steinitz. }
6... Bxc6
{ Taking with the pawn makes an odd impression after Black has played ...Bd7 earlier.   After  6...bxc6  7.d4  exd4  8.Qxd4  we are much better, as Black is so far behind in development. Black has problems getting the kingside pieces out, as  8...Nf6  9.Bf4  Be7  10.e5  demonstrates. }
7. d4
{ This position looks like a regular Steinitz Defense.   One case of an 'almost'-transposition is  7...Nf6  now, when  8.Qd3  is strong. It is not a 100%-transposition because Black has the extra move ...a6, which does not change the evaluation. White is better.   The other line that is close is  7...exd4  8.Nxd4  , when we reach a situation almost identical to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  Bd7  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.Bxc6  Bxc6  8.Qe2  , when we are playing for a quick O-O-O.  Here, in the Deferred Steinitz, we'd get something very similar after @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1bp4/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...exd4  8.Nxd4  , when we'd play a setup with Qe2/Qd3, Bf4 and O-O-O, too.   This leaves the odd-looking move  7...f6  , which is sometimes played in other lines of the Deferred Steinitz. It's not particularly great, but knowing how to answer this setup is good. }
7... f6
{ Not the most obvious move, but Black sometimes plays in a similar style in the Deferred Steinitz. The line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  6.d4  f6  has been tested frequently, for example. Black's setup is quite passive but not easy to break down.  I suggest a setup now that works well here and in similar situations. We employ it the line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  b5  5.Bb3  Na5  6.Nc3  Nxb3  7.axb3  Bb7  8.O-O  d6  9.d4  f6  , too.  We should play @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/1pp3pp/p1bp1p2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3  now and then Qe2 or Qd3. A key idea is playing a rook to d1 @@StartBracket@@here, O-O-O is also possible@@EndBracket@@ and later playing for dxe5, followed by Nd5. Let's have a look. }
8. Be3 { The queen moves to e2 or d3 would also work to reach the same setup. }
8... Ne7 9. Qe2 Ng6 10. O-O-O
{ We have completed our setup and are ready for action now. One idea is playing for the occupation of d5 @@StartBracket@@dxe5&Nd5@@EndBracket@@, but once a knight arrives on g6, we are ready for h4-h5, as well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A4) Ruy Lopez – Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit 3...f5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit 3...f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ In this chapter, we will examine two early gambit lines that feature the move ...f5. We'll see that we don't accept these gambits but rather focus on our development and try to exploit Black's weakening move ...f5. Let's have a look at the two sequences we will cover.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  f5  is the Schliemann/Jänisch Variation. Both names are commonly used, but I think Schliemann is more common. This line will be our focus in the current chapter. It is a risky line for Black and likely not 100% correct. However, trying to prove that takes some effort and precision.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  f5  is the second line we need to check. The insertion of the moves ...a6 and Ba4 changes more than you might think at first. While the Schliemann @@StartBracket@@A@@EndBracket@@ is considered risky for Black, this gambit line is objectively incorrect. The resulting positions are different because we have a powerful response unavailable in A.  We'll start with line B in this chapter, as it is rather easily dealt with. Knowing the best reply and some ideas is enough. Then we'll look at 3...f5, which is considerably better and more popular. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A4) Ruy Lopez – Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit 3...f5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 f5
{ I am tempted to even go for a '?' instead of the '?!' - this move is very dubious! The main point we need to remember is that this line is very different from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  , even though it looks similar. The insertion of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  changes one particular line. What's best for White? }
5. d4
{ This is the best reply, by far! It is important to realize the difference in the situation after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  , when  4.d4?!  is bad due to  4...fxe4  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  c6!  7.Be2  Qa5+  and Black wins the e-pawn. The problem is Black's tempo-gain ...c6! on White's bishop. Here the bishop is not on b5, so the same ideas do not work.  I want to add that 5.d4! is clearly the best move, and there are also no good alternatives. So you need to learn and remember this variation; no recipe would work against both  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  , as they are just different lines. The good news is: once you remember this and the next move, you are already on the right track and don't need much more. }
5... exd4
{ The only move for Black, as  5...fxe4  6.Nxe5  looks great for White. Black's position is just too weakened, as shown by a sequence of natural moves like  6...Nf6  7.O-O  Be7  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Bg5  , with serious pressure on Black. White has some alternatives and other move orders here that also give us a huge advantage. }
6. e5
{ The second key move to know. White has a large advantage, as our strong e5-pawn is hampering Black's development. Furthermore, the f5-pawn sticks out a lot. It weakens Black's position for no benefit. }
6... b5
{ Black is kicking our bishop away, but b3 is no bad spot for our Ruy bishop! Still, an understandable move by our opponent, as the c8-bishop needs a development perspective.   You also meet the move  6...Bc5?  , which gives us the excellent opportunity to play  7.c3  , getting rid of the d4-pawn. After  7...dxc3  8.Nxc3  we have a fantastic position. All pieces can develop quickly, while Black is sitting on weaknesses and a bad c8-bishop. }
7. Bb3 Bb7
{ Again  7...Bc5?  8.c3!  is strong for White, opening the position to exploit Black's weak points. }
8. a4
{ That's stronger than the alternatives.   A.  8.Nxd4??  is a blunder due to the 'Ark Noah' trick  8...Nxd4  9.Qxd4  c5  10.Qf4  c4  and our bishop is lost.   B.  8.c3  is a good move and also better for White, but  8...Na5!  9.Bc2  d6  is surprisingly messy.   The engine suggestion of  8.a4!  looks a bit better to me, but  8.c3  is not a mistake and keeps an advantage. The point of the move  8.a4!  is that we get to keep our bishop on the great a2-g8 diagonal. }
8... Na5
{ The best try for Black.   Something like  8...Bc5  9.c3  dxc3  10.Nxc3  gives White an overwhelming attack, for example,  10...Nge7  11.O-O  h6  12.Nh4  g6  13.Nd5  Nxd5  14.Nxg6  and Black falls apart. This is just one sample line to illustrate how bad Black's situation is. }
9. Ba2
{ We managed to keep our bishop on the strong diagonal, hitting the weaknesses Black has created. }
9... c5 { Black wants to keep the pawn, at least. } 10. O-O
{ It's too early to play  10.Ng5?  due to  10...c4!  , when  11.Qxd4  h6  is fine for Black.  After castling, we have two dangerous ideas: the move c3, to open the position, and the move e5-e6, highlighting why we wanted the bishop on a2. }
10... Ne7
{ After  10...Qb6  both  11.c3  and  11.Re1  , planning e5-e6, give White a huge attack. }
11. e6
{ This is even better than the usual c3-idea. Black's position is already falling apart, with their king stuck in the center.   The whole line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5  looks pretty bad for Black, but it has some surprise value. The main point to remember is that  5.d4!  is the best reply, intending  5...exd4  6.e5  , with great play for White. }
