[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A4) Ruy Lopez – Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit 3...f5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit 3...f5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ This is Black's most aggressive move against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit. It looks a bit outrageous that this move should be possible, and indeed we'll see that it is a risky choice for Black - if White knows what they are doing!  We need to study a good reply to 3...f5, as common sense play is not enough. Ultimately, it is not that much effort to gain an advantage, but it would be tough to figure out without any preparation. Let's get to work. }
4. d3
{ We simply cover our e-pawn, which I consider to be the best choice. Let's check some alternatives to understand Black's opening points.   A.  4.exf5?  e4!  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp2pp/2n5/1B2pp2/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.exf5  e4  should be avoided.   B.  4.d4?  looks logical, but Black has  4...fxe4  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  c6!  7.Bc4  Qa5+  , when the e-pawn drops. This is the key difference to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  , when  5.d4!  is the best move. With the bishop on a4, the move ...c6 does not hit White's bishop.  Another fun comparison is the Vienna Game @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.f4  d5!  , when Black is fine - having the bishop at home is better than b5 in this concrete line.   C.  4.Nc3  is the only good alternative to our choice, but requires more memorization work and is not objectively better. }
4... fxe4
{ Very natural and almost exclusively played.   After a sloppy move like  4...Nf6?!  we are ready to play  5.exf5  , as ...e4 is no reply anymore. }
5. dxe4 Nf6
{ Black develops and attacks our e-pawn. We reach the first crucial point. } 6.
O-O
{ This is White's best move and important to remember. We don't need to cover our e-pawn and can play O-O first, a move that we'll need anyway.   A common mistake is  6.Nc3?  Bb4!  , which is surprisingly comfortable for Black.   After our move, Black has a fundamental choice. They can play the most ambitious move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc5  , a pawn sacrifice, or cover their e-pawn with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  , which keeps material equality.  Black has no good alternatives to these moves. We are threatening Bxc6, followed by Nxe5, to win a pawn.  The greedy @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nxe4?  is far too risky due to  7.Qe2  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n5/1B2p3/4n3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  , eyeing Black's king on e8. }
6... d6
{ Black covers their central pawn but accepts a more passive position of the f8-bishop. We need to be precise to get an advantage, but it's mostly about the next move. }
7. Bc4
{ It is fairly clear that the bishop has a good spot on this diagonal, but why is it crucial to move it to c4 now? We want to prevent Black from kingside castling, which only works this way.   If we start with a different move, they will manage to castle. A line to illustrate this point is  7.Nc3  Be7  8.Bc4  Na5!  9.Be2  O-O  , when they have managed their goal.   After our more incisive move  7.Bc4  , they won't manage the same feat. Now it looks like Black's only good move is  7...Bg4  , which pins our knight and prevents Ng5 this way. There are some worse alternatives, though.   A.  7...Na5?  is a test of our idea to stop kingside castling, but it falls short. We will check this crucial line in some detail.   B.  7...Be7??  ignores our threat completely.  8.Ng5  already wins for White and may lead to fun lines as  8...Rf8  9.Nxh7!  Nxh7  10.Qh5+  Kd7  11.Qg4+  Ke8  12.Qg6+  Kd7  13.Be6#  , which can easily happen in a game! }
7... Na5 { Black tries to accomplish kingside castling by chasing our bishop. }
8. Be2 Be7
{ Black wants to castle kingside next, for sure, the most logical move.   An alternative is  8...Be6  , when  9.Ng5  Bg8  10.Nc3  gives us a great position. Note that Black can never play ...h6, as Bh5+ is a deadly reply. After 10.Nc3, we are ready to play f4 next and start our attack. Black's position looks uncoordinated, to put it mildly. }
9. b4
{ We can push Black's knight back and get a large advantage by concrete means. }
9... Nc6 10. b5 { Straightforward play. Black has no good option now. } 10...
Na5
{ The move  10...Nb8  is rather sad, too. We are more or less winning after  11.Bc4  or  11.Ng5  , which seems to be even stronger than the more obvious bishop move. }
11. Bd2
{ We get rid of the knight this way and manage our dream scenario at the end: the uncontested bishop on c4. }
11... b6
{ Here  11...c6?  12.Qe1!  b6  13.Bxa5  bxa5  14.bxc6  is even more disatrous for Black. }
12. Bxa5 bxa5 13. Bc4
{ Black's position is falling apart now. They can't castle and face an attack that is simple to conduct for us - Black has no counterplay, making it fun to play. }
