{ The final move of this line. We unpin our knight and cover the e-pawn. It looks like White is in great shape, but the position remains complicated. Here are some ideas to be aware of.   A.  11...Be7?  is bad due to  12.Bb5!  , an important idea. The pin can be very annoying for Black.   B.  11...a6?  stops Bb5, but gives us an easy attack with  12.b4!  .   C.  11...Kb8!  is a clever move. Now  12.Bb5?!  is less of a problem for Black due to  12...Bxf3  13.Qxf3  Nd4!  , showing a point of the king move. It is better to start an attack by different means, like @@StartFEN@@1k1r1b1r/pppq2pp/2np1n2/3Np2b/2B1P3/3Q1N1P/PPP2PP1/R1B2RK1 w - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12.b4  or @@StartFEN@@1k1r1b1r/pppq2pp/2np1n2/3Np2b/2B1P3/3Q1N1P/PPP2PP1/R1B2RK1 w - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12.a4  , intending a5-a6 and Ra3 in some lines.  The whole line 6...d6 looks dubious for Black, but we need to be precise to prove it. It's crucial to get the move order right, otherwise Black might get away with their risky opening concept. }
