{ This is White's best move and important to remember. We don't need to cover our e-pawn and can play O-O first, a move that we'll need anyway.   A common mistake is  6.Nc3?  Bb4!  , which is surprisingly comfortable for Black.   After our move, Black has a fundamental choice. They can play the most ambitious move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc5  , a pawn sacrifice, or cover their e-pawn with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  , which keeps material equality.  Black has no good alternatives to these moves. We are threatening Bxc6, followed by Nxe5, to win a pawn.  The greedy @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nxe4?  is far too risky due to  7.Qe2  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n5/1B2p3/4n3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  , eyeing Black's king on e8. }
6... Bc5
{ Certainly the move Black wants to play. They develop the bishop to the most active square and want to castle next. There is an obvious drawback, though: it loses a pawn. }
7. Bxc6
{ White has tried some other ideas here, but I like to grab the pawn. I am generally reluctant to accept gambits, but here we take a central pawn, which is far more important than a pawn on the edge of the board. }
7... bxc6 8. Nxe5 O-O
{ Black needs to get castled, there is no alternative.   A.  8...Nxe4??  9.Qh5+  is easy.   B.  8...Qe7?  9.Nd3  Nxe4  leads to a disaster on the e-file after  10.Nd2  Nxd2  11.Re1!  Ne4  12.Nxc5  , and it's over. }
9. Nc3
{ We cover the e-pawn and ask Black to prove compensation. Black has the bishop pair and open files, but the current theoretical evaluation is favourable for White.  In the current position, Black has tried many moves, particularly if you check games played online or below master level. However, many of these moves can be dismissed rather quickly, as they don't address an idea we have prepared with our last move. The idea is to play Nd3 @@StartBracket@@tempo on the bishop@@EndBracket@@, followed by e4-e5, attacking Black's knight. This simple idea refutes some of Black's attempts convincingly.   I am going to examine  9...Qe8?  in more detail, and give you additional info in the notes to this move about  9...Qe7?  and  9...Re8?  , which have similar drawbacks. This leads to the best moves for Black, which address our threat:  9...d6  and  9...Ba6  . They are not fully satisfactory, either, but put up a much more substantial resistance. }
9... Ba6 { One of the better defensive tries that Black can go for. } 10. Nd3
{ The only move, as  10.Re1??  Bxf2+  shows. } 10... Bd4
{ This is the most active move and is almost always played.   Maybe  10...Bb6  is better, but it is still not fun for Black. You can try  11.e5  Nd5  12.Nxd5  cxd5  13.a4  or my spoilsport suggestion of @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p1pp2pp/bbp2n2/8/4P3/2NN4/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Be3  , when Black has nothing better than  11...Bxe3  12.fxe3  d6  , when  13.Rf4  is nice. It prepares to double on the f-file and removes the rook from the a6-f1 diagonal. Black is suffering, still being a pawn down. }
11. Re1
{ This move looks risky, as we abandon cover of the f2-pawn. However, as far as I @@StartBracket@@and the comp!@@EndBracket@@ can see, there is no way for Black to exploit that. We aim to play Be3 under ideal circumstances and trade off Black's best piece.   I want to mention that  11.e5  also looks good for White.   A.  11.e5  Bxd3  12.exf6  Bxf1  13.Qxd4  is great for White.   B.  11.e5  Bxc3  12.bxc3  Nd5  13.Qg4  also looks promising.   C.  11.e5  Nd5  looks relatively best when  12.Nxd5  cxd5  13.Nb4  Bxf1  14.Qxd4  Bc4  15.Nxd5  Bxd5  16.Qxd5+  Rf7  17.Be3  is a long but forced line. White is better here, but probably not as much as after 11.Re1.  The difference is: this position is simplified and may be easier to play. I guess it comes down to taste. }
11... d5
{ Black opens the center, the most frequently seen move in the games I found. White is better after the alternatives, too.   A.  11...Qe7  is met with  12.Be3  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p1pp2pp/b1p2n2/8/3bP3/2NN4/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 6 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qe8  Be3  @@EndBracket@@, our main idea.   B.  11...d6  12.Nf4  shows why unpinning the knight is a factor.   C.  11...Bxd3  12.Qxd3  Bxf2+??  just doesn't work.  14.Kxf2  Ng4  15.Kg1  Qh4  16.Qg3  and curtains. }
12. exd5 Nxd5
{ Here  12...cxd5?  is too slow and favourably met with many moves, like  13.Bg5  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p1p3pp/b4n2/3p4/3b4/2NN4/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nf4  , for example. }
13. Ne4
{ The knight jumps to e4, giving more cover to f2. Depending on Black's play, it is also ready to jump or g5 or c5 later. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A4) Ruy Lopez – Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit 3...f5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit 3...f5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ This is Black's most aggressive move against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit. It looks a bit outrageous that this move should be possible, and indeed we'll see that it is a risky choice for Black - if White knows what they are doing!  We need to study a good reply to 3...f5, as common sense play is not enough. Ultimately, it is not that much effort to gain an advantage, but it would be tough to figure out without any preparation. Let's get to work. }
4. d3
{ We simply cover our e-pawn, which I consider to be the best choice. Let's check some alternatives to understand Black's opening points.   A.  4.exf5?  e4!  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp2pp/2n5/1B2pp2/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.exf5  e4  should be avoided.   B.  4.d4?  looks logical, but Black has  4...fxe4  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  c6!  7.Bc4  Qa5+  , when the e-pawn drops. This is the key difference to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  f5  , when  5.d4!  is the best move. With the bishop a4, the move ...c6 does not hit White's bishop.  Another fun comparison is the Vienna Game @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.f4  d5!  , when Black is fine - having the bishop at home is better than b5 in this concrete line.   C.  4.Nc3  is the only good alternative to our choice, but requires more memorization work and is not objectively better. }
4... fxe4
{ Very natural and almost exclusively played.   After a sloppy move like  4...Nf6?!  we are ready to play  5.exf5  , as ...e4 is no reply anymore. }
5. dxe4 Nf6
{ Black develops and attacks our e-pawn. We reach the first crucial point. } 6.
O-O
{ This is White's best move and important to remember. We don't need to cover our e-pawn and can play O-O first, a move that we'll need anyway.   A common mistake is  6.Nc3?  Bb4!  , which is surprisingly comfortable for Black.   After our move, Black has a fundamental choice. They can play the most ambitious move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc5  , a pawn sacrifice, or cover their e-pawn with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  , which keeps material equality.  Black has no good alternatives to these moves. We are threatening Bxc6, followed by Nxe5, to win a pawn.  The greedy @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nxe4?  is far too risky due to  7.Qe2  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n5/1B2p3/4n3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  , eyeing Black's king on e8. }
6... Bc5
{ Certainly the move Black wants to play. They develop the bishop to the most active square and want to castle next. There is an obvious drawback, though: it loses a pawn. }
7. Bxc6
{ White has tried some other ideas here, but I like to grab the pawn. I am generally reluctant to accept gambits, but here we take a central pawn, which is far more important than a pawn on the edge of the board. }
7... bxc6 8. Nxe5 O-O
{ Black needs to get castled, there is no alternative.   A.  8...Nxe4??  9.Qh5+  is easy.   B.  8...Qe7?  9.Nd3  Nxe4  leads to a disaster on the e-file after  10.Nd2  Nxd2  11.Re1!  Ne4  12.Nxc5  , and it's over. }
9. Nc3
{ We cover the e-pawn and ask Black to prove compensation. Black has the bishop pair and open files, but the current theoretical evaluation is favourable for White.  In the current position, Black has tried many moves, particularly if you check games played online or below master level. However, many of these moves can be dismissed rather quickly, as they don't address an idea we have prepared with our last move. The idea is to play Nd3 @@StartBracket@@tempo on the bishop@@EndBracket@@, followed by e4-e5, attacking Black's knight. This simple idea refutes some of Black's attempts convincingly.   I am going to examine  9...Qe8?  in more detail, and give you additional info in the notes to this move about  9...Qe7?  and  9...Re8?  , which have similar drawbacks. This leads to the best moves for Black, which address our threat:  9...d6  and  9...Ba6  . They are not fully satisfactory, either, but put up a much more substantial resistance. }
9... Qe8
{ This is the most frequently tried move of the ones that fail to address our basic idea of Nd3&e4-e5. There are two more that have the same defect that I want to mention.   A.  9...Qe7?  10.Nd3  Bb6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p1ppq1pp/2p2n2/2b5/4P3/2NN4/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bd4  11.e5  is about the same as happens after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p1pp2pp/2p2n2/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qe8  10.Nd3  Bd4  11.e5  , which we check in a minute@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p1ppq1pp/1bp2n2/8/4P3/2NN4/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11.e5  Nd5  12.Nxd5  cxd5  13.Bf4  shows a different problem; Black can't afford to play into the knight trade with ...Nd5. There is not enough activity to compensate for the pawn.   B.  9...Re8?  10.Nd3  Bd4  can be exploited in more than one way, but  11.Ne2!  Rxe4  12.Nxd4  Rxd4  13.b3  is powerful. Our bishop will be fantastic on the long diagonal, chasing Black's stray rook. The engine eval of +2.5 is still quite surprising, but once you see that Bb2 and a later Re1-e3-g3 are ideas, you see the extent of Black's problems.  These three lines are bad for Black, and for more than one reason. You need to know the Nd3&e4-e5 idea; there is even some choice of ways to be @@StartBracket@@much@@EndBracket@@ better after these initial moves. Let's check now why 9...Qe8? fails. }
10. Nd3 Bd4
{ Here  10...Bb6  can be refuted with  11.e5  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1qrk1/p1pp2pp/1bp2n2/8/4P3/2NN4/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Re1  , planning Be3. Trading this strong bishop is the end of any faint compensation that Black may have. }
11. e5
{ We can play this move anyway, as 11...Bxe5 leads to a great position for us. }
11... Bxe5
{ Here  11...Nd5?  is not just strategically bad but loses material after  12.Nxd5  cxd5  13.Nf4  Qxe5  14.Re1  Qf6  15.c3  - this is probably met with resignation in a long time control game. }
12. Re1 d6 13. Nxe5 { Simple and good.   Please avoid  13.f4??  Bd4+  . } 13...
dxe5 14. Bf4
{ A very nice move. The material is equal, but Black's pawn structure is wrecked and they are dead on the dark squares. We'll likely win e5 and c7 in the long run. }
