{ Certainly the move Black wants to play. They develop the bishop to the most active square and want to castle next. There is an obvious drawback, though: it loses a pawn. }
7. Bxc6
{ White has tried some other ideas here, but I like to grab the pawn. I am generally reluctant to accept gambits, but here we take a central pawn, which is far more important than a pawn on the edge of the board. }
7... bxc6 8. Nxe5 O-O
{ Black needs to get castled, there is no alternative.   A.  8...Nxe4??  9.Qh5+  is easy.   B.  8...Qe7?  9.Nd3  Nxe4  leads to a disaster on the e-file after  10.Nd2  Nxd2  11.Re1!  Ne4  12.Nxc5  , and it's over. }
9. Nc3
{ We cover the e-pawn and ask Black to prove compensation. Black has the bishop pair and open files, but the current theoretical evaluation is favourable for White.  In the current position, Black has tried many moves, particularly if you check games played online or below master level. However, many of these moves can be dismissed rather quickly, as they don't address an idea we have prepared with our last move. The idea is to play Nd3 @@StartBracket@@tempo on the bishop@@EndBracket@@, followed by e4-e5, attacking Black's knight. This simple idea refutes some of Black's attempts convincingly.   I am going to examine  9...Qe8?  in more detail, and give you additional info in the notes to this move about  9...Qe7?  and  9...Re8?  , which have similar drawbacks. This leads to the best moves for Black, which address our threat:  9...d6  and  9...Ba6  . They are not fully satisfactory, either, but put up a much more substantial resistance. }
9... d6
{ Attacking our knight is Black's main move.   Now we have to avoid being too greedy by playing  10.Nxc6?!  Qe8  11.Nd4  Nxe4  12.Nxe4  Qxe4  , when the wide open position gives Black's bishop pair the right stage to shine on.  Instead, we have a much stronger but less intuitive move. }
10. Na4
{ A tough move to remember, but it is White's best claim for an advantage.   The other move you can play here is  10.Nd3  , which has been tested in some games. After  10...Bd4  11.Ne2  Bb6  12.Bg5  Qe8  13.Bxf6  Rxf6  14.Ng3  White remains a pawn up, but Black has two bishops against our two knights. The computer likes White in this position, but I am not sure how easy it is to play. I have a lot of respect for the bishop when it competes with two knights, so my judgement may be off here. Maybe you like White here more than I do - then this line is a good alternative to my suggestion.   The point of  10.Na4  is to trade off Black's best piece, the c5-bishop. Black has tried various moves, but they don't solve their problems. I will examine  10...Nxe4  and  10...Qe8  in more detail now and want to mention two worse and rather easy-to-handle alternatives.   A.  10...Bxf2+  leads to a forced simplification.  11.Rxf2  dxe5  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.Bg5  Rd4  14.Bxf6  Rxa4  15.Bxe5  Rxe4  16.Bxc7  is a much better endgame for White. Black has drawing chances, but it's no fun to play. We should be careful with rook trades here, as it would help Black a lot.   B.  10...Bb6  11.Nxb6  axb6  12.Nxc6  Qe8  13.Nd4  Qxe4  14.f3  Qg6  15.a4  keeps the extra pawn, and Black has no compensation. }
10... Nxe4 { Black grabs the e-pawn, which prompts the following sequence. }
11. Nxc5 Nxc5 12. Nxc6 Qe8
{ Black is looking for a play on the light squares, so this feels like the best try.   12...Qf6  13.Qd5+  Be6  14.Qg5  Qf7  15.Be3  is a different line that also leads to a position with an extra pawn and insufficient compensation for Black. }
13. Nd4 Bb7 14. f3
{ This move is a key point to remember about this position or similar positions. Our extra pawn is the f-pawn. The advantage of having this pawn is twofold. It has a material value but, more importantly, a strategic one. By placing it on f3, we also blunt Black's bishop and take away the e4-square. Black has been missing their f-pawn since move three, which weakens the kingside permanently.  If we build up pressure with something like Qd2, b3 and Bb2, they have to face a much stronger bishop on the long diagonal, as they can't limit its scope with a pawn. We have attacking chances on the dark squares here - the opposite-coloured bishops are not a drawing factor.  Finally, I want to point out that playing a4 and Ra3 is an interesting idea, too. Getting our rook active via a3 to e3 is a creative way to play this position. }
