1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the odds and ends of the Ruy Lopez, the early sidelines that don't have a dedicated chapter. All other rare lines have their chapters, as some are best studied together due to transpositions or similar concepts. It makes sense to study @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  and  3...a6  4.Ba4  Bc5  in one chapter, rather than a 'sidelines on move three' and 'sidelines on move four' chapter.It's best to make an overview to see what's left:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  is the Bird Defense, a dubious defense that loses time and compromises Black's pawn structure.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  b5  is a rare line on the master level, but quite frequently seen below that. It is not a bad move if Black continues correctly afterward, but most options are risky or bad.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  is the Smyslov Defense and  3...a6  4.Ba4  g6  an even rarer delayed version. I suggest opening the game with an immediate d4, which directly sets Black problems. I have experimented with these lines as Black and now suggest what I always found most annoying to face.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  and  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nge7  are the so-called 'Cozio Defense' and 'Delayed Cozio Defense'. They share some ideas with the Smyslov, as Black often plays ...g6 later. The two Cozio lines are rarely played, but quite reasonable for Black.I suggest a similar approach as against C: play for a quick d4 and try to exploit Black's slow development. This is not the most principled line, but a pragmatic solution that still gives us an edge. It also harmonizes well with the Smyslov, so it's easier to learn.The basic alternative is playing with c3 & d4, but there are multiple move order pitfalls to navigate. Learning these makes no sense for a line that occurs in less than 1% of your games. }
