[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A5) Ruy Lopez – Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Odds & Ends – 3...Nd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4
{ The Bird Defense, named after Henry Bird, not the animal. It's still no good, like all the 'animal openings' - let's examine why. }
4. Nxd4 { Easy - we take the quirky knight. } 4... exd4 5. O-O
{ Again, very natural play. After five moves, we are already castled, while Black has not developed a single piece. There is no doubt that Black's concept must be dubious, but it does have some ideas. The d4-pawn is currently restricting our pieces, in particular our b1-knight. Black can also play the move ...c6 soon, gaining a tempo on our bishop. Our bishop will likely find a good spot on c4, putting some pressure against Black's kingside.   We'll examine two approaches by Black now:  5...Bc5  , starting their kingside development, and  5...c6  ,  chasing our bishop and playing for as ...d5 push.   I also found several online games with the odd-looking move  5...a5?!  , which is bad but sets a trap. If we pay no attention and continue  6.d3??  , Black traps our bishop with  6...c6  7.Bc4  b5  8.Bb3  a4  - duh! About any other move than  6.d3??  is good for White, though. I'd suggest  6.a4  , stopping all funny ideas. }
5... c6 { Black attacks our bishop and prepares the move ...d5. } 6. Bc4
{ Going to a4 wouldn't be a mistake, but our bishop is well-placed on this diagonal. We don't mind Black's possible ...d5, as opening up the game should be great for us - we are much better developed.   Also note that going to c4 has the bonus of setting a small trap, as  6...Bc5??  is a blunder due to  7.Bxf7+!  Kxf7  8.Qh5+  , netting a pawn. }
6... Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn first before playing the pawn to d5. They have also tried  6...d5  , but  7.exd5  cxd5  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Re1+  Ne7   @@StartBracket@@  9...Be7??  10.Qg4!  is a nice shot@@EndBracket@@  10.c4!  leads to a well-known position that Garry Kasparov once reached with the white pieces against Alexander Khalifman. Black is under severe pressure, with their king stuck in the center. }
7. d3 { Make sure to avoid  7.e5?!  d5!  , which is fine for Black. } 7... d5
{ I also found some games in which Black tried  7...d6  ,  but we are better against it by employing the natural plan Nd2-f3, putting pressure on d4. A sample line runs  8.Nd2  Be7  9.h3  @@StartBracket@@we have time to stop a possibly inconvenient pin@@EndBracket@@  9...O-O  10.Nf3  ,  when Black's pawn is weak. }
8. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black's position wouldn't be all that bad if they had about 2-3 extra tempi. As it stands, the king is on e8 and under pressure. }
9. Re1+ Be7 { Black wants to castle, so this makes a lot of sense. } 10. Bg5
O-O
{ Black's king needs to leave the center ASAP.   Here  10...Be6?  would be bad due to  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.Bxd5  cxd5  13.Nd2  ,  when Black's d4-pawn is a juicy target. }
11. Bxe7 Nxe7 12. Qf3
{ I like this move, but  12.Qh5  or  12.Nd2  would be just as good. We exert annoying pressure on f7, and Black's pieces are passive. The next step is Nd2-e4, getting our knight into the game. }
