1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4
{ The Bird Defense, named after Henry Bird, not the animal. It's still no good, like all the 'animal openings' - let's examine why. }
4. Nxd4 { Easy - we take the quirky knight. } 4... exd4 5. O-O
{ Again, very natural play. After five moves, we are already castled, while Black has not developed a single piece. There is no doubt that Black's concept must be dubious, but it does have some ideas. The d4-pawn is currently restricting our pieces, in particular our b1-knight. Black can also play the move ...c6 soon, gaining a tempo on our bishop. Our bishop will likely find a good spot on c4, putting some pressure against Black's kingside.   We'll examine two approaches by Black now:  5...Bc5  , starting their kingside development, and  5...c6  ,  chasing our bishop and playing for as ...d5 push.   I also found several online games with the odd-looking move  5...a5?!  , which is bad but sets a trap. If we pay no attention and continue  6.d3??  , Black traps our bishop with  6...c6  7.Bc4  b5  8.Bb3  a4  - duh! About any other move than  6.d3??  is good for White, though. I'd suggest  6.a4  , stopping all funny ideas. }
5... Bc5
{ Black finally gets a piece out. They intend to further develop with ...Ne7 and ...O-O. }
6. Bc4
{ This move is the most forcing. We will likely have to move the bishop anyway at some point, and doing it right now threatens the standard tactic Bxf7+, followed by Qh5+. Black has to play ...d6, covering the bishop. }
6... d6
{ Here  6...Ne7??  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Qh5+  is the pitfall Black needs to avoid. }
7. d3 Ne7
{ A lot better than  7...Nf6?  , when  8.Bg5  is an extremely annoying pin for Black. }
8. f4
{ Here playing  8.Qh5  and f4 later is a good alternative. I suggest making the pawn move first, focusing more on our general setup. We want the f-pawn involved in our play and may still play the queen to h5 later. }
8... O-O 9. Nd2
{ We develop our knight and ask Black about their intentions. It's tough to play for our opponent. }
9... Kh8
{ The engine already thinks this is the only move, more or less. It wants to have the option of playing ...f6 or ...f5 to defend. Black is under much pressure after other moves, like  9...d5  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Ne4  ,  followed by f4-f5, demonstrates. }
10. Qh5
{ The queen gets closer to the black king and controls the fifth rank, making the move ...d5 more difficult for Black to play. }
10... f5
{ After  10...f6  we have an interesting choice between the brutal  11.g4  and the more sophisticated move  11.a3  ,  which I prefer. The idea is playing against the c5-bishop with b4, later eyeing the d4-pawn. We are not committed to a 'throw-the-kitchen-sink' attack here. }
11. Nf3
{ Our attack is getting dangerous now. Here are two sample lines.   A.  11...fxe4?  12.dxe4  d3+  13.Kh1  dxc2  is far too greedy due to  14.Ng5  , winning on the spot.   B.  11...Qe8!  looks to be best, but  12.Qxe8  Rxe8  13.Re1  is still better for White after  13...fxe4  14.dxe4  d3+  15.Be3  Bxe3+  16.Rxe3  dxc2  17.Rc1  , when we regain the pawn and have the much more active pieces. }
