1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ The Cozio Defense is a sideline and rarely played, but not without its points. Black does not yet tell us how they intend to develop their kingside. We'll know more about their plans after we have castled, a universally useful move. }
4. O-O
{ It is possible to play  4.d4  right away, but Black is happy about trading one knight after  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Nxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  ,  when White is only slightly better. I suggest castling first and delaying d4 for one move. Black has to commit in some way now.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...g6  is the most popular move when we play  5.d4  .   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ng6  is an alternative development option, also answered by  5.d4  I'll examine these two moves in some detail, but there are two more to discuss.   C.  4...a6  5.Ba4  reaches the delayed Cozio, which we also discuss in the current chapter. The ideas are very similar, but the added move ...a6 changes small details. You can argue that  5.Bc4  is maybe even better, but not enough to study this exotic possibility.   D.  4...d6  is a passive move, mixing the Steinitz @@StartBracket@@3...d6@@EndBracket@@ and the Cozio. White is much better with normal moves like  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@or  5.c3  and d4 next, if you prefer that@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Ng6
{ Black wants to develop their bishop to e7 or c5 and moves the knight again to prepare it. }
5. d4
{ We want to open the position to exploit Black's sluggish development. The resulting pawn formation is comfortable for White, too. Let's discuss after Black captures our pawn. }
5... exd4 6. Nxd4
{ We have reached a pawn structure that is well known from the Scotch @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  @@EndBracket@@. In such a structure, Black has two main goals:   ...Accomplish d7-d5 to remove the e-pawn and nullify the space disadvantage,Exert pressure on e4 if the first objective fails.Unfortunately for Black, it isn't easy to realize these goals with a knight sitting on g6. Black's position is resilient because they have no structural weakness. However, generating some activity will be difficult for our opponent. }
6... Bc5
{ The main idea to remember is our next move. Black places their bishop on a good diagonal and attacks our knight. We want to trade the strong c5-bishop but don't want to allow too many simplifications. Therefore,  7.Be3  Nxd4  8.Bxd4  Bxd4  9.Qxd4  is a bit toothless. We have a space advantage, which means keeping more material on the board. It's best to move our knight. }
7. Nf5 { We avoid the knight trade and prepare Be3 next. } 7... O-O 8. Be3
{ It makes sense to trade Black's most active piece but keep the passive ones on the board. }
8... Bxe3
{ You also meet  8...Bb6?!  , when  9.Nc3  d6  10.Bxb6  axb6  11.Ne3  leads to a worse version of 8...Bxe3, as the doubled pawn is a handicap for Black. At some point, Black might want to play the c-pawn to c6, controlling d5. This is more difficult to realize with the doubled pawns on the board, as b6 would be weakened. }
9. Nxe3
{ We have reached a comfortable position. The next step is completing development with Nc3 and Qd2. We can use the d5-square for our knights and also think about playing f4-f5 to start an attack. }
