1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ The Cozio Defense is a sideline and rarely played, but not without its points. Black does not yet tell us how they intend to develop their kingside. We'll know more about their plans after we have castled, a universally useful move. }
4. O-O
{ It is possible to play  4.d4  right away, but Black is happy about trading one knight after  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Nxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  ,  when White is only slightly better. I suggest castling first and delaying d4 for one move. Black has to commit in some way now.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...g6  is the most popular move when we play  5.d4  .   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ng6  is an alternative development option, also answered by  5.d4  I'll examine these two moves in some detail, but there are two more to discuss.   C.  4...a6  5.Ba4  reaches the delayed Cozio, which we also discuss in the current chapter. The ideas are very similar, but the added move ...a6 changes small details. You can argue that  5.Bc4  is maybe even better, but not enough to study this exotic possibility.   D.  4...d6  is a passive move, mixing the Steinitz @@StartBracket@@3...d6@@EndBracket@@ and the Cozio. White is much better with normal moves like  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@or  5.c3  and d4 next, if you prefer that@@EndBracket@@. }
4... g6
{ Black's most popular move. They often combine ...Nge7 and ...g6 in other lines, so this is no surprise. }
5. d4 { We stick to our concept to open the center. } 5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7.
Nxc6
{ The exclam is a bit of an overstatement, but the capture is not an obvious decision and leads to a comfortable game. We'll check  7...Nxc6  and  7...bxc6  now. }
7... Nxc6
{ This position type is well-known to be better for White. We control the d5-square and have more space. The simple and good solution is something like  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Be3  ,  going for a Qd2 and Bh6 plan. However, I found a different way of going for the bishop trade. }
8. Bd2
{ I know it's simpler to play  8.Nc3  ,  but this is a fun move to play! We develop the bishop and ignore that b2 is hanging. It turns out that Black can't take on b2. It's far too risky, as we will see. If you do not want to bother will all that,  8.Nc3  is your move. }
8... Bxb2
{ Black puts greed above everything else - a bad choice. They should play a normal move like  8...O-O  , when  9.Bc3  leads to a nice advantage for White. We trade Black's best piece and enjoy a space advantage. After the bishop trade, playing Nc3, Qd2 is on the agenda next. }
9. Nc3
{ That's the problem! We cut off the bishop from retreating to the kingside. Black can take the exchange now, but we'll have a huge attack! }
9... Bxa1
{ Black can't survive  9...O-O  10.Rb1  Ba3  11.Nd5  , either. Our attack is far too strong. }
10. Qxa1
{ Our threat is Nd5 now, and it will hit with devastating effect. Black can't prevent it with the next move. }
10... Qf6 { OK, no Nd5 now, but the queen move still fails. } 11. e5
{ The most powerful reply. Black can't take the pawn due to a pin on the e-file, and  11...Qe6  12.Ne4  leads to a disaster on the dark squares. Black's pawn grab is far too risky @@StartBracket@@or even loses the game, according to the engine@@EndBracket@@. }
