1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ The Cozio Defense is a sideline and rarely played, but not without its points. Black does not yet tell us how they intend to develop their kingside. We'll know more about their plans after we have castled, a universally useful move. }
4. O-O
{ It is possible to play  4.d4  right away, but Black is happy about trading one knight after  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Nxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  ,  when White is only slightly better. I suggest castling first and delaying d4 for one move. Black has to commit in some way now.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...g6  is the most popular move when we play  5.d4  .   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ng6  is an alternative development option, also answered by  5.d4  I'll examine these two moves in some detail, but there are two more to discuss.   C.  4...a6  5.Ba4  reaches the delayed Cozio, which we also discuss in the current chapter. The ideas are very similar, but the added move ...a6 changes small details. You can argue that  5.Bc4  is maybe even better, but not enough to study this exotic possibility.   D.  4...d6  is a passive move, mixing the Steinitz @@StartBracket@@3...d6@@EndBracket@@ and the Cozio. White is much better with normal moves like  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@or  5.c3  and d4 next, if you prefer that@@EndBracket@@. }
4... g6
{ Black's most popular move. They often combine ...Nge7 and ...g6 in other lines, so this is no surprise. }
5. d4 { We stick to our concept to open the center. } 5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7.
Nxc6
{ The exclam is a bit of an overstatement, but the capture is not an obvious decision and leads to a comfortable game. We'll check  7...Nxc6  and  7...bxc6  now. }
7... bxc6
{ This looks stronger than the knight capture, as Black controls the d5-square. Their pawn structure is damaged, though. Our next move highlights this fact. }
8. Ba4
{ We keep an eye on the c6-pawn and keep the option to play the bishop to b3, which may help to secure the b-pawn. We'll see this idea in a moment. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3
{ We develop our knight, an easy move. Now Black's best is a setup based on ...d6 and ...Rb8. I'll check the sequence that Erwin l'Ami suggested for Black in his course on the Cozio. }
9... Rb8 { Erwin suggested this setup. } 10. Bb3
{ We want to play Be3 and secure the b-pawn first. } 10... d6 11. Be3 c5 12.
Qd2
{ We played all the logical moves. Erwin closes his analysis here with  12...Be6  and assesses the position as 'approximately equal'. I had a closer look to better understand the position. White's job is a bit easier here, but it's not trivial.   Here are some points: The tension between the bishop on b3 and e6 is a key element. Black does not want to take on b3, as axb3 opens the a-file for our rook and exposes Black's a-pawn as a target.White can consider taking on e6. It's possible immediately, but I think the key to the position is that we are better equipped to improve our position while keeping the option in hand. One example of this point is that after @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/p1p1npbp/3pb1p1/2p5/4P3/1BN1B3/PPPQ1PPP/R4RK1 w - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Bxe6  fxe6  Black's rook enjoys the f-file. If we don't take but play improvement moves, Black would be reluctant to play ...Rfe8, for example. It would strengthen the capture on  e6  , as the rook would be better placed on f8.It's not so easy for Black to improve. Some moves have drawbacks that may worsen the situation. One example is ...a5, which might create a target. If Black plays ...Nc6, they make Nd5 stronger.   Let's translate these points into moves. After  12...Be6  , the move  13.Rab1  looks best. We don't want to take e6 yet and must address the pressure on b2. The rook move also helps to increase our knight's mobility. Let's look at possible replies to 13.Rab1.   A. @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/p1p1npbp/3pb1p1/2p5/4P3/1BN1B3/PPPQ1PPP/1R3RK1 b - - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nc6  14.Nd5  Nd4  15.Bg5  f6  16.Be3  looks good for White. Black has created more weaknesses, and the d4-knight is not stable.   B. @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/p1p1npbp/3pb1p1/2p5/4P3/1BN1B3/PPPQ1PPP/1R3RK1 b - - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qd7  14.Rfe1  is a good move to improve a bit. Now  14...Nc6?  15.Ba4!  is terrible for Black. Better is @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/p1pqnpbp/3pb1p1/2p5/4P3/1BN1B3/PPPQ1PPP/1R2R1K1 b - - 5 14@@EndFEN@@  14...a5  15.h3  , when we have improved a bit more. Here Black can fall into a nice trap, as  15...c4?  16.Ba4  Bxc3??  17.Qxc3  Qxa4  18.Qf6!!  wins on the spot.Black has to play some less forcing moves. After  @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/2pqnpbp/3pb1p1/p1p5/4P3/1BN1B2P/PPPQ1PP1/1R2R1K1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Rfe8  16.Bxe6  @@StartBracket@@a better moment for this exchange than before@@EndBracket@@  16...fxe6  17.a4  ,  intending Nb5, we have some advantage: a5 is a target.  The comp often suggests...Bxb3 for Black, and only gives White a small advantage after it. I would be delighted to see the capture, as it gives White an easy target on the a-file.That was a long discussion, but it's a strategically interesting situation. It was fascinating for me to explore it deeper. An interesting idea to try is playing it with Black against an engine. Try out things and see how the comp deals with them. You'll learn plenty of ideas for both sides. }
