[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A5) Ruy Lopez – Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Odds & Ends – 3...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ The move  3...g6  is usually called the Smyslov Variation, but these ...g6 and ...Nge7 lines all blend together. Against the Smyslov and the Delayed version  3...a6  4.Ba4  g6  ,  I suggest immediately pushing d2-d4, opening the center. If you want to go for this approach, it is crucial to play it immediately, as  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1p1p/2n3p1/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  Bg7  gives Black enough control of d4 to stop it. Of course, you can play  5.c3  ,  but that's a different story. }
4. d4
{ Here we go. The following line is more or less forced and gives White a nagging advantage. When I examined 3...g6 for Black, I was always put off by this line, as it felt like Black has to grovel.  OK, let's see how we get to the position type I am talking about. }
4... exd4 5. Bg5
{ A very concrete approach. Black's queen is attacked, which only leaves  5...Be7  or the ugly  5...f6?!  , when  6.Bf4  is simple and good. We castle and regain d4 later when Black has created weaknesses for no benefit. }
5... Be7
{ More or less forced, as  5...f6?!  weakens Black's structure as mentioned. }
6. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ Black has to take with the queen, as  6...Ngxe7  7.Nxd4  leads to a nice advantage for White. We have more space, and Black misses their dark-squared bishop badly. }
7. O-O
{ This move is more challenging than White's alternative  7.Bxc6  , when  7...dxc6  8.Qxd4  Nf6  9.Nc3  is the consequence. If you like technical positions, this might come into consideration. White has a more potent pawn majority on the kingside, and most endgames will be favourable, similar to the Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation. }
7... Nf6
{ Black's usual choice here.   7...Qb4  leads to a barren endgame for Black:  8.Bxc6  dxc6  9.Qxd4  Qxd4  10.Nxd4  gives us a nagging advantage. Black's doubled pawn is a handicap forever, as they can't create a passed pawn. Our kingside majority is far more valuable. }
8. Re1
{ We can always regain the d4-pawn. Our idea is to do it under more favourable circumstances.   The rook move and  8.e5  are of about equal value. They will often lead to the same positions, as I intend to answer  8.Re1  O-O  with  9.e5  . }
8... O-O
{ Black needs to get out of the center; there is no good alternative. I'll now suggest  9.e5  , but  9.Bxc6  dxc6  10.Qxd4  also leads to a small advantage. This is a slightly better version of 7.Bxc6, as Black has already castled kingside. In the 7.Bxc6 line, Black at least manages to castle queenside. }
9. e5
{ The most interesting move. If you forget it and regain the pawn with  9.Bxc6  , you'll still have a nice position. Our structure is better, and Black's dark squares are weak. }
9... Nd5 10. a3
{ A little finesse that is not easy to remember. The idea of the move is not obvious. The move  10.c4  is tempting, but Black can play  10...dxc3!  , as  11.Qxd5  cxb2  works.   The move  10.a3  prepares the move c4 and more or less tells Black: 'You have no great move anyway!' This is probably true, as the most interesting move  10...Qc5  is nice for White, as we will see. The comp wants to play  10...a6  , when  11.Bxc6  dxc6  12.Qxd4  is slightly better for White. Our dream scenario is to place a knight e4 and then manage c4 to remove the guy on d5. Note how useful the move a3 is. Without it, Black has chances based on ...Nb4 or ...Qb4. }
10... Qc5 11. Bf1
{ Better than taking now, as  11...d6  12.b4  Qb6  13.c4  gives White the initiative and sees Black under pressure.   There is no fully satisfactory solution for Black, as  11...Nb6  12.b4  Qe7  13.b5  or @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pppp1p1p/2n3p1/2qnP3/3p4/P4N2/1PP2PPP/RN1QRBK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a5?  12.b4!  look like even worse options.  In conclusion, I think White has the better chances after 4.d4 - this line always annoyed me when I studied 3...g6 as a possible option for Black. }
