[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A5) Ruy Lopez – Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Odds & Ends – 3...a6 4.Ba4 b5 5.Bb3 d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ After  4.Ba4  Black's main move is  4...Nf6  ,  attacking our e4-pawn. This is played in approximately 80-90% of the games, depending on your playing level. This suggests that  4...Nf6  is probably the best move, but some alternatives are worth studying.What options does Black have? In the current chapter, we have a look at  4...b5  ,  a rare move at the master level but seen more often below that. It looks like the best that Black can reach is a transposition to other lines, but we want to check some bad or risky alternatives. Furthermore, we'll examine the delayed versions of the Smyslov and Cozio,  4...g6  and  4...Nge7  . }
4... b5
{ Black continues to chase our bishop. This move is relatively rare, but not objectively bad if Black plays precisely afterwards. This 'precise play' usually means a transposition to other variations. Let's look closely.   Our first move is easy 😀 }
5. Bb3
{ Now we need to consider some options for Black. Some risky/bad ones don't transpose elsewhere, but Black has two reasonable ways to play. So here's the list of the Good, the Bad, and the Risky.The Good:   A.  5...Nf6  looks like Black's best move when I recommend playing  6.d3  to transpose to our Ruy main lines. You could  try  6.d4  as a more maximalist approach, but I don't think it's worth the effort. It's worth mentioning that  6.Ng5?  looks tempting, but is convincingly refuted by  6...d5  7.exd5  Nd4  , when Black is much better.   B.  5...Bb7  is the other reasonable move when  6.d3  Nf6  7.a4  would again transpose to our Ruy main line.The Bad:   C.  5...Bc5  is bad due to a quick c3&d4 push. This line is covered in the chapter on the Classical and related lines, as it is best studied in comparison with other ...Bc5-lines.   D.  5...Be7  6.d4!  is excellent for White.   E.  5...d6  6.a4!  shows the defect of this move order. In these cases, Black plays moves regularly employed in the Ruy, but at a bad moment. For example,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2pp1ppp/p1n5/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.d3  Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2pp1ppp/p1n5/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.d3  Be7  are our main Ruy lines. Here Black plays the bishop moves too early before White has committed to d3. This allows a quicker central play based on d4 in one move.The Risky:   F.  5...Na5  is a creative but risky line. Black gets the bishop pair but is seriously behind in development.So A and B are Black's best options, but they transpose. We have to cover the 'Bad' and 'Risky' now! }
5... d6
{ A pretty rare move here, but worth a quick look for two reasons. We can get a nice position by playing the best @@StartBracket@@or a good@@EndBracket@@ move, but there are also two moves to avoid! }
6. a4
{ I think this is best, immediately hitting the queenside. It also would be fine to play  6.O-O  or  6.c3  , but it is crucial to understand that there are two moves to avoid - the exclam is mostly for not stepping into one of those pitfalls.   A.  6.d4?!  is bad due to  6...Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  , when we reach the famous 'Ark Noah' trap.  8.Qxd4??  c5  9.Qd5  Be6  10.Qc6+  Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  and it's 'Bye-bye bishop'.This trap usually arises via a different move order.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.d4?!  b5  6.Bb3  Nxd4  is the usual path to it. White does not have to play  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4??  ,  but it's already unattractive for White.   B.  6.d3?!  is a strategic mistake due to  6...Na5!  ,  when we have no way to keep our strong Ruy bishop. This idea frequently occurs, most notably after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  , when we should play the move  6.c3!  to create an escape square for our important bishop. }
6... b4
{ Black has to do something about the b-pawn. The move  6...Bb7?  is the most played here, but after  7.axb5  axb5  8.Rxa8  Bxa8  9.Nc3  b4  10.Nd5  White has a strong initiative. Stockfish says White is winning, but this is a common problem nowadays. The engines see all kinds of disasters already, while a human can identify that Black has gone wrong and is in trouble. We can be happy, in any case. }
7. d4 { Now pushing the d-pawn two squares works much better. } 7... Nxd4 8.
Nxd4 exd4 9. Qxd4
{ Black is in serious trouble now, as b4 is attacked and they have no development. }
9... c5 10. Qd3
{ No Ark Noah trap this time! Black is now left with a rotten position, full of weaknesses.   The whole line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2pp1ppp/p1n5/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6?!  is fairly obscure, but I wanted to emphasize that you must avoid the traps on move six. After  6.a4!  or the other mentioned moves, we have a nice version of a Ruy and easy moves to play. }
