[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ After  4.Ba4  Black's main move is  4...Nf6  ,  attacking our e4-pawn. This is played in approximately 80-90% of the games, depending on your playing level. This suggests that  4...Nf6  is probably the best move, but some alternatives are worth studying.What options does Black have? In the current chapter, we have a look at  4...b5  ,  a rare move at the master level but seen more often below that. It looks like the best that Black can reach is a transposition to other lines, but we want to check some bad or risky alternatives. Furthermore, we'll examine the delayed versions of the Smyslov and Cozio,  4...g6  and  4...Nge7  . }
4... b5
{ Black continues to chase our bishop. This move is relatively rare, but not objectively bad if Black plays precisely afterwards. This 'precise play' usually means a transposition to other variations. Let's look closely.   Our first move is easy 😀 }
5. Bb3
{ Now we need to consider some options for Black. Some risky/bad ones don't transpose elsewhere, but Black has two reasonable ways to play. So here's the list of the Good, the Bad, and the Risky.The Good:   A.  5...Nf6  looks like Black's best move when I recommend playing  6.d3  to transpose to our Ruy main lines. You could  try  6.d4  as a more maximalist approach, but I don't think it's worth the effort. It's worth mentioning that  6.Ng5?  looks tempting, but is convincingly refuted by  6...d5  7.exd5  Nd4  , when Black is much better.   B.  5...Bb7  is the other reasonable move when  6.d3  Nf6  7.a4  would again transpose to our Ruy main line.The Bad:   C.  5...Bc5  is bad due to a quick c3&d4 push. This line is covered in the chapter on the Classical and related lines, as it is best studied in comparison with other ...Bc5-lines.   D.  5...Be7  6.d4!  is excellent for White.   E.  5...d6  6.a4!  shows the defect of this move order. In these cases, Black plays moves regularly employed in the Ruy, but at a bad moment. For example,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2pp1ppp/p1n5/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.d3  Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2pp1ppp/p1n5/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.d3  Be7  are our main Ruy lines. Here Black plays the bishop moves too early before White has committed to d3. This allows a quicker central play based on d4 in one move.The Risky:   F.  5...Na5  is a creative but risky line. Black gets the bishop pair but is seriously behind in development.So A and B are Black's best options, but they transpose. We have to cover the 'Bad' and 'Risky' now! }
5... Na5
{ Black REALLY wants our bishop! The knight jump is risky for Black, as it neglects development and the center. On the other hand, they get the bishop pair and hope to survive the onslaught. It's a risky concept, but it has to be taken seriously. }
6. Nc3
{ I suggest this move, which is less popular but just as good @@StartBracket@@or better... it's tough to say with 100% certainty@@EndBracket@@ as the most popular move  6.O-O  .  Playing the knight to c3 is uncommon in our Ruy Lopez repertoire. We are usually focused on building a center with c3&d4. It's crucial to understand that Black has violated opening principles with 5...Na5 - we need to 'punish' it in the correct way.   Let's discuss the situation for a moment. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2pp1ppp/p1n5/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Na5  , the first move to check is  6.Nxe5  , but this is a mistake due to  6...Nxb3  7.axb3  Qg5!  ,  when Black has a double attack and gets the pawn back. What to play, then?Black will get our nice bishop but neglects their development. We must try to exploit our lead in development by focusing on opening the center and playing in a concrete, almost tactical way. If we just let Black grab the bishop and consolidate, their opening concept would be successful.   White's most popular move, kingside castling, is a move that focuses on the development, too. White gets the king secure and, at the same time, attacks the e5-pawn for real. I think that  6.O-O  gives White good chances for an advantage, but I like my suggestion of  6.Nc3  even more. It follows the same concept - rapid development - but sets some unique challenges to Black, who is likely only prepared for the main move. After  6.Nc3  ,  we are not committed to kingside castling and sometimes are a bit faster with creating threats in the center. Even castling queenside is not out of the question. Black has two basic options: taking on b3 or covering the e5-pawn. }
6... d6
{ Black covers their central pawn, and delays/omits the capture of our bishop. The idea is to still have the bishop as a potential target of a queenside pawn advance. Black's dream would be something like  7.d4  exd4  8.Nxd4?  c5!  ,  when White's bishop gets in trouble @@StartBracket@@Ark Noah trap!@@EndBracket@@. We won't allow that by taking with our queen on d4! }
7. d4 { We need to open the game to exploit our lead in development. } 7...
exd4
{ Black could also play  7...Nxb3  8.axb3  exd4  9.Qxd4  ,  which we will examine now via the move order  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p2p4/np2p3/3PP3/1BN2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...exd4  8.Qxd4  Nxb3  9.axb3  , leading to a great position for White. }
8. Qxd4
{ We have to avoid  8.Nxd4?  c5!  , when Black gets what they wanted.   Instead, after  8.Qxd4  we don't need to worry about the move  8...c5??  , as  9.Bxf7+!  Kxf7  10.Qd5+  wins on the spot. We will now examine the capture on b3 @@StartBracket@@rather cooperative@@EndBracket@@ and the more challenging 8...Bb7. }
8... Nxb3
{ This makes our play easier, as we don't have to worry about ...c5 ideas anymore. }
9. axb3 Bb7 10. Bf4
{ We have excellent development and are ready for queenside castling. } 10...
Ne7
{ Black has problems getting their pieces out.   The more natural  10...Nf6  11.O-O-O  Be7  12.e5!  already looks dire. We open the center too quickly. }
11. O-O-O
{ This possibility is one of the incentives of starting with 6.Nc3 over 6.O-O. We are not committed to kingside castling, but have this dynamic option. We have a great position now. Black can play  11...Ng6  , but after  12.Be3  are ready to hit their knight with h4-h5 next. }
*

