exd4
{ Black could also play  7...Nxb3  8.axb3  exd4  9.Qxd4  ,  which we will examine now via the move order  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/2p2ppp/p2p4/np2p3/3PP3/1BN2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...exd4  8.Qxd4  Nxb3  9.axb3  , leading to a great position for White. }
8. Qxd4
{ We have to avoid  8.Nxd4?  c5!  , when Black gets what they wanted.   Instead, after  8.Qxd4  we don't need to worry about the move  8...c5??  , as  9.Bxf7+!  Kxf7  10.Qd5+  wins on the spot. We will now examine the capture on b3 @@StartBracket@@rather cooperative@@EndBracket@@ and the more challenging 8...Bb7. }
8... Bb7
{ This is a more challenging move than taking on b3. Black covers the square d5, so that ...c5 gets back on the map.   A similar idea is  8...Ne7  , when I suggest  9.Qd3  to step out of the ...c5 threat. }
9. Bg5
{ Developing with a tempo is always a tempting option. There is no fully satisfactory reply now, as we will see. }
9... Qd7
{ This seems to be best for Black. The alternatives aren't great, as the following lines suggest.   A.  9...f6  10.Bxg8  @@StartBracket@@we must take first to avoid ...c5-c4@@EndBracket@@  9...Rxg8  10.Be3  .   B.  9...Nxb3  10.axb3  f6  10.Bf4  .  In both cases, Black's position is weakened by the move ...f6. In line A, they can't castle kingside on top of everything. }
10. Nd5
{ A tough call, as  10.O-O-O  is very strong, too. Black can't risk  10...c5  11.Qe3  c4  , as the funny move  12.Ba4!  seems to be killing. I don't want to recommend this as the main move, as we are already deep down the rabbit hole in a sideline.   The move  10.Nd5  works well without any sacrifices to analyze. Black now has nothing better than  10...Nxb3  11.axb3  f6  12.Bf4  ,  when we have a pleasant advantage. The d5-knight is a monster, and Black still can't develop easily. If you want a sharper game, playing 10.O-O-O is good, of course! }
