1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ After  4.Ba4  Black's main move is  4...Nf6  ,  attacking our e4-pawn. This is played in approximately 80-90% of the games, depending on your playing level. This suggests that  4...Nf6  is probably the best move, but some alternatives are worth studying.What options does Black have? In the current chapter, we have a look at  4...b5  ,  a rare move at the master level but seen more often below that. It looks like the best that Black can reach is a transposition to other lines, but we want to check some bad or risky alternatives. Furthermore, we'll examine the delayed versions of the Smyslov and Cozio,  4...g6  and  4...Nge7  . }
4... g6
{ Black goes for a rare move order, the 'Delayed Smyslov'. I have played this line once with Black as a surprise weapon. I didn't look too closely at the time and just played it... now I know it has a serious problem. White is much better after the following line. }
5. d4
{ We go for a quick d4 in this chapter anyway, so this one is easy to remember. }
5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nxc6
{ This is remarkably powerful for White. Black can't allow the awful endgame after  7...dxc6  8.Qxd8+  , which leaves the other recapture. }
7... bxc6 8. O-O
{ Playing  8.Nc3  is also fine. The best way to evaluate the position after  8.O-O  is to compare it to the line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  4.O-O  g6  5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  Bg7  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.Ba4  ,  which also gives White an advantage. Here we are a tempo up, essentially, as Black has made the useless move ...a6.As in the 3...Nge7 line I mentioned, we'll play a setup with Nc3, Be3, and Qd2 and aim to trade Black's bishop. We can stop the trainable here, as an improved version of an already good line is a great result. }
