[Black "Ruy Lopez – Odds & Ends – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nge7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ After  4.Ba4  Black's main move is  4...Nf6  ,  attacking our e4-pawn. This is played in approximately 80-90% of the games, depending on your playing level. This suggests that  4...Nf6  is probably the best move, but some alternatives are worth studying.What options does Black have? In the current chapter, we have a look at  4...b5  ,  a rare move at the master level but seen more often below that. It looks like the best that Black can reach is a transposition to other lines, but we want to check some bad or risky alternatives. Furthermore, we'll examine the delayed versions of the Smyslov and Cozio,  4...g6  and  4...Nge7  . }
4... Nge7
{ The 'Delayed Cozio' is an even more exotic line than the original Cozio. Our general approach is the same as against 3...Nge7, but the pawn being on a6 makes a small difference. In some cases, Let's have a look. }
5. O-O
{ We castle first and want to play d4 next, the same concept as in the Cozio. What difference does the insertion of...a6 and Ba4 make?   A.  5...Ng6  may turn out differently, as Black can use a quick ...b5 idea. It's good for White, but worth a look.   B.  5....g6  is very similar to the line  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  4.O-O  g6  ,  but I'll briefly show it and discuss the small differences.   C.  5...d6  is different from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  4.O-O  d6  , as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp1nppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d4  can be answered with  6...b5  7.Bb3  Nxd4  8.Nxd4  exd4  .  Yes, you might know what's coming now... don't play  9.Qxd4??  c5  and fall into a version of the 'Ark Noah' trap! White has a great position after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2p1nppp/p2p4/1p6/3pP3/1B6/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  , though. After  9...Rb8  10.axb5  axb5  11.c3  dxc3  12.Nxc3  White's compensation is more than sufficient. I considered making this a trainable, but you'll likely never get it on the board. In addition, there is the simple alternative 6.c3 and d4 next, which is nice for White, too.   D.  5...b5?!  6.Bb3  is very risky for Black. They have to watch out for Ng5 now and are far behind in development. }
5... g6
{ Our coverage of this move is brief, as the differences to the variation @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  4.O-O  g6  are minor. }
6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bg7
{ Black could play  7...b5  here, but  8.Nxc6  Nxc6  9.Bb3  or  8.Bb3  Bg7  9.Nxc6  Nxc6  10.Nc3  makes you wonder what Black has accomplished with the queenside expansion. The simple plan Be3, Qd2 and Bh6 works well here, too. }
8. Nxc6
{ Now we get to a difference because  8...bxc6?  9.Nc3  is much weaker now than in the Cozio - it does not gain a tempo on our bishop. White is much better after the pawn capture, as it's an extra tempo that matters. It's funny to see that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  g6  5.d4!  exd4  6.Nxd4  Bg7  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.O-O  Ne7  9.Nc3  leads to the same position. }
8... Nxc6
{ Black has to go for the knight capture here, as the alternatives are much worse. }
9. Bd2
{ We play the same idea in the Cozio. Black can't grab on b2, and after a slow move, we'll play Bc3 and have a nice advantage. }
9... b5 { This is a way to make it different to the Cozio lines. } 10. Bb3 Nd4
{ An interesting idea. Black wants to answer  11.Bc3  with  11...c5  , but we have a much better continuation. }
11. Bd5 c6 { After  11...Rb8  , we have  12.c3  to send the knight back. } 12.
Be3
{ That's the point. After  12...Ne6  13.Bxe6  dxe6  , we have a comfortable advantage, as Black's dark squares are so weak.  14.c3  or  14.Qc1  are good moves to start with. Nd2-b3-c5 is an idea to keep in mind. }
