5... Ng6
{ Black goes for the classical development of their bishop to e7 or c5. Usually, we'll get 'almost the same positions as in the Cozio, but there is one possibility for Black to give it some independent value. }
6. d4 exd4
{ Black may also play  6...b5  7.Bb3  exd4  8.Nxd4  Nxd4  9.Qxd4  , which is a different move order to the position we are about to examine. }
7. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ This is an independent option for Black. They often play  7...Bc5  , when  8.Nf5  O-O  9.Be3  is about the same as the line from the Cozio. The insertion of ...a6 and Ba4 do not change it much. }
8. Qxd4 b5
{ That's a difference to the Cozio. Black gets a tempo on our bishop and has ...Bb7 next. }
9. Bb3 Bb7
{ Black can't play  9...c5??  due to  10.Qd5  or  10.Bxf7+  ,  winning the house. Black needs to play the bishop first, and now ...c5 is a viable idea. The next move is important, as it secures an advantage - other moves don't! }
10. Rd1
{ A compelling engine suggestion! It addresses Black's ...c5 threat with a tactical solution, as  10...c5??  11.Bxf7+!  is crushing. We'll check this in a minute, as the tactics a fun to examine.   OK, Black can't play their main idea, but what else can they do? Our queen has a powerful position in the middle of the board, and Black can't easily develop. Stockfish only sees one reasonable defense, which is tough to see for a human player, the move  10...Qe7!  - it renews the ...c5 threat and covers f7. We'll have a quick look at it, too. }
10... c5 { This loses on the spot - let's check why. } 11. Bxf7+ Kxf7 12. Qxd7+
{ So far, so good. Now  12...Kf6??  13.Qf5+  Ke7  14.Bg5  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1b1r/1b1Q1kpp/p5n1/1pp5/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBR2K1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Be7?  13.Qf5+  are easy wins. The only challenging move is the following. }
12... Qe7 13. Bg5
{ This move is the only winner for White! After  13...Bc8  14.Qd5+  Be6  15.Bxe7  Bxd5  16.Bxf8  Bxe4  17.Bxc5  , we have won material and should win the game, too. }
