[White "A5) Ruy Lopez – Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Odds & Ends – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nge7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ After  4.Ba4  Black's main move is  4...Nf6  ,  attacking our e4-pawn. This is played in approximately 80-90% of the games, depending on your playing level. This suggests that  4...Nf6  is probably the best move, but some alternatives are worth studying.What options does Black have? In the current chapter, we have a look at  4...b5  ,  a rare move at the master level but seen more often below that. It looks like the best that Black can reach is a transposition to other lines, but we want to check some bad or risky alternatives. Furthermore, we'll examine the delayed versions of the Smyslov and Cozio,  4...g6  and  4...Nge7  . }
4... Nge7
{ The 'Delayed Cozio' is an even more exotic line than the original Cozio. Our general approach is the same as against 3...Nge7, but the pawn being on a6 makes a small difference. In some cases, Let's have a look. }
5. O-O
{ We castle first and want to play d4 next, the same concept as in the Cozio. What difference does the insertion of...a6 and Ba4 make?   A.  5...Ng6  may turn out differently, as Black can use a quick ...b5 idea. It's good for White, but worth a look.   B.  5....g6  is very similar to the line  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  4.O-O  g6  ,  but I'll briefly show it and discuss the small differences.   C.  5...d6  is different from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nge7  4.O-O  d6  , as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp1nppp/p1np4/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d4  can be answered with  6...b5  7.Bb3  Nxd4  8.Nxd4  exd4  .  Yes, you might know what's coming now... don't play  9.Qxd4??  c5  and fall into a version of the 'Ark Noah' trap! White has a great position after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2p1nppp/p2p4/1p6/3pP3/1B6/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  , though. After  9...Rb8  10.axb5  axb5  11.c3  dxc3  12.Nxc3  White's compensation is more than sufficient. I considered making this a trainable, but you'll likely never get it on the board. In addition, there is the simple alternative 6.c3 and d4 next, which is nice for White, too.   D.  5...b5?!  6.Bb3  is very risky for Black. They have to watch out for Ng5 now and are far behind in development. }
5... Ng6
{ Black goes for the classical development of their bishop to e7 or c5. Usually, we'll get 'almost the same positions as in the Cozio, but there is one possibility for Black to give it some independent value. }
6. d4 exd4
{ Black may also play  6...b5  7.Bb3  exd4  8.Nxd4  Nxd4  9.Qxd4  , which is a different move order to the position we are about to examine. }
7. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ This is an independent option for Black. They often play  7...Bc5  , when  8.Nf5  O-O  9.Be3  is about the same as the line from the Cozio. The insertion of ...a6 and Ba4 do not change it much. }
8. Qxd4 b5
{ That's a difference to the Cozio. Black gets a tempo on our bishop and has ...Bb7 next. }
9. Bb3 Bb7
{ Black can't play  9...c5??  due to  10.Qd5  or  10.Bxf7+  ,  winning the house. Black needs to play the bishop first, and now ...c5 is a viable idea. The next move is important, as it secures an advantage - other moves don't! }
10. Rd1
{ A compelling engine suggestion! It addresses Black's ...c5 threat with a tactical solution, as  10...c5??  11.Bxf7+!  is crushing. We'll check this in a minute, as the tactics a fun to examine.   OK, Black can't play their main idea, but what else can they do? Our queen has a powerful position in the middle of the board, and Black can't easily develop. Stockfish only sees one reasonable defense, which is tough to see for a human player, the move  10...Qe7!  - it renews the ...c5 threat and covers f7. We'll have a quick look at it, too. }
10... Qe7
{ The comp finds this defense, but I am not sure if a human player will! It looks odd to place the queen on e7, but it seems to be the only move that limits the damage. I have checked others, but they don't help Black.   A.  10...d6  11.c4  is strong. We secure our bishop from ...c5-c4 ideas and want to open the position while being ahead in development.   B.  10...Rc8  11.a4  is a similar idea.  11...c5  still doesn't work due to  12.Bxf7+! }
11. c4
{ A strong move. We stop ...c5-c4 and try to open the position. We keep an advantage now, but Black's best move  11...Qd6!  prevents an immediate disaster. After  12.Qxd6  Bxd6  13.Nc3  bxc4  14.Bxc4  White is undoubtedly better, though. We have a better pawn structure and more active pieces. a good plan to keep in mind is g3, followed by h4-h5. This gains more space and may help to provoke more weaknesses.   Black has no good alternative to  11...Qd6  , by the way. They can't play  11...c5  12.Qe3  Bxe4  13.Nc3  Bc6  14.Qg3  , for instance. Black's king is in terrible shape, and they can't develop. }
