[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A6) Ruy Lopez – Berlin Defense"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Berlin Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ What are Black's best defenses in the Ruy Lopez? If you ask a GM, their answer will be predictable: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  ,  then aim for the Open Spanish/Marshall complex or the Berlin Defense  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  ,  the subject of this chapter.The Berlin became a main defense after the World Championship match between Garry Kasparov and Vladimir Kramnik in 2000 when Kramnik played the Berlin multiple times to defuse Kasparov feared 1.e4 attacking repertoire. In the match, Kasparov repeatedly tried to win the 'Berlin Wall Endgame', as it is now called.After  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  this famous endgame arises. Before the match, it was believed to be better for White, but Kasparov got nowhere and only managed draw after draw. Kramnik didn't lose a single game in the match, won two with White, and dethroned Kasparov. It's not an exaggeration to say that the Berlin Defense was the key to Kramnik becoming the 14th World Champion.Alright, let's fast forward to 2022. What do we play against the Berlin? I suggest  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d3  , keeping the e-pawn. In my mind, this is the best continuation to reach a battle with many pieces on the board. The choice  4.d3  is also in line with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  ,  which follows a similar spirit. Sometimes, we will even transpose from the Berlin chapter to one of these lines, reducing our workload.Finally, a word about the reputation of the Berlin. It is often seen as a boring opening, but I don't think this is fully justified. One reason for this reputation is that the top players use it to make a draw without playing, most notably  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.dxe5  Nxb5  7.a4  Nbd4  8.Nxd4  Nxd4  9.Qxd4  d5  10.exd6  Qxd6  11.Qe4+  Qe6  12.Qd4  Qd6  - and so on.This is indeed boring, but it is a sequence White elects to go for. This is more of an issue for Black than for White - they can't avoid this drawing line, which makes the Berlin a difficult choice for Black if you want to fight for a win against someone who wants a draw.However, White has other options that do not lead to such a direct draw or simplifications. We'll get a strategically interesting position with plenty of chances to play for a win. I don't think White can claim any advantage if Black plays perfectly - we need to be realistic in that regard. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ The starting move of the Berlin. It is no coincidence that Black's most reliable defenses to the Ruy are  3...Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  - both lines feature an early attack on e4. We need to worry about our e-pawn immediately. This turns our ambition to build a full pawn center, with the perfect pawn duo e4 and d4, into a difficult task. My choice against the Berlin is  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d3  ,  covering the important e-pawn.Before we continue, here is a brief overview of the alternatives and how I assess them.   A1.  4.O-O  is the other serious option when  4...Nxe4  leads to a split.  5.d4  leads to the Berlin endgame mentioned in the intro. I am not a fan of playing this endgame. White has no theoretical advantage, and Black plays the Berlin to reach this endgame; it's their home ground.A2. I like  5.Re1  more, and it was a serious candidate that I considered. My main objection: the forced continuation  5...Nd6  6.Nxe5  Be7  7.Bf1  Nxe5  8.Rxe5  O-O  leads to a completely symmetrical pawn structure, which I try to avoid in the second edition of the repertoire. I replaced the French Exchange from the first edition with the Tarrasch, for instance. You can't avoid it completely @@StartBracket@@Petroff@@EndBracket@@, but here we have a good alternative. It is strategically richer than playing for a nibble in a symmetrical structure. }
4. d3
{ We keep our important e-pawn. I want to add that I considered  4.Nc3  , as well - also via the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bb5  move order, of course. However, I think it is too simple for Black to equalise in the Spanish Four Knights. Both  4...Nd4  and  4...Bb4  are fine and don't require much effort for Black to master.   Let's discuss Black's options after  4.d3  -  their choice is rather limited, as our move involves a simple threat: capturing on c6 and winning the e-pawn next. For example, Black can't play  4...Be7?  as  5.Bxc6  dxc6  6.Nxe5  wins the e-pawn. It's not a flank pawn, but the most important pawn on the board!That leaves the following moves:   A.  4...Bc5  is by far the main move. Black develops the bishop and tactically covers the e-pawn. After  5.Bxc6  dxc6  6.Nxe5??  Qd4  White's greed is punished.   B.  4...d6  is the second most popular option. Our coverage of this line will be brief, as it is similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  ,  which we cover in detail. We'll often transpose to said line, as Black frequently inserts ...a6 at a later stage.   C.  4...Ne7  is a crazy-looking move that we need to examine. Black sets a cunning trap, as  5.Nxe5??  c6  6.Bc4  Qa5+  is a sad end of the knight! We'll study a good antidote to the odd 4...Ne7 and claim some advantage. }
