[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A6) Ruy Lopez – Berlin Defense"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Berlin Defense 3...Nf6 4.d3 Ne7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ We keep our important e-pawn. I want to add that I considered  4.Nc3  , as well - also via the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bb5  move order, of course. However, I think it is too simple for Black to equalise in the Spanish Four Knights. Both  4...Nd4  and  4...Bb4  are fine and don't require much effort for Black to master. }
4... Ne7
{ A quirky knight move with two ideas:  - It's a trap! We can't play  5.Nxe5??  c6  6.Bc4  Qa5+  ,  and we lose a piece. This happened in 1000s of online Blitz games, which propelled 4...Ne7 to be the best-scoring move for Black!  - The second idea is playing the knight to g6 and reach a setup with ...c6 and ...d6, keeping the center closed. }
5. Nc3
{ This looks like the most powerful reply, but don't worry about the exact move order too much here. The most important point is to not fall into the trap!   Why  5.Nc3  ,  by the way? We know that Black will likely play ...c6 next, forcing our bishop to move again. It's more attractive for us to retreat the bishop to c4, as we can exert some pressure on f7. Black's development is lagging, which makes f7 more vulnerable.The two moves that come into consideration are mostly  5.Nc3  and  5.O-O  , but there is an argument favouring  5.Nc3  if you wonder about the e7-knight. Black often plays it to g6 soon when we have h2-h4! to start an attack. }
5... c6
{ Black has to start with this move. After  5...Ng6  , we have the strong move  6.d4  ,  when Black can't even play ...d6 to cover the pawn.  6...c6  7.dxe5  is also dreadful for Black. }
6. Bc4
{ Much better than going to a4, as f7 is a target. Black has to be careful now and often fails to be precise.   We'll now check the correct  6...d6  and the common mistake  6...Ng6  , which runs into the planned push of the h-pawn. }
6... Ng6
{ A common mistake. Black is underestimating our reply h4, which proves to be very effective. You also see  6...d5?  , when White wins a pawn. Here are the two relevant lines.   A.  6...d5  7.exd5  cxd5  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Nxe5  Bxb5  10.Nxb5  Qa5+  11.Nc3  d4  12.Nc4  is the more complicated one.   B.  6...d5  7.exd5  Nexd5  8.Nxe5  is even simpler. }
7. h4 h5
{ Black has to stop the h-pawn. Something like  7...d5  8.exd5  cxd5  9.Bb5+  Bd7  10.Bxd7+  Qxd7  11.h5  is just one example of why. }
8. Ng5
{ We get some taste of Fried Liver :-@@EndBracket@@ Now Black has to walk a tightrope to survive the next moves. }
8... d5 9. exd5
{ Now we'll check  9...cxd5?  , as the refutation is fun to study. } 9... cxd5
{ This loses, but it is the more important move to study. Black's only defense is  9...b5!  10.Bb3  cxd5  , because in this case,  11.Nxd5?  does not work. After studying  9...cxd5?  10.Nxd5!  this will become clearer.   The way to go after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2p2nn1/3Pp1Np/2B4P/2NP4/PPP2PP1/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...b5!  10.Bb3  cxd5  is the simple move  11.d4  ,  when we are better without any direct tactics. It can still be a crushing win, for example, after  11...e4  12.Qe2  a6  13.Nxd5!  ,  when our attack is unstoppable. }
10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Qf3 { Black is facing deadly threats on f7 and d5. } 11...
Be6 { The toughest defense.   After  11...Ngf4  12.Bxf4  , it's even simpler. }
12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bb5+
{ A crucial point! Now, you see why Black needs to play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2p2nn1/3Pp1Np/2B4P/2NP4/PPP2PP1/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...b5!  10.Bb3  and only then take d5. We need this check to make the sacrifice work. This trainable is already quite long, but let's have some fun. It's all forced; Black only has one reply the whole time. }
13... Ke7 14. Bg5+ Nf6 15. Qxb7+ Kd6
{ Well, that's what you get for playing tricks on us with 4...Ne7 😏 Now one final strong move, and we're done... }
16. c4
{ I am pretty sure other moves would win, too... but it's the most powerful move. The threat is c4-c5+ now. The sad part for Black is: we are not even down any serious material for this position.   16...Rc8  sure won't save Black either after  17.Bd2!  . }
*

