7. O-O
{ Now Black's e-pawn is attacked and ready to be captured. They have to cover it. We'll now focus on the most popular move  7...Nd7  and the latest trend  7...Bd6  as recommended by Sam Shankland in his Chessable course. }
7... Nd7
{ This is Black's traditional main line after 6...Be6. It looks logical, as Black improves the knight only after developing the bishop to e6. There is a concrete drawback, though. }
8. Nb3
{ A key manoeuvre in the line that sees Black strive for queenside castling. We hit the c5-bishop and got Ng5 on the map simultaneously. It looks like White can keep a small pull now. }
8... Bb6
{ This looks better and is more popular than  8...Be7  , when  9.d4  gives White an initiative. After  9...f6  10.Na5  Rb8  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Qxd8+  Kxd8  13.Rd1+  Ke8  14.Nxe5  fxe5  15.Be3  White has a risk-free endgame advantage. Black's pawn structure deficits are more important than the bishop pair, as it has no targets to attack. }
9. Ng5
{ We remove the e6-bishop and eliminate our opponent's pair of bishops. } 9...
Bxb3
{ This looks a bit better than  9...Nf8  10.Nxe6  Nxe6  11.Qh5  , which is a more active version of the same structure. }
10. axb3 f6 11. Nf3
{ Mission accomplished. We managed to get one of the bishops and discouraged Black's ambition to castle queenside. The resulting position gives us a small pull, using the following plan: we get our knight to c4, then play Kh1 and start playing on the kingside. }
11... Nf8
{ The knight is on the way to e6. It can also go via c5; it makes no difference. }
12. Nd2 Ne6 13. Nc4 Qd7 14. Kh1
{ We are now ready for moves like Qg4, combined with g3 and f4. It's not much, but it still looks like we have more to hope for than Black. }
