7... Bd6
{ This is the latest fashion in this line. It was recommended in the 2021 course on the Berlin, created by GM Sam Shankland. }
8. Nb3
{ I suggest this move, not mentioned in Sam's Chessable course. I guess he didn't consider it an attempt to refute 7...Bd6, which is understandable, to be honest. Sam focused on  8.d4  , which looks more critical as a direct attempt to tackle Black's choice. It is the start of a forced line:  8...Nd7  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.Nxe5  Bxe5  11.f4  Bd4+  12.Kh1  and now  12...f5!  is best. It's one of the rare cases where the engines are slightly wrong in their assessment. The comp gives White a small advantage after a later e4-e5, but White has no way forward. This is Sam's assessment, and I agree.   That's one thing, but more important is a different fact: In the 2022 Candidates Tournament, the position after 7...Bd6 was on the board twice, and both times  8.Nb3  was the choice. The second game may be a 'copycat' issue, but the first game between Fabiano Caruana and Hikaru Nakamura, played in the first round, is a strong indicator that  8.d4  is not the strongest. Caruana prepared  8.Nb3  for this game, expecting Nakamura's Berlin.So does  8.Nb3  lead to an advantage for White? Probably not, but it accomplishes an important goal: Black's intended queenside castling is tougher to realise now, as the knight jump to a5 is a spanner in the works.Let's examine these ideas. }
8... Qe7
{ Nakamura played this move in the mentioned game. It's the one that Black wants to play to prepare queenside castling. The position is closed, so many other moves are possible. In some cases, Black gives up on the queenside castling idea immediately. instead of creating a maze of trainables, I'll show some alternatives and compare them.   A.  8...Nd7  is a worse version of 7...Nd7, as  9.Na5  Rb8  10.Ng5  shows. We get the light-squared bishop and drop our knight back to c4 later.   B.  8...a5  is a radical way to prevent Na5 for the moment, but is also the end of queenside castling ideas. White has an interesting reply in  9.Qe1!?  , when  9...a4  10.Na5  Qc8  was played in an online Blitz game Fedoseev-Nakamura@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@, some weeks after the game in the Candidates against Caruana. So maybe 8...a5 is Hikaru's improvement? After  11.Ng5  @@StartBracket@@Fedoseev played  11.Bd2  @@EndBracket@@  White still looks a bit better, though, intending to push f4.   C.  8...b6  blunts our knight but weakens the queenside. I suggest  9.Bg5  , which leads to a similar situation as after @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2pbbn2/4p3/4P3/1N1P1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  9.Na5  Rb8  10.Bg5  , played in the Caruana-Nakamura game. }
9. Na5
{ Here we go! Now Black needs to decide if they want to dare castling queenside. Nakamura played  9...Rb8  ,  which is an understandable choice, as he certainly feared running into a preparation after the more committal queenside castling. When your opponent blitzes out all the moves up to 9. Na5, you are concerned! }
9... O-O-O
{ That was the idea of Black's setup, but it's risky. White has more than one dangerous attacking idea now. }
10. a3
{ I suggest this one, but  10.c3  or  10.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@ideas are Rb1,b4 and a4@@EndBracket@@ look interesting, too.   After  10.a3  , it's difficult to say what's best for Black. I found one GM game that featured  10...c5?  which is awful due to  11.b4!  ,  which somehow White failed to play. We want to open the queenside, after all. The comp suggests a plan involving ...Bg4 and a later ...Rhg8/...g5 idea. I want to look at this idea, as it can lead to complications on the next move. }
10... Bg4 11. b4
{ Now, Black has the option to strike with a tactic that I want to explore. }
11... Nxe4
{ This could be a shocker, so it's worth checking. The comp prefers  11...Rhg8  ,  preparing a later pawn push to ...g5. A good way to counter such an advance is routing the knight to e3, looking at the weak f5-square. A line to illustrate this idea is  11...Rhg8  12.Re1  g5  13.Nc4  Nd7  14.Ne3  Be6  15.Nd2  ,  when Nf1-g3-f5 is the dream goal. }
12. dxe4 Bxb4 { That's the idea. Now our queen and knight are attacked. } 13.
Nxc6
{ This is the move to remember. We play this desperado move and destroy Black's structure in the process. }
13... bxc6 14. Qe2
{ Black has won a pawn, but at a high price: Their king position is a permanent problem now. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A6) Ruy Lopez – Berlin Defense"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – Berlin Defense 3...Nf6 4.d3 Bc5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ We keep our important e-pawn. I want to add that I considered  4.Nc3  , as well - also via the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bb5  move order, of course. However, I think it is too simple for Black to equalise in the Spanish Four Knights. Both  4...Nd4  and  4...Bb4  are fine and don't require much effort for Black to master. }
4... Bc5
{ Black goes for the most active defense and develops the bishop to a natural square. It's important to understand the difference to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  , when we can go for  4.c3  and want to play d2-d4 next. Black has already provoked the 'small' d-pawn move, taking a quick central expansion out of the equation.   What to play against  4...Bc5?  I started my investigation with the move  5.c3  , a typical move in the Ruy. White wants to still play for the full pawn center at a later stage. We employ this strategy in several lines, for instance, after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.c3  in the current chapter.   I would have liked to suggest @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  ,  as it would fit well to these lines from a conceptual point of view. There are concrete problems, though. I found that Black can get equal chances with more than one defense, and mastering the move orders looked difficult to me.In the end, I have discarded  5.c3  and suggest an option we rarely play in the Ruy: exchanging our bishop for the knight. I will discuss the ideas once the trade is on the board; hang on. }
5. Bxc6
{ Black has to take with the d-pawn now, enabling the defense of the e-pawn. After  5...dxc6  , we can't play  6.Nxe5??  due to  6...Qd4  , when Black wins.   If somehow Black decides to try  5...bxc6?  we can take the e-pawn unpunished. }
5... dxc6
{ Let's discuss this position. Why did we capture the knight and give up our bishop pair? Let's make a list of key points to consider.   The bishop pair is an asset for Black, but the pawn structure is not ideally suited for bishops. They would like open, long diagonals, and Black has difficulty creating them here.  We need to consider the pawn structure. The doubled pawn is a key factor. It is not a weakness we could attack, but it is still a strategic handicap for Black. The problem is that the doubled pawn reduces Black's options for pawn breaks. Currently, there are no open files. To a large extent, closed positions are about both sides trying to open them under favourable circumstances. Due to the doubled pawn, Black's options to change the pawn structure have been reduced. Black can't gain much by advancing pawns on the queenside. The pawn push ...c6-c5-c4 is tough to realise.Black could try to open the position by playing ...f5, attacking our central pawn. This option is also difficult to engineer. Black has no d-pawn, which means that ...f5 would lead the e-pawn unprotected.Let's compare these points with our position. We are much better equipped to alter the pawn structure. We have two basic ideas to change the pawn structure: breaking in the center with d4 and attacking e5 with f4. Our attempts to play f4 are more promising than Black's ...f5 possibilities because we still have a d-pawn to protect e4. It is easier to prepare and involves less risk.  It is important to consider castling options. It's very relevant, as the closed center makes it easier to start flank operations. If Black castles to the kingside, we might launch an attack based on g2-g4, for instance.  What about piece placement? We have discussed pawns; how do the pieces relate to the structure? Black's pieces are not ideally placed at the moment. The knight mostly looks at a well-protected pawn, while the bishop is developed but not doing much, either. Quite often, Black quickly starts a knight tour to improve this piece. Moving the knight has an additional benefit: the option of ...f6, which would reliably cover e5.   Black's sub-optimal piece placement is an important factor. It is the crucial difference to the Ruy Exchange Variation. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  ,  the same pawn structure arises, but Black would never voluntarily play their pieces to f6 or c5. It is much more common for Black to go for an early ...f6 and delay the development of the knight. }
6. Nbd2
{ White has two major options here. My recommendation and  6.O-O  , which I dislike for a simple reason. Black can play  6...Bg4  and pin our knight. It looks like the only way to answer this move is  7.h3  Bh5  8.g4  , when Black can play  8...Nxg4!  9.hxg4  Bxg4  and destroy our pawn cover. This line looks theoretically sound for Black, and there is no way I would want to play this position unless it is REALLY good for me and I see a way to secure my king.   Well, we have a good alternative to castling. By playing  6.Nbd2  ,  we defuse ...Bg4, as our king is not yet committed to the kingside. Once you scratch  6.O-O  off your list,  6.Nbd2  quickly emerges as the main alternative to examine. The knight has no bright future on c3, so developing it to d2 makes much more sense. We often place it on c4 to increase the pressure on e5 or transfer it to the kingside via f1. In some cases, playing Nb3 is motivated by concrete lines, gaining a tempo on the c5-bishop.Black has a fundamental choice now that heavily influences the course of the game. We currently still don't threaten e5, so Black has some flexibility. The main choice is about castling.Black can go for kingside castling:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  commits the king right away.   B.  6...Nd7  7.Nc4  O-O  is a different path to kingside castling.Black can prepare queenside castling:   C.  6...Be6  is probably the best move to get closer to O-O-O.   D.  6...Bg4  looks like a less reliable option with the same intention. }
6... Be6
{ If Black wants to castle queenside, this is the way to go. Against other moves, we usually play the knight to c4, but here this move is prevented. It's best to castle first. }
7. O-O
{ Now Black's e-pawn is attacked and ready to be captured. They have to cover it. We'll now focus on the most popular move  7...Nd7  and the latest trend  7...Bd6  as recommended by Sam Shankland in his Chessable course. }
7... Bd6
{ This is the latest fashion in this line. It was recommended in the 2021 course on the Berlin, created by GM Sam Shankland. }
8. Nb3
{ I suggest this move, not mentioned in Sam's Chessable course. I guess he didn't consider it an attempt to refute 7...Bd6, which is understandable, to be honest. Sam focused on  8.d4  , which looks more critical as a direct attempt to tackle Black's choice. It is the start of a forced line:  8...Nd7  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.Nxe5  Bxe5  11.f4  Bd4+  12.Kh1  and now  12...f5!  is best. It's one of the rare cases where the engines are slightly wrong in their assessment. The comp gives White a small advantage after a later e4-e5, but White has no way forward. This is Sam's assessment, and I agree.   That's one thing, but more important is a different fact: In the 2022 Candidates Tournament, the position after 7...Bd6 was on the board twice, and both times  8.Nb3  was the choice. The second game may be a 'copycat' issue, but the first game between Fabiano Caruana and Hikaru Nakamura, played in the first round, is a strong indicator that  8.d4  is not the strongest. Caruana prepared  8.Nb3  for this game, expecting Nakamura's Berlin.So does  8.Nb3  lead to an advantage for White? Probably not, but it accomplishes an important goal: Black's intended queenside castling is tougher to realise now, as the knight jump to a5 is a spanner in the works.Let's examine these ideas. }
8... Qe7
{ Nakamura played this move in the mentioned game. It's the one that Black wants to play to prepare queenside castling. The position is closed, so many other moves are possible. In some cases, Black gives up on the queenside castling idea immediately. instead of creating a maze of trainables, I'll show some alternatives and compare them.   A.  8...Nd7  is a worse version of 7...Nd7, as  9.Na5  Rb8  10.Ng5  shows. We get the light-squared bishop and drop our knight back to c4 later.   B.  8...a5  is a radical way to prevent Na5 for the moment, but is also the end of queenside castling ideas. White has an interesting reply in  9.Qe1!?  , when  9...a4  10.Na5  Qc8  was played in an online Blitz game Fedoseev-Nakamura@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@, some weeks after the game in the Candidates against Caruana. So maybe 8...a5 is Hikaru's improvement? After  11.Ng5  @@StartBracket@@Fedoseev played  11.Bd2  @@EndBracket@@  White still looks a bit better, though, intending to push f4.   C.  8...b6  blunts our knight but weakens the queenside. I suggest  9.Bg5  , which leads to a similar situation as after @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2pbbn2/4p3/4P3/1N1P1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  9.Na5  Rb8  10.Bg5  , played in the Caruana-Nakamura game. }
9. Na5
{ Here we go! Now Black needs to decide if they want to dare castling queenside. Nakamura played  9...Rb8  ,  which is an understandable choice, as he certainly feared running into a preparation after the more committal queenside castling. When your opponent blitzes out all the moves up to 9. Na5, you are concerned! }
9... Rb8 10. Bg5
{ White goes for an annoying pin. This is not the only good continuation, though. I also like  10.b3  ,  which prepares a later jump back to c4. This position will resemble the lines that usually start with 6...O-O, when our knight usually sits on c4.Caruana's move  10.Bg5  leads to a different situation, as Black has difficulty allowing the pin for a long time and feels tempted to break it with ...h6 and ...g5, as happened in the game. }
10... h6 11. Bh4 g5
{ Black can't live with the pin forever, leading to a permanent problem: king safety. }
12. Bg3 Nd7 13. d4
{ We want to open the position after Black has pushed the kingside pawns. White has the simpler job in this complicated position, as our king is much safe in the long run.   Caruana went on to win a good game after  13...f6  14.Qd3  h5  15.dxe5  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  fxe5  17.Nc4  Rd8  18.Nxd6+  cxd6  19.Qe3  g4  20.Nd2  a6  21.b3  , when  21...O-O  22.f3  demonstrated the core problem: Black's king safety! }
*

