{ White has two major options here. My recommendation and  6.O-O  , which I dislike for a simple reason. Black can play  6...Bg4  and pin our knight. It looks like the only way to answer this move is  7.h3  Bh5  8.g4  , when Black can play  8...Nxg4!  9.hxg4  Bxg4  and destroy our pawn cover. This line looks theoretically sound for Black, and there is no way I would want to play this position unless it is REALLY good for me and I see a way to secure my king.   Well, we have a good alternative to castling. By playing  6.Nbd2  ,  we defuse ...Bg4, as our king is not yet committed to the kingside. Once you scratch  6.O-O  off your list,  6.Nbd2  quickly emerges as the main alternative to examine. The knight has no bright future on c3, so developing it to d2 makes much more sense. We often place it on c4 to increase the pressure on e5 or transfer it to the kingside via f1. In some cases, playing Nb3 is motivated by concrete lines, gaining a tempo on the c5-bishop.Black has a fundamental choice now that heavily influences the course of the game. We currently still don't threaten e5, so Black has some flexibility. The main choice is about castling.Black can go for kingside castling:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  commits the king right away.   B.  6...Nd7  7.Nc4  O-O  is a different path to kingside castling.Black can prepare queenside castling:   C.  6...Be6  is probably the best move to get closer to O-O-O.   D.  6...Bg4  looks like a less reliable option with the same intention. }
6... O-O
{ Black commits to kingside castling. This concept is the most popular, but White's job is easier than against other concepts. We know the address of Black's king, which helps. We want to play on the kingside against Black's king; a key question is where to castle. I think kingside castling is a safer and better option. Let's see how it continues. }
7. Nc4
{ A good move to start with. We attack e5 a second time and activate the knight.   I already mentioned that we want to castle kingside. Playing  7.O-O  first is not a mistake and will likely transpose. I prefer  7.Nc4  , because we start with this move in various other lines @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qe7  7.Nc4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd7  7.Nc4  @@EndBracket@@.Black has to cover the e-pawn now. The most popular move is  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/2N1P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nd7  .  It looks odd to see Black blocking their c8-bishop, but the knight is not well-placed on f6, and the c8-bishop has no great development perspective.An alternative for Black is  7...Re8  - it will often transpose to 7...Nd7, if Black plays the knight soon. We'll have a look at both options. }
7... Re8
{ This move has little independent significance, as Black's best move after our natural reply will transpose to the more popular  7...Nd7  move order. }
8. O-O
{ We castle and remove all the tricks on f2 - Black's e-pawn is attacked now and needs protection. The best move for Black is  8...Nd7  now, transposing to the line 7...Nd7 8.O-O Re8, the main continuation. }
8... Bg4
{ A dubious alternative to  8...Nd7  , as the pin accomplishes nothing. } 9. h3
{ Black has the choice of two bad scenarios now: giving up the bishop pair or having the bishop sidelined on the kingside. }
9... Bh5
{ After  9...Bxf3  10.Qxf3  we have a comfortable advantage. Black has given up the bishop pair, and we have the simple but effective idea to prepare f2-f4 to open the position. Due to the rigid pawn structure, Black has no counterplay.   With  9...Bh5  , Black maintains the pin. Can we play  10.g4  now? It's always tough to evaluate if  10...Nxg4  11.hxg4  Bxg4  is scary or not. It looks like Black is fine in this particular case. We don't need to look at the details, as we have much better options. }
10. Be3
{ I am going with this move, as played by Magnus Carlsen in a Blitz game vs Sergey Karjakin. Stockfish points out the less obvious move  10.Kh1  is strong, too. The idea is to play g4 next, as White has gained the option Rg1 after the possible sacrifice on g4. This looks strong but is quite complicated to remember. The simpler bishop move gives White an advantage, too. }
10... Bxe3
{ Karjakin played  10...Bd6?  when  11.Bg5  was much better for White. The pin is extremely annoying, and White is ready for g4 next. }
11. Nxe3
{ The idea of 10.Be3 was to reach this position. Our knight is well-placed on e3, as it supports the move g4 and can jump to f5 later. }
11... Nd7 { Black finally wants to get the knight to a better square. } 12. g4
{ Now it's safe to expand and push Black's bishop to a passive square. } 12...
Bg6 13. Kh2
{ A tough call here, as White is better after some other moves, too.  13.Qe1  is interesting, going for Qc3 next;  or  13.h4  ,  trying for h4-h5 and Nh4, if possible.The move  13.Kh2  is useful for multiple plans. Ng1-e2, followed by f2-f4, is one example. The plan based on ...Bg4 is dubious for Black, as we'll manage g2-g4 and sideline Black's bishop. }
