[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A7) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This chapter covers the sidelines of the Anderssen Variation. After  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  Black has multiple options.   A.  5...b5  6.Bb3  Be7  - covered in a dedicated chapter.   B.  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  - covered in a dedicated chapter.Other lines are covered in the current chapter. What do we need to check?   C.  5...b5  6.Bb3  and now other moves than  6...Be7  or  6...Bc5  .  Often they eventually lead to worse versions of A or B, though.   D.  5...d6  leads to a slower, strategic battle and is a well-respected choice for Black.   E.  5...Bc5  is possible but is met with a simple solution and does not need much coverage here.You'll see that D will be the main portion of this chapter. Let's get to work. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3
{ The start of the Anderssen Variation. We cover the e-pawn, which limits Black's option. They need to be aware that now we threaten to capture on e5 and snatch the e-pawn. Black can't play  5...Be7?  as  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  wins the most important pawn on the board. It may sound silly, but I found thousands@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ of online games that featured this pawn blunder - and White often didn't even take the pawn!What are the serious options for Black?   A.  5...b5  is the most popular move by a mile. Black kicks our bishop to b3 and then continues development. In the current chapter, we'll examine possible sidelines, as  6.Bb3  Be7  and  6...Bc5  is covered in separate chapters.   B.  5...Bc5  is a good move for Black but has little independent value in our repertoire. I suggest  6.Bxc6  ,  which cuts our workload tremendously. We'll reach a position that is almost identical to the Berlin line  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  ,  but with an irrelevant extra move for Black. I'll talk about the details more in the notes to the line.   C.  5...d6  covers the e-pawn and leads to a slower, strategic game. We will discuss piece placement and ideas in these lines more than actual move sequences.Options A and B don't require much study, as you will see. The most important part of this chapter is C, when we reach the slow, closed Ruy. This type of position can also arise from  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  d6  ,  a line that is also part of our repertoire. Knowing and understanding these lines' typical manoeuvres and ideas will help immensely, as there are many similar variations in the Ruy and even the Italian game. If you want to expand your repertoire at a later stage, you have a solid foundation after studying these lines. }
