[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3
{ The start of the Anderssen Variation. We cover the e-pawn, which limits Black's option. They need to be aware that now we threaten to capture on e5 and snatch the e-pawn. Black can't play  5...Be7?  as  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  wins the most important pawn on the board. It may sound silly, but I found thousands@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ of online games that featured this pawn blunder - and White often didn't even take the pawn! }
5... Bc5
{ Black develops their bishop to the most active square, a natural choice. Compared to  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  ,  they avoid the early ...b5, which changes the situation considerably.   The more enlightening comparison is a different one. In the Berlin, we reach @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  ,  which is very close. In the Berlin, my recommendation is  5.Bxc6  ,  which changes the pawn structure fundamentally. In the chapter on the Berlin, I explain this decision in more detail, as it is not trivial. One key problem is that the slower setups with c3 look harmless in the Berlin.The same applies to the position we have on the board currently. After  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/2b1p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  d6  or  6.c3  O-O  ,  Black looks in good shape.Long story short: I suggest treating this position like the Berlin: by trading on c6. }
6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nbd2
{ We play the same setup in the Berlin: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  dxc6  6.Nbd2  is the line I recommend. Black has the additional move ...a6 here, which is not an important difference. I would treat the position as the same, so we don't need to look at two different versions of all the possible ways Black can play this position. }
