[Round "?"]
[White "A7) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3
{ The start of the Anderssen Variation. We cover the e-pawn, which limits Black's option. They need to be aware that now we threaten to capture on e5 and snatch the e-pawn. Black can't play  5...Be7?  as  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  wins the most important pawn on the board. It may sound silly, but I found thousands@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ of online games that featured this pawn blunder - and White often didn't even take the pawn! }
5... b5 { If you get the next move wrong, we need to talk. } 6. Bb3
{ Now Black's best moves are  6...Be7  and  6...Bc5  ,  which are examined in dedicated chapters. Black has some alternatives, but they usually transpose to worse versions of the above lines. Black can hardly play without developing the kingside soon, and e7 or c5 are the only good squares for the bishop.   We will check  6...d6  now, as it can have some independent value. I also found some games with  6...h6  , and  6...Bb7  , but we don't need a detailed study. The pawn move  6...h6  is slow and weakens the kingside, while the queenside fianchetto is often considered strategically risky. The bishop stares at a well-covered pawn e4 and neglects the cover of f5.A good way to deal with these moves is  7.a4  ,  playing in the style of the 6...Be7 7.a4 lines. But there is nothing wrong with  7.O-O  and maybe playing a4 later. Both moves, ...h6 and ...Bb7, make our knight tour to g3 more powerful, as they neglect control of f5 and weaken the kingside. }
6... d6 { This is the most interesting move of the sidelines to study. } 7. a4
{ A standard idea: attacking Black's queenside structure as soon as possible. Against the main line 6...Be7, we play the same concept. }
7... Bg4
{ Black could play  7...Bb7  , when  8.O-O  Be7  9.Nc3  is a transposition to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  7.a4  Bb7  8.O-O  d6  9.Nc3  variation.  A similar case is  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq a3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Rb8  8.axb5  axb5  9.Nc3  ,  which transposes to the variation  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  6.Bb3  Be7  7.a4  Rb8  8.axb5  axb5  9.Nc3  .Here we'll take a brief look at 7...Bg4, as it has independent value and serves as a good example of how to handle early ...Bg4 ideas. It's a risky concept that can quickly backfire. The first step is to notice that Black is threatening Nd4. We should stop this idea. }
8. c3 { No ...Nd4, please! } 8... Be7 9. h3
{ There is nothing wrong with  9.O-O  and  9.Nbd2  ,  either. A good way to play against ...Bg4 is the knight tour to g3, as we'll see in the main parts of the chapter. The move  9.h3  is stronger, though. Black has to realize that the only good move is the sad  9...Bd7  ,  but that is not what Black intended to do when playing the bishop to g4. }
9... Bh5
{ This move flat-out loses the game! As mentioned, Black should play  9...Bd7  ,  when we can be happy about the opening result, too. It looks like a nice version of the main lines of the current chapter. Well, this is preferable for Black, compared to losing on the spot. After  9...Bh5  , how do we win? }
10. g4 { It's all forced from here. } 10... Bg6 11. g5
{ And we win after the knight moves to h5 or to d5, with the following idea... }
11... Nd7 12. Bd5
{ Oops! We are winning the house after  12...Na7  13.Bxa8  or @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/2pnbppp/p1np2b1/1p1Bp1P1/P3P3/2PP1N1P/1P3P2/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Ndb8  13.axb5  . Quite a sudden knockout! }
