10... b5
{ This is Black's most direct idea. They push our bishop back and want to break in the center next. }
11. Bc2
{ Back to c2, as usual. This position may also arise via other move orders. Black could have started with an earlier ...b5 and then went for ...Bg4, leading to the same position. }
11... d5
{ Black goes for the central break. It is the most popular move for a good reason, as the alternatives look too bleak. If Black doesn't do anything active, we manage our goals on the kingside. Let's say  11...Qd7  12.Nf1  Rad8  13.Ng3  Bg6  14.Nh4  Rfe8  15.Nhf5  ,  with Qf3, Bg5, maybe h4-h5 next. Black needs to get something going before we complete such a setup.   After  11...d5  ,  we have some choice. As it often happens in those ...Bg4 lines, we need to decide if we want to play with g4 or not. I don't want to commit and suggest a universally good move first. }
12. Qe2
{ We want to play Nf1 soon and like to prevent  12.Nf1  dxe4  13.dxe4  Qxd1  , when Black manages to defend by trading material.   Now after @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/2p1bppp/p1n2n2/1p1pp2b/4P3/2PP1N1P/PPBNQPP1/R1B1R1K1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qe2  we need to examine  12...d4  , which leads to the most interesting position. It's good for White, but at least it's complicated. It isn't good for Black to play  12...dxe4  13.dxe4  , as we'll have easy ideas against Black's queenside. The plan  a4  is even more effective than usual, as Black's bishop is offside and has no help in the defense. }
12... d4 13. g4
{ This is the way to go and crucial to remember. I was surprised to see that  13.Nf1  Bxf3  14.Qxf3  a5!  15.Ng3  a4  is quite OK for Black. Our c2-bishop remains passive, and there is no clear way forward. }
13... Bg6
{ Black has to retreat, as  13...Nxg4  14.hxg4  Bxg4  15.Qf1  is a pointless sacrifice. }
14. Nf1 { We are on the way to g3 and f5. } 14... Nd7
{ This looks best. Black has ...Nc5-e6 in mind. } 15. Ng3 Nc5 16. Nf5
{ This position is difficult for Black to play. We have a powerful knight, and taking it would open the g-file for an attack.   Interestingly, the engine now suggests  16...a5  for Black, when  17.Nxe7+!  is best for concrete reasons. After  17...Qxe7  18.cxd4  Nxd4  19.Nxd4  exd4  20.f4  , the pawn structure has changed, giving us an impressive pawn roller. }
