{ Black covers their e-pawn but forfeits the option to play ...Bc5. It looks more natural to play  5...Bc5  or  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  ,  but there are reasons why Black might want to play differently.   - They possibly intended to play a line like  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  d6  or  6...b5  7.Bb3  d6  ,  and want to reach a familiar setup.   - They might want to develop with ...g6, an interesting concept.The move 5...d6 also involves a threat! We need to get the move order correct now. }
6. c3
{ It's crucial to start with  6.c3  and avoid @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O?  b5  7.Bb3  Na5!  ,  when our Ruy bishop will be traded off. Losing the bishop pair is one bad aspect, but it also hurts that Black manages to get rid of their c6-knight so easily. The slightly misplaced knight on c6 is a key strategic issue in these slow Ruy structures. Why misplaced? We have a pawn on c3, which limits the scope of the knight. It mostly looks at protected squares, like b4 and d4.An additional issue for Black is the blocked c-pawn. We can favourably use our c-pawn to support a later d3-d4, building a well-supported pawn center. This is not as easy for Black to accomplish.Before we look at Black's options on move six, a word about our plans and setup. We have a fairly straightforward concept that works well, more or less, regardless of Black's choice: Castle kingside,Play Re1,Start the knight tour Nb1-d2-f1-g3,If Black plays ...b5, we retreat the bishop to c2.  This is the 'default setup' that we play. If Black plays an unexpected move and you see no clear refutation, resort to the described setup. This configuration is harmonious and provides excellent support to play d3-d4 and finally build the full pawn center.   Black has a fundamental choice now: developing the bishop to e7 or going for a kingside fianchetto. In most cases, they play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  or  6...g6  now and commit to one of the setups. These two moves will be our main paths to investigate. Are there other sensible moves? Yes, but they are either not good or have low independent value. Here's a list of the moves that we will check.   A.  6...Be7  is the main move. Black prepares kingside castling as quickly as possible.   B.  6...g6  goes for the kingside fianchetto.   C.  6...b5  is a rare choice at this point. If Black wants to play ...b5, it makes much more sense to do it one move earlier when our bishop had no other option than retreating to b3. Now we have two squares and go for  7.Bc2  ,  which is a small gain for us. I'll talk more about the difference between b3 and c2 in the notes to this move.   Please note that  6...b5  has little independent value, as Black has to continue with the kingside development soon, transposing to option A or B. I will still cover  6...b5  as a short trainable to emphasize the point of retreating to c2.Black can also develop their bishop to g4 or d7, but these moves have no significant independent value.   D.  6...Bd7  is a non-commital move. Black breaks the pin and delays the decision about the kingside formation. A transposition to A or B is likely, as they have to get castled soon. We play with our standard setup @@StartBracket@@O-O, Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ and will transpose to A or B.   E.  6...Bg4  pins our knight, but it is a generally dubious idea. Black's bishop often needs to trade on f3 or gets sidelined on the kingside. Black usually combines ...Bg4 with ...Be7, making the early ...Bg4 an option with limited independent value. After  7.O-O  Be7  ,  we'll transpose to line A quickly. }
6... Be7
{ Black chooses to castle kingside as fast as possible. This setup is often the choice of players who intend to play a more traditional line of the Ruy, like @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  b5  7.Bb3  d6  , for instance. }
7. O-O { We continue with our standard move. } 7... O-O
{ Now Black almost always castles, but they could play  7...b5  8.Bc2  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4  8.Re1  first. These options have no independent value, though. Black can hardly play without castling, so they usually start with this move. We will examine Black's various plans on the next move. }
8. Re1
{ Here we go, the next move to get closer to our desired setup. Black has a ton of possible moves now. As both sides manoeuvre inside their camp, there are many options. I will focus on the two most popular moves and give you some brief info on others. We are always fine and preserve at least a small advantage by completing the knight tour in order to prepare d3-d4. In some cases, playing d3-d4 earlier is also possible.   A.  8...b5  is the main move for Black. After  9.Bc2  , we get a further split.   B.  8...Bg4  is a dubious pin, but frequently seen, particularly below master-level. I will focus on these two moves. Here are some other possibilities for Black. They often eventually will feature ...b5 or ...Bg4 to transpose to positions from A and B.   C.  8...Re8  is a flexible move. Black often wants to play ...Re8 and ...Bf8, which puts some indirect pressure on e4 to make d3-d4 harder to achieve for White. We play  9.Nbd2  Bf8  10.Nf1  ,  when Black usually plays ...b5 soon to get to positions from A.   D.  8...h6  can be a similar story as C, if Black plays ...b5 soon. An independent idea is  9.Nbd2  Nh7?!  , but  10.d4  looks good for White. Black can't get ...f5 to work under good circumstances.A general remark: the move orders can be irritating at first. If you keep in mind that we play the knight tour to g3 to ultimately prepare d3-d4, White's position will always be good. No one tries to memorize all the different permutations of ...h6, ...Re8, ...b5 and so on. There is no need to do that, which is a compelling aspect. We'll get a game full of pieces and possibilities without having to memorize a maze of irritating theory. }
8... b5 { Black's main move, sending our bishop to c2. } 9. Bc2
{ OK, job done. Now it's Black's turn to decide how to develop.   A.  9...Bg4  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nbd2  leads to lines that we've examined in the line 8...Bg4.   B.  9...d5  is the immediate central pawn push. We keep the tension with  10.Nbd2  ,  but we may capture d5 later.   C. Black frequently goes for the famous Breyer manoeuvre ...Nb8-d7. They can start immediately @@StartBracket@@  9...Nb8  @@EndBracket@@ or a bit later. I'll examine it via  9...Bb7  ,  which may also be connected to other ideas. One is ...Re8, followed by ...Bf8. I'll check that via  9...Bb7  ,  too.As usual: it doesn't sound obvious at first, but our job is easy and more or less the same in most cases: get the knight to g3 and play d4. }
9... d5
{ Black immediately strikes in the center. It feels like an active move, but it creates multiple weaknesses. The e-pawn can be vulnerable, and c5 can be a later problem. We can't benefit from taking d5, so it's best to continue developing. }
10. Nbd2
{ Simple and good. We develop our knight and strengthen the idea exd5, as now we would be able to respond to ...Qxd5 with moves like c4 or Ne4. }
10... dxe4
{ Black's main move, as they are worried about the capture. The alternatives are:   A.  10...Bg4  11.h3  Bh5  12.Qe2  transposes to 8...Bg4 lines.   B.  10...d4  looks slightly better for White after  11.cxd4  exd4  12.Nb3  Bg4  13.h3  Bh5  14.Bd2  - an interesting and unconventional position. A fascinating idea is playing Qe2/Bd1 and Qf1 next, which unpins and clears the c-file for a rook. Black has a backward c-pawn, after all. }
11. dxe4
{ This position is slightly better for White. It's mostly symmetrical, but we have some plusses. It's the usual story: Black's c6-knight is misplaced, and ...b5 serves as a target. We want to play a setup with a4 and Qe2, putting pressure on the b-pawn. }
11... Be6 { Black usually develops in this fashion. Our plan is Qe2 and a4. }
12. Qe2 { Let's put our planned moves on the board. } 12... Qc8 13. a4
{ We have a slight but comfortable advantage in this position. Black always has to worry about the weakened queenside. If Black plays ....b4, we'll get c4 for our pieces. }
*

