8... b5 { Black's main move, sending our bishop to c2. } 9. Bc2
{ OK, job done. Now it's Black's turn to decide how to develop.   A.  9...Bg4  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nbd2  leads to lines that we've examined in the line 8...Bg4.   B.  9...d5  is the immediate central pawn push. We keep the tension with  10.Nbd2  ,  but we may capture d5 later.   C. Black frequently goes for the famous Breyer manoeuvre ...Nb8-d7. They can start immediately @@StartBracket@@  9...Nb8  @@EndBracket@@ or a bit later. I'll examine it via  9...Bb7  ,  which may also be connected to other ideas. One is ...Re8, followed by ...Bf8. I'll check that via  9...Bb7  ,  too.As usual: it doesn't sound obvious at first, but our job is easy and more or less the same in most cases: get the knight to g3 and play d4. }
9... Bb7 { Black completes the extended Fianchetto. } 10. Nbd2
{ Our normal move, starting the knight tour. We need to prepare d3-d4 thoroughly. After  10.d4?!  exd4  11.cxd4  Nb4  Black gets good activity for their pieces.   After  10.Nbd2  we'll check two options for Black: the Breyer idea  10...Nb8  , and the setup  10...Re8  ,  followed by ...Bf8. }
10... Re8
{ Another common regrouping is ...Re8 and ...Bf8. This is often combined with the Breyer, but we'll check one different idea. This is more about getting a feel for the concepts, as the move orders are too many to translate into trainable lines. }
11. Nf1
{ A good alternative is  11.a4  ,  which is a similar concept to one we use against the 6...g6 setups. However, completing the knight tour is easier to remember. }
11... Bf8 12. Ng3
{ Now  12...Nb8  13.d4  Nbd7  14.a4  is a common way to return to the Breyer formation. We cover it via 10...Nb8, but reach the same position. }
12... g6 { Going for the fianchetto is Black's main idea now. } 13. d4
{ There is no need for further preparation. We can occupy the center now. }
13... Bg7
{ And Black has completed the fianchetto. Now, depending on what you have studied in this chapter already, you might wonder if this ...Be7, then ...Bf8, and then ...Bg7 is not just a loss of two tempi, compared to 6...g6 formations? You are exactly right! As the position is quite closed, this is not fatal, though. You also have to consider that in the 6...g6 line, I recommend a different setup against ...b5/...Bb7, involving a4, b4 and Nb3.   Here our knight is already on g3, and we have accomplished the pawn move to d4. We have built the center we wanted, but we need to watch out for Black attacking it. We need to be aware of one idea: Black may take on d4, followed by ...Nb4. This would be particularly effective after  14.Be3?  exd4  15.cxd4  Nb4  ,  when e4 is attacked; they also threaten to capture our valuable bishop.   If we want to develop our bishop,  14.Bd2  is a better option. This does not look like an ideal square, though. Another common idea in the Ruy is  14.a4  , but  14...exd4  15.cxd4  Nb4  looks OK for Black again. The move a4 is more effective when our pawn is still on d3, or Black has moved their knight away from c6 @@StartBracket@@the Breyer idea@@EndBracket@@.My suggestion: play the move the strongest players play and the engine recommends. A good strengthening move is best here. }
14. h3
{ I like this universally useful move. We improved our position a bit and ask Black for some commitment. Let's look at two possible ideas.   A.  14...exd4  15.cxd4  Nb4  16.Bb1  c5  17.d5  looks good for White. Black's knight has no way back, so  17...a5  18.a3  Na6  19.a4  is more or less forced. White has a nice advantage on the queenside and in the center.   B. Black can try to play a small, improving move. One example is  14...h6  when I like  15.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@already a good option on move 14@@EndBracket@@, when our bishop covers b4. This is relevant, as  15...Qd7  16.a4  demonstrates. With b4 covered, Black's idea of taking on d4 followed by ...Nb4 is prevented. If Black continues to wait @@StartBracket@@what else?@@EndBracket@@ with something like  16...Kh7  , we play  17.Bd3  ,  attacking b5. We'll make excellent progress with Qc2 and maybe b2-b4 soon after. }
*

