{ Now Black almost always castles, but they could play  7...b5  8.Bc2  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4  8.Re1  first. These options have no independent value, though. Black can hardly play without castling, so they usually start with this move. We will examine Black's various plans on the next move. }
8. Re1
{ Here we go, the next move to get closer to our desired setup. Black has a ton of possible moves now. As both sides manoeuvre inside their camp, there are many options. I will focus on the two most popular moves and give you some brief info on others. We are always fine and preserve at least a small advantage by completing the knight tour in order to prepare d3-d4. In some cases, playing d3-d4 earlier is also possible.   A.  8...b5  is the main move for Black. After  9.Bc2  , we get a further split.   B.  8...Bg4  is a dubious pin, but frequently seen, particularly below master-level. I will focus on these two moves. Here are some other possibilities for Black. They often eventually will feature ...b5 or ...Bg4 to transpose to positions from A and B.   C.  8...Re8  is a flexible move. Black often wants to play ...Re8 and ...Bf8, which puts some indirect pressure on e4 to make d3-d4 harder to achieve for White. We play  9.Nbd2  Bf8  10.Nf1  ,  when Black usually plays ...b5 soon to get to positions from A.   D.  8...h6  can be a similar story as C, if Black plays ...b5 soon. An independent idea is  9.Nbd2  Nh7?!  , but  10.d4  looks good for White. Black can't get ...f5 to work under good circumstances.A general remark: the move orders can be irritating at first. If you keep in mind that we play the knight tour to g3 to ultimately prepare d3-d4, White's position will always be good. No one tries to memorize all the different permutations of ...h6, ...Re8, ...b5 and so on. There is no need to do that, which is a compelling aspect. We'll get a game full of pieces and possibilities without having to memorize a maze of irritating theory. }
8... b5 { Black's main move, sending our bishop to c2. } 9. Bc2
{ OK, job done. Now it's Black's turn to decide how to develop.   A.  9...Bg4  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nbd2  leads to lines that we've examined in the line 8...Bg4.   B.  9...d5  is the immediate central pawn push. We keep the tension with  10.Nbd2  ,  but we may capture d5 later.   C. Black frequently goes for the famous Breyer manoeuvre ...Nb8-d7. They can start immediately @@StartBracket@@  9...Nb8  @@EndBracket@@ or a bit later. I'll examine it via  9...Bb7  ,  which may also be connected to other ideas. One is ...Re8, followed by ...Bf8. I'll check that via  9...Bb7  ,  too.As usual: it doesn't sound obvious at first, but our job is easy and more or less the same in most cases: get the knight to g3 and play d4. }
9... Bb7 { Black completes the extended Fianchetto. } 10. Nbd2
{ Our normal move, starting the knight tour. We need to prepare d3-d4 thoroughly. After  10.d4?!  exd4  11.cxd4  Nb4  Black gets good activity for their pieces.   After  10.Nbd2  we'll check two options for Black: the Breyer idea  10...Nb8  , and the setup  10...Re8  ,  followed by ...Bf8. }
10... Nb8
{ Black invests some time to direct the knight to d7. We often see that the knight is not well-placed on c6. It looks at controlled squares @@StartBracket@@d4/b4@@EndBracket@@ and blocks the c-pawn. Black wants to place it on d7, often followed by ...c5, to involve the c-pawn. This regrouping is known from the Breyer Variation @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  b5  7.Bb3  d6  8.c3  O-O  9.h3  Nb8  @@EndBracket@@, but frequently seen in slower Ruy structure, too. }
11. Nf1
{ After 10...Nb8, there is less pressure on our center. Therefore, playing  11.d4  is possible, too. We still need the knight tour, so it will likely lead to the same positions at the end. One example is @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p2p1n2/1p2p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PPBN1PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11.d4  Nbd7  12.Nf1  Re8  13.Ng3  . }
11... Nbd7 { Both sides improve their knights. } 12. Ng3
{ Alright, we completed our knight tour. Now Black usually goes for ...Re8 and ...Bf8. It makes sense, as Black may play a fianchetto later. It combines defense against Nf5 with possible active ideas on the long diagonal. The bishop has little to hope for on e7, in any case. }
12... Re8 13. d4
{ The eagle has landed! Finally, we get our perfect pawn center. It's well-supported and stable. }
13... Bf8
{ Black is done with their regrouping, too. Now, what's our plan? I prefer to attack the b5-pawn and see if we can get Black to make some concessions on the queenside. }
14. a4
{ A common idea. We attack the pawn and can add more pressure on it with Bd3 later. In most cases, Black will play ...c5 quite soon when we reach the following position type. }
14... c5
{ After a slower move like  14...g6  ,  15.Bd3  is a good way to put more pressure on b5. }
15. d5
{ Closing the center is best. We gain lots of space and make sure that Black's b7-bishop has no scope. }
15... c4
{ Black must play this advance to get the c5-square for their knight. After something like  15...g6  16.b3!  we are ready to answer ...c4 with b4, when this opportunity is gone. }
16. h3
{ It's not strictly necessary to play exactly this move, but it helps us in many ways. It prepares Be3 in the short term and may help later for kingside play.   I want to close with a key idea you should know: after  16...Nc5  17.Be3  Qc7  the move  18.Ra3!  is a strong resource. We want to play Qe2 next, then Rea1, when we have doubled behind the a-pawn and want to open the file soon under optimal circumstances. White is always slightly better here, as we have more active ideas.  The a-file idea is one, but in the long run, often, some action on the kingside takes place. It is also easier for us to generate play on this side of the board. Think of Nh2 and ideas like f2-f4. Piece-based play with Nh2-g4 is also possible. Black's situation is solid, but at the same time, quite passive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A7) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 d6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3
{ The start of the Anderssen Variation. We cover the e-pawn, which limits Black's option. They need to be aware that now we threaten to capture on e5 and snatch the e-pawn. Black can't play  5...Be7?  as  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  wins the most important pawn on the board. It may sound silly, but I found thousands@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ of online games that featured this pawn blunder - and White often didn't even take the pawn! }
5... d6
{ Black covers their e-pawn but forfeits the option to play ...Bc5. It looks more natural to play  5...Bc5  or  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  ,  but there are reasons why Black might want to play differently.   - They possibly intended to play a line like  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  d6  or  6...b5  7.Bb3  d6  ,  and want to reach a familiar setup.   - They might want to develop with ...g6, an interesting concept.The move 5...d6 also involves a threat! We need to get the move order correct now. }
6. c3
{ It's crucial to start with  6.c3  and avoid @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O?  b5  7.Bb3  Na5!  ,  when our Ruy bishop will be traded off. Losing the bishop pair is one bad aspect, but it also hurts that Black manages to get rid of their c6-knight so easily. The slightly misplaced knight on c6 is a key strategic issue in these slow Ruy structures. Why misplaced? We have a pawn on c3, which limits the scope of the knight. It mostly looks at protected squares, like b4 and d4.An additional issue for Black is the blocked c-pawn. We can favourably use our c-pawn to support a later d3-d4, building a well-supported pawn center. This is not as easy for Black to accomplish.Before we look at Black's options on move six, a word about our plans and setup. We have a fairly straightforward concept that works well, more or less, regardless of Black's choice: Castle kingside,Play Re1,Start the knight tour Nb1-d2-f1-g3,If Black plays ...b5, we retreat the bishop to c2.  This is the 'default setup' that we play. If Black plays an unexpected move and you see no clear refutation, resort to the described setup. This configuration is harmonious and provides excellent support to play d3-d4 and finally build the full pawn center.   Black has a fundamental choice now: developing the bishop to e7 or going for a kingside fianchetto. In most cases, they play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  or  6...g6  now and commit to one of the setups. These two moves will be our main paths to investigate. Are there other sensible moves? Yes, but they are either not good or have low independent value. Here's a list of the moves that we will check.   A.  6...Be7  is the main move. Black prepares kingside castling as quickly as possible.   B.  6...g6  goes for the kingside fianchetto.   C.  6...b5  is a rare choice at this point. If Black wants to play ...b5, it makes much more sense to do it one move earlier when our bishop had no other option than retreating to b3. Now we have two squares and go for  7.Bc2  ,  which is a small gain for us. I'll talk more about the difference between b3 and c2 in the notes to this move.   Please note that  6...b5  has little independent value, as Black has to continue with the kingside development soon, transposing to option A or B. I will still cover  6...b5  as a short trainable to emphasize the point of retreating to c2.Black can also develop their bishop to g4 or d7, but these moves have no significant independent value.   D.  6...Bd7  is a non-commital move. Black breaks the pin and delays the decision about the kingside formation. A transposition to A or B is likely, as they have to get castled soon. We play with our standard setup @@StartBracket@@O-O, Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ and will transpose to A or B.   E.  6...Bg4  pins our knight, but it is a generally dubious idea. Black's bishop often needs to trade on f3 or gets sidelined on the kingside. Black usually combines ...Bg4 with ...Be7, making the early ...Bg4 an option with limited independent value. After  7.O-O  Be7  ,  we'll transpose to line A quickly. }
6... g6
{ Black opts for the kingside fianchetto. If it often leads to interesting play, as Black has some ambitious plans available. Before we get there, our decisions are easy. We continue with our standard moves. }
7. O-O
{ The moves are very natural for both sides. We castle and play Re1, While Black completes their kingside development. }
7... Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Nbd2
{ We continue with Nbd2, as we usually do in this line. A standard idea is routing the knight to g3, which supports our center. However, this route is less attractive against a ...g6-setup than the ...Be7-based lines. The g6-pawn restricts our knight, taking away any Nf5-ideas.Still, it often makes perfect sense to complete the knight tour via f1 to g3. Black sometimes starts a kingside initiative based on moving their f6-knight and preparing f7-f5. In such a scenario, our knight is perfectly placed on the kingside. This side of the board is the main battleground.Black's most popular setup is different, though. You mostly meet ...b5, often combined with ...Bb7. We'll attack this queenside formation with a2-a4 so that the main play will evolve in this area. You'll see that using the d2-knight on the queenside is more effective. What to check now?   A.  9...b5  is Black's most popular move. In this case, using our knight on the queenside is a good idea. After  10.Bc2  we'll play a4 to start our play there.   B.  9...Nd7  starts a knight tour, sometimes connected with ...f5 ideas. We go  10.Nf1  to be safe on the kingside.   C.  9...Bd7  is popular and often connected with the plan ...Nh5. Again,  10.Nf1  is a good way to play. If Black goes @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp2pbp/p1np1np1/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nh5  , we'd also play  10.Nf1  , which likely leads to similar positions. }
9... Nd7
{ Black goes for an ambitious but probably dubious idea. They want to free the f-pawn to move or send the knight on tour to e6, where it connects to the d4 and f4-squares. With ...f5 being on the cards, we are happy to send our knight to g3. }
10. Nf1
{ On the way to g3. It's also fine to play  10.Bc2  here, anticipating Black's next move. }
10... Nc5
{ They can't play  10....f5?  , as  11.Bb3+  Kh8  12.Ng5  is simple and strong. }
11. Bc2
{ We keep our Ruy bishop and are now set to play d3-d4, completing our central expansion and gaining time by hitting Black's knight. }
11... Ne6
{ The best reply is stopping our idea. After  11...f5?!  12.exf5  , we have the better chances.   A.  12....gxf5?  is the move Black would like to play, but  13.d4  opens the game favourably. After  13...exd4  14.cxd4  Ne4  15.Ng3  we see a good example of why our knight is directed to the kingside if Black has ...f5 on their mind. We not only challenge Black's knight on e4 but also have Nh5 ideas. All the fight is on this side of the board, and all our pieces participate.   B.  12...Bxf5  is a better choice, but  13.b4  Ne6  14.Ne3  still looks better for White.   The move ...f5 creates some weaknesses. We have good chances to exploit them, particularly in line A, which is much better for White. The whole concept is too ambitious at this point. After the better  11...Ne6  we have some good options, but I suggest completing the knight tour. }
12. Ng3
{ I like this move, as it protects against ...f5 ideas. As we'll see, Black has a hard time playing with this idea now. A move we need to avoid is  12.Be3?  , which runs into  12...f5! }
12... Qf6
{ Black usually goes for this move, which prepares ...Nf4. Black can't play  12...f5??  , as  13.exf5  gxf5  14.d4  more or less wins on the spot. After  14...e4  15.d5  Black is falling apart.   If Black plays something slow, let's say  12...Kh8  , we can progress on the queenside with  13.b4  ,  later a4, Rb1 - Black can't make ...f5 work, while we improve our position. }
13. Be3
{ I like to get more control of d4, preparing the pawn push. It's not the only good move, though. Expanding on the queenside with  13.b4  also looks fine. }
13... Nf4 14. h3
{ It's important to stop ...Bg4, when we'd have difficulty breaking the pin. White is better now, as we are ready to play d3-d4 next. Black has invested a lot of time to get the knight to f4, but it's unclear what they are doing next. We have an advantage in the center and can expand on the queenside. }
*

