e sense to do it one move earlier when our bishop had no other option than retreating to b3. Now we have two squares and go for  7.Bc2  ,  which is a small gain for us. I'll talk more about the difference between b3 and c2 in the notes to this move.   Please note that  6...b5  has little independent value, as Black has to continue with the kingside development soon, transposing to option A or B. I will still cover  6...b5  as a short trainable to emphasize the point of retreating to c2.Black can also develop their bishop to g4 or d7, but these moves have no significant independent value.   D.  6...Bd7  is a non-commital move. Black breaks the pin and delays the decision about the kingside formation. A transposition to A or B is likely, as they have to get castled soon. We play with our standard setup @@StartBracket@@O-O, Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ and will transpose to A or B.   E.  6...Bg4  pins our knight, but it is a generally dubious idea. Black's bishop often needs to trade on f3 or gets sidelined on the kingside. Black usually combines ...Bg4 with ...Be7, making the early ...Bg4 an option with limited independent value. After  7.O-O  Be7  ,  we'll transpose to line A quickly. }
