7... Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Nbd2
{ We continue with Nbd2, as we usually do in this line. A standard idea is routing the knight to g3, which supports our center. However, this route is less attractive against a ...g6-setup than the ...Be7-based lines. The g6-pawn restricts our knight, taking away any Nf5-ideas.Still, it often makes perfect sense to complete the knight tour via f1 to g3. Black sometimes starts a kingside initiative based on moving their f6-knight and preparing f7-f5. In such a scenario, our knight is perfectly placed on the kingside. This side of the board is the main battleground.Black's most popular setup is different, though. You mostly meet ...b5, often combined with ...Bb7. We'll attack this queenside formation with a2-a4 so that the main play will evolve in this area. You'll see that using the d2-knight on the queenside is more effective. What to check now?   A.  9...b5  is Black's most popular move. In this case, using our knight on the queenside is a good idea. After  10.Bc2  we'll play a4 to start our play there.   B.  9...Nd7  starts a knight tour, sometimes connected with ...f5 ideas. We go  10.Nf1  to be safe on the kingside.   C.  9...Bd7  is popular and often connected with the plan ...Nh5. Again,  10.Nf1  is a good way to play. If Black goes @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp2pbp/p1np1np1/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nh5  , we'd also play  10.Nf1  , which likely leads to similar positions. }
9... Bd7
{ Black frequently plays ...Bd7 here or on one of the previous moves. We sometimes see @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/B3P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd7  7.O-O  g6  8.Re1  Bg7  9.Nbd2  O-O  to reach this position, or a similar sequence. }
10. Nf1
{ The move ...Bd7 is fairly flexible, so we don't quite know Black's intentions yet. I suggest continuing our knight tour, as they still might go for ...f5, when we are happy to be on the kingside. }
10... Nh5
{ The most ambitious move for Black. They go for ...f5, or the knight jump to f4. }
11. Ng3
{ I like this straightforward solution, which immediately clarifies the kingside situation. White usually plays  11.h3  , which looks fine, too. After our move, Black has to decide about their knight's fate. }
11... Nxg3
{ The capture looks best. After  11...Nf4  12.d4  it's not clear to me what the knight accomplishes on f4. It looks a bit like a lone warrior that lacks support. Black will not drum up any kingside attack, while we can expand on the queenside. A line like  12...Qe8  @@StartBracket@@threatening ...Nxd4!@@EndBracket@@  13.Bc2  Kh8  14.b4  comes to mind. Black can't play ...f5 while we make progress on the queenside. }
12. hxg3 Qe8
{ The most popular move, and important to check in a trainable line. You may meet this idea in similar positions, too. The move ...Qe8 sets a trap. We can't play  13.d4??  due to  13...Nxd4!  ,  when we have blundered the game! }
13. Be3
{ The main point is to avoid the blunder. Instead, we complete our minor piece development and wait with d3-d4 for a moment. It's possible to play Bc2 and d3-d4 next.   Note that  13...f5?  fails to  14.Qb3+  ,  when b7 falls. }
