[White "A8) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This chapter covers one of Black's main paths in the Ruy Lopez after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  , namely the line  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  .  Compared to 6...Be7, Black elects to develop their bishop to a more active square. This changes the position considerably, compared to 6...Be7, which is less ambitious. One change is the option of Bg5, which establishes a pin now. We will use this motive in some lines, but our starting move is different and somewhat surprising at first sight. We will start with  7.Nc3  .  It looks strange, given the plan of playing c3&d4, which should still be on our agenda.The point of  7.Nc3  is first to play Nc3-d5 and then continue with c3 & d4, depending on Black's response. I like this idea much, compared to the more familiar concept of playing c3 and continuing with the knight tour Nb1-d2-f1-g3. In the line  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  we need to play  6.c3  and go for this plan. This type of play wouldn't be terrible here, but we can be more cunning by playing 7.Nc3. You'll see that Black has many pitfalls to navigate. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. Nc3
{ Here we go.  7.Nc3  is our choice in this line. How should Black react to our move? They must consider our ideas Nd5 and Bg5 - allowing both moves can easily spell trouble. The knight jump to d5 is annoying in itself, as Black would like to capture it, but both exd5 and Bxd5 can be problematic. Our bishop is not badly placed on d5 and usually will recapture.Conceptually speaking, Black has three moves that look reasonable - right now or on the next move. They can think of ...d6, ...h6 and ...O-O, but combining them correctly is tricky. Black has to navigate several pitfalls. Let's check some possible options. Our job is easy, as we want to play Nd5 next in all cases.   A. Black can combine ...h6 and ...d6. The lines  7...h6  8.Nd5  d6  and  7...d6  8.Nd5  h6  lead  to the same position. This prevents early Bg5/Nd5 combos and delays castling for a moment.   B. Black can delay castling. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1pb1p3/4P3/1BNP1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  8.Nd5  h6  9.c3  Rb8  is a sophisticated way for Black to do that. I suggest playing  10.d4  against it, starting the central action. }
