[White "A8) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5 7.Nc3 d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. Nc3 d6
{ Black can start with this move if they intend to delay castling for a while, as after  8.Nd5  , the best choice is  8...h6  . This line is examined via the move order 7...h6 8.Nd5 d6, though. }
8. Nd5
{ We stick with our concept and go for the knight jump. The pin  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bxf6  Qxf6  10.Nd5  Qd8  11.c3  is less challenging for Black, but certainly a healthy alternative. After  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1pb1p3/4P3/1BNP1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nd5  ,  Black's choice is limited, as we threaten Bg5 with a much greater effect. Let's make a list of moves:   A. It is not surprising that @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1pbNp3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...h6!  is the best option, which leads to the main line of this chapter - 7...h6 8.Nd5 d6 is the move order I chose to examine it.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1pbNp3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...O-O?  9.Bg5  is a terrible idea when Black can't avoid the destruction of their kingside. I examine this option via the move order 7...O-O 8.Nd5 d6? 9.Bg5. Please have a look there for more carnage.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1pbNp3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be6?  9.Bg5  is not as terrible as B, but still great for White. Black's damaged structure can't be repaired.   D. That leaves @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1pbNp3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nxd5  to study. It's better for White, but we have to avoid a pitfall. }
8... Nxd5 9. Bxd5 Bd7
{ This looks more logical than going  9...Bb7  and creating a self-pin. We have a nice advantage after a simple play like  10.c3  or  10.O-O  ,  followed by c3.   Let's focus on  9...Bd7  ,  which is more important. We now have to avoid a tempting move: the knight jump to g5. After  10.Ng5?  Black has the amazing  10...h6!  , because  11.Nxf7??  Qf6!  12.O-O  Rf8  sees our knight trapped on f7! The move 10...h6 is not easy to find for Black, but even  10...Qf6  is good for Black... so just avoid the knight jump. }
10. Bg5
{ It's much better to use this square for our bishop! Now we have a nice advantage with easy moves. as  10...f6  11.Bd2  looks horrific for Black due to the weaknesses on the kingside. Let's check 10...Qc8 quickly. }
10... Qc8 11. Nh4
{ We are also substantially better after simpler moves, like  11.O-O  or  11.Be3  ,  but the knight jump is strong. We get Nf5 on the map, but also Qh5. A challenging position for Black! As we are already in quite an exotic territory, I'll end the trainable here.   Want to see a fun line, though? What about  11.Nh4  Rb8  12.Qh5  O-O  13.Bf6!  gxf6  14.Bxc6  Bxc6  15.Nf5  Kh8  16.Qh6  and 'Game over!' }
