[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A8) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5 7.Nc3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. Nc3 O-O
{ Castling can't be a bad move, but we'll see that Black's job is not easy after committing the king that early. I decided to organise the move orders in a way that all early O-O positions are shown here, but Black may also play a different seventh move. Then they castle on move 8 or 9 when we reach the lines discussed here. }
8. Nd5
{ We always start with the knight jump, setting up the Bg5 and c3 ideas. Black now has to worry about Bg5; what are the options?   A.  8...d6?  ignores our idea and runs into  9.Bg5  , when Black's kingside is torn apart.   B. Black's most popular move is  8...h6  now, stopping the pin. We'll see that Black is in danger of losing a miniature - look forward to some fun lines.   C.  8...Nxd5  is rarely played but looks better than the alternatives. We'll get a small and comfortable advantage, but Black won't get checkmated quickly - that might happen in A or B! }
8... d6
{ Black ignores the Bg5 idea, a fairly basic mistake. Let's have a quick look at how to exploit it. }
9. Bg5
{ Now Black is too late to save their kingside structure. Depending on Black's reply, Nxf6+ or Bxf6 tears down Black's defence. }
9... Bg4
{ I'll check this move in the trainable, but Black has tried some other desperate defences.   A.  9...Be6  is the most common move, trying to take our knight. We have a direct win against it:  10.Nxf6+  gxf6  11.Bh6  Re8  12.Bxe6  fxe6  13.Nd4!  and Black loses the house.   B.  9...Na5  is a tougher try. A convincing way to put Black away is  10.Nd2!  ,  clearing the way for our queen to f3 or h5. After  10...c6  11.Nxf6+  gxf6  12.Bh6  Nxb3  13.Nxb3  Re8  14.Nxc5  dxc5  15.Qh5  Black won't survive. We'll open the position with f4 next.These are two sample lines. White has multiple ways to punish Black, so there is no need to learn them by heart. }
10. Qd2
{ We have many winning moves, but  10.Qd2!  is crushing and instructive. We want to play Bxf6 and Qh6 next. Black has no defence. }
10... Re8 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Qh6
{ And it's over. After  12...Re6  White wins with about any move, but  13.Ne3  and  13.h3  are the most convincing. }
