[White "A8) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5 7.Nc3 h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. Nc3 h6
{ Black starts with the h-pawn, stopping our pinning idea. I am using this move order to investigate the concept of delaying castling for Black. }
8. Nd5
{ We play the knight jump against 7...d6, 7...O-O and here, which makes it easy to remember. Now we have to investigate two main moves, but one is a transposition.   A.  8...d6  9.c3  is the main move, delaying castling. A different way to get there is 8...Rb8 9.c3 d6, which we will examine shortly.   B.  8...O-O  9.c3  is a very relevant alternative, examined via the move order 7...O-O 8. Nd5 h6 9.c3, which is dangerous for Black to handle. }
8... d6 { Black delays castling, a good strategy. } 9. c3
{ The knight tour Nc3-d5 was not played to give up on this central expansion. It remains a key part of our strategy. Now Black has to navigate a dangerous pitfall. If they play the natural move  9...O-O?  we have  10.Nxf6+  Qxf6  11.Bd5  Bd7  12.Rg1!  to transpose to the great attacking line we examined via the 7...O-O move order. As you can imagine, this happened A LOT in practice. What should Black do instead?   A.  9...Rb8  looks like a good move and was recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his 1.e4 e5 course on Chessable. Black delays castling and removes the rook from possible problems on the long diagonal. This way, the c6-knight gets mobile after a trade on d5.   B.  9...Be6  is a logical alternative, which intends to get rid of the knight with ...Bxd5 next. We have a fascinating choice against this idea - hang on.Both moves address a common problem for Black: the strong d5-knight. In A, they want to trade on d5 and play ...Ne7 to get rid of the bishop. In B, the bishop intends to take our knight, trying to force a pawn onto the d5-square.   Other moves don't address this issue and can quickly lead to problems. A funny line to demonstrate this issue is  9...Bg4?!  10.h3  Bh5?  @@StartBracket@@relatively best is 10...Be6, but that was not the idea@@EndBracket@@  11.Nxf6+  Qxf6  12.Bd5  , which forces an unfortunate king move for Black! I also found some games with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2pp1/p1np1n1p/1pbNp3/4P3/1BPP1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ba7  , when  10.Nxf6+  Qxf6  11.Bd5  Bd7  12.a4  gives White a strong initiative with simple means. }
9... Be6
{ Black develops their bishop with a clear intention: chop our strong knight. We have an interesting choice now. The simple way to play is capturing f6 and playing for a minimum edge or allowing the capture on d5.   I struggled a bit here about what to recommend. I found a fascinating idea after  10.O-O  that I would play in a game, but it might not be everybody's cup of tea. So I decided to go for  10.Nxf6+  as my main suggestion, but here's the alternative idea I was talking about.   10.O-O  Bxd5  11.exd5  Ne7  is usually answered with  12.d4  , when chances are about equal. The move I suggest is  12.Nh4!?  , which sacrifices the d-pawn. Black has to be very careful now. Here are some ideas.   A. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/2p1npp1/p2p1n1p/1pbPp3/7N/1BPP4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nexd5?  13.d4  Bb6  14.Nf5  shows a key idea. Our knight is a monster on f5. Now  14....O-O?  15.dxe5  dxe5  16.Bxd5  Nxd5  17.Qxd5  is a problem for Black, so they can't castle and have to defend g7 with the king... not good!   B. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/2p1npp1/p2p1n1p/1pbPp3/7N/1BPP4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nfxd5?  13.d4  Bb6  14.Re1  is also great for White.   C. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/2p1npp1/p2p1n1p/1pbPp3/7N/1BPP4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...g5?  13.Nf3  is too risky for Black. d2-d4 will open the game and expose their weaknesses.   D. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/2p1npp1/p2p1n1p/1pbPp3/7N/1BPP4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...O-O  is critical when Black intends to take on d5 later. White has some interesting options now. If we play  13.Qf3  , Black can still go  13...Nfxd5!  , as  14.Bxd5  Nxd5  attacks our h4-knight. One interesting idea is  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/2p1npp1/p2p1n1p/1pbPp3/7N/1BPP4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Kh1!?  , when  13...Nfxd5  14.Qg4  Qc8  15.Qg3  Kh7  16.f4  is a possible continuation. White has compensation for the pawn, but I was unsure if I should recommend this as my main suggestion. It's complicated stuff, and these sample lines are just the tip of the iceberg. It's always good to have some choice.Let's return to our simpler option now. }
10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. O-O
{ It's interesting to check Jan Gustafsson's notes in his course. He mentions @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2pp1/p1np1n1p/1pbNp3/4P3/1BPP1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be6  and evaluates  10.Nxf6  Qxf6  11.O-O  as a tiny edge for White. This is the reason why he prefers 9...Rb8, instead.Let's examine the situation. A key element is the two bishops on b3 and e6. Black could take on b3 or allow us to capture on e6. The easy part is evaluating  11...Bxb3  12.axb3  ,  as it must be a bit better for White. Our rook always eyes the a-pawn, and we have more opportunities in the centre. The configuration of pawn c3 vs Nc6 always makes it easier for us to play for d3-d4.Black probably rather wants us to capture on e6, so they prefer to castle. }
11... O-O
{ It's important to note that Black commits to  12.Bxe6  fxe6  now, as the queen recapture runs into a fork with d4 and d5. If they want to avoid this structure, @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/2p2pp1/p1npbq1p/1pb1p3/4P3/1BPP1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ne7  can be considered.  12.Bxe6  Qxe6  13.d4  Bb6  14.Re1  is still a bit better for White. We have more space and ideas on the queenside, like a2-a4.The position after 10.Nxf6+ Qxf6 11.O-O is a bit easier to play for White - this is a good example. }
12. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Black has to accept the doubled pawns as  12...Qxe6??  13.d4  Bb6  14.d5  is bad news. }
13. b4 Bb6 14. a4
{ This type of position is well-known from many lines of the Ruy and the Italian. White is slightly better because Black's structural problems are more important than the f-file. White always has Be3 or Ra2 to secure f2, and they try to open the a-file at a good moment. }
