[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A8) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Bc5 7.Nc3 h6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. Nc3 h6
{ Black starts with the h-pawn, stopping our pinning idea. I am using this move order to investigate the concept of delaying castling for Black. }
8. Nd5
{ We play the knight jump against 7...d6, 7...O-O and here, which makes it easy to remember. Now we have to investigate two main moves, but one is a transposition.   A.  8...d6  9.c3  is the main move, delaying castling. A different way to get there is 8...Rb8 9.c3 d6, which we will examine shortly.   B.  8...O-O  9.c3  is a very relevant alternative, examined via the move order 7...O-O 8. Nd5 h6 9.c3, which is dangerous for Black to handle. }
8... d6 { Black delays castling, a good strategy. } 9. c3
{ The knight tour Nc3-d5 was not played to give up on this central expansion. It remains a key part of our strategy. Now Black has to navigate a dangerous pitfall. If they play the natural move  9...O-O?  we have  10.Nxf6+  Qxf6  11.Bd5  Bd7  12.Rg1!  to transpose to the great attacking line we examined via the 7...O-O move order. As you can imagine, this happened A LOT in practice. What should Black do instead?   A.  9...Rb8  looks like a good move and was recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his 1.e4 e5 course on Chessable. Black delays castling and removes the rook from possible problems on the long diagonal. This way, the c6-knight gets mobile after a trade on d5.   B.  9...Be6  is a logical alternative, which intends to get rid of the knight with ...Bxd5 next. We have a fascinating choice against this idea - hang on.Both moves address a common problem for Black: the strong d5-knight. In A, they want to trade on d5 and play ...Ne7 to get rid of the bishop. In B, the bishop intends to take our knight, trying to force a pawn onto the d5-square.   Other moves don't address this issue and can quickly lead to problems. A funny line to demonstrate this issue is  9...Bg4?!  10.h3  Bh5?  @@StartBracket@@relatively best is 10...Be6, but that was not the idea@@EndBracket@@  11.Nxf6+  Qxf6  12.Bd5  , which forces an unfortunate king move for Black! I also found some games with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2pp1/p1np1n1p/1pbNp3/4P3/1BPP1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ba7  , when  10.Nxf6+  Qxf6  11.Bd5  Bd7  12.a4  gives White a strong initiative with simple means. }
9... Rb8 { Black prepares to capture the knight, followed by ...Ne7. } 10. d4
{ White has alternatives here, mostly  10.O-O  , of course. I prefer the immediate  10.d4  , as it posed more concrete problems. }
10... Ba7
{ Black doesn't want to give up the centre, of course. Now we need to be cunning. What about our e-pawn? Do we need to defend it? }
11. Be3
{ No, we don't. it turns out that 11...Nxe4 is not to be feared now. Black has a range of moves now. The most reliable is Jan's suggestion 11...Nxd5, but there are more. Let's have a look.   A.  11...Nxd5  is the main move I cover.   B.  11...Nxe4  is playable for Black but is unpopular. Black has to suffer without any winning chances after a forced line.   C.  11...O-O?!  looks normal but promising for White due to concrete tactics after  12.dxe5  . I'll have a closer look at these three moves.   I also checked  11...Ng4  , when the long sequence  12.dxe5  Nxe3  13.Nxe3  Bxe3  14.fxe3  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  dxe5  16.Qxd8+  Kxd8  17.Bxf7  wins a pawn. It's a useless pawn, though - no winning chances for White. This is still not a bad option if you are fine with a draw against a strong player.The way to play for more is  12.O-O  , as we don't have to fear  12...Nxe3  13.fxe3  ,  giving us good play on the f-file. Qe1-g3 and Nh4 are the ideas. Note that Black's a7-bishop stares at a pawn block on d4 now. }
11... Nxe4
{ I only found one single game that featured the pawn grab. Black has to consider too many different annoying replies to make it an attractive prospect. I'll now suggest a simple answer, leading to a risk-free play for two results. It starts with  12.dxe5  , but there are sharp alternatives that I want to mention. They don't promise more than the capture, they are just a lot sharper.   A.  12.O-O  is interesting. It looks like Black has to play  12...O-O  , when  13.Re1  Be6  14.Qd3  Ng5  15.Nxg5  hxg5  16.dxe5  leads to complications that should result in equality.   B.  12.Qd3  Ng5  13.Bxg5  hxg5  14.h4  gxh4  15.O-O-O  is the full caveman, throw the kitchen-sink attack. The comp also says it's all 0.00, but this still could be fun to check. }
12. dxe5 { This starts a sequence of trades. } 12... Bxe3 13. Nxe3 Nxe5
{ OK, it's easy to spot, but still:  13...dxe5??  14.Bd5  wins with a typical tactic. }
14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Qxd8+ Kxd8 16. Bxf7
{ A long but forced line. White has a small endgame advantage now due to Black's weaker structure. Black should play a 'normal' move now, but in the game Stefan Kuipers - Steven Geirnaert, Black tried to solve it by  16...Nxf2?  , when  17.O-O!  Ne4  18.Rad1+  Nd6  19.c4  gave White a strong initiative. }
