11... Nxd5 { Black realizes the core idea of ....Rb8: taking our knight. } 12.
Bxd5 Ne7
{ That's the whole idea of playing 9...Rb8 - the knight can move now. } 13. Bb3
{ I suggest this move instead of  13.dxe5  Bxe3  14.fxe3  Nxd5  15.Qxd5  O-O  ,  which is the line in Jan's course. Black has enough play for the pawn, and I'm not too fond of White's compromised pawn structure. I think preserving our bishop poses more problems.   After  13.Bb3  we are on new grounds - at least I couldn't find a game example after our move. It's not so easy for Black now, in my mind. We'll check two moves:   A.  13...O-O  looks best, but not an easy decision for Black as it offers a pawn again. We won't take it, but more on that in a minute.   B.  13...Ng6?!  looks like a solid move, covering e5. It runs into the powerful  14.h4!  when Black gets under pressure.   Black could take on d4 to release the pressure, but it's a move we like to see. The trade  13...exd4  14.cxd4  gives us an excellent pawn centre; our basic strategic goal has been realised. }
13... Ng6
{ Placing the knight on g6 would be a fine decision if both sides had played kingside castling already. There are multiple reasons why we have not castled yet. Here is one of them. }
14. h4
{ A surprisingly strong move! It's all about the center - we want to attack the knight with h4-h5 and undermine the support of e5.   Black is in trouble now, as this simple idea proves very effective. They can't just ignore it, for example, after  14...O-O  15.h5  Nf4  16.Bxf4  exf4  17.Qd2  Qf6  18.Rh4  White wins the pawn and has a commanding position in the center.   The engine thinks  14...exd4  15.cxd4  is relatively best, but it still gives White a large plus. We have a huge center, and Black can't castle easily. We can still play queenside castling, an unusual sight in the Ruy.I will examine 14...Qe7 now, which looks like a 'human' idea to me. Black covers e5. }
14... Qe7 15. h5 { Here we go. Now we still need to check one point. } 15...
Nf4 16. Bxf4 exf4
{ What to do about the e-pawn? We can cover it by playing  17.Bc2  and keep a large advantage. It is, however, not a forced move. }
17. Qd2
{ We ignore the attacked pawn. After  17...Qxe4+  18.Kf1  ,  we have a fantastic position. Re1 is coming with tempo, and Rh4 will pick up the f-pawn. All our pieces are in the attack! }
