{ We play the knight jump against 7...d6, 7...O-O and here, which makes it easy to remember. Now we have to investigate two main moves, but one is a transposition.   A.  8...d6  9.c3  is the main move, delaying castling. A different way to get there is 8...Rb8 9.c3 d6, which we will examine shortly.   B.  8...O-O  9.c3  is a very relevant alternative, examined via the move order 7...O-O 8. Nd5 h6 9.c3, which is dangerous for Black to handle. }
8... d6 { Black delays castling, a good strategy. } 9. c3
{ The knight tour Nc3-d5 was not played to give up on this central expansion. It remains a key part of our strategy. Now Black has to navigate a dangerous pitfall. If they play the natural move  9...O-O?  we have  10.Nxf6+  Qxf6  11.Bd5  Bd7  12.Rg1!  to transpose to the great attacking line we examined via the 7...O-O move order. As you can imagine, this happened A LOT in practice. What should Black do instead?   A.  9...Rb8  looks like a good move and was recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his 1.e4 e5 course on Chessable. Black delays castling and removes the rook from possible problems on the long diagonal. This way, the c6-knight gets mobile after a trade on d5.   B.  9...Be6  is a logical alternative, which intends to get rid of the knight with ...Bxd5 next. We have a fascinating choice against this idea - hang on.Both moves address a common problem for Black: the strong d5-knight. In A, they want to trade on d5 and play ...Ne7 to get rid of the bishop. In B, the bishop intends to take our knight, trying to force a pawn onto the d5-square.   Other moves don't address this issue and can quickly lead to problems. A funny line to demonstrate this issue is  9...Bg4?!  10.h3  Bh5?  @@StartBracket@@relatively best is 10...Be6, but that was not the idea@@EndBracket@@  11.Nxf6+  Qxf6  12.Bd5  , which forces an unfortunate king move for Black! I also found some games with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p2pp1/p1np1n1p/1pbNp3/4P3/1BPP1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ba7  , when  10.Nxf6+  Qxf6  11.Bd5  Bd7  12.a4  gives White a strong initiative with simple means. }
9... Rb8 { Black prepares to capture the knight, followed by ...Ne7. } 10. d4
{ White has alternatives here, mostly  10.O-O  , of course. I prefer the immediate  10.d4  , as it posed more concrete problems. }
10... Ba7
{ Black doesn't want to give up the centre, of course. Now we need to be cunning. What about our e-pawn? Do we need to defend it? }
11. Be3
{ No, we don't. it turns out that 11...Nxe4 is not to be feared now. Black has a range of moves now. The most reliable is Jan's suggestion 11...Nxd5, but there are more. Let's have a look.   A.  11...Nxd5  is the main move I cover.   B.  11...Nxe4  is playable for Black but is unpopular. Black has to suffer without any winning chances after a forced line.   C.  11...O-O?!  looks normal but promising for White due to concrete tactics after  12.dxe5  . I'll have a closer look at these three moves.   I also checked  11...Ng4  , when the long sequence  12.dxe5  Nxe3  13.Nxe3  Bxe3  14.fxe3  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  dxe5  16.Qxd8+  Kxd8  17.Bxf7  wins a pawn. It's a useless pawn, though - no winning chances for White. This is still not a bad option if you are fine with a draw against a strong player.The way to play for more is  12.O-O  , as we don't have to fear  12...Nxe3  13.fxe3  ,  giving us good play on the f-file. Qe1-g3 and Nh4 are the ideas. Note that Black's a7-bishop stares at a pawn block on d4 now. }
11... Nxd5 { Black realizes the core idea of ....Rb8: taking our knight. } 12.
Bxd5 Ne7
{ That's the whole idea of playing 9...Rb8 - the knight can move now. } 13. Bb3
{ I suggest this move instead of  13.dxe5  Bxe3  14.fxe3  Nxd5  15.Qxd5  O-O  ,  which is the line in Jan's course. Black has enough play for the pawn, and I'm not too fond of White's compromised pawn structure. I think preserving our bishop poses more problems.   After  13.Bb3  we are on new grounds - at least I couldn't find a game example after our move. It's not so easy for Black now, in my mind. We'll check two moves:   A.  13...O-O  looks best, but not an easy decision for Black as it offers a pawn again. We won't take it, but more on that in a minute.   B.  13...Ng6?!  looks like a solid move, covering e5. It runs into the powerful  14.h4!  when Black gets under pressure.   Black could take on d4 to release the pressure, but it's a move we like to see. The trade  13...exd4  14.cxd4  gives us an excellent pawn centre; our basic strategic goal has been realised. }
13... O-O
{ This looks best, but Black needs to know or figure out that  14.dxe5  Bxe3  15.fxe3  is fine for them due to the strong move  15...Rb6!  ,  which is not an easy task. Only the rook move is fully satisfactory for Black. However, I don't want to go pawn hunting with White. }
14. Qd2
{ The sharpest move. We threaten dxe5 now without allowing any structural problems after the trade on e3. We also have the second idea: the bishop sacrifice Bxh6! }
14... exd4
{ Black can cover the pawn with  14...Ng6  , but  15.h4  or  15.O-O-O  gives White good attacking chances. Taking on d4 is probably best, but again not an easy decision. }
15. Bxh6
{ This does not lead to an objective advantage for White, but it's the most dangerous. Now Black has some relatively obvious ways to lose and others that lead to equal chances.   A.  15...gxh6??  16.Qxh6  wins on the spot. Ng5 is a deadly threat.   B.  15...dxc3??  16.Qg5  is also a win due to  16...Ng6  17.Qxg6  - we have a strong bishop!   C.  15...Ng6  is best when  16.Bg5  Qe8  17.O-O  leads to equal chances in the end, according to the comp. I'd still rather be White, besides the assumption of having a large clock advantage. :-@@EndBracket@@ The practical advantage is huge if you manage to blitz all these moves while your opponent has to spend time finding everything.It's not a surprise that Black obtains fair chances in the  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc5  line. Black's play is logical and according to sound principles. I think that  7.Nc3  is a good test of Black's knowledge and abilities, though. There are many pitfalls to navigate, which often prove difficult in practice. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A9) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Be7"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Black's main path after  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  is  5...b5  6.Bb3  and then either  6...Bc5  or  6...Be7  . The current chapter examines  6...Be7  ,  the more modest-looking of the two.This is not a clear-cut assessment, though. Black's motivation behind  6...Be7  is not yet clear. They might want to play conservatively, based on ...d6, or aim at ...d7-d5 to open the centre.One important difference to  6...Bc5  is that our idea of pinning the knight with Bg5 is exclusive to the ...Bc5-setups. We fight  6...Bc5  with  7.Nc3  and hope to manage something like  7...d6  8.Nd5  O-O?  9.Bg5  ,  when Black collapses. A very naive sequence, but it shows our basic plan.   When Black develops the bishop to e7, it makes little sense to play for this idea, as Bg5 is no pin. Therefore, we need a different approach to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2pp1ppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  , as the same patterns don't work. The way to go is playing  7.a4!  ,  attacking Black's queenside. We will still frequently employ the move Nc3, but with different ideas in mind. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Be7 7. a4
{ It's important to remember that we start attacking Black's b-pawn immediately. We will castle kingside soon, but it's more accurate to start with  7.a4  instead of castling. What's the difference?After our move, we threaten to capture the b-pawn. Black has three replies to save it:  7...Bb7  ,  7...Rb8  and  7...b4  - all three moves have certain, small drawbacks; more on that in a moment.Let's compare to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  now. Black' b-pawn is not threatened, and they have the main choice between  7...O-O  and  7...d6  . If they play  7...O-O  and we go  8.a4  ,  the situation is the same as after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4  - Black has the three options I mentioned. However, if Black chooses  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  , they gain the additional option to answer  8.a4  with  8...Bd7  - a better bishop placement than b7 @@StartBracket@@more on this topic in a moment@@EndBracket@@.Of course,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  is not a bad move. It transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O  Be7  6.d3  b5  7.Bb3  ,  one of White's main Anti-Marshall weapons nowadays. But we can take advantage of our move order by playing  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B1P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4  to reduce Black's options.After our move, Black has three answers. They all lead to distinctly different positions and have their individual, small concession that Black needs to make.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq a3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Rb8  gives us the a-file after  8.axb5  and a small advantage.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq a3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...b4  changes the queenside pawn structure. Black gains space and controls c3 @@StartBracket@@no Nc3-d5 ideas@@EndBracket@@ but creates some weaknesses, like the c4-square.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2ppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq a3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb7  is the most popular move. One general objection against the move is that Black directs their bishop against a well-protected pawn on e4. It can be misplaced on its post - Black needs to be precise to prevent this scenario.Interestingly, Black often gets close to equal chances regarding engine evaluation, but White scores heavily against all three moves. In my mind, White's play is a lot easier to conduct. I have played the black side of these lines frequently and never put in any serious study. The consequence was lots of suffering due to inaccurate play. Black needs to know some key points. Otherwise, they'll often struggle. }
