[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A9) Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Be7"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez – 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.d3 b5 6.Bb3 Be7 7.a4 b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Be7 7. a4
{ It's important to remember that we start attacking Black's b-pawn immediately. We will castle kingside soon, but it's more accurate to start with  7.a4  instead of castling. The difference was explained in the informational introduction to this chapter. }
7... b4
{ This pawn advance changes the structure considerably. Now any ideas of Nc3 are out, but Black gives us control of c4, which could be great for a knight or a bishop.There is one essential move that we have to play, though. I suggest making it immediately so that you remember you must play it in this pawn structure: we need to play our a-pawn to a5! }
8. a5
{ Moving the pawn to a5 is an essential part of our strategy after Black has decided to advance their b-pawn. We accomplish multiple goals with the pawn move:   - The most important one: It stops ...Na5. Black was not yet threatening the knight jump, but once they lend cover to e5, it is on. After ...Na5, they'd hit our bishop and can continue with ...c5 to expand on the queenside.   Here's an example:  8.O-O  d6  9.h3?!  @@StartBracket@@still 9.a5! was good@@EndBracket@@  9...Na5!  10.Ba2  c5  ,  which helps Black a lot.   - It's related to the point above: Black's queenside is tough to coordinate. The knight is not ideal on c6, but it has no good target squares to aim for.   - We gain the a4-square for our pieces. Moving the bishop or rook to a4 can be an idea much later, putting pressure on the b4-pawn or the queenside. }
8... O-O
{ Black can also start with  8...d6  and castle on the next move. It makes no difference if they intend to play the pawn to d6. We examine  8...O-O  as the main move, as Black may go for a dubious Marshall-style play on the next move. }
9. O-O
{ It looks most natural to castle first, but I see no problem with starting  9.Nbd2  ,  as our knight wants to go to c4 in the end.   After  9.O-O  , Black's best is  9...d6  , but we'll check the dubious move  9...d5?!  , which is an attempt by Black to play in the style of the Marshall Attack. }
9... d5
{ Black tries to play as actively as possible, but it doesn't work out well, as we will see. I'll devote a bit more coverage to this move, as the arising complications are good to know and instructive. }
10. exd5
{ Black's problem will be the weak e5-pawn after  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Re1  ,  which makes the capture the strongest move by far. }
10... Nxd5 11. Re1
{ We attack Black's e-pawn, but we don't have to capture it if Black wants to sacrifice it. A key problem for Black is the queenside pawn formation, which gives us ideas like Nd2-c4 or Ba4 at the right moment to increase the pressure on the pawn. We'll see this approach against Black's best move  11...Bb7  , when we have an alternative option to grabbing the pawn immediately.   I will also check  11...Bg4  in a trainable line. It is a natural choice and the most popular move in practice. The third move I want to examine is  11...Bf6  , trying to defend the pawn. }
11... Bg4
{ The most popular move - Black goes for a pin. We need to be aware of a typical tactical motive: should we play h3 now? Or is it better to continue with developing our knight? }
12. Nbd2
{ The problem of  12.h3?  is that Black has  12...Bxf3!  13.Qxf3  Nd4!  which leads to complications that result in an equal position. We don't need to worry about it all that much, as  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/2p1bppp/p1n5/P2np3/1p4b1/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nbd2  gives us a huge advantage. We develop the knight to enable Nxf3 after capture and prepare Nc4 to add more pressure on e5. }
12... Nd4
{ It doesn't solve Black's problems, but it at least asks a question: Do we want to take e5 now and give up our star bishop? You probably know the answer already...Before we get there, we look at alternatives. Line B is cute but unlikely to happen, unfortunately.   A.  12...Bf6  13.h3  leads to the line  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1n5/P2np3/1p6/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bf6  12.Nbd2  Bg4  13.h3  .   B.  12...f6  13.h3  Bh5  14.Nxe5!  is a fun queen sacrifice that annihilates Black swiftly. The minor pieces are so much stronger than the queen - amazing! Black has too many weaknesses, so our pieces have stable outposts, a key element. We'll see a similar material distribution in the main trainable. }
13. Bc4
{ After  13.Rxe5  Nxb3  14.Nxb3  we are better, but it's not as convincing as keeping our bishop. There is too much pressure on e5 anyway - Black is running out of tricks. Let's have a look at the coolest line. }
13... f6
{ Black can play something like  13...Bf6  14.h3  Bxf3  15.Nxf3  Nxf3+  16.Qxf3  c6  17.Bd2  ,  but it's an awful position. We have great bishops, weaknesses to attack and easy ideas to improve. Re4 and Rae1 next look good.   However, after  13...f6  , it's a 'White to play and win' exercise. }
14. Nxd4
{ Boom! If you read the notes to more twelve, this is no surprise. Always check if a pin on the queen can be handled by simply ignoring it. Here it works perfectly. }
14... Bxd1 { This will be a longer trainable line, but let's have some fun. }
15. Nc6 Qd7 16. Nxe7+
{ We have to take here, as  16.Bxd5+?  Kh8  wins for Black. } 16... Qxe7
{ Or  16...Kh8  17.Nxd5  Bxc2  18.Nxb4  , which leads to a similarly depressing position for Black. }
17. Bxd5+ Kh8 18. Rxd1
{ It's much better to take the bishop. After  18.Bxa8?  18...Bxc2  , our structure is not as stable as we want it to be.   After  18.Rxd1  we have three minor pieces for the queen and a great position. Our pieces have stable squares and coordinate well. Our bishop is great on c4, rook to e1, and our knight has multiple good options. Be3 and Nb3-c5 come to mind. The route via f1 to e3 is interesting, too.If you wonder how bad this position is for Black: Stockfish is on +5 for White. }
