1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Be7 7. a4
{ It's important to remember that we start attacking Black's b-pawn immediately. We will castle kingside soon, but it's more accurate to start with  7.a4  instead of castling. The difference was explained in the informational introduction to this chapter. }
7... b4
{ This pawn advance changes the structure considerably. Now any ideas of Nc3 are out, but Black gives us control of c4, which could be great for a knight or a bishop.There is one essential move that we have to play, though. I suggest making it immediately so that you remember you must play it in this pawn structure: we need to play our a-pawn to a5! }
8. a5
{ Moving the pawn to a5 is an essential part of our strategy after Black has decided to advance their b-pawn. We accomplish multiple goals with the pawn move:   - The most important one: It stops ...Na5. Black was not yet threatening the knight jump, but once they lend cover to e5, it is on. After ...Na5, they'd hit our bishop and can continue with ...c5 to expand on the queenside.   Here's an example:  8.O-O  d6  9.h3?!  @@StartBracket@@still 9.a5! was good@@EndBracket@@  9...Na5!  10.Ba2  c5  ,  which helps Black a lot.   - It's related to the point above: Black's queenside is tough to coordinate. The knight is not ideal on c6, but it has no good target squares to aim for.   - We gain the a4-square for our pieces. Moving the bishop or rook to a4 can be an idea much later, putting pressure on the b4-pawn or the queenside. }
8... O-O
{ Black can also start with  8...d6  and castle on the next move. It makes no difference if they intend to play the pawn to d6. We examine  8...O-O  as the main move, as Black may go for a dubious Marshall-style play on the next move. }
9. O-O
{ It looks most natural to castle first, but I see no problem with starting  9.Nbd2  ,  as our knight wants to go to c4 in the end.   After  9.O-O  , Black's best is  9...d6  , but we'll check the dubious move  9...d5?!  , which is an attempt by Black to play in the style of the Marshall Attack. }
9... d6
{ Black sensible main move, not trying to solve issues radically. Black wants to develop the bishop to e6 next, in most cases. }
10. Nbd2
{ On the way to c4, a great spot for our knight. Now Black's most popular move is  10...Be6  , challenging our Ruy bishop. Some other moves will likely lead to  10...Be6  territory, as it's such a natural square for the bishop.   Playing  10...Bg4?  makes no sense for Black, as  11.h3  sends the bishop back to e6.  11...Bh5?  would be even worse, as the bishop is offside and abandons the defence of the light squares on the queenside. White is much better after  12.g4  or the less committal  12.c3  Rb8  13.Bc4  ,  when Black is tied to defend a6, and we have Nf1-g3 next to challenge their bishop. Black can try to play ...Bg4 at a more opportune moment, though.   We'll check the move  10...Rb8  , which is a popular choice for Black. They don't decide on a development option for the bishop yet, but first, place the rook in a good spot. }
10... Rb8
{ Black plays an interesting semi-waiting move. They don't decide yet on the bishop's future but play a good improvement move first. The rook move anticipates that we might play c3 @@StartBracket@@correct assumption!@@EndBracket@@ and, on a very good day, might manage ...Rb5 to win the a-pawn. }
11. Nc4
{ It's also possible to start with  11.c3  , a move we have on our agenda. }
11... Bg4
{ This move gives 10...Rb8 some independent flavour. More commonly seen is  11...Be6  ,  when we transpose to the lines with 10...Be6.After Black's bishop move to g4, we need to be precise. What's the best move? We must remember that Black may use ...Nd4 at some point. }
12. Be3
{ This is best because the alternatives don't convince.   A.  12.c3?  is a blunder, as  12...bxc3  13.bxc3  Bxf3!  is a huge problem. We have to take with the pawn, destroying our structure terminally. In this continuation, the point of ...Rb8 is clearly seen.   B.  12.h3?  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  Nd4  is awful, too.   After  12.Be3  ,  we are ready to send the bishop back to e6. I want to show an instructive idea. After  12...Qc8  13.h3  Black should drop their bishop back to e6. It's wrong to play  13...Bh5  ,  as the bishop is offside. But how to exploit that offside position? We can't play  14.g4?  due to  14...Nxg4!  15.hxg4  Qxg4+  ,  when Black wins.We must prepare this idea, as shown in the game Borki Predojevic - Frode Urkedal, Norway 2018. It continued  14.Re1  h6  15.Ncd2  Nh7  16.Kh2  Nd8  17.g4  ,  when Black was in terrible shape. The key idea is to prepare g4 by playing Kh2 first; even Rg1 is possible as a preparatory move. Black has no active idea after we've managed g4 and is condemned to wait passively. In the game, White prepared and realised f2-f4 and later won a good game. }
