{ After the trade, our pawn on c3 is unprotected. This changes the tactics for the central pawn push to d4, as we will see. Black's job is not easy, though. They must worry about d3-d4 all the time and don't have a clear active plan. One key issue is the c6-knight, which is unfortunately placed - a common Ruy Lopez problem for Black.The current position occurred in a game between Peter Svidler and Magnus Carlsen, London Candidates 2013. Magnus now went for a common plan: placing the queen on c8 and playing the f8-rook to d8. He prepared it with ...h6, removing any worries about Ng5. You'll often see a combination of these moves @@StartBracket@@...h6, Qc8, later ...Rd8@@EndBracket@@ as Black tries to improve their chances to play ...d6-d5 at some point. At the same time, they must be ready to meet our d3-d4 idea. }
13... h6
