1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Be7 7. a4
{ It's important to remember that we start attacking Black's b-pawn immediately. We will castle kingside soon, but it's more accurate to start with  7.a4  instead of castling. The difference was explained in the informational introduction to this chapter. }
7... Rb8
{ Black decides to give up the a-file but avoids the concessions of the two alternatives. Black keeps the pawn on b5 and will develop their bishop on its starting diagonal in most cases. We open the a-file now and then discuss piece placement. }
8. axb5 axb5
{ It's not so easy to develop your a1-rook - we already managed it on move nine. In this particular case, we have gained in two ways.    - Black always has to watch out if our rook may enter their camp. This is not an immediate factor but may become relevant later.   - The more important consequence at the moment is different. We stop ...Na5, which can be a key resource for Black, as you'll frequently see in the 7...Bb7 lines. }
9. Nc3
{ It is also possible to play  9.O-O  ,  but I want to suggest a different idea. We can play a quick Nc3-d5, which may pose some unexpected problems for Black. They now have the choice between castling or playing ...d6, which can lead to the same positions, but there are some subtle differences that I want to show. }
9... d6
{ Now we have a simple solution in playing  10.O-O  , when  10...O-O  11.Nd5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@1rbqk2r/2ppbppp/2n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1BNP1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQk - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...O-O  10.O-O  d6  11.Nd5  - we jump to d5 with our knight after castling first. An alternative, though, is that we can start with the knight jump here, which gives us some interesting additional ideas. }
10. Nd5
{ Now Black has to be careful, as only  10...Nxd5  looks like a fully satisfactory solution. After  11.Bxd5  Nb4  12.Bb3  ,  we'll transpose to lines we examine via the move order   @@StartFEN@@1rbqk2r/2ppbppp/2n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1BNP1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQk - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...O-O  10.O-O  d6  11.Nd5  Nxd5  12.Bxd5  Nb4  13.Bb3  .Alright, but what about castling... isn't that a perfectly normal move? It is, but Black has some surprising problems to solve. }
10... O-O 11. c3
{ A small move with great effect! What does it do? We control b4 and d4 now, limiting Black's knight. This way, we stop Black's idea ...Nxd5, as then the guy on c6 runs out of squares. This is surprisingly annoying for Black to deal with. }
11... Be6
{ The natural move leads to serious problems, but the position is not easy for Black regardless. Stockfish suggests the inhuman  11...Qd7!?  ,  intending ...Bd8, followed by ...Nxd5 to untangle. We are better with a normal move like  12.O-O  ,  of course. This is still a much better outcome for Black than after 11...Be6, when Black may lose quickly. }
