{ Again, clearly best and the idea of taking on d5 on the last move. Something like  12...Bd7  13.c3  is annoying for Black. They can't move their minor pieces, and we can improve easily. Playing Be3 and preparing d3-d4 is no rocket science. }
13. Bb3 c5
{ Now we get to an important moment. Black has just played ...c5 to expand on the queenside. We should avoid the tempting  14.c3  now. It looks like a perfectly normal move, but Black has  14...Nxd3!  , a typical tactic. This is not terrible for White, but I'm not too fond of the position after  15.Qxd3  c4  16.Bxc4  bxc4  17.Qxc4  Be6  , when Black has compensation for the pawn. The engine likes White's chances, but playing it with White as a human player isn't easy. I don't want to worry about this issue and prefer a cleaner solution. }
14. Bd2
{ The simplest move, in my mind. We push the knight back, as Black can't allow the capture on b4. }
14... Nc6 15. h3
{ It's not strictly necessary to prevent ...Bg4, but we have the time to do it, so why not? White has a nice, comfortable advantage in this position. We have a range of ideas. A simple one is playing c3 and Be3 and going for d3-d4. The comp also likes Be3, Nd2 and Qh5, which wouldn't cross my mind, but looks interesting, too.   A key issue for Black is the weak d5-square. They can't afford  15...Be6?!  , as  16.Bxe6  fxe6  is a weak pawn structure. A good idea to exploit it is  17.Nh2  ,  allowing Qg4 next. We also have the a-file... these little factors add up. }
