1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Be7 7. a4
{ It's important to remember that we start attacking Black's b-pawn immediately. We will castle kingside soon, but it's more accurate to start with  7.a4  instead of castling. The difference was explained in the informational introduction to this chapter. }
7... Bb7
{ Black develops their bishop to a less than ideal square. It stares at a well-protected e4-pawn, for starters. A second drawback might be the bishop's absence from the kingside, which can make a difference. Think of a knight jumping to f5, for instance.A key decision for us is how to develop our knight. I think both Nc3 and Nbd2 setups are fine, but I prefer Nc3-based play. We use this idea frequently in the 5...b5 lines, and I like to use similar ideas, if possible. I have checked if there is any point in starting with 8.Nc3, but it seems better to play it one move later and castle first. }
8. O-O
{ I suggest starting with this move and playing Nc3 later. The immediate  8.Nc3  is best answered with  8...b4  9.Nd5  Na5  ,  similar to the lines that we will examine soon. The difference is that both sides have not castled kingside yet. In some lines, Black benefits from castling queenside, an incredible resource.   Castling first works better. Now after  8.O-O  Black's best move is  8...O-O  , in my mind. They don't commit the d-pawn yet, which can be beneficial in some complications. Our main line demonstrates the point nicely. Black's alternative is  8...d6  , which is more passive. }
8... d6
{ Black goes for a more conservative setup. It's a welcome sight for us, as our Nc3-plan works even better against slow setups. }
9. Nc3
{ The ideas are similar to 8...O-O 9.Nc3, our main line. We attack Black's b-pawn and they need to react to our threat. Let's check 9...Na5 and 9...b4 now, but we have a simple, good solution.   A.  9...Na5  10.Ba2  b4  11.Ne2  and   B.  9...b4  10.Ne2  Na5  Ba2  lead to the same positions. In line B, there is the additional option  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1bp1bppp/p1np1n2/4p3/Pp2P3/1BNP1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nd5  ,  which is a good alternative. It doesn't look more promising than the transposition, though. }
9... Na5
{ In the comparable position after @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...O-O  9.Nc3  Na5  , we need to play the surprising  10.Bd5!  , as  10.Ba2  b4  11.Ne2  leads nowhere due to  11...d5!  when Black opens the centre favourably.   Here, the move @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1bp1bppp/p2p1n2/np2p3/P3P3/1BNP1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bd5  would work, too. However, as Black has already played ...d6, we can keep our bishop with the simpler move  10.Ba2  in this version. }
10. Ba2
{ Keeping the bishop is best here, in my mind. The following line is more or less forced and promising for White. As mentioned,  10.Bd5!?  would be possible, but it is not better than the retreat to a2.   Note that it's dubious to play  10.axb5?!  Nxb3  11.cxb3  axb5  12.Rxa8  Qxa8  13.Nxb5  ,  as the extra pawn is worthless. We have given up the bishop pair on top of everything. }
10... b4 11. Ne2
{ The move  11.Nd5  leads nowhere, as Black can capture all pieces coming to d5. We want to transfer our knight to g3, eyeing the weak f5-square. A nice point about the knight tour Nb1-c3-e2-g3, compared to Nb1-d2-f1-g3, is that we save a tempo - there is no need to ever move the rook to clear the f1-square. }
11... c5
{ Black expands on the queenside, getting their c-pawn into play.   I want to briefly discuss an alternative for Black, the move  11...b3  ,  which does not work well in this particular case but is a common concept for Black. The point is that after  12.cxb3  c5  Black wants to play ...Nc6-b4 and entomb our poor bishop. We must avoid such a scenario and should react with  13.b4!  , when  13...cxb4  14.Bd2  is excellent for White. This is why 11...b3 doesn't work here. However, it's good to keep an eye out for the resource ...b3, as it can be a serious option in similar positions. }
12. c3
{ I like this more than the more popular move  12.Ng3  , when  12...b3!?  is possible for Black. This also looks slightly better for White, but playing @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b2bppp/p2p1n2/n1p1p3/Pp2P3/3P1N2/BPP1NPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq c6 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.c3  avoids this option and is more to my taste. We can still jump to g3 next. Now I don't see how Black avoids a slight, but annoying disadvantage.   A.  12...bxc3?!  13.bxc3  c4  tries to undermine our centre, but  14.Ng3  O-O  15.Re1  is simple and good. We strengthen our centre and are now ready to play Nf5 to start our attack.   B.  12...O-O  13.cxb4  cxb4  14.Ng3  looks nice for White, too. We also have Bd2 to attack the exposed b4-pawn. }
