{ I stick to Nc3 solutions whenever possible. It's not the only good setup, though. You can also play  9.Re1  or  9.Nbd2  . These lines are good alternatives and should give White some advantage, too. Our choice  9.Nc3  is a more direct way. We attack b5, so Black's choice is limited.   A.  9...Na5  is interesting and requires a cunning reply,  10.Bd5!  - it's a really odd move, but it works well.   B.  9...b4  is the most popular move, leading to a long, forced line that is slightly better for White.   C.  9...Nd4  is rarely played, but no bad move. I prefer White, but it's not much. }
9... Nd4
{ A rarely played move, but it's not bad. We keep a small advantage, but not more if Black plays well. }
10. Ba2
{ This is probably better than  10.Nxd4  exd4  11.Ne2  c5  12.Ng3  , when  12...d5  13.e5  Nd7  14.f4  is a rather deep but logical line. Our a2-bishop is strangely placed in this position, as c5-c4 is a constant worry. This can be tricky to play in practice.   Playing  10.Ba2  intends to delay the capture for one move. We argue that  10...b4  11.Nxd4  exd4  12.Ne2  gives our bishop more scope. }
10... b4
{ Not the only move at this point. Black also has the following ideas:   A.  10...Nxf3+  11.Qxf3  b4  12.Ne2  d5  13.Ng3  is comfortable for White. Our centre is stable and the knight connects to f5. The moves Nf5 and Bg5 may drum up an attack by simple means.   B.  10...d5?!  is pawn sacrifice that looks incorrect. After  11.Nxe5  Bd6  12.f4  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p4n2/1p1pN3/P2nP3/2NP4/BPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...c5  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.c3!  ,  White is better. The last line is compelling, and the refutation of 11...c5. White has other ways to an advantage, but this is the most convincing. }
11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Ne2
{ Now Black has to play the correct move. Otherwise, they are in trouble. }
12... d5
{ The alternative  12...c5?  leads to a grim situation for Black after  13.Bg5  d5  14.Ng3  dxe4  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Nxe4  ,  when our pieces are dominating. Black's f6-bishop is awful and will remain passive. After  16...Bxe4  17.dxe4  ,  our Ruy bishop will become the hero of the day on d5, which is an eternal outpost. }
13. e5
{ Taking on d5 is too tame, but after the pawn advance, I think we have a small advantage. Black has to retreat to d7, and after  13...Nd7  , we have a choice of moves.   A.  14.Nxd4  Nxe5  15.Nf5  is a simple one that looks a bit better for White.   B.  14.Bf4  is more ambitious, angling for  14...c5  15.Ng3  .   C.  14.f4  also comes into consideration.I'd probably go for option B - it looks the most dangerous. }
