8... O-O { A flexible move. Black does not yet commit their d-pawn. } 9. Nc3
{ I stick to Nc3 solutions whenever possible. It's not the only good setup, though. You can also play  9.Re1  or  9.Nbd2  . These lines are good alternatives and should give White some advantage, too. Our choice  9.Nc3  is a more direct way. We attack b5, so Black's choice is limited.   A.  9...Na5  is interesting and requires a cunning reply,  10.Bd5!  - it's a really odd move, but it works well.   B.  9...b4  is the most popular move, leading to a long, forced line that is slightly better for White.   C.  9...Nd4  is rarely played, but no bad move. I prefer White, but it's not much. }
9... b4
{ Black's most natural and popular move. Where to go now? After @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d6  9.Nc3  b4  , we play  10.Ne2  ,  aiming for the g3-square. Here, the situation is different, as Black has not moved their d-pawn yet. This allows a more powerful answer based on ...d7-d5. The way to go is to jump to d5. }
10. Nd5
{ It's crucial to play this move. After  10.Ne2  Na5  11.Ba2  d5!  Black has tricked us and accomplished their desired central break. it is interesting to compare this to @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1BNP1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Na5  , when we need to play  10.Bd5!  , as  10.Ba2  b4  11.Ne2  d5!  leads to the same position that we're trying to avoid.It can be tough to remember the difference between moving the knight to e2 or d5. A good way to remember it is the following:   - After @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d6  ,  it will be a slower game. They can't play ...d7-d5 in one go. We have time for Ne2-g3.   - After @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...O-O  Black hints at the idea of playing ...d7-d5. In the key lines, we need to go to the d5-square to fight it. Think of  9.Nc3  Na5  10.Bd5!  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bppbppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1BNP1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9...b4  10.Nd5!  What's best for Black now? They have a narrow path but many spots to go wrong. The best is the dynamic option  10...Na5!  11.Nxe7+  Qxe7  12.Ba2  d5!  ,  breaking in the centre. Black will often be a pawn down, though. This is not an easy option to go for. In practice, Black often plays differently and is worse. It will often come down to knowledge, as this concept is not easily devised over the board.Besides  10...Na5  , I will also briefly examine  10...d6  and  10...Nxd5  ,  as these are likely to happen if Black plays based on general considerations. }
10... Nxd5
{ We are happy to see the trade, as our bishop will have a great position on d5. }
11. Bxd5 d6
{ Black needs to cover e5. Now we have a wide choice of moves, and more or less, any good move keeps an advantage. }
12. Be3
{ We'll go for the bishop move as the main choice, but there is nothing wrong with @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np4/3Bp3/Pp2P3/3P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Re1  , @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np4/3Bp3/Pp2P3/3P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.h3  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np4/3Bp3/Pp2P3/3P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.c3  - we are not in a rush. Preparing c3 and d3-d4 thoroughly is possible, and the move order is irrelevant.  However, there is a move to avoid! It looks quite normal to play  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np4/3Bp3/Pp2P3/3P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.a5?  , but it fails to a surprising tactic. Black has  12...Nxa5!  13.Rxa5  c6  , when things have gone wrong for us.  After @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np4/3Bp3/Pp2P3/3P1N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Be3  , White is slightly better. We can expand with c3&d4 later, while Black has to handle the annoying pin.  12...Na5  13.Bxb7  Nxb7  14.d4  is a sample line, showing that Black’s knight is awkwardly placed. }
