Nxe7+
{ We don't want to allow Black to capture on d5, so we take the bishop with a check. }
11... Qxe7 12. Ba2
{ We want to keep our bishop, of course. Now Black's only way to justify their play is going for  12...d5!  , as other ideas look bad. I'll look at  12...d6?  to demonstrate the problems. }
12... d6
{ This leads to serious trouble. Even worse is  12...c5?  , by the way. After  13.Nh4  d5  14.Nf5  Qe6  15.f4  White gets a winning attack quickly. }
13. Bg5
{ This is even stronger than  13.Nh4  . Black is stuck in an awkward pin and has no way to untangle. }
13... h6
{ Now we see a great point of the bishop move. We don't go to h4, but we have a much better option. }
14. Bd2
{ We attack the b4-pawn, a simple idea. Why was it important to play Bg5 and now drop back to d2? Is ...h6 such a problem for Black? }
14... c5 15. Nh4
{ Now Black has no way to stop Nf5, as  15...Bc8  is met by  16.Ng6!  , winning the exchange. Black has to play something like @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1b2qpp1/p2p1n1p/n1p1p3/Pp2P2N/3P4/BPPB1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Kh7  , when  16.Nf5  Qd8  17.f4  gives us a crushing attack.Such a scenario illustrates why Black's ...Bb7 lines often lead to practical problems for Black. They need to justify the bishop's position with ideas like  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bppqppp/p4n2/n3p3/Pp2P3/3P1N2/BPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...d5!  , breaking open the centre and giving scope to the bishop. A 'lazy move' like  12...d6?  leads to a disaster, as f5 is weak and they have no counterplay. }
