{ We want to keep our bishop, of course. Now Black's only way to justify their play is going for  12...d5!  , as other ideas look bad. I'll look at  12...d6?  to demonstrate the problems. }
12... d5 { The only way to justify Black's concept. } 13. exd5 Bxd5
{ The most obvious move, but it involves a pawn sacrifice, as  14.Re1  leads to a situation that gives Black no chance to defend the e-pawn.   Black players sometimes try a slower alternative, the move  13...Qd6  .  Black wants to take the pawn later and leave the e-file in anticipation of a rook coming to e1.White has two ways to an advantage against  13...Qd6  . One is  14.d4  e4  15.Nh4  , but the alternative is more fun. It's a long but forced line.  14.Qe1  @@StartBracket@@attacking e5 and b4@@EndBracket@@  14...Rfe8  15.Bd2  Nxd5  and now  16.Ng5  is the idea. After  16...h6  , we can play  17.Nxf7!  , when  17...Kxf7??  16.Bxb4  wins. Better is @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/1bp2Np1/p2q3p/n2np3/Pp6/3P4/BPPB1PPP/R3QRK1 b - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Qe6!  18.Nxe5  Qxe5  19.Qxe5  Rxe5  20.Bxb4  ,  when we reach an endgame with three pawns against a piece. It looks much easier for White to play, in my mind. }
14. Re1 Bxa2
{ Black gives up a pawn, as the alternatives look worse. They can try to keep the material but will be in trouble.  14...Bxf3  15.Qxf3  gives us a fantastic bishop pair and @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/2p1qppp/p4n2/n2bp3/Pp6/3P1N2/BPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Nc6  15.Bf4!  looks strong, too. After  15...Bxa2  16.Rxa2  Nd7  17.d4  White is much better. }
15. Rxe5
{ This is how we win the pawn: a double attack on the queen and the offside knight. I'll continue the trainable line to a key moment - hang on. }
15... Be6 16. Rxa5 c5 { Black has to play this move, shutting off our rook. }
17. d4 { We want to ensure our rook is not trapped on the edge of the board. }
17... cxd4 18. Bf4
{ We must avoid  18.Nxd4?  Qc7  and the even more horrific  18.Qxd4??  Rfd8  , when all the effort was spoiled. After @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/4qppp/p3bn2/R7/Pp1p4/5N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQ2K1 w - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Bf4  ,  we are slightly better, as all queenside pawns are vulnerable. Black mostly hopes that the opposite-coloured bishops help to make a draw, but that's all they can hope for. A computer defends such a position perfectly, but it's tricky for a human player to do the same. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A10) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ One of my favourite TV shows is 'Curb Your Enthusiasm'. If you haven't seen it, you should start right after finishing this course :-@@EndBracket@@ So, what does that have to do with the Petroff? Well, there is no opening better suited to sober up your expectations of winning by a quick attack than the Petroff, so all of you better curb our enthusiasm.Jokes aside, the Petroff has its reputation for being a super-solid opening for a reason. I have checked various ideas against it and recommend the classical main line. I credit the renowned author and theoretician Nikos Ntirlis for suggesting this solution. He was kind enough to provide me with key ideas for this chapter. Follow Nikos on Twitter; you can all benefit from his knowledge there.Now, let's get to work and see how we tackle the Petroff. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting move of the Petroff or Russian Defense. I will stick to Petroff, as it is more commonly known in English, I think. }
3. Nxe5
{ In the first Edition of KIS 1.e4, I recommended  3.Nc3  against the Petroff, which was a simple and good solution. In this course, I advocated the Scotch Four Knights, so that  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.d4  was a transposition to a main pillar of the repertoire. This is not feasible in the second edition, as our weapon vs. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  is  3.Bb5  , the Ruy Lopez.   Therefore, we need a new weapon against the Petroff. I suggest taking the pawn and steering for the classical main line of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.d4  d5  6.Bd3  ,  which aims to play for a small pull from a position of complete safety.   After  3.Nxe5  , Black's main and the best move is  3...d6  , but we need to check  3...Nxe4  , better than its reputation, and the notorious Stafford Gambit  3...Nc6?  , which more or less loses but should be examined to have a good reply ready. }
3... d6 4. Nf3
{ I also looked at  4.Nd3  , but if Black knows  4...Nxe4  5.Qe2  Qe7  6.Nf4  Nc6  7.Nd5  Nd4!  , we'd have absolutely nothing. Black has some alternatives to this forcing line, so it's not like we'd be winning otherwise.  The main move 4.Nf3 remains the critical test, so let's stick to it. }
4... Nxe4
{ After 4...Nxe4 White has a key choice. I am recommending the classical main line  5.d4  now, but there are alternatives that I want to mention briefly.   A.  5.Nc3  was all the rage for years but has recently been de-fanged by the following line:  5...Nxc3  6.dxc3  Be7  7.Be3  O-O!  8.Qd2  Nd7!  ,  which scores very well for Black. The idea is playing ...Nf6 and playing ...c5 to start a queenside attack.I was surprised to discover that, even below the master level, Black regularly goes for this approach. Sometimes, there is a problem on the GM level, but it is less relevant for 'normal' games. Here it looks like Black's best setup is well-known by now. The resulting positions are very sharp and difficult to play, so I don't want to go there.   B.  5.d3  Nf6  5.d4  d5  leads to a symmetrical position usually reached in the French Exchange via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  ,  which was part of the repertoire in the first edition. I considered this line, but I feel the main line 5.d4 asks more questions in the same symmetrical pawn structure. It is just as safe but more dangerous for Black.   C.  5.Bd3  and  5.c4  are two rare lines that I checked. I felt they are not dangerous enough, as Black usually finds their way with natural moves.So the main line 5.d4 is our choice. }
5. d4
{ Very natural play. We want to develop our bishop to d3 next and castle kingside. }
5... d5
{ Black plays this logical move almost all the time. I found games with  5...Be7  6.Bd3  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  would transpose to the main line, still@@EndBracket@@, when White is better with playing natural moves. A good move to play early on is h3, stopping ...Bg4. You can do that immediately with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  to make it as simple as possible. Next, we'd castle, play Re1, c4, centralise, and enjoy a nice advantage in space.   Back to  5...d5  ,  when we reach a symmetrical pawn formation, typical of the Petroff. It's fascinating to see that while the pawns are symmetrical, Black is more actively placed on the surface. They have the centralised knight while our knight is still on f3.Our job is to prove that Black's knight is more of a liability than an asset. This is accomplished by exerting pressure on the knight and the supporting pawn d5. We'll discuss this topic more concretely after our next move. We need to develop our f1-bishop and castle for all these plans. }
6. Bd3
{ White's play in the whole 5.d4 line is all about fighting against Black's e4-knight. We want to increase the pressure on the knight and force some concessions. If Black, for example, would be forced to retreat the knight, we'd consider the opening phase successful.Other forms of concessions could be structural. If Black needs to play ...f5 and weaken the e5-square, we'd usually be happy too. This depends a bit more on the concrete position, though.So how do we put pressure on the knight? There are two basic methods:   Attacking the knight with moves like Re1 and Nbd2,Attacking the supporting pawn of the knight by playing our pawn to c4.What is best? That mostly depends on Black's piece configuration. Their setup will not only be defined by the next move but rather by the next two moves; we are going to castle next in all cases. Let's see the overview and have a brief assessment for them.   A.  6...Bd6  is the main line and most popular on all levels. Black develops the bishop to its most active square and focuses on kingside development first. After  7.O-O  Black castles, not yet committing a queenside piece. In this line, we'll play a quick c4 to attack Black's d-pawn.   B. Black can play a more conservative setup based on ...Be7. There are various versions of it, as Black can start with  6...Be7  , or play a move like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  first, and continue with  7.O-O Be7 to reach the same positions. I'll cover the various ...Be7 ideas via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  and point out our possible transpositions from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  .This sounds a bit complicated at first, but you'll see that our approach against all ...Be7 versions is essentially the same, so it's not too difficult to master. Against these setups, challenging the knight with piece pressure @@StartBracket@@Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ is the most promising. We'll discuss in the notes to the lines why this approach is better than ideas based on pawn to c4, as in A.  C.  There is not much else, really. Black usually wants to castle kingside, so playing the bishop to e7 or d6 is natural. I will look at an ambitious line based on ...Nc6 and ...Bg4 that is worth knowing. It's good for White, but only if played properly. }
