[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A10) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense – 3.Nxe5 Nxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting move of the Petroff or Russian Defense. I will stick to Petroff, as it is more commonly known in English, I think. }
3. Nxe5
{ I suggest taking the pawn and steering for the classical main line of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.d4  d5  6.Bd3  ,  which aims to play for a small pull from a position of complete safety.   After  3.Nxe5  , Black's main and the best move is  3...d6  , but we need to check  3...Nxe4  , better than its reputation, and the notorious Stafford Gambit  3...Nc6?  , which more or less loses but should be examined to have a good reply ready. }
3... Nxe4
{ This move is rarely played and has a dodgy reputation, but it is not awful. We'll get a comfortable advantage with precise play, though. You must know the following forced sequence of moves. }
4. Qe2
{ At first, you might think it's already game over, as Black can't play an obvious move. After a knight move, we win the house, like  4...Nf6??  5.Nc6+  demonstrates. Black can't play  4...d5??  5.d3  , either. The only way is the following tricky sequence. }
4... Qe7 5. Qxe4 { We take the knight, but Black will get ours, too. } 5... d6
{ No way to save the knight now, but it's not a problem. Our best line involves returning the extra material and maintaining annoying pressure in a position with equal material. }
6. d4 { A natural move. We have a more crucial decision a moment later. } 6...
dxe5 7. dxe5
{ This is much better than taking with the queen, when Black gets some compensation for the pawn. }
7... Nc6
{ Now, we have reached the most important moment of this line because there is the potential to go wrong. Knowing the best move pays off here. }
8. Nc3
{ We return the e-pawn. This is MUCH better than  8.Bf4?!  , when  8...g5!  9.Bg3??  f5!  serves as a warning of what can go wrong. }
8... Qxe5
{ After all these adventures, we have reached a completely symmetrical position. It's not an EQUAL position, though. The tempo is very relevant, as we now break the symmetry favourably. }
9. Qxe5+ { We have a good move after the queen trade - hang on. } 9... Nxe5 10.
Nb5
{ Threatening the fork is a very natural -and strong - move, but  10.Bf4  is equally good. The idea is  10...Bd6  11.Bg3  ,  when White aims for Ne4 or Nb5 later. I suggest  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppp2ppp/8/4n3/8/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nb5  , because it's a bit simpler to remember. }
10... Bb4+
{ By far the best defence.  10...Kd8?  11.Bf4  ,  followed by O-O-O, looks awful for Black.   After the check  10...Bb4+  , Black plans to answer  11.c3  with  11...Ba5  ,  covering c7. We have a better way. }
11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2
{ Now Black finally has to attend to the c7-pawn. And only the boss can do this job. }
12... Kd8 13. Re1
{ And here we can conclude this line. We have a comfortable advantage here. Let's have a closer look at why we are better.   A.  13...Re8??  14.f4  is a disaster, as Black can't move the knight.   B.  13...f6  14.f4  Ng6  15.g3  Bd7  16.h4  c6  17.Nd4  keeps the pressure on.   C.  13...Ng6  14.h4  a6  15.Nc3  Re8  16.Bc4  Be6  17.Bxe6  is also awkward for Black. We have much better coordination and active ideas like h4-h5. Black's task is purely defensive, which results in bad practical results.It is important to realise that the whole, long sequence after 3...Nxe4 is more or less forced. Black has no reasonable way to deviate. We need to learn this line, which pays off. }
