[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A10) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense – 3.Nxe5 Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting move of the Petroff or Russian Defense. I will stick to Petroff, as it is more commonly known in English, I think. }
3. Nxe5
{ I suggest taking the pawn and steering for the classical main line of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.d4  d5  6.Bd3  ,  which aims to play for a small pull from a position of complete safety.   After  3.Nxe5  , Black's main and the best move is  3...d6  , but we need to check  3...Nxe4  , better than its reputation, and the notorious Stafford Gambit  3...Nc6?  , which more or less loses but should be examined to have a good reply ready. }
3... Nc6
{ About three years ago, I wouldn't have known this opening line existed. But thanks to tons of fun games by Eric Rosen, it has gotten viral in online Chess. It is an incorrect gambit @@StartBracket@@Eric is completely honest about this fact@@EndBracket@@ but can be tricky to meet if you are unprepared. Let's not make this mistake and study a good line against it. }
4. Nxc6 dxc6
{ Black has gotten two half-open files for the pawn, but White has two centre pawns and no weakness. There are many refutations of the Stafford, and you can argue which is best. I am sticking to the one I already featured in the first edition, when @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bc5  4.Nxe5  Nc6  5.Nxc6  dxc6  6.h3  was the move order that led to the Stafford. }
5. Nc3 { We cover the e-pawn, simple and good. } 5... Bc5
{ Black controls the d4-square and targets the vulnerable f-pawn. } 6. h3
{ No, you are not going to play ...Ng4, not in this game! That's what you need to know. We have kept the extra pawn and avoided tricks on f2.How do we continue, though? A good way to develop is going for d3 and a kingside fianchetto. You may also play Be3 at some point, challenging Black's bishop.   Note that we don't have to castle kingside. In a sequence like  6...h5  7.d3  Be6  8.g3  Qd7  9.Bg2  O-O-O  playing for  10.Bg5  ,  followed by Qd2 and O-O-O is strong. }
