[Round "?"]
[White "A10) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense – 3.Nxe5 d6 4.Nf3 Nxe4 5.d4 d5 6.Bd3 Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting move of the Petroff or Russian Defense. I will stick to Petroff, as it is more commonly known in English, I think. }
3. Nxe5
{ I suggest taking the pawn and steering for the classical main line of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.d4  d5  6.Bd3  ,  which aims to play for a small pull from a position of complete safety.   After  3.Nxe5  , Black's main and the best move is  3...d6  , but we need to check  3...Nxe4  , better than its reputation, and the notorious Stafford Gambit  3...Nc6?  , which more or less loses but should be examined to have a good reply ready. }
3... d6 4. Nf3
{ I also had a look at  4.Nd3  , but if Black knows  4...Nxe4  5.Qe2  Qe7  6.Nf4  Nc6  7.Nd5  Nd4!  ,  we'd have absolutely nothing. Black has some alternatives to this forcing line, so it's not like we'd be winning otherwise. The main move 4.Nf3 remains the critical test, so let's stick to it. }
4... Nxe4
{ As explained in the introduction, the main line  5.d4  is our choice. } 5. d4
{ Very natural play. We want to develop our bishop to d3 next and castle kingside. }
5... d5
{ Black plays this logical move almost all the time. I found games with  5...Be7  6.Bd3  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  would transpose to the main line, still@@EndBracket@@, when White is better with playing natural moves. A good move to play early on is h3, stopping ...Bg4. You can do that immediately with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  to make it as simple as possible. Next, we'd castle, play Re1, c4, centralise, and enjoy a nice advantage in space.   Back to  5...d5  ,  when we reach a symmetrical pawn formation, typical of the Petroff. It's fascinating to see that while the pawns are symmetrical, Black is more actively placed on the surface. They have the centralised knight while our knight is still on f3.Our job is to prove that Black's knight is more of a liability than an asset. This is accomplished by exerting pressure on the knight and the supporting pawn d5. We'll discuss this topic more concretely after our next move. We need to develop our f1-bishop and castle for all these plans. }
6. Bd3
{ White's play in the whole 5.d4 line is all about fighting against Black's e4-knight. We want to increase the pressure on the knight and force some concessions. If Black, for example, would be forced to retreat the knight, we'd consider the opening phase successful.Other forms of concessions could be structural. If Black needs to play ...f5 and weaken the e5-square, we'd usually be happy too. This depends a bit more on the concrete position, though.So how do we put pressure on the knight? There are two basic methods:   Attacking the knight with moves like Re1 and Nbd2,Attacking the supporting pawn of the knight by playing our pawn to c4.What is best? That mostly depends on Black's piece configuration. Their setup will not only be defined by the next move but rather by the next two moves; we are going to castle next in all cases. Let's see the overview and have a brief assessment for them.   A.  6...Bd6  is the main line and most popular on all levels. Black develops the bishop to its most active square and focuses on kingside development first. After  7.O-O  Black castles, not yet committing a queenside piece. In this line, we'll play a quick c4 to attack Black's d-pawn.   B. Black can play a more conservative setup based on ...Be7. There are various versions of it, as Black can start with  6...Be7  , or play a move like  6...Nc6  or  6...Bf5  first, and continue with  7.O-O  Be7  to reach the same positions. I'll cover the various ...Be7 ideas via 6...Be7 and point out our possible transpositions from 6...Nc6 or 6...Bf5.This sounds a bit complicated at first, but you'll see that our approach against all ...Be7 versions is essentially the same, so it's not too difficult to master. Against these setups, challenging the knight with piece pressure @@StartBracket@@Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ is the most promising. We'll discuss in the notes to the lines why this approach is better than ideas based on pawn to c4, as in A.C. There is not much else, really. Black usually wants to castle kingside, so playing the bishop to e7 or d6 is natural. I will look at an ambitious line based on ...Nc6 and ...Bg4 that is worth knowing. It's good for White, but only if played properly. }
6... Nc6
{ Black develops the queenside knight first. A more important split occurs after our natural follow-up. }
7. O-O
{ Easy - we castle first. Now Black's best and most popular move is  7...Be7  ,  when we transpose to a line that we cover via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  , when  7.O-O  Nc6  is a common continuation.   A similar story is the less frequently seen @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bf5  , when  8.Re1  Be7  9.Nbd2  would transpose to 6...Be7 territory again. The only interesting alternative to check is 7...Bg4, which is a sharp, but dubious line. }
7... Bg4
{ This move gives 6...Nc6 an independent flavour. Black pins our knight but delays the development of the kingside. Are there alternatives to this move and the transpositional moves mentioned in the notes before @@StartBracket@@7...Be7, 7...Bf5@@EndBracket@@? Nothing comes to mind as  7...Bd6?  8.c4  is terrible.How to play after the pin 7...Bg4, though? The answer is: as actively as possible by attacking Black's central formation. }
8. c4
{ A crucial decision: This is the only move that challenges Black's line and leads to an advantage. Black's central position is unstable, and we need to strike quickly. Black's choice is unpopular nowadays because of this move and the following lines. Black must be careful to stay in the game, and they will still be worse. I'll show the most important lines but keep the coverage brief, as we rarely meet it. }
8... Nf6
{ The retreat is Black's best try. There are worse alternatives.   A.  8...Bxf3  9.Qxf3  Nxd4?  10.Qe3  Bc5  11.cxd5  wins material for White. Here  9...Nf6  10.Nc3  would still transpose to the line we will check in a minute.   B.  8...Nb4?  loses too much time. White is much better/winning after  9.Nc3  Nxc3  10.bxc3  Nxd3  11.Qxd3  ,  when Black's development is lagging too much. Instead of 9.Nc3, many moves are good, though.   C.  8...Be7  9.cxd5  Qxd5  10.Nc3  Nxc3  11.bxc3  Bxf3  12.Qxf3  and  12.gxf3  are better for White. The bishop pair in a wide-open position matters a lot. }
9. Nc3
{ A lot stronger than  9.cxd5  Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Qxd5  11.Qxd5  ,  when White only has a small edge in the endgame. Now after 9. Nc3 we'll have a split, as Black has two options worth checking.   @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/3p4/2PP2b1/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nxd4??  is not one of them because  10.Qe1+!  Ne6  11.Ne5  Bh5  12.cxd5  wins on the spot. The move we need to check now is the greedy  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/3p4/2PP2b1/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Nxd4  ,  as this could be difficult to handle if you don't know it. I'll also have a quick look at  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/3p4/2PP2b1/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be7  ,  which is more cautious. }
9... Bxf3
{ Black goes for the pawn grab, a risky choice. More sensible is  9...Be7  , but the simple  10.cxd5  Nxd5  11.h3  Be6  12.Re1  gives us a comfortable IQP position. Standard attacking ideas like Bc2&Qd3 are effective here, as Black does not have many defenders on the kingside. }
10. Qxf3 Nxd4 11. Qh3
{ In the early days of this line, White often played  11.Qe3+  , which seems OK for Black. A much better move is  11.Qh3  , when White has a dangerous initiative. Black has to be very careful not to get wiped out now. }
11... dxc4
{ After  11...Be7  12.cxd5  Nxd5  13.Rd1  Black is collapsing on the d-file quickly. }
12. Bxc4 Qd7
{ Black wants to ease their defence by the queen trade. After  12...Be7  13.Bg5  O-O  14.Rfe1  , we'll get a strong attack with simple centralisation. }
13. Re1+ { We have a forcing sequence now that leads to a large advantage. }
13... Be7 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 { After  14...Nxd7  15.Nd5  it's immediately over. }
15. Rd1 c5 16. Nb5
{ A very long line, but forcing and convincing. We'll not only have d4 under fire but can always capture the f-pawn, too. Our bishop pair gives us a large advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A10) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense – 3.Nxe5 d6 4.Nf3 Nxe4 5.d4 d5 6.Bd3 Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting move of the Petroff or Russian Defense. I will stick to Petroff, as it is more commonly known in English, I think. }
3. Nxe5
{ I suggest taking the pawn and steering for the classical main line of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.d4  d5  6.Bd3  ,  which aims to play for a small pull from a position of complete safety.   After  3.Nxe5  , Black's main and the best move is  3...d6  , but we need to check  3...Nxe4  , better than its reputation, and the notorious Stafford Gambit  3...Nc6?  , which more or less loses but should be examined to have a good reply ready. }
3... d6 4. Nf3
{ I also had a look at  4.Nd3  , but if Black knows  4...Nxe4  5.Qe2  Qe7  6.Nf4  Nc6  7.Nd5  Nd4!  ,  we'd have absolutely nothing. Black has some alternatives to this forcing line, so it's not like we'd be winning otherwise. The main move 4.Nf3 remains the critical test, so let's stick to it. }
4... Nxe4
{ As explained in the introduction, the main line  5.d4  is our choice. } 5. d4
{ Very natural play. We want to develop our bishop to d3 next and castle kingside. }
5... d5
{ Black plays this logical move almost all the time. I found games with  5...Be7  6.Bd3  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  would transpose to the main line, still@@EndBracket@@, when White is better with playing natural moves. A good move to play early on is h3, stopping ...Bg4. You can do that immediately with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  to make it as simple as possible. Next, we'd castle, play Re1, c4, centralise, and enjoy a nice advantage in space.   Back to  5...d5  ,  when we reach a symmetrical pawn formation, typical of the Petroff. It's fascinating to see that while the pawns are symmetrical, Black is more actively placed on the surface. They have the centralised knight while our knight is still on f3.Our job is to prove that Black's knight is more of a liability than an asset. This is accomplished by exerting pressure on the knight and the supporting pawn d5. We'll discuss this topic more concretely after our next move. We need to develop our f1-bishop and castle for all these plans. }
6. Bd3
{ White's play in the whole 5.d4 line is all about fighting against Black's e4-knight. We want to increase the pressure on the knight and force some concessions. If Black, for example, would be forced to retreat the knight, we'd consider the opening phase successful.Other forms of concessions could be structural. If Black needs to play ...f5 and weaken the e5-square, we'd usually be happy too. This depends a bit more on the concrete position, though.So how do we put pressure on the knight? There are two basic methods:   Attacking the knight with moves like Re1 and Nbd2,Attacking the supporting pawn of the knight by playing our pawn to c4.What is best? That mostly depends on Black's piece configuration. Their setup will not only be defined by the next move but rather by the next two moves; we are going to castle next in all cases. Let's see the overview and have a brief assessment for them.   A.  6...Bd6  is the main line and most popular on all levels. Black develops the bishop to its most active square and focuses on kingside development first. After  7.O-O  Black castles, not yet committing a queenside piece. In this line, we'll play a quick c4 to attack Black's d-pawn.   B. Black can play a more conservative setup based on ...Be7. There are various versions of it, as Black can start with  6...Be7  , or play a move like  6...Nc6  or  6...Bf5  first, and continue with  7.O-O  Be7  to reach the same positions. I'll cover the various ...Be7 ideas via 6...Be7 and point out our possible transpositions from 6...Nc6 or 6...Bf5.This sounds a bit complicated at first, but you'll see that our approach against all ...Be7 versions is essentially the same, so it's not too difficult to master. Against these setups, challenging the knight with piece pressure @@StartBracket@@Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ is the most promising. We'll discuss in the notes to the lines why this approach is better than ideas based on pawn to c4, as in A.C. There is not much else, really. Black usually wants to castle kingside, so playing the bishop to e7 or d6 is natural. I will look at an ambitious line based on ...Nc6 and ...Bg4 that is worth knowing. It's good for White, but only if played properly. }
6... Bf5
{ This move has very little independent value, as Black can hardly do without ...Be7 soon to transpose to 6...Be7 lines. }
7. O-O Nc6
{ Here  7...Be7  8.Re1  immediately transposes to the line 6...Be7 7.O-O Bf5 8.Re1, a more common way to the same position. The knight move to c6 only delays the ...Be7 move, though. }
8. Re1
{ Now it gets really scary on the e-file, so there is not much choice for Black. }
8... Be7 9. Nbd2
{ We have transposed to the main continuation in the 6...Be7 line. } *

