7... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight first before castling or committing the c8-bishop. It's important to understand that the knight's position on c6 is double-edged for Black. It can be well-placed if Black has pressure on d4 @@StartBracket@@this applies mostly when White wants to play c4@@EndBracket@@, but it will often be in bad shape if White plays a pawn to c3. This will be a common pattern later.We need to play the correct move order now. Otherwise, Black can benefit from their early knight jump. }
8. Nbd2
{ It's important to get this move order right. After  8.Re1  Black may go for  8...Bg4  when their chances are considered to be OK. This is different from @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4?!  8.c4!  , when we hit Black's centre much faster. It's crucial to remember to play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1bppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nbd2!  here.   I want to add that  8.c4  is answered by  8...Nb4  ,  demonstrating a key point of the knight move. It makes a lot more sense to preserve the option of c2-c3 when the knight is placed poorly on c6. The current state of theory is quite clear here: the alternatives to 8.Nbd2 don't promise much.Now we'll check some options for Black:   A.  8...Nxd2  9.Bxd2  is the main continuation. Black acknowledges that they can't keep the knight on e4 under reasonable conditions. A small victory for White, leading to a nagging pull.   B.  8...Bf5  9.Re1  Nxd2  10.Qxd2  is a similar story. We keep annoying pressure, as Black has to trade their best piece.   C.  8...Nf6  9.c3  is a worse option than A or B. Retreating the knight is a large concession.   D.  8...f5?  is far too ambitious and immediately punished by  9.c4!  when the position opens while Black is still not well organised. }
8... Bf5 { Black keeps the knight protected for as long as possible. } 9. Re1
{ No surprise here, we wanted more piece pressure on e4. The position after  9.Re1  can also occur via @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bf5  8.Re1  Nc6  9.Nbd2  , a common path. }
9... Nxd2
{ That's clearly the best move. You sometimes meet  9...Nd6  10.Nf1  , but this is a significantly worse version of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bf5  8.Re1  O-O  9.Nbd2  Nd6  .  10.Nf1  ,  which is slightly better for White. The reason is, as usual here, the badly placed knight on c6.   After the better  9...Nxd2  Black also suffers due to this issue, but they get some material traded, at least. }
10. Qxd2
{ We have to avoid  10.Bxf5?  , as  10...Nxf3+  11.Qxf3  Nxd4  is possible. }
10... Bxd3
{ Black is happy to trade some material to ease their defensive task. A funny line is  10...Bg4??  11.Qg5!  , when Black can resign with a clear conscience. }
11. Qxd3 O-O 12. c3
{ We want the pawn on c3 to secure d4 and make the c6-knight look stupid. At first glance, you might think that White does not have much here, but many little things amount to serious pressure. We have the simple idea of playing Bf4 next and doubling on the e-file. Additional ideas that Black always has to watch out for are Qb5 and the pawn advance h4-h5.It is difficult for Black to address all these ideas. Black would be thrilled to improve their knight, but there won't be an opportunity soon, as they need to focus more on fighting for the e-file.Here are some lines to illustrate Black's problems.   A.  12...Bd6?  stops Bf4, but it is a blunder.  13.Ng5!  g6  14.Qh3  h5  15.g4!  and Black is falling apart already. Relatively best is  15...Qd7  16.gxh5  Qxh3  17.Nxh3  gxh5  18.Bf4  Rad8  19.Bxd6  Rxd6  20.Nf4  ,  when we have a fantastic endgame. h5 and d5 are weak, and one of them will fall.   B.  12...h6  stops Ng5 ideas. After  13.Bf4  Bd6  , we have a strong idea  14.Be5!  , when Black is in a tough spot.  14...Bxe5  15.dxe5!  is great for White. We have pressure on d5 @@StartBracket@@Rad1 to come@@EndBracket@@, and a queen move to d7 can be answered with Nh4-f5.Black shouldn't take on e5, but what to do? We can double on the e-file or play Nh4-f5 again if Black gives up control of the h4-square. A general problem of ...h6 in these structures is that it makes ...f6 much harder to play, as Black usually can't afford to weaken the light squares so much.   C.  12...Bf6  is the most popular move in online games, but it does not make much sense, to be honest. The bishop is looking at the well-protected d-pawn and is passive. White keeps a nice advantage with  13.Bf4  Qd7  14.h4  Rfe8  15.h5  ,  when we see a common problem for Black. They can't trade off everything on the e-file, as c7 is hanging in the end.   D.  12...Qd7  is probably Black's best try. After  13.Bf4  a6  14.Re2  Rae8  15.Rae1  Bd8  16.h4  Rxe2  17.Qxe2  White remains in control of the e-file and continues to exert pressure. You see that Black's task is quite depressing. It is no surprise that this line has fallen out of fashion for Black, as White can push without risking anything. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A10) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense – 3.Nxe5 d6 4.Nf3 Nxe4 5.d4 d5 6.Bd3 Be7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The starting move of the Petroff or Russian Defense. I will stick to Petroff, as it is more commonly known in English, I think. }
3. Nxe5
{ I suggest taking the pawn and steering for the classical main line of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.d4  d5  6.Bd3  ,  which aims to play for a small pull from a position of complete safety.   After  3.Nxe5  , Black's main and the best move is  3...d6  , but we need to check  3...Nxe4  , better than its reputation, and the notorious Stafford Gambit  3...Nc6?  , which more or less loses but should be examined to have a good reply ready. }
3... d6 4. Nf3
{ I also had a look at  4.Nd3  , but if Black knows  4...Nxe4  5.Qe2  Qe7  6.Nf4  Nc6  7.Nd5  Nd4!  ,  we'd have absolutely nothing. Black has some alternatives to this forcing line, so it's not like we'd be winning otherwise. The main move 4.Nf3 remains the critical test, so let's stick to it. }
4... Nxe4
{ As explained in the introduction, the main line  5.d4  is our choice. } 5. d4
{ Very natural play. We want to develop our bishop to d3 next and castle kingside. }
5... d5
{ Black plays this logical move almost all the time. I found games with  5...Be7  6.Bd3  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  would transpose to the main line, still@@EndBracket@@, when White is better with playing natural moves. A good move to play early on is h3, stopping ...Bg4. You can do that immediately with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  to make it as simple as possible. Next, we'd castle, play Re1, c4, centralise, and enjoy a nice advantage in space.   Back to  5...d5  ,  when we reach a symmetrical pawn formation, typical of the Petroff. It's fascinating to see that while the pawns are symmetrical, Black is more actively placed on the surface. They have the centralised knight while our knight is still on f3.Our job is to prove that Black's knight is more of a liability than an asset. This is accomplished by exerting pressure on the knight and the supporting pawn d5. We'll discuss this topic more concretely after our next move. We need to develop our f1-bishop and castle for all these plans. }
6. Bd3
{ White's play in the whole 5.d4 line is all about fighting against Black's e4-knight. We want to increase the pressure on the knight and force some concessions. If Black, for example, would be forced to retreat the knight, we'd consider the opening phase successful.Other forms of concessions could be structural. If Black needs to play ...f5 and weaken the e5-square, we'd usually be happy too. This depends a bit more on the concrete position, though.So how do we put pressure on the knight? There are two basic methods:   Attacking the knight with moves like Re1 and Nbd2,Attacking the supporting pawn of the knight by playing our pawn to c4.What is best? That mostly depends on Black's piece configuration. Their setup will not only be defined by the next move but rather by the next two moves; we are going to castle next in all cases. Let's see the overview and have a brief assessment for them.   A.  6...Bd6  is the main line and most popular on all levels. Black develops the bishop to its most active square and focuses on kingside development first. After  7.O-O  Black castles, not yet committing a queenside piece. In this line, we'll play a quick c4 to attack Black's d-pawn.   B. Black can play a more conservative setup based on ...Be7. There are various versions of it, as Black can start with  6...Be7  , or play a move like  6...Nc6  or  6...Bf5  first, and continue with  7.O-O  Be7  to reach the same positions. I'll cover the various ...Be7 ideas via 6...Be7 and point out our possible transpositions from 6...Nc6 or 6...Bf5.This sounds a bit complicated at first, but you'll see that our approach against all ...Be7 versions is essentially the same, so it's not too difficult to master. Against these setups, challenging the knight with piece pressure @@StartBracket@@Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ is the most promising. We'll discuss in the notes to the lines why this approach is better than ideas based on pawn to c4, as in A.C. There is not much else, really. Black usually wants to castle kingside, so playing the bishop to e7 or d6 is natural. I will look at an ambitious line based on ...Nc6 and ...Bg4 that is worth knowing. It's good for White, but only if played properly. }
6... Be7
{ Black decides on a ...Be7-based setup. We'll talk more about Black's intentions after our natural reply when they have a choice. }
7. O-O
{ Let's discuss the strategy against the ...Be7-based setup. As mentioned, there are two basic strategies against the e4-knight: Piece pressure with Re1 and Nbd2 or playing a pawn to c4 to attack the knight's support pawn on d5. What's best here?White has tried both approaches, but the current state of theory is that going for piece pressure against the knight is the most promising. This assessment is based on concrete lines, but there is a certain logic as to why c4-based play is not as effective. With the bishop on e7, Black supports the d-pawn with the queen. If the bishop is on d6, the pawn moves to c4 and threatens to take the d-pawn.   We play this way after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  9.c4!  , when Black needs to protect the pawn immediately. Now compare to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  , when  9.c4  can be answered with  9...Nc6!  ,  as d5 is covered by the queen.Alright, so we focus on piece pressure against the knight by playing moves like Re1 and Nbd2 - how does that translate to concrete lines?   A.  7...O-O  does not commit a minor piece yet. We play  8.Re1  and see how Black reacts. Common is  8...Bf5  , when  9.Nbd2  is the next step, and leads to line B. Black has worse alternatives on move 8, though.   B.  7...Bf5  is also answered with  8.Re1  ,  when Black has a choice again. they can castle @@StartBracket@@may also arise via the A move order@@EndBracket@@ or play ...Nc6, and both will be answered by Nbd2. You see, in those two cases, we'll play Re1 first, followed by Nbd2 most of the time. We get to an important move order issue, option C.   C.  7...Nc6  should be answered with  8.Nbd2!  immediately. The move  8.Re1  allows Black to develop actively with  8...Bg4  ,  a line that we can avoid with the precise move order 8.Nbd2!   D.  7...Bg4?!  is dubious. We answer with  8.c4!  when Black is under serious pressure in the centre. After  8...Nc6  9.cxd5  we transpose to a line mentioned in the notes here:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  7.O-O  Bg4  8.c4!  Be7  9.cxd5  , which is a more common way to reach it. The premature ...Bg4 is the only case of an early c4! in the ...Be7-complex in our repertoire. }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight first before castling or committing the c8-bishop. It's important to understand that the knight's position on c6 is double-edged for Black. It can be well-placed if Black has pressure on d4 @@StartBracket@@this applies mostly when White wants to play c4@@EndBracket@@, but it will often be in bad shape if White plays a pawn to c3. This will be a common pattern later.We need to play the correct move order now. Otherwise, Black can benefit from their early knight jump. }
8. Nbd2
{ It's important to get this move order right. After  8.Re1  Black may go for  8...Bg4  when their chances are considered to be OK. This is different from @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4?!  8.c4!  , when we hit Black's centre much faster. It's crucial to remember to play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1bppp/2n5/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nbd2!  here.   I want to add that  8.c4  is answered by  8...Nb4  ,  demonstrating a key point of the knight move. It makes a lot more sense to preserve the option of c2-c3 when the knight is placed poorly on c6. The current state of theory is quite clear here: the alternatives to 8.Nbd2 don't promise much.Now we'll check some options for Black:   A.  8...Nxd2  9.Bxd2  is the main continuation. Black acknowledges that they can't keep the knight on e4 under reasonable conditions. A small victory for White, leading to a nagging pull.   B.  8...Bf5  9.Re1  Nxd2  10.Qxd2  is a similar story. We keep annoying pressure, as Black has to trade their best piece.   C.  8...Nf6  9.c3  is a worse option than A or B. Retreating the knight is a large concession.   D.  8...f5?  is far too ambitious and immediately punished by  9.c4!  when the position opens while Black is still not well organised. }
8... Nf6
{ If Black needs to return the knight to f6 in the Petroff, it's a sign that something has gone wrong. This case is a textbook example. Let's consider the points after our conceptually important reply. }
9. c3
{ Black's c6-knight is misplaced after this move. It only looks at well-protected spots @@StartBracket@@d4, b4@@EndBracket@@ and has no clear perspective to improve.It is also important to realise that we have a better chance of using the e5-square in the future, and support it adequately. A good way to continue it is by playing Re1 next to prepare Nf1-g3, then consider jumping to e5. }
9... O-O 10. Re1 Bg4
{ A common idea. Black wants to play ...Bh5-g6, trading our strong bishop.   Black could also try  10...Bd6  ,  planning ...Nc6-e7. In this case,  11.Nf1  Ne7  12.Bg5!  Ng6  13.Ne5  is annoying for Black. We have a strong knight on e5 that is not easily challenged - reversed roles, compared to some moves earlier. }
11. Nf1
{ A strong alternative is  11.Qb3  ,  but I want to show that this simple idea is enough to make ...Bg4-h5-g6 unattractive. }
11... Bh5
{ Otherwise, we play Ng3 @@StartBracket@@taking control of h5@@EndBracket@@ and h3 next. }
12. Ng3 Bg6 13. Bf4
{ And Black has not accomplished much. After  13...Bxd3  14.Qxd3  ,  we are ready to play Nf5. All our pieces are focused on the centre and kingside, while Black's c6-knight remains a problem. }
*

