{ Very natural play. We want to develop our bishop to d3 next and castle kingside. }
5... d5
{ Black plays this logical move almost all the time. I found games with  5...Be7  6.Bd3  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  would transpose to the main line, still@@EndBracket@@, when White is better with playing natural moves. A good move to play early on is h3, stopping ...Bg4. You can do that immediately with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  to make it as simple as possible. Next, we'd castle, play Re1, c4, centralise, and enjoy a nice advantage in space.   Back to  5...d5  ,  when we reach a symmetrical pawn formation, typical of the Petroff. It's fascinating to see that while the pawns are symmetrical, Black is more actively placed on the surface. They have the centralised knight while our knight is still on f3.Our job is to prove that Black's knight is more of a liability than an asset. This is accomplished by exerting pressure on the knight and the supporting pawn d5. We'll discuss this topic more concretely after our next move. We need to develop our f1-bishop and castle for all these plans. }
6. Bd3
{ White's play in the whole 5.d4 line is all about fighting against Black's e4-knight. We want to increase the pressure on the knight and force some concessions. If Black, for example, would be forced to retreat the knight, we'd consider the opening phase successful.Other forms of concessions could be structural. If Black needs to play ...f5 and weaken the e5-square, we'd usually be happy too. This depends a bit more on the concrete position, though.So how do we put pressure on the knight? There are two basic methods:   Attacking the knight with moves like Re1 and Nbd2,Attacking the supporting pawn of the knight by playing our pawn to c4.What is best? That mostly depends on Black's piece configuration. Their setup will not only be defined by the next move but rather by the next two moves; we are going to castle next in all cases. Let's see the overview and have a brief assessment for them.   A.  6...Bd6  is the main line and most popular on all levels. Black develops the bishop to its most active square and focuses on kingside development first. After  7.O-O  Black castles, not yet committing a queenside piece. In this line, we'll play a quick c4 to attack Black's d-pawn.   B. Black can play a more conservative setup based on ...Be7. There are various versions of it, as Black can start with  6...Be7  , or play a move like  6...Nc6  or  6...Bf5  first, and continue with  7.O-O  Be7  to reach the same positions. I'll cover the various ...Be7 ideas via 6...Be7 and point out our possible transpositions from 6...Nc6 or 6...Bf5.This sounds a bit complicated at first, but you'll see that our approach against all ...Be7 versions is essentially the same, so it's not too difficult to master. Against these setups, challenging the knight with piece pressure @@StartBracket@@Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ is the most promising. We'll discuss in the notes to the lines why this approach is better than ideas based on pawn to c4, as in A.C. There is not much else, really. Black usually wants to castle kingside, so playing the bishop to e7 or d6 is natural. I will look at an ambitious line based on ...Nc6 and ...Bg4 that is worth knowing. It's good for White, but only if played properly. }
6... Bd6
{ Black develops their bishop to the most active square. A natural move and the most popular on all levels of play. }
7. O-O
{ Both sides castle first, then we discuss our strategy against the ...Bd6 system. }
7... O-O
{ Let's talk about how to play against Black's setup. We want to fight against the e4-knight and the d5-pawn - what's the best way to do it? We can exert piece pressure on the knight @@StartBracket@@Re1, Nbd2@@EndBracket@@ or attack the d-pawn with c4.It turns out that we must fight ...Be7 and ...Bd6 setups differently. Against ...Be7, going for piece pressure is best, while against ...Bd6, we need the c4-move to make progress. Let's illustrate this point by comparison.   A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  9.Nbd2  is one possible line for the ...Be7-systems. Black has no way to reinforce the knight further and needs to play  9...Nd6  ,  which gives us a small advantage.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  9.Nbd2  Re8!  is a big difference. The bishop does not block the e-file, which allows Black to keep the knight on e4. White has already put maximum pressure on e4 and there is no way to remove the intruder on e4. White's strategy has failed.   The consequence is simple: After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  Bf5  , White needs to play  9.c4!  which is the main line of the whole chapter. }
8. Re1
{ I suggest starting with this move, but it is possible to play  8.c4  first. After  8...c6  9.Re1  we'll transpose to lines that are part of the suggested repertoire, as Black has nothing better than  9...Bf5  or  9...Re8  to transpose.   After  8.Re1  , we will consider  8...Bf5  and  8...Re8  , protecting the knight. Black has no good alternatives to these moves. Here are two less effective options.   A.  8...f5?  is awful for Black after  9.c4  c6  10.Nc3  Be6  11.Qb3  ,  when Black's weakened position is very shaky. The early ...f5 never works properly, creating too many weaknesses.   B.  8...Nf6?!  gives up on the idea of the Petroff and accepts playing a French exchange a tempo down. We also see this scenario sometimes in the ...Be7 lines, but not as much here, as Black's job of keeping the knight on e4 is a bit easier. It makes little sense to return when 8...Re8 or 8...Bf5 are obvious alternatives.In any case, I'd suggest meeting  8...Nf6  with  9.Bg5  ,  establishing an annoying pin. The general strategy is playing Nbd2, c3 and Qc2, preparing a later Ne5, if possible. }
8... Re8
{ Black covers the knight with their rook, a natural and popular move. Still, this line has fallen out of fashion on the top level recently. We'll fight 8...Bf5 and 8...Re8 in the same way: by playing c4 and Qb3 next. }
9. c4
{ As explained before, we get nowhere with  9.Nbd2  Bf5!  ,  as Black keeps the knight on e4; we have no way to increase the piece pressure. We need the c-pawn to make headway. }
9... c6 10. Qb3
{ I suggest the same approach against 8...Bf5, too. Our queen joins the action and puts pressure on d5 and the queenside. A key difference between the two versions is that in the case of @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/3b4/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bf5  9.c4  c6  10.Qb3  Black can play  10...Qd7  and protect b7. Here, in the ...Re8 line, Black has not yet developed the bishop and has difficulty doing so.Now it looks like Black's best move is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3ppp/2pb4/3p4/2PPn3/1Q1B1N2/PP3PPP/RNB1R1K1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Na6  , but they have a list of worse to terrible moves that can easily happen. Here's the list:   A.  10...Na6  looks best. We cover it in a trainable.   B.  10...Bg4?  is popular in online games but more or less loses to  11.Nbd2!  - we'll check this move.   C.  10...b6?  is also bad, but the refutation is not trivial. We also check this move.   D.  10...Qb6?  11.Qc2!  is terrible for Black. We threaten c4-c5 and Nc3 when Black is falling apart.  The same idea works in the  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/3b4/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bf5  line - after  9.c4  c6  10.Qb3  Qb6?  11.Qc2  ,  White is winning. The move 11.Qc2! is all you need, so there is no need for a trainable line.   E. @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3ppp/2pb4/3p4/2PPn3/1Q1B1N2/PP3PPP/RNB1R1K1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...h6  is not very obvious, but in all the bad lines above, Bg5 is a common move. After  11.cxd5  cxd5  12.Nc3  Nxc3  13.Rxe8+  Qxe8  14.bxc3  White keeps a nagging edge due to the pressure on b7 and d5. This line is unattractive for Black but likely the second best after the knight move to a6. }
10... Bg4 { An active move, but it fails to the best reply. } 11. Nbd2
{ A cool-headed reply. We are ready to recapture on f3 with the knight now. }
11... Bxf3
{ This is relatively best. Black can't play  11...Nxd2  12.Bxd2  Bxf3  13.gxf3  ,  as all their active pieces are off the board. The back rank is weak, and b7 is hanging. Black is busted here. }
12. Nxf3 Qd7
{ Black had to give up their bishop pair under bad circumstances but is their position that bad? Black is in serious trouble after many moves by White now. }
13. g3
{ It looks a bit odd at first, but this is a strong move! We get rid of the ...Bxh2+ tactic Black uses to defend their d-pawn. We are now threatening to take on d5, which is a simple but effective idea.   The relatively best for Black is  13...dxc4  14.Qxc4  Nf6  now, when  15.Bg5  gives us a dominating position. }
