10... b6
{ This move looks wrong and can be punished brutally. It's not at all trivial, though. }
11. Nc3 { A normal move to attack the knight. } 11... Nxc3
{ The only move, there was too much pressure on e4. Now comes the key moment! }
12. Bg5 { An amazing shot! But doesn't it blunder a piece? } 12... f6
{ Or  12...Rxe1+  13.Rxe1  f6  14.bxc3  fxg5  15.cxd5  c5  16.Qc2  , with a winning attack. We have all the pieces joining, and Black has no development. }
13. bxc3 fxg5 14. Rxe8+ { Here  14.cxd5  also wins. } 14... Qxe8 15. cxd5
{ Or  15.Re1  first, it's about the same thing. Our attack is devastating here. Black's toughest defense after  15.cxd5  is  15...c5  16.Re1  Qh5  17.dxc5  @@StartBracket@@ 17.Re6 is a second, attractive win@@EndBracket@@  17...bxc5  18.Qa4  Bd7  19.Qa5  ,  when Black collapses.I cut these lines relatively short, as I felt that White's overwhelming development looks very convincing, and we should finish this on our own. If you want to explore this more, it's a fun exercise to enter the position after 12.Bg5!! into your computer and try to beat the engine with White. This is not so easy, as you may imagine! A human opponent will likely fall apart immediately. }
