12... cxd5 13. a3
{ We follow the game Levon Aronian - Arjun Erigaisi, Kolkata 2021. I like the move a3, as we play against the a6-knight. Black can't use ...Nb4 ideas now and will likely need to reroute the piece via c7.   Erigaisi played the logical move  13...Nc7  , but it might not be best. Stockfish wants to defend with  13...h6  ,  when we have some choice of ideas that are all marginally better for White:   A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1q1pp1/n2b3p/3p1b2/3Pn3/PQ1BBN2/1P3PPP/RN2R1K1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nbd2  is possible when  14...Nxd2  15.Bxd2  Bxd3  16.Qxd3  Nc7  17.Qb3  Qb5  18.Re3  is a small pull. It looks tougher if Black doesn't capture d2, but we can always claim a little something due to the a6-knight.   B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1q1pp1/n2b3p/3p1b2/3Pn3/PQ1BBN2/1P3PPP/RN2R1K1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bb5  Qd8  15.Bf1  is a sophisticated idea. We first push the queen back and then retreat the bishop. Our intention is Nc3 next, for instance, after  15...Nc7  16.Nc3  Nxc3  17.bxc3  b6  18.Ne5  , we'd again have a small pull. }
13... Nc7
{ Probably the most logical move and played by Erigaise in the game. Aronian continued with  14.Bf1  now, but the computer suggestion  14.Qc2  looks stronger, indeed. }
14. Qc2
{ This looks better than Aronian's move. Our idea is Nc3 next, increasing the pressure on the knight. Black also has to reckon with Nh4 in some cases. }
14... Rfe8 { A natural move to support the knight. } 15. Nc3
{ White keeps a pull, based on our more active pieces. A key idea in the position is the move Nh4 to attack the supporting bishop. Often, we'd get the bishop pair, as the bishop can't leave its role of covering e4.I do not doubt that a computer vs computer game would always end in a draw here. But between humans, it's a different story. We can always put some pressure on Black and risk very little.I think the move 11.Be3 is a good way to tackle the main line. It's low-risk and still asks some subtle questions. It also has some surprise value, as it is not the main line @@StartBracket@@yet@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A11) 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ In this chapter, we examine the sidelines of the Open Games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  , when Black avoids the two main choices  2...Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  , the topics of the previous chapters.  Are there any good alternatives for Black? Well, not really. I'd describe them as 'The Not Great, The Bad, and The Ugly' to borrow a title idea from one of my favourite movies. Let's look at what we'll check:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  , the Philidor Defence. After  3.d4  exd4!  we reach the 'Not Great' line of this chapter. Black is worse, but it's a playable line.  Black's alternatives on move three are of the 'The Bad' type.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5?  is the Elephant Gambit. All openings named after animals are bad; this one is no exception. Not sure if I'd put it in the 'The Bad' or 'The Ugly' category used above - in any case, we are happy to see it on the board.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...f5?  leads to the Latvian Gambit. No doubt here: this one belongs into the 'The Ugly' category. Black weakens their king position and will usually not survive the opening phase if we play well.  We will cover these three moves with trainable lines. Other moves don't warrant any deeper study, as following standard opening principles will be enough to know: develop pieces, control the center, and get castled quickly.  In the first edition, I devoted some space to the refutation of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...f6?  , the Damiano. It is refuted by  3.Nxe5  , but even the prosaic @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp2pp/5p2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  is enough. Black's king is weakened beyond repair. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A11) 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5
{ Latvia has a great Chess history and was the home of maybe the most fascinating World Champion, Michail Tal.   Sadly, the Latvian Gambit is such a bad opening. It does not develop a piece but instead weakens the king beyond repair. Let's look at how to refute it. }
3. Nxe5
{ White has good alternatives, but taking the pawn is the best and simplest solution. }
3... Qf6
{ By far Black's main move.   They sometimes try the crazy-looking  3...Nc6  , which invites the queen to check on h5. Well,  4.Qh5+  g6  5.Nxg6  objectively wins for White but can be tricky to handle, particularly in fast time controls.   A good practical solution is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp2pp/2n5/4Np2/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d4  , playing for simple development. Black still suffers from all the weaknesses and is in terrible shape. }
4. d4 { I prefer this over the good alternative  4.Nc4  . } 4... d6 5. Nc4 fxe4
{ Black has recovered the pawn, at least. } 6. Nc3
{ We have a huge lead in development and attack Black's e-pawn. } 6... Qg6
{ Black covers the pawn and clears the way for the knight to f6.   Sometimes, Black tries the strange  6...Qf7  here. Doesn't this blunder the e-pawn? Well, after  7.Nxe4  Qe6  White loses a piece... but  8.f3  d5  9.Ne5  dxe4  10.Bc4  leads to a smashing attack that Black won't survive.   This is fun, but  6...Qf7  can also be refuted by the less spectacular  7.Ne3  Nf6  8.f3  . It looks quite similar to our concept against the more popular queen move to g6. }
7. f3
{ This is important. The best approach against the Latvian, or any other shady gambit, is to focus on your attack rather than grabbing material. Here White opens up everything while Black is underdeveloped. }
7... exf3
{ There is no good alternative for Black.   A.  7...Nf6  8.fxe4  Nxe4  9.Bd3  wins material.   B.  7...Be7  hints at the check on h4, but  8.Nxe4  d5  9.Ne5  wins easily. }
8. Qxf3
{ And White has all the fun with the better development and the open lines to use it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A11) 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ Black goes for the Elephant Gambit. I already got the joke in that all openings named after animals are bad, so let's move on and see how to tame the Elephant. }
3. exd5
{ We grab on d5, which looks best.   Now  3...Qxd5  4.Nc3  , followed by d4, gives White a huge advantage by simple means. We get a wide open position with a huge development lead. }
3... e4
{ That is Black's main try.   Sometimes you meet  3...Bd6  , but a simple line like  4.d4  e4  5.Ne5  keeps our extra pawn without any compensation for Black. }
4. Qe2
{ This is important to remember. After a knight move, Black would be in good shape. }
4... Nf6
{ Black covers the attacked e-pawn. Now White has more than one way to gain a clear plus. My recommendation from the first edition is easy to learn and convincing. }
5. d3
{ A good alternative is  5.Nc3  Be7  6.Nxe4  , but it can get a bit murky in some lines.  My recommendation from the first edition is simpler to handle, in my mind. }
5... Qxd5 6. Nbd2
{ We avoid  6.Nc3?!  Bb4!  , which seems reasonable for Black. Now Black has no way to keep the e-pawn. }
6... Nc6
{ The move  6...Bf5  fails to the simple  7.Ng5  or the engine's suggestion @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3q1b2/4p3/3P1N2/PPPNQPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.dxe4  Bxe4  8.Ng5  Qxg5  9.Nxe4  , which is even more devastating. }
7. dxe4 Qh5 8. Qb5
{ I like this move a lot. It is powerful objectively and robs Black of any fun ideas they might have had when venturing the Gambit. The best-case outcome for our opponent is a rotten endgame now. }
8... Bc5
{ The relatively best try, keeping queens on the board for the moment. We can insist on the trade, though. }
9. Nb3 { This forces the following sequence. } 9... Nxe4
{ Okay, Black got the pawn back. But this is not the end of the story. } 10.
Be3 { We attack the bishop a third time, forcing Black's reply. } 10... Bb4+
{ The only move, as  10...a6??  11.Qc4!  wins a piece on the spot. The bishop and knight are hanging - bad luck! }
11. c3 Qxb5 12. Bxb5 Bd6
{ Black has managed to avoid immediate material losses, but our next move highlights that our opponent is still in terrible shape. }
13. Nfd4
{ Now Black's pawn structure gets destroyed. White is much better, and Black has no active play - certainly not what Black had in mind when going for a 'fun' gambit.   13.Na5  is a similar idea and just as strong. }
