[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A11) 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The starting move of the Philidor Defence. Black covers their central pawn but restricts the f8-bishop.   After our natural reply  3.d4  , Black has a wide choice of moves, of which only  3...exd4  is somewhat respectable. }
3. d4
{ We immediately attack the e5-pawn again, trying to force the capture on d4. This approach is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  d6  4.d4  , where ...d6 is answered similarly.   It's instructive to compare these scenarios with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  , when  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  Bb4  highlights the difference: Black can develop their bishop actively. After the early ...d6, the bishop remains passive, and our immediate d4-push gets stronger.   After  3.d4  , Black's best move is  3...exd4  , but they have a long list of bad options to check. Here's an overview of them:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  is best for Black, as mentioned.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd7?!  4.Bc4!  is excellent for White.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg4?  4.dxe5  is known from the famous Morphy Opera game and is much better for White. We'll examine these with trainables. There are some more moves, but they don't warrant closer study.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5?  is a reckless move that can be refuted in many ways, the best being  4.Bc4  , but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp3pp/3p4/4pp2/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exf5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp3pp/3p4/4pp2/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  will lead to a large advantage, too.  E. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  is best answered by  4.Bb5  , transposing to the Ruy Lopez Steinitz, which is excellent for White.  F. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.dxe5  Nxe4  5.Qd5  Nc5  6.Bg5  is good for White, but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  is a pragmatic solution. After  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nbd7  5.Rg1  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  , we'd transpose to lines that are all promising for White, too. }
3... Nd7 { This is quite popular at club level/online play, but quite bad. } 4.
Bc4
{ This is stronger than  4.Nc3  Ngf6  , transposing to a variation we reach via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  4.Nf3  Nbd7  - not bad, but the bishop move is even better.  We immediately put pressure on the weak f7-spot and pose some concrete problems. Black now has various ways to go wrong, which often happens in practice!   We'll now examine @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppn1ppp/3p4/4p3/2BPP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  , played most frequently, and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppn1ppp/3p4/4p3/2BPP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be7?  , a common mistake. }
4... Be7
{ A widespread mistake! This move has been played 1000s of times, even by GMs in classical time control games.   Besides 4...Be7?, there are several other ways for Black to go wrong. Here are four additional examples:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppn1ppp/3p4/4p3/2BPP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ngf6?  5.dxe5  dxe5  6.Ng5  is painful!  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppn1ppp/3p4/4p3/2BPP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ngf6?  5.dxe5  Nxe5  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Bxf7+!  wins a pawn.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppn1ppp/3p4/4p3/2BPP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...h6?  5.dxe5  Nxe5  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Bxf7+!  is a similar story.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppn1ppp/3p4/4p3/2BPP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...h6?  5.dxe5  dxe5  6.Bxf7+!  leads to a crushing attack after  6...Kxf7  7.Nxe5+  Kf6  8.Nc3!  Black's king is in the middle of the board and will not survive. A fun line goes  8...Kxe5  9.Qd5+  Kf6  10.Qf5+  Ke7  11.Nd5+  Kd6  12.Bf4+  Kc6  13.Qe6+  Bd6  14.Nb4+  Kb6  15.Bxd6  Ndf6  16.Bc5+  Kxc5  17.Nd3+  Qxd3  18.Qe5+  , and it's over! }
5. dxe5
{ We follow a concrete idea: open up the queen's path to d5.   Black now has to take with the knight, as  5...dxe5??  6.Qd5!  is even worse... }
5... Nxe5 6. Nxe5 { Our point becomes clear on the next move. } 6... dxe5 7.
Qh5 { Simple Chess! That's it for the important e5-pawn. } 7... g6 8. Qxe5 Nf6
9. Bh6
{ Black has lost their central pawn, and the king is stuck in the center. We have an overwhelming advantage. }
