ch is excellent for White.  F. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.dxe5  Nxe4  5.Qd5  Nc5  6.Bg5  is good for White, but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  is a pragmatic solution. After  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nbd7  5.Rg1  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  , we'd transpose to lines that are all promising for White, too. }
3... Bg4 { Well known from Morphy's famous Opera game... and bad. } 4. dxe5
{ We capture the pawn and force the issue. Black now has to take on f3 or sacrifice the pawn. }
4... Bxf3 { Black keeps the pawn but is in terrible shape anyway. } 5. Qxf3
dxe5 6. Bc4 { Threatening mate on f7 is always fun. } 6... Qf6
{ Morphy's famous Opera game continued with  6...Nf6?  7.Qb3!  , when White is already winning due to the double attack on f7 and b7. }
7. Qb3
{ The early bishop move to g4 as weakened Black's queenside. They have no good way to defend now. }
7... b6 8. Nc3
{ And White is close to winning already. Can Black stop our idea Nd5? } 8... c6
9. Nd5 { Nope! We can play it anyway, as the following line shows. } 9... cxd5
10. Bb5+ Ke7
{ It's all over now.   10....Nd7  11.Bxd7+  Kxd7+  12.Qxd5+  wins easily, too. }
11. Qxd5
{ Black can't even save their extra material here, and we have a decisive attack on top. }
