ch is excellent for White.  F. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.dxe5  Nxe4  5.Qd5  Nc5  6.Bg5  is good for White, but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  is a pragmatic solution. After  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nbd7  5.Rg1  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  , we'd transpose to lines that are all promising for White, too. }
3... exd4
{ This is the only good move for Black if they continue with the following setup: ...Nf6/...Be7/...O-O. We'll see that White retains an advantage, but it's a game. }
4. Nxd4
{ The natural recapture.   We don't want to allow  4.Qxd4  Nc6  with a tempo gain on our queen. }
4... Nf6
{ The natural move, attacking the e-pawn. Other moves have no independent significance:   A.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  Bd7  leads to a favourable Ruy Lopez Steinitz.  6.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@intending Bf4, Qd2 and O-O-O@@EndBracket@@ is strong.   B.  4...g6  5.Nc3  will likely transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  , which gives us a dangerous attack. }
5. Nc3
{ We cover our pawn and wait for Black to decide on a defensive setup. We'll examine  5...Be7  , which seems best, and the more ambitious but dubious  5...g6  , an idea of the Great Dane, Bent Larsen.   A third rarely-played move is  5...Nc6  , when  6.Bb5  again transposes to a good line of the Ruy Lopez Steinitz. }
5... g6
{ This was a pet line of Danish legend Bent Larsen, but it has a somewhat shady reputation today. White's attacking formation, reminiscent of the Sicilian Dragon, is straightforward to play. }
6. Be3
{ We aim for the formation Be3, Qd2 and O-O-O and then will decide how to attack the kingside. }
6... Bg7
{ The move  6...Ng4  leads nowhere due to  7.Bf4  - we can still castle quickly with Qd2 and O-O-O next. }
7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O
{ Compared to the Sicilian Dragon, Black lacks the open c-file for counterplay. It's also not easy to get the queenside pawns involved. Moving the c-pawn, for instance, would weaken d6 substantially. }
8... Nc6
{ The alternative  8...Re8  9.f3  a6  tries to set the queenside pawns in motion. We have various good attacking ideas; here is one of them:  10.g4  b5  11.Bh6  b4  12.Bxg7  Kxg7  13.Nce2  with h4/Ng3 to come. Our job is much easier in these structures - attack with maximum force. }
9. f3
{ We stabilize our center and cover the g4-square. This not only stops ...Ng4 but prepares the push of our g-pawn. }
9... Nxd4 { Black trades to involve their c-pawn in the game. } 10. Bxd4 Be6
11. g4 c5
{ This spells doom for the d-pawn, but Black can't just sit and wait. Slow moves are met with the simple kingside pawn storm h4-h5. }
12. Be3 Qa5 13. Bh6
{ We are much better here. White is better in the center and enjoys attacking prospects on the kingside. What does Black have? }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A11) 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 d6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The starting move of the Philidor Defence. Black covers their central pawn but restricts the f8-bishop.   After our natural reply  3.d4  , Black has a wide choice of moves, of which only  3...exd4  is somewhat respectable. }
3. d4
{ We immediately attack the e5-pawn again, trying to force the capture on d4. This approach is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  d6  4.d4  , where ...d6 is answered similarly.   It's instructive to compare these scenarios with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  , when  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  Bb4  highlights the difference: Black can develop their bishop actively. After the early ...d6, the bishop remains passive, and our immediate d4-push gets stronger.   After  3.d4  , Black's best move is  3...exd4  , but they have a long list of bad options to check. Here's an overview of them:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  is best for Black, as mentioned.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd7?!  4.Bc4!  is excellent for White.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg4?  4.dxe5  is known from the famous Morphy Opera game and is much better for White. We'll examine these with trainables. There are some more moves, but they don't warrant closer study.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5?  is a reckless move that can be refuted in many ways, the best being  4.Bc4  , but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp3pp/3p4/4pp2/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exf5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp3pp/3p4/4pp2/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  will lead to a large advantage, too.  E. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  is best answered by  4.Bb5  , transposing to the Ruy Lopez Steinitz, which is excellent for White.  F. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.dxe5  Nxe4  5.Qd5  Nc5  6.Bg5  is good for White, but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  is a pragmatic solution. After  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nbd7  5.Rg1  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  , we'd transpose to lines that are all promising for White, too. }
3... exd4
{ This is the only good move for Black if they continue with the following setup: ...Nf6/...Be7/...O-O. We'll see that White retains an advantage, but it's a game. }
4. Nxd4
{ The natural recapture.   We don't want to allow  4.Qxd4  Nc6  with a tempo gain on our queen. }
4... Nf6
{ The natural move, attacking the e-pawn. Other moves have no independent significance:   A.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  Bd7  leads to a favourable Ruy Lopez Steinitz.  6.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@intending Bf4, Qd2 and O-O-O@@EndBracket@@ is strong.   B.  4...g6  5.Nc3  will likely transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  , which gives us a dangerous attack. }
5. Nc3
{ We cover our pawn and wait for Black to decide on a defensive setup. We'll examine  5...Be7  , which seems best, and the more ambitious but dubious  5...g6  , an idea of the Great Dane, Bent Larsen.   A third rarely-played move is  5...Nc6  , when  6.Bb5  again transposes to a good line of the Ruy Lopez Steinitz. }
5... Be7
{ Black's best bet in the Philidor. The plan is castling quickly, then exerting pressure on e4 with ...Re8 and ...Bf8. If White is not careful, Black may manage the move ...d5, freeing the position completely. }
6. g3
{ It looks like White has two good options against 5...Be7 and they are fundamentally different.   A.  6.Bf4  , preparing Qd2 and O-O-O, is strong. There are, however, some crazy complications ahead that require detailed study. Some of those lines are nice for White, but one misstep may lead to problems. It's worth checking out if you like to analyze sharp complications, but I felt it is unwarranted for our repertoire approach.   B. The strategically minded move  6.g3  is just as promising but entirely different. White immediately tries to increase control over d5 - this is logical as Black's play is based on a quick ...d6-d5 in most cases. The quick ...d5 break solves Black's problems in many lines, for example, after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  O-O  7.Qd2  d5!  - our fianchetto serves as a prophylaxis against this concept.   After  6.g3  , we need to check  6...d5  @@StartBracket@@principled, but bad@@EndBracket@@ and the better @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  , when  7.Bg2  makes sure that ...d5 is not happening any time soon. }
6... d5
{ This is the most principled move, but it fails for concrete reasons. Let's check why Black's desired pawn break is ultimately insufficient. }
7. e5 { This is the best move, pushing Black's knight to a bad square. } 7...
Ng4
{ This is relatively best. The alternatives are easily dealt with:   A.  7...Nfd7  8.Nf5  is terrible for Black. Too many pawns are attacked.   B.  7...Ne4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Bg2  is good for White, too. Black's e-pawn is too weak, for example, after  9...Qd5  10.O-O  Nc6  11.Nxc6  Qxc6  12.Re1  Bf5  13.c3  , with Qe2 or Qc2 to follow. }
8. Bg2
{ The best move, even though  8.e6  looks very tempting. A closer look shows that  8...Nf6  9.exf7+  Kxf7  is not that bad for Black. Our choice is more effective and forces Black to be very precise.   Black's best bet is now to either immediately take on e5 or play @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/8/3pP3/3N2n1/2N3P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...O-O  9.O-O  Nxe5  , with similar consequences.   The alternative  8...c6?  is much worse, but we need to know the refutation. }
8... c6
{ This is dubious because the knight on g4 is lacking squares after White covers e5. We should get a large advantage with precise play. }
9. Bf4 { I don't see a good reply for Black now. } 9... g5
{ The only critical move to check.   A line like  9...O-O  10.h3  Nh6  11.Bxh6  is too ugly for Black to contemplate. }
10. e6
{ This is strong and necessary to refute Black's play. The g4-knight is under attack and only has a desperado left to irritate us. }
10... Nxf2 11. exf7+ Kf8 { Here  11...Kxf7  12.Qh5+  is even worse. } 12. Kxf2
gxf4 13. Rf1
{ White has three moves here that lead to a crushing attack:  13.Rf1  ,  13.Re1  @@StartBracket@@both preparing Kg1@@EndBracket@@  and  13.Nce2  , transferring the knight to the kingside. }
*

