{ This is the only good move for Black if they continue with the following setup: ...Nf6/...Be7/...O-O. We'll see that White retains an advantage, but it's a game. }
4. Nxd4
{ The natural recapture.   We don't want to allow  4.Qxd4  Nc6  with a tempo gain on our queen. }
4... Nf6
{ The natural move, attacking the e-pawn. Other moves have no independent significance:   A.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  Bd7  leads to a favourable Ruy Lopez Steinitz.  6.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@intending Bf4, Qd2 and O-O-O@@EndBracket@@ is strong.   B.  4...g6  5.Nc3  will likely transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  , which gives us a dangerous attack. }
5. Nc3
{ We cover our pawn and wait for Black to decide on a defensive setup. We'll examine  5...Be7  , which seems best, and the more ambitious but dubious  5...g6  , an idea of the Great Dane, Bent Larsen.   A third rarely-played move is  5...Nc6  , when  6.Bb5  again transposes to a good line of the Ruy Lopez Steinitz. }
5... Be7
{ Black's best bet in the Philidor. The plan is castling quickly, then exerting pressure on e4 with ...Re8 and ...Bf8. If White is not careful, Black may manage the move ...d5, freeing the position completely. }
6. g3
{ It looks like White has two good options against 5...Be7 and they are fundamentally different.   A.  6.Bf4  , preparing Qd2 and O-O-O, is strong. There are, however, some crazy complications ahead that require detailed study. Some of those lines are nice for White, but one misstep may lead to problems. It's worth checking out if you like to analyze sharp complications, but I felt it is unwarranted for our repertoire approach.   B. The strategically minded move  6.g3  is just as promising but entirely different. White immediately tries to increase control over d5 - this is logical as Black's play is based on a quick ...d6-d5 in most cases. The quick ...d5 break solves Black's problems in many lines, for example, after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  O-O  7.Qd2  d5!  - our fianchetto serves as a prophylaxis against this concept.   After  6.g3  , we need to check  6...d5  @@StartBracket@@principled, but bad@@EndBracket@@ and the better @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  , when  7.Bg2  makes sure that ...d5 is not happening any time soon. }
6... O-O
{ This solid line is best for Black, but natural moves give us a slight pull. }
7. Bg2
{ Now it's going to be very tough for Black to engineer ...d5. They are more or less limited to a sit-and-wait strategy. }
7... Re8 { Black completes their ...Re8/...Bf8 is regrouping first. } 8. O-O
Bf8 { Black's setup is compact and solid but rather passive. } 9. h3
{ Our setup controls d5 reliably, so this freeing advance is not available to Black without due preparation. 9.h3 is a fine move that controls g4 and prepares to expand on the kingside. }
9... c6 10. g4
{ This may be the start of an attack with g5 and f4 to come, but it is versatile. Giving the bishop on c1 a good post on g3 makes sense, too. This is the option I prefer if Black continues to wait. }
10... d5
{ Otherwise, Bf4/Qd2/Rad1 are easy moves to follow up with, putting more pressure on the center. }
11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Bf4
{ With a very comfortable edge. Black has a huge development disadvantage, and Nb5 is a threat. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B1) Sicilian – Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "Sicilian – Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and welcome to the coverage of the Sicilian Defense.  The most popular replies to 1.e4 are the symmetrical 1...e5 and the Sicilian 1...c5. Depending on the stats you use, one of them is the most played move. You can expect the Sicilian in 30-40% of your games, which also explains why we need to cover it in detail. It's a significant opening, as it is sound, complex, and frequently played. }
2. Nf3
{ White has many options against the Sicilian, but only a few are considered critical tests. For the first edition, I decided to recommend an approach based on Bb5 lines @@StartBracket@@Rossolimo @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , Moscow  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@, combined with a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  c3  , for example@@EndBracket@@. This set of lines is challenging for Black but keeps our learning effort at reasonable proportions.  When I decided to suggest the Ruy Lopez in the second edition, the idea of sticking with this framework of lines became even more compelling. Many lines in the Rossolimo and Moscow lead to positions with Ruy Lopez characteristics. Let's have an overview of the chapters and talk about their contents. We play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  , when Black's second move leads to a split. Black's plays  2...d6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  about 30%-40% of the time, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  occurs in about 15-20% of the games, while others account for about 10%.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  Bd7  . The reply 3...Bd7 is Black's most popular reply to our check. After  4.Bxd7+  , we'll often reach a comfortable position in the so-called Maroczy Bind structure, which controls the center reliably. Black's position is sound, but we usually reach a small plus and low risk.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5+  Nd7  . Black may also play 3...Nd7 to answer our check. I recommend  4.c3  and d4 soon, leading to structures similar to a Ruy Lopez. In this chapter, Black's best lines get them close to equality, but the positions are interesting and might not be the type of game they wanted. It looks like a Ruy, not a Sicilian.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  . Against 2...Nc6 I suggest 3.Bb5, the Rossolimo. The Rossolimo is White's main weapon against 2...Nc6 and promises a small advantage. Black's main reply is  3...g6  , when  4.O-O  Bg7  5.Re1  Nf6  6.c3  is the main line. I have changed my recommendation to 6.c3, compared to 6.e5 of the first edition. The new line is even more promising and fits better to the Ruy style theme of playing c3&d4 to occupy the center.   D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  . We cover Black's two other main replies to the Rossolimo in this chapter. In both cases, we play O-O, Re1 and play to build a center with c3&d4, if allowed.   E. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Others. Black's rare and mostly dubious replies to the Rossolimo are covered here.   F. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  d5  and Others. Against 2...e6, I suggest playing 3.c3, a delayed Alapin. I like to play c3 on the third move, as Black's move ...e6 has limited their choice of defense. In this chapter, we cover 3...d5 and related systems. White has good chances for a small pull.   G. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  Nf6  . The second chapter on 2...e6 3.c3 covers 3...Nf6, which looks like Black's best reply. I suggest a lesser-known reply that scores well in practice. Black should be close to equality with perfect play, but they often fail.   H. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Others. Black rarely goes for a different move than 2...d6, 2...Nc6 or 2...e6. These rare lines are covered in this chapter. The most important ones are  2...g6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  , when 3.c3 is our choice.  Compared to the first edition, the framework of lines looks the same. There are several changes in all chapters, though. The goal was to improve the repertoire on all accounts. If you know the first edition, you will recognize the overall spirit and most of the lines, but it's all neatly organized and has fresh paint! 😀 }
