[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B2) Sicilian – Moscow 3...Bd7"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Our choice against  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  is the Moscow Variation  3.Bb5+  , when Black's most solid reply is  3...Bd7  , allowing the bishop to trade. This line is the subject of the current chapter.  After  4.Bxd7+  , there is an important split between the two recaptures. The theoretically more complex option is  4...Qxd7  , when we play  5.c4  to strive for a Maroczy Bind center.  After @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd7  , we need to be more flexible and will adjust our pawn formation according to the next moves.  We'll start with the knight recapture and then focus on @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd7  , which requires more study. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+
{ This is the main move and is still my recommendation.  For the second edition, I also considered switching to  4.c4  , but ultimately decided to stick with my old move. My main issue about  4.c4  is that some of the arising positions are difficult to understand. I also felt that the theoretical state of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1bpppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxd7+  is fine, and I found some interesting, new ideas to present. Let's get to work.  Black has two moves after our capture, leading to different scenarios:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd7  is the main line and answered by  5.c4  when we play for the Maroczy Bind after a later d2-d4. After the queen's capture, we immediately know what pawn formation we reach.   B. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxd7  is a different story. In this line, being more flexible is best. My recommendations after the knight capture differ significantly from the first edition, much more than in line A. }
