{ Black plays this move almost all the time, and only on the next move decides if they want to play with ...e6 or ...g6. It's possible to start with one of the pawn moves and play ...Ngf6 later, of course.   A key point to remember is that we want to answer ...g6-based setups with c3&d4, building a perfect pawn center. That would happen after @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  6.c3!  Bg7  7.d4  , when White has a comfortable game, based on the strong center.  We will examine @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ngf6  6.Qe2  g6  7.c3!  in a moment, which will demonstrate this concept. Therefore I decided not to include a trainable line for @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  , as we'll examine this type of position anyway. }
6. Qe2
{ This looks like the most promising setup. Our e-pawn needed protection, which limited our choice.  We don't want to commit our d-pawn with  6.d3  or block the c-pawn by going  6.Nc3  .  This leaves  6.Re1  or our choice, the queen move.  6.Re1  is not bad, but I prefer the queen move because it gives us more flexibility regarding the later rook placement. We will also see that pushing the e-pawn is better supported by the queen, if Black opts for ...g6.   Now we'll examine the two most popular moves in detail:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  is Black's most popular move. Compared to the first edition, I have a new and interesting suggestion against it.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  is also frequently played but makes our task easier. After  7.c3!  we manage to build a strong center, and Black needs to be careful to avoid serious trouble.  Some words about other options:  C. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e5?!  is a bad idea. We are better after  7.c3  , intending d4,  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1n1ppp/3p1n2/2p1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq e6 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c4  , when we reach a much better version of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1Bpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd7  5.c4  e5  - Black's knight is misplaced on d7. We'll examine a similar scenario in line A when Black can opt for ...e5 some moves later.   D. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Rc8  is a good waiting move. Black does not yet commit to a central pawn formation but mostly aims for a ...g6 setup under better circumstances than option B. One example would be  7.c4  , when  7...g6  is better than on move 6, as c3&d4 is out of the window. Now it is interesting to see that  8.Nc3  Bg7  9.d4?!  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Qa5  gives Black good counterplay against White's queenside. I think a good and easy-to-play solution is @@StartFEN@@2rqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1PQPPP/R1B2RK1 w k - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.d3  when we aim for the plan Bd2, Rb1 and b4 to open the queenside. We also play a setup based on c4 and d3 in line A. This is a similar idea. }
6... e6
{ This setup, based on ...e6, is Black's most popular one. Black aims for flexible development and waits for our decision on how to play in the center.Against an early d4, they want to capture the pawn and start counterplay on the c-file, the standard Sicilian Defence idea.If White prepares d4 with c3, aiming for the full pawn center, Black is ready to play a well-timed ...d5 break. This changes the pawn structure and gives it a French flavour. Black has already traded their c8-bishop, though, which helps a lot. I am not a fan of playing c3&d4 if Black has this option.  How do we continue? }
7. b3
{ I have changed my recommendation from the first edition. My original suggestion was  7.d4  , but I see a practical problem with this move. After  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  we intend to play a quick c4, establishing a Maroczy Bind. This is possible, but Black has many move orders to choose from and may start a direct counterplay against c4. A sample line is  8...Be7  9.c4  and now  9...Qa5  ,  which I didn't consider in the first edition. Black wants to play ...Rc8/...Qb4/...Ne5 in various combinations. I don't think White is in trouble here, but playing this setup is more difficult than I previously thought.   I wondered if White has any alternatives and noticed that @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1n1ppp/3ppn2/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.b3  is a popular option which is much easier to handle, in my mind. We actively develop the bishop to b2 and still retain the option to play for a Maroczy-style center with a later c4&d4. We'll see that we have more ideas, though - hang on. }
7... Be7
{ Black prepares castling, and we complete our fianchetto, very natural play. }
8. Bb2 O-O
{ Now we need to commit to a central pawn structure, at least partially. } 9.
c4
{ This looks best to me. We gain some influence in the center and keep the option to play d2-d4 to play for a Maroczy Bind.  This general concept, however, can be difficult to realise against a cunning opponent. It's Black to move now, and they have a wide choice. In SOME cases, not all of them, they can meet our d4 break with ...d5!, a strong counterpunch. Two examples are @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Rc8  10.d4  d5!  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Re8  10.d4  d5!  , when Black gets equal chances and manages to trade lots of material.  I'm not too fond of these lines - we need a different idea against these moves. Black does not play the rook moves all of the time, though. They regularly go for @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...a6  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  , for example. Quite shockingly, even after @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  10.d4  d5!?  is possible, as  10.exd5  exd5  11.Qxe7??  Rfe8  traps our queen! I think you already suspect what I am getting at.   Black has many moves, and the various versions of White's d4 being met with ...d5 are confusing! After studying the lines more, I realised that White has a fundamentally different approach in this position: you don't need to play the move d2-d4 but can opt for a slow setup involving the moves Nc3 and d3. The later plan is moving the f3-knight and going for f2-f4. The charm of this setup is that it works well, regardless of Black's move order!   I will examine two moves now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Rc8  to demonstrate the Nc3/d3 plan - it also works against other, non-committal moves like  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...a6  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Re8  - more on that in the notes.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/2P1P3/1P3N2/PB1PQPPP/RN3RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...e5  is an entirely different approach that I want to check. Black sometimes goes for this central block to stop d2-d4 completely. We didn't intend this move @@StartBracket@@line A@@EndBracket@@, but Black might still want to avoid it. }
9... Rc8
{ The slow plan I am suggesting works against this move. But it is also possible against the other 'small moves, like  9...a6  or  9...Re8  . Black will often combine them in various orders. }
10. d3
{ We go for the slow setup I described earlier. The idea is to complete development with Nc3 next and then aim for Ne1/d2 and f4. }
10... a6 11. Nc3
{ I think that playing  11.Nbd2  here also looks fine. There is room for creativity here, as there is no direct contact between both sides' forces.  One important point to mention is that Black can't do much to change the pawn structure, which gives us the time to play in a relatively slow fashion. For example, they can't easily play ...d5, as we have the strong reply e4-e5. }
11... Qa5
{ This move was recently played @@StartBracket@@2022@@EndBracket@@ by top Indian GM Vidit in an online game against GM Swiercz. Black prepares ...b5 this way.   There are many alternatives for Black, of course. An interesting one is  11...Ne5  , when  12.Nxe5  dxe5  13.f4  exf4  14.Rxf4  Nd7  15.e5!  @@StartBracket@@stopping ...Bf6@@EndBracket@@ looks best and slightly better for White. We have a large space advantage and easy improvements like Ne4 and Raf1 to pile up on the f-file. Black likely needs to play ...f6, which creates some weaknesses. If Black plays further waiting moves, going for the Nd2&f4 plan looks promising. }
12. Nd2
{ We prepare f4, which gains lots of space. Now Black needs to be quite careful. }
12... b5
{ This is - surprisingly - a mistake.   Black should play  12...Ne5  13.f4  Nc6  14.Nf3  , when I prefer White, but Black's chances are not significantly worse. One idea for White is playing e4-e5 to clear the e4-square for our knight. This may quickly turn into a dangerous attack, as most of our pieces point to Black's kingside. }
13. f4
{ It turns out that playing ...b5 didn't help Black much to get counterplay. Taking on c4 nets nothing and advancing the pawn further closes the queenside.   The game Swiercz-Vidit continued with  13...b4  14.Nd1  Qc7  15.Ne3  a5  16.g4  , when White had a strong and probably winning attack. He later spoiled the game @@StartBracket@@it was blitz@@EndBracket@@ but had his strong opponent on the ropes. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B2) Sicilian – Moscow 3...Bd7"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Bd7 4.Bxd7+ Qxd7 5.c4 Qg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ This move signals that Black will play ...Nc6 most of the time to emphasise control over d4. This is most often combined with a kingside fianchetto. }
5. c4
{ A strategically very sound choice. White places his pawns on light squares after this bishop has been traded off. We are aiming for a Maroczy Bind structure, giving White comfortable control.  What options and moves does Black have now? A key decision is about the future of the f8-bishop.  Plan A: Black can aim for a kingside fianchetto and play ...g6 soon. A typical sequence could be @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  g6  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  , both occur frequently.   Plan B:  Our opponent can develop the bishop to e7 after playing ...e6. A sample line for this approach would be  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  e6  , but they may also start with  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  e6  .   Plan C:  Black may keep the center closed by playing a quick ...e5. This could happen after  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  , when we reach this structure.  These are the three basic concepts that Black usually chooses from. I have ranked them in order of popularity; Plan A is the most popular, followed by B and C. The distribution is roughly 60%, 20% and 10%.  What is the remaining 10%? Besides downright strange moves, there are some more concrete ideas that Black can try. I'll mention an example when we look at move orders. Let's discuss concrete move orders and what happens now on move 5.  The first point to realise is that for Plan A and B, Black will develop their g8-knight to f6. No scenario in which playing the knight elsewhere would make any sense. On the other hand, it is not clear if Black always wants to play ...Nc6 soon. It's certainly a natural square for the knight, but there is less urgency to decide the knight's fate. Black can easily delay this decision and complete the kingside formation first. We'll see that this is a viable and interesting strategy for Black.  This leads to the conclusion that the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the most flexible for Black, as they start with the knight move that has to be played anyway. This is also the reason why @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is my choice as the main move order in the following lines. With this starting move, we can examine all lines that combine ...Nf6 and ...Nc6, but also the move orders that omit or delay ...Nc6 for a while.  In practice, the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  is even considerably more popular than @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , but Black will almost always play ...Nf6 quickly afterwards to transpose. This leads to the following moves and structure:  1. The move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is our main move to consider when Black goes for Plan A or B.  2. I will check @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  to demonstrate the transpositions to other lines. There are no good independent options that Black has.  3. Black can play @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  @@EndBracket@@ to employ Plan C.  4. I will also take a brief look at the move @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qg4?!  for a double attack on e4 and g2, an example of the 'other ideas that I mentioned above. }
5... Qg4
{ Black's queen jumps to g4 and goes for a double attack on e4 and g2. This is a rather rare, second-rate move and for good reason, but it can be irritating to meet. What to do about the pawns? }
6. O-O
{ We continue with our development and give up e4. Black will lose a lot of time as we gain tempi on the queen. }
6... Qxe4 7. d4
{ This opens up the position to the utmost. Black will face a tough defensive task, so we don't have to check every imaginable line from here. Just enjoy playing a true gambit-style position over the board!  Let's have a look at a nice line to illustrate the play. After @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/2p5/2PPq3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nf6  9.Re1  Qg4  10.Qa4+  Qd7  11.Nb5!  White has a winning attack, as we threaten the deadly check on c7. }
*

