6. Nc3 Nc6
{ This position is also reached frequently via @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c4  Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  . }
7. d3
{ This is a good moment to discuss the strategy in this type of position.  The center is completely closed and won't open anytime soon. This means that attention is shifted to play on the flanks and to pawn levers. As the center is symmetrical, both sides have the same ideas regarding pawn structure change. The two possible ways are:  A. Playing for f2-f4/...f7-f5,  B. Playing for b2-b4/...b7-b5.  Looking at the current piece placement, it is clear that Black is more likely to go for Plan A, as they have not developed their knight yet, and the f-pawn is not blocked by it. On the other hand, we will focus on Plan B. }
7... g6
{ Black's main move here, by far. They have the ...f5 push in mind, and preparing it with ....g6 makes a lot of sense.   I also found a few games that featured the idea ...Be7-d8, which is better than it looks at first sight. It does not change our plans much, though: we still aim for a3&b4 to expand on the queenside. A sample line is  7...Be7  8.a3  Bd8  9.O-O  Nge7  10.Rb1  Ba5  11.Nd5  , when White is slightly better. Black has spent some time on the bishop moves and didn't yet generate any play on the kingside @@StartBracket@@...f5@@EndBracket@@. }
8. a3
{ We aim for the queenside pawn lever, as discussed.   If you want to experiment with something different, playing  8.h4!?  is an alternative.  I prefer the strategically cleaner approach, as it fits more with the general spirit of the course. }
8... Bg7 9. Rb1 { We are ready to play b4 next. } 9... Nge7
{ Black can't stop our b-pawn push with  9...a5?  , as  10.Nd5  Ra6  11.b4  shows. Our opponent weakened their queenside fatally with the a-pawn move. }
10. b4 O-O
{ You also see  10...b6  here frequently, but we'll discuss this idea after both sides have castled. }
11. O-O
{ We'll now look at two options: Black can play  11...f5  , or wait a bit with  11...b6  - in general, these positions are not very sensitive to move orders. We'll use these two moves to discuss the general ideas in more detail. }
11... f5 { Black goes for the natural pawn break. } 12. Bg5
{ This is a strong move and worth discussing. In this position, our bishop does not have much to attack. The game is closed, which is more favourable for knights. Therefore, we wouldn't mind trading our bishop for a black knight. This trade would also help to fight for the key square d5, as we would remove a defender. }
12... Nc8
{ Black ensures that we don't take the knight! This move looks a bit passive, but it involves a threat: ...f5-f4, trapping our bishop.   Before we continue, let's have a look at two alternatives.  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qn1bp/2np2p1/2p1ppB1/1PP1P3/P1NP1N2/5PPP/1R1Q1RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bf6?  is a strategic mistake. After  13.Bxf6  Rxf6  14.bxc5  dxc5  15.Nd5  Rf7  16.a4  b6  17.a5!  we are much better. The key problem for Black is that their central formation is very shaky, as the e-pawn has no reliable protection. In the long run, the king will also be a potential target.   B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qn1bp/2np2p1/2p1ppB1/1PP1P3/P1NP1N2/5PPP/1R1Q1RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...h6  looks cooperative, but I'll use it to show the bishop vs knight trade.  13.Bxe7  Nxe7  , and now I like  14.Nd2  , planning to play Nd5 next. The knight doesn't do much on f3 now and is better on d2 because of the following idea.  14...Rf7  @@StartBracket@@a waiting move to show the idea@@EndBracket@@  15.Nd5  Nxd5  16.cxd5  , when we have the great c4-square for the knight. This means that Black will be reluctant to capture on d5 and has to tolerate our strong knight. A complex position, but I prefer White. Black's bishop remains passive, and we have more options to improve. }
13. Bd2
{ We have to move the bishop back, as ...f4 was a serious threat. Black's c8-knight is not ideally placed, and we are ready to play Nd5 next.  What if they just go back to e7 and ask us for an active idea? }
13... N8e7 14. bxc5
{ I like this move, playing in a similar style as after @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qnpbp/2np2p1/2p1p3/1PP1P3/P1NP1N2/5PPP/1RBQ1RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...b6  12.bxc5  , when we reach almost the same structure. }
14... dxc5 15. Nd5
{ Black is under slight pressure here. They can't take d5 under great conditions, and we have ways to improve. Note that our bishop can support a later a4-a5 @@StartBracket@@Black will often play ...b6@@EndBracket@@ and be well-placed on c3, eyeing the e-pawn. }
