inly a natural square for the knight, but there is less urgency to decide the knight's fate. Black can easily delay this decision and complete the kingside formation first. We'll see that this is a viable and interesting strategy for Black.  This leads to the conclusion that the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the most flexible for Black, as they start with the knight move that has to be played anyway. This is also the reason why @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is my choice as the main move order in the following lines. With this starting move, we can examine all lines that combine ...Nf6 and ...Nc6, but also the move orders that omit or delay ...Nc6 for a while.  In practice, the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  is even considerably more popular than @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , but Black will almost always play ...Nf6 quickly afterwards to transpose. This leads to the following moves and structure:  1. The move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is our main move to consider when Black goes for Plan A or B.  2. I will check @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  to demonstrate the transpositions to other lines. There are no good independent options that Black has.  3. Black can play @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  @@EndBracket@@ to employ Plan C.  4. I will also take a brief look at the move @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qg4?!  for a double attack on e4 and g2, an example of the 'other ideas that I mentioned above. }
5... Nf6
{ This is the most popular move on the top level nowadays. There are some concrete lines where delaying ...Nc6 is relevant, as an early ...Rf8-c8 will attack the c4-pawn. More about that later. }
6. Nc3
{ We need to cover our pawn, of course. What next? We'll now check the following moves:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , which commits to Plan A as described in the notes to move  5.  B. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@6...e6  , deciding for Plan B.  C. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  , when Black still has the option to switch to Plan A or B after  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  or @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/8/2PNP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6  , as it happens most of the time.  However, Black may try for concrete play based on the queen sortie ...Qd7-Qg4 to attack the still unprotected g-pawn. }
6... Nc6
{ In most cases, Black will play ...e6 or ...g6 right after @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  . These positions are examined via the @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  and @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  move orders, so the unique lines feature early concrete play by Black. }
7. d4
{ Awarding an exclamation mark to the move is a bit much, but it is crucial to play the correct move order here.  While we generally want to castle kingside, the timing is important. As it turns out, playing  7.O-O  first is NOT a transposition to lines that are part of our repertoire. What's the issue? After  7...g6  8.d4  cxd4  9.Nxd4  Bg7  Black is threatening ...Nxe4! and  10.Be3  Ng4  is awkward to meet. White is stuck with @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nde2  - not terrible objectively, but it leads to lines we usually don't aim for.  Is there a way to remember that you shouldn't castle here? Yes, there is. Looking at our main lines, starting with @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , you'll see that Black develops some pressure on our center. The knights and bishops attack it. We aim for a setup with Be3 @@StartBracket@@covering d4@@EndBracket@@ and need the move f3, as ...Ng4 has to be stopped. We don't have time to castle, but we need to play these moves first. Our central structure must be erected first; we only get our king out of the center after.   This leads to the conclusion that we need to play @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.d4  aiming for a direct transposition to this complex. In almost all cases, Black will now play  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  or @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/8/2PNP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6  , transposing to the main lines of this chapter.  The only deviations worth studying are @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/2p5/2PPP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qg4  and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/2p5/2PPP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Qg4  , which aim for a concrete solution. Both lines are rare in practice, but I think they require a look because they could be tricky to meet if you have never seen them. Let's get to work. }
7... Qg4
{ A very rare line, but it's good to know how to answer it. I think 7...Qg4 is unpopular because it leads to a rather joyless position for Black in which White enjoys a small advantage. People usually don't prepare a variation - and the queen jump to g4 is likely not an over-the-board inspiration - to grovel for a draw with it. }
8. d5
{ The only challenging approach is forcing the action.   After  8.O-O?!  Nxd4  9.Nxd4  Qxd1  10.Rxd1  cxd4  11.Rxd4  Black managed to trade a lot of pieces and has equalised.  After our move, we'll reach a more promising endgame. }
8... Nd4 9. Nxd4 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1
{ This looks better than the knight capture, as the following line works well for us. }
10... cxd4 11. Nb5
{ We have a double threat on c7 and d4. Black needs to cover the fork. } 11...
Rc8
{ That's the only move.   They can't play the cheeky  11...Nxe4?  due to  12.Re1  , when we win material. }
12. b3
{ This position White can force after the ...Qg4 sortie. We are slightly better as, after the likely trade of the e-pawn for d-pawn, we will have far more space, and Black has some issues with the f8-bishop. }
12... Nxe4
{ This is a mistake worth checking.   The best for Black is  12...a6  14.Nxd4  Nxe4  15.Ke2  , when White is only slightly better. We have more space and play on the queenside. A setup with Be3 and rooks to c1 and d1 comes to mind. }
13. Nxa7
{ In the first edition, I recommended  13.Re1  here, but taking on a7 is even better.  How does it continue from here?   A. @@StartFEN@@2r1kb1r/Np2pppp/3p4/3P4/2Ppn3/1P6/P4PPP/R1BK3R b k - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nxf2+??  14.Ke2  Nxh1  15.Nxc8  wins for us. We get the knight out, and Black doesn't!  B. @@StartFEN@@2r1kb1r/Np2pppp/3p4/3P4/2Ppn3/1P6/P4PPP/R1BK3R b k - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nxf2+??  14.Ke2  Ra8  15.Nb5  is the same story.  C. @@StartFEN@@2r1kb1r/Np2pppp/3p4/3P4/2Ppn3/1P6/P4PPP/R1BK3R b k - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rd8  14.Rf1  is better for White due to the better pawn structure.  D. @@StartFEN@@2r1kb1r/Np2pppp/3p4/3P4/2Ppn3/1P6/P4PPP/R1BK3R b k - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nc3+  14.Kc2  Ra8  15.Nb5  Nxb5  16.cxb5  leads to a good endgame for White, too. }
