9... Bg7
{ Black is increasing the pressure on d4 and now threatens ...Nxe4!, which prompts our prepared reply. }
10. Be3
{ We need to lend some protection to the knight and develop the bishop to the most natural square. Both sides have prioritised the fight for central control - now it's time to castle. }
10... O-O 11. O-O
{ It isn't easy to analyse these positions on a move-by-move basis. Black has different rook setups @@StartBracket@@...Rfc8, ...Rac8+...Rad8@@EndBracket@@ and moves like ...a6 and ...Qd8-a5, which they can play in various move orders.  White is happy to consolidate the space advantage and prevent the pawn breaks like ...b7-b5 or be ready for ...e7-e6 and ...d6-d5 by Black. We will centralise and often base our play on the knight coming to d5.  The Maroczy center is generally regarded as slightly favourable for White, but it requires patience, building up slowly. It is important to note that the play is quite strategic and slow.  It is a type of position that, in many cases, the Black player did not intend to reach when he learned his main line Open Sicilian theory. Defending the black side of the Maroczy is quite different to a Dragon or Najdorf main line.   Let's overview what we will check now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a6  looks like Black's best bet. They don't commit a rook but play the preparation move for the pawn break ...b5 first.   B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rac8  looks a bit slow. The idea usually combines ...Rac8 with ...Rad8 and go for a central break with ...e6 and ...d5. We'll examine this concept via the 11...Rac8 move order, but they may also play  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rfd8  12.b3  Rac8  or start with @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...e6  - it can lead to the same setup. We'll play b3 and Qd2 anyway.   C. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rfc8  is often played with either ...Qd8-a5 or a quick ...a6 and ...b5 in mind. We'll examine both. }
11... Rac8
{ A relatively slow move that we like to see. It is often played with the following setup in mind: rooks to c8 and d8, then go for a central breakthrough with ...e6 and ...d5. We can reach this setup via various move orders. }
12. b3 { The pawn on c4 needs some cover. } 12... Rfd8
{ This signals that Black is trying to play in the center with ...e6 and ...d5 to come. }
13. Qd2
{ We often have to decide if we want to play the queen to d2 or d3. The d3-square can be attractive in cases where our c-pawn needs cover or ...b5 is an immediate threat. Against slow setups, like the one on the board, Qd2 is the most harmonious setup. }
13... e6
{ Black completes the preparation for ...d5.   Their setup could also be reached via other move orders, like @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rfd8  12.b3  Rac8  13.Qd2  e6  , for example.  Now, after 13...e6, we know Black's idea and need to find a good prophylactic move against their planned ...d6-d5 breakthrough. }
14. Rad1
{ After Black has revealed their plan, we know how to place this rook. White needs more control of the d-file, as we will see in the coming sequence of moves. }
14... d5 15. cxd5 { We start a forced sequence with this capture. } 15... exd5
16. Nxc6 bxc6 { Black has to capture with the pawn to protect d5. } 17. e5
{ Nice! We manage to misplace Black's knight and gain ground. } 17... Ne8 18.
f4
{ Here, it is clear why the rook is needed on d1 and why Rad1 was more appropriate than Rfd1 in this specific situation. White is better here with the superior pawn structure and more active pieces. }
