{ It is crucial to play this move right away before castling.   After  7.O-O  Nc6  8.d4  cxd4  9.Nxd4  Bg7  Black's pressure on White's center more or less forces the move  10.Nde2  , retreating the knight.   By playing the immediate  7.d4  , we will be ready to support our center in time to avoid the retreat and keep our knight on d4. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ Now Black has the choice between delaying the move ...Nc6 or for a while or playing it now.   The position after  8...Nc6  frequently arises, as it may easily occur via other move orders. The sequences @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  and @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  , all lead to the same position.  These various move orders don't make things complicated, by the way. We always play 6.Nc3 and 7.d4  , unless Black stops us with ...e5 first. }
8... Nc6 9. f3
{ This is an important move order detail! We want to play Be3 and f3 to support the center anyway, but it is important to start with this immediately and not waste a tempo on castling.   After  9.O-O?!  Bg7  Black threatens ...Nxe4! and it is too late to play f3. }
9... Bg7
{ Black is increasing the pressure on d4 and now threatens ...Nxe4!, which prompts our prepared reply. }
10. Be3
{ We need to lend some protection to the knight and develop the bishop to the most natural square. Both sides have prioritised the fight for central control - now it's time to castle. }
10... O-O 11. O-O
{ It isn't easy to analyse these positions on a move-by-move basis. Black has different rook setups @@StartBracket@@...Rfc8, ...Rac8+...Rad8@@EndBracket@@ and moves like ...a6 and ...Qd8-a5, which they can play in various move orders.  White is happy to consolidate the space advantage and prevent the pawn breaks like ...b7-b5 or be ready for ...e7-e6 and ...d6-d5 by Black. We will centralise and often base our play on the knight coming to d5.  The Maroczy center is generally regarded as slightly favourable for White, but it requires patience, building up slowly. It is important to note that the play is quite strategic and slow.  It is a type of position that, in many cases, the Black player did not intend to reach when he learned his main line Open Sicilian theory. Defending the black side of the Maroczy is quite different to a Dragon or Najdorf main line.   Let's overview what we will check now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a6  looks like Black's best bet. They don't commit a rook but play the preparation move for the pawn break ...b5 first.   B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rac8  looks a bit slow. The idea usually combines ...Rac8 with ...Rad8 and go for a central break with ...e6 and ...d5. We'll examine this concept via the 11...Rac8 move order, but they may also play  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rfd8  12.b3  Rac8  or start with @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...e6  - it can lead to the same setup. We'll play b3 and Qd2 anyway.   C. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rfc8  is often played with either ...Qd8-a5 or a quick ...a6 and ...b5 in mind. We'll examine both. }
11... a6
{ Against this move, we need to be precise. Black has the simple idea of taking on d4 and then going ...b7-b5 immediately. }
12. Qd3
{ This is not a very common square for the queen, but it is most important to keep an eye on b5, thus preventing the b-pawn push.   Note that  12.Qe2?  fails to  12...Nxe4  , when everything falls apart.   After  12.Qd3  Black has some options that we need to check:  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfc8  looks like the best line for Black, going for a quick ...b5 push.   B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rac8  is played often, but comfortable for us. We'll see that Black does not realise ...b5 in a sound way. It depends on some concrete tactics, but it makes sense that line A is more forceful, as Black has two rooks on the queenside in A; here, the f8-rook is not participating in the fight.   C. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Ne5  looks logical, but is better for White based on a timely knight jump to d5.   D. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rab8  is a different way to support ...b5. }
12... Rab8
{ This move is not played often, but it is an interesting try. Black supports ...b5 with the rook.  I suggest a somewhat unusual solution. }
13. Nxc6
{ We rarely take on c6, but it works quite well here.   After the more conventional move  13.b3  Black has  13...Nxd4  14.Bxd4  b5  15.cxb5  axb5  , when  16.a4  bxa4  17.bxa4  gives us a passed a-pawn. This is a risk-free way of playing, but I want to aim for more. }
13... bxc6
{ Better than  13...Qxc6  14.Rac1  , when we are ready for Nd5 soon, with a standard Maroczy Bind advantage. }
14. b3
{ Our pawn was under attack, an easy move. It's a good moment to take stock. After taking on c6, the Nd5 option is off the table.  What do we play for? The way to go is by playing Rad1 first @@StartBracket@@get out of the long diagonal@@EndBracket@@, then operate with f4-based ideas.  Black's problem is: they have no clear plan to go for. Changing the pawn structure is difficult, and the standard idea ...a5-a4 is not easy to realise. In practice, these positions are much easier for White to play. }
14... Qc7 { This looks best, clearing the d7-square for the knight. } 15. Rad1
{ We need to leave the long diagonal. } 15... Nd7 16. f4
{ We have completed the setup I described earlier. Let's look at some ideas now:  A. @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/2qnppbp/p1pp2p1/8/2P1PP2/1PNQB3/P5PP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nc5?  is bad due to  17.Bxc5  dxc5  18.e5  , when Black's bishop is shut out, their pawn structure is weak.  B. @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/2qnppbp/p1pp2p1/8/2P1PP2/1PNQB3/P5PP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...a5  is a better move when  17.e5  does not net much after  17...Rbd8  . We can't win d6, as our knight hangs after the captures. A much better choice is  @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/2qnppbp/2pp2p1/p7/2P1PP2/1PNQB3/P5PP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Na4  , which stops ...Nc5 ideas. We have time to improve our position, for example, with moves like Kh1. I also like the idea of Bd2-c3, trading bishops.   C. @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/2qnppbp/p1pp2p1/8/2P1PP2/1PNQB3/P5PP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Rbd8  is interesting. The idea is to answer  17.Na4?!  with  17...Nc5!  , using the opposition of rook and queen on the d-file. Black is also threatening ...Nc5, which makes  @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/2qnppbp/p1pp2p1/8/2P1PP2/1PNQB3/P5PP/3R1RK1 w - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Ne2  Nc5  18.Qc2  the best choice.  Our idea is an attack based on f4-f5, maybe Rf3-g3/h3 later. Stockfish also points out h4-h5, which also looks dangerous. }
