{ Black can't play  15...b5??  due to  16.cxb5  axb5  17.Nxb5!  , winning on the spot. }
16. a4
{ We make sure that Black can't play ...b5 in the long run.   It's also important to note that we don't want to play the move Nd5 too early, as  16.Nd5?!  Nxd5  17.cxd5  Qa5  shows. It is much better first to improve our position.  Once the ...b5-break is off the table, like here, we have plenty of time to improve our position. Black can't do much, as they have no pawn break. It's also difficult to move the knight, as Nd5 would hit Black. Playing ...e6 has the drawback of weakening the d-pawn.  White has a range of ideas: Try to make the move Nd5 more effective. This can be accomplished with ideas like Kh1 and Bg5/Bd4 when Bxf6, followed by Nd5, becomes a threat. You can also try to play Nd5 after doubling rooks on the c-file first, making the sequence Nd5, ...Nxd5, and cxd5 more powerful.We can play f4 after due preparation and then aim for e4-e5 or f4-f5. This depends a lot on the concrete piece placement.Finally: White often makes huge progress by exploiting Black's mistakes. They have to play a sit-and-waiting game, and this isn't easy. Often Black plays some pseudo-active move that amounts to self-destruction. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B2) Sicilian – Moscow 3...Bd7"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Bd7 4.Bxd7+ Qxd7 5.c4 Nf6 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ This move signals that Black will play ...Nc6 most of the time to emphasise control over d4. This is most often combined with a kingside fianchetto. }
5. c4
{ A strategically very sound choice. White places his pawns on light squares after this bishop has been traded off. We are aiming for a Maroczy Bind structure, giving White comfortable control.  What options and moves does Black have now? A key decision is about the future of the f8-bishop.  Plan A: Black can aim for a kingside fianchetto and play ...g6 soon. A typical sequence could be @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  g6  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  , both occur frequently.   Plan B:  Our opponent can develop the bishop to e7 after playing ...e6. A sample line for this approach would be  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  e6  , but they may also start with  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  e6  .   Plan C:  Black may keep the center closed by playing a quick ...e5. This could happen after  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  , when we reach this structure.  These are the three basic concepts that Black usually chooses from. I have ranked them in order of popularity; Plan A is the most popular, followed by B and C. The distribution is roughly 60%, 20% and 10%.  What is the remaining 10%? Besides downright strange moves, there are some more concrete ideas that Black can try. I'll mention an example when we look at move orders. Let's discuss concrete move orders and what happens now on move 5.  The first point to realise is that for Plan A and B, Black will develop their g8-knight to f6. No scenario in which playing the knight elsewhere would make any sense. On the other hand, it is not clear if Black always wants to play ...Nc6 soon. It's certainly a natural square for the knight, but there is less urgency to decide the knight's fate. Black can easily delay this decision and complete the kingside formation first. We'll see that this is a viable and interesting strategy for Black.  This leads to the conclusion that the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the most flexible for Black, as they start with the knight move that has to be played anyway. This is also the reason why @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is my choice as the main move order in the following lines. With this starting move, we can examine all lines that combine ...Nf6 and ...Nc6, but also the move orders that omit or delay ...Nc6 for a while.  In practice, the move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  is even considerably more popular than @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , but Black will almost always play ...Nf6 quickly afterwards to transpose. This leads to the following moves and structure:  1. The move  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is our main move to consider when Black goes for Plan A or B.  2. I will check @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  to demonstrate the transpositions to other lines. There are no good independent options that Black has.  3. Black can play @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  e5  @@EndBracket@@ to employ Plan C.  4. I will also take a brief look at the move @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qg4?!  for a double attack on e4 and g2, an example of the 'other ideas that I mentioned above. }
5... Nf6
{ This is the most popular move on the top level nowadays. There are some concrete lines where delaying ...Nc6 is relevant, as an early ...Rf8-c8 will attack the c4-pawn. More about that later. }
6. Nc3
{ We need to cover our pawn, of course. What next? We'll now check the following moves:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , which commits to Plan A as described in the notes to move  5.  B. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@6...e6  , deciding for Plan B.  C. @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp1qpppp/3p1n2/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  , when Black still has the option to switch to Plan A or B after  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  or @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1qpppp/2np1n2/8/2PNP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6  , as it happens most of the time.  However, Black may try for concrete play based on the queen sortie ...Qd7-Qg4 to attack the still unprotected g-pawn. }
6... g6 { The kingside fianchetto is by far Black's most popular option. } 7.
d4
{ It is crucial to play this move right away before castling.   After  7.O-O  Nc6  8.d4  cxd4  9.Nxd4  Bg7  Black's pressure on White's center more or less forces the move  10.Nde2  , retreating the knight.   By playing the immediate  7.d4  , we will be ready to support our center in time to avoid the retreat and keep our knight on d4. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ Now Black has the choice between delaying the move ...Nc6 or for a while or playing it now.   The position after  8...Nc6  frequently arises, as it may easily occur via other move orders. The sequences @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Nc3  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  and @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  g6  , all lead to the same position.  These various move orders don't make things complicated, by the way. We always play 6.Nc3 and 7.d4  , unless Black stops us with ...e5 first. }
8... Nc6 9. f3
{ This is an important move order detail! We want to play Be3 and f3 to support the center anyway, but it is important to start with this immediately and not waste a tempo on castling.   After  9.O-O?!  Bg7  Black threatens ...Nxe4! and it is too late to play f3. }
9... Bg7
{ Black is increasing the pressure on d4 and now threatens ...Nxe4!, which prompts our prepared reply. }
10. Be3
{ We need to lend some protection to the knight and develop the bishop to the most natural square. Both sides have prioritised the fight for central control - now it's time to castle. }
10... O-O 11. O-O
{ It isn't easy to analyse these positions on a move-by-move basis. Black has different rook setups @@StartBracket@@...Rfc8, ...Rac8+...Rad8@@EndBracket@@ and moves like ...a6 and ...Qd8-a5, which they can play in various move orders.  White is happy to consolidate the space advantage and prevent the pawn breaks like ...b7-b5 or be ready for ...e7-e6 and ...d6-d5 by Black. We will centralise and often base our play on the knight coming to d5.  The Maroczy center is generally regarded as slightly favourable for White, but it requires patience, building up slowly. It is important to note that the play is quite strategic and slow.  It is a type of position that, in many cases, the Black player did not intend to reach when he learned his main line Open Sicilian theory. Defending the black side of the Maroczy is quite different to a Dragon or Najdorf main line.   Let's overview what we will check now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a6  looks like Black's best bet. They don't commit a rook but play the preparation move for the pawn break ...b5 first.   B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rac8  looks a bit slow. The idea usually combines ...Rac8 with ...Rad8 and go for a central break with ...e6 and ...d5. We'll examine this concept via the 11...Rac8 move order, but they may also play  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rfd8  12.b3  Rac8  or start with @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...e6  - it can lead to the same setup. We'll play b3 and Qd2 anyway.   C. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp1qppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rfc8  is often played with either ...Qd8-a5 or a quick ...a6 and ...b5 in mind. We'll examine both. }
11... a6
{ Against this move, we need to be precise. Black has the simple idea of taking on d4 and then going ...b7-b5 immediately. }
12. Qd3
{ This is not a very common square for the queen, but it is most important to keep an eye on b5, thus preventing the b-pawn push.   Note that  12.Qe2?  fails to  12...Nxe4  , when everything falls apart.   After  12.Qd3  Black has some options that we need to check:  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfc8  looks like the best line for Black, going for a quick ...b5 push.   B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rac8  is played often, but comfortable for us. We'll see that Black does not realise ...b5 in a sound way. It depends on some concrete tactics, but it makes sense that line A is more forceful, as Black has two rooks on the queenside in A; here, the f8-rook is not participating in the fight.   C. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Ne5  looks logical, but is better for White based on a timely knight jump to d5.   D. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rab8  is a different way to support ...b5. }
12... Rfc8 { This move looks like the most promising for Black. } 13. b3
{ The only move to address the threat of ...Ne5.   After  13.Nxc6  Qxc6  14.Nd5  Nxd5  15.cxd5  Qb5  , our position is falling apart.   Black has a wide choice of moves, but the most critical is clearly @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/1PNQBP2/P5PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...b5  , a resource I didn't consider in the first edition. Let's overview:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/1PNQBP2/P5PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...b5  is the most direct and best move.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/1PNQBP2/P5PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rab8  is the most common move in online play and nice for White. We will have a closer look at this move, as it demonstrates the danger that Black is facing.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/1PNQBP2/P5PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Ne5  14.Qe2  b5  15.Nd5!  is nice for White and examined via the move order @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Ne5  13.Qe2  Rfc8  14.b3  b5  15.Nd5  , which is a more common move order.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/1PNQBP2/P5PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rab8  can be answered with  14.Nxc6!  , when  14...bxc6  leads to a better version of @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/2NQBP2/PP4PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rab8  13.Nxc6  bxc6  , as Black's rooks are misplaced, and we have a comfortable 'Maroczy edge' after @@StartFEN@@1rr3k1/1p1qppbp/p1Np1np1/8/2P1P3/1PNQBP2/P5PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qxc6  15.Rac1  . }
13... b5
{ A strong move that I failed to consider while writing the first edition. It was introduced into tournament practice one year after the release @@StartBracket@@2019@@EndBracket@@ and looks like Black's best option. In most lines, they don't manage ...b5, here they do. It is based on very concrete, computer-style variations, though. }
14. cxb5 { No choice, we have to take. } 14... Ne5
{ That's the point of starting with ...b5 and not ...Ne5. Now we have to move the queen to d2.   The earlier @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/1p1qppbp/p1np1np1/8/2PNP3/1PNQBP2/P5PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Ne5  can be met with  14.Qe2  b5  15.Nd5!  , as analysed before. }
15. Qd2
{ At first, you think Black has given up the b-pawn for no reason, but they removed a defender of d5, so... }
15... d5
{ The only way to make this concept work. As you see, this is not an idea people devise over the board but rather find in computer-assisted preparation.   Now White has two main options. After  16.Nxd5  Nxd5  17.exd5  axb5  18.Rad1  Qxd5  19.Qe2  Nc6!  20.Nxb5  wins a pawn, but Black has enough compensation. I'm not too fond of this continuation, as I feel Black's task is easier. It is equal by engine standards, but I prefer the other idea on move 16. }
16. Nc6 { I suggest this move, which forces the following sequence. } 16...
Nxc6 17. bxc6 Rxc6
{ They have to take with the rook, as  17...Qxc6?  18.Nxd5  wins a pawn. } 18.
e5
{ This is the move to play for a win in a complicated position with equal chances. It continues with @@StartFEN@@r5k1/3qppbp/p1r2np1/3pP3/8/1PN1BP2/P2Q2PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Ne8  19.f4  e6  20.Ne2  , when I suggest the following plan: trade one rook on the c-file, then aim for a kingside expansion with g4 and possibly f5. This will create tension and pose problems, leading to an interesting battle.  One good practical point is: if you are fine with a draw you can also play  @@StartFEN@@r5k1/3qppbp/p1r2np1/3p4/4P3/1PN1BP2/P2Q2PP/R4RK1 w - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Nxd5  Nxd5  19.exd5  Rd6  20.Rad1  Rd8  21.Qa5  , when Black will eventually regain the d-pawn and equalise, but never reach more. If you play a very strong opponent @@StartBracket@@they just played 18 moves of perfect preparation@@EndBracket@@, this can be a good option if a draw suits you. }
