[White "B3) Sicilian – Moscow 3...Nd7"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Nd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3
{ Against 3...Nd7, White has a wide range of options. I looked at them in-depth, trying to determine if I should change my current recommendation. There are some interesting ideas, but I prefered the strategic clarity of  4.c3  in the end.  I still want to share some of my results - maybe you see an interesting idea you like to explore yourself.   4.O-O  was the main candidate I considered. The idea is to play Re1 and Bf1 next, which works well after  4...Ngf6  5.Re1  , but @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  5.Bd3  is the main line. White wants to play c3 and Bc2, which leads to similar positions to the ones we are aiming for: play c3&d4 for the perfect pawn center. Black has some ways to prevent this ideal scenario, and these lines lead to slightly odd positions. I have some doubts about the Bd3 setup in the context of our KIS approach, as it looks a bit unnatural. You'd need to learn more theory for little gain and some murky situations.    4.Ba4!?  is a cunning move that I also checked. The idea is still c3&d4, but we move the bishop out of the tempo move ...a6 first. A fun point is  4...Ngf6  5.O-O  , when White can offer the e-pawn. I don't recommend this line because of  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/2p5/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.O-O  a6!  , when White needs to play  6.c4  , leading to a position that top players discussed in recent years. White's chances are intact, but it's an unconventional position and tough to understand. It's also unlike anything else that we play. It has some Maroczy Bind vibes, but the center is closed, and sometimes our bishop ends up on b3 or c2, which looked odd to me.  Conclusion: interesting, but not in line with my intended repertoire spirit. These two lines were my main alternatives. There are plenty more, but they feel too different from the rest of the repertoire  - @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d4  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  come to mind.  Let's return to my choice, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c3  .  Black has two main options now that will often lead to the same lines. They can start with  4...Ngf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  , immediately attacking our e-pawn or our bishop. These moves are the most logical, for sure.  At some point, Black needs to decide how to develop the kingside: ...e6, ...e5 or ...g6 come to mind. We'll examine these options at various moments on the next moves, and there are some possible transpositions. Our job is quite easy, though. We play natural moves and can get by with some general principles. Let's continue. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B3) Sicilian – Moscow 3...Nd7"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Nd7 4.c3 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 a6
{ A very popular move that likely leads to the same positions as after  4...Ngf6  , but it gives White some additional options. These additional ideas are not exceptionally promising, though. I'll show how we'll transpose to  4...Ngf6  and point out the possible ways to deviate in case you want to try them out. They are not theory-heavy, so this is easily possible. }
5. Ba4 { OK, that was easy. } 5... b5
{ They can also play  5...Ngf6  , of course. Then you have the simple option  6.Qe2  , which transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ngf6  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  - part of our repertoire anyway.   A possible alternative is  5.Bc2  to cover the pawn, thus omitting the queen move. You can try to continue with a later O-O and Re1, which works just as well as the Qe2 setup. I'll talk about the Re1  alternative again in a moment, as we can get it via 5...b5, as well. }
6. Bc2
{ We always go back to c2, covering the e-pawn.   It makes no sense to go  6.Bb3  and run into  6...c4  with a tempo for Black. }
6... Bb7
{ The other logical move is  6...Ngf6  , when  7.d4  Bb7  8.Qe2  leads to the main line of the current chapter, usually reached via  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ngf6  5.Qe2  etc.   An alternative for White is  6...Ngf6  7.O-O  Bb7  8.Re1  , which I will talk about in a moment, as we'll arrive there via 6...Bb7, too. }
7. d4
{ This is how to transpose to our chapter's main line.   If you'd like to play differently without studying much, consider  7.O-O  Ngf6  8.Re1  to cover the e-pawn. The idea is still d4 next, but Black could try to make it more difficult with  8...c4  when  9.a4  is the way. It's an interesting alternative, but the more practical decision is to allow the transposition to our main line, as mentioned. }
7... Ngf6 8. Qe2
{ And finally, we have arrived at a key position of our main line. We discuss it via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ngf6  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  b5  7.Bc2  Bb7  8.d4  , when Black is at an important crossroads. Please see the analysis of the main line for details. }
