[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B3) Sicilian – Moscow 3...Nd7"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Nd7 4.c3 Ngf6 5.Qe2 e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 Nf6
{ 'Knights out first' is one of the general rules you should always take with a grain of salt. However, there often is a strong logic to it. Here it's fairly clear that Black's knight is best on f6, so it makes sense to place it there first, with a tempo on our e-pawn. }
5. Qe2
{ Black attacked the pawn, and we cover it.   There is an alternative here, though. White can also play  5.Bd3  ,  which has its points. The bishop might end on c2 anyway, so why not go there immediately? The drawback is that Black never needed to play ...a6 to kick the bishop and may use the tempo differently.  I am not a fan of the Bd3 setups for conceptual reasons, for the most part. If you play an early c3, you should be ready to occupy the center and not block the pawn.  How does it continue now? Black has to decide on the kingside development. The three options are ...g6, ...e6 and ...e5. The main question is when to decide on one of them. There are three possible moments:   A. Right now, after 5.Qe2. This is rarely played and is imprecise. We play d4 quickly and can retreat our bishop to d3, which saves a bit of time compared to the more common b5-a4-c2 route.   B. Black goes @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  and then decides on a central setup. This is very similar and often transposes to C below, as playing ...b5 is frequently useful and happens quickly.   C. Black first develops the queenside with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  b5  7.Bc2  Bb7  8.d4  and only then decides on a pawn formation.  B and C are very similar and of about equal strength.  I'll now continue to check the possibilities mentioned under A: the moves  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  . }
5... e5
{ A premature decision that we can exploit by immediate action in the center. }
6. d4
{ It's important to play it immediately to benefit from Black's move order.   After  6.O-O  a6  7.Ba4  b5  , they would be able to return to mainline style play, usually started by  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  .  The advantage of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/3p1n2/1Bp1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq e6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d4!  is: we attack e5 now, so Black needs to react directly. }
6... Qc7
{ Black defends the e5-pawn.   A different way to handle the problem would be to capture on d4, but we are happy about it. It allows us to develop our knight to c3 and weakens Black's pawn structure. A sample line is  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  exd4  8.Nxd4  Be7  9.Nc3  , when we have a comfortable advantage. }
7. O-O
{ Let's castle first and then decide how to proceed. The important part was playing the early d4 to force a concession on the previous move. }
7... Be7
{ We have a comfortable choice now. A simple development move would be fine, but we have a more concrete idea that is very strong and instructive. }
8. dxe5
{ This type of trade is usually a rather lame decision, as White's d-pawn is more active than Black's, but concrete beats the abstract. The key idea comes on the next move. }
8... dxe5 9. c4
{ We transform the central pawn structure to a purely symmetrical one, with both sides suffering from a weak center square d5/d4. The all-important factor is the piece placement, though. Whenever you place multiple pawns on one colour complex, you need to be careful that you don't create a bad bishop mostly staring at its own pawns.  Here, we are always ready to trade our bishop for Black's knight while our opponent's Be7 remains passive.A second advantage for us: we can play a quick Nc3, directly connecting a knight to the dream square d5.Finally, we may play Bg5 and trade our bishop for a knight to emphasize control of said dream square.  With all these factors combined, we are likely to reach a strategically dominant position.   I want to illustrate these points with a basic sample line. @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppqnbppp/5n2/1Bp1p3/2P1P3/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...O-O  10.Bxd7  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppqnbppp/5n2/1Bp1p3/2P1P3/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB2RK1 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nc3  first is also fine, as  10...Nb6  11.a4!  is good for White.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppqBbppp/5n2/2p1p3/2P1P3/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB2RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bxd7  11.Bg5  Rad8  12.Bxf6  Bxf6  13.Nc3  leads to a great position for White. Black's bishops are passive, and we'll play Nd5 next. After  13...Bc6  14.Nd5  Bxd5  15.cxd5  , we can attack the queenside, while Black has no counterplay and a terrible bishop. }
