5... e6
{ A slightly imprecise mover order, as we manage to retreat our bishop to d3 now comfortably. }
6. d4 { We need to play d4 right away to allow the comfortable retreat to d3. }
6... cxd4
{ A frequently played move, but we are happy to gain Nc3 as an option.   Black should probably prefer  6...a6  7.Bd3  , when we reach a slightly better version of our chapter's main line. We only needed two moves to get to d3, while Bb5-a4-c2 takes three. }
7. cxd4 Be7
{ Or  7...a6  8.Bd3  , of course. I want to take a quick look at this move to illustrate why allowing Nc3 benefits White. }
8. Nc3
{ We have this nice square now, which changes one important factor of the position: the pawn advance e4-e5 is more dangerous now, as Black can't reply ...Nd5 that comfortably now. Let's have a look at this idea. }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ The direct  9.e5  is not bad, but preparing the move is stronger. } 9... a6
{ Black needs to develop the queenside and finally plays for the extended fianchetto. }
10. Bd3
{ Now we are well-positioned to advance to e5, and Black has to be careful. }
10... b5
{ A mistake, but I want to show the refutation.   Black's best is the sad move  10...e5  , which stops our pawn push. We are still in excellent shape as the sample line  11.Rd1  b5  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Bg5  demonstrates. We are faster to occupy the open files and have more options, like playing a4 at the right moment. }
11. e5
{ Black's problem: they need to move the knight to d5 now, or after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/3nbppp/p2ppn2/1p2P3/3P4/2NB1N2/PP2QPPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...dxe5  12.dxe5  , as @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/3nbppp/p2ppn2/1p2P3/3P4/2NB1N2/PP2QPPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ne8??  12.Qe4!  is curtains. }
11... Nd5
{ Or  11...dxe5  12.dxe5  Nd5  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.Qc2  , when it's tough to say if we are more likely to win on the kingside or queenside, as Black has weaknesses on both flanks. }
12. Nxd5 { The best move amongst a range of promising ones. } 12... exd5 13. e6
{ Disaster strikes; Black is in terrible shape now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/3nbppp/p2pP3/1p1p4/3P4/3B1N2/PP2QPPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...fxe6  14.Qxe6+  Kh8  15.Qxd5  is easy.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/3nbppp/p2pP3/1p1p4/3P4/3B1N2/PP2QPPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nb6  14.exf7+  Rxf7  15.h3  @@StartBracket@@stopping ...Bg4@@EndBracket@@ gives White a huge strategic plus, as Black's pawn structure and kingside are terminally weak. }
