1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 Nf6
{ 'Knights out first' is one of the general rules you should always take with a grain of salt. However, there often is a strong logic to it. Here it's fairly clear that Black's knight is best on f6, so it makes sense to place it there first, with a tempo on our e-pawn. }
5. Qe2
{ Black attacked the pawn, and we cover it.   There is an alternative here, though. White can also play  5.Bd3  ,  which has its points. The bishop might end on c2 anyway, so why not go there immediately? The drawback is that Black never needed to play ...a6 to kick the bishop and may use the tempo differently.  I am not a fan of the Bd3 setups for conceptual reasons, for the most part. If you play an early c3, you should be ready to occupy the center and not block the pawn.  How does it continue now? Black has to decide on the kingside development. The three options are ...g6, ...e6 and ...e5. The main question is when to decide on one of them. There are three possible moments:   A. Right now, after 5.Qe2. This is rarely played and is imprecise. We play d4 quickly and can retreat our bishop to d3, which saves a bit of time compared to the more common b5-a4-c2 route.   B. Black goes @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  and then decides on a central setup. This is very similar and often transposes to C below, as playing ...b5 is frequently useful and happens quickly.   C. Black first develops the queenside with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  b5  7.Bc2  Bb7  8.d4  and only then decides on a pawn formation.  B and C are very similar and of about equal strength.  I'll now continue to check the possibilities mentioned under A: the moves  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  . }
5... g6
{ Let's have a look at the fianchetto. We'll see that Black has to be careful, as we sometimes manage a dangerous advance of the e-pawn. }
6. d4 cxd4
{ Black can also start with  6...a6  7.Bd3  and play  7...cxd4  , which will transpose to the line we are about to examine.  Black has to be careful here, as  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npp1p/3p1np1/1Bp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg7?!  shows. It looks normal, but  7.e5!  is already annoying for Black. The two following lines demonstrate the problem:   A.  7...dxe5  8.dxe5  Nd5  9.e6  fxe6  10.Ng5  ,   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/1Bp1P3/3P4/2P2N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nd5  8.e6  fxe6  9.Ng5  Nc7  10.dxc5  dxc5  11.Bf4  .  In both cases, Black's weak light squares are permanent problems and give us a substantial advantage. }
7. cxd4 Bg7
{ As usual, Black could insert  7...a6  8.Bd3  here.  I want to check @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npp1p/3p1np1/1B6/3PP3/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg7  , as it leads to the interesting question if we should pull the trigger now, with  8.e5  , or continue with development. }
8. Nc3
{ We should focus on development here and prefer  8.Nc3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/1B6/3PP3/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.O-O  over direct action in the center.  Let's examine: @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/1B6/3PP3/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.e5  Nd5  and now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p2p1/1B1nP3/3P4/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.e6  fxe6  10.Ng5  Nc7  leads nowhere for White. After  11.Nxe6  Nxe6  12.Qxe6  a6  we are even in trouble, as  13.Bc4  Ne5!  shows. An interesting comparison is the line we saw earlier: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npp1p/3p1np1/1Bp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg7?!  7.e5  Nd5  8.e6  fxe6  9.Ng5  Nc7  , when we have  10.dxc5!  dxc5  11.Bf4  and are much better.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p2p1/1B1nP3/3P4/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.exd6  can be answered with  9...e6  or the more complicated @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nppbp/3P2p1/1B1n4/3P4/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...a6!?  , when we have not accomplished much.   It's important to see how much Black is helped by the trade on d4, compared to the earlier  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npp1p/3p1np1/1Bp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg7?!  7.e5!  , which is great for White.  Alright, back to our choice,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/1B6/3PP3/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nc3  - by controlling d5, we now threaten e4-e5 with a much greater effect. }
8... a6
{ This is the only good move for Black.   After  8...O-O?  9.e5!  dxe5  10.dxe5  Ne8  11.O-O  , we have an overwhelming position. Black is confined to little space, and we can improve with simple moves - develop the c1-bishop, and place rooks on the open files. }
9. Bd3 O-O
{ Black can also play  9...e5  , when  10.dxe5  will lead to the same positions we'll examine in a minute.  Castling first is trickier because it allows us to go wrong. }
10. O-O
{ The most normal-looking move ever, but we need to avoid a misstep here. Don't play  10.e5?  , as  10...dxe5  11.dxe5  Ng4  is good for Black! Covering the pawn with  12.Bf4  fails to  12...Qa5  , and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1nppbp/p5p1/4P3/6n1/2NB1N2/PP2QPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.e6  is refuted by  12...Nde5!  , when Black is in great shape.  It is amazing to see how the insertion of ...a6 and Bd3 changes the tactics. If you go back to the notes to move 8, you see that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/1B6/3PP3/2N2N2/PP2QPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...O-O?  9.e5!  is great for White. A key difference is that after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/1B6/3PP3/2N2N2/PP2QPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...O-O?  9.e5!  dxe5  10.dxe5  Ng4  11.Bf4  Qa5  does not attack the e5-pawn, and  12.h3  is possible. }
10... e5
{ Black stops our e-pawn, finally.   The move  10...b5?!  , however, makes our advance stronger again, as  11.e5  dxe5  12.dxe5  Ng4  13.e6  Nde5  14.exf7+  Rxf7  15.Be4  shows. The final move of the sequence is key, stabilizing f3 and gaining a crucial tempo. }
11. dxe5
{ Simple and good. With our queen on e2, we are less eager to allow exd4, followed by ...Re8. Instead, taking on e5 leads to a nagging advantage for us. }
11... Nxe5
{ It makes sense for Black to include the knight trade, as d7 was not a happy place for it. }
12. Nxe5
{ We are happy to close the long diagonal again. Our main asset in this position is: our king's bishop is much better placed than Black's. }
12... dxe5 13. Bc4
{ There are some other good moves here, but it makes a lot of sense to emphasize our key advantage: the guy on c4 is much better than the one on g7. We'll play on the open files and the queenside, with moves like f3, Be3 and Rfd1 next.  A key conclusion about this early ...g6 line is: Black has some pitfalls to avoid, but that also applies to White. A properly timed e4-e5 advance can be very effective, but it needs to be carefully timed! }
