7... e5
{ Black goes for an ...e5-based setup, which gives the game a Ruy Lopez feel. This kind of structural transposition is not easy to make for all players on the black side, as they might have no or little experience defending a Ruy. }
8. d4
{ The usual question is: play d4 first, or castle first. It makes no substantial difference here, as we'll need both moves anyway. In this particular case, the order does not matter. }
8... Be7 { Black usually plays this move first, preparing kingside castling. }
9. O-O
{ You can make a case for  9.d5!?  here. We gain space and should have a small advantage. However, this is less clear-cut than in cases with a black bishop on b7.  I see nothing wrong in castling first and deciding on a central formation later. Black could trade on d4 to open the position, but this is rarely played and should help us. We gain the square c3 for a later knight development, for starters. }
9... O-O
{ A good move that avoids  9...Bb7?!  10.d5!  , which leads to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3n1ppp/p2p1n2/1pp1p3/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bb7  9.d5!  , of course. }
10. Rd1
{ After this move, we attack the pawn on e5. Black now almost always plays 10...Qc7, keeping the tension. }
10... Qc7
{ How to continue? As stated before, I am not a fan of closing the position with d4-d5 before Black has played their bishop to b7. It is an option, but  11.d5  Nb6  12.b3  c4  looks OK for Black. They can play ...Bd7 and ...Rfc8 to support the c-pawn. Black's bishop is a LOT better on d7 than on b7. I suggest keeping the central tension and attacking Black's queenside right away. }
11. a4 { We attack the pawn and ask Black for a commitment. How to cover it? }
11... Rb8
{ This is much better than  11...Bb7?!  , when  12.d5!  is strong again. After  12...c4  13.Na3  Black is not in time to consolidate their pawn formation. }
12. axb5 { Let's open the a-file. } 12... axb5
{ Playing a4 has given us the benefit of opening the a-file for our rook. This is particularly beneficial here, as Black has not yet developed the queenside minor pieces. Without the open file, our rook would have needed to wait longer to enter the game. }
13. h3
{ A difficult move at this point, but it makes a lot of sense. We want to develop our bishop to e3, but currently,  13.Be3  Ng4  is annoying. We invest a tempo in playing Be3 on the next move, undisturbed.   I'll end the trainable line here and continue with some sample lines and ideas.  A. @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/2qnbppp/3p1n2/1pp1p3/3PP3/2P2N1P/1PB1QPP1/RNBR2K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...c4  releases the tension. After  14.Be3  Re8  15.Nbd2  we are slightly better. It is always an option for us to play d4-d5 now and enter on a7 with our rook. It's also possible to play for b2-b3, but this requires preparation.   B. @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/2qnbppp/3p1n2/1pp1p3/3PP3/2P2N1P/1PB1QPP1/RNBR2K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Re8  is a way to keep the central tension. After  14.Be3  Bf8  is a good moment for  15.d5  , because  15...c4  16.Ra7  Rb7  17.Na3!  is an attractive idea.   C. @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/2qnbppp/3p1n2/1pp1p3/3PP3/2P2N1P/1PB1QPP1/RNBR2K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Bb7  is possible, too. Here  14.Na3  is interesting, as  14...b4  15.Nb5  looks a bit better for White, too.   These positions are all complex and interesting to play. I am happy with these structures, as Black started the game with different intentions. If they wanted to defend a Closed Ruy, they'd start with 1...e5, not with 1...c5! 😀 }
