{ A less popular, but good move. It's Anish Giri's choice in his Chessable LTR Najdorf, so it won't surprise you that I can't present a refutation of it 😀  White has some choice, though. You can pick your type of fight. First, we should castle and then consider what's on next. }
9. O-O Bg7
{ After Black's natural move, we have a choice. There is one very sharp move and a range of slower ones. I recommend the more cautious move, as it is more in the style of this repertoire, but I will show you the alternative - maybe you are more adventurous and want to try it. }
10. Rd1
{ That's my conservative suggestion for White.   The sharper alternative is  10.e5  , immediately crashing through in the center. It continues in a rather forced way with  10...Bxf3  11.gxf3  dxe5  12.dxe5  Nh5  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/3nppbp/p4np1/1pp1P3/8/2P2P2/PPB1QP1P/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nd5  is also possible, but I am sticking with Giri's line@@EndBracket@@, when White has a choice between @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/3nppbp/p5p1/1pp1P2n/8/2P2P2/PPB1QP1P/RNB2RK1 w kq - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.e6  or @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/3nppbp/p5p1/1pp1P2n/8/2P2P2/PPB1QP1P/RNB2RK1 w kq - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Rd1  Qc7  14.f4  , both lead to sharp and unclear play. Our kingside is not in great shape, but we have the bishops and play on the light squares. I could not find any advantage for White here and felt it was not the right choice as the main path to recommend.   The move  11.Rd1  has the idea to play e4-e5 under better circumstances, as Black has to be careful about the d-file @@StartBracket@@rook opposing queen@@EndBracket@@. We'll now examine Giri's suggestion and a worse alternative that is still frequently played. }
10... O-O
{ After this move, Black is walking a tightrope. Often, they don't manage to defend themselves perfectly and get into serious trouble. }
11. e5 Ne8
{ One of the two possible defences that Black has. Many other tries fail miserably. Here is an overview:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1b1nppbp/p2p1np1/1pp1P3/3P4/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNBR2K1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nd5?  12.e6  fxe6  13.Qxe6+  Kh8  14.Qh3  is awful for Black,  B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1b1nppbp/p2p1np1/1pp1P3/3P4/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNBR2K1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...dxe5?  12.dxe5  Nd5  13.e6  N7b6  14.exf7+  Rxf7  15.Ng5  is great for White, too,  C. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1b1nppbp/p2p1np1/1pp1P3/3P4/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNBR2K1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bxf3!  is the second defence that works after  12.Qxf3  dxe5  13.dxc5  , when we reach a complicated position with chances for both sides. We have a potentially strong c-pawn, but Black is well-centralized and developed. }
