5. Qe2
{ Black attacked the pawn, and we cover it.   There is an alternative here, though. White can also play  5.Bd3  ,  which has its points. The bishop might end on c2 anyway, so why not go there immediately? The drawback is that Black never needed to play ...a6 to kick the bishop and may use the tempo differently.  I am not a fan of the Bd3 setups for conceptual reasons, for the most part. If you play an early c3, you should be ready to occupy the center and not block the pawn.  How does it continue now? Black has to decide on the kingside development. The three options are ...g6, ...e6 and ...e5. The main question is when to decide on one of them. There are three possible moments:   A. Right now, after 5.Qe2. This is rarely played and is imprecise. We play d4 quickly and can retreat our bishop to d3, which saves a bit of time compared to the more common b5-a4-c2 route.   B. Black goes @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  and then decides on a central setup. This is very similar and often transposes to C below, as playing ...b5 is frequently useful and happens quickly.   C. Black first develops the queenside with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  b5  7.Bc2  Bb7  8.d4  and only then decides on a pawn formation.  B and C are very similar and of about equal strength.  I'll now continue to check the possibilities mentioned under A: the moves  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  . }
