{ This is Giri's suggestion. Inserting the trade on d4 takes out the sting of the pawn advance e4-e5. More on that subject in a minute. }
11. cxd4 O-O
{ Now it's a bad idea to play @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1b1nppbp/p2p1np1/1p6/3PP3/5N2/PPB1QPPP/RNBR2K1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.e5?  , as  12...Bxf3!  works fine for Black. White can't play  13.Qxf3  due to  13...dxe5  14.dxe5  Nxe5!  , when Black wins on the spot.  With c-pawns on the board, the pawn advance works as @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nppbp/p2p1np1/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNBR2K1 b kq - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10...O-O  11.e5  Bxf3  12.Qxf3  dxe5  13.dxc5!  is possible.  So we can't play the pawn advance. What else to do? I have checked some slower options, but Black's chances look fine. Something like @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1b1nppbp/p2p1np1/1p6/3PP3/5N2/PPB1QPPP/RNBR2K1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.a3  Rc8  13.Nc3  Nb6  14.Bd3  Qc7  leads to a position with little to play for. The c4-knight is strong, and we have no clear plan. The knight transfer to g3 is also not tempting, as Black has a pawn on g6 already.  I concluded that the best chance was to attack the b5-pawn immediately. }
12. a4
{ We put some pressure on b5 but are not yet threatening to capture it, as Black has their knight and bishop directed towards e4. }
12... Qc7
{ We follow Giri's suggestion. The queen move is very logical, connecting the rooks. }
13. Bd3
{ We increase the pressure on b5 but are still not threatening to take the pawn. }
13... e5
{ Here, Anish Giri concluded his analysis and assessed chances as equal. This is ultimately true, but Black still has to avoid some pitfalls. }
14. axb5
{ We'll trade on b5 and a8 first, leading to the first critical moment. } 14...
axb5 15. Rxa8 Rxa8
{ An important detail.   In the GM game A.David-I.Papaioannou, Black played  15...Bxa8?  . This is inaccurate due to  16.d5!  Nc5  17.Ne1  , when White has the advantage. We can protect our e-pawn with f3, while b5 remains weak and the a8-bishop is passive.  Taking with the rook is much better. }
16. dxe5
{ The move  16.d5?!  is much weaker now, as  16...Nc5  17.Ne1  b4  shows. Black is ready for ...Ba6 now, showing the large difference to  @@StartFEN@@R4rk1/1bqn1pbp/3p1np1/1p2p3/3PP3/3B1N2/1P2QPPP/1NBR2K1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bxa8?  @@StartBracket@@on the previous move@@EndBracket@@. }
16... dxe5
{ And another accurate move that Black needs to play.   After  16...Nxe5?!  17.Nxe5  dxe5  18.f3  we have a nagging advantage our e-pawn is safe, while Black's b-pawn remains a target. }
17. b4
{ I want to conclude the trainable with this move, which fixes the b-pawn.   You can play  17.Bxb5  , but Black is OK after  17...Nc5  or @@StartFEN@@r5k1/1bqn1pbp/5np1/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/1P2QPPP/1NBR2K1 b - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Bxe4  . Chances are equal in these lines, but they are an alternative if you prefer a position without further manoeuvring.   After  17.b4  , we'll get exactly that. Our idea is playing the bishop to c3, which keeps the b-pawn covered and puts some pressure on e5. This can be increased with Re1 @@StartBracket@@covering e4@@EndBracket@@ and Qb2. An important practical consideration is that Black always has to check whether we can take on b5.  The evaluation of 'equal' is certainly appropriate, but Black needed to be very precise to get there. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B3) Sicilian – Moscow 3...Nd7"]
[Black "Sicilian – Moscow 3...Nd7 4.c3 Ngf6 5.Qe2 a6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 Nf6
{ 'Knights out first' is one of the general rules you should always take with a grain of salt. However, there often is a strong logic to it. Here it's fairly clear that Black's knight is best on f6, so it makes sense to place it there first, with a tempo on our e-pawn. }
5. Qe2
{ Black attacked the pawn, and we cover it.   There is an alternative here, though. White can also play  5.Bd3  ,  which has its points. The bishop might end on c2 anyway, so why not go there immediately? The drawback is that Black never needed to play ...a6 to kick the bishop and may use the tempo differently.  I am not a fan of the Bd3 setups for conceptual reasons, for the most part. If you play an early c3, you should be ready to occupy the center and not block the pawn.  How does it continue now? Black has to decide on the kingside development. The three options are ...g6, ...e6 and ...e5. The main question is when to decide on one of them. There are three possible moments:   A. Right now, after 5.Qe2. This is rarely played and is imprecise. We play d4 quickly and can retreat our bishop to d3, which saves a bit of time compared to the more common b5-a4-c2 route.   B. Black goes @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  and then decides on a central setup. This is very similar and often transposes to C below, as playing ...b5 is frequently useful and happens quickly.   C. Black first develops the queenside with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qe2  a6  6.Ba4  b5  7.Bc2  Bb7  8.d4  and only then decides on a pawn formation.  B and C are very similar and of about equal strength.  I'll now continue to check the possibilities mentioned under A: the moves  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/3p1n2/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  . }
5... a6
{ Black gains time for their queenside expansion, a logical move and Black's most popular choice. }
6. Ba4
{ After this automatic move, Black's most obvious and popular move is  6...b5  , expanding with a tempo gain.   It is not the only move, though. Black can delay ...b5, but often will play the move soon enough and will transpose to lines that we'll examine via 6...b5 in a moment. There is an interesting move order question, though.   If Black plays @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1npppp/p2p1n2/2p5/B3P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  , for example, is it best to answer with  7.d4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1n1ppp/p2ppn2/2p5/B3P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O?  The issue about playing d4 first can be the vulnerable position of our a4-bishop, which Black may exploit with a quick ...Qa5.  The situation is slightly different for each move. Here is the overview and a simplified conclusion. There are two cases where the quick d4 is to be avoided:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1npppp/p2p1n2/2p5/B3P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.d4?!  im precrise due to  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  d5  9.e5  Qa5+  10.Nc3  Ne4  @@StartBracket@@not the only problematic line, there are more@@EndBracket@@.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1npppp/p2p1n2/2p5/B3P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  7.d4?!  Qa5!  is very annoying, as Black attacks our bishop and threatens ...cxd4! when we can't recapture with our pawn. In those two cases, you should castle first and play d4 next.   A different story is  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1npppp/p2p1n2/2p5/B3P3/2P2N2/PP1PQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e5  when both options work well.  This leads to the conclusion that the 'Keep It Simple' approach is: castle first, in all cases. }
6... b5 { Black hits our bishop and prepares ...Bb7, very natural play. } 7.
Bc2
{ Now Black most of the time plays  7...Bb7  , which certainly looks very logical.  There is an important alternative in @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  , though. It's important to note that Black should play ...e5 now and not delay it with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb7  8.d4  e5  , because  9.d5!  is great for White. We will examine this point in the notes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  in a moment.  Black may also play the moves @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e6  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...g6  , but will usually play ...b5 soon. It makes little sense not to play ...Bb7, an active way to develop the queenside.   This means we must check:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  is an important move and checked in detail,  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...c4?!  is ambitious but dubious against best play,  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e6  8.d4  Bb7  9.O-O  transposes to our main line,  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...g6  8.d4  Bb7  9.O-O  transposes to our main line in C and D  , you may also castle first and play d4 next - it makes no difference and looks very natural. }
7... Bb7
{ Black emphasizes the queenside development and only wants to commit to a central pawn formation on the next move. }
8. d4
{ We have arrived at an important crossroads. Black needs to decide how to develop the kingside. We'll consider the following options now:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6  is a popular and sound way for Black to play.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...g6  is seen less often but was recommended by Anish Giri in his Najdorf course. It can lead to sharp play, but it's our call to tackle this line - sharp or more strategically focused.  C. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  is frequently seen but has little independent value, as often Black will play ...e6 or ...g6 soon to get to positions similar to A or B. We'll check some independent possibilities and talk about possible 'semi-transpositions' to A or B.   D. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e5?!  is dubious due to  9.d5!  , when we transpose to a favourable line that we examine via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p2p1n2/1pp5/4P3/2P2N2/PPBPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  8.d4  Bb7  9.d5  , an alternative move order. }
8... e6
{ Black goes for 8...e6, which would probably be the move I'd play with the black pieces. They keep the tension and avoid possible problems related to e4-e5-e6, which is a factor in the ...g6-based system.  While I appreciate Black's approach, I don't think White has anything to complain about. We'll reach an interesting middlegame with all pieces and pawns on the board. }
9. O-O { We'll castle first and then decide how to proceed. } 9... Be7
{ Black prepares castling, too. Now we are at an important crossroads, as White has to decide on further plans. It looks to me that White has a range of options roughly of the same quality, so taste plays a role, for sure. }
10. Re1
{ I suggest this move, which is still not too committal. The main idea is twofold: we lend some additional protection to e4 and clear f1 for the knight tour Nd2-f1-g3 later. Our queenside is not developed, and the knight transfer to g3 is a standard idea, well-known from the Ruy Lopez.   As mentioned, White has some possible alternatives here. Some notes:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Rd1  is less precise than @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Re1  , I think. There is little chance the rook is doing anything useful on this file. On e1, it protects e4. If you like to prepare for the knight tour,  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Re1  looks better to me.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB1QPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.a4  is a different idea that I like more. If you want to investigate an alternative to 10. Re1, this is the one I'd go for. }
10... O-O
{ Or Black plays  10...Qc7  here, when you need to be aware of the threat ...cxd4 - we want to recapture with our c-pawn, so  11.Bd3!  must be played. We'll see the same idea again in a moment. }
11. Nbd2 Qc7
{ Attention: Black now wants to take on d4 - we need to ensure that we can recapture with our pawn. }
12. Bd3
{ We remove the bishop from the c-file. This ensures that we'll always be able to keep the center intact.   The move  12.Nf1  is possible, but we'll likely need to move the bishop at some point.   After  12.Bd3  , there are loads of possibilities for both sides. You can't analyze it like a position dependent on concrete tactics. I want to show some ideas to give you a better idea of what's going on.  A. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqnbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2PB1N2/PP1NQPPP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12...e5  can be answered by  13.d5  c4  14.Bc2  , with a slow, manoeuvring fight. This is not a great version of this structure, though. We have lost a lot of time with our bishop, which helps Black. I prefer a different idea.  After @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqnbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2PB1N2/PP1NQPPP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12...e5  I suggest  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.c4!  , which leads to a pawn structure change. Now  14...b4  15.Nf1  is the idea, transferring the knight to d5 via e3. This leads to an interesting strategic struggle, as we are quicker to use the d5-square.   B. Black can play @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqnbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2PB1N2/PP1NQPPP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12...cxd4  13.cxd4  e5  when we have the choice between advancing the d-pawn and keeping the tension. I'd suggest  14.b3  exd4  15.Bb2  , when we regain the pawn quickly.  C. Black can keep the tension and don't change the pawn structure. There are many possible moves to do that, of course. An idea that I like is @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqnbppp/p2ppn2/1pp5/3PP3/2PB1N2/PP1NQPPP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfc8  and now  13.a3!?  , which has the idea to play b4 at the right moment. A sample line for this point is  13...cxd4  14.cxd4  e5  15.b4  , which looks interesting. We fix the black queenside pawns on light squares and gain the b3-square for our knight. This line leads to equal chances and interesting positions to play.   The key point is that the slow nature of the game, often in the style of the Ruy Lopez, might not be the forte of many Sicilian players. This makes our choice a good practical weapon, in my mind. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This chapter covers Black's most popular reply to the Rossolimo: 3...g6, preparing the kingside fianchetto. It is played in roughly 50% of all the Rossolimo games and is a cornerstone of our Sicilian repertoire. Compared to the first edition, I have made some changes in my recommendations that I will discuss further in the notes to the fifth move. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1
{ I suggest playing  5.Re1  , just as I did in the first edition. There is an important difference, though. After Black's main reply,  5...Nf6  , I am now recommending  6.c3  ,  aiming for a full pawn centre. This continuation is more in line with the general spirit of our repertoire, which emphasises building a pawn duo e4&d4. The Ruy Lopez is the perfect example of this strategy, of course.   Now, seeing that we'll answer @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  with  6.c3  , what about playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  instead? This is indeed an excellent alternative, which I seriously considered. Let's briefly discuss the difference between the two.   The simple part is that  5.c3  Nf6  6.Re1  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  Nf6  6.c3  lead to the same position. However, @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  e5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  e5  differ considerably.After  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  e5  , we have the strategically complex but promising option  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.d3  ,  with a later queenside initiative in mind. The capture on c6 is not as promising after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  e5  ,  as the move c3 is less useful and weakens our central structure. White's best @@StartBracket@@and more or less only@@EndBracket@@ way forward is  6.d4!?  , an interesting pawn sacrifice. It usually continues with  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  exd4  8.Bf4  ,  when White has active pieces for the pawn and enough compensation. The conclusion is that 5.c3 involves a commitment to this gambit play, while 5.Re1 is more geared towards a strategic battle.   It's a tough call between these concepts, but I decided to stick with  5.Re1  for consistency reasons. We play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  5.Re1  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.O-O  Nge7  5.Re1  ,  which makes the rook move look very consistent.There is one conceptual difference, though. In the mentioned lines, we play Re1 to prepare Bf1 in reply to ...a6, as the capture on c6 had become unattractive. Here, in the  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.O-O  Bg7  5.Re1  line, we will take on c6 frequently, as it creates doubled pawns that we can exploit.Here is an overview of Black's options. A and B are the most important by a mile, played in about 75-80% of the games. We'll also check some minor moves, as their study has enormous instructional value.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is very popular and logical   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  aims to block the centre. It's Black's second most popular move.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6?  is bad due to  6.c3  & d4 - we get the full centre and Black has no counterplay.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6?  is met by  6.e5!  ,  which is surprisingly strong. We study these four moves with trainable lines.   A fifth move worth mentioning is @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6?!  , when the capture leads to a good game for us, so we don't mind giving up the bishop pair. In this particular situation, there is also no good alternative. After  6.Bf1?  e5!  our play is very toothless. After  6.Bxc6  bxc6  7.h3!  we transpose to an excellent position that we examine via 3...a6 in the Rossolimo sidelines chapter. Please have a look at this chapter for more information.Relatively better is probably  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/1p1pppbp/p1B3p1/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...dxc6  , but it does not merit special coverage. We'll play  7.d3  and reach a very similar position to one of the following two lines:   A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  in the Rossolimo sidelines chapter.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  g6  4.O-O  Bg7  5.Re1  e5  6.Bxc6  dxc6  , which is a main option in the current chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e6
{ Combining the moves ...e6 and ...g6 does not work well for Black in the Rossolimo. It weakens the dark squares substantially and is slow. We should open the position quickly to exploit this deficit. }
6. c3
{ A tough call here, as  6.Bxc6  is just as good. This was my recommendation in the first edition, intending to answer  6...bxc6  with  7.c3  - this is very good for White. I am now switching to 6. c3, as the theme of playing c3&d4 is so prominent in the course. }
6... Nge7
{ That was Black's idea, of course. They have discouraged the capture on c6, but we are playing for central dominance. }
7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 d5
{ Black needs some pawn in the centre. Here  8...O-O  9.d5  looks awful for Black. }
9. e5
{ And we have reached a dream French-type position. After  9.e5  , a typical continuation could be  9...Bd7  10.Nc3  O-O  11.h4  h6  12.Bf4  putting pressure on Black's kingside. We are much better here as Black's kingside is seriously weakened, and they have no clear counterplay. An interesting line to compare is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  g6  3.c3  Bg7  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  d5  6.e5  , when a similar scenario arises frequently. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 d6
{ Attaching a question mark to this move is a bit harsh, but it is a mistake. In practice, White quite often fails to punish it. }
6. e5
{ A very strong reply! Black's pawn structure is seriously weakened now, as we'll see in a minute. A word about two alternatives:   A.  6.Bxc6+  bxc6  7.e5!  is very similar to my recommendation and just as good.   B.  6.c3  is not a bad move, but a bit pedestrian in comparison to the best options. After  6.c3  Bg4!  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  White is slightly better, but not more. }
6... dxe5 7. Nxe5 Bd7
{ Here  7...Qc7  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Qf3!  is great for White, too. } 8. Bxc6
{ Taking with the knight is just as good. } 8... Bxc6
{ Black's other capture is no better:  8...bxc6  9.Qf3  Nf6  10.Nxc6  already wins a pawn. }
9. Nxc6
{ I am stopping the trainable line here, as after  9...bxc6  about every sensible move is good enough to give White a large advantage. Black's pawn structure is destroyed, and we have good ways to use it. A typical plan is playing d3 and moving our knight to c4, a fantastic, uncontested square. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5
{ The only fully respectable alternative to  5...Nf6  .  Black clamps down on d4 and intends to develop with Nge7 next. }
6. Bxc6
{ One of the few cases where I recommend taking on c6 when still relatively unprovoked. Why is the capture a good choice? There is no one-sentence answer because Black has two possible recaptures, and we need different plans against each. Let's discuss the two moves and see why White should keep a pull. }
6... bxc6
{ Black captures towards the centre, according to an old 'rule' that rarely applies in the opening. Well, I am just making a joke here, but VERY often, taking away from the centre makes a lot of sense to speed up development.   In the case at hand, Black should also prefer  6...dxc6  , the far more popular move. Let's see how to exploit Black's sideline. }
7. c3
{ White opens up the centre while being better developed and ultimately aims to target central weaknesses, particularly d6. Contrary to general wisdom, it is often an idea to open the position against the Bishop pair - it's a matter of timing and often very much dependent on concrete factors. We'll see that Black's c8-bishop has a difficult time ever becoming relevant, which is the key issue. }
7... Ne7 { The next moves are more or less forced and always played. } 8. d4
cxd4 9. cxd4 exd4 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. Nc3
{ This sequence is forced after 7. c3. Black's main problem is that the pawns on d7 and c6 have problems moving to set up a reliable central structure. There will always be some square or pawn weakness that White might play against. As a logical consequence, the c8-bishop remains passive. }
11... Rb8
{ This move is the most challenging to face. Black activates their rook before we might play Bf4 to stop it.Black has some much worse alternatives:   A.  11...d5?  12.exd5  cxd5  13.Bg5  a  lready amounts to a disaster for Black. Their position is full of holes and weaknesses.   B.  11...h6  12.Bf4  d6  14.Qd2  is terrible for Black, too. The d6-pawn is too weak.   C.  11...Qb6  attacks our knight, but after  12.Nb3  we threaten Be3 with tempo. Black has gained nothing. }
12. Nb3
{ White threatens Bf4-d6 now with a deadly bind. I already recommended this move in the first edition, and I still like it for White.   A good alternative is the engine alternative  12.h3  , arguing that Black has no great move. }
12... d5
{ The most interesting try. After  12...Qc7  13.Be3  d6  14.Bd4  , we trade off Black's best piece and have a substantial advantage. Black's pawns are long-term weaknesses. }
13. Bf4
{ This looks best and most forcing as we attack Black's rook. Let's see how it may continue:   A.  13...Rb7  can be answered with a queen move to c1 or c2.   B.  13...Rb4  is more interesting when the black rook exerts some pressure on the fourth rank. A good reply is  14.Qd2  ,  which threatens the discovered attack Nxd5 and keeps an advantage, as  14...a5  15.Bg5  or  15.Rad1  are good ways to increase the pressure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5
{ The only fully respectable alternative to  5...Nf6  .  Black clamps down on d4 and intends to develop with Nge7 next. }
6. Bxc6
{ One of the few cases where I recommend taking on c6 when still relatively unprovoked. Why is the capture a good choice? There is no one-sentence answer because Black has two possible recaptures, and we need different plans against each. Let's discuss the two moves and see why White should keep a pull. }
6... dxc6
{ This is more reliable than  6...bxc6  . Black opens a path for the c8-bishop and increases control over the d4-square, which leads to an entirely different game than  6...bxc6  ,  when c3&d4 opens the centre favourably.  We won't play in the center. Our target in the ...dxc6 pawn structure is the queenside. Depending on Black's setup, we have multiple ways of attacking this side of the board, but our main device will be a pawn break: a3&b4. We'll start with a universally useful move that we need anyway. }
7. d3
{ Now we need to consider three moves by Black. Our strategy against them is quite similar, but there are enough differences to make a split worthwhile. We want to open the queenside with a3&b4, attacking Black's weakened pawn structure.   A.  7...Ne7  is the most popular move below master level. it looks normal to develop the knight and prepare to castle, but the move has a serious drawback: the knight is passively placed on e7 and does not connect to the dark squares that will be crucial in the coming battle on the queenside.   B.  7...Qe7  covers the e-pawn and prepares ...Nf6-d7 to help cover the queenside. This move is likely the best choice for Black and the most popular on the GM level.   C.  7...Qc7  follows a similar idea, but the different queen position changes some details, compared to B. }
7... Ne7
{ This looks natural, but the knight is not ideally placed on e7. Our plan to open the queenside works better here, compared to 7...Qe7 or 7...Qc7. }
8. a3 { It's also possible to start with  8.Be3  here. } 8... a5
{ Black tries to slow us down this way. After  8...O-O  9.b4  cxb4  10.axb4  ,  we have an excellent position. Black has no counterplay, as ...f5 is tough or even impossible to engineer. We can easily build up pressure on the queenside. Moves like Be3 and knight tours to c4 or b3-c5, or a5 come to mind. }
9. Be3 { We develop and provoke ...b6. } 9... b6 10. Nbd2
{ Black's defensive task is tough now. Even with the best play, they will be worse, but a wrong move can easily lead to disaster. I will have a look at  10...a4  and  10...O-O  now. }
10... O-O { Black is walking a tightrope after this move. } 11. Nc4
{ More convincing than  11.b4  cxb4  12.axb4  a4  , which I rather want to avoid. }
11... Bg4
{ The only move, as  11...Qc7?  12.b4!  is a disaster.  12...axb4  13.axb4  Rxa1  14.Qxa1  b5  15.Ncxe5  leads to a dominating position for White. }
12. h3 { We get rid of the pin and force Black to give up the bishop pair. }
12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3
{ We have a comfortable advantage here. Black has avoided a breakdown on the queenside, but there are other ideas. The comp suggests  13...a4  14.Qg3  ,  followed by h4-h5. A sudden change in the battle area, but it makes a lot of sense. h4-h5 and the knight tour Nd2-f3 looks scary for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 e5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5
{ The only fully respectable alternative to  5...Nf6  .  Black clamps down on d4 and intends to develop with Nge7 next. }
6. Bxc6
{ One of the few cases where I recommend taking on c6 when still relatively unprovoked. Why is the capture a good choice? There is no one-sentence answer because Black has two possible recaptures, and we need different plans against each. Let's discuss the two moves and see why White should keep a pull. }
6... dxc6
{ This is more reliable than  6...bxc6  . Black opens a path for the c8-bishop and increases control over the d4-square, which leads to an entirely different game than  6...bxc6  ,  when c3&d4 opens the centre favourably.  We won't play in the center. Our target in the ...dxc6 pawn structure is the queenside. Depending on Black's setup, we have multiple ways of attacking this side of the board, but our main device will be a pawn break: a3&b4. We'll start with a universally useful move that we need anyway. }
7. d3
{ Now we need to consider three moves by Black. Our strategy against them is quite similar, but there are enough differences to make a split worthwhile. We want to open the queenside with a3&b4, attacking Black's weakened pawn structure.   A.  7...Ne7  is the most popular move below master level. it looks normal to develop the knight and prepare to castle, but the move has a serious drawback: the knight is passively placed on e7 and does not connect to the dark squares that will be crucial in the coming battle on the queenside.   B.  7...Qe7  covers the e-pawn and prepares ...Nf6-d7 to help cover the queenside. This move is likely the best choice for Black and the most popular on the GM level.   C.  7...Qc7  follows a similar idea, but the different queen position changes some details, compared to B. }
7... Ne7
{ This looks natural, but the knight is not ideally placed on e7. Our plan to open the queenside works better here, compared to 7...Qe7 or 7...Qc7. }
8. a3 { It's also possible to start with  8.Be3  here. } 8... a5
{ Black tries to slow us down this way. After  8...O-O  9.b4  cxb4  10.axb4  ,  we have an excellent position. Black has no counterplay, as ...f5 is tough or even impossible to engineer. We can easily build up pressure on the queenside. Moves like Be3 and knight tours to c4 or b3-c5, or a5 come to mind. }
9. Be3 { We develop and provoke ...b6. } 9... b6 10. Nbd2
{ Black's defensive task is tough now. Even with the best play, they will be worse, but a wrong move can easily lead to disaster. I will have a look at  10...a4  and  10...O-O  now. }
10... a4 { This move makes it more difficult to open the queenside. } 11. b3
{ It's also possible to not play this break immediately, but prepare it with a different move first. Moves like  11.Nc4  and  11.Qb1  are just as good, given that you play for b3 next. We want to open the queenside quickly. }
11... O-O
{ Black can't even consider  11...axb3?  , as  12.Nxb3  ,  followed by a4-a5, dismantles the queenside. }
12. bxa4 Rxa4 13. Qb1
{ Our idea is playing Qb3 and/or Nc4. If Black retreats the rook, a4-a5 is the plan. Black needs to defend carefully to stay in the game, which is a fair assessment of the whole 7...Ne7 variation. }
