[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 e5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5
{ The only fully respectable alternative to  5...Nf6  .  Black clamps down on d4 and intends to develop with Nge7 next. }
6. Bxc6
{ One of the few cases where I recommend taking on c6 when still relatively unprovoked. Why is the capture a good choice? There is no one-sentence answer because Black has two possible recaptures, and we need different plans against each. Let's discuss the two moves and see why White should keep a pull. }
6... dxc6
{ This is more reliable than  6...bxc6  . Black opens a path for the c8-bishop and increases control over the d4-square, which leads to an entirely different game than  6...bxc6  ,  when c3&d4 opens the centre favourably.  We won't play in the center. Our target in the ...dxc6 pawn structure is the queenside. Depending on Black's setup, we have multiple ways of attacking this side of the board, but our main device will be a pawn break: a3&b4. We'll start with a universally useful move that we need anyway. }
7. d3
{ Now we need to consider three moves by Black. Our strategy against them is quite similar, but there are enough differences to make a split worthwhile. We want to open the queenside with a3&b4, attacking Black's weakened pawn structure.   A.  7...Ne7  is the most popular move below master level. it looks normal to develop the knight and prepare to castle, but the move has a serious drawback: the knight is passively placed on e7 and does not connect to the dark squares that will be crucial in the coming battle on the queenside.   B.  7...Qe7  covers the e-pawn and prepares ...Nf6-d7 to help cover the queenside. This move is likely the best choice for Black and the most popular on the GM level.   C.  7...Qc7  follows a similar idea, but the different queen position changes some details, compared to B. }
7... Qe7
{ This is played to cover e5 and thus prepare Nf6. Nf6 is the first step for a possible later Nd7-f8-e6-d4. }
8. a3
{ White has a wide choice here, but I still like my suggestion from the first edition. Trying to open the queenside quickly makes a logical impression.   Black now usually continues development with  8...Nf6  , but they may also try  8...a5  to close the queenside. }
8... a5 { Black doesn't want to allow b2-b4 without a fight. } 9. Nbd2
{ This is a new suggestion, compared to  9.Be3  Nf6  10.a4  from the first edition. It's not a bad plan to close the queenside and shift focus to other ideas - very long-term f2-f4 is an idea in such a structure.  Still, my choice was clear when I discovered that after 9.Nbd2 it is still possible to play for b2-b4. }
9... Nf6
{ Black's usual reply might not be best. The move 9.Nbd2 is a newer idea, so there aren't as many game samples to draw from. The engine prefers  9...Be6  , when I'd suggest  10.b3  ,  planning to go Nc4 next. A later Bd2 and b3-b4 is still an option. }
10. Nc4 Nd7 11. Bg5 { An annoying move for Black, forcing a small concession. }
11... f6 12. Bd2 a4
{ This looks a bit better than  12...b6  13.b4  , but we still manage to open the queenside now. }
13. b4
{ And finally, we have managed to push the b-pawn as we wanted all along. After  13...axb3  14.cxb3  O-O  15.Qc2  we have pressure on the queenside, with the idea to play a4 and prepare b4 next. It's tough to play for Black, who has no counterplay. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 e5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5
{ The only fully respectable alternative to  5...Nf6  .  Black clamps down on d4 and intends to develop with Nge7 next. }
6. Bxc6
{ One of the few cases where I recommend taking on c6 when still relatively unprovoked. Why is the capture a good choice? There is no one-sentence answer because Black has two possible recaptures, and we need different plans against each. Let's discuss the two moves and see why White should keep a pull. }
6... dxc6
{ This is more reliable than  6...bxc6  . Black opens a path for the c8-bishop and increases control over the d4-square, which leads to an entirely different game than  6...bxc6  ,  when c3&d4 opens the centre favourably.  We won't play in the center. Our target in the ...dxc6 pawn structure is the queenside. Depending on Black's setup, we have multiple ways of attacking this side of the board, but our main device will be a pawn break: a3&b4. We'll start with a universally useful move that we need anyway. }
7. d3
{ Now we need to consider three moves by Black. Our strategy against them is quite similar, but there are enough differences to make a split worthwhile. We want to open the queenside with a3&b4, attacking Black's weakened pawn structure.   A.  7...Ne7  is the most popular move below master level. it looks normal to develop the knight and prepare to castle, but the move has a serious drawback: the knight is passively placed on e7 and does not connect to the dark squares that will be crucial in the coming battle on the queenside.   B.  7...Qe7  covers the e-pawn and prepares ...Nf6-d7 to help cover the queenside. This move is likely the best choice for Black and the most popular on the GM level.   C.  7...Qc7  follows a similar idea, but the different queen position changes some details, compared to B. }
7... Qe7
{ This is played to cover e5 and thus prepare Nf6. Nf6 is the first step for a possible later Nd7-f8-e6-d4. }
8. a3
{ White has a wide choice here, but I still like my suggestion from the first edition. Trying to open the queenside quickly makes a logical impression.   Black now usually continues development with  8...Nf6  , but they may also try  8...a5  to close the queenside. }
8... Nf6
{ Black's main move by far. They prepare castling and don't try to stop our b-pawn. }
9. b4
{ Here we go. White immediately opens up the queenside. Of course, a slower course of action is also possible. }
9... O-O
{ Taking the b-pawn would be a serious concession. Black can't play  9...cxb4  10.axb4  Qxb4?  , as  11.Ba3  gives White a fantastic attack. Playing 10...Qxb4? is naive, of course. It would be better to play a sensible move like castling, but we have clearly benefited from the opening of the queenside. }
10. bxc5 Qxc5
{ Black can also play  10...Nd7  when  11.a4  Nxc5  12.Ba3  leads to the same structure. The queen capture has been the recent preference on the GM level, but White still retains a pull. }
11. a4
{ A simple threat to win the exchange, but it's not about a simple trick. Gaining space on the queenside is useful, and Ba3 may be attractive even without immediately winning material. }
11... Re8 12. Ba3
{ This looks very natural and was played successfully in 2022 by Anish Giri vs Wang Hao, but it's not clear if it is best. Stockfish also likes a setup with h3 and Be3, which looks good, too.   The mentioned game continued  12...Qa5  13.Nbd2  Be6  14.Qb1  Qc7  and now  15.Ng5  would be a small engine improvement on Giri's  15.a5  .  I think that White has a nagging pull in this type of position, as Black has to defend the weakened squares, and their bishop pair doesn't count for much. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 Nf6
{ Black develops the kingside and prepares to castle. It's a very natural move and the most popular one. }
6. c3
{ In the first edition of the course I recommended  6.e5  , which remains a good option. My main incentive to switch to  6.c3  is the conceptual consistency with the Ruy Lopez. Building a pawn centre by playing c3&d4 is a logical concept here is a challenging approach for Black.How can the game continue from here? Here is an overview. There are mostly three scenarios.   A.  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  d5   B.  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  cxd4  8.cxd4  d5   C. Black plays ...a6 at some point, forcing a decision about our bishop.     A and B are very similar lines. By inserting the capture on d4, Black is limiting their options. A usual scenario is a transposition to comfortable lines of A.We will focus the coverage on lines A and B, which occur in about 80-90% of the games. Option C is rare, but Black has different moments to go for ...a6, and it might be unclear if you haven't studied it.As Black is experiencing problems in A/B, option C might become more popular. White looks better, but the positions are not as well-explored.   After  6.c3  , Black almost always castles. The other rare idea is  6...a6  to attack our bishop. }
6... a6
{ Black attacks our bishop and forces a decision. To take or not to take, that's the question. }
7. Bxc6
{ As usual in this chapter, or general against all the unprepared ...a6 moves, I suggest capturing on c6.   The move  7.Bf1  is not a mistake, but it makes Black's life easier after  7...O-O  8.d4  d5  when they reach a better version of the current chapter's main line. In those lines, we often capture c6 to worsen Black's structure. }
7... dxc6
{ Black's almost exclusive choice. They avoid  7...bxc6  8.e5  Nd5  9.c4  Nc7  10.Nc3  , when we have a comfortable advantage. This position is very similar to the line we examine in the Rossolimo sidelines chapter. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Bxc6  bxc6  5.O-O  g6  6.Re1  Bg7  7.h3!  Nf6  8.e5  Nd5  9.c4  Nc7  10.Nc3  ,  we reach almost the same position - the extra tempo h3 is nice, but not a large difference. We are much better in both cases, going for d4 next to open the position favourably.   After  7...dxc6  , we reached an interesting position. It's interesting to compare it to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.O-O  g6  6.Re1  .  In this variation, we play a d3-based setup and avoid the move c3, preferring the stable pawn chain c2-d3-e4. With c3 already on the board, a d3-based continuation is still possible, but I want to suggest a different option. }
8. h3
{ We start with this move to prevent ...Bg4 and want to play d4 next to occupy the centre. In this scenario, we'll see that Black's bishop has no good squares, making h3 a tempo well-spent. }
8... O-O
{ The move  8...c4?  is refuted by  9.b3  cxb3  10.axb3  ,  when Black has strengthened our centre even more. Trading the d-pawn vs the a-pawn can't be good. }
9. d4
{ Going for a full pawn centre. It is possible to play  9.d3  here for a slower, manoeuvring game. White continues with moves like Be3, Qc2 and Nbd2 and tries to exploit Blacks's weakened queenside.   I suggest  9.d4  ,  though. There are two reasons: White preserves an advantage, and it makes a lot of sense from a repertoire perspective. Black may play  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  7.d4  a6  , when  8.Bxc6  dxc6  9.h3  transposes to our position on the board. This way, one solution works for both lines. }
9... cxd4
{ Black manages to get rid of their doubled pawns, but it does not solve some key issues. Le's consider after our recapture. }
10. cxd4
{ Black has three basic problems in this position. - We have a full pawn centre that is not easily challenged - The c8-bishop has no clear role or development perspective - The queenside's dark squares are permanently weakened.   I think Black has only one satisfactory reply now. I will check the moves  10...c5!  and  10...Qc7?!  to demonstrate why Black should rather push the c-pawn instead. }
10... Qc7
{ I think Black should take the chance to strike with  10...c5  - a slow move like this looks too passive. }
11. Nc3 Rd8
{ A natural move, lining up the rook against our queen. Playing  11...b5  is strategically risky, as the c-pawn and the c5-square may end up terminally weak. After  12.Bd2  c5  13.dxc5  Qxc5  14.Rc1  Black is in trouble because of the various Nd5 and e4-e5 ideas. }
12. Bd2
{ A strong move! We want our rook on c1 as soon as possible to be ready for ...c5 ideas. It looks more natural to play  12.Be3  ,  but placing the bishop on d2 allows the capture of dxc5, as we will see. The bishop move to e3 is still much better for White but after  12.Bd2  it looks like Black is in even more trouble. }
12... c5
{ This fails to convince, but it's tough to give Black good advice. If they go for a slow move like  12...a5  , we play  13.Rc1  and Black will likely never manage ...c5. We can slowly improve and exploit the queenside weaknesses in such a position. One idea is Na4, Qc2 and playing for d4-d5 next. Black has no active ideas, which gives us time to prepare carefully. }
13. Rc1
{ Black is more or less busted now. We threaten to take and win the c-pawn, and  13...b6  14.dxc5  bxc5  15.Na4  hardly counts as a solution. }
