[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 Nf6
{ Black develops the kingside and prepares to castle. It's a very natural move and the most popular one. }
6. c3
{ In the first edition of the course I recommended  6.e5  , which remains a good option. My main incentive to switch to  6.c3  is the conceptual consistency with the Ruy Lopez. Building a pawn centre by playing c3&d4 is a logical concept here is a challenging approach for Black.How can the game continue from here? Here is an overview. There are mostly three scenarios.   A.  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  d5   B.  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  cxd4  8.cxd4  d5   C. Black plays ...a6 at some point, forcing a decision about our bishop.     A and B are very similar lines. By inserting the capture on d4, Black is limiting their options. A usual scenario is a transposition to comfortable lines of A.We will focus the coverage on lines A and B, which occur in about 80-90% of the games. Option C is rare, but Black has different moments to go for ...a6, and it might be unclear if you haven't studied it.As Black is experiencing problems in A/B, option C might become more popular. White looks better, but the positions are not as well-explored.   After  6.c3  , Black almost always castles. The other rare idea is  6...a6  to attack our bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Black's almost universal choice. Castling is the most natural move in the world. We played c3 to prepare the central pawn push, so our choice is easy now. }
7. d4
{ Now we need to consider some options for Black.   A.  7...d5  is the main line and probably the best move. Black is correctly concerned about our centre rolling forward, so they fight for central space.   B.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  d5  is a worse version of A, as we are happy about the trade on d4. It only helps White, as far as I can see.   C.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  and other tries than 8... d5.   D.  7...a6  8.Bxc6  dxc6  9.h3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  7.Bxc6  dxc6  8.h3  O-O  9.d4  , which is slightly better for White. Black can't deviate with  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1pppbp/p1B2np1/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...bxc6?  , as  9.e5  Nd5  10.dxc5  wins a pawn with a large advantage. }
7... cxd4
{ Black goes for the pawn trade, a choice that we are happy about. This can only help our cause, as we will see. }
8. cxd4
{ Now Black's main move, by a large margin, is  8...d5  , when  9.e5  Ne4  10.Be3  transposes to  7...d5 8.e5 Ne4 9.Be3 cxd4 10.cxd4, a main line of the current chapter. I will also discuss  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1B6/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d6  and  8...a6  , which look better for White, too. }
8... d6
{ This move is a conceptual mistake. Black has given us a full pawn centre and now fails to fight against it. }
9. h3
{ A very typical move, stopping ...Bg4. It leaves the c8-bishop without any reasonable squares to go to. I like  9.h3  the most, but  9.d5  is a good alternative. }
9... Bd7
{ We'll have a look at this move. Black could also start with  9...a6  when White has a range of good bishop moves. I like  10.Bf1  , but  10.Bd3  is an option, too. This position may also occur via @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1B6/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a6  9.Bd3  d6  ,  a rare move order. The position of the bishop @@StartBracket@@f1 compared to d3@@EndBracket@@ does not change the situation fundamentally. White's advantage is based on the strong centre, which applies regardless of the bishop's position. }
10. Nc3 { The trade of the c-pawn always allows this comfortable development. }
10... a6
{ Always a tricky question: where to retreat the bishop? Or is taking an option? }
11. Bf1
{ I generally like this tidy bishop retreat, but you can also make a case for other moves. White would be better after  11.Ba4  ,  11.Bc4  and after  11.Bxc6  , as the central dominance, is the key factor in all cases. }
11... Rc8
{ This is the most popular choice, often combined with the move ...b5. A different direction is  11...e5  ,  when you have a choice between advancing the d-pawn or trading on e5. The advance leads to a good version of a King's Indian structure. If you feel at home there, it is a good option. If you want a different structure, trading on e5 is a good alternative. In such a scenario, Black's g7-bishop is always an issue, giving White some advantage. }
12. Be3 { Or  12.Bf4  , which is just as good. } 12... b5 13. a3
{ A good moment to assess the position. We have a comfortable advantage due to the strong centre. Black always has to reckon with e4-e5 or d4-d5, which makes it difficult to play. Black's queenside advance may backfire in the long run, too. }
