{ Black's almost universal choice. Castling is the most natural move in the world. We played c3 to prepare the central pawn push, so our choice is easy now. }
7. d4
{ Now we need to consider some options for Black.   A.  7...d5  is the main line and probably the best move. Black is correctly concerned about our centre rolling forward, so they fight for central space.   B.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  d5  is a worse version of A, as we are happy about the trade on d4. It only helps White, as far as I can see.   C.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  and other tries than 8... d5.   D.  7...a6  8.Bxc6  dxc6  9.h3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  7.Bxc6  dxc6  8.h3  O-O  9.d4  , which is slightly better for White. Black can't deviate with  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1pppbp/p1B2np1/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...bxc6?  , as  9.e5  Nd5  10.dxc5  wins a pawn with a large advantage. }
7... cxd4
{ Black goes for the pawn trade, a choice that we are happy about. This can only help our cause, as we will see. }
8. cxd4
{ Now Black's main move, by a large margin, is  8...d5  , when  9.e5  Ne4  10.Be3  transposes to  7...d5 8.e5 Ne4 9.Be3 cxd4 10.cxd4, a main line of the current chapter. I will also discuss  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1B6/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d6  and  8...a6  , which look better for White, too. }
8... a6
{ Black can play 8...a6 at various moments. Here's a list to help you understand the difference.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  a6  is the earliest - we capture  7.Bxc6  . At this early stage, we haven't even played d4 yet, so a retreat to d3 makes no sense.  7.Bf1  is a bit passive, so we take on c6.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  a6  is a bit different. I suggest  8.Bxc6  ,  as it is a simple transposition to A. The move  8.Bd3  is an option, but  8...d5!  9.e5  Ne4  looks OK for Black. In comparison, taking c6 and transposing to A looks better.   C. Our case here is, again, a bit different. It is possible to play  9.Bxc6  dxc6  10.h3  ,  again transposing to A. However, the trade on d4 has changed the situation compared to B. After  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1pppbp/p1n2np1/1B6/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bd3!  d5  10.e5  Ne4  , we have  11.Nc3  to challenge the intruder on e4, a consequence of the early trade on d4.  Therefore 9.Bd3! is my choice. }
9. Bd3
{ Even better than taking on c6. Now I'll focus on  9...d5  , as  9...d6  leads to structures that I examine via 8...d6, a more common way to reach them. White is much better due to the significant space advantage in the centre. }
9... d5 10. e5 Ne4
{ Not an easy move to make. Black needs to understand that White's pawn grab  11.Bxe4?  dxe4  12.Rxe4  Bf5  13.Re1  Bg4  gives excellent compensation for the pawn.   In practice, many players go for  10...Ne8?!  , when their situation is even worse after  11.h3  Nb4  12.Nc3  Nxd3  13.Qxd3  Bf5  14.Qe2  ,  when Black's knight will be a bad piece for a long while. Their bishop pair is no compensation, as the one on g7 is so passive. We'll also have better prospects on the c-file - a very pleasant situation. }
11. Nc3
{ A lot better than snatching the pawn. The knight move is the simplest solution, but  11.h3  also looks good, stopping the bishop pin. }
11... Nxc3 12. bxc3
{ We have an excellent position based on the large space advantage on the kingside. An attacking idea based on Bf4, Qd2, and Bh6 is simple yet effective. Black can play  12...Bg4  , but after  13.h3  Bxf3  14.Qxf3  ,  the situation has not changed. We can still attack, but rather with h4-h5 this time. Black's only idea is counterplay against c3, but this weakness is minor. }
