[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B4) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...g6 4.O-O Bg7 5.Re1 Nf6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 Nf6
{ Black develops the kingside and prepares to castle. It's a very natural move and the most popular one. }
6. c3
{ In the first edition of the course I recommended  6.e5  , which remains a good option. My main incentive to switch to  6.c3  is the conceptual consistency with the Ruy Lopez. Building a pawn centre by playing c3&d4 is a logical concept here is a challenging approach for Black.How can the game continue from here? Here is an overview. There are mostly three scenarios.   A.  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  d5   B.  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  cxd4  8.cxd4  d5   C. Black plays ...a6 at some point, forcing a decision about our bishop.     A and B are very similar lines. By inserting the capture on d4, Black is limiting their options. A usual scenario is a transposition to comfortable lines of A.We will focus the coverage on lines A and B, which occur in about 80-90% of the games. Option C is rare, but Black has different moments to go for ...a6, and it might be unclear if you haven't studied it.As Black is experiencing problems in A/B, option C might become more popular. White looks better, but the positions are not as well-explored.   After  6.c3  , Black almost always castles. The other rare idea is  6...a6  to attack our bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Black's almost universal choice. Castling is the most natural move in the world. We played c3 to prepare the central pawn push, so our choice is easy now. }
7. d4
{ Now we need to consider some options for Black.   A.  7...d5  is the main line and probably the best move. Black is correctly concerned about our centre rolling forward, so they fight for central space.   B.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  d5  is a worse version of A, as we are happy about the trade on d4. It only helps White, as far as I can see.   C.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  and other tries than 8... d5.   D.  7...a6  8.Bxc6  dxc6  9.h3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  7.Bxc6  dxc6  8.h3  O-O  9.d4  , which is slightly better for White. Black can't deviate with  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1pppbp/p1B2np1/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...bxc6?  , as  9.e5  Nd5  10.dxc5  wins a pawn with a large advantage. }
7... d5
{ Black's main reply to consider. Black wants a foothold in the centre and avoids the early trade on d4. }
8. e5
{ An important feature of our concept is the strong central pawn chain, limiting Black's bishop on g7. }
8... Ne4 9. Be3
{ We develop and attack the c-pawn, limiting Black's choice. They can take on d4 or play ...Qb6 to address our threat. An important motive to consider: Black's central knight does not have any possible retreat squares. It is not in danger of getting trapped at the moment, but the lack of retreats affects how to evaluate other moves. For instance,  9...Bg4?  makes no sense at all, as  10.h3  Bxf3??  11.gxf3!  wins the knight. }
9... cxd4
{ Black goes for the trade. As usual, the trade makes our decisions a bit easier. }
10. cxd4
{ This position also frequently occurs via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - d3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  d5  9.e5  Ne4  and now  10.Be3  is the transposition.   Now it's tough to suggest a different move than  10...Qb6  , which is by far the most popular and more or less the only move played on the master level. Let's check quickly why some alternatives are dubious.   A.  10...Bg4?  fails to the simple  11.h3  , when Black can't play  11...Bxf3??  12.gxf3  , which drops a piece.   B.  10...f6?  11.Nc3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  fxe5  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.Nxe5  looks terrible for Black, too. We dominate on the dark squares, as often happens in this structure. }
10... Qb6
{ This looks best for Black. We will still keep an advantage, but the alternatives make a worse impression. }
11. Bxc6
{ We will only examine the queen recapture because  11...bxc6  12.Qc1  leads to a position that more commonly arises via 9...Qb6 10.Bxc6 bxc6 11.Qc1 cxd4 12.cxd4, our chapter's main line. }
11... Qxc6
{ Black captures with the queen, avoiding the backward c-pawn and possible weak c5-square. What is our goal now? There is no clear structural target, but we can still hope for a small pull. The idea is to reach a position with a knight against Black's c8-bishop, which points into thin air. This concept will become clearer after our next move. }
12. Nfd2
{ We have two moves with a similar idea. This one and the interesting alternative  12.Ng5  . I suggest  12.Nfd2  , as it is a bit simpler to handle. Now  12...Nxd2  13.Qxd2  Bf5  14.Nc3  shows our basic idea. We'll play Bh6 soon, trading off the bishops, which leaves our knight vs Black's ineffective bishop. This is not much, but easier for White to play. Black can't completely avoid this scenario, but they can be more cunning than simply taking on d2. }
12... Be6
{ This move sets a deep trap that I want to show, as you can easily stumble into it. }
13. f3
{ We force the capture and get the same structure as after 12...Nxd2, only with the added move f3 - not a huge difference.   What's the trap I was talking about? The move  13.Nb3  looks tempting, but after  13...f5!  14.f3  f4  15.Bc1  Black has the amazing move  15...Rad8!!  ,  played by Magnus Carlsen in an online rapid game against Polish No.1 Jan-Krzysztof Duda. The engine thinks the whole thing is about equal, but I rather have a small advantage with  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp2ppbp/2q1b1p1/3pP3/3Pn3/4B3/PP1N1PPP/RN1QR1K1 w - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.f3  and try to grind from a position of total safety. }
13... Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Rfc8 15. Nc3
{ And we have reached the same situation as after the earlier 12...Nxd2 - the added moves f3 and ...Be6 make no difference. White has a slight advantage, as Black's e6-bishop will remain a passive piece. We can trade the other bishops with Bh6 and have a flexible knight against the dummy on e6.I don't want to sound too optimistic here, as Black should not lose with good defense. It is still nice to play for two results as White - losing is NOT one of the results. :-@@EndBracket@@ }
