{ Black's main reply to consider. Black wants a foothold in the centre and avoids the early trade on d4. }
8. e5
{ An important feature of our concept is the strong central pawn chain, limiting Black's bishop on g7. }
8... Ne4 9. Be3
{ We develop and attack the c-pawn, limiting Black's choice. They can take on d4 or play ...Qb6 to address our threat. An important motive to consider: Black's central knight does not have any possible retreat squares. It is not in danger of getting trapped at the moment, but the lack of retreats affects how to evaluate other moves. For instance,  9...Bg4?  makes no sense at all, as  10.h3  Bxf3??  11.gxf3!  wins the knight. }
9... Qb6
{ Black attacks our bishop. We are happy to take on c6, as both recaptures lead to favourable outcomes. }
10. Bxc6
{ Capturing c6 is strong and secures White some advantage. A key point to remember is our answer to  10...bxc6  , which is not an obvious move. }
10... Qxc6
{ This capture leads to different positions than  10...bxc6  ,  but they both share a theme. We have given up our bishop for excellent dark-square control, which is the motivation behind our next move. }
11. dxc5 { We clear the d4-square for our pieces. } 11... Nxc5
{ Black restores material equality. } 12. h3
{ We stop any ...Bg4 ideas. This move is not strictly necessary, as  12.Na3  Bg4?!  13.Nd4!  demonstrates. In the long run, however, we'll likely need h3, so let's play it right away.Our idea in this position is a domination of the light squares. We claim that Black's light-squared bishop is a bad piece and ideally want to achieve a position that features a monster knight on d4 against a dumb bishop. We have a step-by-step plan to get closer. - Play Na3-c3-d4 - Play Bf4, Qd2 and Bh6, if possible. - Trade a pair of knights. In the meantime, it is unclear what Black's aim is - besides trying to prevent the horror scenario painted above.   Here's an interesting sample line from a GM Blitz game. After  12.h3  b6  13.Na3  Ba6  15.Nc2  Nd3?!  White had the strong move  16.Nb4!  ,  when Black was in severe trouble in the game Alexandra Goryachkina-Piotr Nguyen, played in 2021. White controls the excellent square d4, and the open c-file helps greatly. An idea like Rc1 and Nd4 comes with tempo. }
