1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 Nf6
{ Black develops the kingside and prepares to castle. It's a very natural move and the most popular one. }
6. c3
{ In the first edition of the course I recommended  6.e5  , which remains a good option. My main incentive to switch to  6.c3  is the conceptual consistency with the Ruy Lopez. Building a pawn centre by playing c3&d4 is a logical concept here is a challenging approach for Black.How can the game continue from here? Here is an overview. There are mostly three scenarios.   A.  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  d5   B.  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  cxd4  8.cxd4  d5   C. Black plays ...a6 at some point, forcing a decision about our bishop.     A and B are very similar lines. By inserting the capture on d4, Black is limiting their options. A usual scenario is a transposition to comfortable lines of A.We will focus the coverage on lines A and B, which occur in about 80-90% of the games. Option C is rare, but Black has different moments to go for ...a6, and it might be unclear if you haven't studied it.As Black is experiencing problems in A/B, option C might become more popular. White looks better, but the positions are not as well-explored.   After  6.c3  , Black almost always castles. The other rare idea is  6...a6  to attack our bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Black's almost universal choice. Castling is the most natural move in the world. We played c3 to prepare the central pawn push, so our choice is easy now. }
7. d4
{ Now we need to consider some options for Black.   A.  7...d5  is the main line and probably the best move. Black is correctly concerned about our centre rolling forward, so they fight for central space.   B.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  d5  is a worse version of A, as we are happy about the trade on d4. It only helps White, as far as I can see.   C.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  and other tries than 8... d5.   D.  7...a6  8.Bxc6  dxc6  9.h3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  7.Bxc6  dxc6  8.h3  O-O  9.d4  , which is slightly better for White. Black can't deviate with  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1pppbp/p1B2np1/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...bxc6?  , as  9.e5  Nd5  10.dxc5  wins a pawn with a large advantage. }
7... d5
{ Black's main reply to consider. Black wants a foothold in the centre and avoids the early trade on d4. }
8. e5
{ An important feature of our concept is the strong central pawn chain, limiting Black's bishop on g7. }
8... Ne4 9. Be3
{ We develop and attack the c-pawn, limiting Black's choice. They can take on d4 or play ...Qb6 to address our threat. An important motive to consider: Black's central knight does not have any possible retreat squares. It is not in danger of getting trapped at the moment, but the lack of retreats affects how to evaluate other moves. For instance,  9...Bg4?  makes no sense at all, as  10.h3  Bxf3??  11.gxf3!  wins the knight. }
9... Qb6
{ Black attacks our bishop. We are happy to take on c6, as both recaptures lead to favourable outcomes. }
10. Bxc6
{ Capturing c6 is strong and secures White some advantage. A key point to remember is our answer to  10...bxc6  , which is not an obvious move. }
10... bxc6
{ Now we arrive at an important moment. We have to do something about the hanging b-pawn. }
11. Qc1
{ This is a strong move and a good moment to discuss our strategy. We have traded on c6 and given up our bishop pair. In return, we have weakened Black's queenside structure. An additional consequence is emphasised control of the dark squares. We have three minor pieces that can fight for the dark squares; Black only has two.   This concept becomes the most apparent if Black captures on d4. After  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  ,  the square c5 is weak, and we can connect all minor pieces with it, while the Black's c8-bishop has no target to attack. This is a key concept. We try to prove that this bishop is operating on empty diagonals. A dream scenario after the trade on d4 would be to play with a knight on c5 against the lights-squared bishop.Let's see how our strategy unfolds. I'll examine 11...cxd4, 11...c4, and 11...Rb8 now. It's tough to say what Black's best defence is, as they suffer a bit in all of them. }
11... c4 { Black makes sure that the c-file remains closed, } 12. Nbd2
{ We need to get rid of the knight first. } 12... Nxd2 13. Nxd2
{ A good move to remember. We take with the knight to prepare b2-b3 next. }
13... Bf5
{ Black needs to find a role for the bishop. It's well-placed on f5, keeping an eye on b1. }
14. b3
{ The idea of the knight capture. Black has only one move now.   A.  14...cxb3?  15.Nxb3  is terrible for Black. Our knight reaches c5.   B.  14...Bd3  is best when White has some choice.  15.Qa3  is the most played move, but the engine suggests, unsurprisingly, to go for  15.h4  ,  later followed by Qd1-f3 ideas. This looks a bit better to me than playing the queen to a3.The position in B is one of the better defensive tries for Black. It's still rather passive but makes a solid impression. The engine's idea to switch to the kingside makes some sense. Considering bxc4 at the sight moment is also interesting, as ...dxc4 might allow Ne4. }
*

