{ Black attacks our bishop. We are happy to take on c6, as both recaptures lead to favourable outcomes. }
10. Bxc6
{ Capturing c6 is strong and secures White some advantage. A key point to remember is our answer to  10...bxc6  , which is not an obvious move. }
10... bxc6
{ Now we arrive at an important moment. We have to do something about the hanging b-pawn. }
11. Qc1
{ This is a strong move and a good moment to discuss our strategy. We have traded on c6 and given up our bishop pair. In return, we have weakened Black's queenside structure. An additional consequence is emphasised control of the dark squares. We have three minor pieces that can fight for the dark squares; Black only has two.   This concept becomes the most apparent if Black captures on d4. After  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  ,  the square c5 is weak, and we can connect all minor pieces with it, while the Black's c8-bishop has no target to attack. This is a key concept. We try to prove that this bishop is operating on empty diagonals. A dream scenario after the trade on d4 would be to play with a knight on c5 against the lights-squared bishop.Let's see how our strategy unfolds. I'll examine 11...cxd4, 11...c4, and 11...Rb8 now. It's tough to say what Black's best defence is, as they suffer a bit in all of them. }
11... Rb8
{ After our forced reply  12.b3  Black often trades on d4 when we transpose to 11...cxd4, but there is one interesting independent try. }
12. b3
{ Only move. Now Black usually captures on d4, transposing to the line 11...cxd4 12.cxd4 Rb8, a common position. There is one different try that is worth checking. }
12... Qa5
{ This move could be irritating, as they put some pressure on c3. After  12...Qa6  , we'd have the simple  13.Nbd2  with a large advantage, as we finally manage to provoke the trade on d4.   Note that Black has a limited choice. The line  12...a5?  13.dxc5!  Nxc5?  14.Qa3  is a nice example of a pitfall they might stumble into. }
13. dxc5
{ We start a forced sequence, correctly evaluating that Black's capture on b3 is no problem. }
13... Rxb3 14. axb3 Qxa1 15. b4
{ I found five master games in my database, and White won them all! Not a bad result and an indication that we are in good shape. It's not that bad of a position for Black, though.   Our idea is Nd4, which attacks c6 and threatens f3. According to the engine, a logical move and best for Black is  15...Qa4  ,  which covers c6 in anticipation of the knight jumping to d4. In the game Fabiano Caruana-Daniil Dubov, Wijk an Zee 2020,  16.Nd4!?  was played anyway, giving up a pawn. After  16...Bxe5  17.f3  Nf6  18.Qa3  Qxa3  20.Nxa3  White had compensation for the pawn and went on to win a great game.A more pedestrian alternative is  16.Nbd2  ,  though, when White is a bit better without giving up a pawn. After  16...a5  17.Qb2  axb4  18.cxb4  ,  we are quicker on the a-file and can still target c6 with Nd4. }
