12... Rb8
{ Black plays this move most of the time, particularly below master level. A closer look shows that provoking b3 might even help White, as we get control of a4 @@StartBracket@@...a5-a4 is a plan for Black@@EndBracket@@ and get the Qa3 idea for free. }
13. b3
{ Forced, but it is a good move. I want to check the move 13...f6 now, as it leads to more direct play. }
13... f6
{ Black attacks our centre and wants to find some use for the bishop. As usual,  13...Bg4?  14.h3  is bad, while @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/p3ppbp/1qp3p1/3pP3/3Pn3/1P2BN2/P4PPP/RNQ1R1K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...a5  14.Nc3  Nxc3  15.Qxc3  is the comfortable edge we want. }
14. Nc3
{ Finally the knight joins it to either trade Black's best piece or jump to a4. }
14... Bf5
{ Black keeps it complicated. After  14...Nxc3  15.Qxc3  Bg4  16.exf6  exf6  17.Bf4  ,  we are better in a one-sided position. Black has weaknesses, and we have the potential to invade. The idea Bd6-c5 comes to mind. }
15. Na4
{ This looks best, aiming at the c5-square. After  15...Qa5  I suggest  16.exf6  exf6  17.Nd2  ,  trading Black's best piece and clearing the way to c5. }
