[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B5) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e6 & 3...d6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e6 & 3...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ This chapter covers Black's second and third most popular reply to the Rossolimo, the moves @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  . Covering these moves in one chapter makes a lot of sense once you see Black's concept and how we counter it.  Let's have a look at the main lines of both:   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  5.Re1  a6  6.Bf1  ,  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.O-O  Nge7  5.Re1  a6  6.Bf1  .  Conceptually, there is a clear pattern. Black wants to get rid of our bishop without allowing a doubled pawn. Therefore, they play ...d6 & ...Bd7 or ...e6 & ...Nge7 to enable a piece to recapture on c6.  We counter both moves in the same way, too: by playing O-O and Re1, we clear the f1-square for our bishop. Once we have established this tidy kingside setup, we are ready to play in the center with c3&d4 or just d4, depending on the concrete lines.  If Black plays well, we'll see that White has good chances of maintaining a small edge in both lines. There are plenty of opportunities to go wrong for Black, of course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B5) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e6 & 3...d6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ Black opts for 3...d6, reaching a position that could also arise via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  Nc6  , as a less common sequence.  Black's basic idea is to play ...Bd7 and ...a6, kicking our bishop back without accepting doubled pawns. }
4. O-O
{ Just as after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  , we castle first. It's a move we need anyway, and being ready for Re1 to protect e4 is useful.   Now Black's only fully satisfactory move is  4...Bd7  , breaking the pin and preparing ...a6. Are there alternatives worth checking?   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg4?!  is dubious, but worth checking. We examine it in a trainable line.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6?!  looks odd, and after  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  6.e5!  transposes to a line that we examine via  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  in the chapter on rare Rossolimo lines.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6?  looks wrong due to  5.e5  , when  5...dxe5  6.Nxe5  will lead to a damaged pawn structure for Black. They should avoid @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/1Bp1P3/8/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxe5  , but moving the knight again is not ideal, either. We have too much of a development advantage here. }
4... Bg4
{ This move is quite ambitious, trying to set up a counter pin on our knight. It's a dubious choice, but worth checking. }
5. c3
{ We are aiming for the ideal pawn center e4&d4. In this case, d4-d5 would even be fatal for Black's knight. They have to react in some way. }
5... Nf6
{ Black has no fully satisfactory way here, but this looks relatively best.   You may encounter two alternatives:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P1b1/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qb6  6.Ba4  Nf6  7.d4  O-O-O  is a very risky line that features queenside castling by Black in the Rossolimo - a rare sight! After  8.Bxc6  Qxc6  9.d5  White is much better, as we have a ready-made attack on Black's king - preparing b2-b4 is not rocket science.   B. @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P1b1/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  is a common move, but  6.Bxc6+  bxc6  7.d4  is much better for White. We examine some similar positions in the Rossolimo sidelines chapter. White's development advantage is too severe to overcome for Black. }
6. d4
{ There is no need to spend time covering the e-pawn. We occupy the center and threaten d4-d5 now. There is a good reason why Black usually plays ...Bd7 and ...a6 first, and only then moves the bishop to g4. }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4 a6
{ Black has to do something about the pin and the d4-d5 threat. } 8. Bxc6+ bxc6
9. Nc3 e6
{ Black has also tried  9...g6  , which looks even worse. After  10.h3  , they have to give up the bishop pair, as  10...Bd7?  11.e5  is a disaster. }
10. h3 { The direct  10.Qa4  is just as powerful. } 10... Bh5 11. Qa4
{ Black is in terrible shape here. c6 is attacked, and there is no good way for Black to handle this threat. }
11... Qd7
{ This move requires a strong response.   After  11...Qc7  12.d5  Black's queenside is falling apart without any effort. }
12. Nd2
{ I was surprised to see that this move is the only one to secure an advantage! But it is more or less decisive, as Black has to deal with too many threats now. There is Nc4, combined with ideas of e4-e5. Black's h5-bishop is also short on squares, given the move f2-f4.   A sample to illustrate this point is @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/3q1ppp/p1pppn2/7b/Q2PP3/2N4P/PP1N1PP1/R1B2RK1 b kq - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Be7  12.f4  h6  14.Nc4  Rb8  15.f5  , when Black has no good way to stop g2-g4, winning the piece. }
