[White "B5) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e6 & 3...d6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ Black opts for 3...d6, reaching a position that could also arise via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  Nc6  , as a less common sequence.  Black's basic idea is to play ...Bd7 and ...a6, kicking our bishop back without accepting doubled pawns. }
4. O-O
{ Just as after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  , we castle first. It's a move we need anyway, and being ready for Re1 to protect e4 is useful.   Now Black's only fully satisfactory move is  4...Bd7  , breaking the pin and preparing ...a6. Are there alternatives worth checking?   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg4?!  is dubious, but worth checking. We examine it in a trainable line.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6?!  looks odd, and after  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  6.e5!  transposes to a line that we examine via  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  in the chapter on rare Rossolimo lines.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6?  looks wrong due to  5.e5  , when  5...dxe5  6.Nxe5  will lead to a damaged pawn structure for Black. They should avoid @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/1Bp1P3/8/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxe5  , but moving the knight again is not ideal, either. We have too much of a development advantage here. }
4... Bd7
{ This is by far the most popular and best move. Others delay the development even more and are quite risky. }
5. Re1
{ There is nothing fundamentally wrong about  5.c3  here  , but I prefer the rook move.   The reasoning is similar to the situation after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.O-O  Nge7  , when Black is ready to answer Bxc6 with a piece recapture and avoids the doubled pawn. This makes the capture unattractive for White, and we need to decide if we want to retreat the bishop via a4-c2 or f1. In both cases going to f1 is a better choice, as it doesn't allow Black's queenside expansion with tempo.   Now, after @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  , Black's best setup is  5...Nf6  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  Bg4  , pinning our knight. We can also reach this position via the move order @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Nf6  7.c3  Bg4  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Bg4  7.c3  Nf6  - all lead to the same position.  Our job is quite simple here: if they play ...a6, we retreat to f1. Otherwise, we continue with the logical move c3 to prepare our central expansion.   I will examine @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  as the path to the main position on move  7. We will also examine @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@5...g6  to illustrate why Black usually goes for the setup mentioned above. }
5... g6
{ This move is a conceptual mistake, as it does not fight our plan to build a full pawn center.   In the main line  5...Nf6  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  Bg4  Black pins our knight and makes d4 more difficult to play. I'll talk more about this topic once we arrive at this key moment. }
6. c3 { We want the full center with c3+d4, so here we go. } 6... Bg7
{ If Black goes for  6...a6  , playing  7.Bf1  is a satisfactory reply. However, you could make an argument for @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/1p1bpp1p/p1np2p1/1Bp5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bxc6  Bxc6  8.d4  , trying to open up the position as fast as possible. We are ahead in development by a lot, so it makes sense. Stockfish slightly prefers the capture, but this is more of a matter of taste. }
7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4
{ A great position for White. We have the dream center and are ahead in development. }
8... Nf6 9. Nc3 O-O
{ After Black has castled, the move ...Bg4 becomes possible again. We should spend a tempo on preventing it. }
10. h3
{ A strong prophylactic move. In this position, Black has problems finding a job for their d7-bishop. An additional problem is the lack of a clear plan for counterplay. We have a large space advantage and easy moves to improve, like developing the c1-bishop and playing Rc1. Black also has to worry about pawn advances in the center.   After  10...a6  11.Bf1  @@StartBracket@@other bishop retreats aren't bad here, either@@EndBracket@@  11...b5  , we have  12.e5  Ne8  13.a4  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/3bppbp/p1np1np1/1p6/3PP3/2N2N1P/PP3PP1/R1BQRBK1 w - b6 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.d5  Na5  13.Bd2  Rc8  14.b3  , both leading to a nice advantage. In one case, the knight on e8 is bad; in the other, they suffer from the offside knight on a5. }
