{ This is by far the most popular and best move. Others delay the development even more and are quite risky. }
5. Re1
{ There is nothing fundamentally wrong about  5.c3  here  , but I prefer the rook move.   The reasoning is similar to the situation after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.O-O  Nge7  , when Black is ready to answer Bxc6 with a piece recapture and avoids the doubled pawn. This makes the capture unattractive for White, and we need to decide if we want to retreat the bishop via a4-c2 or f1. In both cases going to f1 is a better choice, as it doesn't allow Black's queenside expansion with tempo.   Now, after @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  , Black's best setup is  5...Nf6  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  Bg4  , pinning our knight. We can also reach this position via the move order @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Nf6  7.c3  Bg4  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Bg4  7.c3  Nf6  - all lead to the same position.  Our job is quite simple here: if they play ...a6, we retreat to f1. Otherwise, we continue with the logical move c3 to prepare our central expansion.   I will examine @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  as the path to the main position on move  7. We will also examine @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@5...g6  to illustrate why Black usually goes for the setup mentioned above. }
5... Nf6
{ Heading for the main line, in most cases. As mentioned before, they could also start with  5...a6  to reach this main position we are about to examine. }
6. c3
{ According to plan. We are now ready to play d4, which Black should fight. }
6... a6 7. Bf1
{ We prepared this retreat with the early Re1.   Now Black has two continuations: the main move  7...Bg4  and @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1bpppp/p1np1n2/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  , gaining some ground in the center. }
7... e5
{ The only serious alternative to  7...Bg4  , staking a claim in the center. }
8. h3
{ White spends a tempo avoiding the pin after d2-d4.   You may play  8.d4  immediately, but after  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Bg4  , you need to deal with the c6-knight coming to d4 in many cases. I like to avoid it, but it is not objectively bad for White.   Now we'll check the solid @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1b1ppp/p1np1n2/2p1p3/4P3/2P2N1P/PP1P1PP1/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  and the wild move @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1b1ppp/p1np1n2/2p1p3/4P3/2P2N1P/PP1P1PP1/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...g5  , which is good to know. }
8... g5
{ A bit of a shocker, and not objectively good. I was even more critical of the move in the first edition, but it is not AS bad as I thought. }
9. Nxg5
{ This is a change on the line I recommended in the first edition. I suggested  9.d4  g4  10.hxg4  Bxg4  11.d5  , but these positions are not that simple to handle.  I think taking the pawn is a better practical solution. }
9... Rg8
{ That's Black's idea. They attack our knight and want to take the h3-pawn after it moves away. }
10. d4
{ This is much better than retreating. We will try to open the center immediately - Black's king is still on e8, after all. }
10... h6
{ The only good move.   Instead,  10...cxd4?  11.cxd4  Nxd4  12.Nc3  h6  13.Nf3  is great for White. Black's position is full of weaknesses, and they have no attack on the g-file. }
11. Nf3 Bxh3
{ Black has regained the pawn. Now we have a fundamental choice: how to handle the central tension? }
12. dxe5
{ I suggest this move, as it leads to a risk-free, stable advantage.   From a purely analytical point of view, the engine suggestion  12.d5  might be slightly more powerful. White closes the center and plays on the queenside, while Black has the g-file play going.  By taking on e5, we go for a queen trade and take away all the fun for our opponent. }
12... Nxe5
{ Here  12...dxe5  13.Qxd8+  Rxd8  14.Nbd2  is a similar story. We are better due to the better pawn structure. }
13. Nxe5 { We continue to trade, reaching a nice position at the end. } 13...
dxe5 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Nd2
{ We have a nagging advantage in this endgame, as Black has some weaknesses. Their kingside has split pawns, and the queenside is not entirely safe, either. I like this position from a psychological point of view: Black played very ambitiously with the early ...g5 and now has to defend a slightly worse endgame. }
