[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B5) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e6 & 3...d6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6
{ This move is Black's second most popular one against the Rossolimo. Its basic idea is to cover the c6-knight with ...Nge7 and then chase our bishop with ...a6. They want to only play ...a6 after ensuring that a piece can recapture on c6. }
4. O-O
{ Here, White's main alternative is  4.Bxc6  , immediately creating an imbalance in the position. White gives up the pair of bishops but creates weaknesses in Black's camp.  I prefer @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  for our repertoire because it is easier to learn and understand.  In the introduction to the current chapter, I spoke about the conceptual overlaps between 3...e6 and 3...d6 - this was an important factor in making the repertoire as consistent as possible. }
4... Nge7
{ The consistent move after 3...e6. Black is now ready for ...a6, attacking our bishop without worrying about doubled pawns. They also prepare the move ...d5, a common feature of our main line.   Alternatives don't require deeper study. The move  4...a6  provokes the capture when  5.Bxc6  will transpose to position types we examine via the move order 3...a6 featured in the subsequent chapter.   Sometimes you meet  4...Nf6  when many natural replies are good. You can play  5.e5  Nd5  6.Nc3  , as I suggested in the first edition, or prefer @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/2n1pn2/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  , planning c3&d4 later. Both options @@StartBracket@@and some more@@EndBracket@@ look convincing and comfortable to play. }
5. Re1
{ We have to decide how to retreat our b5-bishop after the expected move ...a6. We could play  5.c3  , signalling our intention to drop it to b3/c2 later. This is similar to the Ruy Lopez, which would fit with our choice in the 1.e4 e5 universe.  However, a closer look has led me to conclude that clearing  f1  for our bishop is a better choice. This is certainly a matter of taste to some degree, but I like that we play in the same way after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  when we face a similar choice. }
5... a6
{ Black almost always plays this move first and only after our bishop retreat decides their further setup.  Black's main choices are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  d5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng6  , which are of about equal strength.  We'll also look at the weaker move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6?!  , demonstrating why mixing ...e6 and ...g6 doesn't go well.   I am presenting this overview here because Black could omit the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  and start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ng6  , when  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  is a transposition to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Ng6  7.c3  , which we examine in a minute.  Black may also play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6?!  here, which is just as dubious as one move later and similarly handled  @@StartBracket@@  6.d4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnp1p/2n1p1p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  & d4 next is good  @@EndBracket@@.  Finally, the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d5?  looks really odd, as  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.d4  is a much better version of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  d5  7.exd5  Nxd5  , as analyzed later.  Long story short: it makes sense for Black to start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  .  Going @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ng6  is not a mistake, though, and likely will transpose to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Ng6  , after all. }
6. Bf1
{ Preserving our bishop, according to plan. Now Black has to commit in some way to a development scheme. Here's an overview of the options that we will examine:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  is Black's most popular move. After  7.exd5  Nxd5  8.d4  , the position opens, and we retain a small advantage.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng6  leads to a more complex game, often reminiscent of the French Defence.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6?!  is dubious for Black, as they weaken the dark squares too much.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...b5?!  gains space on the queenside but gives us attacking targets on this side of the board. }
6... Ng6
{ Black's traditional main line,  6...d5  , is not attractive for Black if they are looking for a more unbalanced position. If Black wants to fight, they often go for @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng6  , which will lead to positions more typical of the French Defence. }
7. c3
{ We prepare d4, a logical plan in our opening concept. The position on the board could also appear via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ng6  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  , which is a common route, too. }
7... Be7
{ Black prepares the move ...d5 this way.   The immediate  7...d5  8.exd5  Qxd5  is dubious, as the black queen is vulnerable in the center. Good moves for White are  9.Na3  or  9.d4  , both leading to a nice advantage. We examine a similar line in this chapter: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  7.exd5  Qxd5  , which shares the same problems. }
8. d4 cxd4
{ Black has to take first and avoid  8...d5?  , which is refuted by  9.exd5  Qxd5  @@StartBracket@@taking with the pawn drops c5@@EndBracket@@  10.c4  Qd8  11.d5  with a central breakthrough. Black has to be careful with any center opening, as our development lead is substantial. }
9. cxd4 d5 10. e5
{ Advancing the pawn and entering a French-type structure is best here.   White has also tested  10.exd5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2bppp/p1n1p1n1/3p4/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQRBK1 w kq d6 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nc3  , but I am convinced that grabbing ventral space is more promising here. Why exactly? What's the difference to a French Advance Variation?  In the French Advance, Black usually focuses their counterplay on the d4-pawn, the base of White's pawn chain. A line like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nf3  Qb6  6.a3  Nh6  @@StartBracket@@  planning ...Nf5@@EndBracket@@ comes to mind. In our version of the Rossolimo, Black's knight is on g6, unable to exert any pressure on d4.  Black has to generate some counterplay against White's center, though. Sitting passively and waiting for White to build up on the kingside is no option. This leads to the conclusion that Black's only plan is ...f6 here, attacking the pawn chain differently.  For this pawn break, the knight is placed well on g6. We will take on f6 and then have clear targets on the e-file, a scenario I like. Let's have a look at how this unfolds. }
10... O-O 11. Nc3
{ After this natural development move, I'll focus on the reply  11...f6  for Black. I think Black needs to go for a pawn break to get counterplay - playing it straightaway makes sense.   If Black does not go for ...f6, we plan to play g3&h4-h5, attacking Black's knight. We'll have a look at the move  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2bppp/p1n1p1n1/3pP3/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQRBK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bd7  to illustrate this plan. }
11... Bd7
{ I selected this move to demonstrate White's ideas against a passive approach.   I also found many games with  11...b5  , which is a strange plan. Why would Black want to put the bishop on b7 and weaken the queenside? Against this move, the plan we'll examine now would also work well. }
12. g3
{ We not only prepare h4-h5 this way, but also enable a later Bh3 in case Black still wants to play for ...f6, when e6 is our target @@StartBracket@@see the 11...f6 line for this scenario@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Rc8
{ Black could still play ...f6 here, and should do that before it's too late. }
13. h4
{ Now we have gotten to the point where Black needs to play the f-pawn. } 13...
f6
{ Black can't allow something like  13...Bb4  14.h5  Nge7  15.h6  , when their kingside is falling apart. }
14. h5
{ That's the problem with waiting with ...f6 for too long. Now we'll get a much better version of 11...f6, as  14...Nh8  15.exf6  Bxf6  16.Bf4  or @@StartFEN@@2rq1rkn/1p1b2pp/p1n1pb2/3p3P/3P4/2N2NP1/PP3P2/R1BQRBK1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bh3  demonstrates. Black's knight is not ideal on h8! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B5) Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e6 & 3...d6"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6
{ This move is Black's second most popular one against the Rossolimo. Its basic idea is to cover the c6-knight with ...Nge7 and then chase our bishop with ...a6. They want to only play ...a6 after ensuring that a piece can recapture on c6. }
4. O-O
{ Here, White's main alternative is  4.Bxc6  , immediately creating an imbalance in the position. White gives up the pair of bishops but creates weaknesses in Black's camp.  I prefer @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  for our repertoire because it is easier to learn and understand.  In the introduction to the current chapter, I spoke about the conceptual overlaps between 3...e6 and 3...d6 - this was an important factor in making the repertoire as consistent as possible. }
4... Nge7
{ The consistent move after 3...e6. Black is now ready for ...a6, attacking our bishop without worrying about doubled pawns. They also prepare the move ...d5, a common feature of our main line.   Alternatives don't require deeper study. The move  4...a6  provokes the capture when  5.Bxc6  will transpose to position types we examine via the move order 3...a6 featured in the subsequent chapter.   Sometimes you meet  4...Nf6  when many natural replies are good. You can play  5.e5  Nd5  6.Nc3  , as I suggested in the first edition, or prefer @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/2n1pn2/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Re1  , planning c3&d4 later. Both options @@StartBracket@@and some more@@EndBracket@@ look convincing and comfortable to play. }
5. Re1
{ We have to decide how to retreat our b5-bishop after the expected move ...a6. We could play  5.c3  , signalling our intention to drop it to b3/c2 later. This is similar to the Ruy Lopez, which would fit with our choice in the 1.e4 e5 universe.  However, a closer look has led me to conclude that clearing  f1  for our bishop is a better choice. This is certainly a matter of taste to some degree, but I like that we play in the same way after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  when we face a similar choice. }
5... a6
{ Black almost always plays this move first and only after our bishop retreat decides their further setup.  Black's main choices are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  d5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng6  , which are of about equal strength.  We'll also look at the weaker move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6?!  , demonstrating why mixing ...e6 and ...g6 doesn't go well.   I am presenting this overview here because Black could omit the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  and start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ng6  , when  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  is a transposition to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Ng6  7.c3  , which we examine in a minute.  Black may also play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6?!  here, which is just as dubious as one move later and similarly handled  @@StartBracket@@  6.d4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnp1p/2n1p1p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  & d4 next is good  @@EndBracket@@.  Finally, the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d5?  looks really odd, as  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.d4  is a much better version of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  d5  7.exd5  Nxd5  , as analyzed later.  Long story short: it makes sense for Black to start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  .  Going @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ng6  is not a mistake, though, and likely will transpose to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Bf1  Ng6  , after all. }
6. Bf1
{ Preserving our bishop, according to plan. Now Black has to commit in some way to a development scheme. Here's an overview of the options that we will examine:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  is Black's most popular move. After  7.exd5  Nxd5  8.d4  , the position opens, and we retain a small advantage.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng6  leads to a more complex game, often reminiscent of the French Defence.  C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6?!  is dubious for Black, as they weaken the dark squares too much.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...b5?!  gains space on the queenside but gives us attacking targets on this side of the board. }
6... Ng6
{ Black's traditional main line,  6...d5  , is not attractive for Black if they are looking for a more unbalanced position. If Black wants to fight, they often go for @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng6  , which will lead to positions more typical of the French Defence. }
7. c3
{ We prepare d4, a logical plan in our opening concept. The position on the board could also appear via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1pnppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ng6  6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  , which is a common route, too. }
7... Be7
{ Black prepares the move ...d5 this way.   The immediate  7...d5  8.exd5  Qxd5  is dubious, as the black queen is vulnerable in the center. Good moves for White are  9.Na3  or  9.d4  , both leading to a nice advantage. We examine a similar line in this chapter: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1pnppp/p1n1p3/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  7.exd5  Qxd5  , which shares the same problems. }
8. d4 cxd4
{ Black has to take first and avoid  8...d5?  , which is refuted by  9.exd5  Qxd5  @@StartBracket@@taking with the pawn drops c5@@EndBracket@@  10.c4  Qd8  11.d5  with a central breakthrough. Black has to be careful with any center opening, as our development lead is substantial. }
9. cxd4 d5 10. e5
{ Advancing the pawn and entering a French-type structure is best here.   White has also tested  10.exd5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2bppp/p1n1p1n1/3p4/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQRBK1 w kq d6 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nc3  , but I am convinced that grabbing ventral space is more promising here. Why exactly? What's the difference to a French Advance Variation?  In the French Advance, Black usually focuses their counterplay on the d4-pawn, the base of White's pawn chain. A line like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nf3  Qb6  6.a3  Nh6  @@StartBracket@@  planning ...Nf5@@EndBracket@@ comes to mind. In our version of the Rossolimo, Black's knight is on g6, unable to exert any pressure on d4.  Black has to generate some counterplay against White's center, though. Sitting passively and waiting for White to build up on the kingside is no option. This leads to the conclusion that Black's only plan is ...f6 here, attacking the pawn chain differently.  For this pawn break, the knight is placed well on g6. We will take on f6 and then have clear targets on the e-file, a scenario I like. Let's have a look at how this unfolds. }
10... O-O 11. Nc3
{ After this natural development move, I'll focus on the reply  11...f6  for Black. I think Black needs to go for a pawn break to get counterplay - playing it straightaway makes sense.   If Black does not go for ...f6, we plan to play g3&h4-h5, attacking Black's knight. We'll have a look at the move  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2bppp/p1n1p1n1/3pP3/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQRBK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bd7  to illustrate this plan. }
11... f6
{ Going for counterplay immediately and getting rid of White's advanced pawn. }
12. exf6
{ We have no good way to keep our pawn, but we also don't mind the capture on f6. Creating the e6-pawn as a long-term target is welcome. }
12... Bxf6 13. g3
{ Playing  13.Be3  here is also fine and was my suggestion in the first edition of the course.  I am switching to @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p4pp/p1n1pbn1/3p4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQRBK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.g3  to show a point on the next move. The objective value of both moves is identical - after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p4pp/p1n1pbn1/3p4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQRBK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.g3  Bd7  , I suggest  14.Be3  to get to the same thing. }
13... Bd7 14. Be3
{ The exclam is a bit strong, but it serves as a reminder of how we should approach this position: calmly strengthening our control and coordinating well. Instead of  14.Be3  , two moves lead to trouble.  A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1p1b2pp/p1n1pbn1/3p4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP3P1P/R1BQRBK1 w - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.h4?!  looks aggressive and was played in a GM game, but Black can answer it with  14...Bxh4!  , when they get a strong attack.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1p1b2pp/p1n1pbn1/3p4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP3P1P/R1BQRBK1 w - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bh3?!  is another tempting move, but not well-timed.  14...e5!  is strong, when  15.Bxd7  Qxd7  leaves us weak on the light squares and gives Black good play.   We don't need to analyze these any deeper; they show that we shouldn't be in a hurry here. Black's e-pawn is not going away, so we have time first to play moves like Be3 and Rc1. The idea of Na4-c5 also comes into consideration in some cases.  This does not mean we never play h4 or Bh3; it just needs to be better prepared. A possible line to show this is  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1p1b2pp/p1n1pbn1/3p4/3P4/2N1BNP1/PP3P1P/R2QRBK1 b - - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Be7  15.Rc1  h6  @@StartBracket@@Black prepares ...Bd6 and wants to avoid Ng5@@EndBracket@@,  when  16.Bh3  works well. Or consider @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1p1b2pp/p1n1pbn1/3p4/3P4/2N1BNP1/PP3P1P/R2QRBK1 b - - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Rc8  15.Rc1  Nge7  , when  16.h4  is a possible move for White. }
*

