{ After this capture, Black has three ways to take.  A. We can immediately rule out  7...exd5?  , as  8.d4  cxd4  9.Nxd4  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  leads to a terrible position for Black. Their king is stuck in the center, and d5 is terminally weak.   B. The most common move by far is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p2nppp/p1n1p3/2pP4/8/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nxd5  , as played in the mentioned Carlsen-Gelfand game.  C. We'll briefly look at @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p2nppp/p1n1p3/2pP4/8/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qxd5  , too. This move is worse, but the best reply is not obvious. }
7... Nxd5
{ The natural recapture. By taking with the knight, Black prepares ...Be7 and kingside castling. }
8. d4
{ We open the center as fast as possible. We are much better developed and have already castled, after all. Now we'll check three lines of defense for Black:  A. The main move is the prophylactic retreat @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/2pn4/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nf6  ,  B. Developing with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/2pn4/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  , which looks better for White.  C.  8...cxd4  . This move is not bad, but it needs to be followed by precise play - otherwise, Black can easily get into trouble. }
8... cxd4
{ Not a bad move, but Black needs to be precise afterwards - and often they are not. }
9. Nxd4
{ What now? Some options are regularly played, but they are worse for Black and easy for us to play. Let's have a look.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/3n4/3N4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nxd4?  10.Qxd4  is awful for Black. They can't prepare to castle, and our queen has a dominating position. Very nice for us.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/3n4/3N4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be7  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Nd2  gives us an eternal structural edge due to Black's split queenside pawns. Our knight is heading towards c4, a great square.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/3n4/3N4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bd7  can be answered in two ways.  10.Nf5  is sharp, but it is unclear that we have more than after @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1b1ppp/p1n1p3/3n4/3N4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 w kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c4  Nf6  11.Be3  , when we transpose to the main line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/2pn4/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq d3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nf6  9.Be3  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Bd7  11.c4  , which we will examine shortly. I suggest transposing, cutting our workload.  This leaves @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/3n4/3N4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQRBK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ndb4  to be checked. Stockfish thinks it is one of the better options, but White retains a nagging pull. }
9... Ndb4
{ This knight jump leads to simplifications, but does not solve Black's problems. }
10. Nxc6 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nxc6
{ Black keeps their pawn formation sound.   After  11...bxc6  12.Na3  , they'll suffer eternally due to the split queenside.  The situation after the knight recapture looks better at first but is still far from being fun for Black. }
12. c3
{ Starting with this move makes sense, stopping any ...Nb4-d5 ideas. We have a nice advantage here, based on the weak dark squares in Black's camp on the queenside. Ideas like Be3 and Nd2-c4 suggest themselves.   It's interesting to note that @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/8/8/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBR1BK1 b kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bc5  is well met by  13.b4  Ba7  14.a4  , which is excellent for White. Ba3, with b4-b5 in mind, is a strong idea. }
