{ Black can also delay the capture for a moment. After  9...Be7  I suggested  10.dxc5  in the first edition, but  10.c4  is a much simpler approach that will transpose to our main line after  10...cxd4  11.Nxd4  Bd7  12.Nc3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2bppp/p1n1pn2/2p5/2PP4/4BN2/PP3PPP/RN1QRBK1 b kq c3 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...O-O  11.Nc3  cxd4  12.Nxd4  ,  which are both common sequences.In the first edition, I expressed concerns about  10.c4  Ng4  , but after  11.d5  Nxe3  12.fxe3  exd5  14.cxd5  Na5  15.e4  White is in good shape, as the a5-knight looks terrible. }
10. Nxd4 Bd7
{ Here  10...Nxd4  11.Bxd4  Be7  is an alternative move order for Black. We can play  12.c4  , transposing to our main line, or try  12.a4  instead. This is an interesting idea, trying to use the c4-square for a knight later. }
11. c4
{ An important part of our concept. We have not yet played Nc3 and blocked our c-pawn. Now we see a benefit of the delayed queenside development. By playing c4, we gain more control of the center, particularly the square d5. An additional aspect is our pawn majority on the queenside. We have three pawns against two pawns of our opponent, which is a good starting point for space gains on this side of the board. }
11... Nxd4
{ Black needs some space for their pieces. The square c6 is better suited for the bishop, so trading on d4 makes perfect sense. }
12. Bxd4 Bc6 13. Nc3
{ We managed to develop our knight behind our pawn chain and pawn majority, which is strategically very desirable. }
13... Be7 14. a3
{ We start to set our majority in motion. Black has a fundamental choice now: allowing b2-b4 or stopping it.   A.  14...a5  was played in the game Carlsen-Gelfand I mentioned before. After  15.Qd3  O-O  16.Rad1  Carlsen enjoyed a comfortable advantage and managed to win a fine game.   B.  14...O-O  15.b4  looks even better for us. Here's an instructive idea worth knowing: after  15...Qd7  , there is the attractive move  16.Ra2!  ,  going for the rook lift to d2.All in all, I am happy with White's chances in this line. We enjoy a comfortable position without taking risks, and Black's game is more difficult to conduct. }
*

