[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B6) Sicilian – Rossolimo Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Black's main replies to the Sicilian Rossolimo are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  ,  3...e6  , and  3...d6  . I examine these main moves in dedicated chapters, while other options are discussed here. Let's have a look at what we will check.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd4  is a premature knight jump - this line has no name, but 'Sicilian Bird' would be a fitting one.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  is rare, but not a bad move. We'll open the centre with c3 & d4, trying to exploit Black's slow development.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qc7  and  3...Qb6  are similar ideas. I examine  3...Qc7  ,  but show how the other queen move will usually lead to the same positions. Black loses too much time with multiple queen moves and gives us good attacking chances.Finally, two moves may lead to similar positions.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6?!  forces us to capture the knight, a dubious move. White often takes on c6 unprovoked, which leads to the next line.   E. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is possible, attacking our e-pawn. I suggest taking on c6 to create the doubled pawns. I discuss the reasoning in the notes to the move. }
