[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B6) Sicilian – Rossolimo Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...Nd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4
{ This move is premature. The knight jump to d4 is quite common in positions where White already has a Knight on c3. One example for such a scenario would be @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nc3  Nc6  3.Nf3  e6  4.Bb5  Nd4  ,  when a capture on d4 is far less attractive for White. In these cases, taking on d4 loses time as the c3-knight is immediately attacked. Here White has not committed to anything yet, so we can adapt perfectly to the pawn structure change that Black initiates. }
4. Nxd4 { An easy decision. On the next move, we have some choice, though. }
4... cxd4 5. c3
{ In the first edition, I suggested  5.O-O  here, which is a good move. Still, playing  5.c3  immediately and trying to open the position is more forceful.White is much better already, pretty much regardless of what Black does. The only way for Black to make it challenging is to try keeping the pawn on d4 as long as possible. After  5...dxc3?  6.Nxc3  , our lead in development reaches epic proportions. }
5... Qb6
{ Black attacks the bishop and covers their d4-pawn. Black has also tried  5...a6  6.Ba4  b5  7.Bb3  Bb7  8.d3  ,  but at some point, they'll have to take on c3 and accelerate our development. }
6. Ba4 { The other bishop moves to c4, or e2 are fine, too. } 6... Nf6
{ We'll have a look at this move, as it features an attractive idea for us later. }
7. e5 { The most powerful, gaining some space. } 7... Nd5 8. O-O
{ We don't want to take on d4, but rather provoke Black to capture on c3. A good way to increase the pressure is our next move. }
8... e6 9. Qg4
{ Very nice. We get our queen to an active position and exert more pressure on d4. Black has massive problems to even staying in the game. }
