[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B6) Sicilian – Rossolimo Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e5
{ At the time of the first edition's release, 2018, this move was a very rare, fresh idea. Since then, it has seen a few more tests. The current state of the theory is that White is a bit better - Let's see how it unfolds. }
4. O-O
{ We castle first before committing to anything in the centre. Of course,  4.Bxc6?!  dxc6  5.Nxe5?  Qd4  leads nowhere. }
4... Bd6
{ This probably would have gotten some bad press 100 years ago, but it is not that bad. The position is closed so Black can afford some liberties. }
5. c3
{ White has also tried the pawn sacrifice  5.d4!?  , which gives good compensation after  5...Nxd4  6.Bc4  . My suggestion of @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1p1ppp/2nb4/1Bp1p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  looks very logical, though. }
5... a6
{ This is an improvement on  5...Nge7  6.d4  cxd4  7.cxd4  exd4  8.Nxd4  a6  9.Bc4  O-O  10.Nf3!  ,  when White has some advantage. This is the line that I featured in the first edition when 3...e5 was less explored. }
6. Ba4 b5 7. Bc2
{ There is nothing wrong with  7.Bb3  ,  either. The position looks like a weird hybrid of a Ruy and a Sicilian. Our ideas are well-known from the Ruy, too: We'd like to attack Black's pawns with a4 and play d4 to open the centre. I'll continue this line to demonstrate a typical development. }
7... Nge7 8. a4
{ A typical Ruy-style pawn lever. We open the a-file for our rook. } 8... Rb8
9. axb5 axb5 10. d4
{ White is slightly better here, as Black's pieces are oddly placed. Now a fun line goes  10...cxd4  11.cxd4  exd4  12.Nxd4  Nxd4  13.Qxd4  ,  when we attack d6 and g7. Black holds with  13...Qc7!  , though, when  14.h3  gives us the advantage. Black's structure is not pretty. }
