[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B6) Sicilian – Rossolimo Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...Qc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Qc7
{ This move is mostly played to allow a recapture on c6 with the queen. There is one substantial drawback - Black further delays kingside development and castling.   A similar idea to  3...Qc7  is  3...Qb6  , which often leads to the same positions. After  3...Qb6  4.Nc3  e6  5.O-O  a6  6.Bxc6  Qxc6  7.d4  , we'd transpose to the line we are about to examine. }
4. O-O a6
{ The most popular and principled move. On other moves, we go Re1/c3/d4, opening up the position while ahead in development. }
5. Bxc6 Qxc6 6. Nc3
{ White's advantage in development has reached scary proportions, but the position is not yet open. We need to play a quick d2-d4 now and accelerate the play.   Instead of  6.Nc3  , White has many good alternatives, like  6.Re1  or even the gambit  6.d4  . The main point to remember is: develop quickly and open the position as soon as possible. }
6... e6 7. d4 { Here we go! } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ Here,  8.Qxd4  is not bad, either. Taking with the knight to gain a tempo on the queen is tempting, though. }
8... Qc7 9. Re1
{ This is best here. It prevents the natural move ...Nf6 due to e4-e5. White has excellent attacking chances here. Note that White has ideas like Qg4, preparing Bf4. An additional option is Bg5-h4-g3 to put more pressure on d6. Black's position is tough to defend. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B6) Sicilian – Rossolimo Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ A dubious move, but it is instructive to study its consequences. We are forced to take the knight and create the doubled pawn on c6. Let's discuss why this is dubious.Against the main lines 3...e6/3...g6/3...d6, it is a major option for White to trade on c6 completely unprovoked. I suggest a different approach, but this is a matter of personal taste.   In the current chapter, we examine  3...Nf6  ,  when the attack on our e-pawn does not allow us to castle. In this particular case, I recommend taking the knight.I think it gets pretty clear that  3...a6?!  must be dubious. It loses time to provoke a structure we don't mind playing anyway.   Alright, we have to check both recaptures now. Our coverage of  4.Bxc6  dxc6  will be very brief, as it amounts to a worse version of the line 3...Nf6 4.Bxc6 dxc6, which we examine in more detail.We'll have a closer look at  4...bxc6  ,  as these structures can feature other knight developments @@StartBracket@@...e6 and ...Ne7@@EndBracket@@, or they may appear when Black had started with a different third move and then played ...a6 soon after. }
4. Bxc6 dxc6
{ I think this is better than  4...bxc6  as it at least opens up the c8-bishop. Our advantage is not in doubt, though - Black's structural problems on the queenside are serious. There is a simple way to evaluate this position - let's discuss it after our next move. }
5. d3
{ The main choice here is between playing  5.O-O  or starting with the pawn move. I went for castling in the first edition, which remains a good choice. I switched to the pawn move now for two reasons: it's easier to counter ...Bg4 ideas, and it is more in line with the variation  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.d3  ,  which we discuss later in the current chapter.This already gets to the point I was hinting at on the previous move. The mentioned line 3...Nf6 is better for White, and Black has played ...a6 instead, which must make Black's situation worse. I can't see a setup where ...a6 would be more useful than ...Nf6, which makes our job easy here. We play in the same way as against 3...Nf6, it's just going to be even better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B6) Sicilian – Rossolimo Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ A dubious move, but it is instructive to study its consequences. We are forced to take the knight and create the doubled pawn on c6. Let's discuss why this is dubious.Against the main lines 3...e6/3...g6/3...d6, it is a major option for White to trade on c6 completely unprovoked. I suggest a different approach, but this is a matter of personal taste.   In the current chapter, we examine  3...Nf6  ,  when the attack on our e-pawn does not allow us to castle. In this particular case, I recommend taking the knight.I think it gets pretty clear that  3...a6?!  must be dubious. It loses time to provoke a structure we don't mind playing anyway.   Alright, we have to check both recaptures now. Our coverage of  4.Bxc6  dxc6  will be very brief, as it amounts to a worse version of the line 3...Nf6 4.Bxc6 dxc6, which we examine in more detail.We'll have a closer look at  4...bxc6  ,  as these structures can feature other knight developments @@StartBracket@@...e6 and ...Ne7@@EndBracket@@, or they may appear when Black had started with a different third move and then played ...a6 soon after. }
4. Bxc6 bxc6
{ This might amplify Black's difficulties as they fall even more behind in development. The other pawn capture at least opens the c8-bishop. }
5. O-O
{ We castle first and like to see how Black intends to develop. This is not an easy task, to be honest. Black has problems creating a pawn presence in the centre, which can be proven with many sample variations, but I want to discuss it in general terms. What possible pawn structures could Black play for?  A. A pawn on d5. This structure is generally dubious, as White can pressure the weak c5-pawn. Ideas like Nc3-a4,b3&Ba3 come to mind. This type of play is well-known from the Nimzo-Indian, but here we have a compelling version with extra tempi and a pawn on e4.  B. Playing pawns to d6 and e5. This is tough to accomplish, as it is very slow. We manage to open the centre quickly while being ahead in development. Black might manage to play ...d6, but not ...e5.  C. Go for ...g6 and ...d6. Again, a slow plan. The move ...d6 is often effectively answered with e4-e5!, opening the position. The move ...Nf6 is hit by e4-e5, too.   These three approaches are very problematic for Black. It looks like the best try is to play the sophisticated setup ...e6, ...Ne7 and ...Ng6, avoiding any direct contact with White's forces. This is a significantly worse version of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  ,  when Black goes for the same ...Ne7-g6 plan.To illustrate the mentioned themes, I'll now examine the moves  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/3ppppp/p1p5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  ,  5...g6  and  5...e6  . They sometimes play  5...d5?  , which immediately leads to scenario A, as described above. We are much better with many moves, like  6.d3  ,  6.Nc3  or  6.Re1  .  The main point to remember is the play against the weak c5-pawn. We'll examine this plan in the line 5...d6 6.e5! d5, when the same pawn structure arises. }
5... e6
{ This looks relatively best for Black if they connect it with the idea ...Ne7-g6. This is unlikely to happen, though - people rarely play a dodgy move like 3...a6 and then proceed to find a sophisticated setup. Still, we want to be ready. }
6. d3
{ I suggest this move, but White has some other interesting tries, like  6.b3  , for instance. I like  6.d3  , because of the following idea. }
6... Ne7
{ Black's best bet. Moves like  6...d6?  7.e5!  or the immediate @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/3p1ppp/p1p1p3/2p5/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5?  ruin Black's pawn structure, as we examine in various similar lines. }
7. e5
{ This is an important idea. We want to restrict Black's pieces and gain space. The only way Black can fight this grip is by playing for ...f6 now. }
7... Ng6 8. Nbd2
{ The move d3 was played to get our knight to c4 in this structure. } 8... Be7
9. Nc4
{ We have an excellent position now. Black needs ...f6, but it doesn't work out. }
9... O-O { Here  9...f6  10.Nd6+  Bxd6  11.exd6  looks horrible for Black. }
10. Nfd2
{ Very nice! A strong move, intending to answer Black's planned move  10...f6  with  11.f4  . Let's see this on the board. }
10... f6 11. f4
{ And we are in great shape. We maintain the pawn on e5, which is burying both black bishops. }
