4. Bxc6 bxc6
{ This might amplify Black's difficulties as they fall even more behind in development. The other pawn capture at least opens the c8-bishop. }
5. O-O
{ We castle first and like to see how Black intends to develop. This is not an easy task, to be honest. Black has problems creating a pawn presence in the centre, which can be proven with many sample variations, but I want to discuss it in general terms. What possible pawn structures could Black play for?  A. A pawn on d5. This structure is generally dubious, as White can pressure the weak c5-pawn. Ideas like Nc3-a4,b3&Ba3 come to mind. This type of play is well-known from the Nimzo-Indian, but here we have a compelling version with extra tempi and a pawn on e4.  B. Playing pawns to d6 and e5. This is tough to accomplish, as it is very slow. We manage to open the centre quickly while being ahead in development. Black might manage to play ...d6, but not ...e5.  C. Go for ...g6 and ...d6. Again, a slow plan. The move ...d6 is often effectively answered with e4-e5!, opening the position. The move ...Nf6 is hit by e4-e5, too.   These three approaches are very problematic for Black. It looks like the best try is to play the sophisticated setup ...e6, ...Ne7 and ...Ng6, avoiding any direct contact with White's forces. This is a significantly worse version of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  ,  when Black goes for the same ...Ne7-g6 plan.To illustrate the mentioned themes, I'll now examine the moves  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/3ppppp/p1p5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  ,  5...g6  and  5...e6  . They sometimes play  5...d5?  , which immediately leads to scenario A, as described above. We are much better with many moves, like  6.d3  ,  6.Nc3  or  6.Re1  .  The main point to remember is the play against the weak c5-pawn. We'll examine this plan in the line 5...d6 6.e5! d5, when the same pawn structure arises. }
5... d6 { Black hopes to play ...e5 next, occupying central space. } 6. e5
{ This is a powerful move! White is also better after other sensible moves, like  6.c3  , but  6.e5  is very powerful. Black only has a choice between different bad outcomes. We will examine  6...d5  as the main move - here are two alternatives.   A.  6...dxe5  7.Nxe5  ruins Black's pawn structure.   B.  6...Bg4  7.h3  Bh5  8.Re1  leaves Black with no good move.  8...d5  is again strategic bankruptcy, but allowing something like  8...e6  9.exd6  is no fun, either.The c-pawns are weak. }
6... d5
{ Otherwise, the position, especially the e-file, will open even more quickly. After giving up the Bishop pair, White will usually need compensation in the form of a structural weakness @@StartBracket@@exploitable doubled pawns@@EndBracket@@ or a lead in development. }
7. h3
{ A strong prophylactic move, stopping ...Bg4. Now we can follow up with the mentioned plan of b3, Ba3, Nc3-a4, which will often win the c5 pawn. I want to illustrate this plan with a sample sequence of moves. }
7... e6 { Black gives some support to c5. } 8. Nc3 Ne7
{ The only way to get the knight out. } 9. b3 Ng6 10. Ba3 Qa5 11. Na4
{ This is the setup that we are aiming for. Black has managed to keep the pawn for the moment, but that is not a solution for the weak queenside. After  11...Be7  12.c3  O-O  13.d4  cxd4  14.Bxe7  Nxe7  15.cxd4  we see an instructive way to make progress. In the final position, Black is in terrible shape, as the bishop is dead, and both c5 and c6 are hopelessly weak. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B6) Sicilian – Rossolimo Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – Rossolimo 3...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Black develops their knight and attacks our pawn. It's a rare line, but it looks like the best one in the current chapter. White has multiple ways to gain an advantage, but choosing one is not a simple decision. As you'll meet 3...Nf6 in only roughly 5% of your Rossilimo games, you want an economical solution.   In the first edition, I recommended  4.e5  Nd5  5.O-O  , trying to transpose to the line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.O-O  Bg7  5.Re1  Nf6  6.e5  Nd5  ,  which was my main suggestion against 3...g6. In the second edition, I replaced this line with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  ,  playing for a different structure.Can we play something similar to this c3-based solution? No, there is no way to get to similar concepts. Our pawn is attacked, and we need to react to the threat. Here's a list of options and what I went for.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/2n2n2/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxc6  is my choice. We rarely capture voluntarily on c6 in the Rossolimo, but I think it is the most pragmatic choice here. I know it sounds odd initially, but we'll reach positions resembling  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  dxc6  ,  which is an important part of our repertoire. A main attraction of the bishop capture is that you can play the resulting positions without knowing many concrete lines, making it a good option against a rare line.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/2n2n2/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  is a good move but leads to complicated and often unusual positions. I feel it is not warranted to study multiple trainables for a sideline.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/2n2n2/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  remains a good move but leads to positions that we don't regularly play in this course.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/2n2n2/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d3?!  is a mistake you must avoid! The problem:  4...Qa5+  5.Nc3  Nd4  is annoying and fine for Black. }
4. Bxc6
{ It's important to capture immediately and not start with  4.d3?!  , as  4...Qa5+  is a problem. }
4... dxc6
{ Black's best way to capture. After  4...bxc6  5.e5  Nd5  6.O-O  g6  7.Re1  Bg7  8.c4  , we'll reach a position very similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Bxc6  bxc6  5.O-O  g6  6.Re1  Bg7  7.h3!  Nf6  8.e5  Nd5  9.c4  ,  when only the moves h3 and a6 are added. This makes no substantial difference. White is better after the position opens after Nc3 and d4 next. }
5. d3
{ We cover our pawn and create a stable pawn chain. Our formation is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  dxc6  ,  a surprising parallel. While Black's setup differs, some strategic elements are still the same. With the centre closed for the near future, action will often be on the flanks.The specifics depend a lot on Black's choice now. We'll examine the two most popular moves,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/2p5/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  , and  5...g6  . }
5... g6
{ A fairly odd choice, as Black could have played 3...g6 if they wanted to fianchetto the bishop. It's still a sensible move, of course. Interestingly, we now reach lines that may also arise via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.Bxc6  , which is not part of our repertoire but a great alternative for later. Here, after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.d3  g6  ,  Black is already committed to ...Nf6, so we need to examine a subset of lines that may occur after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.Bxc6  .  Therefore, the following lines give you a good insight into how the bishop capture works without studying all the options.   How to handle this position: it's important to compare it to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  g6  4.O-O  Bg7  5.Re1  e5  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.d3  ,  which is part of our repertoire. The crucial difference is that Black has not played ...e5 here, keeping the long diagonal open. Thus Black's bishop will be much stronger on g7, making it our opponent's best piece.The standard way of dealing with it: trying to trade it as soon as possible, using the Be3, Qd2 and Bh6 plan. To realise this plan undisturbed, we also want to play the moves h3 @@StartBracket@@stopping ...Ng4 in response to Be3@@EndBracket@@ and Nc3. We don't need to castle kingside yet. }
6. h3
{ The move order is not paramount. Starting with  6.Nc3  would lead to the same formation. }
6... Bg7 7. Nc3
{ We have to play the knight first, as  7.Be3?  Nxe4!  is embarrassing.   After  7.Nc3  ,  Black has some flexibility. They can castle kingside quickly or try to delay his decision; our plan is the same, pretty much regardless of Black's choice. We play Be3 and Qd2 and try for Bh6. We'll have a look at both options for Black. }
7... Nd7
{ Black wants to prevent our Be3+Qd2+Bh6 idea and delays castling. Once Bh6 is a threat, they want to go for ...h6 and stop it. The idea of ...Nd7 is to improve the knight via f8 to e6 later. This idea is commonly seen in the Ruy Lopez Berlin, a curious similarity. }
8. Be3 b6 { Black covers c5 so that the knight will get more mobile. } 9. Qd2
{ We have completed our initial setup. } 9... h6
{ OK, no Bh6 for us. No problem, as we have a different plan. We can castle kingside and play Nh2 to prepare the f-pawn to join. }
10. O-O Nf8
{ You also frequently see  10...e5  11.Nh2  Nf8  12.f4  , which will lead to the same positions. }
11. Nh2 e5
{ Black needs some foothold in the centre. They can't allow us to build up even more with f4 and later f4-f5 or e4-e5. }
12. f4 { Here we go, finally opening a file. } 12... exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne6 14. Be3
{ White is better here, as Black can't castle kingside and suffers from weaknesses. Here's a sample line that shows how we can exploit the weak dark squares.   Black's most common move is  14...Nd4  , when  15.Rae1  Be6  is a logical sequence. Black prepares ...Qd7 and castling queenside. But we have the strong move  16.e5!  ,  showing the point of Rae1. Now  16...Bxe5  17.Ng4  gives White a huge attack, as  17...Bg7  18.Nxh6  shows. We threaten Nxf7 here. Even worse is  17...Bxg4?  18.Bf4  ,  when Black loses on the spot. Probably Black should take on move 16, but then Bf4 and Ne4-d6 show that we can use the weak spots. }
*

