sitions that we don't regularly play in this course.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/2n2n2/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d3?!  is a mistake you must avoid! The problem:  4...Qa5+  5.Nc3  Nd4  is annoying and fine for Black. }
4. Bxc6
{ It's important to capture immediately and not start with  4.d3?!  , as  4...Qa5+  is a problem. }
4... dxc6
{ Black's best way to capture. After  4...bxc6  5.e5  Nd5  6.O-O  g6  7.Re1  Bg7  8.c4  , we'll reach a position very similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Bxc6  bxc6  5.O-O  g6  6.Re1  Bg7  7.h3!  Nf6  8.e5  Nd5  9.c4  ,  when only the moves h3 and a6 are added. This makes no substantial difference. White is better after the position opens after Nc3 and d4 next. }
5. d3
{ We cover our pawn and create a stable pawn chain. Our formation is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  dxc6  ,  a surprising parallel. While Black's setup differs, some strategic elements are still the same. With the centre closed for the near future, action will often be on the flanks.The specifics depend a lot on Black's choice now. We'll examine the two most popular moves,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/2p5/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  , and  5...g6  . }
5... g6
{ A fairly odd choice, as Black could have played 3...g6 if they wanted to fianchetto the bishop. It's still a sensible move, of course. Interestingly, we now reach lines that may also arise via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.Bxc6  , which is not part of our repertoire but a great alternative for later. Here, after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.d3  g6  ,  Black is already committed to ...Nf6, so we need to examine a subset of lines that may occur after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.Bxc6  .  Therefore, the following lines give you a good insight into how the bishop capture works without studying all the options.   How to handle this position: it's important to compare it to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  g6  4.O-O  Bg7  5.Re1  e5  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.d3  ,  which is part of our repertoire. The crucial difference is that Black has not played ...e5 here, keeping the long diagonal open. Thus Black's bishop will be much stronger on g7, making it our opponent's best piece.The standard way of dealing with it: trying to trade it as soon as possible, using the Be3, Qd2 and Bh6 plan. To realise this plan undisturbed, we also want to play the moves h3 @@StartBracket@@stopping ...Ng4 in response to Be3@@EndBracket@@ and Nc3. We don't need to castle kingside yet. }
6. h3
{ The move order is not paramount. Starting with  6.Nc3  would lead to the same formation. }
6... Bg7 7. Nc3
{ We have to play the knight first, as  7.Be3?  Nxe4!  is embarrassing.   After  7.Nc3  ,  Black has some flexibility. They can castle kingside quickly or try to delay his decision; our plan is the same, pretty much regardless of Black's choice. We play Be3 and Qd2 and try for Bh6. We'll have a look at both options for Black. }
7... O-O { Black castles kingside, allowing our idea. } 8. Be3
{ We develop with tempo. } 8... b6
{ You also see  8...Nd7  , when we still play  9.Qd2  and Bh6 and angle for a later f4-push. The strategy will be the same after 8...b6. }
9. Qd2 e5
{ Black does not need to prepare this move, as  10.Nxe5?  Nxe4!  is possible. We should stick to our general plan. }
10. Bh6
{ We still want to trade this bishop to weaken Black's defences on the dark squares. A later Nh2 and f4 will open the position to use those weaknesses; It's crucial to see that f2-f4 is the key pawn lever. If we don't trade bishops and play for f4, the guy on g7 will get stronger again. So better trade them right away and then proceed with the preparation of f4. }
10... Re8 11. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ We have reached a strategically fascinating position. Our general idea, playing for f2-f4, is clear. The most obvious way to go for that would be O-O, Nh2 and f4.   However, Black can play ...Nh5 to make that move difficult. If we play  12.O-O  , the reply  12...Nh5!  is annoying. It looks like we need Ne2 at some point to support f4. It would be ideal if Black's move ...Nh5 would be more difficult for them to play. We could try to play  @@StartFEN@@r1bqr3/p4pkp/1pp2np1/2p1p3/4P3/2NP1N1P/PPPQ1PP1/R3K2R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ne2  , but  12...c4!  is a good reply. This leads us to the excellent idea I'll show now. }
12. b3
{ A great concept. We give more stability to our structure so that Ne2 becomes possible. We can even consider playing Ne2-g3, then Nh2 and f2-f4. White is always slightly better in these structures, as we have a pawn lever f4 to play for. This is comparable to the Berlin structure when the same applies. }
