{ Black's best way to capture. After  4...bxc6  5.e5  Nd5  6.O-O  g6  7.Re1  Bg7  8.c4  , we'll reach a position very similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Bxc6  bxc6  5.O-O  g6  6.Re1  Bg7  7.h3!  Nf6  8.e5  Nd5  9.c4  ,  when only the moves h3 and a6 are added. This makes no substantial difference. White is better after the position opens after Nc3 and d4 next. }
5. d3
{ We cover our pawn and create a stable pawn chain. Our formation is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  dxc6  ,  a surprising parallel. While Black's setup differs, some strategic elements are still the same. With the centre closed for the near future, action will often be on the flanks.The specifics depend a lot on Black's choice now. We'll examine the two most popular moves,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/2p5/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  , and  5...g6  . }
5... Bg4
{ By far Black's most popular choice. It's always tempting to pin the knight, but we have not castled yet and have a powerful reply. }
6. h3 Bh5
{ Black wants to keep the pin, of course. Giving up the bishop pair isn't right and makes our life easy. A simple idea after  6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  is to move the queen and play for f2-f4 to gain valuable space. }
7. g4
{ i am surprised that this move is not played more often. White is doing well with the slower moves @@StartBracket@@like b3, Nbd2 first@@EndBracket@@, but I see no problem with being more direct. }
7... Bg6
{ We have to be aware that Black may play ...c4, if we are not careful. } 8.
Nbd2
{ The alternative  8.b3  also looks fine. Black needs to develop the guy on f8, so ...e5 needs to be prepared. }
8... Nd7 9. Qe2
{ I was tempted to end the trainable even on the previous move, because White has a long list of good moves here that all lead to an advantage. The queen move is flexible and gets us one step closer to queenside castling, but there was nothing wrong with  9.Nc4  ,  9.b3  or even  9.a4  , as we don't need to castle queenside necessarily.   After  9.Qe2  ,  we have a comfortable advantage. Black can play ...e5, but it invites our d2-knight to hop to f5. Black's bishops are passive, and we have a much easier job of making progress. If Black plays ...e5 in this structure, the similarities to the Ruy Lopez Berlin are obvious. In this line, the early ...Bg4 is often dubious if we have not castled yet. the same applies here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B7) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 & Other 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 & Other 3rd Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3
{ After our move  3.c3  , Black has two main continuations and some minor alternatives that we will check:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  is the most popular move @@StartBracket@@50% of games@@EndBracket@@,  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  is possible, but either transposes into A or leads to problems for Black,  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  is a similar story, as Black can still transpose to A territory, but sometimes plays differently and is much worse,  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is the main alternative, played in about 25% of games. It is covered in a dedicated chapter, as the arising positions are very different to A-C.  As you see, B and C often lead to lines covered via A. Therefore, I decided to cover these in the current chapter, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  is discussed in a separate chapter.  A quick word about the rare move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...b6  , which we don't cover here. The reason is that the natural sequence  4.d4  Bb7  5.Bd3  directly transposes into a line of Owen's Defence @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  b6  @@EndBracket@@  that we cover in the final chapter of the course. }
