[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B7) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 & Other 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 a6
{ This move is rare via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  a6  , but we'll sometimes get the position via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  , when  3...e6  is a common move. }
4. d4
{ Alight, an easy move for us. Black's only option to still get a good game is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d5  , when we have a choice.  A.  5.e5  leads to a French Advance line @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.c3  a6  5.Nf3  @@EndBracket@@  , which looks slightly better for White. My objection to this transposition is that we don't play the French Advance and these positions are not easy to play. It is a different story when Black inserts the trade on d4, as these lines are excellent for White. We'll have a look at this scenario in a moment.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pp4/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.exd5  is my recommendation when we transpose to lines that we cover via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  4.exd5  exd5  5.d4  a6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5  5.d4  a6  , both being slightly better for White.  So we have established that Black should play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d5  now... what else do they have?  We'll have a look at the trade on d4, as this is a common mistake. If Black makes some slow move, we'll continue with our development @@StartBracket@@Bd3, O-O@@EndBracket@@ and enjoy a nice advantage in the center. }
4... cxd4 { This trade is a mistake, as we gain the square c3 for our knight. }
5. cxd4 d5
{ Black has to put a pawn in the center at some point to fight for space. Now we face the question about the e-pawn again: taking on d5 or advancing? }
6. e5
{ This is the best move. The trade on d4 has significantly improved White's position, as we can now place our knight on the attractive c3-square.   I am already ending the trainable line here, as we meet the same scenario after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  4.d4  cxd4?!  5.cxd4  d5  6.e5!  , which we examine in more detail, as it occurs far more frequently.  The main point to remember is that the Advance becomes much more promising if Black decides to trade on d4 prematurely. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B7) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 & Other 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 Nc6
{ A natural developing move that will very often transpose to lines examined via 3...d5, if Black is precise on the next move. }
4. d4
{ Now Black's best option is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d5!  , when we have the following choice:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2pp4/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e5  all of a sudden leads to a French Advance Variation @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nf3  @@EndBracket@@, which is not part of our repertoire. If you have some knowledge/experience with this line, it's certainly an option to consider.  B. I suggest @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2pp4/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.exd5  , as this will transpose to lines that are part of our repertoire and covered via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  4.exd5  exd5  5.d4  Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  Nc6  , depending on Black's recapture.  Is there an alternative for Black? Yes, you sometimes meet the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4?!  , which is dubious. We will examine it now. }
4... cxd4
{ This is the only independent option and is regarded as imprecise, as White should benefit from the trade. The c3-square is now available for our knight. }
5. cxd4
{ Now we'll look at  5...d5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  . }
5... Nf6
{ Black attacks our pawn. Not a frequently met move, but I can't resist showing the following line. }
6. Nc3
{ This is why trading on d4 is imprecise: we can cover e4 with this natural move. }
6... d5
{ Black is understandably concerned about our center advancing, so they play ...d5 finally. }
7. e5 { Now we reach a favourable French Defence structure again. } 7... Ne4
{ The knight looks active on e4, but after our natural reply, Black won't be able to maintain the knight on e4. }
8. Bd3 Nxc3 { Or  8...Bb4  9.Qc2  , which is excellent for White, too. } 9.
bxc3
{ Our central pawn chain is very stable now, as the c3-pawn is much easier to defend than the d-pawn. }
9... Be7
{ Now we have reached an instructive point. What's best now? Should we just castle kingside? }
10. h4
{ This is a lot better than castling. We can start a direct kingside initiative and put pressure on Black. The immediate problem is that they can't castle. }
10... O-O
{ This allows the classic 'Greek Gift' sacrifice! Black has to play something else, but we'll have a nice play on the kingside in any case. Ideas like h4-h5, Rh3-g3 or Ng5 come to mind.  After 10...O-O?? there is no need for any subtleties. }
11. Bxh7+
{ Boom! We have reached a textbook example of the greek gift sacrifice - White wins easily. My Stockfish gives +61, which sounds pretty good! 😀 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B7) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 & Other 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 Nc6
{ A natural developing move that will very often transpose to lines examined via 3...d5, if Black is precise on the next move. }
4. d4
{ Now Black's best option is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d5!  , when we have the following choice:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2pp4/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e5  all of a sudden leads to a French Advance Variation @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nf3  @@EndBracket@@, which is not part of our repertoire. If you have some knowledge/experience with this line, it's certainly an option to consider.  B. I suggest @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2pp4/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.exd5  , as this will transpose to lines that are part of our repertoire and covered via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  4.exd5  exd5  5.d4  Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  Nc6  , depending on Black's recapture.  Is there an alternative for Black? Yes, you sometimes meet the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4?!  , which is dubious. We will examine it now. }
4... cxd4
{ This is the only independent option and is regarded as imprecise, as White should benefit from the trade. The c3-square is now available for our knight. }
5. cxd4
{ Now we'll look at  5...d5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  . }
5... d5 { Black needs a pawn in the center. } 6. e5
{ This is the theoretical argument against Black's move order. We get to an Advance French with an early trade on d4 that benefits White, as we can play Nc3 early on.  However, I must say that it is not a situation where White is much better and needs to learn some moves to win the game. We have an advantage, but not more than that if Black plays the best line now. This is somewhat unlikely, though. People rarely play a conceptually inferior line and then continue perfectly.   Black's best move is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  5...Nge7  now  , but you'll often meet a combination of ...Qb6 and ...Bd7, which we'll examine, too. }
6... Qb6
{ Black applies pressure on d4, a normal strategy in such a pawn structure. It is wrong in this particular case, though. }
7. Nc3
{ This is possible now compared to the French Advance, where there are still pawns on c5 and c3. }
7... Bd7
{ This position could also arise via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd7  7.Nc3  Qb6  , of course. }
8. a3
{ It's good to remember this idea. We prepare the move Na4 by taking away possible checks on b4. }
8... Nge7 9. Na4
{ This is a strong manoeuvre. We push the black queen to a passive square and are ready to continue with moves like Bd3, Bf4 and Rc1. We have a huge space advantage, and Black lacks active possibilities. }
