5. cxd4
{ Now we'll look at  5...d5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/3PP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  . }
5... d5 { Black needs a pawn in the center. } 6. e5
{ This is the theoretical argument against Black's move order. We get to an Advance French with an early trade on d4 that benefits White, as we can play Nc3 early on.  However, I must say that it is not a situation where White is much better and needs to learn some moves to win the game. We have an advantage, but not more than that if Black plays the best line now. This is somewhat unlikely, though. People rarely play a conceptually inferior line and then continue perfectly.   Black's best move is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  5...Nge7  now  , but you'll often meet a combination of ...Qb6 and ...Bd7, which we'll examine, too. }
