[White "B7) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 & Other 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 exd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5
{ Probably Black's most natural and popular move. After our capture on d5, we'll have a further split. }
4. exd5
{ Now, we often reach an IQP position. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  , Black often goes for the IQP and after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5  ,  we will play with the isolated pawn in many cases. }
4... exd5
{ Black's recapture with the e-pawn frequently leads to positions in which Black plays with an IQP. Let's consider the various scenarios after our natural reply. }
5. d4
{ We have arrived at an important moment for Black to choose their development plan. Before we consider their options, I need to make a crucial point.  This position is very similar to a line of the French Defence that is part of our repertoire: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  c5  4.Ngf3  Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  sees Nbd2 played instead of a pawn to c3.  There are various transpositions or lines that are very similar.    I organised the material, so the main coverage is done in the French chapter. This makes the most sense, as the arising structures are more typical of the French Tarrasch than a Sicilian. The term 'French Tarrasch IQP structure' exists, while there is no 'Black IQP in the c3-Sicilian' structure.   Let's check Black's options now:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Bb5  is a popular line that will likely transpose into the French Tarrasch. We'll check possible @@StartBracket@@bad@@EndBracket@@ deviations for Black, of course.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Bb5+  also happens frequently. We again reach a position that is very similar to a line of the French Tarrasch.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c4  is a questionable move, but I want to show why to demonstrate a typical idea.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  is rare but stops our preferred bishop move to b5. We are fine with natural development moves, though.   Lines A and B are played in about 70-80% of the games. Their coverage is relatively brief here due to their frequent transpositions to the French Tarrasch. }
5... Nf6 { Black develops the knight to the most natural square. } 6. Bb5+
{ White does not mind trading this bishop against his c8 counterpart or pinning the knight on c6 if Black avoids the trade. Playing against the IQP by trading minor pieces is a good approach. In a very similar position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  c5  4.Ngf3  Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  we also play  6.Bb5+  , following the same logic. }
