{ The move  6...Nc6  is covered via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Bb5  Nf6  and a welcome sight. }
7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ Black takes with the knight, enabling ...Nxc5 in reply to our capture on c5.   Playing  7...Qxd7  is less precise, as we gain a sizable advantage with simple means. }
8. O-O Be7 { Black quickly closes the e-file before it is too late. } 9. dxc5
{ We create the IQP and thus our target for the foreseeable future. } 9... Nxc5
10. Be3
{ I suggest the setup with Be3 and Nbd2, which looks harmonious. It is not the only reasonable way to develop your pieces, though. You could also direct your knight to d4 quickly via Na3-c2-d4, for example. It does not change our overall strategy: keep the d4-square under control and increase the pressure on the d-pawn. }
10... O-O 11. Nbd2
{ This position is slightly better for White but easy to play. You go Qc2, centralise rooks and maybe go for Bd4 and Nf1-e3, to put pressure on the IQP. Black has active pieces, of course, so we cannot count on any substantial edge. }
