[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B7) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 & Other 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 exd5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5
{ Probably Black's most natural and popular move. After our capture on d5, we'll have a further split. }
4. exd5
{ Now, we often reach an IQP position. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  , Black often goes for the IQP and after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5  ,  we will play with the isolated pawn in many cases. }
4... exd5
{ Black's recapture with the e-pawn frequently leads to positions in which Black plays with an IQP. Let's consider the various scenarios after our natural reply. }
5. d4
{ We have arrived at an important moment for Black to choose their development plan. Before we consider their options, I need to make a crucial point.  This position is very similar to a line of the French Defence that is part of our repertoire: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  c5  4.Ngf3  Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  sees Nbd2 played instead of a pawn to c3.  There are various transpositions or lines that are very similar.    I organised the material, so the main coverage is done in the French chapter. This makes the most sense, as the arising structures are more typical of the French Tarrasch than a Sicilian. The term 'French Tarrasch IQP structure' exists, while there is no 'Black IQP in the c3-Sicilian' structure.   Let's check Black's options now:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Bb5  is a popular line that will likely transpose into the French Tarrasch. We'll check possible @@StartBracket@@bad@@EndBracket@@ deviations for Black, of course.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Bb5+  also happens frequently. We again reach a position that is very similar to a line of the French Tarrasch.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c4  is a questionable move, but I want to show why to demonstrate a typical idea.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  is rare but stops our preferred bishop move to b5. We are fine with natural development moves, though.   Lines A and B are played in about 70-80% of the games. Their coverage is relatively brief here due to their frequent transpositions to the French Tarrasch. }
5... Nc6
{ This is the most popular move, placing the knight on the most logical square, looking at the crucial d4 spot in front of the future IQP. }
6. Bb5
{ Why is developing the bishop to b5 the most promising square?  Let's consider: if we'd play  6.Bd3  , Black has  6...cxd4  , and we wouldn't be able to blockade Black's d5-pawn. After  7.cxd4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3p4/3p4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.cxd4  , we'd have total symmetry and no structural advantage.  Playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  makes more sense but is less powerful than @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5  because it blocks the e-file. We want to castle next and get a rook to e1 with a check. This is not possible with a bishop on e2.  The second advantage of Bb5 over Be2 is the pin that we establish. The pin and the quick Re1 idea are why Black has problems developing their knight to f6.   Can Black play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  , by the way? It is very risky, as  7.Bxc6+  bxc6  8.Qa4  is a natural sequence that poses serious problems. We attack c6 and are ready for O-O and Re1 - Black faces an unenviable defensive task.   We'll check @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  and the main move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  now. }
6... Nf6
{ This is the move that Black ideally wants to play. The knight has its most active post on f6, but it allows a pin by Bg5 and does not block the e-file, like ...Nge7 in the main line does. }
7. O-O { Black has to reckon with Re1+ now. } 7... Be7
{ Black blocks the e-file, a sensible move.   The alternative  7...Bd6  8.dxc5  would lead to the same positions, though. A different story is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/1Bpp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bd7  , when  9.Re1+  Be7  10.Qe2  is annoying for Black. They can't castle now and  10...Nxd4  11.cxd4  Bxb5+  12.Qxb5+  Qd7  13.Qe2  keeps the pressure on. }
8. dxc5 { We capture and force Black's bishop to move again. } 8... Bxc5 9. Bg5
{ The pin is even more powerful than the more obvious check with the rook. We threaten Bxf6 now, so Black has little choice. }
9... Be6 10. Nbd2 { We are ready for Nb3-d4, winning time along the way. }
10... O-O 11. Nb3
{ Here we see Black's dilemma: the bishop can go to the passive e7-square to break the pin, but that looks unattractive.   The move @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp3ppp/2n1bn2/1Bbp2B1/8/1NP2N2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bb6  looks better, but  12.Nbd4  gives White a comfortable edge. We have a good blockade of the IQP, and Black still has to deal with the annoying pin. }
