[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 exd5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5
{ Probably Black's most natural and popular move. After our capture on d5, we'll have a further split. }
4. exd5
{ Now, we often reach an IQP position. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  , Black often goes for the IQP and after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5  ,  we will play with the isolated pawn in many cases. }
4... exd5
{ Black's recapture with the e-pawn frequently leads to positions in which Black plays with an IQP. Let's consider the various scenarios after our natural reply. }
5. d4
{ We have arrived at an important moment for Black to choose their development plan. Before we consider their options, I need to make a crucial point.  This position is very similar to a line of the French Defence that is part of our repertoire: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  c5  4.Ngf3  Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  sees Nbd2 played instead of a pawn to c3.  There are various transpositions or lines that are very similar.    I organised the material, so the main coverage is done in the French chapter. This makes the most sense, as the arising structures are more typical of the French Tarrasch than a Sicilian. The term 'French Tarrasch IQP structure' exists, while there is no 'Black IQP in the c3-Sicilian' structure.   Let's check Black's options now:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Bb5  is a popular line that will likely transpose into the French Tarrasch. We'll check possible @@StartBracket@@bad@@EndBracket@@ deviations for Black, of course.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Bb5+  also happens frequently. We again reach a position that is very similar to a line of the French Tarrasch.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c4  is a questionable move, but I want to show why to demonstrate a typical idea.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  is rare but stops our preferred bishop move to b5. We are fine with natural development moves, though.   Lines A and B are played in about 70-80% of the games. Their coverage is relatively brief here due to their frequent transpositions to the French Tarrasch. }
5... Nc6
{ This is the most popular move, placing the knight on the most logical square, looking at the crucial d4 spot in front of the future IQP. }
6. Bb5
{ Why is developing the bishop to b5 the most promising square?  Let's consider: if we'd play  6.Bd3  , Black has  6...cxd4  , and we wouldn't be able to blockade Black's d5-pawn. After  7.cxd4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3p4/3p4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.cxd4  , we'd have total symmetry and no structural advantage.  Playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  makes more sense but is less powerful than @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5  because it blocks the e-file. We want to castle next and get a rook to e1 with a check. This is not possible with a bishop on e2.  The second advantage of Bb5 over Be2 is the pin that we establish. The pin and the quick Re1 idea are why Black has problems developing their knight to f6.   Can Black play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  , by the way? It is very risky, as  7.Bxc6+  bxc6  8.Qa4  is a natural sequence that poses serious problems. We attack c6 and are ready for O-O and Re1 - Black faces an unenviable defensive task.   We'll check @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  and the main move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  now. }
6... Bd6
{ Black needs to get their kingside developed to get castled quickly. With ...Bd6, they usually intend to play ...Nge7 to avoid the issues that we discuss following  6...Nf6  - it leaves the e-pawn open and allows a pin. }
7. dxc5 { A good moment to capture, making Black's bishop move again. } 7...
Bxc5 8. O-O Ne7
{ That is usually Black's intention behind the ...Bd6 move order.   They block the e-file and avoid the troubles of  8...Nf6  9.Bg5  , leading to a position we examine via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Bg5  , a more common move order. }
9. Nbd2
{ We want to connect our knight to the key d4-square, very logical play. } 9...
O-O 10. Nb3
{ Now Black has the choice between the two bishop moves. Both moves transpose to the chapter on the French Tarrasch:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2n5/1Bbp4/8/1NP2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bb6  11.Re1  @@StartBracket@@intending Be3@@EndBracket@@ - this variation,   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2n5/1Bbp4/8/1NP2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bd6  11.Bd3  @@StartBracket@@stopping ...Bg4 due to Bxh7+@@EndBracket@@ - this variation.  These are two answers with the key ideas. Of course, this is discussed in more detail in the actual chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B7) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 & Other 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 Qxd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5
{ Probably Black's most natural and popular move. After our capture on d5, we'll have a further split. }
4. exd5
{ Now, we often reach an IQP position. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  , Black often goes for the IQP and after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5  ,  we will play with the isolated pawn in many cases. }
4... Qxd5
{ Black avoids the IQP with this move; in fact, White could soon be the one with a @@StartBracket@@favourable@@EndBracket@@ IQP.  Most of the time, however, we play with an early Na3, intending to harass the queen with Nb5, leading to an open center without an isolated pawn. }
5. d4
{ After our move  5.d4  , it is a good moment to talk about various scenarios that may arise now.  A. Black captures on d4 now @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4  @@EndBracket@@ and after  6.cxd4  , we will play with an IQP. We are happy about their choice, as it is a favourable version of the isolated pawn. The key reason is that we will play Nc3, gaining a tempo on the queen. Of course, we'll discuss this in more detail in the notes to the move.   B. Our opponent realises that taking on d4 is premature and keeps the tension by playing @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  . Often, Black will play both knights to their natural squares, and it does not matter what move they started with. We will examine  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , the far more popular of the two, as the main move.  C. The rare move @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  deserves brief coverage for multiple reasons. I think it is somewhat underestimated and recommended the move in my course on the O'Kelly Sicilian for Black. The position after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  may also be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  e6  , which is the move order I advised to play with the black pieces. }
5... cxd4
{ This is quite clearly a concession, giving White the good c3-square for the knight. White will easily get a comfortable IQP position. }
6. cxd4
{ The IQP structure has been discussed a lot in chess literature or media, so I only want to summarise what is most important:  The side with the IQP enjoys fluent piece development and does not have any problem pieces. With many pieces on the board, the weakness of the isolated pawn is not that pronounced, as it is difficult to attack it multiple times.  This is not the case after trading minor pieces, when the rooks and queen may focus on attacking the pawn. Following this logic, the IQP side should keep minor pieces on, and if there are no active opportunities for the rooks, allow them to be traded.  The square in front of the pawn @@StartBracket@@d5 in this case@@EndBracket@@ is significant as it may serve as an outpost for the opponent. It is often favourable if the IQP side manages to push the pawn forward and break this potential blockade. The piece activity persists while the weakness gets removed. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3
{ We gain a tempo on Black's queen. Black's best moves are @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/3q4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qd6  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/3q4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qd8  now - they lead to similar positions, though. We'll focus on @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/3q4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qd8  to illustrate typical IQP play. A different idea for Black, but not a good one, is going for the @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/3q4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb4  pin. This move is quite popular below the master level and worth a look. }
7... Bb4
{ 'Pin and lose', you could say! 😏 Well, that's a bit too harsh, but we are surely happy to see the move. }
8. Bd3
{ This is clearly our best square for the bishop, aiming at Black's kingside. }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ Now the relatively best option for Black is something like  9...Qd8  10.a3  Be7  , when they accept a position of the 7...Qd8 line a full tempo down.  This is bad news for Black, but it's still better than the capture on c3, which is played most of the time. }
9... Bxc3 10. bxc3
{ We have reached a fantastic position now. Our pawn duo in the center can advance, and we have the bishop pair in a wide-open position. }
10... b6 11. c4
{ Black has no good square for the queen:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/p4ppp/1p2pn2/3q4/2PP4/3B1N2/P4PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qh5  12.Be2!  is very annoying for Black. Here's a funny line:  12...Bb7  13.Ng5  Qg6  14.Bd3  Qh5  15.Bxh7+!  , winning a pawn!  B. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/p4ppp/1p2pn2/3q4/2PP4/3B1N2/P4PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qd6  12.a4  looks to activate the bishop on a3.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/p4ppp/1p2pn2/3q4/2PP4/3B1N2/P4PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qd8  12.Bg5  is an annoying pin.  These lines amount to serious trouble for Black. We have long-term assets and the much easier game. }
*

