[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5
{ Probably Black's most natural and popular move. After our capture on d5, we'll have a further split. }
4. exd5
{ Now, we often reach an IQP position. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  , Black often goes for the IQP and after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5  ,  we will play with the isolated pawn in many cases. }
4... Qxd5
{ Black avoids the IQP with this move; in fact, White could soon be the one with a @@StartBracket@@favourable@@EndBracket@@ IQP.  Most of the time, however, we play with an early Na3, intending to harass the queen with Nb5, leading to an open center without an isolated pawn. }
5. d4
{ After our move  5.d4  , it is a good moment to talk about various scenarios that may arise now.  A. Black captures on d4 now @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4  @@EndBracket@@ and after  6.cxd4  , we will play with an IQP. We are happy about their choice, as it is a favourable version of the isolated pawn. The key reason is that we will play Nc3, gaining a tempo on the queen. Of course, we'll discuss this in more detail in the notes to the move.   B. Our opponent realises that taking on d4 is premature and keeps the tension by playing @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  . Often, Black will play both knights to their natural squares, and it does not matter what move they started with. We will examine  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , the far more popular of the two, as the main move.  C. The rare move @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  deserves brief coverage for multiple reasons. I think it is somewhat underestimated and recommended the move in my course on the O'Kelly Sicilian for Black. The position after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  may also be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  e6  , which is the move order I advised to play with the black pieces. }
5... cxd4
{ This is quite clearly a concession, giving White the good c3-square for the knight. White will easily get a comfortable IQP position. }
6. cxd4
{ The IQP structure has been discussed a lot in chess literature or media, so I only want to summarise what is most important:  The side with the IQP enjoys fluent piece development and does not have any problem pieces. With many pieces on the board, the weakness of the isolated pawn is not that pronounced, as it is difficult to attack it multiple times.  This is not the case after trading minor pieces, when the rooks and queen may focus on attacking the pawn. Following this logic, the IQP side should keep minor pieces on, and if there are no active opportunities for the rooks, allow them to be traded.  The square in front of the pawn @@StartBracket@@d5 in this case@@EndBracket@@ is significant as it may serve as an outpost for the opponent. It is often favourable if the IQP side manages to push the pawn forward and break this potential blockade. The piece activity persists while the weakness gets removed. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3
{ We gain a tempo on Black's queen. Black's best moves are @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/3q4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qd6  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/3q4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qd8  now - they lead to similar positions, though. We'll focus on @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/3q4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qd8  to illustrate typical IQP play. A different idea for Black, but not a good one, is going for the @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/3q4/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb4  pin. This move is quite popular below the master level and worth a look. }
7... Qd8
{ This is probably the wisest decision.   Black has a similar alternative in  7...Qd6  , when we'd use the same setup after the retreat to d8. }
8. Bd3
{ White has a good choice here between playing the bishop on d3 or c4. They are of equal strength, so it comes down to personal preference.  I'd like to show you a typical attacking plan that works best in the Bd3-based setups, which explains my preference. }
8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1
{ We want to place our pieces as actively as possible. Our rooks will likely be best on e1 and d1/c1, so starting with the rook move makes sense.   It's also possible to start with  10.Bg5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2bppp/4pn2/8/3P4/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 7 10@@EndFEN@@  10.a3  , all moves I suggest playing soon, too. More on it in a moment. }
10... Nc6
{ Black's best and most active piece setup. Sometimes you meet setups with ...Nbd7-b6-d5, which we are happy to see. Black's knight looks nice on d5 but does not attack much. The attacking plan I'll suggest in the notes to the next move would work well against this setup. }
11. a3
{ White usually plays this move in IQP structures. A key idea is establishing a battery of a bishop on c2/b1 and the queen on d3, building pressure on Black's kingside. This is often combined with Bg5, a move that fits perfectly with our mindset of developing as actively as possible. }
11... b6
{ Black prepares a queenside fianchetto, a good way to develop the queen's bishop. }
12. Bg5
{ Starting with the move  12.Bc2  is slightly inaccurate, as Black can play  12...Ba6!  to stop the Qd3 idea. We can start with the bishop development instead. }
12... Bb7 13. Bc2
{ Not the only good move, of course. There is nothing wrong about  13.Rc1  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2bppp/1pn1pn2/6B1/3P4/P1NB1N2/1P3PPP/R2QR1K1 w - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qd2  , intending Qf4-h4. }
13... Rc8 14. Qd3
{ Not the 'Mr. Subtle' approach, but this game is about checkmate, right? }
14... g6 { The purpose of our crude threat was creating this weakness. } 15. h4
{ Not the only good move, but I like to point out this somewhat underappreciated idea in IQP positions. We don't immediately threaten h4-h5, but Black always has to watch out for this attacking move.  In general, this IQP position is considered favourable for White, as it is easier to play with the initiative. I gave you some basic pointers, but it is useful for your general chess knowledge to study these structures more. IQP formations nicely demonstrate the struggle between dynamic and static aspects of chess.  In our repertoire, we usually play against the IQP; here, we take on the opposite role. }
