[White "B7) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 & Other 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 Qxd5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5
{ Probably Black's most natural and popular move. After our capture on d5, we'll have a further split. }
4. exd5
{ Now, we often reach an IQP position. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  , Black often goes for the IQP and after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5  ,  we will play with the isolated pawn in many cases. }
4... Qxd5
{ Black avoids the IQP with this move; in fact, White could soon be the one with a @@StartBracket@@favourable@@EndBracket@@ IQP.  Most of the time, however, we play with an early Na3, intending to harass the queen with Nb5, leading to an open center without an isolated pawn. }
5. d4
{ After our move  5.d4  , it is a good moment to talk about various scenarios that may arise now.  A. Black captures on d4 now @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4  @@EndBracket@@ and after  6.cxd4  , we will play with an IQP. We are happy about their choice, as it is a favourable version of the isolated pawn. The key reason is that we will play Nc3, gaining a tempo on the queen. Of course, we'll discuss this in more detail in the notes to the move.   B. Our opponent realises that taking on d4 is premature and keeps the tension by playing @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  . Often, Black will play both knights to their natural squares, and it does not matter what move they started with. We will examine  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , the far more popular of the two, as the main move.  C. The rare move @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  deserves brief coverage for multiple reasons. I think it is somewhat underestimated and recommended the move in my course on the O'Kelly Sicilian for Black. The position after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  may also be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  e6  , which is the move order I advised to play with the black pieces. }
5... Nf6
{ This is the main line by a mile. This follows the logic that this knight will be best placed on f6 with almost 100% certainty, while the optimal position of the other knight is not as obvious.  In line A, Black trades on d4 prematurely and thus allows the move Nc3, developing with a tempo on the Black's queen. In the other lines, Black avoids the capture on d4, making developing the b1-knight more difficult.  I suggest immediately tackling the question by playing  6.Na3  , intending to activate the knight on b5 or c4. This is a change to the first edition, when Na3 was usually combined with a more modest Nc2 continuation, securing the center. I suggest playing more aggressively in this course while keeping the initial moves identical. }
6. Na3
{ We immediately get our knight into the game, intending to activate it via b5 or c4. Now Black has a choice of lines:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pq4/3P4/N1P2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  is very natural and our main line. This position may also arise via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Na3  Nf6  .   B. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pq4/3P4/N1P2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qd8  is a prophylactic move. Black is afraid their queen on d5 is vulnerable and retreats voluntarily.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pq4/3P4/N1P2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...cxd4  is a premature trade, as is often the case. Here  7.Nb5  leads to a nice initiative for us.   D. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pq4/3P4/N1P2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  covers b5 but weakens the queenside a bit. We cover this move via the move order  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  6.Na3  Nf6  , which is more common. }
6... Qd8
{ Black retreats the queen, a prophylactic move. Black is afraid to be hit by Nb5 with a tempo and 'returns home' before this may happen. }
7. Nc4
{ In the first edition, I suggested  7.Nc2  here, which remains a solid option. White follows the simple development plan of Bd3, O-O, Qe2, Bf4/g5 and centralising the rooks. It's an easy-to-play alternative to my new suggestion, which is more ambitious. }
7... Nc6
{ Putting some pressure on d4 and threatening to take on d4, which would create an IQP. This pawn formation is less desirable here because our knight would not be well placed on c4.  Fortunately, we have a better way of entering the IQP position. }
8. Be3
{ We lend more cover to d4, allowing us to always recapture with a piece. We would retain a powerfully centralised minor piece on d4 after multiple trades. }
8... Nd5
{ This looks better than  8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  Nxd4  10.Bxd4  , when White's position is much better already. We can easily drum up an attack with Bd3 and Qf3. Both castling options are viable here, too. I prefer the more conservative kingside castling, but going to the other side looks tempting as well. }
9. Bd3
{ I like White's position here due to the much more active piece and superior development. Black can easily go wrong here, as the following line demonstrates. }
9... cxd4 10. Nxd4
{ Now Black should play a modest move like  10...Bd7  , when  11.Qf3  is an interesting reply, with O-O-O in mind. I prefer White, but Black is still in the game.  But what about the capture on e3 here? }
10... Nxe3 11. fxe3
{ At first, you might think that White's pawn structure is ruined and something has gone wrong, but a closer look shows that this is irrelevant, as our attack is powerful. We have Qf3 or Qg4 next, followed by O-O-O, which will set a challenging defensive task for Black. }
*

