[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B8) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nf6"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3
{ Our choice against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  is the move  3.c3  , the Delayed Alapin. Black's most popular reply is  3...d5  , but  3...Nf6  is an important alternative that leads to different positions. Black attacks our e-pawn and forces the advance. In my mind, 3...Nf6 is more promising for Black than 3...d5,  but these early decisions are often a matter of taste.Against  3...Nf6  , I decided to keep my suggestion from the first edition:  4.e5  Nd5  5.g3  , which has proven to be very effective in practice. In online games, it scores much better than  5.d4  or  5.Bc4  ,  showing that these more popular lines are not easy for White to play.One problem in these lines is: White tries to keep the pawn on e5, which is double-edged. The pawn can be strong but may also be a weakness. We go for the simple approach of always taking a pawn coming to d6, avoiding this strategic complexity. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B8) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nf6"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 Nf6 { Black attacks our pawn and forces it forward. }
4. e5 Nd5
{ After  4...Nd5  , White usually goes for  5.d4  or  5.Bc4  ,  with d4 to follow. They are the most popular lines but difficult to handle in practice. In the first edition, I recommended the setup starting with  5.g3  ,  which is simpler to play and scores well in practice. }
5. g3
{ I am sticking with my recommendation from the first edition. We follow a simple. yet effective idea: our bishop will be well-placed on the long diagonal, while Black's c8-bishop takes a while to develop. Black will attack our e5-pawn sooner rather than later. If they play ...d6, we take this pawn and avoid a possible target on e5.How does Black continue now?   A.  5...d6  is our main line. Black attacks our advanced pawn immediately and forces a decision. As mentioned: we take on d6.   B.  5...Nc6  will often lead to A, as ...d6 next is very natural. There are some worse/risky alternatives for Black, though.   C.  5...b6  is rare but worth a look. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4  cxd4  6.cxd4  , a popular way for Black is  6...b6  - some players might want to play in a similar vein against our line. }
5... Nc6
{ This knight is undoubtedly best placed on c6, so Black starts with this development. }
6. Bg2
{ It's important to note that we don't play the move d4 early on. Our strategy is to wait for the move ...d6 and then capture this pawn. If we play  6.d4  cxd4  7.cxd4  d6  ,  the capture on d6 is unattractive, as we would reach an IQP position when our bishop is misplaced.   The type of position we want is reached after  6.Bg2  d6  7.exd6  Bxd6  8.O-O  O-O  9.d4  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Nxd4  11.Qxd4  , when we have no structural weakness @@StartBracket@@like an IQP@@EndBracket@@ and a strong fianchetto bishop. }
6... Qc7
{ A risky move, but it's tempting to attack the e-pawn. Black's best move is  6...d6  , when  7.exd6  Bxd6  transposes to our main line 5...d6, when the same situation occurs. Sometimes Black plays  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2pnP3/8/2P2NP1/PP1P1PBP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  and ...d6 soon after - this would be a worse version of the main line, as ...Be7 is an unnecessary move.Let's check the queen move to c7 now. How do we react to the attack on our pawn? }
7. O-O
{ We don't need to cover the pawn, as Black can hardly risk taking it. It's objectively better for Black to play a move like  7...d6  ,  but we keep a good advantage against it. The move ...Qc7 makes little sense if the pawn grab on e5 is too risky. }
7... d6
{ Not very principled, but better than taking. We can now get a better version of the main line by playing a precise move order. }
8. exd6
{ An interesting alternative is  8.c4  Nb6  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.Nc3  ,  but the simpler capture is enough if you remember the next move. }
8... Bxd6 9. Na3
{ Highlighting the unfortunate position of Black's queen and bishop. } 9... a6
10. Nc4
{ We activate the knight with a tempo gain. Black can't afford to give up their bishop. }
10... Be7 11. d4
{ As we finally open the centre. This is a slightly better version of the main line, as Black has lost some time with the bishop. }
*

