[White "B8) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nf6"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 Nf6 { Black attacks our pawn and forces it forward. }
4. e5 Nd5
{ After  4...Nd5  , White usually goes for  5.d4  or  5.Bc4  ,  with d4 to follow. They are the most popular lines but difficult to handle in practice. In the first edition, I recommended the setup starting with  5.g3  ,  which is simpler to play and scores well in practice. }
5. g3
{ I am sticking with my recommendation from the first edition. We follow a simple. yet effective idea: our bishop will be well-placed on the long diagonal, while Black's c8-bishop takes a while to develop. Black will attack our e5-pawn sooner rather than later. If they play ...d6, we take this pawn and avoid a possible target on e5.How does Black continue now?   A.  5...d6  is our main line. Black attacks our advanced pawn immediately and forces a decision. As mentioned: we take on d6.   B.  5...Nc6  will often lead to A, as ...d6 next is very natural. There are some worse/risky alternatives for Black, though.   C.  5...b6  is rare but worth a look. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4  cxd4  6.cxd4  , a popular way for Black is  6...b6  - some players might want to play in a similar vein against our line. }
5... b6
{ After 5. d4, some lines based on ...b6 are popular. Going for the fianchetto here is a different story, though. }
6. Bg2 Bb7
{ Going  6...Ba6  does not net Black anything after  7.d3  when we can castle on the next move. The bishop is misplaced on a6 if it fails to prevent castling. }
7. O-O
{ This position has been reached in a fair amount of online Blitz games, one of them with me playing White. This game made me realise that 5...b6 is played sometimes and is worth a look. Let's check how my game continued. }
7... d6
{ A bad move, but my reaction was far from perfect. Black has also played  7...Be7  frequently, when  8.d4!  cxd4  9.Nxd4  is a strong reply, in the same style as we will see now against 7...d6. }
8. d4
{ I captured on d6, as it is usual in the g3 Variation. Here, however, d2-d4 is very strong. Of course, the point is very tough to spot in a Blitz game. Let's see. }
8... cxd4 { 8...dxe5?  9.Nxe5  is even worse, as we threaten c4 and Qa4+. } 9.
Nxd4
{ A very cool idea! Now Black can't take on e5, as we will see. At the same time, we threaten c4, winning the bishop. Black is in danger already. }
9... dxe5
{ Black should go for  9...Nc6  , when White is 'only' much better, for example, after  10.exd6  Bxd6  11.Qg4  , when  11...O-O?  12.Nxe6  is crushing. Black must play  11...Kf8  in this line and suffer. }
10. Nxe6 { Boom! } 10... fxe6 11. Qh5+
{ Even better than  11.c4  . we can inflict more damage first.   Black is completely lost after  11.Qh5+  . All three options are resignable now:   A.  11...Kd7  12.c4   B.  11...Ke7  12.Bg5+   C.  11...g6  12.Qxe5  . }
