[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B8) Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nf6"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2...e6 3.c3 Nf6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 Nf6 { Black attacks our pawn and forces it forward. }
4. e5 Nd5
{ After  4...Nd5  , White usually goes for  5.d4  or  5.Bc4  ,  with d4 to follow. They are the most popular lines but difficult to handle in practice. In the first edition, I recommended the setup starting with  5.g3  ,  which is simpler to play and scores well in practice. }
5. g3
{ I am sticking with my recommendation from the first edition. We follow a simple. yet effective idea: our bishop will be well-placed on the long diagonal, while Black's c8-bishop takes a while to develop. Black will attack our e5-pawn sooner rather than later. If they play ...d6, we take this pawn and avoid a possible target on e5.How does Black continue now?   A.  5...d6  is our main line. Black attacks our advanced pawn immediately and forces a decision. As mentioned: we take on d6.   B.  5...Nc6  will often lead to A, as ...d6 next is very natural. There are some worse/risky alternatives for Black, though.   C.  5...b6  is rare but worth a look. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4  cxd4  6.cxd4  , a popular way for Black is  6...b6  - some players might want to play in a similar vein against our line. }
5... d6 6. exd6
{ Our concept does not involve keeping this pawn. In the 5. d4 variation, White's aim is different. They try to keep the pawn on e5 and establish a space advance. The practical problem often turns out to be that the advanced pawn can be a weakness, too.We play a simpler strategy. After taking on d6, we want to complete kingside castling and open the centre with d4. }
6... Bxd6 7. Bg2 Nc6
{ This position may also arise via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2NP1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Bg2  d6  7.exd6  Bxd6  , a common alternative move order. }
8. O-O
{ Starting with  8.d4  is also fine and should lead to a transposition. } 8...
O-O 9. d4
{ Our idea is to use the superior bishop position on g2, compared to the counterpart on c8. We will also try to use the queenside pawn majority, which is often nicely supported by our fianchettoed bishop.After 9. d4, Black's most natural move is taking d4 to clarify the central situation. If they want to keep the tension, 9...b6 is a sensible choice. }
9... cxd4
{ Taking d4 is by far the most popular move. Black clarifies the ventral structure and then organises their pieces accordingly. }
10. Nxd4
{ We open the bishop diagonal and avoid any structural weakness. Black usually trades knights on d4, but a quick look at  10...Bd7  is warranted. }
10... Bd7
{ Black avoids the trade and develops the bishop. We can exploit this idea by keeping the d4-knight on the board now. }
11. c4
{ I want to get this move in first, then move our d4-knight.   It's important to avoid  11.Nf5?  here, by the way. After  11...exf5!  12.Qxd5  Be6  Black is better due to the much better development. }
11... Nf6
{ They can also go to e7, but we'd still retreat our knight. A sample line is  11...Nde7  12.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@or 12.Nb3@@EndBracket@@  12...Qc7  13.Nc3  ,  when we threaten Nb5. }
12. Nb3
{ The comp also likes  12.Nf3  , but keeping the long diagonal open looks more natural. }
12... Qe7 13. Nc3
{ Our general idea is putting pressure on the queenside, based on the strong bishop. Black also has to worry about Bg5, though. If you believe the comp, this is not that dangerous, but a human might easily play  13...h6?  14.Nb5  Be5  15.Be3  , and end up in trouble. }
