O-O 9. d4
{ Our idea is to use the superior bishop position on g2, compared to the counterpart on c8. We will also try to use the queenside pawn majority, which is often nicely supported by our fianchettoed bishop.After 9. d4, Black's most natural move is taking d4 to clarify the central situation. If they want to keep the tension, 9...b6 is a sensible choice. }
9... cxd4
{ Taking d4 is by far the most popular move. Black clarifies the ventral structure and then organises their pieces accordingly. }
10. Nxd4
{ We open the bishop diagonal and avoid any structural weakness. Black usually trades knights on d4, but a quick look at  10...Bd7  is warranted. }
10... Nxd4 { Black has less space; trading is a logical step. } 11. Qxd4
{ We always want to take on d4 with a piece to avoid an IQP. Now we get to an important crossroads, as Black needs to be precise to avoid getting under serious pressure.   The first point to understand for both sides: White is not threatening to win a pawn by capturing twice on d5. We can't give up our best piece, activate Black's position and weaken our kingside for a stupid pawn. Black's best move is  11...Qc7  ,  which correctly ignores the possibility of Bxd5.Master-level players usually play this move, but there are plenty of alternatives that more materialistic or inexperienced players may go for. I will take a look at  11...Nf6  and  11...Qb6  , as these look quite logical, but give White an excellent position. }
11... Nf6
{ A passive move that gives us a huge advantage. I also found games with  11...Be7  , which has a similar idea. After  12.Rd1 }
12. Rd1 { Centralising with tempo is simple and strong. } 12... Be7
{ Black has no good alternative. It's important to understand how strong our position is after the following sequence. }
13. Qxd8 { We trade the heavy pieces to reach a dream position. } 13... Rxd8
14. Rxd8+ Bxd8 15. a4
{ The difference between our bishop on g2 and the guy on c8 is enormous. Black can't move anything on the queenside and can easily lose in short order now. If you look at something like  15...Bc7  16.a5  a6  17.c4  Rb8  18.Be3  Nd7  19.b4  b6  20.b5  axb5  21.a6  , you see how bad it can get quickly. }
