{ After  4...Nd5  , White usually goes for  5.d4  or  5.Bc4  ,  with d4 to follow. They are the most popular lines but difficult to handle in practice. In the first edition, I recommended the setup starting with  5.g3  ,  which is simpler to play and scores well in practice. }
5. g3
{ I am sticking with my recommendation from the first edition. We follow a simple. yet effective idea: our bishop will be well-placed on the long diagonal, while Black's c8-bishop takes a while to develop. Black will attack our e5-pawn sooner rather than later. If they play ...d6, we take this pawn and avoid a possible target on e5.How does Black continue now?   A.  5...d6  is our main line. Black attacks our advanced pawn immediately and forces a decision. As mentioned: we take on d6.   B.  5...Nc6  will often lead to A, as ...d6 next is very natural. There are some worse/risky alternatives for Black, though.   C.  5...b6  is rare but worth a look. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4  cxd4  6.cxd4  , a popular way for Black is  6...b6  - some players might want to play in a similar vein against our line. }
5... d6 6. exd6
{ Our concept does not involve keeping this pawn. In the 5. d4 variation, White's aim is different. They try to keep the pawn on e5 and establish a space advance. The practical problem often turns out to be that the advanced pawn can be a weakness, too.We play a simpler strategy. After taking on d6, we want to complete kingside castling and open the centre with d4. }
6... Bxd6 7. Bg2 Nc6
{ This position may also arise via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2pnP3/8/2P2NP1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Bg2  d6  7.exd6  Bxd6  , a common alternative move order. }
8. O-O
{ Starting with  8.d4  is also fine and should lead to a transposition. } 8...
O-O 9. d4
{ Our idea is to use the superior bishop position on g2, compared to the counterpart on c8. We will also try to use the queenside pawn majority, which is often nicely supported by our fianchettoed bishop.After 9. d4, Black's most natural move is taking d4 to clarify the central situation. If they want to keep the tension, 9...b6 is a sensible choice. }
9... cxd4
{ Taking d4 is by far the most popular move. Black clarifies the ventral structure and then organises their pieces accordingly. }
10. Nxd4
{ We open the bishop diagonal and avoid any structural weakness. Black usually trades knights on d4, but a quick look at  10...Bd7  is warranted. }
10... Nxd4 { Black has less space; trading is a logical step. } 11. Qxd4
{ We always want to take on d4 with a piece to avoid an IQP. Now we get to an important crossroads, as Black needs to be precise to avoid getting under serious pressure.   The first point to understand for both sides: White is not threatening to win a pawn by capturing twice on d5. We can't give up our best piece, activate Black's position and weaken our kingside for a stupid pawn. Black's best move is  11...Qc7  ,  which correctly ignores the possibility of Bxd5.Master-level players usually play this move, but there are plenty of alternatives that more materialistic or inexperienced players may go for. I will take a look at  11...Nf6  and  11...Qb6  , as these look quite logical, but give White an excellent position. }
11... Qc7
{ Black's best defence. They are not worried about the capture on d5 and prepare the moves ...Rd8 and ...Bd7. }
12. c4
{ I already suggested this move in the first edition and still think it is better than  12.Nd2  , which was more popular at the time. Now after  12.c4  it looks like  12...Nf6  is best, while  12...Nb4?  is a tempting but bad alternative. We'll also have a look at  12...Nb6  , which can be tricky to meet if you don't know the best reply. }
12... Nf6 { This is the best knight move. } 13. Nc3
{ Natural and best. We develop the knight and threaten Nb5. } 13... Bd7
{ Black's best move. There are two alternatives which are worse.   A.  13...a6  14.Ne4!  is nice for White after  14...Nxe4  15.Qxe4  or @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1pq2ppp/p2bpn2/8/2PQN3/6P1/PP3PBP/R1B2RK1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Be5  15.Qc5  - In both cases, our pressure based on the monster bishop is the key factor.   B.  13...Be5  14.Nb5!  is a typical motive, giving us the advantage. Black has to play  14...Qb8  or  14...Bxd4  15.Nxc7  Rb8  16.Nb5  , when we have great play against Black's queenside again.   After Black's best move  13...Bd7  , I suggest a different move now compared to the first edition. My original suggestion was  14.Rd1  , which remains a reasonable choice. In the meantime, however, a different continuation has emerged that I prefer now. }
14. Nb5
{ I like the direct nature of this move. We get the bishop pair and ensure that our g2-bishop is not traded against its counterpart on d7. }
14... Bxb5 15. cxb5
{ Alright, we have forced this position with our knight jump. I assess this position as equal, but I think it is easier to play for White. Black always needs to decide how to handle the pressure on b7. Covering b7 with a piece is not ideal, but ...b6 has drawbacks, too. Giving up the c6-square can be a problem for Black.   A likely continuation is  15...Rfd8  16.Qd3  Rac8  17.Qe2  , when the comps suggest  17...b6  as the best, which I would be reluctant to play as Black, as it feels committal to weaken c6.   I think the endgame after @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/ppqb1ppp/3bpn2/8/2PQ4/2N3P1/PP3PBP/R1B2RK1 w - - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nb5  is a good option for White to play without any risk. If you want to keep more pieces on the board, my old suggestion of  14.Rd1  is still valid. }
