[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B9) Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ After 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3, Black's three main moves  2...d6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , comprise about 90% of the games. You'll meet a different move in about 1 out of 10 ten games.  In this chapter, we'll examine the most important ones.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  , the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon, is the most common of the sidelines.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  is the O'Kelly Variation. I have released a course on the O'Kelly for the black pieces, which tells you that I think it is quite reasonable.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  is the Nimzovich Variation - it's not one of Nimzo's best ideas.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...b6  starts an early queenside fianchetto.  We'll have a look at these four lines. Other moves look decidedly odd and can be handled with common sense approaches. }
