[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B9) Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzovich Variation in the Sicilian is one of Nimzo's more dubious inventions. White can achieve an advantage in multiple ways. }
3. e5 { Clearly best. We gain space with a tempo on the knight. } 3... Nd5 4.
Nc3
{ This is the strongest move, attacking Black's centralised piece.  Black now can choose between taking on c3 or covering the knight with 4...e6, the most popular move. }
4... Nxc3
{ This is the modern way to play the Nimzovich. In recent years, it was sometimes played by stronger players as a surprise weapon but did not withstand any closer scrutiny. }
5. dxc3
{ We take away from the center to speed up development, a common sight in many openings. }
5... Nc6 6. Bf4
{ We cover our strong e5-pawn, severely restricting Black's pieces. A good general plan for White is completing development with Qd2 or Bd3/Qe2 and playing for O-O-O, in most cases.  Often, our h-pawn can advance to h5 to gain more space and enable Rh3-g3 at some point. Playing the h-pawn also makes it tougher or impossible for Black to play ...h6 and ...g5, an idea to activate the f8-bishop finally.   Black could play  6...Qb6  now, when we keep our pawn with  7.b3  - fancy pawn sacrifices are unnecessary here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B9) Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzovich Variation in the Sicilian is one of Nimzo's more dubious inventions. White can achieve an advantage in multiple ways. }
3. e5 { Clearly best. We gain space with a tempo on the knight. } 3... Nd5 4.
Nc3
{ This is the strongest move, attacking Black's centralised piece.  Black now can choose between taking on c3 or covering the knight with 4...e6, the most popular move. }
4... e6 { This is the traditional main line of the Nimzovich. } 5. Ne4
{ This is a new recommendation in the second edition. In the first one, I recommended the 'official refutation'  5.Nxd5  exd5  6.d4  here, which remains excellent for White.  There was a problem, though.  You meet this Nimzovich line once in a blue moon and 5.Nxd5 gets very tactical and sharp in some cases.  Only after writing the first edition in 2018, I saw that 5.Ne4 is just as good and much easier to handle. It was recommended in John Shaw's Playing 1.e4, where I saw it first. }
5... f5
{ Black attacks our knight, the most forcing move.   They have also tried  5...d6  , when  6.exd6  Bxd6  7.Bb5+  is great for White. Black has nothing better than allowing  7...Nc6  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.Nxd6+  Qxd6  10.O-O  , when Black's pawn structure is ruined.   Another dreadful line for Black is  5...Nc6  6.c4  Nb6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nd6+  Bxd6  9.exd6  , when it feels like the c8-bishop might never move in this game. }
6. Nc3
{ That's the funny point! We ask Black what their weakening pawn move has accomplished. }
6... Nc6
{ This is played most of the time.   After  6...Nxc3  7.dxc3  leads to a position similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/8/2pnP3/8/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nxc3  5.dxc3  , when White is much better, too. }
7. Nxd5 exd5 8. d4
{ Let's open the position and expose all the weaknesses in Black's camp. Compared to 5.Nxd5, Black has the additional moves ...Nc6 and ...f5 on the board. The latter weakens the whole kingside and compromises the king's safety. Black is in serious trouble here. }
