[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B9) Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2.Nf3 b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ This is a rather uncommon variation, but it is slightly annoying for our repertoire. The reason is that the way to punish Black is to play 3.d4, heading for an open Sicilian where ...b6 is a slow setup. Still, I will not recommend playing that way, as the move is scarce.  If you know beforehand that your opponent will play this line, you might want to prepare 3.d4 in detail for such a game. The critical line goes  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Bb7  5.Nc3  a6  6.Bg5  Qc7  , and now  7.Nd5  is tough for Black, but it is better prepared before the game.  If your opponent surprises you with 2...b6, I recommend a simple approach. }
3. Bc4
{ The general plan is the very natural O-O, Re1, c3 and d4.   Note that  3.c3  does not work all that well here, as after  3...Bb7  , there is no great way to react to the threat against e4. }
3... Bb7
{ Black attacks our e-pawn, which gets us to the only point worth remembering in this line. }
4. O-O
{ We don't have to cover the pawn, as now  4...Bxe4?  5.Bxf7+!  Kxf7  6.Ng5+  Ke8  7.Nxe4  leads to a dreadful position for Black. We have restored the material balance and weakened Black's king position. Their king is on e8, but they have forfeited castling rights. }
4... e6 5. Re1
{ We have conveniently covered our central pawn and enjoy an easy-to-play position. We want to play c3 & d4 next, occupying the center.   Against  5...Nf6  6.e5  Nd5  7.d4  is strong - we open the game while Black is still far away from completing development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
