1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ Black goes for the O'Kelly Variation, a sideline with some tricky ideas. In 2022, I created a course on the O'Kelly for Black, which tells you that I think the opening has some merit. What's my recommendation for White? }
3. c3
{ This fits well with our repertoire.  3.c4  leads to Maroczy bind/Hedgehog positions, while  3.Nc3  will most likely later transpose to an open Sicilian.  Our Alapin-style approach is also a very respectable choice. Compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  , we now have Nf3, and ...a6 inserted. This means it must be at least slightly more favourable for White. Nf3 is always useful, while ...a6 delays development and weakens the queenside, particularly the square b6.   What do we have to check now?  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  is Black's most popular and best move, I think. We cover this move in a trainable line.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  is also reasonable, but just a transposition. After  4.d4  d5  , we land in the chapter on @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.c3  , a common transposition.  Other moves can be met with common sense, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.d4  , or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.e5  Nd5  5.d4  when the move ...a6 makes no sense. You'll be fine by just playing normal moves that develop and control the center - there is no need to learn moves by heart for such a rare line. }
3... d5
{ This is the most popular move, even though it opens the position while remaining rather less well developed, compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  d5  . }
4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4
{ Now we have reached an important crossroads for Black. I studied these lines in detail for my course from Black's perspective. I believe Black's only fully satisfactory move is  5...e6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ now, when we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  a6  , which we examine in the dedicated chapter on this branch of the Sicilian.  Why do I think that only 5...e6 works well? Let's have a look at the alternatives to understand this point.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  is an active-looking move and is frequently played. It is too ambitious, though. We'll examine this line in a moment.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4?  6.cxd4  is a scenario that Black wants to avoid. We get to play Nc3 with a tempo on Black's queen.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is met with the powerful move  6.Be3!  , when Black is stuck in a dilemma. Taking on d4 is undesirable @@StartBracket@@like in option B@@EndBracket@@, but c5 is hanging. There is no good solution for Black, as we'll examine shortly.   By the way: the idea of @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  is to meet  6.Be3  with  6...Nd7!  , covering the c-pawn. Our reply for White to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  is  6.Na3  , but this is covered in a different chapter, as already mentioned. }
5... Nf6
{ A natural and popular move, but Black has problems after the best reply. } 6.
Be3
{ A strong move! Now we threaten to grab the c5-pawn, which is an idea that Black can't ignore. Other lines in the c3-Sicilian feature a sacrifice of the c-pawn, but the move ...a6 has weakened Black's queenside. This makes ideas like Nd2-c4 even more powerful. }
6... cxd4
{ There is no good way to avoid this move.   After, for example,  6...Bg4  7.dxc5!  Qxd1+  8.Kxd1  , we are much better. We can support the c-pawn with b4, and Nd2-c4 is an important idea later. }
7. cxd4 { Very nice - now we manage Nc3 with a gain of tempo. } 7... Bg4
{ This is too ambitious.   Black has to try  7...e6  8.Nc3  Qd8  , and accept that it will be an unattractive version of the IQP for Black. We examine this scenario in the chapter about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  , when  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  cxd4?!  6.cxd4  leads to the same story. }
8. Nc3 { Here we go! } 8... Qd6
{ 8...Qa5  is also favourably met with  9.Qb3!  , attacking the weak b-pawn. }
9. Qb3 Bxf3 10. gxf3 { Black has no good way to defend the b-pawn now. } 10...
b5 11. a4
{ Black's position is falling apart.   After  11...b4  12.Ne4  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/4pppp/p2q1n2/1p6/P2P4/1QN1BP2/1P3P1P/R3KB1R b KQkq a3 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...bxa4  12.Rxa4  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/4pppp/p2q1n2/8/p2P4/1QN1BP2/1P3P1P/R3KB1R w KQkq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qxa4+  @@EndBracket@@  Black is not surviving the opening phase. }
