{ Now we have reached an important crossroads for Black. I studied these lines in detail for my course from Black's perspective. I believe Black's only fully satisfactory move is  5...e6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ now, when we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  a6  , which we examine in the dedicated chapter on this branch of the Sicilian.  Why do I think that only 5...e6 works well? Let's have a look at the alternatives to understand this point.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  is an active-looking move and is frequently played. It is too ambitious, though. We'll examine this line in a moment.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd4?  6.cxd4  is a scenario that Black wants to avoid. We get to play Nc3 with a tempo on Black's queen.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is met with the powerful move  6.Be3!  , when Black is stuck in a dilemma. Taking on d4 is undesirable @@StartBracket@@like in option B@@EndBracket@@, but c5 is hanging. There is no good solution for Black, as we'll examine shortly.   By the way: the idea of @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  is to meet  6.Be3  with  6...Nd7!  , covering the c-pawn. Our reply for White to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  is  6.Na3  , but this is covered in a different chapter, as already mentioned. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the move that Black would love to play, but it has a serious drawback. The following line looks convincing and renders the bishop move quite dubious. }
6. Be2 { We break the pin and prepare to castle. } 6... e6
{ Black's best try, getting the kingside development going.   6...Nf6  7.h3  Bh5  8.O-O  e6  may lead to the same position, of course. }
7. h3
{ It is useful to insert this as h3 is a little improvement for White in all cases. It also has a concrete plan attached, as we will see later. }
7... Bh5 8. O-O
{ White has a great alternative here with  8.c4  Qd8  9.d5  , but I like my suggestion from the first edition even more. Our job is a bit simpler here. }
8... Nf6 9. Be3
{ We already know this idea from examining @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Be3!  - Black has to capture d4 now; otherwise, we'd win the c-pawn.I must add that  @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2pq3b/3P4/2P2N1P/PP2BPP1/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.c4  Qd8  10.d5  , similar to 8.c4, is a more complicated but promising option. }
9... cxd4
{ If Black tries to delay this, we might take on c5 and keep the pawn. c3-c4 and Nc3 is also an idea. }
10. cxd4 Nc6 11. Nc3 Qd6
{ The most testing move.   After  11...Qd8  12.Qb3  Bb4  13.Rfd1  White is comfortably better. We threaten d4-d5, and  13...Bxc3  14.bxc3  is nice for White, too. We have the bishops and ideas of c4&d5, breaking through in the center. }
12. g4 { White is also OK after a more standard approach, but this is strong. }
12... Bg6 13. Ne5
{ The point. Black cannot take the pawn on e5, and White prepares moves like Qb3, Bf3 and/or Bf4 to increase the pressure. Let's examine why Black can't take twice on e5 and some alternatives:   A.  13...Nxe5  14.dxe5  Qxe5  15.Qa4+  Nd7  16.Bf4!  Qc5  17.Rfd1  gives White a winning attack.   B.  13...Nxe5  14.dxe5  Qxd1  15.Rfxd1  Nd7  already looks horrible, but  16.Nb5!  is a direct win even.   C. Best for Black is the modest move  13...Be7  , but we have a good choice between  14.Qb3  Rb8  15.Rad1  to keep the pressure up, or to go for @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1p2bppp/p1nqpnb1/4N3/3P2P1/2N1B2P/PP2BP2/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bf3  O-O  15.Nxg6  hxg6  16.d5  , when the position opens for our pair of bishops. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B9) Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2.Nf3 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ The Hyper-accelerated Dragon with 2....g6 is mostly played to reach a Dragon setup while avoiding the Rossolimo after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  or the Moscow after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  . It is the most common among the second-tier options for Black. }
3. c3
{ White now has two main tries for an advantage: the first is going for a Maroczy Bind with  3.c4  , followed by 4.d4. This is probably most critical for Black, but White needs to study quite a body of theory, as Black chooses the setup. This means that you need to be ready for a range of lines. I decided against covering this complex option here as 2...g6 is a line you won't face very frequently.   Fortunately, there is a second option in  3.c3  , which fits nicely with our repertoire choices against 2...e6 and 2...a6. After  3.c3  , we again get a c3-Sicilian while avoiding the most respectable setups available to Black. In this version of the Alapin, Black is committed to ...g6 and has trouble equalising completely.  Black now must choose when to play ...d5: right away, to recapture with the queen, or wait until White has played d4. It looks like  3...d5  is the strongest move, but  3...Bg7  is significantly more popular - good news for us! }
3... Bg7
{ This natural move is by far the most popular, but White has good chances for an edge against it. }
4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4
{ Now Black should hit at our center with the move 5...d5, and that's the most popular move by far. }
5... d6
{ This move is too passive. Black does not attack White's center and will suffer in a cramped position. }
6. h3
{ I like this prophylactic move best. White prevents ...Bg4, and Black now struggles to find a good square for this piece.   It is, of course, not a mistake to play  6.Nc3  or  6.Be2  here, White's center is a large asset in any case. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3
{ White is better with natural moves, supporting the center.   Again, there is nothing wrong with  8.Be2  or  8.Bd3  - we want to support our center. Later we can generate play, usually on the c-file and the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B9) Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2.Nf3 g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ The Hyper-accelerated Dragon with 2....g6 is mostly played to reach a Dragon setup while avoiding the Rossolimo after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  or the Moscow after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  . It is the most common among the second-tier options for Black. }
3. c3
{ White now has two main tries for an advantage: the first is going for a Maroczy Bind with  3.c4  , followed by 4.d4. This is probably most critical for Black, but White needs to study quite a body of theory, as Black chooses the setup. This means that you need to be ready for a range of lines. I decided against covering this complex option here as 2...g6 is a line you won't face very frequently.   Fortunately, there is a second option in  3.c3  , which fits nicely with our repertoire choices against 2...e6 and 2...a6. After  3.c3  , we again get a c3-Sicilian while avoiding the most respectable setups available to Black. In this version of the Alapin, Black is committed to ...g6 and has trouble equalising completely.  Black now must choose when to play ...d5: right away, to recapture with the queen, or wait until White has played d4. It looks like  3...d5  is the strongest move, but  3...Bg7  is significantly more popular - good news for us! }
3... Bg7
{ This natural move is by far the most popular, but White has good chances for an edge against it. }
4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4
{ Now Black should hit at our center with the move 5...d5, and that's the most popular move by far. }
5... d5 6. e5
{ We happily grab space in the center and blunt Black's bishop. A good way to assess this position is a comparison with the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  g6  4.O-O  Bg7  5.Re1  Nf6  6.c3  O-O  7.d4  cxd4  8.cxd4  d5  9.e5  Ne4  , which is part of our repertoire. White is slightly better in these positions.  Now, compare this outcome to the current position. Black is stuck with a knight on g8 and has problems getting it into the game. In the Rossolimo, this piece is in the center of the board. It is fascinating to see that playing Bb5 is also a key element for White's strategy here. Our bishop has no good job on other squares @@StartBracket@@d3 is less attractive against a g6-pawn@@EndBracket@@, so trading it against a knight on c6 makes some sense.   Let's see how it unfolds. We examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp2ppbp/6p1/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp2ppbp/6p1/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , Black's most popular moves. I also found some games where @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp2ppbp/6p1/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  was tried, stopping our Bb5 idea. White has multiple ways to gain an advantage against it, but I like the simple reply  7.h3  when Black's c8-bishop has no good development option. We have a massive space advantage, and Black's only potential counterplay ...f6, will create severe weaknesses on the kingside. }
6... Bg4 { A very logical move. Black pins the knight that supports d4. } 7.
Bb5+
{ This is a powerful move to remember. Black will be OK if White does not opt for this disruptive check. }
7... Nd7
{ This is better than  7...Nc6  , but the knight does not put any pressure on d4 now and is rather misplaced. After  7...Nc6  , we'd transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp2ppbp/6p1/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  7.Bb5  Bg4  , which frequently arises from both move orders. }
8. O-O
{ We have more than one good move here, of course.   8.Nbd2  is a good alternative, for example. }
8... a6 9. Be2
{ White is better here due to the space advantage and Black's slightly awkward pieces. It is harder for Black to play ...f6 after a trade on f3 as the light squares are weakened a lot. }
