[White "B9) Sicilian – 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian – 2.Nf3 g6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ The Hyper-accelerated Dragon with 2....g6 is mostly played to reach a Dragon setup while avoiding the Rossolimo after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  or the Moscow after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  . It is the most common among the second-tier options for Black. }
3. c3
{ White now has two main tries for an advantage: the first is going for a Maroczy Bind with  3.c4  , followed by 4.d4. This is probably most critical for Black, but White needs to study quite a body of theory, as Black chooses the setup. This means that you need to be ready for a range of lines. I decided against covering this complex option here as 2...g6 is a line you won't face very frequently.   Fortunately, there is a second option in  3.c3  , which fits nicely with our repertoire choices against 2...e6 and 2...a6. After  3.c3  , we again get a c3-Sicilian while avoiding the most respectable setups available to Black. In this version of the Alapin, Black is committed to ...g6 and has trouble equalising completely.  Black now must choose when to play ...d5: right away, to recapture with the queen, or wait until White has played d4. It looks like  3...d5  is the strongest move, but  3...Bg7  is significantly more popular - good news for us! }
3... d5 { This is Black's best option, I think. } 4. exd5
{ White has a good alternative in  4.e5!?  , which gains space in the center. It shares some ideas with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppp1p/6p1/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg7  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  d5  6.e5  , when White is much better.   Here, after  4.e5  , Black is in a slightly better situation as they are more flexible. It's even feasible for Black never to play ...Bg7, which would only put the bishop in a passive spot anyway. I think White is still better after  4.e5  , but I prefer the clarity of the capture on d5. The resulting positions look simpler to play. }
4... Qxd5 5. d4 Bg7
{ In the first edition, I devoted some space to the analysis of  5...Nc6  , when I suggested  6.Be2  , leading to some complications. Now I think that @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pp2pp1p/2n3p1/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  is much simpler when Black has an unpleasant choice: taking on d4 allows us to play Nc3 with tempo, or they can play  6...Bg7  7.dxc5!  giving up the c-pawn. I see no compensation for Black in this scenario. }
6. Nbd2
{ This move was a recent discovery when I wrote the first edition of the course. Now, about five years later, it is established as a major option for White. }
6... cxd4
{ This looks like the critical choice. Black clarifies the pawn structure after it is clear that Nc3 can never hit the queen, a common problem after trading on d4. }
7. Bc4 { That was the idea of Nbd2, of course. } 7... Qd8
{ Black usually retreats to d8, placing the queen out of danger.   After  7...Qh5  it's best to play  8.Qb3  , a nice intermediate move to allow Nxd4 next without involving a queen trade. }
8. Nxd4
{ It's best to avoid the IQP structure here, as  8.cxd4  Nh6  @@StartBracket@@and ...Nf5 later@@EndBracket@@  or the more conventional @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp2ppbp/6p1/8/2BN4/2P5/PP1N1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nf6  is fine for Black. Our d2-knight is misplaced and too passive.   After the correct  8.Nxd4  , White has a small advantage due to our good development and active pieces @@StartBracket@@Bc4@@EndBracket@@. A likely continuation is  8...Nf6  9.O-O  O-O  10.Re1  , but our moves are fairly flexible. You may also play @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/5np1/8/2BN4/2P5/PP1N1PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.N2f3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/5np1/8/2BN4/2P5/PP1N1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.N2f3  , for example. }
