[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C1) French – Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "French – Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ Hello and Welcome to the section on the French Defense.  The French Defense 1.e4 e6 is popular for Black, particularly those below the master level. Depending on the data, the French ranks third or fourth in popularity rankings and occurs about 10-15% of the time. }
2. d4 d5
{ In the first edition of this course, I suggested the Exchange Variation  3.exd5  exd5  , which was a controversial choice. While some students liked it and had good results, the symmetrical character of the positions felt stale for others. I still like the Exchange and think it is a good option.   However, for this course, I suggest a different option. I recommend the Tarrasch Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , the favourite move of many players who prefer to exert pressure from a position of safety.  A key difference to the Exchange Variation is that we keep the central tension and do not determine the pawn structure. Depending on Black's reply, we'll reach different pawn structures. The Tarrasch is more sophisticated to play but will lead to a wider variety of position types. The move 3.Nd2 looks more passive than 3.Nc3, but has two advantages to 3.Nc3 - we prevent the ...Bb4 pin and still have c2-c3 supporting our centre.   Let's discuss our three chapters. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  , the coverage is split as follows:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.e5  leads to a typical French pawn centre and space advantage for White. In my mind, White reaches an advantage in many ways. I recommend a setup based on f4, which is very difficult for Black to handle.  In the first edition, one argument favouring the Exchange Variation was to avoid the typical French structure, as Black wanted to reach this formation. I suggest a different approach this time: we play for a particularly GOOD version of the French centre. There is no doubt that  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.e5  is the best version and offers better prospects for White than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  , two popular lines.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  is Black's second main line. I suggest  4.Ngf3  , when Black frequently accepts an Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. A sample line is  4...Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  . White has good chances for a comfortable pull here. A better alternative for Black is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  , which currently looks like Black's best line against the Tarrasch. Black should get equal chances with perfect play.  C. The third chapter is about other moves for Black, most importantly @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...dxe4  @@StartBracket@@the solid Rubinstein@@EndBracket@@ and the quirky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  , which looks much better for White.  I think Black only reaches equal chances in a particular subset of lines in B, and they need to know this complex well. If the opponent has learned 20 moves of perfect theory, we must try to beat them from an equal position. These positions are not boring, which is important.  There are some essential incentives to play the Tarrasch.If Black wants a closed centre, typical of the French, they must play 3...Nf6, which looks good for White. It is by far the most popular move below master level.The currently best lines for Black are played in less than 10% of the games below master level.The Tarrasch is not popular at the moment, and often, your opponents will only have superficial knowledge.White plays with sound and classical pawn structures. Complex pawn structures can be a problem after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bb4  , for example.  I want to add a personal note. When I wrote the first edition, I wanted to suggest the Tarrasch. I always liked it and played it when given the chance.  I got interested in the Exchange because I saw some impressive games of the World Champion, Magnus Carlsen, and liked these ideas. I was surprised to see how poisonous this line can be and decided to recommend it.  Now, for the second edition, I return to my old favourite, and I am happy to present it to you. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C2) French Tarrasch – 3...Nf6"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter, we examine 3...Nf6, which remains Black's most popular reply to the Tarrasch. In my mind, the prospect of getting this move on the board is a huge incentive to play 3. Nd2; I am pleased about White's prospects in the lines I'll suggest in this chapter. }
1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn and tells us they want to play a true French-style position. We are happy to advance our pawn and gain space. }
4. e5
{ We advance the e-pawn and establish the typical 'French' pawn centre. The next moves are more or less mandatory, so I'll explain why I think this particular version of the French centre is favourable for us. }
4... Nfd7 5. c3
{ I want to play the moves c3 and f4 to support our centre. The order of these moves does not matter, it is just as good to start with  5.f4  and after  5...c5  6.c3  reach the same position. }
5... c5 { Black needs to attack our centre quickly. } 6. f4
{ White has a wide choice of variations. The main alternatives for White are  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ne2  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP1N1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ngf3  ,  which also gives White good chances to keep a small advantage.  However, I have always thought that the ambitious 6.f4 line must be the critical test of Black's game, as White tries to grab as much space as possible and challenges Black to find any counterplay. In my mind, Black is worse and needs to be precise to avoid being hopelessly passive.What's the difference to other, similar lines in the French? This is best explained after the next moves are on the board. }
6... Nc6 7. Ndf3
{ This is much better than  7.Ngf3  ,  when our knights step on each other's toes. We better keep the knight on g1 for the moment and later decide if e2 or h3 are the best squares to get it into the game.Now let's see why I think White is in good shape here. We have a nice version of the French pawn centre, which becomes clearer if we compare it to two other lines.   A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nf3  - Advance Variation.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.f4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.Be3  - Classical Steinitz.In A, Black has not yet developed the g8-knight. This is helpful, as the knight quickly reaches the good square f5. The knight is well-placed there, putting pressure on d4. In the Tarrasch, the knight is on d7, a much worse square. The knight might support ...f6 at some point, but it mostly clogs up the queenside development. In the Advance, Black's pieces are not standing on each other's toes that much.In B, the Classical Steinitz, Black's setup is identical to the one we have here. Therefore this comparison is the most instructive. In the Steinitz, White has a knight on c3. Thus they don't manage to keep a pawn on d4 by covering it with c3. A key element for Black is the capture on d4, followed by piece pressure.The current main line of the Steinitz is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.f4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.Be3  cxd4  8.Nxd4  Qb6  ,  when Black starts a direct counterplay against d4 and b2. In the Tarrasch, Black also frequently plays the move ...Qb6, but we always keep a pawn on d4, maintaining our space advantage.So is Black just much worse here, and it's all fun and an easy win for us? No, it is not that simple. I think our position is good and advantageous, but there is a drawback. We have neglected development a bit, and we need to be careful not to overextend and run into a counterblow. We'll often push more pawns on the kingside to attack. This can backfire if executed carelessly. We must examine Black's possible replies.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qb6  is the main reply. Black puts pressure on our d-pawn and prevents our natural development move Bd3.   B.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  ,  followed by a further split.   C.  7...Be7  ,  preparing kingside castling. This line looks a bit passive and difficult for Black to play. They can't afford this slow type of play, in my mind.We'll check these three moves. If Black plays something strange, we continue with Bd3 and Ne2, supporting our centre and preparing to castle. There is a reason why Black usually goes for a quick ...Qb6: to prevent this natural development. If we finish our development undisturbed, Black is in trouble - they have too little space and counterplay. }
