[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C2) French Tarrasch – 3...Nf6"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.c3 c5 6.f4 Nc6 7.Ndf3 Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn and tells us they want to play a true French-style position. We are happy to advance our pawn and gain space. }
4. e5
{ We advance the e-pawn and establish the typical 'French' pawn centre. The next moves are more or less mandatory, so I'll explain why I think this particular version of the French centre is favourable for us. }
4... Nfd7 5. c3
{ I want to play the moves c3 and f4 to support our centre. The order of these moves does not matter, it is just as good to start with  5.f4  and after  5...c5  6.c3  reach the same position. }
5... c5 { Black needs to attack our centre quickly. } 6. f4
{ White has a wide choice of variations. The main alternatives for White are  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ne2  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP1N1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ngf3  ,  which also gives White good chances to keep a small advantage. However, I have always thought that the ambitious f4 line must be a critical test of Black's game, as White tries to grab as much space as possible and challenges Black to find any counterplay. In my mind, Black is worse and needs to be precise to avoid being hopelessly passive. }
6... Nc6
{ Black almost always plays this logical move first. They could start with  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  , and then play  7...Nc6  8.Ndf3  ,  which transposes to a line we'll examine soon. There is no reasonable scenario in which Black wouldn't want the knight on c6, so playing it immediately makes sense. }
7. Ndf3
{ This is much better than  7.Ngf3  ,  when our knights step on each other's toes. We better keep the knight on g1 for the moment and later decide if e2 or h3 are the best squares to get it into the game. }
7... Be7
{ Black want to castle kingside quickly but fails to put any pressure on our centre. We are allowed to construct our best possible development setup: Bd3&Ne2. }
8. Bd3
{ Here we go. We placed the bishop on the best diagonal, eyeing Black's kingside. }
8... O-O
{ Black sometimes tries  8...Qb6  here, leading to a worse version of 7...Qb6. We continue  9.Ne2  and have more or less saved the tempo on playing a3, a move which we need to make usually. This point is much more obvious if you have studied the main line 7...Qb6 8.a3 already. }
9. Ne2
{ I recommend sticking to this setup. Here we have much leeway, so moves like  9.h4  or  9.Nh3  are good, too. After our move  9.Ne2  I want to check two options: Black can play  9...f6  , attacking our pawn chain, or  9...f5  , trying to block further play on the kingside. }
9... f5
{ Black tries to shut down the kingside. How to react? This type of kingside formation frequently occurs in the current chapter, and there is a standard reply that usually works well. This case is no exception. The way to go is O-O, Kh1, Rg1 and g4! opening the kingside, after all. This takes a while, but Black has no active play and can't do much to stop it. }
10. O-O
{ I will continue this trainable to demonstrate our plan. Black's position is already quite bad, and there is no clear-cut best way to defend. I use a frequently seen defensive idea for Black's moves, but they might play differently. It does not change our kingside plan, as Black can't do anything to distract us - there is no real counterplay. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Nb6
{ Black intends ...Bd7-e8 to add a defender to the kingside. If Black plays ...Nb4 here or over the next moves, we'd preserve the bishop with Bb1. After a later g4, the bishop helps to put pressure on f5. }
12. Kh1
{ We continue with our plan. As mentioned, Black can't do anything active in the meantime. }
12... Bd7 13. Rg1 Be8
{ We have reached an interesting moment. Should we play g4 as planned? } 14. g4
{ You might think that  14...fxg4  15.Rxg4  Bh5  helps Black's bishop to activate, but the open file is more important, as we will see. }
14... fxg4
{ Black has nothing better.   A.  14...g6  15.gxf5  exf5  is fantastic for White strategically. We won't win by a quick checkmate, but we have all the assets, like the protected passed pawn on e5. We can still play for an attack with h4-h5, but this needs some preparation. A cool idea would be to play pawns to a3 and b3 @@StartBracket@@take away squares for Black's knights@@EndBracket@@ and then play for a rook lift on the second rank with Ra2, Ng3, h3, Ra2-h2 and finally push the h-pawn. You can be patient here, as Black's position is so passive.   B.  14...Bg6  15.gxf5  Bxf5  16.Ng3  Bxd3  17.Qxd3  is great for White, as Black can't do much about our attack based on f4-f5. A sample line continues  17...Nb4  18.Qe2  Rc8  19.f5!  exf5  20.Nh5  g6  21.Bh6  Rf7  22.e6  and White wins. }
15. Rxg4 Bh5
{ It looks like Black has gained something, but our attack on the g-file proves too strong. }
16. Rg3
{ The key attacking idea is a combination of Qg1 and f4-f5 now. There is no way for Black to defend against it.   A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2b1pp/1nn1p3/3pP2b/3P1P2/3B1NR1/PP2N2P/R1BQ3K b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nb4  is directly killed by  17.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  18.Rh3  g6  19.Ng3  Qe8  20.Nxh5  gxh5  21.Ng5+  Bxg5  22.Rxh5+  Kg7  23.Rxg5+  Kf7  24.f5  and White wins.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2b1pp/1nn1p3/3pP2b/3P1P2/3B1NR1/PP2N2P/R1BQ3K b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Qe8  17.Qg1  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r3qrk1/pp2b1pp/1nn1p3/3pP2b/3P1P2/3B1NR1/PP2N2P/R1BQ3K w - - 3 17@@EndFEN@@  17.f5  is strong, too@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3qrk1/pp2b1pp/1nn1p3/3pP2b/3P1P2/3B1NR1/PP2N2P/R1B3QK b - - 4 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Kh8  18.Qg2  ,  with Rh3 next, is also great for White.   C. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2b1pp/1nn1p3/3pP2b/3P1P2/3B1NR1/PP2N2P/R1BQ3K b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Kh8  17.f5  exf5  18.Nf4  Bxf3  19.Qxf3  Nxd4  20.Qh5  Qe8  21.Ng6+  Kg8  22.Nxe7+  Qxe7  23.Bh6  g6  24.Rxg6+  ,  and again White crashes through.These lines are meant to illustrate some of the ideas. White has great attacking chances after the opening of the g-file. In general, Black's defensive setup based on ...f5 is a welcome sight, as we don't have to worry much about counterplay. }
