[White "C2) French Tarrasch – 3...Nf6"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.c3 c5 6.f4 Nc6 7.Ndf3 Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn and tells us they want to play a true French-style position. We are happy to advance our pawn and gain space. }
4. e5
{ We advance the e-pawn and establish the typical 'French' pawn centre. The next moves are more or less mandatory, so I'll explain why I think this particular version of the French centre is favourable for us. }
4... Nfd7 5. c3
{ I want to play the moves c3 and f4 to support our centre. The order of these moves does not matter, it is just as good to start with  5.f4  and after  5...c5  6.c3  reach the same position. }
5... c5 { Black needs to attack our centre quickly. } 6. f4
{ White has a wide choice of variations. The main alternatives for White are  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ne2  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP1N1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ngf3  ,  which also gives White good chances to keep a small advantage. However, I have always thought that the ambitious f4 line must be a critical test of Black's game, as White tries to grab as much space as possible and challenges Black to find any counterplay. In my mind, Black is worse and needs to be precise to avoid being hopelessly passive. }
6... Nc6
{ Black almost always plays this logical move first. They could start with  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  , and then play  7...Nc6  8.Ndf3  ,  which transposes to a line we'll examine soon. There is no reasonable scenario in which Black wouldn't want the knight on c6, so playing it immediately makes sense. }
7. Ndf3
{ This is much better than  7.Ngf3  ,  when our knights step on each other's toes. We better keep the knight on g1 for the moment and later decide if e2 or h3 are the best squares to get it into the game. }
7... Be7
{ Black want to castle kingside quickly but fails to put any pressure on our centre. We are allowed to construct our best possible development setup: Bd3&Ne2. }
8. Bd3
{ Here we go. We placed the bishop on the best diagonal, eyeing Black's kingside. }
8... O-O
{ Black sometimes tries  8...Qb6  here, leading to a worse version of 7...Qb6. We continue  9.Ne2  and have more or less saved the tempo on playing a3, a move which we need to make usually. This point is much more obvious if you have studied the main line 7...Qb6 8.a3 already. }
9. Ne2
{ I recommend sticking to this setup. Here we have much leeway, so moves like  9.h4  or  9.Nh3  are good, too. After our move  9.Ne2  I want to check two options: Black can play  9...f6  , attacking our pawn chain, or  9...f5  , trying to block further play on the kingside. }
9... f6
{ Black attacks our advanced pawn, which sounds like an active idea. However, there is a fundamental problem. They don't have enough pressure on e5 to force a capture on f6. We will maintain the pawn on e5 and continue to improve our position. Black has to be cautious about ever taking on e5, as it only improves our bishop on c1 and the e2.knight. We'll examine this scenario in a minute. }
10. O-O cxd4
{ I want to examine the structure after Black trades on d4 and e5. I also found several games in which Black played  10...Qb6  11.Kh1  then decided to clarify the central structure, leading to the same scenario. }
11. cxd4 fxe5 12. fxe5
{ We have now gained more space for our pieces, particularly the c1-bishop and the e2-knight. We have plenty of attacking ideas now. One that I like is the queen manoeuvre Qe1-g3. Here's an example of this idea. }
12... Rf7
{ Black needs to get their knight to f8. The line  12...Nb6?  13.Qc2  h6  14.Bxh6!  gxh6  15.Bh7+  Kh8  16.Qg6  is just one extreme example of why White has a crushing attack. It's funny that Stockfish already evaluates all moves other than 12...Rf7 as about +5 for White @@StartBracket@@the rook move is 'only' +2@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Qe1 { Starting the queen manoeuvre. } 13... Nf8 14. a3
{ A useful prophylaxis.  14.Qg3  Nb4  15.Bb1  Bd7  16.a3  Bb5  is unnecessarily complicated. }
14... Bd7 15. Qg3
{ We threaten Bh6 now, but that's the immediate idea. It takes three moves - Be3, Rf2 and Raf1 - to get all the pieces involved in the attack. There is no way Black is surviving this force. }
