[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C2) French Tarrasch – 3...Nf6"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.c3 c5 6.f4 Nc6 7.Ndf3 cxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn and tells us they want to play a true French-style position. We are happy to advance our pawn and gain space. }
4. e5
{ We advance the e-pawn and establish the typical 'French' pawn centre. The next moves are more or less mandatory, so I'll explain why I think this particular version of the French centre is favourable for us. }
4... Nfd7 5. c3
{ I want to play the moves c3 and f4 to support our centre. The order of these moves does not matter, it is just as good to start with  5.f4  and after  5...c5  6.c3  reach the same position. }
5... c5 { Black needs to attack our centre quickly. } 6. f4
{ White has a wide choice of variations. The main alternatives for White are  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ne2  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP1N1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ngf3  ,  which also gives White good chances to keep a small advantage. However, I have always thought that the ambitious f4 line must be a critical test of Black's game, as White tries to grab as much space as possible and challenges Black to find any counterplay. In my mind, Black is worse and needs to be precise to avoid being hopelessly passive. }
6... Nc6
{ Black almost always plays this logical move first. They could start with  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  , and then play  7...Nc6  8.Ndf3  ,  which transposes to a line we'll examine soon. There is no reasonable scenario in which Black wouldn't want the knight on c6, so playing it immediately makes sense. }
7. Ndf3
{ This is much better than  7.Ngf3  ,  when our knights step on each other's toes. We better keep the knight on g1 for the moment and later decide if e2 or h3 are the best squares to get it into the game. }
7... cxd4
{ Black trades on d4 first, before making other commitments. It will often transpose to positions we examine via different move orders. Let's consider after our recapture. }
8. cxd4
{ Black now has many moves, but they will often lead to lines or position types that we discuss elsewhere. Here's an overview.   A.  8...Qb6  is the most popular move in practice, when I suggest  9.a3  to transpose to  the line 7...Qb6 8.a3 cxd4 9. cxd4, this chapter's main line.   B.  8...Be7  ,  8...f6  or  8...f5  lead to positions that we have examined via 7...Be7 - we play Bd3/Ne2 and O-O and get an excellent position.   C. Black can start a queenside activity with  8...a5  or  8...Nb6  ,  often followed by ...a5. This is an option with an independent value that does not transpose.   D. There is  8...Bb4+  ,  which also leads to independent play. In the line 7...Qb6 8.a3 this option is gone. }
8... Bb4+
{ Black goes for the check and has concrete ideas, depending on our reply. You might be surprised by my suggestion, hang on. }
9. Kf2
{ It looks a bit odd at first, but the king move makes a lot of sense once you look deeper. First, playing  9.Bd2  is not a mistake, but I think  9.Kf2  is stronger. We avoid trades and plan g3 and Kg2 next. This is a good setup and maybe even better than castling in some cases, as our rook might be well-placed on h1 @@StartBracket@@think of h4 ideas@@EndBracket@@. We still intend to develop our kingside with Bd3&Ne2 - this is the ideal formation to attack and defend our centre.An additional point to mention is that Black's bishop has no useful role on b4 now and will likely move again, which compensates for the slight loss of time we accept by moving the king.We will check 9...f6, and 9...Qb6 now. }
9... Qb6
{ A typical move in this line. Black puts pressure on d4 and places the queen in a threatening position across from our king. We have multiple ways to maintain an advantage now; it's not easy to pick one, but I think my suggestion is the easiest to play in practice. }
10. Be3
{ I like this move, securing the diagonal g1-a7. It is crucial to understand that Black's only chance is an aggressive strike against our king. If we avoid any immediate trouble, we are in fantastic shape. Black has no space and bad pieces all over the place.   Instead of  10.Be3  , the move  10.h4  is just as good. We'll play this advance on the next turn, most likely. }
10... f6
{ Or  10...O-O  11.h4!  f6  12.Nh3  ,  leading to the same position. I'll explain the benefits of h4&Nh3 in a moment. }
11. h4
{ This is a powerful move and important to discuss. Black hopes to create some counterplay against our king. This can be based on opening the f-file, but also on the move ...g5. If we played  11.g3  here, Black has  11...g5!?  to make it messy. This is still better for White, but there is no need to give Black that much hope.The move 11.h4! makes ...g5 impossible and allows our knight to be developed to h3. It is surprisingly well-placed on this square. Pushing the h-pawn is an excellent example of combining prophylactic thinking with active ideas. }
11... O-O 12. Nh3
{ We have to avoid  12.Bd3?  fxe5  13.fxe5  Nxd4  , when Black uses the insecure king position. A good alternative is @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp1n2pp/1qn1pp2/3pP3/1b1P1P1P/4BN2/PP3KP1/R2Q1BNR w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ne2  , though. I suggest  12.Nh3  , as it is more aggressive and sets a little trap. }
12... Be7 { A natural move, attacking the b-pawn... and 'something else'... }
13. Rb1 { We cover the b-pawn and allow the following sequence. } 13... fxe5
14. fxe5 Bxh4+
{ That was the second threat of 12...Be7, but we don't mind it at all. } 15.
Kg1 Be7 16. Bd3
{ Black has snatched a pawn, but the h-file is open, and we have a devastating attack. A fun line is  16...Ndxe5  17.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  18.Nfg5+  Kg8  19.Qh5  and Black can't avoid checkmate. }
*

