9... f6
{ Black wants to open files against our king. They could also start with  9...O-O  , when  10.g3  f6  11.Kg2  leads to the same positions. }
10. g3 { We clear the way to g2. } 10... O-O 11. Kg2
{ Our king walk is finished, and now we are ready to complete development. Black now needs to do something drastic to make it interesting. I found many games that featured  11...fxe5?  12.fxe5  when we get an automatic attack by simple means. Bishop to d3, h4, Nh3-g5 come to mind. This is comparable to the situation after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Ne2  f6  , when Black is in a similarly awful spot. }
11... g5
{ Pretty desperate measures, but passive play won't do it. A continuation like  11...fxe5?  12.fxe5  Be7  13.Bd3  Qb6  14.Ne2  Rf7  15.h4  is too one-sided. Black's ...g5 move requires a precise reply. }
12. Bd3
{ A cool-headed response refutes Black's trying to muddy the waters. We don't need to take any pawns but prefer to develop. It turns out that Black has no fully satisfactory move now.   A.  12...g4  13.Nh4  f5  14.h3  opens kingside decisively   B.  12...gxf4  13.Bxf4  only helps White.   C.  12...fxe5  13.fxe5  is doomed, too. Black is just hopelessly weak on the kingside. }
