[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.c3 c5 6.f4 Nc6 7.Ndf3 Qb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn and tells us they want to play a true French-style position. We are happy to advance our pawn and gain space. }
4. e5
{ We advance the e-pawn and establish the typical 'French' pawn centre. The next moves are more or less mandatory, so I'll explain why I think this particular version of the French centre is favourable for us. }
4... Nfd7 5. c3
{ I want to play the moves c3 and f4 to support our centre. The order of these moves does not matter, it is just as good to start with  5.f4  and after  5...c5  6.c3  reach the same position. }
5... c5 { Black needs to attack our centre quickly. } 6. f4
{ White has a wide choice of variations. The main alternatives for White are  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ne2  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP1N1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Nc6  7.Ngf3  ,  which also gives White good chances to keep a small advantage. However, I have always thought that the ambitious f4 line must be a critical test of Black's game, as White tries to grab as much space as possible and challenges Black to find any counterplay. In my mind, Black is worse and needs to be precise to avoid being hopelessly passive. }
6... Nc6
{ Black almost always plays this logical move first. They could start with  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  , and then play  7...Nc6  8.Ndf3  ,  which transposes to a line we'll examine soon. There is no reasonable scenario in which Black wouldn't want the knight on c6, so playing it immediately makes sense. }
7. Ndf3
{ This is much better than  7.Ngf3  ,  when our knights step on each other's toes. We better keep the knight on g1 for the moment and later decide if e2 or h3 are the best squares to get it into the game. }
7... Qb6
{ Black increases the pressure on our centre and makes it more difficult for us to develop our pieces. We currently can't play  8.Bd3?  ,  as it blunders our d-pawn. Playing Be3 also won't work, as the queen attacks b2. These are the key reasons why 7...Qb6 is the main line and Black's most popular move. How to react? }
8. a3
{ I award an exclam to the move because I am fascinated by the idea. This move always annoyed me when I still played the French Defence with Black. I wanted to play this line with Black but never found a good solution against it. This all dates back to the pre-engine era. At the time, I didn't even properly understand the idea of the move. Now I got the chance to analyze it with modern technology and am happy to show you what it is all about.   What does  8.a3  do? We need to consider some points.◉ Black exerts pressure on d4 and b2. The most problematic point is that we can't play Bd3, as d4 is under attack.◉ How do we develop the kingside if Bd3 is impossible? It is unattractive to play 8. Ne2,  as it takes Bd3 completely out of the picture. And where is the knight going next? What about developing the knight to h3? After  8.Nh3  , Black has  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Bb4+  when we need to play  10.Kf2  f6!  ,  leading to a slightly uncomfortable situation. We have seen that moving the king to f2 is an option, but it is awkward with a knight on h3.◉ This leads to the conclusion that there is no promising piece development. That leaves the moves  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.g3  and  8.h4  , which have been tested numerous times. The move  8.h4  is the more interesting of the two, as it grabs a lot of space on the kingside. It turned out that the best reply to  8.h4  is the surprising move  8...a5!  ,  when Black intends to push the pawn to a4 and possibly a3 to create weaknesses on the queenside.◉ So Black has the idea to push the a-pawn up the board. This is where  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.a3!  comes into play. Its purpose is not to play b2-b4, which you might think at first. We want to be ready to meet  8...a5  with  9.b3!  ,  stopping Black's queenside play. Once this counterplay is stopped, our job gets a lot easier. We can still play h4 to start the kingside expansion - it will frequently be our next move.It is fascinating to analyze this line, as you frequently get the impression that Black is running out of constructive moves. Many normal-looking moves turn out to be mistaken. Let's consider Black's options now.   A.  8...a5  is the most popular move, claiming some queenside space. It also stops b2-b4, but the pawn advance was not our main intention. We answer with  9.b3!  , when Black's queenside campaign is stopped.   B.  8...Be7  develops and aims at kingside castling. It is important to see that we don't play  9.b4  against it, but  9.h4  , which is significantly stronger.   C.  8...cxd4  is frequently played but has little independent value. It leads to worse versions of A, B, or other lines that don't convince. I'll examine these three moves in detail.   D. I also want to mention the following briefly:  8...f6?!  is questionable and rare at this point. We examine  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  f6  ,  a more common way to play ...f6 for Black. The story is the same, though. After  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...f6?!  we have the strong move  9.Bd3  , just as after @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  f6  10.Bd3  is great for White.   E.  8...c4?!  shuts down the queenside and gives us a free hand to play on the kingside. We can immediately expand with  9.h4  or go for a slower approach with  9.Qc2  to prepare Be3 and develop pieces. We have a large space advantage on the kingside, so there is no rush. }
8... Be7
{ Black develops and seems to prepare kingside castling. It is not easy for Black to make ...O-O work satisfactorily, though. We'll see that Black's job is difficult, as many natural continuations lead to trouble. }
9. h4
{ The main point to understand about 8. a3: it is NOT played to continue with b2-b4, if allowed. Here the move  9.b4  is possible, but after  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  a6!  Black gets enough to play with the following plan: ...Qc7, ...b5, ...Nb6-c4, using the hole we created on the c-file.   Playing  9.h4  and expland on the kingside is much stronger. It is instructive to see that @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.a3  a5  9.b3  Be7  is also answered with  10.h4!  ,  which leads to a very similar position to the current one.   After  9.h4  it is tough to make a constructive move.   A.  9...a5  10.b3!  transposes to  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a5  9.b3  Be7  10.h4  , which is nice for White and our chapter's main line.   B.  9...O-O?!  10.Bd3!  allows our dream formation.   C.  9...f6?!  10.Bd3!  is the same story. We discuss these two options with the moves ...a5 and b3 included. There is no need to look at this slightly different version, as the ideas are the same.   D.  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  is possible, but leads to lines that we examine via  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Be7  10.h4  . This means that we can already stop the trainable line here. }
