h4
{ We continue with the planned kingside operation. We must avoid  10.Bd3?  Nb3  @@StartBracket@@'Oh No, my d-pawn!'@@EndBracket@@ and @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1q2p3/n2pP3/3P1P2/P4N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.b4?!  Nc4  @@StartBracket@@@@StartBracket@@'Oh No, my c4-square!'@@EndBracket@@. The move  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1q2p3/n2pP3/3P1P2/P4N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.h4  fits best with our other choices, but I want to add that  10.Ne2  is good here, too. We usually don't want to block the f1-bishop with Ne2, but here the knight has a clear path to the good c3-square. The knight move is just as good as 10. h4, I mostly award the exclam for avoiding the mistakes mentioned earlier. }
10... Qb3
{ I will examine this move in more detail, but there are alternatives for Black.   A.  10...Be7  is a waiting move. These positions may also arise via other move orders, for example,  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/P1P2N2/1P4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  9.h4!  cxd4  10.cxd4  Na5  is possible. I suggest  11.h5  h6  @@StartBracket@@ Black can play a piece to b3, but this is the same story as on move 10@@EndBracket@@  12.Ne2  ,  intending Nc3. If Black goes  12...Qb3  13.Qd2  Nc4  14.Qc3  Qxc3+  15.Nxc3  ,  we reach an excellent endgame. This is all very similar to 10...Qb3, which we will examine now.   B.  10...Nb3  is the other way to use the b3-square. After  11.Rb1  Black is more or less forced to capture our bishop. If they don't take it, we'll move it to e3 and leave the knight on b3 sitting without any purpose. After  11...Nxc1  12.Qxc1  White has a comfortable advantage. We can develop easily with Bd3 and have already made progress on the kingside. Black has invested lots of time but for little gain. Compared to all the drawbacks of Black's position, the bishop pair does not play a major role here. }
11. Qd2
{ This looks best. We attack the knight and ask Black for a decision. They can go for  11...Nc4  or move the queen to protect the knight. }
11... Qa4
{ More interesting than  11...Nc4  12.Qd3  , when  12...Qxd3  13.Bxd3  leads to an excellent position for White. We don't mind the queen trade, as the large space advantage will remain a key factor. Even without queens, attacking the kingside with a pawn storm will be effective. }
12. Ne2
{ We also have  12.Rb1  or  12.Qd3  here, but the knight move looks best to me. We are threatening Nc3 now, so Black has little choice now. }
12... Nb3 { Black nothing else, in view of our Nc3 idea. } 13. Qd1
{ We save our rook with the pin and force Black's next move. } 13... Qa5+ 14.
Bd2 Qb6
{ After  14...Nxd2  15.Qxd2  Qxd2+  16.Kxd2  ,  we get a good endgame. Black has to worry about Nc3-b5 ideas and still suffers from a lack of space. }
15. Rb1 Nxd2 16. Nxd2
{ Just avoid the embarrassing  16.Qxd2??  Bxa3!  ,  which would spoil everything with a careless move. After the correct recapture, we are in good shape. A setup with Nf3, Nc3 and Bd3 looks like a good way to start. }
