{ Exactly! Now they can't grab the d-pawn, as  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  Nxd4??  13.Nxd4  Qxd4  14.Bxh7+  wins the queen. Black also needs to worry about a possible greek gift sacrifice. We'll check now:   A.  11...f6?  , which allows the greek gift and leads to spectacular lines.   B.  11...cxd4  is better when we can't take on h7, but  12.cxd4  still gives us a huge advantage. Black can also play the passive move @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p1nbppp/1qn1p3/p1ppP3/3P1P1P/PPPB1N2/6P1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...f5  12.h5  ,  when we reach a similar position to 10...f5 11. h5, which we have examined already. }
11... cxd4
{ A much better move than 11...f6, as now the sacrifice only leads to a draw. It's best to simply recapture d4. }
12. cxd4
{ I checked  12.Bxh7+  here, but it only leads to a draw after  12...Kxh7  13.Ng5  Kh6  , when we don't have a win. It's a close call for Black, but they can hold with only moves after  14.Qd3  f5  15.exf6  Nxf6  16.h5  Ne4  17.Nxe4  dxe4  18.Qxe4  Rf5  19.g4  dxc3  ... And it even continues from here. Long story short: just recapture on d4. }
12... f6
{ Black's best try is probably still  12...f5  ,  but we need to check why we can't smash on h7 now. }
13. Ne2
{ This is best, completing our desired piece setup. It's tempting to go for the Greek gift, but it does not work here. Compared to @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p1nbppp/1qn1p3/p1ppP3/3P1P1P/PPPB1N2/6P1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...f6?  12.Bxh7+!  , the insertion of the pawn trade makes a huge difference in one key line: @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p1nb1pp/1qn1pp2/p2pP3/3P1P1P/PP1B1N2/6P1/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Bxh7??  Kxh7  14.Ng5+  fxg5  15.Qh5+  Kg8  16.hxg5  looks great at first, but Black has the shocking  16...Bxg5!!  17.fxg5  Qxd4  ,  when you see why having traded on d4 makes a huge difference!The good news is: after our simple move 13. Ne2, we are much better. I want to check one typical idea now that you need to be aware of. }
13... fxe5
{ Theis capture only helps us from a strategic point of view, but we need to check an attacking idea that Black can try. Objectively best for Black is still a passive play like  13...f5  14.h5  , or @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p1nb1pp/1qn1pp2/p2pP3/3P1P1P/PP1B1N2/4N1P1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rf7  14.h5  Nf8  , when  15.O-O!  is a cool move. The idea is to play Kh1/Kh2, followed by g4 next. After playing h4-h5, it's easy to forget that you can still castle. It is strong here because our king has a good spot on h1. }
14. fxe5 Ndxe5
{ We need to check this attacking idea. Black did not want to sit and wait but tried to open up the centre by force. It doesn't work in this particular case - let's have a look. }
15. dxe5
{ Both captures work here. After  15.Nxe5  Nxe5  16.dxe5  Qf2+  17.Kd2  Black's attack is going nowhere. An important idea in this line is the move Qg1, trying to trade queens or force it to retreat.   I think that  15.dxe5  is a bit simpler to handle. Now Black gets no real attack. After  15...Rxf3  16.gxf3  Nxe5  17.Nf4  or @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p2b1pp/1qn1p3/p2pP3/7P/PP1B1N2/4N1P1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bc5  16.Rf1  ,  we have no problems coordinating and converting the extra material. In this particular case, Black's sacrifices fail. We still need to be alert about this idea, as it is one of the few aggressive options available for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C3) French Tarrasch – 3...c5"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Black has two main responses to the Tarrasch: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  , examined in the previous chapter, and  3...c5  , the topic we'll discuss now. The character of those two main lines is distinctly different. After  3...Nf6  4.e5  , we reach a closed centre named 'French pawn structure'.   The idea of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  is different. Black gets the c-pawn into play and attacks our d-pawn. It's a very logical choice, as it highlights a drawback of the Tarrasch: our d-pawn is unprotected. This way, they create an early conflict in the middle of the board that will lead to an open or semi-open position.A common pawn structure after  3...c5  is the Isolated Queen Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@ that Black frequently accepts. A sample line is  4.Ngf3  Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  ,  which leads to the IQP quickly.I think Black's best chance of equalising against the Tarrasch is 3...c5 but then avoid the IQP structures. They are not objectively bad, but I'd always prefer White as our play is simpler to understand, in my mind. I'll discuss the IQP positions later once they are on the board.Our chapter's main line is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  , which looks like Black's best line in a theoretical sense. However, I want to add that this line is only played in about 15-20 % of the games. It's very relevant to study the other lines, as they frequently occur, in particular below master level. }
1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ After 3...c5, White has an important choice to make. Two good moves CAN lead to the same positions, but there are important differences. Let's compare and understand the nuances.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  leads to an immediate split between two answers:  A1. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/3P4/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  leads to the IQP lines after  5.Ngf3  Nc6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  - all three options are welcome and lead to this pawn structure. I am happy to play against the IQP, a common strategy in our repertoire.  A2. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/3P4/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5!  is a much more serious challenge. Black avoids the IQP in this line and currently has excellent chances to equalise the game. I checked it in detail and felt it was best avoided, if possible. That gets us to option B.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  is my choice when we have a split, too.  B1. Black can play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  when we trade on d5 and reach the lines mentioned under A1 above. In these cases, capturing on d5 with the queen is worse. We more or less force the transposition to the IQP structures, as Black can't sensibly deviate.  B2. The main alternative and likely best is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  , when Black hopes for  5.exd5  Qxd5  , which would transpose to A2 above. But we played the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  for a reason. After  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  we reach the main lines of this chapter.  To summarise: we play the slightly more sophisticated move order B to avoid the ...Qxd5 lines. White chooses to fight Black in this line or opt for  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  cxd4  5.Nxd4  , as I suggest. My reasons are twofold: I think we can pose more problems, and it is simpler to play. }
