[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C3) French Tarrasch – 3...c5"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...c5 4.Ngf3 dxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types.   A.  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  is this chapter's main line, as it looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.   B.  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line.   C.  4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.   D.  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure. It is rare, but worth a quick look as our reply is different to B and C, as we don't have the b5-square available.   E.  4...dxe4?  is a mistake that is nevertheless played quite regularly in online chess. It's instructive to study why this move is wrong. }
4... dxe4
{ I was surprised to find a fair amount of online games that featured this mistaken capture. I want to cover it briefly, as the refutation is instructive. }
5. Nxe4
{ Now we see Black's problem. c5 is attacked, and they are already lacking in development considerably. }
5... cxd4 { How do we capture the d-pawn now? } 6. Qxd4
{ Taking with the knight is not bad, but this recapture is more powerful. Black has no good alternative to the queen trade now. }
6... Qxd4 7. Nxd4
{ We aimed for this position when we allowed the queen trade. Now Black has to deal with the threat of Nb5, which only leaves one move. }
7... a6 { They can't allow Nb5, which would create threats of Nc7+ and Nbd6+. }
8. Bf4
{ White has some good alternatives here, but I like this move a lot. It shows how a dynamic advantage, the lead in development, can be transformed into a static one: Black cannot stop Nd6+ when we gain the bishop pair and have a dominating dark-squared bishop. I'll continue this line to see this scenario unfold on the board. }
8... Nf6 9. Nd6+ Bxd6 10. Bxd6
{ Black is in terrible shape here. They have to fight our monster bishop pair and can't castle kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C3) French Tarrasch – 3...c5"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...c5 4.Ngf3 Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types.   A.  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  is this chapter's main line, as it looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.   B.  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line.   C.  4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.   D.  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure. It is rare, but worth a quick look as our reply is different to B and C, as we don't have the b5-square available.   E.  4...dxe4?  is a mistake that is nevertheless played quite regularly in online chess. It's instructive to study why this move is wrong. }
4... Nc6
{ Black puts more pressure on d4 and, more or less, accepts to enter an IQP structure after our reply. }
5. exd5
{ Now Black's best move is  5...exd5  when we reach the common line that features the IQP structure. We'll also have a look at  5...Qxd5  and check why it is dubious. }
5... Qxd5
{ Black captures with the queen, similar to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Qxd5  , which has a good reputation. Maybe they were planning to play this system, but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ngf3  posed a move order challenge. If Black still wants to enter ...Qxd5 territory, they should play  4.Ngf3  cxd4  , as then  5.exd5  Qxd5  transposes to the desired lines directly. We play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3p4/3pP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxd4  to avoid that, of course.Back to the worse version of ...Qxd5 - why is it bad? }
6. Bc4 { Simple and strong. We gain a tempo on the queen. } 6... Qd8
{ It's relatively best for Black to return home. After the more active-looking  6...Qh5?!  we have  7.Be2  , when the queen feels unsafe again. }
7. dxc5
{ I give this move an exclam, as it is the key difference to the 'good ...Qxd5 lines'. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.Ngf3  cxd4  6.Bc4  Qd6  @@StartBracket@@or other queen moves@@EndBracket@@ Black already took the pawn on d4. This is much better than allowing the capture on c5, as we'll win more tempi on the bishop after it has recaptured. }
7... Bxc5 8. Qe2
{ Castling kingside is not a bad move, but I like to preserve the queenside castling option. The idea of Qe2 is playing Ne4 to gain time on the bishop. }
8... Nf6 9. Ne4
{ We hit Black's bishop and opened our bishop for development. } 9... Be7
{ After  9...Nxe4  10.Qxe4  O-O  11.Bd2  , we can play for queenside castling, a promising prospect. We are far ahead in development, and Black needs to defend carefully. }
10. Bd2
{ You may also castle kingside here, which is the more conservative option. With  10.Bd2  , we want to castle queenside and be more aggressive. A sample line would be  10...O-O  11.O-O-O  Qc7  12.Kb1  Rd8  13.h4  ,  when our initiative on the kingside can mount quickly. }
