[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C3) French Tarrasch – 3...c5"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...c5 4.Ngf3 Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types.   A.  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  is this chapter's main line, as it looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.   B.  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line.   C.  4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.   D.  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure. It is rare, but worth a quick look as our reply is different to B and C, as we don't have the b5-square available.   E.  4...dxe4?  is a mistake that is nevertheless played quite regularly in online chess. It's instructive to study why this move is wrong. }
4... Nc6
{ Black puts more pressure on d4 and, more or less, accepts to enter an IQP structure after our reply. }
5. exd5
{ Now Black's best move is  5...exd5  when we reach the common line that features the IQP structure. We'll also have a look at  5...Qxd5  and check why it is dubious. }
5... exd5
{ Black captures with the pawn, signalling the intention to play with the Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. We don't have an IQP on the board yet, but a trade of our d-pawn for Black's pawn is more or less unavoidable. These IQP structures have the reputation of being solid for Black but slightly passive and tough to win. White can create a nagging pull and pressure Black without running any undue risks.Our general strategic outline is quite simple:  Create the IQP,Keep it blockaded/place a piece on d4,Trade minor pieces and pressurise the pawn,Endgames are generally favourable for us. }
6. Bb5
{ 'Pin and win' - Well, we are not winning, but I am still happy with this move. Bb5 not only creates a pin but prepares to castle next. Black must be careful about a rook coming to e1 while their king is still in the centre. We'll consider three options now:   A.  6...Bd6  is the traditional main line for Black. They usually want to combine ...Bd6 and ...Nge7, which shields against the early attack on the e-file.   B.  6...Nf6?  is a bad idea, as we quickly expose Black's problems on the e-file. Black would like to develop their knight to f6 but does not manage to do it in this simple way.   C.  6...Qe7+  is a clever move and probably Black's best bet nowadays. After White's best reply  7.Be2  ,  Black plays the queen to c7 and later manages to develop the knight to f6. While this line might be Black's best option, White still retains a small advantage.   Black sometimes plays  6...cxd4  ,  but we don't need a more detailed study. We'll easily get the pawn back with Nb3xd4 and reach a position similar to line A above. }
6... Qe7+
{ This move makes an odd impression at first, but it makes some sense once you have a closer look. Black correctly argues that  7.Qe2?!  is harmless due to  7...a6  ,  when Black is in good shape. The queens will come off, and White has to take on c6 now.   We wouldn't mind  6...a6?  , as  7.Bxc6+  bxc6  8.O-O  gives us a great attack due to the development advantage. With the queen moves inserted, Black can trade queens and is safe. Long story short, we must retreat the bishop to e2. }
7. Be2
{ As explained, we need to play this move. Moving the bishop again is no big deal, as Black's queen move to e7 is not ideal, either. To develop the kingside, they must move the queen a second time. }
7... Qc7 { Black needs to move the queen again to get developed. } 8. O-O
{ I think this gives Black more opportunities to go wrong, compared to  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Nb3  , which is of about equal value, objectively. Note that White is not winning a pawn after  9...Be7  10.Qxd5??  due to  10...Nb4  , when Black wins! }
8... Nf6
{ Black manages to develop both knights to their most active squares without being punished - this is the main achievement of the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qe7+  variation, at the cost of time. Black's queen needed to move twice to allow the best setup. The immediate  6...Nf6?  does not work well, as we'll see in the next trainable. It's a fundamental problem of Black's variation. Black would be in perfect shape if they could develop that easily. }
9. Re1
{ Now we are threatening discovered checks... well... not really, to be honest. There is not a single scary bishop move in sight, but it still can be unpleasant for Black. }
9... Be6
{ This is the move I hope to provoke by playing Re1. Black blocks the e-file, 'just in case' a check could be dangerous. I don't think 9...Be6 is a big mistake, but it gives White some promising options.   Instead,  9...cxd4  is the main alternative when  10.Nb3  Be7  11.Nbxd4  is the natural continuation. White is slightly better in this standard position. Black has decently active pieces, but we have a clear target and the easier game. }
10. Bb5
{ I also looked at  10.Bd3  ,  intending Bf5 - not bad, either. I went for  10.Bb5  , because the most likely outcome is a position with a one-sided advantage for White. }
10... Bd6
{ Black needs to get castled kingside. They can't stay on the e-file forever. }
11. Nb3
{ A strong move, recently played by GM David Howell at the Chess Olympiad. }
11... c4
{ After  11...cxd4  12.Nbxd4  Black is pinned multiple times. They have to give up some material, but  12...O-O  13.Nxe6  fxe6  14.Rxe6  does not give Black enough compensation. }
12. Nc5 Bxc5
{ That's the idea. We have too much pressure on e6, so Black needs to take our knight. Note that after  12...O-O?!  we would play  13.Rxe6!  fxe6  14.Nxe6  to win the pawn. }
13. dxc5
{ The Nb3-c5 operation has led to a change in the pawn structure. We have gained control of the d4-square, which gives us a nice plus.   The mentioned game Howell-Juksta continued  13...O-O  14.Bxc6  Qxc6  15.Nd4  Qxc5  16.Rxe6  fxe6  17.Nxe6  Qb6  18.Nxf8  Rxf8  19.Be3  Qxb2  20.Bxa7  Qb5  21.Bd4  ,  when White's bishop had a commanding position on d4, giving Howell the advantage. Note that this scenario is almost arising by force after 12. Nc5, as the deviations look worse for Black. }
*

