11... Nf5 { Directed against Be3 and a more interesting choice for Black. } 12.
Bd3
{ Against Nf5 setups, the battery with Bc2/Qd3 is usually a good idea. Once this battery is on the board, threats on the kingside appear. It's good to note that we use the same concept in the 9...Bd6 line. }
12... h6
{ A slow move, but Black wants to develop the bishop to e6 without being hit by Ng5. }
13. Bc2 Be6 14. Qd3
{ Here we go: battery in place! Now Black has to be careful, as g2-g4 is a threat. }
14... Qf6
{ That looks best, as now  15.g4?  Qg6!  defends. We have a much better move, though.   Before we check this, a word about  14...Re8  , which also defends against our threat.  15.g4?  Nh4  works for Black, as the king has gained the f8-square. After a different move, like  @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/pp3pp1/1bn1b2p/3p1n2/8/1NPQ1N2/PPB2PPP/R1B1R1K1 w - - 4 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Bf4  ,  15.Bd2  or  15.a4  ,  for example, we are still better. The threat g4 is still on the cards for later, while our structure remains better - Black has the IQP, after all. }
15. Be3
{ An important point. The Nf5 is pinned, so Be3 is possible now. Note that  15.g4  is answered by  15...Qg6!  and White gets nothing out of this weakening pawn push.   Now, after the much better  15.Be3  , we have a pleasant advantage. Black has to go into  15...Bxe3  16.Rxe3  ,  when we have good chances to exploit the IQP in the long run. }
