{ Black can still go wrong with  8...Nf6?  , when  9.Re1+  transposes to the line  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Re1+  , with a large advantage for White. }
9. Nb3
{ After this natural move, Black needs to decide between retreating to d6 or b6. We need to check these options separately, as the most promising plans against them are quite different. }
9... Bd6
{ From d6, the bishop is not looking at the blockade square d4, but is instead pointed towards our kingside. Our strategy is slightly different than after ...Bb6, as this bishop retreat invited the Be3-plan. We need a different approach here, but we'll see that many ideas are shared amongst the two lines. }
10. c3
{ Taking more control of d4 makes a lot of sense. It's also an efficient choice, as it will become clearer on the next move. }
10... O-O
{ We have reached a position that we might also play in the Sicilian. It is the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  exd5  5.d4  Nc6  6.Bb5  Bd6  7.O-O  Nge7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Nbd2  O-O  10.Nb3  Bd6  , when we reach the position currently on the board. }
11. Bd3
{ This retreat is, in fact, the most active move. It prevents ...Bg4 due to Bxh7+ and prepares the battery with Bc2+Qd3 to provoke weaknesses. This concept is also used in the 9...Bb6 line. }
11... h6
{ After  11...Bg4??  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Ng5+  and Qxg4, White wins an important pawn and hopefully the game later on.  The move 11...h6 prevents this tactic and prepares the bishop for development. }
12. h3 { No pin, please, an important move. } 12... Nf5
{ A good move that prevents our bishop development to e3.   I also found many games with  12...Bf5  , when  13.Re1  Qd7  14.Bxf5  Nxf5  15.Qd3  Rae8  16.Rxe8  Rxe8  17.Bd2  is a sample line to demonstrate how this could develop further. We plan Rd1 next and maybe Bc1 to put more pressure on d5. Black's d5-pawn will remain a target. }
13. Bc2 { Going for the battery idea. } 13... Re8 14. Qd3
{ Quite inconvenient for Black to meet. Black has to decide how to defend against the g4 idea. It is important to realise that g4 is not a deadly threat, as there is no checkmate on h7. }
14... Qf6
{ Black could also try  14...g6  , making sure the queen is not invading at all. After  15.Bd2  Be6  16.Nbd4  we manage to trade some minor pieces, which is a substantial accomplishment when fighting the IQP. Without any minor pieces, our heavy pieces can exert more pressure on the weak pawn. }
15. Bd2
{ Grabbing the pawn on d5 does not lose immediately but gives Black substantial compensation. We should rather focus on development.   Note that  15.g4?  Nh4  leads to nothing, as we only have a harmless check on h7. Here, the battery is a constant worry for Black, but we need to be cautious about executing the 'threat', especially if we have to weaken our position like 15.g4? does here. Instead, we should focus on small improvements, like playing a rook on the e-file and potentially double rooks there. }
