[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types.   A.  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  is this chapter's main line, as it looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.   B.  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line.   C.  4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.   D.  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure. It is rare, but worth a quick look as our reply is different to B and C, as we don't have the b5-square available.   E.  4...dxe4?  is a mistake that is nevertheless played quite regularly in online chess. It's instructive to study why this move is wrong. }
4... Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn and forces a decision. White can advance the e-pawn or capture d5, which is our choice. Playing  5.e5  is not a mistake, but it leads to a version of the 3.Nd2 Nf6 lines that we don't play. We aim for a quick f4-setup in this formation, while here, we have already committed our knight to f3. Instead, taking on d5 fits much better to our repertoire concept. }
5. exd5
{ Now we have to consider the three captures on d5. Looking a bit closer, it turns out that only 5...exd5 has some independent value.   A.  5...exd5  6.Bb5+  leads to a typical IQP structure.   B.  5...Nxd5  is a good move, but after  6.Nb3  cxd4  7.Nbxd4  leads to a surprising transposition to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nf6  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.N2f3  , which we examine via this move order.   C.  5...Qxd5?!  6.Bc4  Qd8  7.dxc5  is questionable and handled just as the line  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.exd5  Qxd5?!  ,  which we examine a bit more closely. It might easily lead to the same positions, as playing the knights to f6 and c6 looks natural for Black. Therefore, we can focus on the pawn recapture now. }
5... exd5
{ Black accepts the IQP structure, similar to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  ,  which we studied before. I discussed the anti-IQP strategy in the notes to this more popular option, and there is nothing to add to these points. You can follow the same guidelines here, as well. }
6. Bb5+
{ The fastest way to get castled. Now Black only has one good reply, the move 6...Bd7, offering the bishop trade. }
6... Bd7
{ The only good reply. The move  6...Nc6  looks normal but leads to problems for Black. We examine this move via the move order 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Nf6, which is also commonly seen. }
7. Bxd7+
{ Our general strategic guideline says: 'trade minor pieces' - OK, done! } 7...
Nbxd7
{ The alternative  7...Qxd7  is rarely seen, but it doesn't seem to be a clear mistake. Our job against it is easy, though. A normal continuation like  8.O-O  cxd4  9.Nxd4  gives us a slight advantage, typical for the whole IQP complex. }
8. O-O
{ We castle and are ready for Re1+ now. Black needs to get the e-file closed and castled quickly. }
8... Be7
{ By far the best move. Black can capture on c5 with the knight while the bishop secures the e-file against checks. }
9. dxc5 { We create the IQP, our target for the foreseeable future. } 9... Nxc5
10. Nb3
{ I suggest this move, but White keeps a small advantage with several setups. Playing  10.Nd4  ,  intending N2f3, or  10.Re1  ,  with Nf1 and Be3 next, also looks comfortable for White. }
10... Nce4
{ Black wants to avoid further trades. Now emphasising control over d4 with Be3 and c3 looks very harmonious. }
11. Be3 { Starting with  11.c3  is fine, too. } 11... O-O 12. c3
{ I am happy with White's prospects here. Black is not in immediate danger, but we have a simple plan to trade minor pieces and simplify to a good endgame. Black has to stay active enough, which is not a trivial task. }
