[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...c5 4.Ngf3 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types.   A.  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  is this chapter's main line, as it looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.   B.  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line.   C.  4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.   D.  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure. It is rare, but worth a quick look as our reply is different to B and C, as we don't have the b5-square available.   E.  4...dxe4?  is a mistake that is nevertheless played quite regularly in online chess. It's instructive to study why this move is wrong. }
4... a6
{ A rarely played move, but it has an interesting idea. Black is willing to play the IQP structure but wants to prevent our bishop from going to b5 @@StartBracket@@compare to  4...Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  6.Bb5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  6.Bb5+  @@EndBracket@@. }
5. exd5 exd5
{ We can't use the b5-square now to develop actively, but we have a different option that is simple to play and comfortable for us. }
6. dxc5 { Starting a concrete sequence of moves. } 6... Bxc5
{ Black has to take when we gain a tempo on the bishop. } 7. Nb3
{ We attack Black's bishop. } 7... Ba7
{ The move ...a6 was also played to create the comfortable retreating square a7 for the bishop, Still,  7...Bb6  is also seen frequently here, but our continuation would be similarly strong. }
8. Qe2+
{ I like this straightforward idea. Black has only one good reply, after which we'll gain a nagging endgame edge. That said, the move  8.Bd3  is just as good. It remains a favourable anti-IQP position in any case. }
8... Qe7
{ That's the best move. After  8...Ne7  9.Be3  ,  we are much better. The bishop trade is favourable for White, and we are ready for O-O-O, which generates quick pressure on d5.   The move  8...Be6  is even worse, as the simple  9.Nbd4  is immediately annoying for Black. }
9. Bg5
{ The important point of our check. Now Black either has to trade immediately or weaken their structure, which is highly undesirable. }
9... Qxe2+
{ Clearly best, as  9...f6  10.Bf4  Nc6  11.Bd6  Qxe2+  12.Bxe2  only leads to a worse version of the same endgame type. In general, playing ...f6 creates too many weaknesses for Black, with little benefit. }
10. Bxe2
{ A very nice opening result for us. We have created the IQP as a clear target and traded queens. Our bishop on g5 is not attacking anything, but Black has to think twice about developing the g8-knight now. If they attack our bishop with ...h6, the manoeuvre Bg5-d2-c3 is a good idea. }
