[White "C3) French Tarrasch – 3...c5"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3...c5 4.Ngf3 cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types.   A.  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  is this chapter's main line, as it looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.   B.  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line.   C.  4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.   D.  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure. It is rare, but worth a quick look as our reply is different to B and C, as we don't have the b5-square available.   E.  4...dxe4?  is a mistake that is nevertheless played quite regularly in online chess. It's instructive to study why this move is wrong. }
4... cxd4
{ Black captures on d4, which signals their intention to play  5.exd5  Qxd5  , transposing to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.Ngf3  cxd4  ,  which has a good reputation nowadays. We specifically played 4.Ngf3 to avoid this line, though. The way to do it is recapturing on d4. }
5. Nxd4
{ Black is quite far behind in development and needs to catch up. Therefore, they now usually play either  5...Nf6  or  5...Nc6  , which is the more popular and combative move. }
5... Nf6
{ Black develops and puts pressure on e4. We have the usual question to answer: advance or capture? In this chapter, we always take on d5. }
6. exd5
{ Black now has the choice between the two piece recaptures, as  6...exd5?!  leads to a bad version of the IQP after  7.Bb5+  Bd7  8.Qe2+  Be7  9.Nf5  ,  which is a nice idea. The pawn recapture is more or less never played, though - the whole sequence of 4...cxd4 5.Nxd4 Nf6 is usually played by someone who aims for one of the piece recaptures on d5. If they wanted an IQP, there are better and more obvious ways to get there.   We have to consider  6...Nxd5  and  6...Qxd5  now. The knight move is far more popular, but we need to look at the queen capture briefly because it is distinctively different and knowing the best response helps a lot. }
6... Qxd5
{ Taking with the queen looks a bit worse than the knight capture but needs to be checked, as the best response and the following lines are not obvious. }
7. Nb5
{ The simple part of it: We move our attacked knight and threaten the royal fork. }
7... Na6
{ Black's main reply by far. They don't want to move the queen again and develop the knight to cover c7. It's not the perfect place for the knight, though.   Before we continue a word about the alternative  7...Qd8  8.Nc4  , when  8...Nd5  9.Ne3  a6  10.Nxd5  exd5  11.Nd4  leads to a comfortable anti-IQP structure. Trading queens on move eight is bad for Black, as our knights have too many threats on c7 and d6. }
8. Nc3
{ I mentioned earlier that there was a non-obvious follow-up. This is the move I was referring to. It took me a while to appreciate the logic; here is why it makes sense to retreat the knight. Black's queen on d5 made it difficult for us to develop easily. We can't move the f1-bishop, as g2 is under attack.The move 8.Nc3 is a concrete solution to this issue. We push the queen away from the central post and have a particular continuation in mind -hang on. }
8... Qd8
{ Black usually retreats all the way to avoid further tempo losses due to attacks on the queen. After  8...Qd6  , we'd play similarly as after  8...Qd8  - the plan of a3/moving the queen and then playing Nc4 or Ne4, here with a tempo on the queen, works well. }
9. a3
{ A very powerful move! It accomplishes multiple goals.   ⦿  9.Qf3  Nb4?  immediately is bad for White. With a3 we prepare the move Qf3, without being annoyed by ...Nb4 jumps.⦿ It makes sense to get the queen to f3, as it puts pressure on Black's queenside and prepares to move the d2-knight.⦿ We also prepare the move b2-b4! which prepares to fianchetto our bishop and removes the square c5 from Black's pieces, particularly the offside knight. }
9... Be7
{ Black wants to get castled, very understandable and by far Black's main choice. }
10. Qf3
{ Realising the idea of a3. We develop our queen and pose a direct threat now that can easily be overlooked in a fast time control game. Fabiano Caruana played  10...O-O??  11.Bxa6  and resigned against Magnus Carlsen in 2014 OTB Blitz game! }
10... Nc7
{ Black avoids disaster and secures the knight. After  10...Nc5  , the move  11.b4  looks attractive. Now, after the knight retreat, we have some good options. }
11. Bd3
{ This looks best to me, developing the bishop to its move active square. I also looked at  11.b4  ,  but it is unclear that we need a bishop on b2. }
11... Ncd5
{ That's played most of the time. Black can also castle first, but it likely leads to the same type of position, like  11...O-O  12.O-O  Ncd5  13.Nde4  shows. }
12. Nde4
{ White has a comfortable advantage in this position. Here are some lines to illustrate.   A.  12...Nxe4  13.Nxe4  is welcome, as we are ready for a later c4 and b4 queenside expansion.   B.  12...Nxc3  13.Nxc3  is a bit different but also promising for White. We can swiftly develop with O-O and Bf4 and aim for play on the kingside. Ideas like Qh3 and Be5 come to mind. In both lines, Black is somewhat passively placed and has no clear counterplay. }
