1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types.   A.  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  is this chapter's main line, as it looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.   B.  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line.   C.  4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.   D.  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure. It is rare, but worth a quick look as our reply is different to B and C, as we don't have the b5-square available.   E.  4...dxe4?  is a mistake that is nevertheless played quite regularly in online chess. It's instructive to study why this move is wrong. }
4... cxd4
{ Black captures on d4, which signals their intention to play  5.exd5  Qxd5  , transposing to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.Ngf3  cxd4  ,  which has a good reputation nowadays. We specifically played 4.Ngf3 to avoid this line, though. The way to do it is recapturing on d4. }
5. Nxd4
{ Black is quite far behind in development and needs to catch up. Therefore, they now usually play either  5...Nf6  or  5...Nc6  , which is the more popular and combative move. }
5... Nf6
{ Black develops and puts pressure on e4. We have the usual question to answer: advance or capture? In this chapter, we always take on d5. }
6. exd5
{ Black now has the choice between the two piece recaptures, as  6...exd5?!  leads to a bad version of the IQP after  7.Bb5+  Bd7  8.Qe2+  Be7  9.Nf5  ,  which is a nice idea. The pawn recapture is more or less never played, though - the whole sequence of 4...cxd4 5.Nxd4 Nf6 is usually played by someone who aims for one of the piece recaptures on d5. If they wanted an IQP, there are better and more obvious ways to get there.   We have to consider  6...Nxd5  and  6...Qxd5  now. The knight move is far more popular, but we need to look at the queen capture briefly because it is distinctively different and knowing the best response helps a lot. }
6... Nxd5
{ This looks like Black's best option here. As we have seen, taking with the queen likely leads to later time losses. }
7. N2f3
{ A good way to coordinate our knights. This position may also occur via a different move order: after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  c5  4.Ngf3  Nf6  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Nb3  cxd4  7.Nbxd4  , we get the same situation. }
7... Bb4+
{ Black's most popular move by a wide margin. It makes a lot of sense for two reasons: firstly, Black hopes for  8.c3??  Nxc3!  ,  a trap that we will avoid!   Secondly, after the forced reply  8.Bd2  ,  Black hopes to make their defence easier by trading a piece. They have less space, so trades are welcome.   Black has other moves, like  7...Be7  or  7...a6  ,  but they don't require a detailed study. I suggest developing with Bd3 and O-O when we have a small advantage. Our pieces are more active, and Black has yet to solve the issue of the c8-bishop. In the long run, advancing the majority on the queenside is always an idea. }
8. Bd2
{ As mentioned: DON'T play  8.c3??  and allow  8...Nxc3!  , which has happened in countless Blitz games. Even GMs fell into it, so be aware. }
8... O-O
{ Better than  8...Bxd2+  9.Qxd2  , which helps us. After  9...O-O  we even have the attractive  10.O-O-O  , speeding up our development. After the more precise @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/4p3/3n4/1b1N4/5N2/PPPB1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...O-O  , we can only get a small advantage with the following sequence. }
9. Bxb4 Nxb4 10. c3 N4c6
{ This looks better than  10...Nd5  11.Bc4  ,  as Black can't easily develop the b8-knight without allowing structural damage. }
11. Nxc6
{ The difference between this move and  11.Bd3  or  11.Bc4  is not substantial. I suggest the capture, as it gives a bit more flexibility - hang on. }
11... Nxc6 12. Bd3
{ I decided to stop the trainable here, as Black has plenty of moves that make no substantial difference to the strategy. We have two basic options:  Castle kingside and play a strategic game with moves like Qe2, Be4, Rfd1, etc. We have slightly more active pieces and can advance the queenside majority.  Castle queenside, which is obviously more controversial. We can play for an attack against Black's king, but they'll also get counterplay against our monarch.The choice is purely a matter of taste. It depends on your preferences and the game's circumstances. }
