[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3
{ After  4.Ngf3  , we reach an important crossroads. Black now has a list of moves that may lead to quite different position types.   A.  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  is this chapter's main line, as it looks like Black's best option. It is becoming more popular on the master level but is not as frequently seen below.   B.  4...Nc6  is met by  5.exd5  when  5...exd5  is best and leads to an IQP structure. I'll discuss our strategy against the IQP in the notes to this line.   C.  4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5  also gets us to the IQP scenario, with a similar strategy as in B. Black can deviate with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pP4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd5  , when we will transpose to a line we examine via A.   D.  4...a6  5.exd5  exd5  is a third way to an IQP structure. It is rare, but worth a quick look as our reply is different to B and C, as we don't have the b5-square available.   E.  4...dxe4?  is a mistake that is nevertheless played quite regularly in online chess. It's instructive to study why this move is wrong. }
4... cxd4
{ Black captures on d4, which signals their intention to play  5.exd5  Qxd5  , transposing to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.Ngf3  cxd4  ,  which has a good reputation nowadays. We specifically played 4.Ngf3 to avoid this line, though. The way to do it is recapturing on d4. }
5. Nxd4
{ Black is quite far behind in development and needs to catch up. Therefore, they now usually play either  5...Nf6  or  5...Nc6  , which is the more popular and combative move. }
5... Nc6
{ Black attacks our knight and hopes for the capture on c6, which strengthens Black's centre. The knight jump to c6 is Black's main move by far and leads to interesting play. First, we must see that we can't avoid capturing on c6. It is, however, imperative to remember the next move and the attached idea. }
6. Bb5
{ It's much more challenging for Black first to pin the knight, and only after  6...Bd7  capture on c6. Let's compare:   A.  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3   B.  6.Bb5  Bd7  7.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3    We prefer the version in B as the extra move ...Bd7 is not helpful for Black, quite the opposite. The bishop is better placed on c8, as it leaves d7 free for the knight @@StartBracket@@think of a later e4-e5 attack on the f6-knight@@EndBracket@@ and may get to b7 later.So don't forget to play 6. Bb5, an important subtlety. }
6... Bd7 7. Nxc6
{ After provoking ...Bd7, we are better positioned to capture. Now Black captures with the pawn most of the time, as  7...Bxc6  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.c4  leads to a rather unattractive position. We'll briefly examine this option and then focus on the more interesting and popular main line. }
7... bxc6 { Better and more combative than taking with the bishop. } 8. Bd3
{ Mission accomplished! Our bishop returns after fulfilling their job to lure Black's bishop to d7. We need to consider two moves now. Black can't play  8...Nf6?  now, as  9.e5  sends the knight home immediately. This is why the d7-bishop is misplaced.What are Black's best options? It makes sense to take control of e5, trying to develop the knight soon.   A.  8...Bd6  is Black's most popular move. They develop the bishop to a good square first and then decide how to continue with the problematic knight on g8.   B.  8...Qc7  is Black's main alternative to A. The queen move also connects to the e5-square and fights against a possible e4-e5 by White. The queen move is usually connected with the idea ...Ne7-g6, which aims to strengthen control of e5 and f4.I will examine both moves in more detail and depth, as they are featured in Chessable courses as recommendations for Black. Line A is Anish Giri's suggestion, and Kamil Plichta recommended line B. Both authors did a good job, so we can't expect a significant advantage for White - given that Black knows 20 moves of perfect theory, which is not to be expected. We still want to be thorough, so let's get to work. }
8... Qc7
{ Black connects the queen to the e5-square and delays the decision about the kingside development. Kamil Plichta suggested this option in his LTR on the French Defence, so I want to take a closer look. }
9. Qe2
{ We play the same move against 8...Bd6, and follow the same idea. We want to get the pawn advance e4-e5 back on the map. }
9... Ne7
{ A key idea of Black's last move. Black wants to place the knight on g6, looking at the key squares e5 and f4.   A different idea is  9...Bd6  ,  but it leads to a position that we examine via the move order  @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/p2b1ppp/2p1p3/3p4/4P3/3B4/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bd6  9.Qe2  Qc7  ,  which is a more common path. }
10. Nf3
{ Given Black's ...Ng6 idea, we need to get some control of f4 and free our c1-bishop. It's also fine to start with  10.O-O  ,  and after 10...Ng6 11.Nf3 get to the same position. }
10... Ng6 11. O-O
{ All logical so far. Now we have reached an important moment. Black wants to complete kingside development, but where to place the bishop? }
11... Be7
{ We will focus on this move. It is Kamil's recommendation and likely the one you'll encounter if you play a theory buff.   What about  11...Bd6  , then? Not a bad move, but I think that  12.Re1  is a good and logical reply. We want to advance e4-e5 with a tempo, highlighting the drawback of the move. White keeps a small advantage after  12.Re1  Nf4  13.Bxf4  Bxf4  14.e5  ,  when the plan g3, h4 and ultimately Ng5 is good to know. Black is not obliged to play 12...Nf4, but allowing e4-e5 and moving the bishop again is not attractive, either. The move 11...Be7 avoids this tempo loss in case of the pawn advance. Now, we reach an important moment, as I recommended NOT to advance the e-pawn but to go for a different strategy. }
12. c4
{ This is the only critical test of Black's system, in my mind. After  12.e5  c5  Black can be happy with the opening result. They can even be ambitious by playing  13.c4  f6  ,  immediately attacking our advanced pawn. Compared to other e4-e5 structures @@StartBracket@@compare to 8...Bd6@@EndBracket@@, Black is better off. It is better to change gears and attack Black's d-pawn. We now enter a long and straightforward sequence. }
12... dxe4
{ Black has to play this capture. Taking on c4 leads to a thankless task, as the c-pawn is weak for no compensation. By taking on e4, Black creates interesting counterplay in the centre, using the f- and e-pawns. }
13. Bxe4 f5 { That's Black's idea: setting the central pawns in motion. } 14.
Bc2 e5 15. Ng5
{ We have to play aggressively against Black's ambitious plan. It is my rule to avoid trainables extending beyond move 15, but I need to go a bit deeper here. If you are that far, you know Black is booked up @@StartBracket@@or 'coursed up'@@EndBracket@@ to the teeth and knows their stuff. }
15... e4 { The only move, as  15...O-O?  16.Nxh7!  demonstrates. } 16. Qh5
{ We get our queen into action and force the capture. } 16... Bxg5 17. Qxg5
{ An important point. It looks more natural to take with the bishop, but the bishop is not well-placed on g5. Black's e- and f-pawn can be the base for an attack on our king - we need a concept to address this idea. The one I am suggesting only works with the queen capture. }
17... O-O
{ We have arrived at an important crossroads. The position on the board arises almost by force after 11...Be7, which makes it theoretically important. It gives White some choice, and we have some interesting alternatives.One of them is Wesley So's suggestion in his LTR 1.e4 course, which is  18.Bd2  Rae8  19.Bc3  f4  20.Rfe1  Rf5  21.Qg4  , when he gives a fair assessment. He states that he'd prefer White due to the bishop pair, but Black's chances are not to be underestimated.My practical concern is that Black managed to advance the f-pawn, which gives them attacking chances against our king. I was not too fond of this prospect and wanted to recommend an easier-to-handle solution. }
18. f4
{ I prefer this move for practical reasons. Now there are two main options for Black.   A.  18...exf3  19.Rxf3  looks nice for White. We managed to open the game for our bishops and broke Black's pawn formation in the centre.   B.  18...Qb6+  is Kamil's suggestion and better than the capture, in my mind. It continues  19.Kh1  c5  ,  when he concludes by mentioning the plan of ...Rf7, followed by ...Nf8-e6-d4. This sounds scary, but it does not materialise if we are precise. We need to connect to the d4-square as soon as possible, so:  20.Qg3  Rf7  21.Qc3  Nf8  22.Be3  Ne6  23.Rad1  ,  when Black does not manage to occupy d4. The resulting position is interesting to play for both sides, I think. I want to emphasise that it looks much safer than 18.Bd2, at least to my eye. We can always try to exploit the bishop pair in the long term. }
*

