{ Black is quite far behind in development and needs to catch up. Therefore, they now usually play either  5...Nf6  or  5...Nc6  , which is the more popular and combative move. }
5... Nc6
{ Black attacks our knight and hopes for the capture on c6, which strengthens Black's centre. The knight jump to c6 is Black's main move by far and leads to interesting play. First, we must see that we can't avoid capturing on c6. It is, however, imperative to remember the next move and the attached idea. }
6. Bb5
{ It's much more challenging for Black first to pin the knight, and only after  6...Bd7  capture on c6. Let's compare:   A.  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3   B.  6.Bb5  Bd7  7.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3    We prefer the version in B as the extra move ...Bd7 is not helpful for Black, quite the opposite. The bishop is better placed on c8, as it leaves d7 free for the knight @@StartBracket@@think of a later e4-e5 attack on the f6-knight@@EndBracket@@ and may get to b7 later.So don't forget to play 6. Bb5, an important subtlety. }
6... Bd7 7. Nxc6
{ After provoking ...Bd7, we are better positioned to capture. Now Black captures with the pawn most of the time, as  7...Bxc6  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.c4  leads to a rather unattractive position. We'll briefly examine this option and then focus on the more interesting and popular main line. }
7... bxc6 { Better and more combative than taking with the bishop. } 8. Bd3
{ Mission accomplished! Our bishop returns after fulfilling their job to lure Black's bishop to d7. We need to consider two moves now. Black can't play  8...Nf6?  now, as  9.e5  sends the knight home immediately. This is why the d7-bishop is misplaced.What are Black's best options? It makes sense to take control of e5, trying to develop the knight soon.   A.  8...Bd6  is Black's most popular move. They develop the bishop to a good square first and then decide how to continue with the problematic knight on g8.   B.  8...Qc7  is Black's main alternative to A. The queen move also connects to the e5-square and fights against a possible e4-e5 by White. The queen move is usually connected with the idea ...Ne7-g6, which aims to strengthen control of e5 and f4.I will examine both moves in more detail and depth, as they are featured in Chessable courses as recommendations for Black. Line A is Anish Giri's suggestion, and Kamil Plichta recommended line B. Both authors did a good job, so we can't expect a significant advantage for White - given that Black knows 20 moves of perfect theory, which is not to be expected. We still want to be thorough, so let's get to work. }
8... Bd6
{ The bishop move is the most popular move and was recommended by Anish Giri in his Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. }
9. Qe2
{ This looks like the most dangerous move. The main idea is preparing e4-e5, gaining space while hitting the bishop. Now we come to an important split.   A.  9...e5  is the latest trend and was recommended by Anish Giri in his LTR French. I will check this move as the main one, as it also requires the most effort to fight.   B.  9...Ne7  is the former main line that we'll check, too. Black allows the pawn to push to e5, which we are happy about.   C.  9...Qc7  stops e4-e5 and is worth checking, too. }
9... Ne7
{ Black's traditional main line allows our pawn to advance, an invitation that I suggest accepting. }
10. e5 Bc7
{ This makes a lot more sense than going to c5, as Black wants to activate their passive bishop by playing ...c6-c5 and ...Bc6 at some point. }
11. O-O
{ We need to castle, so let's go for this simple move. Now Black can opt for various move orders, but they usually end in the same formation. They castle, play the knight to g6 and go for the already mentioned ...c5 and ...Bc6 idea.Our setup is also pretty clear. We want some support for e5 in the form of playing our pawn to f4. The second pawn move we need is c4 in response to ...c5, as our bishop is short of squares. Finally, there is b3, which prepares Bb2 or Ba3 after Black has played ...c5. Let's examine this type of position with one possible move order. }
11... Ng6 12. f4 O-O 13. b3
{ Playing  13.c4  or  13.Nf3  is also fine, of course. } 13... c5
{ Black wants more scope for the d7-bishop. } 14. c4 Bc6 15. Bb2
{ This is a good moment to assess the position. Here are some points to consider.   - Black does not want to move the d-pawn, as it gives up the squares e4 or/and c4 for our pieces.   - At the same time, they need to consider that we might take on d5 when ...exd5 would allow f4-f5, sooner or later. This means they probably have to recapture on d5 with the bishop, which again leads to the same structural issue as in the previous point.   - We may play Rad1 soon, which makes Black's queen feel uncomfortable on the d-file. This would be a good reply to a move like 15...Qd7, when Black tries to wait for a moment.I think it's an interesting position to play for both sides. I'd rather be White, but it is certainly not a significant advantage for us. }
