9... Qc7
{ They stop our e-pawn and prevent castling, certainly a move worth considering. It is not played much on the master level, but frequently seen below that. I think we'll get a nice advantage in the following line. }
10. Nf3
{ A very logical choice. We reload on the e4-e5 idea, open our c1-bishop and prepare castling by covering h2. Black has a choice between some moves, but they all have drawbacks. }
10... dxe4
{ This is relatively best, but it's not a happy move. The alternatives look worse, though.   A.  10...e5?  is a direct blunder due to  11.exd5  cxd5  12.Nxe5!  Bxe5  13.f4  , when we are more or less winning on the spot.   B.  10...Ne7  11.e5  Bc5  12.O-O  or  12.h4  ,  when we have good attacking chances on the kingside. Black's setup with a bishop on c5 looks odd, making it rather difficult to activate the other one on d7. We can compare this to  @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/p2b1ppp/2pbp3/3p4/4P3/3B4/PPPNQPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ne7  ,  when c7 was available for the bishop, and ...c5 was easier to accomplish. }
11. Qxe4 Nf6 12. Qh4
{ We can already conclude that White has a small advantage due to our queen's better pawn structure and active post. Black needs to be careful with kingside castling here, of course. We can continue with O-O and Re1 next, as a general idea. An additional idea to note can be Nf3-d2-c4 at a later stage, challenging Black's best piece. }
