7... bxc6 { Better and more combative than taking with the bishop. } 8. Bd3
{ Mission accomplished! Our bishop returns after fulfilling their job to lure Black's bishop to d7. We need to consider two moves now. Black can't play  8...Nf6?  now, as  9.e5  sends the knight home immediately. This is why the d7-bishop is misplaced.What are Black's best options? It makes sense to take control of e5, trying to develop the knight soon.   A.  8...Bd6  is Black's most popular move. They develop the bishop to a good square first and then decide how to continue with the problematic knight on g8.   B.  8...Qc7  is Black's main alternative to A. The queen move also connects to the e5-square and fights against a possible e4-e5 by White. The queen move is usually connected with the idea ...Ne7-g6, which aims to strengthen control of e5 and f4.I will examine both moves in more detail and depth, as they are featured in Chessable courses as recommendations for Black. Line A is Anish Giri's suggestion, and Kamil Plichta recommended line B. Both authors did a good job, so we can't expect a significant advantage for White - given that Black knows 20 moves of perfect theory, which is not to be expected. We still want to be thorough, so let's get to work. }
8... Bd6
{ The bishop move is the most popular move and was recommended by Anish Giri in his Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. }
9. Qe2
{ This looks like the most dangerous move. The main idea is preparing e4-e5, gaining space while hitting the bishop. Now we come to an important split.   A.  9...e5  is the latest trend and was recommended by Anish Giri in his LTR French. I will check this move as the main one, as it also requires the most effort to fight.   B.  9...Ne7  is the former main line that we'll check, too. Black allows the pawn to push to e5, which we are happy about.   C.  9...Qc7  stops e4-e5 and is worth checking, too. }
9... e5
{ This move looks incredibly risky, but nowadays, engines show that it is a valid option. Anish Giri suggested this move in his Chessable repertoire, and I understand his reasoning: in the other lines, Black is usually forced to allow e4-e5 at some point, which the ultra-principled 9...e5 stops in its tracks. You won't be surprised to learn that you can't refute 9...e5, but I think we'll be able to get an interesting game against it. }
10. c4
{ The start of a rather forcing line. We attack the d5-pawn and lure it forward. }
10... d4
{ We follow Giri's recommendation. This is best, as  10...Ne7?!  11.cxd5  cxd5  12.O-O  opens the position too quickly for Black's taste. The game could continue  12...O-O  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Ne4  Be7  15.Rd1  , when Black is poorly coordinated. }
11. c5
{ This is the real point of the previous move. We sacrifice a pawn to activate our knight and weaken Black's dark squares. }
11... Bxc5 12. Nc4
{ A fantastic square for our knight. Now Black has only one good continuation. They have to play the bishop check; otherwise, our pawn push to f4 would become even more effective.   A sample line would be  12...Qc7  13.f4!  Bb4+  14.Bd2  Bxd2+  15.Qxd2  exf4  16.e5!  ,  when we reach a better version of our main line. The move Nd6+ is looming. }
12... Bb4+ { Clearly best, going for the bishop trade. } 13. Bd2 Qe7
{ Here, Black can also play  13...Bxd2+  14.Qxd2  Qe7  , which likely leads to the same position. }
14. O-O Bxd2 15. Qxd2 Nh6
{ Black has to play this odd-looking move as  15...Nf6?  fails to  16.Qg5  or  16.Qa5  , winning the pawn! }
16. f4
{ It's a tough call when ending a trainable line. I decided to do it here, as we are already deep down the rabbit hole. You can get this position in your games, but only against people booked up like a GM. Of course, I want to provide more information, but not as more trainables.   A.  16...f6?  17.fxe5  fxe5  18.Qa5!  Nf7  19.Rxf7!  Kxf7  20.Rf1+  Kg8  21.Nb6  leads to a crushing attack. It is improbable to happen against those well-prepared players, but you never know.   B.  16...exf4  17.Qxf4  O-O  18.h3  gives us good play for the pawn, with the idea e4-e5 and placing the knight on d6. Black's knight on h6 makes a sad impression. Chances are about equal here, but it's certainly interesting to play.   C.  16...Ng4  is Black's safest move when  17.h3  Ne3  18.Nxe3  dxe3  19.Qxe3  exf4  20.Rxf4  leads to a position that Giri evaluates as equal. It's hard to argue with this assessment, but given a choice, I'd still rather be White here. We have the slightly better pawn structure, still.  In any case, this is a very safe position that White can play for two results, with a high draw probability.   A bit of additional info: I think  16.f4  is the most logical move in the position, but maybe you are put off by the simplifying line C. An alternative is  16.Rac1  ,  which is not analysed in Giri's course. The idea is to put pressure on the c-pawn. As far as I can see, White regains the pawn easily. It's still an equal position, but not as simplified as in C. This could be an option if you want more pieces on the board in your game.We can conclude that perfect play gives Black equal chances in the Tarrasch after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  c5  4.Ngf3  cxd4  , but the path is narrow. I like that White is always in control of the position and can ask questions from a position of safety. }
