[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2
{ Against the Tarrasch, Black's most popular replies are @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  .  In this chapter, we will have a look at Black's sidelines. We will check the following moves:   A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...dxe4  leads to the Rubinstein Variation. It is a solid but slightly passive option for Black. The Rubinstein is quite popular in online chess and at the club level, making it the most important line of the chapter.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  is a dubious knight jump, but it leads to unconventional positions and is worth checking.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Be7  is rare, but an interesting waiting move. It's often played by theoretically versed players who want to trick us into unwelcome transpositions.  We will check these three moves with trainable lines. Others are too rare and can be met with common-sense replies without the need to learn specific variations. }
