[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C4) French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Sidelines"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6
{ Black develops the knight and attacks our d-pawn. This is a dubious concept because Black blocks their c-pawn. In a typical French structure, Black wants to attack our d-pawn with ...c5, for example, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.c3  c5  - covered in a dedicated chapter.  In the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  line, they can't go for ...c5, but they need to try to create counterplay differently. We'll discuss this more once the central structure is more defined. }
4. Ngf3
{ An important moment, as  4.c3  is less precise due to  4...e5!  , when Black has better chances to equalise. }
4... Nf6 { Black attacks our pawn and encourages the advance. } 5. e5
{ We are happy about all the space Black gifts us, so here we go! } 5... Nd7
{ We have reached the 'real' starting position of the 3...Nc6 line now.  Let's discuss the strategy for a moment. Black has forfeited the option to attack our center by playing the c-pawn. The only way to make some sense of the knight's position on c6 is by playing a quick ...f6 break. Both knights are connected to the e5-square, so ...f6 would exert serious pressure on our e-pawn.  White has a choice between various promising options now. They are all related to answering the expected move ...f6 properly. The basic choice is to keep the pawn on e5 or prepare for the scenario after capturing on f6. I suggest going for the second option, as it is simple to learn and effective. }
6. Be2
{ A modest-looking move, but it is the best one if you intend to take after Black's expected ...f6-break.   It looks more natural to play  6.Bd3  , but  6...Nb4  is an annoying reply. }
6... f6
{ Black has to do something about their lack of space. Black goes for 3...Nc6 with the ...f6 concept in mind. }
7. exf6 Qxf6
{ Taking with the queen is Black's almost exclusive choice.   After  7...Nxf6  , we can get an advantage in various ways, for example, by playing  8.O-O  Bd6  9.c4!  , an idea that we also play in the main continuation. Black is in trouble, as they don't want to capture the pawn and activate our knight, but  9...O-O  10.c5  Bf4  11.Bb5  is a worse version of the main line that we will examine shortly. Black has no control of e5, and their bad bishop has few prospects to improve.  Taking with the queen is more challenging for us. Black attacks our d-pawn - what to do about it? }
8. Nf1
{ The two key points to remember about the 3...Nc6 line is playing 6.Be2 and this important move.   We had a limited choice because our d-pawn was attacked. This makes you think about  8.c3  and @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pppn2pp/2n1pq2/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNBPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  , but these moves have drawbacks. It is unclear what the knight is doing on b3 or if we need to move c3 in the long run.  Why do we play the knight to f1? Once you learn the idea of  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pppn2pp/2n1pq2/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNBPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nf1  , it all makes sense. We want to place the knight on e3, where it is well placed, for two reasons:We enable the knight to jump to g4, which hits the queen and might get our knight to e5.The knight helps prepare the move c4, which tries to open the position favourably.  Let's see how it plays out. }
8... Bd6
{ Black develops and prepares to castle.   The premature  8...e5?  is refuted by  9.Ne3  , when Black will regret their f-pawn move soon. The center is falling apart, and the king is insecure. }
9. Ne3 { The knight has reached its destination. } 9... O-O 10. O-O
{ Both sides have castled - time for Black to decide what's next. It's not a comfortable situation for our opponent, as we have two good ideas: attacking the queen with Ng4 and the pawn break c4. }
10... Qg6
{ Black's main line by far. They stop the Ng4 idea and often want to play ...Nf6 next.   The alternatives to the queen move look good for White, too. After  10...Nb6  11.Ng4  Qg6  12.h3  we have great control of the e5-square and can improve easily with moves like Re1 and Bd3. Our targets on the e-file are clear-cut, while Black's perspectives are dubious. }
11. c4 { The second idea of the knight tour to e3 is this pawn lever. } 11...
Nf6 { Black's best try, but it does not lead to good play, either. } 12. c5
{ We release the pressure on d5, but get more benefits in return. Black has to return to e7 when Bb5 successfully fights to control the e5-square.   Let's see how it unfolds.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppp3pp/2nbpnq1/2Pp4/3P4/4NN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bf4  looks more active, but the bishop is more exposed on f4. After  13.g3  Bd7  14.Nh4  Qh6  15.Nhg2  , Black has nothing better than to take on e3, which amounts to strategic bankruptcy. They are weak on the dark squares and now have to give up this crucial defender.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppp3pp/2nbpnq1/2Pp4/3P4/4NN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Be7  is better but after  13.Bb5  Bd7  14.Bxc6  Bxc6  15.Ne5  we establish a monster knight in the middle of the board. }
