[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C4) French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Sidelines"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ Black argues that our knight move didn't exert direct pressure on the center, so a slow waiting move in return should be possible. Black still wants to play the moves ...c5 or ...Nf6 but wants to be flexible and react according to our next move. }
4. Bd3
{ I suggest playing  4.Bd3  here because I think it is a pragmatic solution and dangerous for Black due to a less-know idea we'll examine in a moment. White has some alternatives here, though. It is important to understand some points about them, so let's look.   A.  4.Ngf3  Nf6  5.e5  Nfd7  leads to a version of 3.Nd2 Nf6. It differs significantly from our repertoire choice, which involves an early f4 @@StartBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.c3  c5  6.f4  is our line@@EndBracket@@. Therefore, we'd have to learn a different setup just to tackle the rare 3...Be7 line. This is not an economical choice, in my mind.   B.  4.c3  c5  5.e5  and  4.e5  are alternatives, but Black's chances look fine.I think White's best options are A and my move 4. Bd3, which is much easier to learn than A.Let's continue and talk about Black's reply to the bishop move. It is very likely that the next moves in our trainable, up to move eight, will be played. The rare 3...Be7 is quite a sophisticated choice, and Black usually has their response ready up to this point. Let's have a look. }
4... c5
{ This is Black's best move and almost exclusively played. As mentioned, Black usually plays 3...Be7 with some knowledge of the subtleties. Is there anything else?   A.  4...Nf6?  is a real mistake. After  5.e5  Nfd7  6.Qg4!  Black is under huge pressure on the kingside. You don't need to know more - develop pieces and start an attack on Black's king. If you forget this idea and play  6.f4  ,  it's also not a problem. We'd transpose to a favourable line of the 3.Nd2 Nf6 complex. Here the queen move is just even stronger and puts the whole idea 4...Nf6 out of business.   B.  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  transposes to a type of Rubinstein with the premature move ...Be7. We are better by playing normal development moves, like Ngf3 and Qe2. }
5. dxc5
{ A good moment to capture, as Black has already moved their bishop. It is unattractive to play  5...Bxc5  , as  6.exd5  exd5  leads to a nice version of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  c5  ,  when Black sometimes manages to capture on c5 in one go -  4.Ngf3  a6  5.exd5  exd5  6.dxc5  Bxc5  is an example. Here, we would reach a similar scenario with an extra tempo. }
5... Nf6
{ Black avoids the tempo loss ...Bxc5 and instead accelerates kingside development. We must be precise, as the wrong move order would help Black greatly. }
6. Qe2
{ The move to avoid is  6.Ngf3  , which allows.  6...dxe4  7.Nxe4  Nxe4  8.Bxe4  Qxd1+  ,  when Black manages to simplify and gets equal chances. This is not a disaster, but it lets Black off the hook far too easily. The queen move is much stronger, as it avoids all the simplifications. }
6... O-O
{ Black's most obvious and popular move. You sometimes meet  6...a5  , when  7.Ngf3  O-O  8.c3  is a transposition to the position we will check in a moment. }
7. Ngf3 a5
{ Black's idea is to regain the pawn by playing ...a5 and ...Na6, allowing the a6-knight to capture. This makes sense, as they don't want to move the e7-bishop again. This position is likely to occur against a knowledgeable opponent. Now I suggest a rarely played but very dangerous continuation. }
8. c3
{ White's most popular move is the more obvious  8.O-O  , when  8...Na6  9.e5  Nd7  10.c3  Naxc5  11.Bc2  looks slightly better for White. It is a fine alternative to my move, which will likely pose some unexpected problems. What's the idea? Hang on! }
8... Na6 9. e5 Nd7 10. h4
{ You could still castle and transpose to the lines that usually start with 8. O-O, but pushing the h-pawn is more fun. We have a simple yet dangerous idea: the Greek Gift! In practice, Black struggled against this concept. Most of the time, they play the move 10...h6, which we will examine as our main line. }
10... h6
{ Black stops the Greek Gift but weakens the kingside in the process. There are some alternatives, of course.   A.  10...Ndxc5??  11.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  12.Ng5+  is a textbook Greek Gift and wins easily. The other knight capture is punished in the same way, of course.   B.  10...f5  was tried in some games, but  11.Bxa6  looks promising. After  11...Rxa6  12.b4  we are just material up with a large advantage, while  11...bxa6  12.c6  Nb8  13.Nb3  Nxc6  14.Bg5  gives us slightly better chances.   C.  10...Qc7  is interesting, as it prevents the Greek Gift. After  11.Bxh7+??  Kxh7  12.Ng5+  Kg8  13.Qh5  Qxe5+  14.Kf1  Nf6  Black defends the critical spot h7 in time. Much better is  @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1pqnbppp/n3p3/p1PpP3/7P/2PB1N2/PP1NQPP1/R1B1K2R w KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nb3  , when  11...Naxc5  12.Nxc5  Nxc5  13.Bc2  leads to an interesting position that I like for White, but it could be Black's best bet against the 10.h4!? line. }
11. Bc2 { Better than  11.Nb3?!  a4!  , which helps Black. } 11... Naxc5 12.
Nb3
{ We wouldn't mind trading Black's active knight, of course. The second idea is simple: get the c1-bishop out. A crude, but a very dangerous idea, is Bf4, followed by Qe3 and Bxh6! to crush Black's kingside. This is why the move ...h6 entails some risk: it gives us a target to attack.You won't face 3...Be7 frequently. If you meet a specialist in this line, the suggested idea will be an unpleasant surprise! }
