[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C4) French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Sidelines"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 dxe4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has a choice of lines that lead to different scenarios.   A.  4...Nd7  is the main continuation. Black prepares ...Ngf6 next and aims for a later ...c5 break. We can count on a small advantage in this line.   B.  4...Bd7  leads to the so-called Fort Knox Variation. Black wants to activate the bishop via c6 but often ends up trading the bishop for one of our knights. The Fort Know has its name for a reason: it has the reputation of being a solid, albeit passive defence.   C.  4...Nf6  is imprecise but regularly played in online and amateur games. We'll see how to gain a comfortable advantage against it. }
4... Nf6
{ A dubious choice, but it is a move that you'll meet regularly in online games or at club-level play. }
5. Nxf6+
{ Natural and best. Black either has to weaken their pawn structure or expose their queen. }
5... Qxf6
{ Black usually takes with the queen, but  5...gxf6  is not necessarily worse. Both moves give White a clear advantage, though. Against the pawn capture, White has a range of good options. I'm not too fond of a quick kingside castling, though. Black sometimes manages to pose problems on the g-file.A good plan, in my mind, is  6.Be3  to get closer to queenside castling. Black's pawn structure deficits remain, and they get no possible counterplay against our king. }
6. Nf3
{ If we are allowed to play three moves in a row, Black's queen is trapped! If we manage Nf3, Bd3 and Bg5, we win the queen! OK, Black will certainly stop that, but they must lose some time to prevent this idea. }
6... Nc6
{ Black usually combines the moves ...Nc6, ...Bd6 and ...h6 in this line. They can also start with a different move, but we'll likely reach the same situation later:   A.  6...Bd6  7.Bd3  h6  8.c3  Nc6  9.Qe2   B.  6...h6  7.Bd3  Nc6  8.c3  Bd6  9.Qe2   C.  6...Nc6  7.Bd3  h6  8.c3  Bd6  9.Qe2  - this is the move order I selected for the trainable line. }
7. Bd3
{ Danger, Danger! Well, we are not too subtle here, but it still regularly happens that Black overlooks the threat and allows the queen trap. }
7... h6
{ After  7...Bd6??  or  7...Bd7??  8.Bg5  , we win the unlucky queen.   If they play  7...Nxd4??  , we win with a different trick.  8.Nxd4  Qxd4  9.Bb5+  is the problem. }
8. c3
{ We play this move to prepare Qe2 next. This queen move is a nice finesse that poses more problems for Black than  8.O-O  , for example. }
8... Bd6 9. Qe2
{ I believe this move is strong and difficult for Black to handle. We don't commit to kingside castling and prepare a strong response if Black decides to castle now. }
9... O-O
{ Black should play  9...Bd7  and delay this decision. After  10.O-O  O-O  11.Re1  White still has the much better position, with Ne5 to come. Black could play  10...O-O-O  , but our attack is easy to play and faster. Just  11.b4  as a start of the pawn storm will do. }
10. h4
{ A dangerous move for Black. We get Bg5! back on the map, as Black has to be VERY cautious about opening the h-file. I will examine 10...e5 now, as it is the most popular in online games. }
10... e5
{ It looks like Black's best is a cautious move, like  10...Qd8  . We have excellent chances after  11.Be3  ,  followed by queenside castling, though. The move ...h6 makes it much easier to attack - think of g4-g5 to open files.   Still, this is better than allowing our  Bg5  idea to materialise. There are various ways for Black to allow it. A fun line is  10...Re8  11.Bg5!  hxg5  12.hxg5  Qe7  13.Qe4  f5  14.Qe4  and White's attack crashes through. }
11. d5
{ After  11.Bg5?  Qe6  we don't have anything special. Taking away the e6-square first is a key difference. }
11... Ne7
{ Here  11...e4  12.Qxe4  Qe7  is the relatively best defence. Black is a pawn down and has little hope, but it's not an immediate disaster. }
12. Bg5 hxg5 13. hxg5 { Black's queen has only one square left. } 13... Qf4 14.
g3 { The final touch. Now it can only go to a light square when we win it. }
14... Qa4 { Or  14...Qg4  15.Bh7+  Kh8  16.Bf5+  , the same story. } 15. Bh7+
{ Not the only win, but the simplest.  15.Nd4  leads to a mate and is a good 'alternative'! }
15... Kh8 16. Bc2+ { And that's it for the black queen! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C4) French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Sidelines"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 dxe4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has a choice of lines that lead to different scenarios.   A.  4...Nd7  is the main continuation. Black prepares ...Ngf6 next and aims for a later ...c5 break. We can count on a small advantage in this line.   B.  4...Bd7  leads to the so-called Fort Knox Variation. Black wants to activate the bishop via c6 but often ends up trading the bishop for one of our knights. The Fort Know has its name for a reason: it has the reputation of being a solid, albeit passive defence.   C.  4...Nf6  is imprecise but regularly played in online and amateur games. We'll see how to gain a comfortable advantage against it. }
4... Bd7
{ The Fort Knox Variation. Black wants to activate their passive bishop via d7 to c6. This line has a solid reputation, but White retains a comfortable advantage. A common problem for Black is that they don't manage to keep their bishop on c6 but are more or less forced to trade for a knight. Let's have a look. }
5. Nf3
{ Developing the knight first is natural, but  5.Bd3  Bc6  6.Nf3  leads to the same position. }
5... Bc6 6. Bd3
{ We develop and keep our knight on the central square, a natural move. } 6...
Nd7
{ Black's main move by a mile. They want to play ...Ngf6 and be ready to recapture on f6 with a knight.   You sometimes meet  6...Bxe4  7.Bxe4  c6  , when Black gives up their bishop voluntarily. We are better by playing normal moves.  8.c3  Nf6  9.Bc2  Bd6  10.O-O  Nbd7  11.Re1  is a natural sequence. We have the bishop pair and more space. Playing a knight to e5 is an idea, too. }
7. c3
{ The exclam for this move is a bit strong, but I like it a lot. We play a universally useful move and set a trap simultaneously. What's the trap? We'll see in a moment. }
7... Ngf6
{ Black's planned move, and no mistake. But they might make one on the next move, as we'll see! }
8. Nxf6+ { Alright, how should Black recapture now? } 8... Qxf6
{ I can't resist covering this blunder in a trainable, as it is so much fun to trap Black's queen now! }
9. Bg5
{ We have trapped the queen, but Black probably thought they have a saving move... }
9... Bxf3 { Nice try, buddy... } 10. Qd2
{ And we have trapped the queen, after all! In this position, you see why we played c3. It covers the d-pawn, so Black can't take it. }
