[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "C4) French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Sidelines"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 dxe4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has a choice of lines that lead to different scenarios.   A.  4...Nd7  is the main continuation. Black prepares ...Ngf6 next and aims for a later ...c5 break. We can count on a small advantage in this line.   B.  4...Bd7  leads to the so-called Fort Knox Variation. Black wants to activate the bishop via c6 but often ends up trading the bishop for one of our knights. The Fort Know has its name for a reason: it has the reputation of being a solid, albeit passive defence.   C.  4...Nf6  is imprecise but regularly played in online and amateur games. We'll see how to gain a comfortable advantage against it. }
4... Bd7
{ The Fort Knox Variation. Black wants to activate their passive bishop via d7 to c6. This line has a solid reputation, but White retains a comfortable advantage. A common problem for Black is that they don't manage to keep their bishop on c6 but are more or less forced to trade for a knight. Let's have a look. }
5. Nf3
{ Developing the knight first is natural, but  5.Bd3  Bc6  6.Nf3  leads to the same position. }
5... Bc6 6. Bd3
{ We develop and keep our knight on the central square, a natural move. } 6...
Nd7
{ Black's main move by a mile. They want to play ...Ngf6 and be ready to recapture on f6 with a knight.   You sometimes meet  6...Bxe4  7.Bxe4  c6  , when Black gives up their bishop voluntarily. We are better by playing normal moves.  8.c3  Nf6  9.Bc2  Bd6  10.O-O  Nbd7  11.Re1  is a natural sequence. We have the bishop pair and more space. Playing a knight to e5 is an idea, too. }
7. c3
{ The exclam for this move is a bit strong, but I like it a lot. We play a universally useful move and set a trap simultaneously. What's the trap? We'll see in a moment. }
7... Ngf6
{ Black's planned move, and no mistake. But they might make one on the next move, as we'll see! }
8. Nxf6+ { Alright, how should Black recapture now? } 8... Nxf6
{ Black has successfully avoided our small trap. We don't win the queen here, but there is no reason to complain. }
9. O-O
{ A perfectly normal and logical move, but there is a bit more to it. We want to play our knight to e5, but  9.Ne5  fails to  9...Bxg2  .  After kingside castling, we threaten the centralisation of our knight. The knight jump is annoying, as we'd threaten Nxc6 to destroy Black's pawn structure. }
9... Bxf3
{ This is Black's most popular move, stopping Ne5 forever! It is a good moment for the capture, as  10.Qxf3  Qd5  is the point. The alternatives are less precise.   A.  9...Be7?!  10.Ne5  is nice for us. Black has to play some strange moves now to avoid the doubled c-pawns or go for the relatively best  10...Qd5  , when  11.Nxc6  leads to a better version of 9...Bxf3 for us.   B.  9...Bd6  is best answered by  10.Re1  ,  aiming for Ne5 again. You need to avoid  10.Ne5??  , when  10...Bxe5  11.dxe5  Qd5!  picks up our center pawn. After the better 10. Re1, we either manage Ne5, or they take on f3, which is again a nicer version of 9...Bxf3 for us. }
10. Qxf3 Qd5
{ A strong move. Black would be delighted about the trade on d5, as they have less space. Our goal in this position is to keep pieces on the board and try to exploit the bishop pair, our long-term asset. Alright, we don't want to trade queens just yet - where do we go then? }
11. Qd1
{ It looks surprising to go back, but there is a logic to it. There are two points to consider:A. Our d3-bishop is not ideally placed on d3, as we are unlikely to drum up play on the kingside after the piece trades. It would be better to use the long diagonal h1-a8, so clearing the way for Bd3-e2-f3 or Re1&g3&Bf1-g2 makes some sense.   B. There is the concrete question of 'Where else?'  11.Qe2  Qh5  tries to trade queen again, and is a bit annoying. Going to e3 or g4 also feels unharmonious.   I'll finish with a sample sequence to illustrate the plan described for point A:  11.Qd1  c6  12.Re1  Bd6  13.g3  O-O  14.Bf1  is one way to complete the regrouping. Our idea is to slowly expand on the queenside, while Black will likely follow a sit-and-wait strategy. They can't change the pawn structure favourably, as ...c5 or ...e5 would open the position for our bishops. The key virtue is patience for both sides. Black needs to avoid weaknesses, while we must slowly progress and avoid hasty actions. }
