[Round "?"]
[White "C4) French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 Sidelines"]
[Black "French Tarrasch – 3.Nd2 dxe4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has a choice of lines that lead to different scenarios.   A.  4...Nd7  is the main continuation. Black prepares ...Ngf6 next and aims for a later ...c5 break. We can count on a small advantage in this line.   B.  4...Bd7  leads to the so-called Fort Knox Variation. Black wants to activate the bishop via c6 but often ends up trading the bishop for one of our knights. The Fort Know has its name for a reason: it has the reputation of being a solid, albeit passive defence.   C.  4...Nf6  is imprecise but regularly played in online and amateur games. We'll see how to gain a comfortable advantage against it. }
4... Nd7
{ The knight move was Rubinstein's original intention, and it remains Black's main choice on all levels. Black wants to play ...Ngf6 next and challenge our centralised knight. }
5. Nf3
{ As standard as it gets. A crucial point arises on move seven, so let's fast forward to this crossroads. }
5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+
{ This looks like White's best. There is a wide range of options on the next move, though. }
6... Nxf6 7. Be3
{ White has a wide range of options here. It is tough to decide, as  7.c3  ,  7.Bd3  ,  7.Be3  and  7.g3  all seem to give White a small pull, but not more. I ultimately decided to recommend  7.Be3  ,  as I felt it is the easiest to play. The idea is twofold: we stop Black's pawn push ...c5 for the moment and get one move closer to queenside castling. If Black continues their kingside development and castles, we'll play Bd3, followed by Qe2 and O-O-O.We'll examine two moves now. One is  7...Bd6  , showing this plan. An entirely different approach would be  7...Nd5  , when Black wants to take our bishop. }
7... Nd5
{ A different approach than  7...Be7  or  7...Bd6  . Black wants our bishop, but we don't comply. }
8. Bd2
{ We keep our bishop and are ready to play c4 at the right moment, kicking the knight back. }
8... c5
{ That was Black's secondary idea. We have kept our bishop but released control of the c5-square. Black can play the desired pawn break now, but we have a strong reply. It is a forcing sequence that gives us a comfortable advantage. }
9. Bb5+
{ The motivation behind this move is a concrete sequence of moves that Black can't avoid. }
9... Bd7 { The only move. } 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ And again, the only move. This whole sequence only makes sense due to the next move. }
11. c4
{ This move is very powerful now. We attack the knight, forcing the reply  11...Nb6  . Other knight moves are much worse, for example,  11...Nf6  12.Ne5!  Qxd4  13.Qa4+  ,  with a winning attack. The knight jump to e5, followed by Qa4+, is the justification of the sequence that started on the ninth move. }
11... Nb6
{ Not a happy square for a knight, but it covers a4, thus preventing Ne5&Qa4+ ideas. }
12. Rc1
{ Simple, but strong. White has a nice advantage now, as Black has to be cautious.   A.  12...cxd4?  13.c5!  Nd5  14.Ne5  Qc7  15.Qa4+  is a recipe for disaster.   B.  12...Be7?!  13.dxc5  Bxc5  14.b4  Be7  15.c5  Nd5  16.Ne5  is a similar story.   C.  12...f6  is the engine defence. After  13.dxc5  Bxc5  14.O-O  we are slightly better, though. Black has created some weaknesses, and the b6-knight is less than ideally placed. }
