1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has a choice of lines that lead to different scenarios.   A.  4...Nd7  is the main continuation. Black prepares ...Ngf6 next and aims for a later ...c5 break. We can count on a small advantage in this line.   B.  4...Bd7  leads to the so-called Fort Knox Variation. Black wants to activate the bishop via c6 but often ends up trading the bishop for one of our knights. The Fort Know has its name for a reason: it has the reputation of being a solid, albeit passive defence.   C.  4...Nf6  is imprecise but regularly played in online and amateur games. We'll see how to gain a comfortable advantage against it. }
4... Nd7
{ The knight move was Rubinstein's original intention, and it remains Black's main choice on all levels. Black wants to play ...Ngf6 next and challenge our centralised knight. }
5. Nf3
{ As standard as it gets. A crucial point arises on move seven, so let's fast forward to this crossroads. }
5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+
{ This looks like White's best. There is a wide range of options on the next move, though. }
6... Nxf6 7. Be3
{ White has a wide range of options here. It is tough to decide, as  7.c3  ,  7.Bd3  ,  7.Be3  and  7.g3  all seem to give White a small pull, but not more. I ultimately decided to recommend  7.Be3  ,  as I felt it is the easiest to play. The idea is twofold: we stop Black's pawn push ...c5 for the moment and get one move closer to queenside castling. If Black continues their kingside development and castles, we'll play Bd3, followed by Qe2 and O-O-O.We'll examine two moves now. One is  7...Bd6  , showing this plan. An entirely different approach would be  7...Nd5  , when Black wants to take our bishop. }
7... Bd6
{ Black can also prepare kingside castling with  7...Be7  ,  when our reaction would be the same: Bd3, Qe2 and O-O-O. In a few moves, I'll show a position where the difference between the two bishop positions is relevant. }
8. Bd3 { According to plan. We want to go Bd3, Qe2 and castle queenside. } 8...
O-O
{ Black usually castles kingside here. They can play for queenside castling, but it takes a while to accomplish and feels passive. After  8...Bd7  9.Qe2  Qe7  10.O-O-O  O-O-O  11.c4  we are better due to our space advantage. A good alternative is  11.Bd2  Nd5  12.g3  - it stops further exchanges and makes the space advantage more pronounced. }
9. Qe2 { The next step. } 9... b6
{ The only active way for Black to develop their bishop. } 10. O-O-O Bb7 11.
Bg5
{ Pinning the knight looks like the most powerful move. Here we have arrived at a good moment to talk about Black's earlier option @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/4BN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  , when  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Qe2  b6  10.O-O-O  Bb7  looks natural and is frequently played. Playing the bishop to g5 makes little sense in this situation, as we wouldn't pin the knight. Instead, it looks a lot better to play a good prophylactic move:  11.Kb1  is strong, as it takes the sting out of many counterplay ideas, like Black's queen attacking the a-pawn or ...Nd5-b4. Black can't play  11...c5?  , as  12.dxc5!  threatens Bxh7+, winning the queen. White is in good shape here, with plenty of attacking ideas. Pushing the h-pawn or Ne5 comes to mind. }
11... h6
{ Black's game is not easy to play. Here  11...c5?  loses on the spot to  12.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.Qd3+  , a nice tactic. }
12. Bh4
{ Black is under some pressure, and it isn't easy to defend. In some GM games, the move  12...Be7  was tested now. I like  13.Ne5  , when Black's most obvious ideas are the knight moves.   A.  13...Nd7?  14.Bg3  is great for White. After  14...Nxe5  15.Bxe5  our bishops are hitting Black's kingside, with Qg4 ideas to come.   B.  13...Nd5  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  15.Qe4!  f5  16.Qf3  also looks good for White. We have provoked ...f5 and Black's counterplay idea  16...c5  17.dxc5  Rfc8  18.c6!  Bxc6  19.Nxc6  Rxc6  gives White a choice between  20.Bxf5  and  20.Rhe1  ,  which looks even more promising.My overall conclusion is that the plan based on 7.Be3 and queenside castling looks like a good try to keep an advantage. Black has to play a sharper position than they likely aimed for. }
