[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "D1) Caro-Kann – Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Hello and welcome to the Caro-Kann section of the course.  The Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 is a popular defense on all levels of play, from amateur to GM. Depending on the parameters, it ranks in third or fourth place and should appear in 10% of your games, a bit more if you play higher-level opposition. }
2. d4 d5 3. exd5
{ How to battle the Caro-Kann? In the first edition of the course, I suggest the Two Knights variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  d5  3.Nf3  - a choice that I still like from a theoretical point of view.  However, for this course, I suggest a different line. Why the change? In December 2021, I released Keep It Simple for Black. My suggestion for Black is the Caro-Kann. For this course, I needed to check all White's tries and find antidotes for them. This drew my attention to the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann, which proved far more difficult to handle for Black than I expected. In addition, White's concepts are easy to learn and employ. These aspects make it an ideal weapon for a KIS repertoire with White. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ Here is an overview of the chapters:  A. Caro-Kann Exchange Sidelines. The main line is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.h3  is examined in a dedicated chapter. It is the most popular setup for Black, as developing the knight to c6 and f6 is very natural. In the sidelines chapter, we discuss ways for Black to deviate from this concept.   B. Caro-Kann Exchange Main Line. In the main line, Black develops their knight to the most natural and best squares. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.h3  Black has the fundamental choice between  6...e5  @@StartBracket@@good equalising chances, but not to every Caro-Kann players taste@@EndBracket@@ or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , which looks slightly better for White and features strategic elements that Black will likely not know as well as we do.  The Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann leads to a non-symmetrical pawn structure. This is an important difference to openings like the French Exchange or Slav Exchange, which have a drawish reputation. The open files can be a chopping block for the pieces, leading to simplifications and less exciting games.  In the Caro-Kann Exchange, there is no open file. The pawn structure, which we determine from the very start, features some key elements.  We have no problems developing our pieces on active squares and can usually play a similar setup. We play Bd3, c3, Nf3, h3, O-O and Re1 in the majority of the lines.Black's development is not that simple: by playing Bd3 and h3 early, we stop any ...Bg4 ideas.Black often decides to play ...g6, preparing ...Bf5. This makes sense, as ...Bg4 is impossible.The move ...g6 has serious drawbacks, though. One standard idea in the Exchange Caro for Black is the Minority Attack on the queenside. It features the push of the b-pawn to b4, trying to create weaknesses on our queenside. The Minority attack is more difficult to engineer with a bishop on g7, as it does not contribute to the queenside action. It would be much better on d6, for example, looking at the b4- and c5-squares. In many cases, we are happy to see Black's attempt to play for ...b5 in the ...g6-setups.  These concepts are discussed in the Caro-Kann main lines chapter. Black regularly misplays these positions, as the differences to other minority attacks are not obvious.  Black has other options than ...g6, of course. My recommendation for Black is a different one featuring a quick ...e5. In these lines, Black should reach equal chances. They are not that popular amongst Black players, as they rarely want to play a position with an Isolated Pawn. The resulting positions are often not to their taste and thus avoided. We often fight against the IQP in our repertoire @@StartBracket@@French Tarrasch@@EndBracket@@ and have a familiar structure that is easy to play. These points make the Exchange Variation a great practical choice for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "D2) Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation Sidelines"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation 4...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ We develop our bishop to its most active square and stop ...Bf5 simultaneously. In most games, the next moves are  4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  when I suggest playing  6.h3  , again preventing Black's bishop development. This position is the starting point of the second Caro-Kann Chapter, the Exchange Variation main line.  In the current chapter, we will examine ways for Black to play differently. It is difficult to devise something entirely different, as developing the two knights to their natural squares makes a lot of sense. In many cases, Black might start a bit differently on the first moves but then plays both knight moves after all. }
4... Nf6
{ Black starts with the king's knight and gets the idea ...Bg4 on the map.   Black follows the same concept in our main line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/3P4/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  , when I suggest  6.h3  to stop the bishop move. Therefore, my suggestion in the position at hand shouldn't surprise you. }
5. h3
{ No bishop to g4, please. Now Black has three logical options. They have little independent value, as playing the knight to c6 at some point will almost certainly transpose to the main line:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/3B3P/PPP2PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.c3  transposes to the main line and is the most popular here. Note that you should play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/3p4/3P4/3B3P/PPP2PP1/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  and not @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/3p4/3P4/3B3P/PPP2PP1/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  , as  6...Nb4  is annoying. We need the move c3 anyway, so better play it straight away.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/3B3P/PPP2PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  will almost certainly transpose to the main line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/3B3P/PPP2PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.c3  g6  , as Black has no reason to avoid ...Nc6.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/3B3P/PPP2PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/3P4/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.c3  e6  , but Black has committed to ...Nf6 already.  We'll examine B and C now. Line B will be a transposition at the end, but seeing our standard setup against ...g6 is helpful. }
5... e6
{ A similar concept as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/3P4/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.c3  e6  , but Black has forfeited the most interesting option to use the setup ...Bd6 & ...Nge7, keeping the option to play ...f6.  The drawback of combining ...Nf6 and ...e6 is the weakness of the e5-square, which is an excellent potential outpost for our knight.  Our next moves are very natural. We complete kingside castling and prepare the knight jump to e5. }
6. Nf3 Bd6
{ The move orders are flexible here. Black could always play ...Nc6 at some point when it's a good moment to play c3. Instead of ...Bd6, they could also develop the bishop to e7. It doesn't change our strategy, though. We'll castle and start a kingside initiative based on Ne5. }
7. O-O
{ You can also play  7.c3  first. We'll likely reach the same position anyway, as both sides' moves are natural. }
7... O-O 8. Re1 { Or  8.c3  , amounting to the same thing. } 8... Nc6 9. c3
{ This setup, after nine moves, is a frequent guest in our Caro-Kann repertoire. We have developed the kingside, castled and prepared to use our outpost - the e5-square. }
9... Qc7 { Black stops Ne5 for a moment, but we can 'reload'. } 10. Qe2
{ Alright, let's get Ne5 back on the map. } 10... a6
{ This is the most frequently played move in online games. You won't find many master-level games in this position, as stronger players on the black side generally avoid it.  Here are two possible alternatives that I find interesting to study:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2ppp/2nbpn2/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP2QPP1/RNB1R1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Re8  11.Ne5  Nd7??  is a common mistake and  12.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  13.Qh5+  Kg8  14.Qxf7+  is the due punishment.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2ppp/2nbpn2/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP2QPP1/RNB1R1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nd7  is Black's stubborn attempt to stop our knight jump. I like the move  11.Na3  now, when  11...a6  12.Nc2  starts a transfer of the knight to the kingside.  Black can play for ...e6-e5 in this position, but the resulting IQP positions are a bit better for White, as usual. This is similar to positions from the Tarrasch with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.exd5  exd5  , when Black's activity is enough to be OK, but it's easier for White to play. }
11. Ne5 { Here we go! } 11... b5
{ The interesting question after this move is: should we prevent further advances on the queenside by playing  12.a3  , or ignore a possible ...b5-b4? }
12. Bf4
{ Playing  12.a3  is not a mistake, but we don't need to worry about ...b5-b4 at all. }
12... b4
{ Or  12...Bb7  13.Nd2  Rac8  14.Nb3  Rfe8  15.a4  , showing that Black's queenside advance has created some weaknesses. }
13. Nd2 { We continue our development and don't mind the capture on c3. } 13...
bxc3 14. bxc3
{ At first, you might think Black has made some progress. The c3-pawn is a structural weakness, after all. This is only a part of the story, though.  A closer look shows Black's problems. They can't create any pressure on c3 and might easily get into serious trouble if they are too ambitious on the queenside:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/2q2ppp/p1nbpn2/3pN3/3P1B2/2PB3P/P2NQPP1/R3R1K1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Bb7  15.Rab1  Ne7?  16.c4!  dxc4  17.Ndxc4  gives us a huge attack on the queenside.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/2q2ppp/p1nbpn2/3pN3/3P1B2/2PB3P/P2NQPP1/R3R1K1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Bb7  15.Rab1  Na5?  16.Qf3  covers c3 by tactical means and prepares Qg3-h4 to attack Black's king.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/2q2ppp/p1nbpn2/3pN3/3P1B2/2PB3P/P2NQPP1/R3R1K1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Bb7  15.Rab1  Rfc8  16.Bg5  also looks dire for Black.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/2q2ppp/p1nbpn2/3pN3/3P1B2/2PB3P/P2NQPP1/R3R1K1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...a5  is the engine suggestion, but  15.Ndf3  Ne7  16.Rac1  is still better for White. We easily defend c3 and shift more pieces towards Black's king.  In practice, this position is much more difficult to play for Black. }
