[White "D2) Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation Sidelines"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation 4...Nc6 5.c3 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ We develop our bishop to its most active square and stop ...Bf5 simultaneously. In most games, the next moves are  4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  when I suggest playing  6.h3  , again preventing Black's bishop development. This position is the starting point of the second Caro-Kann Chapter, the Exchange Variation main line.  In the current chapter, we will examine ways for Black to play differently. It is difficult to devise something entirely different, as developing the two knights to their natural squares makes a lot of sense. In many cases, Black might start a bit differently on the first moves but then plays both knight moves after all. }
4... Nc6
{ In most cases, Black starts with this knight move. It looks like a natural choice, as you can hardly imagine a scenario where developing it to d7, let alone a6, would make any sense. }
5. c3
{ It's important to play this move and avoid  5.Nf3  Bg4!  , when Black solves a key issue immediately. Black should work harder to get their bishop developed!  Now we have to consider different options for Black.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the main line by a mile. We play  6.h3  against it and stop Black's idea ...Bg4 in its tracks. The main line is discussed in a dedicated chapter. Black has some alternatives with independent value. Some might still transpose to the main line because a later ...Nf6 is a natural move.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qc7  is Black's most important alternative. They prevent Bf4 and hope to develop the c8-bishop later.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  looks a bit passive but has some points if Black plays correctly afterwards.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  prepares the fianchetto and the move ...Bf5, a common idea in the Exchange Caro-Kann. This move will often transpose to the main line after a later ...Nf6, but Black has some worse alternatives that we should check.   I also found some games with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  , when  6.dxe5  Nxe5  7.Nf3  leads to a better version of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.h3  e5  7.dxe5  Nxe5  8.Nf3  , an important part of the Caro-Kann main line chapter. It is a slightly better version because it is not clear yet that we need the move h3, while ...Nf6 will always be useful for Black. }
5... g6
{ Black plays the ...g6 plan fairly early, even before developing the knight to f6. Usually, they will play ...Nf6 soon and still transpose to the main line, but there is one independent option. }
6. Nf3
{ There is no need for the move  6.h3  here, as we don't need to worry about ...Bg4. Black has played ...g6, which means a later h3 forces a retreat or the capture on f3, as ...Bh5 fails to g4.   After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pp1p/2n3p1/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  Bg4?!  you can play  7.h3  right away, but preparing it with O-O and Nbd2 is sensible too. }
6... Bg7
{ Black can also play  6...Bf5  here when I suggest to castle and avoid the capture. This will often lead to positions from the main line Caro-Kann chapter, which are very similar. Here we have not played h3, but the strategy is very similar.  A sample line for such a scenario is  6...Bf5  7.O-O  Bxd3  8.Qxd3  Bg7  9.Re1  Nf6  , when  10.h3  would be a transposition to the main line. You could try to improve with @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp2ppbp/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PQ1N2/PP3PPP/RNB1R1K1 w kq - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bf4  here, but the difference is minor. This position type is more dependent on the right strategic decisions than on single moves. We discuss it in greater detail in the mentioned chapter on the main line. }
7. O-O Nh6
{ This move could be why Black avoided ...Nf6 prior. It is fairly dubious, in my mind, but the only independent option here.   Black could still play  7...Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bf5  with a possible transposition to the main line chapter.   What's the point of @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nh6  , by the way? Black has two possible ideas.Playing ...Bf5 and allowing the knight to recapture on f5,A very ambitious plan involving ...f6, ...Nf7 and ...e5, but against good play, this should not materialise. }
8. Re1 { Business as usual for the rook in the Caro Exchange. } 8... O-O
{ Black should castle first.  I found some games that went terribly wrong with the following alternatives:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp2ppbp/2n3pn/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bf5?  fails to  9.Bxh6  Bxh6  10.Bxf5  gxf5  11.Nh4  and f5 falls!   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp2ppbp/2n3pn/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...f6?  9.c4!  looks even worse than the later ...f6 idea, which we will examine in a moment. }
9. h3
{ Alright, we play h3 after all! This is not the only good move here, but it makes perfect sense and fits well with other lines.  So what does h3 do? Not THAT much immediately, but I think it is well-suited to meet Black's two plans that I outlined before.   The most obvious alternative would be  9.Bf4  , which can't be bad. However, after  9...f6  10.c4  g5  , it gets messier than I'd like. The counterpunch c4 is much more effective after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n3pn/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h3  f6?  10.c4!  , as we will see. }
9... Bf5 10. Bf1
{ A strong reply! Black's pieces on f5 and h6 make a strange impression now, both competing for one square. This is why retreating our bishop makes a lot of sense. A later Bf4, combined with Qc1/Qd2, might lead to a bad day in the office for the pony on h6. }
