[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "D2) Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation Sidelines"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation 4...Nc6 5.c3 e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ We develop our bishop to its most active square and stop ...Bf5 simultaneously. In most games, the next moves are  4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  when I suggest playing  6.h3  , again preventing Black's bishop development. This position is the starting point of the second Caro-Kann Chapter, the Exchange Variation main line.  In the current chapter, we will examine ways for Black to play differently. It is difficult to devise something entirely different, as developing the two knights to their natural squares makes a lot of sense. In many cases, Black might start a bit differently on the first moves but then plays both knight moves after all. }
4... Nc6
{ In most cases, Black starts with this knight move. It looks like a natural choice, as you can hardly imagine a scenario where developing it to d7, let alone a6, would make any sense. }
5. c3
{ It's important to play this move and avoid  5.Nf3  Bg4!  , when Black solves a key issue immediately. Black should work harder to get their bishop developed!  Now we have to consider different options for Black.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the main line by a mile. We play  6.h3  against it and stop Black's idea ...Bg4 in its tracks. The main line is discussed in a dedicated chapter. Black has some alternatives with independent value. Some might still transpose to the main line because a later ...Nf6 is a natural move.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qc7  is Black's most important alternative. They prevent Bf4 and hope to develop the c8-bishop later.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  looks a bit passive but has some points if Black plays correctly afterwards.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  prepares the fianchetto and the move ...Bf5, a common idea in the Exchange Caro-Kann. This move will often transpose to the main line after a later ...Nf6, but Black has some worse alternatives that we should check.   I also found some games with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  , when  6.dxe5  Nxe5  7.Nf3  leads to a better version of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.h3  e5  7.dxe5  Nxe5  8.Nf3  , an important part of the Caro-Kann main line chapter. It is a slightly better version because it is not clear yet that we need the move h3, while ...Nf6 will always be useful for Black. }
5... e6
{ Black locks in the c8-bishop, which is not in the spirit of the Caro-Kann, you might think.  However, in recent years this move has received some attention, as the setup involving ...Bd6 and ...Nge7 looks reasonable for Black. They have some control of the e5-square and might even play ...f6 at some point, stopping any ideas we may have about playing our knight to the attractive square e5.  Let's examine how to play against this approach. }
6. Nf3
{ I suggest continuing with our kingside development.   It's also possible to play  6.Bf4  here, when  6...Bd6  leads to the bishop trade. This is a good alternative, but I prefer keeping more pieces on the board. }
6... Bd6 7. O-O Nge7
{ This setup is the most interesting for Black and the reason why 5...e6 has recently become more popular.  Black could also play  7...Nf6  here, but we are happy to see this move. This chapter examines @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/3P4/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.h3  e6  6.Nf3  , which is slightly better for White and comfortable to play. Compared to this line, we have 'saved' the move h3. This has two benefits:We are a bit faster with the occupation of e5,Having the pawn on h2 may prove useful: we can later play a rook lift to h3 or use Qf3-h3, for example.   Long story short: @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp3ppp/2nbp3/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nf6  leads to a good game for us. }
8. Re1 O-O
{ After Black's kingside castling, it's a good time to consider further plans. Here are some points to look at:  Playing our knight to e5 does not lead to much. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2nbp3/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne5  f6  works fine for Black, as  10.Qh5  Nf5  defends h7. At a later stage, Black might play ...Qc7 and stop the move Ne5 completely, as Black has too much control of the square.  We have one pawn break available, the move c4. This move should always be strongly considered if Black plays the move ...f6, which frequently happens. It is much more attractive in this case, as we open the position to attack the weakened soft spot e6. Conclusion: we want to be ready to play c4 at a favourable moment but shouldn't play it prematurely.  We need to organise our pieces. Our forces are directed towards the kingside, but there is nothing concrete yet. Have you thought about @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2nbp3/3p4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxh7+?  It doesn't work due to  9...Kxh7  10.Ng5+  Kg6!  , when Black's king is safe. I want more forces on this side of the board, trying to create weaknesses. I like the knight tour Nbd2-f1 as a first step. The knight may hop to g3 or e3 later.  Black frequently plays the move ...Qc7 on the next moves. It is a good idea to invest a tempo on the move h3 to mobilize the knight@@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nbd2
{ We start the knight tour to f1.   Starting with the move  9.h3  is also fine and will lead to the same positions.  We'll check two scenarios now: Black plays ...f6 or prefers to complete their piece setup first. }
9... f6
{ Black goes for ...f6 and hopes to create a full pawn center with ...e5 later. Our standard reply to ...f6 is the pawn break c4, so here we go. }
10. c4
{ An almost automatic response - if they play ...f6, go for c4!  Black could take on c4 now, but the resulting IQP position is better for White. The move ...f6 does not help at all, as it created a potentially weak pawn on e6 and made Black's king less secure.  Black should probably hold the tension now. }
10... Kh8
{ A slow move like this looks best. The king move can be useful in many scenarios to prevent a later Qc2 hitting h7 with a tempo.   As mentioned, Black should avoid  10...dxc4  11.Nxc4  , when our pieces get more active, and e6 is a more severe weakness than d4. }
11. a3
{ The final move and idea I want to point out. In some cases, I want to prepare the move b4 but also take away ...Nb4 ideas by Black.  One important point is that we want to keep the tension in the center and not play the move c4-c5 unless it nets some immediate gain. Let's assume Black plays a small waiting move now, like @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r1k/pp2n1pp/2nbpp2/3p4/2PP4/P2B1N2/1P1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bc7  .  Now  12.c5??  e5!  is a disaster!  Instead, we should play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r1k/ppb1n1pp/2n1pp2/3p4/2PP4/P2B1N2/1P1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.b4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r1k/ppb1n1pp/2n1pp2/3p4/2PP4/P2B1N2/1P1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nf1  , improving our position slowly and trying to provoke the move ...dxc4 to open the position. It's an interesting and complicated position for both sides, which is why the early 5...e6 line has attracted some players recently. }
*

