[White "D2) Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation Sidelines"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation 4...Nc6 5.c3 Qc7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ We develop our bishop to its most active square and stop ...Bf5 simultaneously. In most games, the next moves are  4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  when I suggest playing  6.h3  , again preventing Black's bishop development. This position is the starting point of the second Caro-Kann Chapter, the Exchange Variation main line.  In the current chapter, we will examine ways for Black to play differently. It is difficult to devise something entirely different, as developing the two knights to their natural squares makes a lot of sense. In many cases, Black might start a bit differently on the first moves but then plays both knight moves after all. }
4... Nc6
{ In most cases, Black starts with this knight move. It looks like a natural choice, as you can hardly imagine a scenario where developing it to d7, let alone a6, would make any sense. }
5. c3
{ It's important to play this move and avoid  5.Nf3  Bg4!  , when Black solves a key issue immediately. Black should work harder to get their bishop developed!  Now we have to consider different options for Black.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  is the main line by a mile. We play  6.h3  against it and stop Black's idea ...Bg4 in its tracks. The main line is discussed in a dedicated chapter. Black has some alternatives with independent value. Some might still transpose to the main line because a later ...Nf6 is a natural move.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qc7  is Black's most important alternative. They prevent Bf4 and hope to develop the c8-bishop later.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  looks a bit passive but has some points if Black plays correctly afterwards.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  prepares the fianchetto and the move ...Bf5, a common idea in the Exchange Caro-Kann. This move will often transpose to the main line after a later ...Nf6, but Black has some worse alternatives that we should check.   I also found some games with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  , when  6.dxe5  Nxe5  7.Nf3  leads to a better version of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.h3  e5  7.dxe5  Nxe5  8.Nf3  , an important part of the Caro-Kann main line chapter. It is a slightly better version because it is not clear yet that we need the move h3, while ...Nf6 will always be useful for Black. }
5... Qc7
{ Black's most popular alternative to the main line. Their idea is to wait for the knight to move and then pin it: @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  Bg4  and @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ne2  Bg4  are the lines they have in mind. }
6. h3
{ We play this move to prepare Nf3.   After  6.Nf3  Bg4!  Black manages to get their bishop developed easily.  Black has some moves now, but there are plenty of possible transpositions.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  looks very natural, and after  7.Nf3  transposes to the main line, examined in a separate chapter.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  leads to positions that we examine via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  . We have played the early move h3, but it will also be useful in these structures.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  is s common idea. I suggest  7.Nf3  here, which will transpose to the main line chapter, as Black's development ...Nf6, ...Bg7 and ...Bf5 is very natural. If you want to explore a different idea,  7.Ne2  is interesting here, too. White plans Bf4, gaining a tempo.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e5  is possible and leads to IQP play. We'll examine this move in a trainable line. }
6... e5
{ Black goes for a radical solution to get space for the pieces at the cost of playing with an Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. This line is a slightly worse version of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.h3  e5  , which we discuss in the main line Caro-Kann chapter. We'll see in a minute why it is slightly worse. }
7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. Bb5+
{ In the Caro-Kann main line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.h3  e5  7.dxe5  Nxe5  we play  8.Nf3  , emphasising development. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/5n2/3pn3/8/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Bxd7+  Qxd7  is unpromising - White has lost time with the bishop check, and Black is well developed.  The key difference to the line we are currently examing: Black has played ...Qc7 already, so after  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq2ppp/8/3pn3/8/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Bxd7+  Qxd7  they are a tempo down on the comparable situation in the main line. A tempo makes a huge difference in a wide-open position. }
8... Bd7
{ I was surprised to find some games with  8...Nc6  , which looks like a pawn blunder at first. White can take the d-pawn, but I wouldn't recommend it. Black gets a good compensation after  9.Qxd5  Nf6  10.Qd3  Bd7  11.Ne2  O-O-O  , which looks tricky to play for White.  After @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq2ppp/8/1B1pn3/8/2P4P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nc6  I suggest  9.Nf3  , preparing kingside castling. Black's IQP remains a good target and gives us better chances. }
9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Nf3
{ We need to catch up in development. We played the slow move h3 and moved our bishop three times! We traded this time loss for a structural advantage, the play against Black's IQP. }
10... Nxf3+
{ Black's usual choice at this point, but keeping the knight on the board looks reasonable, too.   After  10...Nc6  , a logical sequence is  11.O-O  Bd6  12.Re1+  Nge7  13.Be3  O-O  14.Nbd2  , when I prefer White slightly. Black has no substantial problems, but we have a clear target: trade minor pieces and put pressure on the IQP. }
11. Qxf3
{ We have a small but comfortable advantage. We want to play O-O and Rd1, putting pressure on the IQP.   If Black plays ...Bc5, we should consider Be3, offering additional trades. A sample line for this strategy is @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp1q1ppp/8/3p4/8/2P2Q1P/PP3PP1/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bc5  12.O-O  Ne7  12.Be3  , when each trade helps to make the IQP's weakness more pronounced. }
*

