5... Qc7
{ Black's most popular alternative to the main line. Their idea is to wait for the knight to move and then pin it: @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  Bg4  and @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ne2  Bg4  are the lines they have in mind. }
6. h3
{ We play this move to prepare Nf3.   After  6.Nf3  Bg4!  Black manages to get their bishop developed easily.  Black has some moves now, but there are plenty of possible transpositions.  A. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  looks very natural, and after  7.Nf3  transposes to the main line, examined in a separate chapter.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  leads to positions that we examine via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  . We have played the early move h3, but it will also be useful in these structures.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e5  is possible and leads to IQP play. We'll examine this move in a trainable line.  D. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  is interesting to study. The idea ...g6 is frequently seen, but the combination with the early ...Qc7 is not ideal. I suggest  7.Ne2!  here, deviating from our usual knight development to f3. }
6... g6
{ I think this specific combination of ...Qc7 and ...g6 does not work well. }
7. Ne2
{ This is the only case where I recommend developing the knight to e2, but I think it works very well here. The obvious idea is to gain a tempo on the queen with Bf4, which can prove very effective.   I want to mention that  7.Nf3  is not a mistake, of course. We'll likely transpose to a position out of the main line chapter, which would be fine - I believe @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppq1pp1p/2n3p1/3p4/3P4/2PB3P/PP3PP1/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ne2  to be better here, though. }
7... Bf5
{ The most popular move by far. Black develops the c8-bishop first to prepare ...Qd7 in response to Bf4.   After  7...Bg7  8.Bf4  they don't have a great square and  8...Qb6  9.Qb3  Qxb3  10.axb3  looks good for White. The open a-file and ideas like b3-b4 and Nd2-b3-c5 are ways to increase pressure on the queenside. }
8. Bf4
{ My general advice is to avoid the capture on f5 unless you see an immediate tactical gain or it is forced - we'll see an example of this case in a moment.  I suggest continuing with development first and gaining the tempo on the queen.  Now Black has two sensible queen moves. }
8... Qb6
{ We have reached a crucial point now. Our b-pawn is attacked - how to react? }
9. Bxf5
{ Yes, this time, we capture on f5. It's a case where the alternatives look bad. Our b-pawn was attacked, and we don't want to play a passive move to defend it. I suggest a more active approach. }
9... gxf5
{ Black can't play  9...Qxb2??  , as  10.Bd3  Qxa1  11.Qb3  traps the queen. We play O-O and Nd2 next, and it's over. }
10. Nd2
{ We don't need to spend time protecting the pawn.   A similar idea and just as strong is  10.O-O  , when Black can't take the pawn, either. }
10... Nf6
{ They can't grab on b2, which renders the whole operation a bit dubious. After  10...Qxb2?  11.Rb1  Qa3  12.Rxb7  is great for White - and we are not even a pawn down!  Note that @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp2pp1p/2n5/3p1p2/3P1B2/2P4P/Pq1NNPP1/1R1QK2R b Kkq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qxa2??  12.Ra1  Qb2  13.Nb3!  is even worse, as Black's queen is trapped! We threaten Bc1 and  13...Bh6  14.O-O  Bxf4  15.Nxf4  e6  16.Nd3  Qxc3  17.Rc1  is a fun line to show that there is no way out. }
11. O-O e6 12. c4
{ I like this straightforward move more than a slow approach. Computers are very happy with White after manoeuvres like Rc1-c2, Nc1-d3 and similar ideas, but going for the attack has a more human touch to me.   Black's path is narrow.  A. @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp3p1p/1qn1pn2/3p1p2/2PP1B2/7P/PP1NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nxd4?  13.Nc3  or the simpler @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp3p1p/1q2pn2/3p1p2/2Pn1B2/7P/PP1NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nxd4  Qxd4  14.Be3  is great for White. Black can't go pawn hunting with their king on e8.   B. @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp3p1p/1qn1pn2/3p1p2/2PP1B2/7P/PP1NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bg7?  13.c5!  Qd8  14.b4  is also horrific for Black.  14...Nxb4  15.Rb1  or @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp3pbp/2n1pn2/2Pp1p2/1P1P1B2/7P/P2NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 b kq b3 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...O-O  15.b5  is a quick attack on the queenside, and Black has no counterplay.  C. @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp3p1p/1qn1pn2/3p1p2/2PP1B2/7P/PP1NNPP1/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...dxc4!  is the only move.  13.Nxc4  Qa6  14.Rc1  Rd8  15.Ne5  is a logical sequence when Black is worse. They can't avoid Nxc6, destroying the pawn structure. After  15...Nxe5?  16.Bxe5  Bg7  17.Nf4  White is ready for Qf3 when threats on the queenside @@StartBracket@@Rc7@@EndBracket@@ and kingside @@StartBracket@@Qg3@@EndBracket@@ are combined. }
