[White "D3) Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation Main Line"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation Main Line"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. h3
{ White has a choice between  6.Bf4  and  6.h3  , the latter of which I suggest playing. I think both moves are of equal strength, but I feel that  6.h3  is simpler to handle and likely not as well prepared by Black. An additional benefit becomes more obvious once you examine Black's possible replies. I did this when I wrote Keep It Simple for Black, which made me aware of the  6.h3  line. Let's have an overview.   A.  6...e5  is the best move, in my opinion. I recommended it in KIS Black and still think Black should equalise with the best play. Still, this move is not the most popular in practice. Why? After  7.dxe5  Nxe5  Black needs to play an IQP position, which is a rare sight for Black in the Caro. Many opponents won't feel comfortable defending the IQP and avoid 6...e5 for this reason. I was also reluctant to recommend the move in KIS Black with the same reasoning, but I think it is objectively the best solution.So, you won't get 6...e5 that often in your games. I like it from White's point of view: it is easy to play and involves minimal risk, as you will see. The positions are similar to those in our repertoire, like the French Tarrasch with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  c5  Ngf3  Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  ,  also leading to an IQP.   B.  6...g6  is Black's most popular move. It serves two purposes: preparing Bg7 and, more importantly ...Bf5. Our move 6.h3 stopped the bishop's development, and Black insists on developing it to f5. I examined this option for KIS Black and concluded that I'd rather be White in this line, which now comes in handy for this course!   C.  6...e6  leads to a nice game for White but is examined in the Caro-Kann sidelines chapter via a different move order.   D.  6...Qc7  is a rare move with little independent value. After  7.Nf3  Black will decide between  7...e6  @@StartBracket@@leading to C and the sidelines chapter@@EndBracket@@ or  7...g6  when we get the same position type as in B, but with an early ...Qc7. You'll see that 6...g6 is more about understanding strategic features than concrete lines. }
