9. Qxd3
{ If you know my courses or videos, you know that I am a bishop pair fan and don't like to give up a bishop for a knight, in general. In this particular case, it was more important for White to speed up development than lose time to preserve the bishop. We also need to discuss some points about this specific IQP position. White has an iron grip on the blockade square d4. Black should never be able to advance the d-pawn to trade off the weakness. This is a result of the minor piece trade, as Black's knight has potential influence over d4, while our light-squared bishop was not part of the 'blockading team'.  Black has the pair of bishops, but it is not easy to activate the c8-bishop, as we control f5 and g4.  White has an effective setup that works well, more or less, regardless of Black's play. The basic idea is placing the bishop on d4 and moving the d2-knight to e3 via f1. This configuration keeps the blockade of d4 and exerts pressure on d5.  Black needs to ensure that we don't manage to trade minor pieces favourably. An important idea for Black is using the e4-square, as our pieces are more focused on dark-square control @@StartBracket@@d4, e3@@EndBracket@@.Let's see how these points work out in practice. Black now has a choice between the bishop moving to d6 or e7. Black is often scared about the possible pin Bg5 and opts for Be7, but I think this is unnecessarily cautious.My recommendation in KIS for Black is 9...Bd6, ignoring the pin idea. From White's perspective, it does not matter what bishop move Black plays, as I don't think we should go for the pin anyway. I will check both moves to show examples of how the game unfolds. }
9... Bd6 { The more active choice, not fearing the Bg5 pin. } 10. O-O O-O 11.
Be3
{ As mentioned before, I don't want to play for the pin with Bg5. Of course, it is not a mistake, but I want to aim for the central piece setup, often including Bd4. After  11.Bg5  Black's best move is  11...h6!  when White chooses between keeping the bishop with  12.Bh4  @@StartBracket@@far away from my suggested setup with Bd4@@EndBracket@@ or grabbing the pawn with  12.Bxf6  Qxf6  13.Qxd5  , when  13...Rd8  gives Black good play. I analysed these lines in KIS Black and concluded that Black is fine.The move 11.Be3, now my suggestion for White, is not mentioned in KIS Black, as I focused more on the direct attempts to pressure Black. Our strategy with White is a slow grind, trying to keep Black's pieces passive and making slight progress. I think that chances are equal, but White's job is quite easy, and it is not every Caro player's forte to defend IQP positions. There is a reason why 6...g6 is far more popular. }
11... Re8
{ This looks like a logical move. Black prepares ...Ne4, a resource not readily available in the ...Be7 lines. }
12. Nbd2
{ Now we get to an interesting moment. This position has occurred multiple times, and Black often played an attractive-looking, but imprecise move, the knight jumping to e4. We'll look at this move and the slower alternative  12...h6  , which is better. }
12... h6
{ This looks better than the knight jump, Black plays a useful move and might want to play ...Ne4 next. }
13. Rad1
{ A good move, directed against ...Ne4. Black does not have a particularly active move that they can play. I found an online Blitz game between two 2700 GMs, V.Artemiev-V.Keymer, which continued as follows:  13...Qc7  14.Rfe1  Be6?!  15.Bd4  Nd7  16.Nf1  Nc5  17.Bxc5  Bxc5  18.Ne3  ,  when White had a nice pull. A key idea is Nd4-f5 for White. Black bishops are quite ineffective here.It looks like the less obvious move  @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/ppq2pp1/3b1n1p/3p4/8/2PQBN1P/PP1N1PP1/3RR1K1 b - - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Bd7  is better when Black needs to understand that  15.Bd4  can be answered with  15...Nh5!  , which is not easy to see. After  16.Rxe8+  Rxe8  17.Be3  Nf6  18.Qd4  chances are balanced if Black keeps making the best moves.Black's chances in the 6...e5 line are fair; they should equalise with optimal play. I think it is a good line to go for. We risk very little and have a slightly easier job. This is supported by the stats, which favour White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "D3) Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation Main Line"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation 4...Nc6 5.c3 Nf6 6.h3 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. h3 g6
{ More often than not, Black opts for 6...g6 in the main line. I think that many Caro-Kann players do not like playing with an IQP after 6...e5 and prefer this alternative. Black's setup has two ideas:  Playing ...Bf5 to trade the bishop. How should we answer ...Bf5? We can take the bishop and create a doubled pawn or allow Black to trade on d3.I suggest a clear guideline: We don't take on f5, unless it is motivated by a concrete tactic or we reach a particularly favourable scenario. This is rare, but we'll see two cases that apply. I will analyse the motivation behind my advice when ...Bf5 is on the board after 7.Nf3 Bf5, when I suggest to castle kingside.    Complete the fianchetto and castle kingside. Understanding that the fianchetto is NOT an ideal setup for Black is crucial. The bishop is not well-placed on g7, as it bites on the d4+c3 pawn chain. It is also missing as a participant in a possible queenside play for Black. Black would definitely prefer a setup with ...e6 and ...Bd6 or ...Be7.A further drawback of ...g6 is weakening the kingside dark squares. I understand that this sounds far-fetched, but you'll agree once you have studied this chapter till the end. Let's continue with our next, very natural move. }
7. Nf3
{ We continue with the most natural move and prepare kingside castling. It's also possible to play  7.Bf4  here, but there is no particular benefit in playing the bishop to f4 early. We are not concerned about Black playing ...Qc7, for example. With the more natural  7.Nf3  ,  we intend to complete a piece setup that we use a standard in the Caro-Kann Exchange: Bd3, Nf3, h3, O-O and Re1 is a common sight across many lines.What now for Black? They have two points on the agenda: completing castling and playing ...Bf5. You meet all kinds of move orders that combine the two. It will usually lead to the same positions, as our moves are the same in all cases. We castle and play Re1 next. I decided to organise the lines as follows:   A.  7...Bf5  is our main line and covers all situations that feature the move ...Bf5.   B.  7...Bg7  is just as popular but will usually include a later ...Bf5, too. I will use the 7...Bg7 move order to examine if Black has any ideas without ...Bf5 and point out the transpositions to 7...Bf5.   C.  7...Qc7  is a third option that will also likely transpose to A, but it has some interesting move-order subtleties worth seeing. The move 7...Qc7 is very rare in this particular position, but the position with an early combination of ...g6 and ...Qc7 more regularly occurs via different move orders. Examples are  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Qc7  6.h3  Nf6  7.Nf3  g6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.h3  Qc7  7.Nf3  g6  ,  both of which are more frequently seen.It doesn't sound straightforward, but you'll see that we always play the same moves. We castle and play Re1 next. }
7... Qc7
{ As mentioned before, this position may occur via different move orders. More common are cases where Black started with ...Qc7 and then decided to go for ...g6 next. }
8. O-O
{ Our normal move. This moment is, somewhat surprisingly, an interesting one. If Black wants to play ...Bf5, they have to do it now, or they won't manage under good circumstances. I'll demonstrate this point by splitting between 8...Bf5 and 8...Bg7 now and check the differences. }
8... Bg7 { Black continues with kingside development and delays ...Bf5. } 9.
Re1
{ Now Black should play  9...O-O  and transpose to a position that we examine via the move order  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Re1  Qc7  , when  10.Ne5  is a strong move and leads to a comfortable game for us. It is still much better than the blunder 9... Bf5?. }
9... Bf5
{ This move has been played a lot, and White often missed the direct refutation. }
10. Bxf5
{ One of the cases where you must take on f5: it's good for concrete reasons, as we will see. }
10... gxf5 11. Nh4
{ That's the problem for Black! they lose the f-pawn as  11...e6  12.Nxf5  or @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppq1ppbp/2n2n2/3p1p2/3P3N/2P4P/PP3PP1/RNBQR1K1 b kq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qd7  12.Qf3  is no remedy. }
11... Qd7 { Trying to keep the pawn, but we can add further pressure on f5. }
12. Qf3
{ And it's over - we win the pawn and also have an overwhelming position on top. }
*

