7... Qc7
{ As mentioned before, this position may occur via different move orders. More common are cases where Black started with ...Qc7 and then decided to go for ...g6 next. }
8. O-O
{ Our normal move. This moment is, somewhat surprisingly, an interesting one. If Black wants to play ...Bf5, they have to do it now, or they won't manage under good circumstances. I'll demonstrate this point by splitting between 8...Bf5 and 8...Bg7 now and check the differences. }
8... Bf5 { Black goes for the generally desirable bishop trade. } 9. Re1
{ I suggest continuing with our standard play. In this particular position, there are some interesting ways to deviate, but I don't want to complicate matters for, as I see it, little benefit. Interesting alternatives are:   A.  9.Bxf5  gxf5  10.c4  ,  opening the position. I don't think this is better than 9. Re1, but it leads to a different, more open game.   B.  9.Ne1!?  is a fun move. White knows that the knight will be well positioned on d3 @@StartBracket@@we'll talk about this later on when discussing 7...Bf5 in detail@@EndBracket@@ and hopes for a trade on d3. If Black does not take, the idea is to capture on f5 and go for Nd3 and Bf4 later. }
9... Bxd3
{ Why is this move awarded with an exclam, isn't it a perfectly normal choice? Yes, but  9...Bg7?  is to be avoided due to  10.Bxf5  gxf5  11.Nh4!  when we are more or less winning. This line is discussed via the  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppq1pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bg7  9.Re1  Bf5?  move order. }
10. Qxd3
{ And we reach positions that usually occur via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bf5  8.O-O  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  Qc7  10.Re1  - please see this move order for details. }
