[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation 4...Nc6 5.c3 Nf6 6.h3 g6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. h3 g6
{ More often than not, Black opts for 6...g6 in the main line. I think that many Caro-Kann players do not like playing with an IQP after 6...e5 and prefer this alternative. Black's setup has two ideas:  Playing ...Bf5 to trade the bishop. How should we answer ...Bf5? We can take the bishop and create a doubled pawn or allow Black to trade on d3.I suggest a clear guideline: We don't take on f5, unless it is motivated by a concrete tactic or we reach a particularly favourable scenario. This is rare, but we'll see two cases that apply. I will analyse the motivation behind my advice when ...Bf5 is on the board after 7.Nf3 Bf5, when I suggest to castle kingside.    Complete the fianchetto and castle kingside. Understanding that the fianchetto is NOT an ideal setup for Black is crucial. The bishop is not well-placed on g7, as it bites on the d4+c3 pawn chain. It is also missing as a participant in a possible queenside play for Black. Black would definitely prefer a setup with ...e6 and ...Bd6 or ...Be7.A further drawback of ...g6 is weakening the kingside dark squares. I understand that this sounds far-fetched, but you'll agree once you have studied this chapter till the end. Let's continue with our next, very natural move. }
7. Nf3
{ We continue with the most natural move and prepare kingside castling. It's also possible to play  7.Bf4  here, but there is no particular benefit in playing the bishop to f4 early. We are not concerned about Black playing ...Qc7, for example. With the more natural  7.Nf3  ,  we intend to complete a piece setup that we use a standard in the Caro-Kann Exchange: Bd3, Nf3, h3, O-O and Re1 is a common sight across many lines.What now for Black? They have two points on the agenda: completing castling and playing ...Bf5. You meet all kinds of move orders that combine the two. It will usually lead to the same positions, as our moves are the same in all cases. We castle and play Re1 next. I decided to organise the lines as follows:   A.  7...Bf5  is our main line and covers all situations that feature the move ...Bf5.   B.  7...Bg7  is just as popular but will usually include a later ...Bf5, too. I will use the 7...Bg7 move order to examine if Black has any ideas without ...Bf5 and point out the transpositions to 7...Bf5.   C.  7...Qc7  is a third option that will also likely transpose to A, but it has some interesting move-order subtleties worth seeing. The move 7...Qc7 is very rare in this particular position, but the position with an early combination of ...g6 and ...Qc7 more regularly occurs via different move orders. Examples are  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Qc7  6.h3  Nf6  7.Nf3  g6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.h3  Qc7  7.Nf3  g6  ,  both of which are more frequently seen.It doesn't sound straightforward, but you'll see that we always play the same moves. We castle and play Re1 next. }
7... Bf5
{ The main purpose of ...g6, in my mind, is preparing this move. Black wants to trade the bishop. }
8. O-O
{ I already mentioned that I advise not to capture on f5. The question 'to take or not to take' can occur in various versions. We have the very early situation here @@StartBracket@@Black has not even played ...Bg7@@EndBracket@@ or at the later stages of the kingside development. The capture is the most unattractive option right here when Black might even play a quick ...Rg8 ...e6, and ...Bd6 to take over the initiative. At a later stage, the capture gets a bit more compelling, but I still advise against it to make our job easier unless there is a concrete idea.   We'll now consider two scenarios: Black takes on d3, or Black keeps the tension with  8...Bg7  . I also found some online games that featured the move  8...e6?!  , when  9.Bb5!  is a good reply. Black's f5-bishop is running low on squares, and Ne5/Qa4 ideas are dangerous. }
8... Bg7 { Black avoids the capture and continues their kingside development. }
9. Re1
{ Completing our standard setup. Now Black again decides between taking on d3 and keeping the tension. If they take, we'll transpose into lines that I cover via 8...Bxd3, the earlier capture. }
9... O-O
{ The alternatives are  9...Bxd3  ,  leading to 8...Bxd3 lines, or  9...Qc7?  , a blunder that we can punish with  10.Bxf5!  gxf5  11.Nh4!  ,  as covered via the move order  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7  8.O-O  Bg7  9.Re1  Bf5?  10.Bxf5!  , leading to the same disaster.   After  9...O-O  ,  we reach an interesting position which allows a wide range of moves. My choice is not the most obvious but will pose a likely unexpected challenge. In practice, Black usually does not react properly to the next move. }
10. Bf1
{ I like this surprising move. We argue that Black missed their chance to trade bishops, so we take away this option.   Before I continue, a word about alternatives. The main one I see is  10.Bf4  , which is a more obvious move. I was not too fond of the reply  10...Bxd3  11.Qxd3  Qb6  ,  when defending the b-pawn is a bit awkward. This is still viable for White, but I found the bishop retreat to f1 more challenging for Black to handle. In practice, Black often goes wrong quickly.So, what's the idea of our move?   A. If Black continues with a slow move @@StartBracket@@  10...Rc8  ,  10...a6  @@EndBracket@@,  we play Bf4 and Nbd2 to complete our development most actively. This type of position is comfortable for White, as we will see.   B. Black's most popular reply in practice is  10...Ne4?!  ,  which is surprisingly difficult for Black to handle. We get a nice advantage against it, as the knight is ultimately unstable on e4.   C. It looks like Black's best is  10...Qc7  ,  as the engines point out. This is rarely played, though, and I still have an interesting suggestion against the move. It's fascinating that we currently have most pieces on the first rank. The key point is that Black has developed the pieces, but most are not effectively placed. The g7-bishop is biting on d4, and the other one of f5 is pointing into thin air. The c6-knight is looking at protected squares. We'll check 10...Rc8, 10...Qc7 and 10...Ne4 now. }
10... Rc8
{ Black frequently reacts with a routine move like this one. It allows our most active piece setup. }
11. Bf4 a6
{ This is the most popular move in online games. They also sometimes start with 10...a6 and play ...Rc8 next. }
12. Nbd2
{ We have completed our development; Somewhat surprisingly, it is already difficult for Black to play this position. Many ideas fail quite miserably.   A.  12...b5?  is awful due to  13.a4  , when Black's queenside collapses.  13...Qb6  14.axb5  axb5  15.Qb3  b4  16.Ra6  is one good way to exploit the untimely advance.   B.  12...Ne4  13.Nxe4  Bxe4  14.Nd2  Bf5  15.Nb3  is great for White, as we have Nc5 lined up. We have strong pressure on Black's queenside.   C. The comp wants to wait with a move like  12...Re8  , when I like  13.Ne5  , to play  13...Nxe5  14.dxe5!  ,  when we clear the great d4-square for our knight. }
*

