{ I like this surprising move. We argue that Black missed their chance to trade bishops, so we take away this option.   Before I continue, a word about alternatives. The main one I see is  10.Bf4  , which is a more obvious move. I was not too fond of the reply  10...Bxd3  11.Qxd3  Qb6  ,  when defending the b-pawn is a bit awkward. This is still viable for White, but I found the bishop retreat to f1 more challenging for Black to handle. In practice, Black often goes wrong quickly.So, what's the idea of our move?   A. If Black continues with a slow move @@StartBracket@@  10...Rc8  ,  10...a6  @@EndBracket@@,  we play Bf4 and Nbd2 to complete our development most actively. This type of position is comfortable for White, as we will see.   B. Black's most popular reply in practice is  10...Ne4?!  ,  which is surprisingly difficult for Black to handle. We get a nice advantage against it, as the knight is ultimately unstable on e4.   C. It looks like Black's best is  10...Qc7  ,  as the engines point out. This is rarely played, though, and I still have an interesting suggestion against the move. It's fascinating that we currently have most pieces on the first rank. The key point is that Black has developed the pieces, but most are not effectively placed. The g7-bishop is biting on d4, and the other one of f5 is pointing into thin air. The c6-knight is looking at protected squares. We'll check 10...Rc8, 10...Qc7 and 10...Ne4 now. }
10... Qc7
{ A rarely played move, but it looks like the best choice. Black keeps an eye on the f4-square and prevents Bf4. }
11. Be3
{ We can't go to f4, so we settle for e3 instead. This move looks innocuous, but a cunning idea is hidden. We want to play Qc1 and Bf4 to get to f4 anyway!   This idea is so annoying for Black that the comp now suggests  11...h6  to prepare ...g5 as an antidote. I doubt that a human would play this way @@StartBracket@@ I found one game out of 60 where it happened@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Rfe8
{ Black's most popular move here. As mentioned, the engine wants to play  11...h6  here. I see two good replies:   A.  12.Qc1  g5  13.h4  g4  14.Bf4  , when I prefer White. The engine only gives White a minimal advantage, but I am happy to have provoked Black's kingside moves.   B.  12.Nbd2  is a non-forcing idea. If Black goes for ...g5, playing Rc1 and c4 can open the centre. }
12. Qc1
{ We are now ready to play Bf4 and get our bishop to a good square with tempo. The resulting positions may resemble the lines after 10...Rc8, when we are in good shape. The engine wants to play ...e5 now, but  12...e5  13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Rxe5  15.Nd2  is a typical, small advantage against the IQP. }
