{ The main purpose of ...g6, in my mind, is preparing this move. Black wants to trade the bishop. }
8. O-O
{ I already mentioned that I advise not to capture on f5. The question 'to take or not to take' can occur in various versions. We have the very early situation here @@StartBracket@@Black has not even played ...Bg7@@EndBracket@@ or at the later stages of the kingside development. The capture is the most unattractive option right here when Black might even play a quick ...Rg8 ...e6, and ...Bd6 to take over the initiative. At a later stage, the capture gets a bit more compelling, but I still advise against it to make our job easier unless there is a concrete idea.   We'll now consider two scenarios: Black takes on d3, or Black keeps the tension with  8...Bg7  . I also found some online games that featured the move  8...e6?!  , when  9.Bb5!  is a good reply. Black's f5-bishop is running low on squares, and Ne5/Qa4 ideas are dangerous. }
8... Bxd3 { Black goes for the trade of bishops. } 9. Qxd3
{ Now Black's almost automatic move is  9...Bg7  ,  when we develop our bishop to f4. Black may also play  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PQ1N1P/PP3PP1/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  ,  which requires a different way to develop our bishop, as the more active f4-square is not available.I will focus on 9...Qc7 now, as it makes our job a bit harder, and the arising position and strategy are the same as after the bishop move. }
9... Bg7
{ This move is far more popular than  9...Qc7  ,  but it makes our job a bit easier as we manage Bf4 without any problems. }
10. Bf4 O-O 11. Nbd2
{ Compared to the line @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PQ1N1P/PP3PP1/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  10.Re1  Bg7  11.Be3  O-O  12.Nbd2  ,  we have accomplished the more active bishop post on f4. As the position is less based on concrete move sequences than plans and strategy, I am stopping the trainable here and suggest studying the detailed strategy discussion for the 9...Qc7 line. }
