[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "D3) Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation Main Line"]
[Black "Caro-Kann – Exchange Variation 4...Nc6 5.c3 Nf6 6.h3 g6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. h3 g6
{ More often than not, Black opts for 6...g6 in the main line. I think that many Caro-Kann players do not like playing with an IQP after 6...e5 and prefer this alternative. Black's setup has two ideas:  Playing ...Bf5 to trade the bishop. How should we answer ...Bf5? We can take the bishop and create a doubled pawn or allow Black to trade on d3.I suggest a clear guideline: We don't take on f5, unless it is motivated by a concrete tactic or we reach a particularly favourable scenario. This is rare, but we'll see two cases that apply. I will analyse the motivation behind my advice when ...Bf5 is on the board after 7.Nf3 Bf5, when I suggest to castle kingside.    Complete the fianchetto and castle kingside. Understanding that the fianchetto is NOT an ideal setup for Black is crucial. The bishop is not well-placed on g7, as it bites on the d4+c3 pawn chain. It is also missing as a participant in a possible queenside play for Black. Black would definitely prefer a setup with ...e6 and ...Bd6 or ...Be7.A further drawback of ...g6 is weakening the kingside dark squares. I understand that this sounds far-fetched, but you'll agree once you have studied this chapter till the end. Let's continue with our next, very natural move. }
7. Nf3
{ We continue with the most natural move and prepare kingside castling. It's also possible to play  7.Bf4  here, but there is no particular benefit in playing the bishop to f4 early. We are not concerned about Black playing ...Qc7, for example. With the more natural  7.Nf3  ,  we intend to complete a piece setup that we use a standard in the Caro-Kann Exchange: Bd3, Nf3, h3, O-O and Re1 is a common sight across many lines.What now for Black? They have two points on the agenda: completing castling and playing ...Bf5. You meet all kinds of move orders that combine the two. It will usually lead to the same positions, as our moves are the same in all cases. We castle and play Re1 next. I decided to organise the lines as follows:   A.  7...Bf5  is our main line and covers all situations that feature the move ...Bf5.   B.  7...Bg7  is just as popular but will usually include a later ...Bf5, too. I will use the 7...Bg7 move order to examine if Black has any ideas without ...Bf5 and point out the transpositions to 7...Bf5.   C.  7...Qc7  is a third option that will also likely transpose to A, but it has some interesting move-order subtleties worth seeing. The move 7...Qc7 is very rare in this particular position, but the position with an early combination of ...g6 and ...Qc7 more regularly occurs via different move orders. Examples are  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Qc7  6.h3  Nf6  7.Nf3  g6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.h3  Qc7  7.Nf3  g6  ,  both of which are more frequently seen.It doesn't sound straightforward, but you'll see that we always play the same moves. We castle and play Re1 next. }
7... Bf5
{ The main purpose of ...g6, in my mind, is preparing this move. Black wants to trade the bishop. }
8. O-O
{ I already mentioned that I advise not to capture on f5. The question 'to take or not to take' can occur in various versions. We have the very early situation here @@StartBracket@@Black has not even played ...Bg7@@EndBracket@@ or at the later stages of the kingside development. The capture is the most unattractive option right here when Black might even play a quick ...Rg8 ...e6, and ...Bd6 to take over the initiative. At a later stage, the capture gets a bit more compelling, but I still advise against it to make our job easier unless there is a concrete idea.   We'll now consider two scenarios: Black takes on d3, or Black keeps the tension with  8...Bg7  . I also found some online games that featured the move  8...e6?!  , when  9.Bb5!  is a good reply. Black's f5-bishop is running low on squares, and Ne5/Qa4 ideas are dangerous. }
8... Bxd3 { Black goes for the trade of bishops. } 9. Qxd3
{ Now Black's almost automatic move is  9...Bg7  ,  when we develop our bishop to f4. Black may also play  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PQ1N1P/PP3PP1/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  ,  which requires a different way to develop our bishop, as the more active f4-square is not available.I will focus on 9...Qc7 now, as it makes our job a bit harder, and the arising position and strategy are the same as after the bishop move. }
9... Qc7
{ Black stops our development option Bf4. This move is fairly rare at this point, but you can always reach these positions if Black plays Qc7 earlier and then opts for ...Bf5. A possible sequence covered in the current chapter is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7  8.O-O  Bf5  9.Re1  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  ,  which leads to the same scenario.How do we play now? A good way to go is to play a setup with Re1, Be3, and Nbd2. Let's put these moves on the board and discuss the strategy once these initial steps are completed. }
10. Re1
{ It's no mistake to start with  10.Be3  ,  of course. I go for Re1 first, as we usually play this move first in other lines. }
10... Bg7 11. Be3
{ It looks more active to play  11.Bg5  , but  11...Ne4  is a good reply. }
11... O-O 12. Nbd2
{ We have developed the minor pieces and connected rooks, a good moment to take stock. What is the strategy here? Here are some points to consider.It is crucial to understand that Black has no clear active idea. There are two possible ways for our opponent to change the pawn structure: Playing for ...e5. This is tough to realise and not that attractive, to begin with. Black would create an IQP that is likely going to be weak. The minority attack, based on ...b5. This is a far more common and popular idea but usually quite dubious in this particular version of the Carlsbad pawn structure.The key issue is Black's bishop on g7, which does not support the queenside play and fails to cover the c5-square. If you would modify the current position, put Black's pawn back on g7 and set up ...e6 and ...Bd6, Black would be in excellent shape. Black controls e5 and c5 and has the bishop ideally placed to support b5-b4 and cover c5.In the current configuration, the move ...b5 gives us an excellent square for our knight @@StartBracket@@Nb3-c5@@EndBracket@@. You also commonly see that b4 answers Black's ...b5 if White installs the knight on c5. In such a case, the technically backward pawn on c3 would not matter compared to the monster knight on c5.Black's lack of clear ideas is key; it allows us to make small, incremental progress in the center and on the kingside.Some steps we can take:  Playing g3&Bf4 to activate our bishop and strengthen control of e5.  We can consider h4-h5 at a later stage. This attack could become dangerous quickly if the f6-knight had to leave its post.  It would be excellent to manoeuvre our d2-knight to d3, its ideal square. On d3, it would look at all crucial squares: e5, c5, b4 and b2. It is active and defending simultaneously.  Doubling on the e-file is an idea. One rook is often well-placed on e2 to cover b2.  Trading bishops can be a good idea. This could happen in a sequence like g3, Be3-f4 first, later Ne5/ ...Nxe5/ Bxe5, when our bishop arrives on e5. With more minor pieces traded, an attack based on h4-h5 becomes more likely and dangerous.This position and overall type of position is not something to learn on a move-by-move basis. Therefore I think it is best to continue with some possible lines to see the points above in action.   A.  12...a6  signals the intention to play for ...b5. This often backfires, as mentioned.  13.Nb3  @@StartBracket@@or @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1ppbp/p1n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PQBN1P/PP1N1PP1/R3R1K1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.g3  , but I like to connect the knight to the sensitive c5-square@@EndBracket@@. Now let's look at some options.   A1. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1ppbp/p1n2np1/3p4/3P4/1NPQBN1P/PP3PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...b5?  is a mistake due to  14.Nc5  Nd7  15.b4  , when our knight is great on c5 and can hardly be taken.   A2. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1ppbp/p1n2np1/3p4/3P4/1NPQBN1P/PP3PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nd7  covers c5 but allows  14.Qd2  Rfe8  15.Bf4  Qd8  16.Re2  a5  17.Rae1  , when we are ready for Nc1-d3 for a dream formation. We have a grip on the dark squares and may play h4-h5 soon. If Black moves the knight back to f6, we may jump to c5.   A3. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1pq1ppbp/p1n2np1/3p4/3P4/1NPQBN1P/PP3PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Ne4  14.Ng5  Nxg5  15.Bxg5  Rfe8  16.Re2  also looks good. Black is getting nowhere on the queenside, and we shift forces to the center and kingside. h4-h5 is the idea. I am generally happy to see Black playing for a minority attack here, as it often creates weaknesses. The move ...a6 is no problem for Black, but it rarely serves to prepare ...b5 in a good way.   B. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/ppq1ppbp/2n2np1/3p4/3P4/2PQBN1P/PP1N1PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 6 12@@EndFEN@@  12...e6  is more of a waiting move. Black should probably play such a strategy.  13.g3  Rfe8  14.Bf4  Qb6  15.a3  Rac8  is an example of such an approach. It could continue with  16.Kg2  a6  17.g4  Nd7  18.Bg3  , when we have gained some ground on the kingside. I feel that this type of position is easier to play for White. I see chances on the kingside in the long term, while Black can easily go wrong with misguided queenside initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "E1) Scandinavian – Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "Scandinavian – Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ Hello and welcome to our section on the Scandinavian Defense.  The Scandinavian enjoys considerable popularity, particularly if you examine stats for the amateur level or for online play. Therefore, we must devote some effort to studying how to fight the various branches of the Scandi. }
2. exd5
{ A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Qa5  . The most popular and important line of the Scandi features the queen move to a5. White has no problem gaining an advantage, but we need to be precise and play aggressively. We play a setup based on Ne5 and Bc4, often connected with an attack on the kingside. My recommendation is unchanged from the first edition; there are minor tweaks. Black's problems in these lines are well-known and are unlikely to be fixed. This is why the ...Qa5 Scandi is extinct on the professional level.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Qd6  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qd8  . Black may retreat the queen to d6 or d8. I devoted one chapter to these options. Compared to the first edition, there are several changes and improvements. It looks like Black has to accept a slightly worse and more passive position @@StartBracket@@the main line of ...Qd8@@EndBracket@@ or play more ambitiously and risk getting blown off the board. This is particularly true for the ...Qd6 complex, which features several lines that look difficult for Black.   C. Scandi Sidelines. The sidelines chapters could have been coined Scandinavian with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  , as there are no other reasonable sidelines. I suggest the same antidote as in the first edition, as the theoretical verdict is unchanged. White has a comfortable, small advantage @@StartBracket@@or more@@EndBracket@@.  A general observation about the ...Qxd5 chapters: if you want to fight for an advantage against the Scandi, it is crucial to play aggressively and study some sharper lines, as presented in the chapters. Black hopes the opponent plays 'on general grounds' and avoids a duel in sharp lines. Avoid this mistake - playing the aggressive lines suggested here is fun and will yield good results. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "E2) Scandinavian – 3...Qa5"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 3...Qa5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the traditional main line, but it is not as popular anymore, as Black players began to appreciate that the queen is a bit safer on d8 and that there is little tangible benefit in having the queen on a5. }
4. d4
{ A natural and strong move. We are now ready to develop all minor pieces and control the center well.  Sounds excellent - what does Black have? And what is our opponent's idea? In almost all cases, Black has one particular setup in mind: Develop the knight to f6, Develop the bishop to f5 or g4, if possible, Play the pawn to c6, which gives the queen some other retreat squares.   Black has various move orders that may lead to the same positions. The most popular move to start with is @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , which will be the move order we focus on.  Instead, @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  will often transpose to lines we'll examine via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  .  Black can try to develop the bishop earlier, but @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5?!  is a dubious move order. We could angle for a transposition to the main lines with  5.Nf3  , but @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q4b2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qf3  looks even stronger. We intend to answer  5...Nc6  with  6.Bb5  . White has a nice advantage in this line, but don't worry if you forget this detail and play the routine knight move - the main lines are also comfortable for White.   Does Black have anything entirely different? There is the rare move @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e5?  , which opens the position while being severely behind in development. The natural reply  5.Nf3  gives White a large advantage already when  5...Bg4  is the most interesting reply for Black. In the first edition, I analysed the complications after  6.Bc4  quite extensively, but Black's line is too scarce to merit this effort. A simpler solution is @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/ppp2ppp/8/q3p3/3P2b1/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  to break the pin when White is much better by simple means. The sample line  6...Nc6  7.O-O  O-O-O  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.Bxg4+  shows Black's problems. }
4... c6
{ Black starts with 4...c6 and delays the natural move ...Nf6. This move order has very little independent significance, though. In most cases, Black will play ...Nf6 soon to transpose to lines usually reached via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  - let's check possible deviations. }
5. Nf3
{ Just as after 4...Nf6, we start with the knight development to f3. As mentioned, there are various ways to transpose to the main lines of this chapter. Here are three options:   A.  5...Nf6  6.Bc4  is the quickest way to transpose.   B.  5...Bg4  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  Nf6  8.Bd2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  c6  8.Bd2  , giving White a pleasant edge.   C.  5...Bg4  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  c6  9.h4  is examined via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  c6  9.h4  , leading to a strong attack.  This leaves the move 5...Bf5, which requires a precise response. }
5... Bf5
{ A rare move order, but we now need to decide if we want to start with  6.Ne5  or  6.Bc4  - both moves are frequently part of our setup. Which one is best? }
6. Ne5
{ The knight jump is the best way to stay within our repertoire.   Starting with  6.Bc4  is less precise, as  6...Nd7  stops our aggressive intentions - Black controls e5 now.   Now, after  6.Ne5  , we immediately prepare to attack the bishop with g2-g4. Now, after the natural continuation  6...Nf6  7.Bc4  , the game would transpose into our repertoire's main line that usually starts with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  6.Bc4  Bf5  7.Ne5  , giving White good chances. Let's check if Black has alternatives to this transposition. }
6... Nd7
{ Black challenges our knight, but we have an excellent reply.   An even worse alternative for Black would be  6...e6?  , when  7.g4  Bg6  8.h4  is close to decisive already. White has a huge attack and will often win material, as the sample line  8...Nd7  9.h5  Be4  10.Nc4  shows. }
7. Nc4 { A powerful move. We attack the queen and win a crucial tempo. } 7...
Qd8
{ The safest square for her majesty.   The alternative  7...Qc7  8.Qf3  e6  9.Bf4  is dreadful for Black, too. }
8. d5
{ A strong move! It makes sure that the position opens up as quickly as possible. We are ahead in development, and Black's pieces are unfortunately placed.   White has good, aggressive alternatives in  8.g4  or  8.h4  , but advancing the d-pawn is the strongest. }
8... Ngf6 9. dxc6 bxc6 10. Qf3
{ A crucial point. We have a double attack on the bishop and the c-pawn. Now Black can't grab on c2 - this pawn is poisoned! }
10... Bxc2
{ Let's check why this fails.   Black has to play something sad like  10...e6  11.Qxc6  instead, accepting the pawn loss. They can't play  11...Bxc2?  due to  12.Nb5  , with a huge check on d6 looming. }
11. Qe2 { Attacking the unlucky bishop and setting up something else... } 11...
Bg6 12. Nd6#
{ I always want to have at least one checkmate in a trainable line - here it is! Chess is fun!   To summarise: the move order @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  will mostly transpose to lines that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  - attempts to deviate are at least risky, usually even downright bad. }
*

