[White "E2) Scandinavian – 3...Qa5"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 3...Qa5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the traditional main line, but it is not as popular anymore, as Black players began to appreciate that the queen is a bit safer on d8 and that there is little tangible benefit in having the queen on a5. }
4. d4
{ A natural and strong move. We are now ready to develop all minor pieces and control the center well.  Sounds excellent - what does Black have? And what is our opponent's idea? In almost all cases, Black has one particular setup in mind: Develop the knight to f6, Develop the bishop to f5 or g4, if possible, Play the pawn to c6, which gives the queen some other retreat squares.   Black has various move orders that may lead to the same positions. The most popular move to start with is @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , which will be the move order we focus on.  Instead, @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  will often transpose to lines we'll examine via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  .  Black can try to develop the bishop earlier, but @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5?!  is a dubious move order. We could angle for a transposition to the main lines with  5.Nf3  , but @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q4b2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qf3  looks even stronger. We intend to answer  5...Nc6  with  6.Bb5  . White has a nice advantage in this line, but don't worry if you forget this detail and play the routine knight move - the main lines are also comfortable for White.   Does Black have anything entirely different? There is the rare move @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e5?  , which opens the position while being severely behind in development. The natural reply  5.Nf3  gives White a large advantage already when  5...Bg4  is the most interesting reply for Black. In the first edition, I analysed the complications after  6.Bc4  quite extensively, but Black's line is too scarce to merit this effort. A simpler solution is @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/ppp2ppp/8/q3p3/3P2b1/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  to break the pin when White is much better by simple means. The sample line  6...Nc6  7.O-O  O-O-O  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.Bxg4+  shows Black's problems. }
4... Nf6 { By far Black's most popular and natural move. } 5. Nf3
{ 'Develop the knights before the bishops' is an old rule, often taught to players that make their first steps in learning opening play. Here it applies, too. Our knight is developed to its most active square, while we do not commit our bishops just yet. We often combine the moves Nf3 and Bc4 in the current chapter but never start with the bishop move.   Now we need to consider different options for Black:  A. They can play  5...c6  , staying flexible about the development of the c8-bishop. This move is the most popular on the master level.   B. Develop the bishop immediately with  5...Bf5  . This will often transpose to lines we examine via A.   C. Black pins our knight with  5...Bg4  . This move is prevalent in online chess and at the club/amateur level. White is much better after  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  , starting an immediate attack.   D. While lines A-C are somewhat similar and sometimes transpose to one another, the fourth option  5...Nc6?  is entirely different. The move is a mistake but requires precision to punish effectively. }
5... Bg4
{ This early bishop sortie is tremendously popular but very dubious. Let's see how to exploit this premature pin. As always, we need to play aggressively to punish Black. }
6. h3
{ 'Give me the bishop pair or allow a kingside attack... what's your choice?' }
6... Bh5
{ Black's most interesting continuation to check.   What are the alternatives?  A.  6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  is excellent for White. We have the bishop pair without having made any concessions. The way to go is Bd2, O-O-O and advancing on the kingside - what does Black have?   B.  6...Qh5??  looks fun for Black, but...  7.hxg4!  Qxh1  8.Ne2!  is a great concept. Black has no way to stop 9.Ng3, winning the queen! }
7. g4 { As usual, White needs to act quickly to exploit Black's play. } 7...
Bg6 8. Ne5
{ This is already very critical for Black. One misstep might now lead to a quick defeat, as the bishop is threatened due to h3-h4-h5. Our secondary idea is Nc4, attacking Black's queen. }
8... Nbd7
{ This move is played most often, challenging our knight.   Black can only choose between bad and worse, as the alternatives give White some leeway about how to exploit the deficits of Black's position.  A.  8...c6  9.h4  Be4  10.Nc4  Qd8  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.Qd3  Nf6  13.g5  is terrible for Black.   B.  8...e6  9.h4  Bb4  10.Bd2  Nbd7  11.Nxd7  Kxd7  12.h5  is a disaster, too.   As mentioned, these are two sample lines to illustrate Black's trouble. White also has some alternatives against these two moves that are strong. }
9. Nc4 { Black's queen is dangerously low on squares. } 9... Qa6
{ The only move, as  9...Qb4  is answered by  10.a3  and it's curtains. } 10.
Bf4
{ Probably the most powerful move, threatening Nd6+ to win the queen.   White has strong alternatives in  10.Qf3  and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pppnpppp/q4nb1/8/2NP2P1/2N4P/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne3  , though. }
10... Qe6+
{ There is no other defence against our threat, but 10... Qe6+ doesn't save Black either. }
11. Ne3
{ The best reply, because  11.Be2  Nd5  helps Black a bit.   After @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pppnpppp/4qnb1/8/2NP1BP1/2N4P/PPP2P2/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 7 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Ne3  I don't see a good defence for Black. We threaten d4-d5, followed by Nc4. This idea materialises after  11...O-O-O  12.d5  Qb6  13.Nc4  Qc5  14.Be3  Qb4  15.a3  , when we trap the unlucky queen.   A better try is @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pppnpppp/4qnb1/8/3P1BP1/2N1N2P/PPP2P2/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 8 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb6  , but  12.Nb5  Rc8  13.g5  already looks fantastic. We win material after  13...c6  14.Nc7+  Rxc7  15.Nc4!  Qb5  16.Bxc7  , and likely the game.   It's clear that @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  is a dubious move for Black. Make sure to play as aggressively as possible to exploit it. }
