4... Nf6 { By far Black's most popular and natural move. } 5. Nf3
{ 'Develop the knights before the bishops' is an old rule, often taught to players that make their first steps in learning opening play. Here it applies, too. Our knight is developed to its most active square, while we do not commit our bishops just yet. We often combine the moves Nf3 and Bc4 in the current chapter but never start with the bishop move.   Now we need to consider different options for Black:  A. They can play  5...c6  , staying flexible about the development of the c8-bishop. This move is the most popular on the master level.   B. Develop the bishop immediately with  5...Bf5  . This will often transpose to lines we examine via A.   C. Black pins our knight with  5...Bg4  . This move is prevalent in online chess and at the club/amateur level. White is much better after  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  , starting an immediate attack.   D. While lines A-C are somewhat similar and sometimes transpose to one another, the fourth option  5...Nc6?  is entirely different. The move is a mistake but requires precision to punish effectively. }
5... c6
{ This is the most common move, giving the queen retreat squares. Often, this position is reached via the @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  5.Nf3  Nf6  move order. By playing ...c7-c6, Black is not yet committing where the c8-bishop will be developed. }
6. Bc4
{ We develop our bishop to the most active square. It's a simple development move but has some finer points.  We anticipate the move @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/2BP4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  and intend to answer with  7.Ne5  @@StartBracket@@tempo on f7@@EndBracket@@  7...e6  8.g4!  , starting our initiative on the kingside.  It's better to start with the bishop move and avoid @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ne5  Be6!  , which deprives us of the more active post for the bishop on c4. Black has much better chances in this line, compared to our choice.   There are cases of playing Ne5 before Bc4. These sequences are @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Ne5  and the similar @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Ne5  , which both feature early ...Bf5 moves.  A good rule of thumb is: 'We develop our bishop first, instead of Ne5, when Black develops their bishop last'. A different way to put it is: 'Our response to ...Bf5 is always Ne5. If Black delays the move, we play Bc4.'   Alright, what happens after  6.Bc4  is played? As usual in this chapter, Black has the choice between the bishop's moves to f5 and g4. Black does not obtain equal chances in either case, but it looks like  6...Bf5  is better than @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/2BP4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , when Black is walking on a tightrope. Let's examine those two moves. }
6... Bg4
{ Such a pin can be annoying, but we strongly react to all cases of ...Bg4 in this chapter: chasing the bishop with h3+g4, if allowed.   Before we continue, a quick word about  7.Bxf7+??  , which looks tempting, as  7...Kxf7  8.Ne5+  Ke8  9.Nxg4  is great for White. Very nice, but @@StartFEN@@rn3b1r/pp2pkpp/2p2n2/q3N3/3P2b1/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qxe5+!  is the end of White's hopes - after all the captures, Black remains a piece up! }
7. h3
{ Here we go. Black now usually plays  7...Bh5  , but we'll also examine  7...Qh5  briefly.If Black captures on f3 and gives up the bishop pair, we'll enjoy a standard advantage and an easy plan: we'll continue with Bd2 and O-O-O and expand on the kingside later. }
7... Qh5
{ This is a risky move, to put it mildly, but any possible refutation is not trivial at all. In fact, I will not recommend the absolute best reply now, but the one that is easiest to handle. }
8. Be2
{ This move gives White a comfortable advantage without any hassle.   As mentioned, there is a more forceful method that I want to show but not recommend for practical purposes. It is  8.hxg4  Qxh1+  9.Bf1  , when  9...e6  10.g5  Nfd7  11.Ne4  gives White a strong attack for the sacrificed exchange. It looks scary for Black, but there are multiple possible deviations along the way, and we are not talking about a forced win. }
8... e6 9. O-O
{ That was our idea. After Be2 and O-O, Black's bishop is attacked and forced to capture on f3. }
9... Bxf3
{ There is nothing else.   Black can't play  9...Bxh3?  due to @@StartBracket@@amongst others@@EndBracket@@  10.Ne5  Qf5  11.Bd3  , when they have nothing better than the sad  11...Qh5  12.Qxh5  Nxh5  13.gxh3  , leaving White with an extra piece and queens off the board. }
10. Bxf3 Qa5 11. Ne2
{ A strong move. Our knight was only observing well-protected squares and blocked our c-pawn. Now we are ready for c2-c4, expanding in the center and trying to open the position for our bishops. White has a comfortable advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "E2) Scandinavian – 3...Qa5"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 3...Qa5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the traditional main line, but it is not as popular anymore, as Black players began to appreciate that the queen is a bit safer on d8 and that there is little tangible benefit in having the queen on a5. }
4. d4
{ A natural and strong move. We are now ready to develop all minor pieces and control the center well.  Sounds excellent - what does Black have? And what is our opponent's idea? In almost all cases, Black has one particular setup in mind: Develop the knight to f6, Develop the bishop to f5 or g4, if possible, Play the pawn to c6, which gives the queen some other retreat squares.   Black has various move orders that may lead to the same positions. The most popular move to start with is @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , which will be the move order we focus on.  Instead, @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  will often transpose to lines we'll examine via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  .  Black can try to develop the bishop earlier, but @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5?!  is a dubious move order. We could angle for a transposition to the main lines with  5.Nf3  , but @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q4b2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qf3  looks even stronger. We intend to answer  5...Nc6  with  6.Bb5  . White has a nice advantage in this line, but don't worry if you forget this detail and play the routine knight move - the main lines are also comfortable for White.   Does Black have anything entirely different? There is the rare move @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e5?  , which opens the position while being severely behind in development. The natural reply  5.Nf3  gives White a large advantage already when  5...Bg4  is the most interesting reply for Black. In the first edition, I analysed the complications after  6.Bc4  quite extensively, but Black's line is too scarce to merit this effort. A simpler solution is @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/ppp2ppp/8/q3p3/3P2b1/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  to break the pin when White is much better by simple means. The sample line  6...Nc6  7.O-O  O-O-O  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.Bxg4+  shows Black's problems. }
4... Nf6 { By far Black's most popular and natural move. } 5. Nf3
{ 'Develop the knights before the bishops' is an old rule, often taught to players that make their first steps in learning opening play. Here it applies, too. Our knight is developed to its most active square, while we do not commit our bishops just yet. We often combine the moves Nf3 and Bc4 in the current chapter but never start with the bishop move.   Now we need to consider different options for Black:  A. They can play  5...c6  , staying flexible about the development of the c8-bishop. This move is the most popular on the master level.   B. Develop the bishop immediately with  5...Bf5  . This will often transpose to lines we examine via A.   C. Black pins our knight with  5...Bg4  . This move is prevalent in online chess and at the club/amateur level. White is much better after  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  , starting an immediate attack.   D. While lines A-C are somewhat similar and sometimes transpose to one another, the fourth option  5...Nc6?  is entirely different. The move is a mistake but requires precision to punish effectively. }
5... c6
{ This is the most common move, giving the queen retreat squares. Often, this position is reached via the @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  5.Nf3  Nf6  move order. By playing ...c7-c6, Black is not yet committing where the c8-bishop will be developed. }
6. Bc4
{ We develop our bishop to the most active square. It's a simple development move but has some finer points.  We anticipate the move @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/2BP4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  and intend to answer it  7.Ne5  @@StartBracket@@tempo on f7@@EndBracket@@  7...e6  8.g4!  , starting our initiative on the kingside.  It's better to start with the bishop move and avoid @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ne5  Be6!  , which deprives us of the more active post for the bishop on c4. Black has much better chances in this line, compared to our choice.   There are cases of playing Ne5 before Bc4. These sequences are @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Ne5  and the similar @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Ne5  , which both feature early ...Bf5 moves.  A good rule of thumb is: 'We develop our bishop first, instead of Ne5, when Black develops their bishop last'. A different way to put it is: 'Our response to ...Bf5 is always Ne5. If Black delays the move, we play Bc4.'   Alright, what happens after  6.Bc4?  As usual in this chapter, Black has the choice between the bishop's moves to f5 and g4. Black does not obtain equal chances in either case, but it looks like  6...Bf5  is better than @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/2BP4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , when Black is walking on a tightrope. Let's examine those two moves. }
6... Bg4
{ Such a pin can be annoying, but we strongly react to all cases of ...Bg4 in this chapter: chasing the bishop with h3+g4, if allowed.   Before we continue, a quick word about  7.Bxf7+??  , which looks tempting, as  7...Kxf7  8.Ne5+  Ke8  9.Nxg4  is great for White. Very nice, but @@StartFEN@@rn3b1r/pp2pkpp/2p2n2/q3N3/3P2b1/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qxe5+!  is the end of White's hopes - after all the captures, Black remains a piece up! }
7. h3
{ Here we go. Black now usually plays  7...Bh5  , but we'll also examine  7...Qh5  briefly.If Black captures on f3 and gives up the bishop pair, we'll enjoy a standard advantage and an easy plan: we'll continue with Bd2 and O-O-O and expand on the kingside later. }
7... Bh5 { Black maintains the pin but allows our g4-pawn push. } 8. g4
{ In the first edition, I recommended  8.Qe2  , which was correctly assessed as leading to a large advantage for White. This suggestion was based on @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q6b/2BP4/2N2N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.g4  Bg6  9.Ne5?!  , when  9...Nbd7  is fine for Black.   Now, for the second edition, I suggest playing  8.g4  , but play a better move than  8...Bg6  9.Ne5?!  - let's see how it works. }
8... Bg6
{ Now we need to avoid  9.Ne5?!  , as after  9...Nbd7  Black is still in reasonable shape. One problem is that we can't play  10.Qe2  due to  10...Nxe5  11.dxe5  Ne4  , which is annoying.  My suggestion tries to solve exactly this issue: the pin on the a5-e1 diagonal. }
9. Bd2 { Breaking the pin and preparing knight discoveries, if appropriate. }
9... Qc7
{ Black's usual response, avoiding the mentioned knight discoveries.   After  9...e6  , we are spoilt for choice. Stockfish wants to kill Black immediately with  10.h4  Nxg4  11.h5  Bf5  12.Qe2  @@StartBracket@@with the idea of Nh4@@EndBracket@@, but the simpler @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pnb1/q7/2BP2P1/2N2N1P/PPPB1P2/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qe2  is fantastic for White, too. We prepare d4-d5, on top of everything. }
10. Qe2 { Many moves are great here, like  10.h4!?  or  10.Ne5  immediately. }
10... Nbd7
{ Or  10...e6  11.Ne5  , with similar play and an overwhelming position.   They clearly can't afford  10...Bxc2??  11.Ne5  e6  12.Bf4  , when resigning is a good option for Black to avoid a world of pain. }
11. Ne5
{ White has a fantastic position. We are ready to castle queenside and push the f-pawn @@StartBracket@@and/or h-pawn@@EndBracket@@ to further attack Black's unlucky bishop on g6. }
*

