6... Bf5
{ Developing the bishop to f5 is Black's main and more reliable option. } 7.
Ne5 { Not only attacking f7 but preparing g4 simultaneously. } 7... e6 8. g4
{ As usual, we need to play forcefully to put pressure on Black.   Now they most often play  8...Bg6  , but we need to check  8...Be4  , too. It's a very dubious move but requires some precision to tackle. }
8... Be4
{ This is no solution for Black's problems but needs to be answered precisely if we want to get the maximum out of it. }
9. O-O
{ It looks odd to castle after g4 is on the board, but we threaten g4-g5, winning a piece. }
9... Bd5
{ The only move to avoid simple material losses. We have reached a fascinating situation because White has a range of crushing moves. }
10. g5
{ I suggest this move, going for the immediate kill.   In the first edition, I recommended  10.Bd3  Nbd7  11.f4  - it is not a knock-out attempt, but it still looks fantastic. }
10... Nfd7
{ The alternative  10...Bxc4  11.Nxc4  Qa6  12.b3  Nd5  13.Ne4  is great for White, too. The check on d6 is looming. }
11. Bxd5 { The idea of the whole sequence is revealed on the next move. } 11...
cxd5 12. Nxf7
{ This leads to a winning attack. The engine sees the win and can calculate it till the end. We can't do that, but we can see that White's attack is extremely dangerous. }
12... Kxf7 13. Qf3+ Kg8
{ The most testing move.   After  13...Ke7  14.Re1  Black can't survive. } 14.
Qg4 Qb6
{ Here  14...Kf7  loses to  15.Re1  Qb6  16.Nxd5!  exd5  17.Qf5+  Nf6  18.gxf6  , when Black collapses. }
15. Re1
{ This silent but strong move is still good to know. We'll get the e-pawn next, and Black is under massive pressure.   The whole line after 8...Be4 is more or less winning for White by computer standards. For play between humans, it's important to note that White has all the fun, attacking relentlessly. Even if you don't know all the details, your job is much easier than Black's! }
*

