{ As usual, we need to play forcefully to put pressure on Black.   Now they most often play  8...Bg6  , but we need to check  8...Be4  , too. It's a very dubious move but requires some precision to tackle. }
8... Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7
{ Black challenges our knight, the most frequently played move.   Note that Black could play  9...Be4  , similar to 8...Be4. The only difference between the two positions is that we have the additional move h4. This leads to a situation in which we are spoilt for choice.  A. We could play the same way as shown before:  10.O-O  Bd5  11.g5  Nfd7  12.Bxd5  cxd5  13.Nxf7  , with a crushing attack.  B. In the first edition, I suggested @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/q3N3/2BPb1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Rh3  , which also looks excellent after  10...Bd5  11.Bd2  Bxc4  12.Nxc4  Qd8  13.g5!  , with a large advantage. A nice choice to have! }
10. Nxd7
{ We trade on d7 and continue with h4-h5 next. For Black, both recaptures are possible and lead to similar structures, as we will see. }
10... Nxd7
{ By far the most popular move, still keeping the option of queenside casting. After   10...Kxd7  11.h5  Be4  12.O-O  Bd5  13.Nxd5  cxd5  14.Bd3  we reach a better version of 10...Nxd7 - Black likely needs to castle 'by hand', losing time. }
11. h5 Be4 12. O-O
{ Similar to @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1N1ppp/2p1pnb1/q7/2BP2PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Kxd7  11.h5  Be4  12.O-O!  , we castle kingside after pushing our pawns. }
12... Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3
{ An excellent moment to take stock. I prefer White here, but it is quite clearly a complicated position.  Don't be afraid of the seemingly open king position. Black does not have any attacking pieces to threaten us directly, so it is not particularly risky - that being said, it's not like being completely safe as in a typical castling scenario.  An interesting plan for Black is trying to trade the dark-squared bishop through ...Qc7 and ...Bd6.   They could continue with @@StartFEN@@@@EndFEN@@  14...Bd6  15.Bd2  Qc7  , when  16.Qf3  stops the intended plan of ...Bf4, going for the trade. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "E3) Scandinavian – 3...Qd6 & 3...Qd8"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 3...Qd6 & 3...Qd8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Black has a choice of queen moves. The main line  3...Qa5  is covered in a separate chapter, while the current chapter examines Black's other options. The two moves that need some analysis are  3...Qd8  and  3...Qd6  - they are also played with about the same frequency. Black plays  3...Qa5  in about 50% of the games, while the queen retreats to d8 and d6 share the other half.Other queen moves don't make a lot of sense, but  3...Qe5+  is not as stupid as it looks. After  4.Be2  c6  5.Nf3  Qc7  Black's queen returns to a safer spot, but White has a nice advantage by simply developing with  6.d4  Bf5  7.Ne5  Nd7  8.Bf4  Nxe5  9.Bxe5  ,  winning a tempo on the queen again.Let's look at the two more serious options now, the retreats on the d-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "E3) Scandinavian – 3...Qd6 & 3...Qd8"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 3...Qd8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8
{ Black retreats the queen on the safest square - on d8, it is certainly not getting into trouble soon. Still, moving the queen twice in the opening, only to return it to its initial square, can't be ideal.How do we play against 3...Qd8 then? The first step is easy. }
4. d4
{ Our natural reply against all the sensible queen moves. Now Black has two popular setups that we need to check in detail. They usually play a combination of the moves ...Nf6, ...c6 and bishop development to f5 or g4. This may happen in various move orders. We'll examine 4...Nf6 as the main move order but will look at 4...c6, too.Does Black have any serious alternatives to this development concept? From a logical point of view, there is not much else. Black needs to develop the f8-bishop but does not want to play ...e6 right away and lock in its colleague on c8. Therefore developing the bishop to f5 or g4 first makes sense, followed by ...e6.   The only other approach to developing the f8-bishop is trying a kingside fianchetto with  4...g6  .  Against this move, any normal development is fine, but I want to mention that a setup based on a quick Bf4&Qd2, intending O-O-O and Bh6, is strong. After  5.Bf4  Bg7  6.Qd2!  Black can't play  6...Qxd4?  , because  7.Qxd4  Bxd4  8.Nb5  Bb6  9.Bxc7  is great for White. They need to be content with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/6p1/8/3P1B2/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KBNR b KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  7.O-O-O  c6  8.Bh6  , which gives White excellent attacking chances. }
4... c6
{ Black starts with the move 4...c6 and avoids the knight development to f6 for the moment. Does this make a substantial difference? Not substantial, but subtle. Let's have a look. }
5. Nf3
{ This natural development move is our answer to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , as well. After  5.Nf3  Black often plays  5...c6  , leading to a position that we would also reach now after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  . The move we need to check is the immediate pin of our knight,  5...Bg4  .   I want to mention that  5.Bc4  is a good move here, as well. This was my recommendation in the first edition, intending to answer  5...Nf6  with  6.Nf3  ,  which transposes to the move order 4...Nf6 5.Nf3 c6 6. Bc4, which we examine in the current chapter. Black may try  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/8/2BP4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  , but  6.g4  and  6.Bxf7+  are powerful replies.For the second edition, I decided to switch to 5.Nf3, as this move is more consistent with other lines in the Scandinavian: we never play Bc4 in any other line before the g1-knight is developed. }
5... Bg4
{ The only interesting move worth checking here. The alternatives transpose to other lines, at best.   A.  5...Nf6  6.Bc4  transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  6.Bc4  .   B.  5...Bf5?  6.Ne5  immediately sees Black in trouble, facing ideas of g4 and h4. After  6...Nd7?  we win on the spot with  7.Nxf7!  Kxf7  8.Qf3  Kg6  9.g4  Bxc2  10.h4  ,  to show just one sample line of the disasters Black is dealing with. }
6. h3
{ Our usual reply to early ...Bg4 moves in the Scandinavian. Here, we need to consider a specific line: what if Black plays  6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  Qxd4  , grabbing a pawn? We'll see that White gets great compensation for the pawn, so this is nothing to worry about.   Still, I'd like to point out that  6.Be3  is a good move, too. After  6...Nf6  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  we transpose to a main line of this chapter, usually reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  c6  ,  which is comfortable for White. This is an excellent alternative to my suggestion 6. h3, not allowing the pawn grab on d4. }
6... Bxf3
{ The only good move. After  6...Bh5?  7.g4  Bg6  8.h4  Black is already close to lost, as  8...h6  9.Ne5  Bh7  10.Qf3  demonstrates. }
7. Qxf3 Qxd4
{ Black can grab the d-pawn, which is a key difference to the comparable line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  , when we attack the b-pawn. So did we just blunder a pawn and have no compensation? Of course not; we have a huge advantage in development and excellent attacking chances, as we'll see in a moment.   Before we continue, I need to mention that Black is not obliged to capture the pawn. Objectively, it is much better to play  7...Nf6  , when  8.Be3  transposes to the main line of the ...Qd8 Scandi, usually reached via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  c6  8.Be3  . }
8. Bf4
{ After 8.Bf4 we have excellent compensation for the pawn, as Black faces serious threats of Rd1 and even Nb5 in some lines. The engine already thinks Black is lost, which is a strong statement, but it looks grim for Black. }
8... Nd7
{ The alternatives are not convincing, either.   A.  8...e5  9.Bg5  Be7  10.Rd1  Qb6  11.Bc4  Nf6  12.Bxf6  gxf6  13.Qg4  gives White a winning attack.   B.  8...Nf6  9.Nb5!  is crushing, as  9...cxb5  10.Bxb5+  Nbd7  11.Qxb7  Qe4+  12.Qxe4  Nxe4  13.Bc6  demonstrates.It's not necessary to study all these complications in minute detail. We have a strong attack and a much easier task than our opponent. }
9. Rd1 { Developing with tempo is so nice! } 9... Qb4
{ This is the most challenging move, pinning our knight. } 10. a3
{ An important point to remember. We attack the queen, offering the b-pawn on top! }
10... Qxb2
{ Let's have some fun examining this greedy move. After  10...Qb6  11.Bc4  White has a smashing attack, too. Note that we have serious threats now, as  11...Ngf6?  12.Bxf7+!  Kxf7  13.Rxd7  Nxd7  14.Bc7+  shows. }
11. Rxd7 { The fancy way to finish Black off, but  11.Bc4  is enough, too. }
11... Kxd7 12. Bc4
{ White has a winning attack now - there are just too many attackers. What if Black is even more greedy now? After  12...Qa1+  13.Ke2  Qxh1  14.Qd3+  it's over.  14...Kc8  15.Bxf7  already leads to a forced mate, while  14...Ke8  15.Nb5  smashes through, as well.Entertaining stuff and worth checking. This is not a matter of opening preparation but of learning attacking skills. Here it's nice to know that 6.Be3 is a sound alternative, while 6.h3 is the move that tries to tempt Black into grabbing a poisoned pawn. }
