1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8
{ Black retreats the queen on the safest square - on d8, it is certainly not getting into trouble soon. Still, moving the queen twice in the opening, only to return it to its initial square, can't be ideal.How do we play against 3...Qd8 then? The first step is easy. }
4. d4
{ Our natural reply against all the sensible queen moves. Now Black has two popular setups that we need to check in detail. They usually play a combination of the moves ...Nf6, ...c6 and bishop development to f5 or g4. This may happen in various move orders. We'll examine 4...Nf6 as the main move order but will look at 4...c6, too.Does Black have any serious alternatives to this development concept? From a logical point of view, there is not much else. Black needs to develop the f8-bishop but does not want to play ...e6 right away and lock in its colleague on c8. Therefore developing the bishop to f5 or g4 first makes sense, followed by ...e6.   The only other approach to developing the f8-bishop is trying a kingside fianchetto with  4...g6  .  Against this move, any normal development is fine, but I want to mention that a setup based on a quick Bf4&Qd2, intending O-O-O and Bh6, is strong. After  5.Bf4  Bg7  6.Qd2!  Black can't play  6...Qxd4?  , because  7.Qxd4  Bxd4  8.Nb5  Bb6  9.Bxc7  is great for White. They need to be content with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/6p1/8/3P1B2/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KBNR b KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  7.O-O-O  c6  8.Bh6  , which gives White excellent attacking chances. }
4... Nf6 { The most natural and flexible move for Black. } 5. Nf3
{ The most natural move, for sure. Now Black must decide if they want to develop the bishop to f5 or g4. If ...Bg4 is the intention, they need to start with  5...Bg4  right away. After  5...c6  , we play  6.Bc4!  , when  6...Bg4??  7.Bxf7+!  is a common tactic.Black has to resort to  6...Bf5  , when after  7.Ne5  we transpose to a position that we may also reach via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  6.Ne5  c6  7.Bc4  ,  giving White excellent chances. In general, we will see that Black gets into trouble in the ...Bf5-setups. }
5... Bf5 { This has little independent value. } 6. Ne5
{ This knight jump is an important move order finesse. We immediately prepare two aggressive moves: pushing the pawn to g4 and playing the queen to f3, attacking both the bishop and the b-pawn. Playing  6.Ne5  is a lot stronger than  6.Bc4  , when  6...e6  7.Ne5  Nbd7  is fine for Black.The early knight jump in reply to ...Bf5 is a common theme in the Scandinavian, as three similar lines show:   A. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qd8  4.d4  c6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Ne5!   B. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qa5  4.d4  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Ne5!   C. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qa5  4.d4  c6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Ne5! }
6... c6
{ This move is relatively best but still leads to serious trouble for Black. Even worse are the two alternatives:   A.  6...Nbd7?  7.Qf3!  , with a deadly double attack.   B.  6...e6?  7.g4  Bg6  8.Bg2  c6  9.h4  is even better than the similar position after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/4Nb2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6  7.Bc4  e6  8.g4  Bg6  9.h4  ,  as the bishop on g2 controls the e4-square and serves as the king's guard after kingside castling. This is relevant after  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pnb1/4N3/3P2PP/2N5/PPP2PB1/R1BQK2R b KQkq h3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bb4  10.O-O!  Nfd7  11.Nxd7  Nxd7  12.h5  Qh4  , when we can play  13.hxg6  hxg6  14.Bf4  and win. This wouldn't work with our bishop on c4, of course. }
7. Bc4
{ This position may also arise via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6  6.Bc4  Bf5  7.Ne5  , a frequently seen sequence. }
7... e6
{ We played 7.Bc4 to provoke this move - it's time to attack with our kingside pawns. If we had played @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/4Nb2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.g4  , Black still had  7...Be6  . Not great for Black either, but now things are even worse. }
8. g4 Bg6
{ Playing  8...Be4  doesn't help Black, either. After  9.Nxe4  Nxe4  White would already be much better on general grounds @@StartBracket@@space, bishop pair@@EndBracket@@, but we even have the direct smasher  10.Nxf7  Kxf7  11.Qf3+  Nf6  12.g5  Qxd4  13.gxf6  , with a decisive attack. }
9. h4
{ A usual scenario, pushing on the kingside and threatening to trap the bishop. The main idea is f2-f3 first, then h4-h5! }
9... Bb4
{ Black may also try  9...Nbd7  , when  10.f3!  is the crucial move to remember! It is very similar to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pnb1/4N3/2BP2PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQK2R b KQkq h3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bb4  10.f3!  , which we will examine now.   If Black goes for  9...Be4  , we again have  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Nxf7!  , as shown in the notes to move  8. }
10. f3
{ This is an important idea to remember! It is also a key point after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pnb1/4N3/2BP2PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQK2R b KQkq h3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nbd7  10.f3!  ,  when the threat h4-h5 is becoming decisive, too. }
10... Nd5
{ This is relatively best, as  10...h6  11.Nxg6  fxg6  12.Qd3  won't end well for the black king. }
11. Bd2
{ This looks like the cleanest solution. Instead,  11.Bxd5  is better for White, but this seems even more effective. Black now only has a choice between ways to be much worse or lost. Here are two sample lines.   A.  11...f6  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Bd3  gives us a strong attack.   B.  11...Bxc3  12.bxc3  b5  13.Bxd5  Qxd5  14.h5  f6  15.hxg6  fxe5  16.Rxh7  Rg8  17.Rh5  wins for White. }
