5... Bg4
{ This pinning move is Black's main continuation. The lines involving ...Bf5 look excellent for White, so this is no surprise. }
6. h3
{ Our usual reaction to early ...Bg4 moves in this chapter: attack the bishop immediately. Black is now more or less forced to capture our knight and give up the bishop pair. After  6...Bh5?  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  , we reach a scenario quite similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  6.Ne5  e6  7.g4  Bg6  - Sometimes, we might even get to the same positions.   One of those, and likely to occur, is  6...Bh5?  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  e6  9.Bg2  c6  10.h4  , when  10...Bb4  11.O-O  leads to a winning advantage for White. Black can try @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5nb1/4N3/3P2P1/2N4P/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nbd7  instead, but both  9.Qe2  or  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.g5  Nh5  11.d5  are awful for Black. }
6... Bxf3
{ This is forced, as  6...Bh5?  7.g4  leads to a disaster. White now gets the usual type of edge against the Scandinavian with the bishop pair and a space advantage. Black is content with a solid structure, as we will see. }
7. Qxf3 c6 { Black has to cover b7 and now attacks d4 for real. } 8. Be3
{ We develop the bishop and cover the attacked d-pawn. This move was my recommendation in the first edition, intending to castle queenside. I still like the move, but want to adjust the intended plan. I see no objective problem in castling queenside, but I think that playing with O-O is much easier to handle in practice. White's king on c1/b1 is often a potential target for ideas like ...b5, followed by ...Nd7-b6-c4, to name just one plan.   Before we continue, I want to point out a cunning engine suggestion that did not fit the concept of the course: the move  8.g4!?  is possible, offering the d-pawn. It leads to crazy complications that are definitely dangerous for Black. This is a good line to dig into if you like to analyse something fun. }
8... e6 9. Bd3 { We develop and prepare kingside castling. } 9... Nbd7
{ We aren't worried about  9...Bb4  10.O-O  Bxc3?  11.bxc3  O-O  12.c4  ,  as our pawns do an excellent job of controlling key central squares. We have two bishops against two knights in an open position, which is a huge asset. }
10. O-O
{ Castling queenside was my recommendation in the first edition. While I still think White retains an edge, castling kingside is simpler to handle in practice and better for White. }
10... Bd6
{ Blach has also tried the bishop development to e7, but it doesn't change the evaluation and plans much. We'll discuss the strategy in a moment. }
11. Rfe1 { We'll centralise our rooks and then decide how to proceed. } 11...
O-O 12. Rad1
{ We have completed our development, reaching a position that could be in a textbook under the section 'Centralisation'. How do we continue from here, though?   The type of position is a frequent guest in several openings. In our repertoire, we could reach a similar scenario in the French Rubinstein, Fort-Knox Variation @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  dxe4  4.Nxe4  Bd7  5.Nf3  Bc6  ,  with a later ...Bxe4 or ...Bxf3 to follow@@EndBracket@@. Let's make a list of strategy pointers:  We have the bishop pair, a long-term asset. We should keep both bishops on the board, as the bishop pair will prove useful deep into the endgame.  The position is not easy to open for our bishops. As a long-term idea, playing c2-c4 and d4-d5 comes to mind, breaking the center wide open. This is a long way to materialise, though. In addition, playing the pawn to c4 has the drawback of weakening our d-pawn - We can't protect it with c2-c3 anymore. Therefore, I advise carefully considering if playing the pawn to c4 is a good idea. Often, stabilising the center with a pawn to c3 is a better idea - you can still go for c3-c4 later, anyway.  Black can't do much in terms of active play. They have the pawn breaks ...c5 and ...e5, but these might backfire as our bishops get more scope. Quite often, Black will resort to a sit-and-wait strategy. Patience is key for us. We don't need to rush anything and can try small things to progress.   I want to illustrate these points with moves taken from an online Blitz game I found, played in 2022 between K.Mekhitarian and O. Yurovskich.  12....Re8  13.Bc1  Not strictly necessary, but White is in no hurry  13...Qc7  14.g3  Rad8  15.Kg2  Continuing to make small improvements. This kingside setup makes it a bit easier to advance the h-pawn, and to have a pawn on g3 stops a possible ...Bf4 idea by Black, forever.  15...Nb6  16.Ne4!  Now we get to an interesting moment. The knight on c3 is not well placed, as it attacks nothing and blocks the c-pawn. We want the option to play the pawn to c3 to support the d-pawn. White doesn't mind the trade, so Ne4 is a good way to proceed.  16...Nxe4  17.Qxe4  g6   Now White played the move  18.c4?!  ,  which I don't like that much. It helps to restrict Black's knight but creates a target on d4. With ...Bf8-g7, Black gets something to attack.  If White plays  18.c3  instead, the center remains perfectly safe. We could continue with h4-h5 ideas and still have many options to improve our pieces. Our bishop could be well-placed on b3, for instance. This would more or less rule out any ...e6-e5 option by Black due to the pressure on f7. If Black decides to stop h4-h5 by playing ...h5, we can prepare g3-g4, of course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "E3) Scandinavian – 3...Qd6 & 3...Qd8"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 3...Qd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6
{ This move enjoyed popularity some years ago, but White has worked out what to do by now. It is not a trivial affair, but we can frequently be optimistic about gaining a significant advantage. }
4. d4 Nf6
{ Black sometimes starts with  4...c6  or  4...a6  ,  but Black will play ...Nf6 soon, so these don't have any independent value. }
5. Nf3
{ After 5. Nf3 Black has a wide choice. Here's an overview.   A. The immediate  5...Bg4  is premature due to the standard reply  6.h3  , as seen throughout many lines in the Scandi.   B. Black can play  5...c6  ,  which makes the queen feel more secure on d6 and waits to play the bishop to f5 or g4 later. In the first edition, I recommended  6.h3  here.  In the meantime, I learned that White has a much more promising option. It is the move  6.Ne5  , which is more aggressive than my former suggestion.   C.  5...a6  is also possible and shares some ideas with line B. Another point might be ...b5, going for the extended queenside fianchetto.Like the situation in line B, theory has progressed, and now White has a stronger line than  6.Bd3  , as recommended in the first edition. After  6.g3!  it looks like Black is in serious trouble, particularly if they play too ambitiously - which happens often.   Black has tried some rare moves, but I don't think a deeper investigation is warranted. An idea to keep in mind is the knight jump to b5, followed by the move c4. This could be employed, for example, after  5...g6  6.Nb5  Qb6  7.c4  ,  when we get our c-pawn involved and correct a deficit of our setup: the knight is not well-placed on c3, blocking the c-pawn. We'd rather have the c-pawn involved, controlling the d5-square.On a side note: in the specific line above, the move  7.a4  is also interesting, intending  7...a6  8.Na3  @@StartBracket@@on the way to c4-e5@@EndBracket@@.Let's check Black's main options now. }
5... Bg4
{ The usual recipe against ...Bg4 is to question the bishop with h3 and g4 immediately. It works well here, too. }
6. h3 Bh5
{ Here  6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  leads to the standard advantage that we often get in the Scandi. In this particular case, we'll reach a similar scenario to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qd8  4.d4  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  ,  but even more favourable as Black's queen is on a worse spot on d6. }
7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5
{ We know this idea from many similar lines. Black is under some pressure. as we threaten h3-h4-h5 to trap the bishop. Often it makes sense to play Bg3, controlling e4 first. }
8... Nbd7
{ This looks relatively best. Black immediately fights our strong knight. } 9.
Nxg6
{ 9.Qe2  or  9.Nc4  are more complicated alternatives, but the capture works well here. }
9... hxg6 10. g5
{ This move seems to be even more effective than  10.Bg2  , as suggested in the first edition of the course. It also leads to a large advantage, though. }
10... Nd5 11. Bg2
{ This is the idea of 10. g5. We attack the knight and like to provoke the capture on c3, which would open the b-bile and strengthen our center. We'd be clearly better in this case. If Black does not take it, the move Ne4 becomes an option. White has a significant advantage in either case, as we enjoy the bishop pair and more space in a position bound to open up even more. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "E3) Scandinavian – 3...Qd6 & 3...Qd8"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 3...Qd6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6
{ This move enjoyed popularity some years ago, but White has worked out what to do by now. It is not a trivial affair, but we can frequently be optimistic about gaining a significant advantage. }
4. d4 Nf6
{ Black sometimes starts with  4...c6  or  4...a6  ,  but Black will play ...Nf6 soon, so these don't have any independent value. }
5. Nf3
{ After 5. Nf3 Black has a wide choice. Here's an overview.   A. The immediate  5...Bg4  is premature due to the standard reply  6.h3  , as seen throughout many lines in the Scandi.   B. Black can play  5...c6  ,  which makes the queen feel more secure on d6 and waits to play the bishop to f5 or g4 later. In the first edition, I recommended  6.h3  here.  In the meantime, I learned that White has a much more promising option. It is the move  6.Ne5  , which is more aggressive than my former suggestion.   C.  5...a6  is also possible and shares some ideas with line B. Another point might be ...b5, going for the extended queenside fianchetto.Like the situation in line B, theory has progressed, and now White has a stronger line than  6.Bd3  , as recommended in the first edition. After  6.g3!  it looks like Black is in serious trouble, particularly if they play too ambitiously - which happens often.   Black has tried some rare moves, but I don't think a deeper investigation is warranted. An idea to keep in mind is the knight jump to b5, followed by the move c4. This could be employed, for example, after  5...g6  6.Nb5  Qb6  7.c4  ,  when we get our c-pawn involved and correct a deficit of our setup: the knight is not well-placed on c3, blocking the c-pawn. We'd rather have the c-pawn involved, controlling the d5-square.On a side note: in the specific line above, the move  7.a4  is also interesting, intending  7...a6  8.Na3  @@StartBracket@@on the way to c4-e5@@EndBracket@@.Let's check Black's main options now. }
5... c6
{ It is useful to compare this to similar positions with the queen on a5. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  Qa5  4.d4  Nf6  5.Nf3  c6  , we play  6.Bc4  , as  6...Bg4  can be met by  7.h3  Bxf3  @@StartBracket@@  7...Bh5?  8.g4  is even worse@@EndBracket@@  8.Qxf3  .  Our d-pawn is not under attack.Here, with the queen on d6,  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2pq1n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bc4  Bg4  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Qxd4  is possible and fine for Black. We need a different solution. The critical move now is not very natural, but it is strong. }
6. Ne5
{ My suggestion in the first edition was  6.h3  , intending to answer  6...Bf5  with  7.Nh4  - not bad at all. However, after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2pq1n2/8/3P4/2N2N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  , Black's position is rather solid.   This is not a problem, but when I checked possible alternatives, I discovered  6.Ne5  looks more powerful and aggressive. It is also fairly simple to play, in my mind. The main idea of the two is twofold. We avoid the ....Bg4 pin altogether and simultaneously prepare Bf4 or pawn to f4, supporting our knight. }
6... Nbd7
{ Black's main move by a mile, directly challenging our knight. Alternatives like  6...g6  7.Bf4  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2pq1n2/4N3/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  7.g4!  @@StartBracket@@we know these ideas from the 3...Qa5 Scandi@@EndBracket@@ don't convince at all. }
7. f4
{ This is the most powerful continuation. Black now has a hard time ever removing the strong knight on e5. I want to show two alternatives to illustrate matters better.   A.  7.Bf4  looks good at first, but  7...Nd5!  helps Black a bit, trading a pair of knights. White still has a small advantage, though.   B.  7.Nc4  Qc7  8.a4  is an interesting alternative of a more strategic nature. White plans to play a4-a5, limiting the d7-knight. Later, g3 and Bf4 are on the agenda. Line B is a worthy alternative to my main suggestion 7. f4, if you like a slower game. }
7... Nb6
{ That's Black main move, by far. They prevent Bc4 and open the c8-bishop.   After  7...g6  I suggest  8.Bc4  e6  9.Qe2  Bg7  10.Be3  , followed by queenside castling. White has excellent attacking chances against Black's king, while Black's counterplay looks slow. }
8. g4
{ Here we go! This is a very effective move with multiple purposes: we stop ...Bf5 and prepare Bg2 at the same time. Black is in some trouble now. }
8... Nbd5
{ Played most of the time. The alternatives are not convincing, either.   A.  8...g6  9.Bg2  Bg7  10.O-O  O-O  11.f5!  prepares Bf4 and makes it difficult for Black to develop the c8-bishop.   B.  8...Be6  tends to walk into f4-f5 ideas, like  9.Bg2  O-O-O  10.f5  Bc4  11.b3  demonstrates. Black is already lost here. }
9. Bg2 { We continue as planned, allowing the capture on c3. } 9... Nxc3 10.
bxc3
{ We don't mind the doubled c-pawn, as d4 gets more support, and the open b-file and c1-a3 diagonal might prove useful. }
10... g6
{ This looks logical, finally preparing to get the king out of the middle of the board. I'll continue this line to show an interesting idea. }
11. O-O Bg7 12. a4
{ A good idea to remember. The doubled pawn enables our bishop to be developed to a3. An additional point can be a4-a5-a6, destroying Black's queenside.   All in all, the @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2pq1n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ne5  Nbd7  7.f4!  line looks like a difficult one for Black to handle. We have a strong initiative and many dangerous ideas. }
