[Black "Scandinavian – 3...Qd6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6
{ This move enjoyed popularity some years ago, but White has worked out what to do by now. It is not a trivial affair, but we can frequently be optimistic about gaining a significant advantage. }
4. d4 Nf6
{ Black sometimes starts with  4...c6  or  4...a6  ,  but Black will play ...Nf6 soon, so these don't have any independent value. }
5. Nf3
{ After 5. Nf3 Black has a wide choice. Here's an overview.   A. The immediate  5...Bg4  is premature due to the standard reply  6.h3  , as seen throughout many lines in the Scandi.   B. Black can play  5...c6  ,  which makes the queen feel more secure on d6 and waits to play the bishop to f5 or g4 later. In the first edition, I recommended  6.h3  here.  In the meantime, I learned that White has a much more promising option. It is the move  6.Ne5  , which is more aggressive than my former suggestion.   C.  5...a6  is also possible and shares some ideas with line B. Another point might be ...b5, going for the extended queenside fianchetto.Like the situation in line B, theory has progressed, and now White has a stronger line than  6.Bd3  , as recommended in the first edition. After  6.g3!  it looks like Black is in serious trouble, particularly if they play too ambitiously - which happens often.   Black has tried some rare moves, but I don't think a deeper investigation is warranted. An idea to keep in mind is the knight jump to b5, followed by the move c4. This could be employed, for example, after  5...g6  6.Nb5  Qb6  7.c4  ,  when we get our c-pawn involved and correct a deficit of our setup: the knight is not well-placed on c3, blocking the c-pawn. We'd rather have the c-pawn involved, controlling the d5-square.On a side note: in the specific line above, the move  7.a4  is also interesting, intending  7...a6  8.Na3  @@StartBracket@@on the way to c4-e5@@EndBracket@@.Let's check Black's main options now. }
5... a6
{ The move 5...a6 has more than one idea. Black covers the b5-square and sometimes prepares the extended fianchetto ...b5 and ...Bb7.   It is important to realise an important difference to  5...c6  ,  which is that the c6-square is still available for the b8-knight. This becomes immediately relevant after  5...a6  6.Ne5?!  Nc6!  ,  which is fine for Black. The knight jump to e5 is our answer to 5...c6, while here, it is harmless and easy for Black to handle.We need a different approach. In the first edition, I suggested  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1pp1pppp/p2q1n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  , which was considered strong at the time of writing. The move has no fundamental problem, but  6...g6  looks fairly solid for Black. It is a similar situation as after 5...c6, actually. The old recommendation is fine, but we now know that there is something better and more dangerous for Black. }
6. g3
{ In recent years, this move has earned the reputation of refuting the 5...a6 variation. This is a slight exaggeration, but it is clear that Black struggles against it. Our idea is twofold:A. Preparing Bf4, winning a tempo.B. Enabling Bg2, which is particularly relevant against Black's extended fianchetto.   We now need to consider two options for Black,  6...b5  and  6...Bg4  , which is by far the most popular. What about  6...g6  here? We have the simple reply  7.Bf4  Qd8  8.Qd2  ,  preparing Bh6 and O-O-O. We are not always committed to Bg2 and O-O after g3 is played! }
6... Bg4
{ Black's sharper option at this point. They pin our knight and might have ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O in mind. }
7. h3
{ Our usual reaction to ...Bg4 is good here, too. However, make sure not to continue in auto-pilot mode after. Let's see why! }
7... Bh5
{ The capture  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3  leads to the standard edge for White, as usual. The arising position type is discussed more in the 3...Qd8 lines of this chapter. }
8. Bg2
{ It is crucial NOT to play  8.g4  here, as we want to keep the Bf4 option. Note that  8.g4  Bg6  9.Ne5  is ineffective due to  9...Nc6  - our move 8.Bg2 strengthens the g4+Ne5, as it defuses this defensive resource. }
8... Nc6
{ Black prepares queenside castling and stops Ne5 at the same time. The problem with the move is: it does not work for concrete reasons. }
9. d5 Nb4
{ The other knight jump  9...Ne5  doesn't help either due to  10.g4  Bg6  11.O-O  ,  when we threaten too much. It's not only Nf4 but also the capture on e5, followed by f4-f5. }
10. Bf4 { That's why we avoided g3-g4 earlier. } 10... Qc5
{ After  10...Bxf3  we can play  11.Qxf3!  Nxc2+  12.Kf1  Qb6  13.Rc1  and are more or less winning. The general problem after we have accomplished d4-d5 is that Black has no reasonable way to develop. How are they going to play ...e6 to get the bishop out? This is the way to assess the final position of the line above. The pawn is not relevant, given these problems. }
11. Be3 Qa5
{ Here  11...Qd6  is met by  12.Qe2  Nbxd5  13.Nxd5  Nxd5  14.O-O-O  , when our attack is already decisive. There are funny lines like  14...Qe6  15.Qd2  Nxe3  16.Ng5!  Qf5  17.Bxb7!  , when Black can resign with a clear conscience. }
12. O-O
{ After ...Qa5, we need to leave the center quickly and be ready for the capture of our d-pawn. Black can take it in various ways, but none of them work.   A.  12...Nfxd5  13.Nxd5  Nxd5  14.Bd2  Qc5  15.g4  Bg6  and now  16.Ne5  or  16.c4  are decisive.   B.  12...Nfxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  14.Qe2  and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/1pp1pppp/p4n2/q2P3b/1n6/2N1BNPP/PPP2PB1/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 6 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nbxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  14.Qe2  are two similar lines; Black is helpless because of all the tempo moves, like g4 followed by knight moves or a rook to d1. It's just far too much development for a mere pawn.   C.  12...O-O-O  13.g4  Bg6  14.Nd4  Nbxd5  15.Nb3  Qb4  16.Nxd5  Nxd5  17.Bxd5  wins a piece, as  17...e6  18.a3  Qb5  19.c4  fails.It's not necessary to learn all these sample variations. Objectively speaking, by computer standards, Black has been dead lost for a while already. We still have to play the position, and humans are fallible - we are not computers. But: we have a huge attack here, and Black has a tough job defending. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "E4) Scandinavian – 2...Nf6"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 2.exd5 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5
{ After the capture, Black's main move is  2...Qxd5  , but  2...Nf6  enjoys some popularity, too. }
2... Nf6
{ Black intends to capture on d5 with the knight @@StartBracket@@most of the time@@EndBracket@@.   Now  3.c4  keeps the pawn, but Black has  3...c6  and even @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/2P5/8/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  , both interesting gambit-style moves.   The main move is, of course,  3.d4  , but I think @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5+  is comfortably better for White and avoids the murky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  Bg4!?  lines.  The bishop check was already my choice in the first edition, and there is no need for a change. Let's have a look. }
3. Bb5+
{ A disturbing check. In this line, you need to know that White will retreat the bishop to e2 soon and then aim for a setup of c4, d4, Nc3, Nf3, O-O and often h2-h3 to prevent any ...Bg4 ideas. We are always better due to our pawn center in this scenario.   Now Black plays  3...Bd7  most of the time.   The move  3...Nbd7  is rarer but not worse than the bishop move. Both moves lead to the same position described above: our strong center offers us an advantage.   We'll also briefly check the incorrect gambit  3...c6  , which you sometimes meet in online games. }
3... c6
{ This is an incorrect gambit; Black does not get enough play for the pawn. }
4. dxc6 bxc6
{ This way Black at least gets a tempo on our bishop.   After  4...Nxc6  5.Nf3  Black also has no compensation for the pawn. }
5. Be2
{ We always retreat to e2 in this chapter. Therefore I chose this move to be consistent.   There is nothing wrong about  5.Bc4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p3pppp/2p2n2/8/8/8/PPPPBPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Ba4  , either. }
5... e5 6. d3
{ We want to avoid  6.Nf3  e4  and prepare the knight development this way. }
6... Bc5 7. Nf3
{ Again, Black does not have enough for the pawn.  Comparing this with the main line of the Two Knights Defence/Fried Liver is useful. The sequence@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.Ng5  d5  5.exd5  Na5  6.Bb5+  c6  7.dxc6  bxc6  8.Be2  h6  9.Nf3  e4  leads to a similar structure. However, White has lost far more time with Nf3-g5-f3, and bishop moves.  Here our job is easy. We castle kingside next and then continue with ...Nbd2, b3 and Bb2, completing development and putting pressure on e5. Black is a pawn down and has a terrible pawn structure, giving us a large advantage. }
