[White "E4) Scandinavian – 2...Nf6"]
[Black "Scandinavian – 2.exd5 Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5
{ After the capture, Black's main move is  2...Qxd5  , but  2...Nf6  enjoys some popularity, too. }
2... Nf6
{ Black intends to capture on d5 with the knight @@StartBracket@@most of the time@@EndBracket@@.   Now  3.c4  keeps the pawn, but Black has  3...c6  and even @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/2P5/8/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  , both interesting gambit-style moves.   The main move is, of course,  3.d4  , but I think @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5+  is comfortably better for White and avoids the murky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  Bg4!?  lines.  The bishop check was already my choice in the first edition, and there is no need for a change. Let's have a look. }
3. Bb5+
{ A disturbing check. In this line, you need to know that White will retreat the bishop to e2 soon and then aim for a setup of c4, d4, Nc3, Nf3, O-O and often h2-h3 to prevent any ...Bg4 ideas. We are always better due to our pawn center in this scenario.   Now Black plays  3...Bd7  most of the time.   The move  3...Nbd7  is rarer but not worse than the bishop move. Both moves lead to the same position described above: our strong center offers us an advantage.   We'll also briefly check the incorrect gambit  3...c6  , which you sometimes meet in online games. }
3... Nbd7
{ Black blocks with the knight and hopes for  4.c4  a6  5.Ba4  b5!?  , which is quite interesting and should be avoided, in my opinion. }
4. d4 { No fun for you! } 4... Nxd5 5. Nf3
{ We focus on completing castling first. } 5... c6 6. Be2
{ Quite amazingly, this position often arises from the Alekhine Defence! The move order there is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Nf6  2.e5  Nd5  3.d4  d6  4.Nf3  dxe5  5.Nxe5  c6  6.Be2  Nd7  7.Nf3  . White is slightly better due to the space advantage and easier development.  We'll now check two setups for Black: playing for a kingside fianchetto and developing with ...Bf5 and ...e6. }
6... N7f6 { Black prepares the bishop development to f5. } 7. c4 Nb6 8. h3
{ A useful move to remember. Black is not allowed to go ...Bg4, with a potential future capture on f3 to simplify matters and maybe weaken the d4-pawn in the process. }
8... Bf5
{ We are going for a natural setup with Nc3 and O-O now, the move order is irrelevant. }
9. O-O { Or  9.Nc3  first. } 9... e6 10. Nc3
{ With a standard position, better for White due to the space advantage. } *

