1. e4 d5 2. exd5
{ After the capture, Black's main move is  2...Qxd5  , but  2...Nf6  enjoys some popularity, too. }
2... Nf6
{ Black intends to capture on d5 with the knight @@StartBracket@@most of the time@@EndBracket@@.   Now  3.c4  keeps the pawn, but Black has  3...c6  and even @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/2P5/8/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  , both interesting gambit-style moves.   The main move is, of course,  3.d4  , but I think @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5+  is comfortably better for White and avoids the murky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  Bg4!?  lines.  The bishop check was already my choice in the first edition, and there is no need for a change. Let's have a look. }
3. Bb5+
{ A disturbing check. In this line, you need to know that White will retreat the bishop to e2 soon and then aim for a setup of c4, d4, Nc3, Nf3, O-O and often h2-h3 to prevent any ...Bg4 ideas. We are always better due to our pawn center in this scenario.   Now Black plays  3...Bd7  most of the time.   The move  3...Nbd7  is rarer but not worse than the bishop move. Both moves lead to the same position described above: our strong center offers us an advantage.   We'll also briefly check the incorrect gambit  3...c6  , which you sometimes meet in online games. }
3... Bd7
{ Black's most popular move. As already mentioned, I now suggest a pragmatic approach: retreating to e2. }
4. Be2
{ We are happy to have misplaced the bishop on d7 and retreat to e2 while preventing any ...Bg4 ideas.   White has a sharper alternative in  4.Bc4  , but  4...Bg4  5.f3  Bh5  6.g4  leads to some wild complications that look good for White at the end. The problem with lines like that is: they require some study, and then you'll never get them on the board and have forgotten everything when it counts.  My suggestion keeps an advantage by simple means and reduces our workload. }
4... Nxd5
{ Black recovers the pawn.   I also found online games with  4...c6?!  , when  5.dxc6  Nxc6  6.d4  e5  7.dxe5  Nxe5  gives Black some play for the pawn. I still like White after  8.Nf3  Qc7  9.Nxe5  Qxe5  10.Nd2  , with the idea of Nf3 and c3 next. Black has active pieces, but we have no weaknesses. }
5. d4
{ Just as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/1B1P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  4.d4  Nxd5  5.Nf3  , we have a split of possible setups.   I want to check  5...Bf5  @@StartBracket@@the most common move@@EndBracket@@ and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pppbpppp/8/3n4/3P4/8/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  now, which is surprisingly solid.  Black also plays @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pppbpppp/8/3n4/3P4/8/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  here, but we'll play our standard setup of Nf3, O-O, c4, and Nc3 and have a comfortable advantage. This is a worse version of the similar ...Nbd7 line, as Black's bishop is misplaced on d7. We are better by simply centralizing and slowly pushing forward. }
5... e6
{ This looks very modest but not bad. It resembles the Rubinstein line of the French a bit, and the evaluation is similar. White must have a little something, but Black's position is solid. }
6. Nf3
{ We want to play Nf3, c4 and Nc3, a natural setup typical for the current chapter.   You may also start with  6.c4  , of course. }
6... c5
{ The main merit of ...e6 is preparing this move. In other lines of this chapter, Black often struggles to mount some attack against our center. }
7. c4 Nf6 8. Nc3 cxd4 9. Qxd4
{ There is nothing wrong with  9.Nxd4  , but after  9...Nc6  Black wants to trade on d4 and play ...Bc6 next. This feels like a small accomplishment.  I try to keep more material on the board with the queen capture. }
9... Nc6 10. Qd3
{ I think White is a bit better here, as Black is still somewhat cramped. A good way to develop is Bf4 next, looking at important squares like d6 and c7.   Black should probably play  10...Qc7  , but  11.Nb5  pushes the queen back to b8 then. }
