{ Just as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/1B1P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  4.d4  Nxd5  5.Nf3  , we have a split of possible setups.   I want to check  5...Bf5  @@StartBracket@@the most common move@@EndBracket@@ and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pppbpppp/8/3n4/3P4/8/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  now, which is surprisingly solid.  Black also plays @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pppbpppp/8/3n4/3P4/8/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  here, but we'll play our standard setup of Nf3, O-O, c4, and Nc3 and have a comfortable advantage. This is a worse version of the similar ...Nbd7 line, as Black's bishop is misplaced on d7. We are better by simply centralizing and slowly pushing forward. }
