[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F1) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "1...d6 & 1...g6 – Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and welcome to the world of ...d6 and ...g6 based Defenses.  This part of the course is about all setups that start with either @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  .  In most cases, Black does not fight for the centre with pawns but focuses on their kingside development. This approach gives us a wide choice of setups to choose from.  I recommend one standard formation to aim for whenever possible. The way to go is playing e4, d4, Nc3, f4, and Nf3, staking as much central space as possible. In most cases, we will continue with Bd3 and castle kingside. A common plan is the pawn advance e4-e5, which aims to blunt Black's bishop on g7.   Let's overview the chapters and see how and when we can apply this standard formation:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  The Pirc Defence. We play  4.f4  , according to our standard setup. This line is called the Austrian Attack and one of the main branches of the Pirc. It's an aggressive line that forces Black to be precise. As we will see, they can't get away with 'half knowledge' or improvisation.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  The Modern Defence. The Modern Defense starts with a kingside fianchetto, but Black does not yet determine their central pawn formation. In almost all cases, our f4 based setup works well, and the play develops similarly to the Pirc.   C.  1...d6  Other Defences. Black can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  , but avoid the Pirc. In some cases, we can still play with f4 and reach a nice advantage, but the main line of this chapter requires a different approach. It is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  , the modern way to reach a Philidor Defence. I suggest an aggressive line:  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Rg1  prepares an early kingside attack and will often hit your opponent by surprise.  This part of the repertoire is completely new compared to the first edition. The main reason for the changes is the conceptual clarity of the new set of lines. I suggested Be3 based setups against the Pirc and Modern in the first edition. These are good lines, but their main asset is the flexibility of not yet committing to a kingside pawn formation. Exploiting this asset is sophisticated. Therefore, the first edition featured a range of pawn structures with added complexity and move order tricks.  The new set of lines, based on f4, is simpler to learn, as we follow a common concept and don't have to deal with move order finesses. In the Philidor, I switched to the Rg1 line for two reasons. Due to move order issues, the Classical lines of the first edition were more complicated than I liked. My new suggestion is fun to play and poses Black problems early on. Black can't play on 'auto-pilot', as they often manage against more conservative play by White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F2) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense"]
[Black "1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ This chapter examines the Pirc Defence after the moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  . Black prepares the kingside Fianchetto and delays the immediate fight for central control. They allow us to build a strong center but are confident to attack it later. Black has multiple ways to strike at our center, most importantly the moves ...c5 and ...e5.   After 3...g6, White has a wide choice of possible systems against the Pirc. In the first edition, I recommended @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be3  , which remains a strong option. One drawback of my suggestion was that it allows a wide range of replies, often leading to rather sophisticated move order issues.  For this course, I decided to switch to a different reply that is considerably simpler to master: the Austrian Attack @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.f4  , White's most aggressive option. Let's discuss this further once the move is on the board. }
4. f4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F2) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense"]
[Black "1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense 3...g6 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nc3 c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4
{ We push the f-pawn and increase our pawn control of the center, showing our aggressive intentions. The label 'aggressive' often suggests that tactical complications lead to an additional workload. Fortunately, this is not the case here. On the contrary: our maximalist approach reduces Black's choice, as only few replies are even playable. I'll present an overview after the natural continuation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg7  5.Nf3  , hang on. }
4... Bg7 { The logical follow-up to Black's third move. } 5. Nf3
{ We develop the knight to the natural square and get one move closer to kingside castling. I promised to present an overview of Black's possible replies... here it is.   A. Black immediately attacks our center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  , leading to complications that are favourable for White and tricky for Black to handle.  B. Black plays the flexible move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  and only after our reply  6.Bd3  decides how to fight our imposing center. In my mind, only  6...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  gives Black fair chances, while other continuations are downright bad or difficult to play in practice. Of course, we'll look closely at Black's inferior options later. }
5... c5
{ Black immediately strikes at our center, even before completing kingside castling. From a strategic point of view, playing ...c5 makes a lot of sense. Our e4-e5 push is most effective if supported by the d-pawn and the f-pawn, like in the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  6.Bd3  c6?  7.O-O  b5  8.e5!  dxe5  9.fxe5  , when the e-pawn is safely guarded. It's desirable for Black to trade the c-pawn for our d-pawn and reduce the danger of our standard idea e4-e5.   If we answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  with  6.Be2?!  Black is happy to play  6...cxd4  when it will be much more difficult for White to play e4-e5 favourably. There is no support from the d-pawn, which is a crucial difference. This leads to the conclusion that we should not allow the capture on d4.  Fortunately, White has more than one good option available. Here's a quick overview:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.e5  starts an immediate attack. This variation is well explored by theory - White has chances to keep an edge after long complications.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d5  is less popular but not bad. It leads to a Benoni pawn structure, which would be unusual for our repertoire.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.dxc5  , which is my recommendation. This line is easy to play and difficult for Black to handle. After  6...Qa5  I suggest  7.Qd3!  , a surprising but strong move. }
6. dxc5
{ As mentioned in the notes to move five: White has some good alternatives, but I like this approach. }
6... Qa5
{ The only good move and Black's idea behind playing the quick ...c5. The queen pins our knight and enables the threat ...Nxe4.   We can't play @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.cxd6?  now, as  7...Nxe4  is great for Black. We need to provide some protection for the e-pawn, stopping this threat. }
7. Qd3
{ A surprising move, but it is strong! The idea is quite concrete: Black's only good reply is @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2NQ1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qxc5  , when  8.Be3  Qa5  9.Qb5+  leads to an initiative for White, which will not be easy for our opponent to handle. They may easily misstep, given that 7.Qd3 is still not as well known as White's main continuation.   What is White's main move, and is something wrong with it? The most popular move for White is  7.Bd3  , followed by  7...Qxc5  8.Qe2  to prepare Be3. White has slightly better chances in this line, too. }
7... O-O
{ This move is bad, but it requires the correct response to refute it convincingly. }
8. Qb5
{ This move is much stronger than  8.cxd6?  Nxe4  , when the game gets very murky.  After the queen move, Black is in huge trouble. }
8... Qxb5
{ What else?   8...Qd8  9.cxd6  exd6  10.Be3  is very sad for Black, too. We are a pawn up and have a large positional advantage to boot. }
9. Bxb5 dxc5
{ Black regains the pawn, but that's not the end of the story.   Black may also play  9...a6  10.Be2  and only then  10...dxc5  , but  11.e5  is very similar to the line we are about to examine. }
10. e5
{ That's the problem: we attack our opponent's knight and gain access to the fantastic square d5. }
10... Ne8
{ The other knight moves are no improvement - @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/pp2ppbp/5np1/1Bp1P3/5P2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nh5  11.Nd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/pp2ppbp/5np1/1Bp1P3/5P2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nfd7  11.Nd5  are just as bad. Black can't avoid disaster on c7 or e7. }
11. Nd5
{ And it's curtains already. We threaten Nxe7+, and the sequence Bxe8, followed by Nc7 - Black loses material now. }
*

