1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4
{ We push the f-pawn and increase our pawn control of the center, showing our aggressive intentions. The label 'aggressive' often suggests that tactical complications lead to an additional workload. Fortunately, this is not the case here. On the contrary: our maximalist approach reduces Black's choice, as only a small set of replies are even playable. I'll present an overview after the natural continuation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg7  5.Nf3  , hang on. }
4... Bg7 { The logical follow-up to Black's third move. } 5. Nf3
{ We develop the knight to the natural square and get one move closer to kingside castling. I promised to present an overview of Black's possible replies... here it is.   A. Black immediately attacks our center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  , leading to complications that are favourable for White and tricky for Black to handle.  B. Black plays the flexible move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  and only after our reply  6.Bd3  decides how to fight our imposing center. In my mind, only  6...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  gives Black fair chances, while other continuations are downright bad or difficult to play in practice. Of course, we'll look closely at Black's inferior options later. }
5... c5
{ Black immediately strikes at our center, even before completing kingside castling. From a strategic point of view, playing ...c5 makes a lot of sense. Our e4-e5 push is most effective if supported by the d-pawn and the f-pawn, like in the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  6.Bd3  c6?  7.O-O  b5  8.e5!  dxe5  9.fxe5  , when the e-pawn is safely guarded. It's desirable to trade the c-pawn for our d-pawn and reduce the danger of our standard idea e4-e5.   If we'd answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  with  6.Be2?!  Black is happy to play  6...cxd4  when it will be much more difficult for White to play e4-e5 favourably. There is no support from the d-pawn, which is a crucial difference. This leads to the conclusion that we should not allow the capture on d4.  Fortunately, White has more than one good option available. Here's a quick overview:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.e5  starts an immediate attack. This variation is well explored by theory - White has chances to keep an edge after long complications.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d5  is less popular but not bad. It leads to a Benoni pawn structure, which would be unusual for our repertoire.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.dxc5  , which is my recommendation. This line is easy to play and difficult for Black to handle. After  6...Qa5  I suggest  7.Qd3!  , a surprising but strong move. }
6. dxc5
{ As mentioned in the notes to move five: White has some good alternatives, but I like this approach. }
6... Qa5
{ The only good move and Black's idea behind playing the quick ...c5. The queen pins our knight and enables the threat ...Nxe4.   We can't play @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.cxd6?  now, as  7...Nxe4  is great for Black. We need to lend some protection to the e-pawn, stopping this threat. }
7. Qd3
{ A surprising move, but it is strong! The idea is quite concrete: Black's only good reply is @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2NQ1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qxc5  , when  8.Be3  Qa5  9.Qb5+  leads to an initiative for White, which will not be easy for our opponent to handle. They may easily misstep, given that 7.Qd3 is still not as well known as White's main continuation.   What is White's main move, and is something wrong with it? The most popular move for White is  7.Bd3  , followed by  7...Qxc5  8.Qe2  to prepare Be3. White has slightly better chances in this line, too. }
7... Qxc5
{ Black's only playable move and the usual choice. They intended to answer @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  with  7...Qxc5  , after all.  Are there any alternatives worth checking? We study @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2NQ1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  in a trainable line, as it at least involves a tricky decision. Other moves are even less of a challenge:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2NQ1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nxe4??  is a blunder due to  8.Qb5+  Nc6  9.Qxa5  Bxc3+  10.Qxc3  , with an extra piece for White.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2NQ1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...dxc5?  8.Qb5+  Qxb5  9.Bxb5+  Bd7  10.e5  is devastating. Black's knight has no good square, and Be3 & O-O-O come next. }
8. Be3
{ One point of 7.Qd3: we gain a tempo on Black's queen and prepare queenside castling. }
8... Qa5
{ Again, the only good move.   The move  8...Qc7?  is refuted by  9.e5  , pushing Black's knight away and enabling Nd5 with a tempo. After  9...Ng4  10.Nd5  Qd8  11.O-O-O  we have an overwhelming position, as  11...dxe5??  12.Nf6+  leads to checkmate.   Against @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2q5/4PP2/2NQBN2/PPP3PP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qb4  we have many good moves, but I like  9.a3  , asking Black what the queen is doing on b4 in the first place. The point of our move is  9...Qxb2??  10.Ra2!  , trapping the queen! Black has to go to a5 after all when  @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/8/1q2PP2/P1NQBN2/1PP3PP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qa5  10.Qb5+  is an improved version of our main line, while @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q7/4PP2/P1NQBN2/1PP3PP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O-O  looks strong, too. }
9. Qb5+
{ We force a queen trade under favourable circumstances, as the following sequence shows. }
9... Qxb5
{ Black has to take our queen.   After  9...Nc6  10.Qxa5  Nxa5  11.Nb5  Black is in severe trouble. There is no good way to cover c7. }
10. Bxb5+
{ This is stronger than  10.Nxb5  Na6  , when we attack a7, but our e-pawn is also hanging.  After our move, Black has a difficult choice: how to answer the check? }
10... Nc6
{ This is certainly the best square for the knight, but Black seems reluctant to create a pin voluntarily. }
11. O-O-O
{ We continue our development with the natural queenside castling. Now Black needs to decide what to do with their light-squared bishop. One idea for us is a kingside expansion with h3&g4. If we manage that, the bishop will have limited scope. Therefore 11...Bg4 makes some sense, but it will likely cost Black the bishop pair.   Note that the immediate  11.h3  is a bit slow due to  11...a6  . Meanwhile, after @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/1B6/4PP2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/R3K2R w KQkq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.O-O-O  , the move  11...a6?!  is worse because of  12.Bxc6+  bxc6  13.e5! }
11... O-O
{ This is by far the most common move in practice.   After  11...Bg4  12.Rhf1  Nd7  13.Nd5  Rc8  14.a3  a6  15.Be2  , I prefer White slightly. In the long run, Black will have to give up their bishop on f3. Still, 11...Bg4 looks reasonable for Black. }
12. h3
{ This is a universally strong move. We prepare g4 but also take away the important square. This might make a future e4-e5 much more dangerous. Here is a sample line for this idea: @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/1B6/4PP2/2N1BN1P/PPP3P1/2KR3R b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Be6  13.Rhe1  Rfc8  14.e5!  dxe5  15.fxe5  Nd7  16.Ng5  Ndxe5  17.Nxe6  fxe6  18.Ne4  , when we are in great shape. The black e-pawns are weak, and we have fantastic pieces.  I think it is enough to know these ideas. Thus I cut the line after the key move 12.h3, which looks nice for White. }
