{ We develop the knight to the natural square and get one move closer to kingside castling. I promised to present an overview of Black's possible replies... here it is.   A. Black immediately attacks our center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  , leading to complications that are favourable for White and tricky for Black to handle.  B. Black plays the flexible move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  and only after our reply  6.Bd3  decides how to fight our imposing center. In my mind, only  6...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  gives Black fair chances, while other continuations are downright bad or difficult to play in practice. Of course, we'll look closely at Black's inferior options later. }
5... c5
{ Black immediately strikes at our center, even before completing kingside castling. From a strategic point of view, playing ...c5 makes a lot of sense. Our e4-e5 push is most effective if supported by the d-pawn and the f-pawn, like in the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  6.Bd3  c6?  7.O-O  b5  8.e5!  dxe5  9.fxe5  , when the e-pawn is safely guarded. It's desirable to trade the c-pawn for our d-pawn and reduce the danger of our standard idea e4-e5.   If we'd answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  with  6.Be2?!  Black is happy to play  6...cxd4  when it will be much more difficult for White to play e4-e5 favourably. There is no support from the d-pawn, which is a crucial difference. This leads to the conclusion that we should not allow the capture on d4.  Fortunately, White has more than one good option available. Here's a quick overview:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.e5  starts an immediate attack. This variation is well explored by theory - White has chances to keep an edge after long complications.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d5  is less popular but not bad. It leads to a Benoni pawn structure, which would be unusual for our repertoire.  C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.dxc5  , which is my recommendation. This line is easy to play and difficult for Black to handle. After  6...Qa5  I suggest  7.Qd3!  , a surprising but strong move. }
6. dxc5
{ As mentioned in the notes to move five: White has some good alternatives, but I like this approach. }
6... Qa5
{ The only good move and Black's idea behind playing the quick ...c5. The queen pins our knight and enables the threat ...Nxe4.   We can't play @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.cxd6?  now, as  7...Nxe4  is great for Black. We need to lend some protection to the e-pawn, stopping this threat. }
7. Qd3
{ A surprising move, but it is strong! The idea is quite concrete: Black's only good reply is @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2NQ1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qxc5  , when  8.Be3  Qa5  9.Qb5+  leads to an initiative for White, which will not be easy for our opponent to handle. They may easily misstep, given that 7.Qd3 is still not as well known as White's main continuation.   What is White's main move, and is something wrong with it? The most popular move for White is  7.Bd3  , followed by  7...Qxc5  8.Qe2  to prepare Be3. White has slightly better chances in this line, too. }
7... Qxc5
{ Black's only playable move and the usual choice. They intended to answer @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  with  7...Qxc5  , after all.  Are there any alternatives worth checking? We study @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2NQ1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  in a trainable line, as it at least involves a tricky decision. Other moves are even less of a challenge:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2NQ1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nxe4??  is a blunder due to  8.Qb5+  Nc6  9.Qxa5  Bxc3+  10.Qxc3  , with an extra piece for White.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q1P5/4PP2/2NQ1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...dxc5?  8.Qb5+  Qxb5  9.Bxb5+  Bd7  10.e5  is devastating. Black's knight has no good square, and Be3 & O-O-O comes next. }
8. Be3
{ One point of 7.Qd3: we gain a tempo on Black's queen and prepare queenside castling. }
8... Qa5
{ Again, the only good move.   The move  8...Qc7?  is refuted by  9.e5  , pushing Black's knight away and enabling Nd5 with a tempo. After  9...Ng4  10.Nd5  Qd8  11.O-O-O  we have an overwhelming position, as  11...dxe5??  12.Nf6+  leads to checkmate.   Against @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2q5/4PP2/2NQBN2/PPP3PP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qb4  we have many good moves, but I like  9.a3  , asking Black what the queen is doing on b4 in the first place. The point of our move is  9...Qxb2??  10.Ra2!  , trapping the queen! Black has to go to a5 after all when  @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/8/1q2PP2/P1NQBN2/1PP3PP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qa5  10.Qb5+  is an improved version of our main line, while @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/q7/4PP2/P1NQBN2/1PP3PP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O-O  looks strong, too. }
9. Qb5+
{ We force a queen trade under favourable circumstances, as the following sequence shows. }
9... Qxb5
{ Black has to take our queen.   After  9...Nc6  10.Qxa5  Nxa5  11.Nb5  Black is in severe trouble. There is no good way to cover c7. }
10. Bxb5+
{ This is stronger than  10.Nxb5  Na6  , when we attack a7, but our e-pawn is also hanging.  After our move, Black has a difficult choice: how to answer the check? }
10... Bd7
{ This move is played most of the time, but 10...Nc6 looks like a better option. }
11. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 12. O-O-O
{ This position is surprisingly difficult for Black to play. The central breakthrough e4-e5 is dangerous in connection with Nb5 in some cases. I see no fully satisfactory way for Black now. }
12... O-O
{ This is the move that was played in most of the games that I found, but White is better after it.  I didn't find anything great for Black, though. Here are two ideas:  A. @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/8/4PP2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/2KR3R b kq - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...a6  13.Rhe1  Ng4  14.Bd4  Bxd4  15.Rxd4  is great for White, as e4-e5 is looming.   B. @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/8/4PP2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/2KR3R b kq - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Ng4  13.Bd4  e5  14.fxe5  Ngxe5  15.Nb5  hits the weak d6-pawn and wins. }
13. e5 Ng4
{ Or  13...dxe5  14.fxe5  Ng4  15.Rxd7  Nxe3  16.Rxb7  Nxg2  17.Nd5  and White wins. After  17...e6  18.Nf6+  Bxf6  19.exf6  ,  White has not yet won material, but will have a dominating position with Ne5 next. }
14. exd6
{ There also is  14.Bg1  Bh6  15.Kb1!  Bxf4  16.Rd4  , but it's a very odd idea and tough to remember. }
14... Nxe3
{ Here  14...exd6  15.Bd4  is hopeless for Black. The d6-pawn is doomed, and they have badly placed pieces. }
15. dxe7 { A forced line - we are a pawn up for nothing at the end. } 15...
Nxd1 16. exf8=Q+ Nxf8 17. Nxd1
{ All this mayhem for just a pawn! Well, we can be delighted with this result, of course. I think the 7.Qd3 idea is dangerous for Black and may easily lead to a fantastic position for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F2) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense"]
[Black "1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense 3...g6 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nc3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4
{ We push the f-pawn and increase our pawn control of the center, showing our aggressive intentions. The label 'aggressive' often suggests that tactical complications lead to an additional workload. Fortunately, this is not the case here. On the contrary: our maximalist approach reduces Black's choice, as only a small set of replies are even playable. I'll present an overview after the natural continuation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg7  5.Nf3  , hang on. }
4... Bg7 { The logical follow-up to Black's third move. } 5. Nf3
{ We develop the knight to the natural square and get one move closer to kingside castling. I promised to present an overview of Black's possible replies... here it is.   A. Black immediately attacks our center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  , leading to complications that are favourable for White and tricky for Black to handle.  B. Black plays the flexible move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  and only after our reply  6.Bd3  decides how to fight our imposing center. In my mind, only  6...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  gives Black fair chances, while other continuations are downright bad or difficult to play in practice. Of course, we'll look closely at Black's inferior options later. }
5... O-O
{ This is Black's most popular move by far. They delay the decision about the central counterplay for a move. }
6. Bd3
{ Our concept against 5...O-O is based on kingside castling. Playing 6.Bd3 is the best way to prepare it, as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bc4?  is a mistake due to the instructive tactic  6...Nxe4!  7.Nxe4  d5  , when our central phalanx is destroyed.   After our move  6.Bd3  Black has a wide choice, but I think that only  6...Nc6  gets Black close to equal chances. This move is my recommendation in my Lifetime Repertoires: Pirc Defence. My work on this course made me appreciate the 'Austrian Attack' more.  Black's path to a good game is narrow! Let's make an overview of Black's options - we'll check all of them in a trainable.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  is the best line for Black, in my mind. Black plans to strike at our center with ...e5.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Na6  prepares the move ...c5. This seems to be Black's second-best option. White often gets a dangerous attack, but Black has some counter chances.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5?  is amazingly popular, but  7.dxc5  dxc5  8.e5  gives White a large advantage.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4?  is known to be bad since Fischer's days, but still played in lower-level games. After  7.h3  , we gain the bishop pair on top of everything.  E. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6?  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6?  is far too slow. We'll have a look at @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6  to demonstrate Black's problems. }
6... c5
{ This move is amazingly popular, but a mistake, I think Black sometimes confuses the move order and thinks that @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  6.Bd3  c5  are the same thing - they are not! }
7. dxc5
{ We take the pawn, the best response and just the same as after 5...c5, which is a far better moment for the pawn push. }
7... dxc5
{ Here  7...Qa5?  doesn't work due to the simple  8.cxd6  , winning a pawn. Compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.dxc5  Qa5  , our e-pawn is safely protected. }
8. e5
{ Our strategic goal in the Austrian Attack is to establish a well-protected pawn on e5 that blunts the g7-bishop. The position on the board is a perfect example of a successful realization of this strategy. }
8... Nd5
{ Black centralizes the knight. We are happy to trade it and later gain time on the queen. }
9. Nxd5
{ Simple and good. After the sequence  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Qe2  , we are ready to gain time on Black's queen. }
9... Qxd5 10. Qe2
{ A strong move. We want to play Be4 next, placing the bishop in a commanding position. This is one huge asset of our f4/e5 pawn wedge: control of the e4-square.  In this case, having the pawn on c5 is a huge problem for Black. It weakens key squares, like b5 and d5, makes the bishop even stronger on e4, and serves as a target after a later Be3. }
10... Nc6
{ We'll have a look at this move to demonstrate White's setup.  The alternatives are similar or no improvement:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/pp2ppbp/6p1/2pqP3/5P2/3B1N2/PPP1Q1PP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bg4  11.Be4  Qd7  12.Be3  is much better for White, similar to our examined move.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/pp2ppbp/6p1/2pqP3/5P2/3B1N2/PPP1Q1PP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bf5  stops our idea, but  11.Bxf5  gxf5  is not a happy sight for Black, either. After  12.Be3  @@StartBracket@@or similar moves@@EndBracket@@ Black's pawn structure is a long-term problem. We are also much faster on the d-file, and c5 is vulnerable, as usual in the 6...c5 line. }
11. Be4 Qd8 12. Be3
{ You may also start with  12.c3  here and play the bishop on the next move.   White has a large advantage now, based on the strong pressure on the queenside and Black's passive g7-bishop. I don't see a good way for Black to continue. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/2p1P3/4BP2/4BN2/PPP1Q1PP/R3K2R b KQ - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nd4  13.Bxd4  cxd4  14.O-O-O  wins the d-pawn and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/2p1P3/4BP2/4BN2/PPP1Q1PP/R3K2R b KQ - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qa5+  13.c3  Bg4  14.O-O  Rad8  15.Qc4  is just one possible line to show that Black cannot hold the queenside together. }
*

