[White "F2) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense"]
[Black "1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense 3...g6 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nc3 O-O #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4
{ We push the f-pawn and increase our pawn control of the center, showing our aggressive intentions. The label 'aggressive' often suggests that tactical complications lead to an additional workload. Fortunately, this is not the case here. On the contrary: our maximalist approach reduces Black's choice, as only a small set of replies are even playable. I'll present an overview after the natural continuation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg7  5.Nf3  , hang on. }
4... Bg7 { The logical follow-up to Black's third move. } 5. Nf3
{ We develop the knight to the natural square and get one move closer to kingside castling. I promised to present an overview of Black's possible replies... here it is.   A. Black immediately attacks our center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  , leading to complications that are favourable for White and tricky for Black to handle.  B. Black plays the flexible move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  and only after our reply  6.Bd3  decides how to fight our imposing center. In my mind, only  6...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  gives Black fair chances, while other continuations are downright bad or difficult to play in practice. Of course, we'll look closely at Black's inferior options later. }
5... O-O
{ This is Black's most popular move by far. They delay the decision about the central counterplay for a move. }
6. Bd3
{ Our concept against 5...O-O is based on kingside castling. Playing 6.Bd3 is the best way to prepare it, as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bc4?  is a mistake due to the instructive tactic  6...Nxe4!  7.Nxe4  d5  , when our central phalanx is destroyed.   After our move  6.Bd3  Black has a wide choice, but I think that only  6...Nc6  gets Black close to equal chances. This move is my recommendation in my Lifetime Repertoires: Pirc Defence. My work on this course made me appreciate the 'Austrian Attack' more.  Black's path to a good game is narrow! Let's make an overview of Black's options - we'll check all of them in a trainable.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  is the best line for Black, in my mind. Black plans to strike at our center with ...e5.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Na6  prepares the move ...c5. This seems to be Black's second-best option. White often gets a dangerous attack, but Black has some counter chances.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5?  is amazingly popular, but  7.dxc5  dxc5  8.e5  gives White a large advantage.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4?  is known to be bad since Fischer's days, but still played in lower-level games. After  7.h3  , we gain the bishop pair on top of everything.  E. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6?  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6?  is far too slow. We'll have a look at @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6  to demonstrate Black's problems. }
6... Bg4
{ A bad move, but still played quite frequently below master level. There is a very famous Fischer game that featured this move. In 1963, the 11th World Champion already demonstrated the best play against it. }
7. h3
{ Give me the bishop pair, please!   I prefer this move over  7.e5  , which also gives a clear advantage. }
7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 { We have gained the bishop pair for nothing, a huge asset. }
8... Nc6
{ This is Black's idea. They removed our knight, thus weakening the control of the d4-square. }
9. Be3
{ We cover d4 and now threaten e4-e5, with devastating effect. Black has to stop this move. }
9... e5 { The only move. Now it's good to know the best reply. } 10. dxe5
{ By far the best move.   After  10.d5  Nd4  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2pbp/2np1np1/4p3/3PPP2/2NBBQ1P/PPP3P1/R3K2R w KQ e6 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.fxe5  dxe5  11.d5  Nd4  Black gets more counterplay than we should allow. }
10... dxe5 11. f5
{ We gain more space and have a simple plan now: g4-g5 and Black resigns. It's very tough for Black to stay in the game now. }
11... Nd4
{ The only move to put up a fight.   In the mentioned game Fischer-Benko, Black played  11...gxf5?  12.Qxf5  Nd4  , a worse version of the knight jump. After  13.Qf2  Ne8  14.O-O  Nd6  15.Qg3  Kh8  16.Qg4  c6  17.Qh5  Qe8  18.Bxd4  exd4  Fischer played one of his most famous moves,  19.Rf6!!  - what a shot! The remaining moves were  19...Kg8  20.e5  h6  21.Ne2  , and Benko resigned. }
12. Qf2
{ The best square for our queen. Now Black only has one defence that generates some counterplay. They need to play @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2pbp/5np1/4pP2/3nP3/2NBB2P/PPP2QP1/R3K2R b KQ - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...b5  13.g4  c5  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2pbp/5np1/4pP2/3nP3/2NBB2P/PPP2QP1/R3K2R b KQ - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...c5  13.g4  b5  , leading to the same position. }
12... b5
{ The alternative route  12...c5  13.g4  b5  leads to the same thing. Black needs to play this quick pawn storm. Otherwise, our simple  g4-g5 idea is crushing. }
13. g4
{ Here we go! I am continuing this line rather deeply, but there is a crucial point on move 16, when the best move makes a huge difference. }
13... c5 14. g5 b4
{ Black's best try.   After  14...c4  15.gxf6  Bxf6  16.O-O-O  cxd3  17.Rxd3  White is more or less winning, with Nd5 to come. }
15. gxf6 Bxf6 { Black is threatening ...Bh4 now, a crucial moment. } 16. O-O
{ This move leads to a great position for White, while  16.Ne2  c4!  is still playable for Black.  Now we are much better, as @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p4p1p/5bp1/2p1pP2/1p1nP3/2NBB2P/PPP2Q2/R4RK1 b - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...bxc3  17.bxc3  c4  18.fxg6  cxd3  19.gxh7+  Kxh7  20.cxd4  illustrates. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F2) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense"]
[Black "1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense 3...g6 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nc3 O-O #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4
{ We push the f-pawn and increase our pawn control of the center, showing our aggressive intentions. The label 'aggressive' often suggests that tactical complications lead to an additional workload. Fortunately, this is not the case here. On the contrary: our maximalist approach reduces Black's choice, as only a small set of replies are even playable. I'll present an overview after the natural continuation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg7  5.Nf3  , hang on. }
4... Bg7 { The logical follow-up to Black's third move. } 5. Nf3
{ We develop the knight to the natural square and get one move closer to kingside castling. I promised to present an overview of Black's possible replies... here it is.   A. Black immediately attacks our center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  , leading to complications that are favourable for White and tricky for Black to handle.  B. Black plays the flexible move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  and only after our reply  6.Bd3  decides how to fight our imposing center. In my mind, only  6...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  gives Black fair chances, while other continuations are downright bad or difficult to play in practice. Of course, we'll look closely at Black's inferior options later. }
5... O-O
{ This is Black's most popular move by far. They delay the decision about the central counterplay for a move. }
6. Bd3
{ Our concept against 5...O-O is based on kingside castling. Playing 6.Bd3 is the best way to prepare it, as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bc4?  is a mistake due to the instructive tactic  6...Nxe4!  7.Nxe4  d5  , when our central phalanx is destroyed.   After our move  6.Bd3  Black has a wide choice, but I think that only  6...Nc6  gets Black close to equal chances. This move is my recommendation in my Lifetime Repertoires: Pirc Defence. My work on this course made me appreciate the 'Austrian Attack' more.  Black's path to a good game is narrow! Let's make an overview of Black's options - we'll check all of them in a trainable.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  is the best line for Black, in my mind. Black plans to strike at our center with ...e5.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Na6  prepares the move ...c5. This seems to be Black's second-best option. White often gets a dangerous attack, but Black has some counter chances.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5?  is amazingly popular, but  7.dxc5  dxc5  8.e5  gives White a large advantage.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4?  is known to be bad since Fischer's days, but still played in lower-level games. After  7.h3  , we gain the bishop pair on top of everything.  E. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6?  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6?  is far too slow. We'll have a look at @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6  to demonstrate Black's problems. }
6... c6
{ Black prepares the move ...b5, a typical idea in the Pirc. The problem, in this case, is that it is far too slow against our 'maximalist' setup. We now see some typical ideas of the Austrian Attack. }
7. O-O { We castle first and want to play e4-e5 next. } 7... b5 8. e5
{ This type of position is the dream scenario of the Austrian Attack player. We establish the pawn wedge d4/e5/f4, which accomplishes much:  It blunts Black's g7-bishop.It pushes the knight away, a key defender of the kingside.It clears the e4-square for our pieces.  These points already suggest that we are playing for an attack on the kingside. A key idea for us is Qe1-h4, as we will see. }
8... Ne8 9. Qe1
{ I wanted to include this move in the trainable line, as it is a common attacking resource, as mentioned.  Black has tremendous problems now, even to pose problems. In computer terms, it is already a lost cause.  I'll show you a line that has happened in some online games: @@StartFEN@@rnbqnrk1/p3ppbp/2pp2p1/1p2P3/3P1P2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1QRK1 b - - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...b4  10.Ne4  a5  11.Neg5  , when  11...h6  can already be met by  12.Nxf7  , but @@StartFEN@@rnbqnrk1/4ppb1/2pp2pp/p3P1N1/1p1P1P2/3B1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1QRK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qh4  is strong, too. }
*

