[White "F2) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense"]
[Black "1...d6 & 1...g6 – Pirc Defense 3...g6 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nc3 O-O #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4
{ We push the f-pawn and increase our pawn control of the center, showing our aggressive intentions. The label 'aggressive' often suggests that tactical complications lead to an additional workload. Fortunately, this is not the case here. On the contrary: our maximalist approach reduces Black's choice, as only a small set of replies are even playable. I'll present an overview after the natural continuation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg7  5.Nf3  , hang on. }
4... Bg7 { The logical follow-up to Black's third move. } 5. Nf3
{ We develop the knight to the natural square and get one move closer to kingside castling. I promised to present an overview of Black's possible replies... here it is.   A. Black immediately attacks our center with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  , leading to complications that are favourable for White and tricky for Black to handle.  B. Black plays the flexible move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  and only after our reply  6.Bd3  decides how to fight our imposing center. In my mind, only  6...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  gives Black fair chances, while other continuations are downright bad or difficult to play in practice. Of course, we'll look closely at Black's inferior options later. }
5... O-O
{ This is Black's most popular move by far. They delay the decision about the central counterplay for a move. }
6. Bd3
{ Our concept against 5...O-O is based on kingside castling. Playing 6.Bd3 is the best way to prepare it, as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bc4?  is a mistake due to the instructive tactic  6...Nxe4!  7.Nxe4  d5  , when our central phalanx is destroyed.   After our move  6.Bd3  Black has a wide choice, but I think that only  6...Nc6  gets Black close to equal chances. This move is my recommendation in my Lifetime Repertoires: Pirc Defence. My work on this course made me appreciate the 'Austrian Attack' more.  Black's path to a good game is narrow! Let's make an overview of Black's options - we'll check all of them in a trainable.  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  is the best line for Black, in my mind. Black plans to strike at our center with ...e5.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Na6  prepares the move ...c5. This seems to be Black's second-best option. White often gets a dangerous attack, but Black has some counter chances.   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5?  is amazingly popular, but  7.dxc5  dxc5  8.e5  gives White a large advantage.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4?  is known to be bad since Fischer's days, but still played in lower-level games. After  7.h3  , we gain the bishop pair on top of everything.  E. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6?  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6?  is far too slow. We'll have a look at @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6  to demonstrate Black's problems. }
6... Na6
{ The immediate 6...c5 is bad, as we examine in a trainable line. With 6...Na6, Black prepares the push of the c-pawn. }
7. O-O { We castle kingside, as planned. } 7... c5
{ The only sensible move in connection with 6...Na6, for sure. } 8. d5
{ This is best, reaching a Benoni structure.  Usually, we like to advance the e-pawn in the Austrian Attack, but it does not work well here. After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/n2p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - c6 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.e5  Black has  8...Nd7!  , when our central pawn wedge crumbles. Taking on c5 is no good, as Black can take with the knight.   It's conceptually important to understand that @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/n2p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - c6 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.dxc5?!  dxc5?  9.e5!  is great for White - our e-pawn is strong, and Black has no pressure against it. When Black plays the correct @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/n2p1np1/2P5/4PP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nxc5  , however, we have no clear way forward in the center. Playing e4-e5 is much more difficult, as the d-pawn is missing.  Alright, back to the move that we play. Advancing the d-pawn is welcome, as it gains space in a different way than our more common e4-e5. Black usually tries to generate play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@...b7-b5 is an idea@@EndBracket@@, while we aim for the kingside and the center.  We'll check two moves now: 8...Bg4, which looks like Black's best, and 8...Nc7, aiming for quick queenside play. }
8... Nc7
{ Black prepares to play on the queenside with ...b5.   They can also start this idea with  8...Rb8  , which will often lead to the same type of position. }
9. a4
{ It's best for us first to ensure that Black is not getting too much activity on the queenside. We already have accomplished much in the center, so there is no rush. }
9... a6
{ Black sticks with the queenside plans.   Note that  9...e6?!  is best answered by  10.dxe6  , when both  10...fxe6  11.e5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppn2pbp/3pPnp1/2p5/P3PP2/2NB1N2/1PP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bxe6  11.f5  look great for White. }
10. Qe1
{ Getting to h4 is a typical plan in the Austrian Attack. We want to mix our active ideas like Qe1 with prophylactic play against Black's queenside ambitions.   Note that  10.a5?!  is not so great due to  10...Nb5!  , a surprising resource. }
10... Rb8
{ Black is now ready to push ...b5. Our answer is simple but strong. } 11. a5
{ Now, this advance is much stronger than on the move before. Have you wondered what would have happened after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pn1ppbp/p2p1np1/2pP4/P3PP2/2NB1N2/1PP3PP/R1B1QRK1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...b6  , stopping our a-pawn? This move is far too slow and met with  11.Qh4  , when we are ready for our attack. One dangerous attack scheme looks like  11...Rb8  12.f5  b5  13.Bh6  bxa4  14.Ng5  - now the threat is fxg6, followed by Bxg7, Rxf6 and Q@@StartBracket@@x@@EndBracket@@h7#! This attacking plan happens A LOT in the 6...Na6 line! }
11... b5 { Black manages their intended pawn push. } 12. axb6 Rxb6
{ We have reached an interesting moment. White has a range of possibilities that are all promising. }
13. Na4
{ I like this idea, as it ensures that our center and queenside are rock-solid after @@StartFEN@@2bq1rk1/2n1ppbp/pr1p1np1/2pP4/N3PP2/3B1N2/1PP3PP/R1B1QRK1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rb4  14.c4!  , the point of the knight jump.   Instead of this concept, it is also possible to play more aggressively. Stockfish suggests the interesting  13.f5!?  , for instance, but agrees with my human assessment that the more prophylactic knight move is best. }
13... Rb4 14. c4
{ Very nice! Now we have optimal central support, and our queenside is safe. With Black's counterplay slowed down, we can think of attacking! Note that the move c4 has covered d5, which gets e4-e5 on the map. White has a large advantage, as Black struggles to find enough active ideas to counter our space advantage. }
*

