6... Na6
{ The immediate 6...c5 is bad, as we examine in a trainable line. With 6...Na6, Black prepares the push of the c-pawn. }
7. O-O { We castle kingside, as planned. } 7... c5
{ The only sensible move in connection with 6...Na6, for sure. } 8. d5
{ This is best, reaching a Benoni structure.  Usually, we like to advance the e-pawn in the Austrian Attack, but it does not work well here. After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/n2p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - c6 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.e5  Black has  8...Nd7!  , when our central pawn wedge crumbles. Taking on c5 is no good, as Black can take with the knight.   It's conceptually important to understand that @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/n2p1np1/2p5/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - c6 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.dxc5?!  dxc5?  9.e5!  is great for White - our e-pawn is strong, and Black has no pressure against it. When Black plays the correct @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/n2p1np1/2P5/4PP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nxc5  , however, we have no clear way forward in the center. Playing e4-e5 is much more difficult, as the d-pawn is missing.  Alright, back to the move that we play. Advancing the d-pawn is welcome, as it gains space in a different way than our more common e4-e5. Black usually tries to generate play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@...b7-b5 is an idea@@EndBracket@@, while we aim for the kingside and the center.  We'll check two moves now: 8...Bg4, which looks like Black's best, and 8...Nc7, aiming for quick queenside play. }
8... Bg4
{ This move looks like Black's best try. Before starting any queenside action, they want to trade the bishop for our knight. The c8-bishop is often a weak piece in Benoni structures, and trading it against a potential attacker on the kingside makes some sense.  Still, you already know I'll be making my usual speech about two bishops. }
9. h3
{ Gimme! Gimme! Gimme! Jokes aside, there are good alternatives.   A move that I like is  9.Kh1  , as it is almost always useful to have the king a bit safer. I still prefer  9.h3  for the sake of clarity. }
9... Bxf3 10. Rxf3
{ Important! Not the more obvious  10.Qxf3  , as  10...Nb4!  'wins back' the bishop pair for Black. What's more, they get rid of the less than pretty a6-knight. }
10... Nc7
{ Whenever Black is hinting at ...b5, we should play a4 to stop it or slow it down. }
11. a4
{ An automatic reply. Now Black can stick with a straightforward queenside campaign, but we will meet it similarly as in the 8...Nc7 line. Two examples of this development are @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppn1ppbp/3p1np1/2pP4/P3PP2/2NB1R1P/1PP3P1/R1BQ2K1 b - a3 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rb8  12.Qe1  a6  13.a5  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppn1ppbp/3p1np1/2pP4/P3PP2/2NB1R1P/1PP3P1/R1BQ2K1 b - a3 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a6  12.a5  . Instead, I want to take a closer look at an alternative strategy for Black. }
11... e6
{ Black exerts a lot of pressure on d5. It is almost always best to answer ...e6 with the capture. }
12. dxe6
{ After something like  12.Bc4?!  exd5  13.exd5  , our pawn structure has lost any dynamic, and the bishops are no happy campers. Taking on e6 is better to open the game. }
12... fxe6
{ After  12...Nxe6  13.f5!  Nd4  14.Rf2  we are happy, too. The simple plan is Be3, Qd2 and doubling on the f-file for the attack. In the meantime, Black is hard-pressed for any active idea. }
13. Qe1
{ I suggest this move, as it is a common idea in many lines.   It's not the only good move, though. The prophylactic  13.Kh1  or  13.Be3  are fine, too.   After  13.Qe1  , Black has no immediate way to get active. After  13...d5?  14.e5  Nd7  15.h4!  we get a strong attack.  Black has a hard time ever moving a central pawn, as ...e5 kills the g7-bishop. A good way for us to continue is Bd2 and Rad1 next, centralizing our forces. We can then decide if Qh4 or an action in the center is the best way forward. }
