6... Nc6
{ I recommended this move in my course on the Pirc. I think it's the best line against the Austrian Attack, as White can't get a clear advantage. }
7. O-O
{ As usual, I suggest casting before taking any central action. Now Black has a choice between @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bg4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  , which is better, in my opinion.  Before we continue, I want to mention that it is unpromising to attack the c6-knight with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7.d5?!  , as  7...Nb4  is fine for Black. They play ...c6 quickly, attacking our advanced pawn. Playing d4-d5 in this line is not promising unless Black already has a pawn on e5, blocking the g7-bishop. }
7... e5
{ The logic of the 6...Nc6 line is compelling. Black stops White from advancing e4-e5 by 'getting there first'. }
8. dxe5
{ One of the main tries, but I'll suggest a surprise on the next move. } 8...
dxe5
{ It's important to mention that  9.fxe5?!  Nxe5!  10.Nxe5  Qd4+  leads nowhere for White. }
9. Qe1
{ A less explored move that contains a fair amount of poison. One reason I am selecting it for White: while preparing my course on the Pirc for Black, I didn't recognize that it was worth analyzing and only mentioned it briefly. I think it makes a good surprise weapon for White, as Black's path is narrow. }
9... exf4
{ That's the only good move for Black. If they don't take it, the pawn advance f4-f5 becomes very dangerous.   Instead of @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/2n2np1/4p3/4PP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qe1  , the move @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/2n2np1/4p3/4PP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.f5  is an idea for White. We are trying to get a better version of it. A sample line is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/2n2np1/4p3/4PP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1B1QRK1 b - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Re8?!  10.f5!  , when  10...gxf5  11.Bg5  sets up an annoying pin.  11...h6  12.Bxf6  Qxf6  13.exf5  Bxf5  14.Ne4  Qe7  15.Nh4  is a possible continuation. Allowing the move f4-f5 is playing with fire, for sure.   As @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/2n2np1/4p3/4PP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qe1  is a new idea, there is a lack of game samples. I found two games with  9...Nh5?!  10.f5  Nb4  11.g4!  , which is great for White after  11...Nf4  12.Bxf4  exf4  13.Rd1  , when White's pawn mass and piece activity is menacing. }
10. Bxf4
{ Our bishop got developed, and we have also cleared the way for Rad1. Black's defence is not simple now. }
10... Be6
{ I suggested this move for Black in my course.   An alternative for Black is  10...Bg4  11.Rd1  Bxf3  12.gxf3  , but Black needs to understand that  12...Nb4!  is the best move now. After  13.Bc4  Qe7  14.Qf2  I'd still prefer White due to the bishop pair, even though Stockfish claims equality. }
11. Rd1
{ This move, opposing the queen, still sets some problems for Black that they are likely unprepared for. It's tough to predict what would happen in a game, as the best move according to the engine won't happen, I assume. }
11... Qe7
{ The human move, and likely the one that I would play.   The engine suggestion  11...Nd4  is very unintuitive and is supposed to lead to equal play. White has plenty of ideas, though, like  12.Ng5  , for example. }
12. Qh4
{ This position is still not easy to play for Black, as we have the more active pieces. Stockfish suggests @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/ppp1qpbp/2n1bnp1/8/4PB1Q/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/3R1RK1 b - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfe8  13.Kh1  Nd7  is now best for Black, but that's not very attractive, as we have the pleasant choice between grabbing a pawn with  14.Qxe7  Rxe7  15.Bxc7  or to keep the tension with @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/pppnqpbp/2n1b1p1/8/4PB1Q/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/3R1R1K w - - 7 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qg3  .  The pawn grab should only lead to equality, as @@StartFEN@@r5k1/ppBnrpbp/2n1b1p1/8/4P3/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/3R1R1K b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Nde5  gives Black enough compensation. All this is hard to figure out, though. My suggestion will pose some problems for the Pirc theory buffs, as it has significant surprise value. }
