[White "F3) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Modern Defense"]
[Black "1...g6 – Modern Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ In this chapter, we will examine the 'Modern Defence', which certainly looked 'modern' back when it was getting more popular. The Modern starts with the moves   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  and incorporate various lines with a common theme. Black neglects central control for the moment and allows White to build a broad centre. They plan to attack the pawn centre later, often based on playing on the queenside @@StartBracket@@...a6 and ...b5@@EndBracket@@.   The Modern has an opening relative: the Pirc Defence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  , which we examine in a dedicated chapter. Black frequently starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Bg7  but quickly plays the moves ...d6 and ...Nf6 to transpose into the Pirc. A sample variation for this transposition is  3.Nc3  d6  4.f4  , when  4...Nf6  gets the game into Pirc territory and might be Black's best move.   Let's have an overview of the chapter. After  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Bg7  3.Nc3  Black has a major choice. We'll examine these three options in more detail:   A.  3...d6  is the main line by a mile. We'll play  4.f4  in 'Austrian Attack' style - our approach vs the Pirc.   B.  3...c6  aims for a setup with ...d5. We'll also play  4.f4  and build a broad centre. Black suffers from a severe lack of space and counterplay in this system.   C.  3...c5  attacks our centre with the c-pawn and aims for transposition into a Sicilian. After  4.Nf3  cxd4  ,  we'd reach a line that is not part of our repertoire.This is no problem, as  4.dxc5!  more or less refutes the whole idea.In addition, Black has tried many obscure lines that I will mention in the text, but they don't require a deeper analysis. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F3) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Modern Defense"]
[Black "1...g6 – Modern Defense 2.d4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7
{ Almost a 'pre-move' in Online Chess terminology. Black plays this natural move almost all the time, but there are off-beat alternatives or different move orders to lines that we will examine in this chapter. These move orders could be  2...d6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.f4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppp1p/6p1/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c6  3.Nc3  d5  4.e5  Bg7  5.f4  ,  leading to lines that are in our repertoire. It shows our general approach in this chapter and vs the Pirc, the other ...g6-based defence: we play a quick f4, going for as much central pawn control as possible.   Black also has the funky move  2...Nf6?!  , which has different names. The funniest one is 'The Norwegian Rat', which doesn't sound too nice. After  3.e5  , Black jumps to the edge of the board with  3...Nh5  . As you can imagine, this is not a healthy concept, and White is better with any sensible way of development. In the first edition, I suggested  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bc4  ,  which still looks like a strong reply to me. }
3. Nc3
{ As mentioned in the intro, Black now mostly plays  3...d6  ,  but we'll also check the two c-pawn moves. Is there anything else worth knowing?If Black plays a slow move, like  3...b6  ,  3...a6  or  3...e6  ,  we continue with our standard approach of playing f4, followed by Nf3, Bd3, supporting our centre. We might transpose into lines that we examine after 3...d6, for example,  3...a6  4.f4  b5  5.Nf3  Bb7  6.Bd3  d6  7.a4  leads to the main line of the current chapter.   I noticed one funny, independent option for Black, the move  3...d5!?  - it is based on the idea  4.Nxd5  c6  , when Black gets the pawn back. There are two problems for Black. After  5.Ne3  Qxd4  6.Qxd4  Bxd4  7.a4  ,  followed by Nc4, White has a comfortable plus. This is a much better version of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.Nf3  d5  3.d3  dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  ,  which already requires some precision by Black to equalize. White has annoying pressure on the queenside in this endgame/queenless middlegame.The second, more obvious, problem is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Nf6  5.Bc4  ,  grabbing and holding the pawn for the moment. Black can win it back with ...Nbd7-b6, but we retain a comfortable position that resembles the line  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Nf6  3.Bb5+  Nbd7  when a similar pawn structure occurs. After, for example,  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3P4/2BP4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  Nb6  7.Bb3  Nbxd5  8.Nxd5  Nxd5  9.O-O  White's position is easy to play. We may use the e5-square for our knight @@StartBracket@@Re1&Ne5@@EndBracket@@, and Black can't easily accomplish the pawn breaks ...c5 or ...e5. }
3... c6
{ Black mixes the Fianchetto with a Caro-Kann pawn formation in the centre. White has a good choice of lines against it, and one features our standard setup against all the ....g6 lines. }
4. f4
{ Our standard setup works well here. Grabbing as much space as possible looks very logical against defences that don't fight for central space, like all the ...g6-based systems. }
4... d5
{ According to the plan and almost always played. I found some games with an interesting idea, though. Some players have tried  4...Qb6  , attacking our d-pawn. After  5.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@ 5.e5!? is a rare reply, but not bad at all@@EndBracket@@, they play  5...d5!?  , a creative pawn sacrifice we should not accept. After  6.exd5?!  Nh6  or  6...Bg4  Black gets good play against our d-pawn and enough compensation. We should avoid this pitfall and instead play  6.e5!  ,  when we reach a position similar to 4...d5 5.e5 and favourable for White. If you like to be creative,  @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/pp1pppbp/1qp3p1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e5  is an unexplored but fine alternative. }
5. e5
{ Having a soundly protected pawn on e5, blunting the g7-bishop, is a nice strategic asset. We'll check two lines now: Black can play for a quick break, based on ...f6, or employ a more defensive strategy based on a kingside blockade with ...h5. }
5... Nh6
{ Black goes for a more active strategy than  5...h5  ,  but it involves considerable risk. The idea is attacking our centre with ...f6, in most cases.   They can also start with  5...f6  , when I recommend  6.Be3  Nh6  7.Be2  to transpose to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp2ppbp/2p3p1/3pP3/3P1P2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nh6  6.Be2!?  f6  7.Be3  , the line we will investigate now. }
6. Be2
{ It took me a while before I decided to recommend this move. I like to have similar solutions and setups, if possible. Therefore, the move  6.Nf3  suggests itself. It is a good move, and maybe even a bit stronger than  6.Be2  in a purely analytical sense.However, there is a drawback. White has to be ready to play some sharp lines that are tricky to handle in practice. Black has some different move orders that can be confusing, too. When I saw that  6.Be2  is much easier to play and keeps a comfortable advantage, my choice was made.What's the idea of playing the bishop to e2? We take control of g4 and wait with our knight development to f3. This way, Black can't play a quick ...Bg4 and needs to attack our centre now with ...f6 to get some play. We also prioritize queenside development to allow queenside casting in some cases. I like this idea, as expanding on the kingside with g4 is often an option.In the  6.Nf3  lines, White often plays h3&g4, but the king remains in the centre or kingside, leading to murky positions. I want to play g4 when my king is closer to queenside castling. }
6... f6
{ After  6...O-O  7.Be3  Black has nothing better than  7...f6  , which leads to the same position. }
7. Be3
{ We still delay the knight move to f3. With Qd2 next, queenside castling is possible, too. }
7... O-O 8. Qd2
{ White is in great shape here, as Black has difficulty generating counterplay. }
8... Nf5
{ An understandable move, as Black is likely concerned about the knight's future on the edge of the board. Alternatives?   A.  8...Ng4  is driven by similar concerns. After  9.Bxg4  Bxg4  10.h3  Be6  11.Nf3  White is in great shape, though. Black has a huge space disadvantage and passive bishops.   B.  8...c5  is a desperate measure, but it won't work after  9.dxc5  fxe5  10.fxe5  Nf5  11.Nf3  Nc6  12.Bf4  , when we keep our centre covered.   C.  8...fxe5  is best answered with  9.dxe5  , which is similar to the line we will examine now. }
9. Bf2
{ We want to keep our bishop, of course. Now Black is in trouble, as we are ready to play g4 and send the knight back to h6. }
9... fxe5 { Important to check, as it gives us a chance to go wrong. } 10. dxe5
{ We have to avoid  10.fxe5?  , when  10...Bh6  is fine for Black. After the accurate capture dxe5, we are much better, as Black's pieces on the kingside are passive. We can play Nf3 next and combine O-O-O and g4 to start an attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F3) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – Modern Defense"]
[Black "1...g6 – Modern Defense 2.d4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7
{ Almost a 'pre-move' in Online Chess terminology. Black plays this natural move almost all the time, but there are off-beat alternatives or different move orders to lines that we will examine in this chapter. These move orders could be  2...d6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.f4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppp1p/6p1/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c6  3.Nc3  d5  4.e5  Bg7  5.f4  ,  leading to lines that are in our repertoire. It shows our general approach in this chapter and vs the Pirc, the other ...g6-based defence: we play a quick f4, going for as much central pawn control as possible.   Black also has the funky move  2...Nf6?!  , which has different names. The funniest one is 'The Norwegian Rat', which doesn't sound too nice. After  3.e5  , Black jumps to the edge of the board with  3...Nh5  . As you can imagine, this is not a healthy concept, and White is better with any sensible way of development. In the first edition, I suggested  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bc4  ,  which still looks like a strong reply to me. }
3. Nc3
{ As mentioned in the intro, Black now mostly plays  3...d6  ,  but we'll also check the two c-pawn moves. Is there anything else worth knowing?If Black plays a slow move, like  3...b6  ,  3...a6  or  3...e6  ,  we continue with our standard approach of playing f4, followed by Nf3, Bd3, supporting our centre. We might transpose into lines that we examine after 3...d6, for example,  3...a6  4.f4  b5  5.Nf3  Bb7  6.Bd3  d6  7.a4  leads to the main line of the current chapter.   I noticed one funny, independent option for Black, the move  3...d5!?  - it is based on the idea  4.Nxd5  c6  , when Black gets the pawn back. There are two problems for Black. After  5.Ne3  Qxd4  6.Qxd4  Bxd4  7.a4  ,  followed by Nc4, White has a comfortable plus. This is a much better version of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.Nf3  d5  3.d3  dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  ,  which already requires some precision by Black to equalize. White has annoying pressure on the queenside in this endgame/queenless middlegame.The second, more obvious, problem is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Nf6  5.Bc4  ,  grabbing and holding the pawn for the moment. Black can win it back with ...Nbd7-b6, but we retain a comfortable position that resembles the line  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Nf6  3.Bb5+  Nbd7  when a similar pawn structure occurs. After, for example,  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3P4/2BP4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  Nb6  7.Bb3  Nbxd5  8.Nxd5  Nxd5  9.O-O  White's position is easy to play. We may use the e5-square for our knight @@StartBracket@@Re1&Ne5@@EndBracket@@, and Black can't easily accomplish the pawn breaks ...c5 or ...e5. }
3... c6
{ Black mixes the Fianchetto with a Caro-Kann pawn formation in the centre. White has a good choice of lines against it, and one features our standard setup against all the ....g6 lines. }
4. f4
{ Our standard setup works well here. Grabbing as much space as possible looks very logical against defences that don't fight for central space, like all the ...g6-based systems. }
4... d5
{ According to the plan and almost always played. I found some games with an interesting idea, though. Some players have tried  4...Qb6  , attacking our d-pawn. After  5.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@ 5.e5!? is a rare reply, but not bad at all@@EndBracket@@, they play  5...d5!?  , a creative pawn sacrifice we should not accept. After  6.exd5?!  Nh6  or  6...Bg4  Black gets good play against our d-pawn and enough compensation. We should avoid this pitfall and instead play  6.e5!  ,  when we reach a position similar to 4...d5 5.e5 and favourable for White. If you like to be creative,  @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/pp1pppbp/1qp3p1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e5  is an unexplored but fine alternative. }
5. e5
{ Having a soundly protected pawn on e5, blunting the g7-bishop, is a nice strategic asset. We'll check two lines now: Black can play for a quick break, based on ...f6, or employ a more defensive strategy based on a kingside blockade with ...h5. }
5... h5 { Black goes for the blockading plan on the kingside. } 6. Nf3
{ We aim for a natural piece setup to support our centre. The bishop will be well-placed on d3 and e3, the next development step. }
6... Nh6
{ They can also start with  6...Bg4  , when  7.Be3  Nh6  leads to the same position. This move order is the more popular one, but I chose 6...Nh6 to talk about dubious deviations for Black. }
7. Be3
{ We want to develop our bishops to d3 and e3,  what to play first. Here  7.Bd3  is a bit less precise, as  7...Bf5  is a good reply. We don't want to trade bishop vs bishop, and retreating to e2 is lame. Starting with the queen's bishop is more effective here. }
7... Bg4
{ Black best and most commonly played move. Black is ready to trade the bishop and play ...Nf5 and ...e6 next to fortify the kingside. There is no good alternative to this concept, as the bishop and the h6-knight compete for the squares f5 and g4. If both stayed on the board, they would step on each other's toes.   A sample line  7...Bf5?!  8.h3  shows the issue: the knight is stuck on h6. If  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppb1/2p3pn/3pP2p/3P1P2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nf5?!  8.Bf2  ,  the bishop remains passive.   You sometimes see the move  7...Qb6  , attacking our b-pawn. A simple, good reply is  8.Rb1  , covering the pawn. Black has not gained anything by inserting these moves. }
8. Bd3
{ Playing  8.h3  is just as good and will likely lead to the same position. }
8... Nf5
{ Black can also start with  8...e6  , when  9.h3  Bxf3  10.Qxf3  will ultimately transpose to the same position. Black needs the moves ...e6, ...Nf5 and ...h4 and can play them in various orders. }
9. Bf2 e6 10. h3 { You can also castle first and play h3 next. } 10... Bxf3 11.
Qxf3 h4
{ That is Black's target formation when they play the ...h5 setup. They trade their light-squared bishop and create a blockade on the kingside. The fundamental problem of Black's position is the lack of active ideas. We'll talk about our options in a moment. }
12. O-O
{ This position is a good one to take stock, as it is likely to occur after Black went for the ...h5-setup. Black has a quite reliable blockade on the kingside. There is no easy way to open this side of the board. Therefore, we need to focus on gaining grounds elsewhere: the queenside.Black has invested a lot of time on the kingside formation but has not made any progress in attacking our centre - this is the main defect of Black's position. They have less space and can't do much to change that. We should play on the queenside - how to do that? It depends on Black's choice now. Black's most popular move looks like a mistake to me, as it makes our job easier.   A:  12...Nd7?  is played most often, but a conceptual mistake, in my mind. The knight is passively placed and won't have any useful role to fight our plan.  13.Ne2!  is the way to go, preparing b3&c4 next. In this scenario, the d7-knight is doing nothing.  13...Bf8  14.b3  a5  15.c4  is a sample line to show the problem.   B.  12...Bf8  is more flexible. Black can develop the knight to a6, which makes the Ne2&b3&c4 plan less attractive. Knight jumps to b4 would be irritating. We have plenty of good alternatives to b3&c4, though. One way to play is  13.Ne2  Na6  14.c3  and continue with a4 and b4. Black is condemned to sitting passively on three ranks and waiting.A plan that is good to know for both scenarios: Our knight usually goes to e2 to allow the c-pawn to join. The knight is not very active on e2, though. One way to improve is the regrouping of Kh2, Ng1, Qe2 and Nf3, which puts some pressure on h4. This is a slow plan, but the position is closed and therefore allows those manoeuvres. }
