4. dxc5
{ That's my recommendation from the first edition. I still think it's the best move, and I stick with it. We take the pawn and ask Black how they intend to regain it.   We'll now examine two moves:  4...Qa5  and  4...Bxc3+  , which leads to the rare sight of tripled pawns after just five moves. }
4... Bxc3+
{ Black damages our pawn structure but gives up their best piece and the pair of bishops. We get tripled pawns, a feast for sore eyes! }
5. bxc3
{ The tripled pawn might deter some players from choosing the continuation 4.dxc5, as they are overly concerned about pawn structure. Here, Black is in deep trouble. The key issue is that they don't manage to win the c5-pawn. As long as this pawn is on the board, they have difficulty moving the d-pawn or b-pawn. This, in turn, means that the c8-bishop has a problem joining the game. Black has no good solution for this issue. }
5... Qa5 { Black's queen attacks two pawns... } 6. Qd4
{ ...our queen defends them! Well, we also attack the h8-rook, of course. }
6... Nf6 7. Qb4
{ A key move to remember. Now I don't see a satisfactory way for Black to continue.   A.  7...Qxb4  8.cxb4  Nxe4  9.f3  Nf6  10.Bb2  regains the pawn, but we are much better due to our monster bishop pair and the dead bishop on c8.   B.  7...Qc7  looks like the best try, but we are still much better after various moves.  8.Bd3  Nc6  9.Qa4  Ne5  10.Be3  keeps our pawn on c5, the nightmare scenario for our opponent's c8-bishop. }
