1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7
{ Almost a 'pre-move' in Online Chess terminology. Black plays this natural move almost all the time, but there are off-beat alternatives or different move orders to lines that we will examine in this chapter. These move orders could be  2...d6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.f4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppp1p/6p1/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c6  3.Nc3  d5  4.e5  Bg7  5.f4  ,  leading to lines that are in our repertoire. It shows our general approach in this chapter and vs the Pirc, the other ...g6-based defence: we play a quick f4, going for as much central pawn control as possible.   Black also has the funky move  2...Nf6?!  , which has different names. The funniest one is 'The Norwegian Rat', which doesn't sound too nice. After  3.e5  , Black jumps to the edge of the board with  3...Nh5  . As you can imagine, this is not a healthy concept, and White is better with any sensible way of development. In the first edition, I suggested  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bc4  ,  which still looks like a strong reply to me. }
3. Nc3
{ As mentioned in the intro, Black now mostly plays  3...d6  ,  but we'll also check the two c-pawn moves. Is there anything else worth knowing?If Black plays a slow move, like  3...b6  ,  3...a6  or  3...e6  ,  we continue with our standard approach of playing f4, followed by Nf3, Bd3, supporting our centre. We might transpose into lines that we examine after 3...d6, for example,  3...a6  4.f4  b5  5.Nf3  Bb7  6.Bd3  d6  7.a4  leads to the main line of the current chapter.   I noticed one funny, independent option for Black, the move  3...d5!?  - it is based on the idea  4.Nxd5  c6  , when Black gets the pawn back. There are two problems for Black. After  5.Ne3  Qxd4  6.Qxd4  Bxd4  7.a4  ,  followed by Nc4, White has a comfortable plus. This is a much better version of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.Nf3  d5  3.d3  dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  ,  which already requires some precision by Black to equalize. White has annoying pressure on the queenside in this endgame/queenless middlegame.The second, more obvious, problem is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Nf6  5.Bc4  ,  grabbing and holding the pawn for the moment. Black can win it back with ...Nbd7-b6, but we retain a comfortable position that resembles the line  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Nf6  3.Bb5+  Nbd7  when a similar pawn structure occurs. After, for example,  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3P4/2BP4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  Nb6  7.Bb3  Nbxd5  8.Nxd5  Nxd5  9.O-O  White's position is easy to play. We may use the e5-square for our knight @@StartBracket@@Re1&Ne5@@EndBracket@@, and Black can't easily accomplish the pawn breaks ...c5 or ...e5. }
3... d6
{ Black's main move at this point, leading to the main lines of the Modern Defence. }
4. f4
{ Not a surprise. We always play for this formation against the ...g6-defences. Now we'll look at some moves; here's an overview.   A.  4...Nf6  is probably the best move, but it transposes to the Pirc Defence, covered in the previous chapter.   B. Black could go for a Hippo setup. I'll cover that via the move order  4...e6  ,  but they could start with other moves, of course. More on that later.   C.  4...Nc6  is worth a quick look, as some initial precision is required.   D.  4...a6  is Black's main alternative to 4...Nf6, going for a quick queenside expansion. }
4... Nc6
{ Black attacks our d4-pawn. As usual in Pirc/Modern structures, an early ...Nc6 should not be answered by d4-d5, as Black's fianchetto bishop is the main beneficiary. The tempo gain is less important than this long-term factor. We need to cover the d-pawn, but how? }
5. Be3
{ Better than  5.Nf3  Bg4!  6.Be3  e5  ,  when Black's play in the centre is serious. It is better not to allow the pin so easily. Now Black has no easy way to develop the c8-bishop. }
5... Nf6
{ What else? After this move, the position looks a lot like a Pirc. The moves ...Nc6 and Be3 are added compared to the regular Austrian Attack. }
6. Nf3
{ We don't need to worry about a piece coming to g4. The move  6.Be2  has some merit, but the knight development is more forceful. }
6... O-O
{ Black usually castles here. We don't have to fear  6...Ng4  7.Bg1  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/3PPP2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  e5  9.Bb5  ,  when we are much better. Black is violating too many opening principles to be OK. }
7. e5
{ Our main strategic goal in the Austrian Attack is playing this advance, so here we go! I want to make a small comparison here, though.   In the Pirc, we reach a similar position: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  4.f4  Bg7  5.Nf3  O-O  6.Bd3  Nc6  , when we play  7.O-O  and wait for Black to decide about their centre.   Here we have the bishop on e3 instead of d3. It looks normal to play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/3PPP2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3?  here to prepare to castle and get a similar game as in the Pirc. There is a difference, though - the vulnerable position of our e3-bishop. Black has  7...Ng4  8.Bg1  e5!  ,  when our position lacks harmony. Therefore, we must 'get there first and immediately push our pawn to e5. }
7... dxe5
{ Black plays this capture most of the time. You also meet  7...Ng4  8.Bg1  , when  8...dxe5  9.dxe5  leads to a position we will examine in a moment. Black could go  8...Nh6  , but  9.h3!  Nf5  10.Bf2  leaves the knight stranded. }
8. dxe5
{ It is, again, conceptually interesting to compare to the Pirc. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  4.f4  Bg7  5.Nf3  O-O  6.Bd3  Nc6  I recommend castling. White also has  7.e5  , when  7...dxe5  8.dxe5  Nd5!  is possible and fine for Black. In our current position with Be3 instead of Bd3, Black's knight only has bad squares available. }
8... Ng4 9. Bg1 Nh6
{ A prophylactic retreat. It doesn't convince, but Black has nothing great anyway. I found a remarkable amount of online games with  9...Bf5??  , when  10.h3  Nh6  11.g4  is miserable for Black. }
10. h3
{ A very powerful move. We accomplished multiple goals with this move: stopping ...Bg4 and preparing our pawn storm g4, which would make the h6-knight look even sillier. }
10... Be6
{ This looks best as  10...Nf5?  11.Bf2  is excellent for White - g4 next shows that Black's knight move was pointless. After the better move  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2n3pn/4P3/5P2/2N2N1P/PPP3P1/R2QKBBR b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Be6  White has many promising and natural-looking moves, like  11.Bd3  or  11.Bb5  - but I want to suggest a different one that will pose Black severe problems. If you have gotten that far already, theory-wise, you might face someone very knowledgeable. Having a surprise is always nice! }
11. Qe2
{ As mentioned, 11.Bb5 or 11.Bd3 are more natural, but I think the queen move is strong and surprising. We are preparing the move Rd1, but we also have g4&Bg2 combinations in mind. It isn't easy to defend the black side here, as they have little space. I show some sample lines to illustrate it.   A.  11...Nf5  12.Rd1  Qe8  13.Bf2  ,  followed by g4, is terrifying for Black.   B.  11...f6  is the only active move available, but a tough move to play for a human.  12.exf6  Rxf6  13.g4  is great for White, but at least a bit messy. This looks like Black's best try, but it doesn't solve the problems. }
