{ Almost a 'pre-move' in Online Chess terminology. Black plays this natural move almost all the time, but there are off-beat alternatives or different move orders to lines that we will examine in this chapter. These move orders could be  2...d6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.f4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppp1p/6p1/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c6  3.Nc3  d5  4.e5  Bg7  5.f4  ,  leading to lines that are in our repertoire. It shows our general approach in this chapter and vs the Pirc, the other ...g6-based defence: we play a quick f4, going for as much central pawn control as possible.   Black also has the funky move  2...Nf6?!  , which has different names. The funniest one is 'The Norwegian Rat', which doesn't sound too nice. After  3.e5  , Black jumps to the edge of the board with  3...Nh5  . As you can imagine, this is not a healthy concept, and White is better with any sensible way of development. In the first edition, I suggested  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bc4  ,  which still looks like a strong reply to me. }
3. Nc3
{ As mentioned in the intro, Black now mostly plays  3...d6  ,  but we'll also check the two c-pawn moves. Is there anything else worth knowing?If Black plays a slow move, like  3...b6  ,  3...a6  or  3...e6  ,  we continue with our standard approach of playing f4, followed by Nf3, Bd3, supporting our centre. We might transpose into lines that we examine after 3...d6, for example,  3...a6  4.f4  b5  5.Nf3  Bb7  6.Bd3  d6  7.a4  leads to the main line of the current chapter.   I noticed one funny, independent option for Black, the move  3...d5!?  - it is based on the idea  4.Nxd5  c6  , when Black gets the pawn back. There are two problems for Black. After  5.Ne3  Qxd4  6.Qxd4  Bxd4  7.a4  ,  followed by Nc4, White has a comfortable plus. This is a much better version of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.Nf3  d5  3.d3  dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  ,  which already requires some precision by Black to equalize. White has annoying pressure on the queenside in this endgame/queenless middlegame.The second, more obvious, problem is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Nf6  5.Bc4  ,  grabbing and holding the pawn for the moment. Black can win it back with ...Nbd7-b6, but we retain a comfortable position that resembles the line  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Nf6  3.Bb5+  Nbd7  when a similar pawn structure occurs. After, for example,  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3P4/2BP4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nbd7  6.Nf3  Nb6  7.Bb3  Nbxd5  8.Nxd5  Nxd5  9.O-O  White's position is easy to play. We may use the e5-square for our knight @@StartBracket@@Re1&Ne5@@EndBracket@@, and Black can't easily accomplish the pawn breaks ...c5 or ...e5. }
3... d6
{ Black's main move at this point, leading to the main lines of the Modern Defence. }
4. f4
{ Not a surprise. We always play for this formation against the ...g6-defences. Now we'll look at some moves; here's an overview.   A.  4...Nf6  is probably the best move, but it transposes to the Pirc Defence, covered in the previous chapter.   B. Black could go for a Hippo setup. I'll cover that via the move order  4...e6  ,  but they could start with other moves, of course. More on that later.   C.  4...Nc6  is worth a quick look, as some initial precision is required.   D.  4...a6  is Black's main alternative to 4...Nf6, going for a quick queenside expansion. }
4... a6 5. Nf3
{ We continue, as usual, aiming for the setup with Nf3, Bd3 and O-O. We argue that Black's slow play on the flanks should be answered by centralization and therefore don't stop the ...b5 idea.   I have checked the rarely played  5.a4  , though, and I think it is somewhat underestimated. Black's best seems to be  5...Nc6  ,  which is similar to 4...Nc6, just with the a-pawn moves added. This favours Black a little, but 4...Nc6 is pretty bad, to begin with. The main reason White is not playing 5.a4, and I am also not recommending it: ignoring Black's ...b5 idea and developing naturally is even stronger. Let's examine this approach. }
5... b5 6. Bd3
{ No surprise here. We complete our usual piece formation. Now Black has two moves that lead to similar positions, and we'll answer both with the same concept.   A.  6...Bb7  7.a4!  b4  8.Ne2  is the slightly less popular version of the same structure, as Black is a bit slower to start their counterplay.   B.  6...Nd7  7.a4!  b4  8.Ne2  is the main path.   Even worse is  6...c5?  , when  7.dxc5!  dxc5  8.e5!  is a textbook refutation in Austrian Attack style. White gets the strong, supported e5-pawn, and Black has weaknesses on the queenside. We get to use the e4-square, too. }
6... Nd7 7. a4
{ We attack Black's pawn and force it forward. The main idea is that after  7...b4  8.Ne2  White is always ready to answer ...c5 with c3, maintaining the perfect pawn centre. In many other lines that look more aggressive at first, Black trades their c-pawn for White's d-pawn because White never got the chance to support d4 with the c-pawn. }
7... b4 8. Ne2
{ Now we are always ready to support our d-pawn with c3 - very comfortable. A large benefit of the 7.a4 line is that the resulting positions are relatively easy to play and not much dependent on deeper, concrete theoretical knowledge. We'll check some lines now, but you'll see that our play is quite natural. We have a split now.   A.  8...c5  is possible when Black starts their play without fianchettoing the queen's bishop.   B.  8...Bb7  is the alternative, leading to a position that also arises via  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/2p1ppbp/p2p2p1/1p6/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bb7  7.a4  b4  8.Ne2  Nd7  . }
8... c5
{ Black attacks our centre immediately and avoids ...Bb7 for the moment. They try to be faster with their counterplay, but our centre is well-supported. }
9. c3
{ The idea of the a4-line: support the centre this way. Now Black could still play  9...Bb7  to transpose to 8...Bb7, but most of the time, they open the b-file now. The transposition seems the best option, though. }
9... bxc3 10. bxc3
{ I don't see a good continuation for Black now, to be honest. They have tried many moves, but nothing looks convincing. The engine evaluates  10...e6  as the relatively best, but this move is rarely played and poses no particular problem. We are much better with simple moves like O-O and Rb1. The computer thinks everything else loses, but this is a bit too harsh.I'll take a look now at 10...Ngf6, which is the most played move online. }
10... Ngf6
{ Played frequently in online games, but bad for Black. I also found some games in which Black played something like  10...Qc7  to delay the knight move. We can handle this type of play like the 8...Bb7 line. We castle, play Ng3 and Rb1 if they play ...Bb7. A well-timed e4-e5 will be a key idea. }
11. e5
{ Here we go. Black needs to go to g4 now, as  11...Nd5??  12.Be4  Bb7  13.Qb3  wins on the spot. }
11... Ng4 12. h3 { Or  12.O-O  ,  as we can still play h3 next. } 12... Nh6 13.
O-O
{ A great position for us, as we've accomplished all you can hope for in the Austrian Attack. Our pawn wedge restricts Black's pieces, and we have excellent attack chances on the kingside. Ideas like Qe1-h4 and Ng5 come to mind. }
*

