8... Bb7 { Black goes for the fianchetto. } 9. c3
{ We have two move orders that should lead to the same positions. I suggest  9.c3  c5  10.O-O  , but @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/1bpnppbp/p2p2p1/8/Pp1PPP2/3B1N2/1PP1N1PP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.O-O  c5  10.c3  will lead to the same. Black can't play without ...c5, regardless. }
9... c5
{ Black covers their b-pawn and starts attacking our centre. It's a bad idea to open the b-file, with ...bxc3, as Black's bishop will be vulnerable on the open file. This is a key consideration when playing 8...c5 and avoiding the bishop move. We'll see an example of a bad ...bxc3 on the next move - hang on. }
10. O-O
{ Black has tried some moves here, but there is no fully effective solution. Here's an overview:   A.  10...Ngf6  is played frequently but allows  11.e5  Nd5  12.Ng5  , a dangerous attack.   B.  10...cxd4  10.cxd4  is not popular but may be best. One idea of the capture is that after a later ...Ngf6, our reply e4-e5 is less effective, as ...Nd5 places the knight on a stable square. We'll examine these two moves in more detail.   A worse alternative for Black is taking on c3, as it only helps us. The bishop is exposed on the b-file. A simple line runs  10...bxc3  11.bxc3  Ngf6  12.e5  Nd5  13.Rb1  Qc8  , when  14.Ng5!  is even more effective than in line A above. White's attack is already decisive, for example, after  14...h6  15.Nxf7!  Kxf7  16.f5  dxe5  17.fxg6+  Kg8  18.Bf5  Qc6  19.Rxb7  . Fun stuff! }
10... cxd4
{ This trade is probably best. Black delays ...Ngf6 for a moment and creates stability on the queenside with the next move. }
11. cxd4 a5
{ Slow, but it's a good idea. The move secures the b6-square for Black's queen and may prepare ...Ba6 at a later stage.   Black has to avoid  11...Ngf6?  12.e5  Nd5  13.Ng5  , which is too dangerous. }
12. Ng3
{ An important move order finesse. We want to complete development with Be3, but  12.Be3?  is not well-timed due to  12...Ngf6  , when  13.e5  Nd5  and @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nppbp/3p1np1/p7/Pp1PPP2/3BBN2/1P2N1PP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.h3  Ng4  are both awkward. The bishop is a target for the knight jumps.   After the much better  12.Ng3  , Black still can't play  12...Ngf6?  due to  13.e5  Nd5  14.Ng5  , which is devastating. }
12... Qb6
{ Black attacks our pawn and wants to provoke Be3, so that they finally can develop the knight. }
13. Be3 Ngf6 { Finally, after 13 moves, Black manages to get the knight out. }
14. h3
{ They have managed to avoid immediate disasters by stopping e4-e5, but after the simple prophylaxis  14.h3  White is nevertheless much better. It is important to realize that Black has navigated the initial dangers of being overrun by e4-e5, and we need more patience and preparation now. You don't need to play for checkmate in this position. After  14...O-O  15.Qe2  Ba6  , for example,  16.Bxa6  Qxa6  17.Qxa6  Rxa6  18.Rfc1  is an excellent endgame. }
