{ Black has tried some moves here, but there is no fully effective solution. Here's an overview:   A.  10...Ngf6  is played frequently but allows  11.e5  Nd5  12.Ng5  , a dangerous attack.   B.  10...cxd4  10.cxd4  is not popular but may be best. One idea of the capture is that after a later ...Ngf6, our reply e4-e5 is less effective, as ...Nd5 places the knight on a stable square. We'll examine these two moves in more detail.   A worse alternative for Black is taking on c3, as it only helps us. The bishop is exposed on the b-file. A simple line runs  10...bxc3  11.bxc3  Ngf6  12.e5  Nd5  13.Rb1  Qc8  , when  14.Ng5!  is even more effective than in line A above. White's attack is already decisive, for example, after  14...h6  15.Nxf7!  Kxf7  16.f5  dxe5  17.fxg6+  Kg8  18.Bf5  Qc6  19.Rxb7  . Fun stuff! }
10... Ngf6 { Black's most common move, but it invites a strong attack. } 11. e5
{ I suggest going for the throat immediately. It is, however, no mistake at all to play  11.Ng3  and try to play e4-e5 under even better circumstances later. Black is in serious trouble in both cases. }
11... Nd5 12. Ng5
{ White has some good alternatives, but this move is the most forceful. } 12...
h6
{ Not the best move, but I want to show the key attacking idea in a trainable. What else is there for Black?   A.  12...e6?  13.Ne4  wins on the spot, fork time on d6.   B.  12...Nc7?  13.f5  dxe5  14.fxg6  fxg6  also loses. White has multiple wins here, like  15.Bc4  ,  15.Qb3  or  15.Qc2  still crush Black.   C.  12...dxe5!  is the only move when both recaptures are excellent for White. I like  13.dxe5  more, as  13...e6  14.c4  Ne7  15.Be4  looks dominating. We have the great central squares, and Black's g7-bishop is awful. }
13. Ne6
{ Smashing on f7 should also win, but this move is cleaner and more attractive, in my mind. }
13... fxe6 14. Bxg6+ Kf8 15. f5
{ And Black is wiped out on the f-file. With perfect play, Black can still avoid a quick mate, but they will need to return the piece with something like  15...dxe5  16.fxe6+  N7f6  17.dxe5  , when we aren't even material down. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F4) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – 1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 Sidelines"]
[Black "1...d6 & 1...g6 – 1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6
{ This chapter covers the opening lines after the move 1...d6 that are not covered in dedicated chapters. The main split in this chapter arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  , when we need to examine the following moves more closely:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  is by far the most popular and leads to the Pirc, which we examine in a dedicated chapter.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  leads to the Neo-Philidor. The original Philidor move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  Nd7?!  is dubious, as examined in our chapter on the Open Games Sidelines. In the current chapter, we examine the improved move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  , when I suggest the fascinating reply  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Rg1  . More on that later!   C. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  is an attempt by Black to reach the position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  4.Nf3  Nbd7  without allowing the trade @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  , which is often perceived as annoying to play by Black. The move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  has a more serious drawback for Black: we can play  4.f4!  , which gives White a comfortable advantage.  D. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6  is the Czech Defence. It's a rare line best answered by  4.f4!  , when Black has trouble getting any counterplay against our strong center.   We answer 3...g6, 3...c6 and 3...Nbd7 with 4.f4!, forming a consistent approach.   The exception is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  , which puts a pawn in the center and requires a different antidote. }
