[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F4) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – 1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 Sidelines"]
[Black "1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6
{ We'll focus on this move, as others are either transposing to a different chapter or are too obscure to warrant detailed coverage.   Here are two possible ways to transpose:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  leads to a Modern Defence.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e5  3.Nf3  leads to the old Philidor move order. Instead, taking on e5 and trading queens is also somewhat better for White  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8+  @@EndBracket@@, but I prefer to transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  , giving White good chances for an advantage. }
3. Nc3
{ After 3.Nc3, we arrive at the crossroads of the chapter. We will examine 3...c6, 3...Nbd7 and 3...e5, which is the most popular of the three.  Black may also play 3...g6 for the Pirc, which we cover in a dedicated chapter. }
3... Nbd7
{ Black likes to play the position after  3...e5  4.Nf3  Nbd7  , but wants to avoid the queen trade line after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  , which can be a bleak prospect if you want a fight.  The move order 3...Nbd7 tries to address this point, but it's a case of the cure being worse than the disease. We don't comply with Black's intentions because we have a better option on move four. }
4. f4
{ In the first edition, I recommended allowing the transposition by playing  4.Nf3  e5  , as this position is part of the repertoire anyway. It is still an option, particularly if you like to play the quirky line involving  5.Rg1  that I suggest.  However, from a purely objective point of view, White should play the f-pawn and exploit Black's risky move order. }
4... e5
{ Black needs to put a pawn in the center before we hit them with e4-e5. } 5.
Nf3
{ We increase the pressure on e5 and already threaten to take the pawn. Black has no good alternative to the capture on d4. }
5... exd4
{ There is nothing else. We attacked the pawn and a line like  5...c6?  6.dxe5  dxe5  7.fxe5  Ng4  8.e6!  fxe6  9.Ng5  Nde5  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8  11.h3  Nh6  12.Bf4  illustrates why Black can't ignore the threat. }
6. Qxd4
{ Important to remember: we take with the queen. After Black has committed their knight to d7, we can safely capture without being worried about being hit with ...Nc6. You can compare this situation with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  , when we'd love to play  4.f4?  , but  4...exd4  5.Qxd4  Nc6!  is the problem. }
6... c6
{ Black has to tread carefully here. They already have to watch out for e4-e5, which would work after the careless  6...Be7?  7.e5  dxe5  8.fxe5  Bc5  9.Qf4  Qe7  10.Be2  , when the f6-knight has no good square to go to.   The move  6...c6  controls d5 to allow the knight to jump to d5 in such a scenario. The other idea is playing ...d6-d5, generating some play in the center. }
7. Be3
{ We continue developing the bishop and prepare O-O-O simultaneously.   Instead,  7.e5  is premature, as  7...dxe5  8.fxe5  Bc5  9.Qf4  Qe7  10.Be2  Nd5  is possible. }
7... d5
{ That was Black's intention.   Some active idea is badly needed, such as something passive like  7...Be7  8.O-O-O  O-O  9.e5  is excellent for White. Black has no counterplay and may quickly lose, for example, after  9...dxe5  10.fxe5  Bc5  11.Qxc5  , when it's curtains. }
8. e5
{ Here  8.O-O-O  is a good alternative, but I prefer grabbing more space.  Black now has 8...Ng4 and 8...Bc5, but they lead to the same type of position. It looks like the knight jump is the better version of the two. }
8... Ng4
{ Or  8...Bc5  9.Qd2  Bxe3  10.Qxe3  Ng4  11.Qd2  Qb6  12.O-O-O  , similar to our main line; the only difference is the rook placement. Note that  12...Nf2  does not work due to  13.Na4  , winning the overambitious knight! }
9. Bg1
{ We need to ensure that we trade our bishop only for Black's counterpart so that the dark squares in our camp are not weakened. }
9... Bc5 10. Qd2 Bxg1 11. Rxg1 Qb6 12. O-O-O
{ This looks the most logical to me, but  12.Na4  or  12.h3  are of similar strength.   Note that  12.h3  is answered by the cunning  12...Nh2!  , revealing an idea of the previous move.  13.Nd4!  still would lead to interesting complications.  Back to my main move, castling queenside. Black has some concrete problems to solve. The g4-knight creates some play, but it all hangs by a thread. If we manage to play h3 and the knight has to retreat to h6, we play g4, and it's game over. Black has to be rather cunning to avoid this type of scenario. Here are some sample lines.   A. @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp1n1ppp/1qp5/3pP3/5Pn1/2N2N2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1BR1 b kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nf2??  13.Na4  is a direct blunder.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp1n1ppp/1qp5/3pP3/5Pn1/2N2N2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1BR1 b kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...O-O?  13.Nd4  @@StartBracket@@taking away the squares e3 and f2@@EndBracket@@  13...Nc5  14.h3  Nh6  15.g4  is our dream. We have a deadly attack on the kingside, and the knight on h6 is a sight to behold.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp1n1ppp/1qp5/3pP3/5Pn1/2N2N2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1BR1 b kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qe3?  13.h3  Qxd2+  14.Rxd2  Ne3  15.Bd3  Nc5  16.Re1  Nf5  17.g4  , again with a large advantage. We have much more space and initiative.   D. @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp1n1ppp/1qp5/3pP3/5Pn1/2N2N2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1BR1 b kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12....Nc5!  is the only good move, intending ...Ne4.  13.Re1!  covers e4 and supports the following idea.  13...Bd7  14.Nd4  h5  15.f5  , with a scary pawn duo on the fifth rank.   I think it's clear that Black faces serious difficulties in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  4.f4!  line. We enjoy a large space advantage, and Black can easily go wrong. }
