[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "F4) 1...d6 & 1...g6 – 1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 Sidelines"]
[Black "1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6
{ We'll focus on this move, as others are either transposing to a different chapter or are too obscure to warrant detailed coverage.   Here are two possible ways to transpose:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  leads to a Modern Defence.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e5  3.Nf3  leads to the old Philidor move order. Instead, taking on e5 and trading queens is also somewhat better for White  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8+  @@EndBracket@@, but I prefer to transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  , giving White good chances for an advantage. }
3. Nc3
{ After 3.Nc3, we arrive at the crossroads of the chapter. We will examine 3...c6, 3...Nbd7 and 3...e5, which is the most popular of the three.  Black may also play 3...g6 for the Pirc, which we cover in a dedicated chapter. }
3... c6
{ This is the Czech Defence, also called the Pribyl Defence, after its main 'developer' IM Josef Pribyl. It has never fully caught on, as White's best reply is too powerful, it seems. }
4. f4
{ This is the most testing move here by far. It's a logical choice for our repertoire, as we answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  @@StartBracket@@Pirc Defence@@EndBracket@@ with  4.f4  , the Austrian Attack. Generally, it's hard to imagine that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6  could be as useful as  3...g6  , which prepares development and gets Black closer to castling. A closer look reveals that Black must react here immediately; otherwise, the centre will be too strong. }
4... Qa5
{ The mentioned immediate reaction. Black attacks the e4 pawn by pinning. A slower move won't work well against our early aggression in the centre.   You sometimes meet  4...g6  , but this will transpose into a good line of the Pirc after  5.Nf3  Bg7  6.Bd3  O-O  7.O-O  , when  7...b5  8.e5  is the typical continuation. This line is analyzed in the Pirc chapter. }
5. Bd3
{ The natural move to cover our pawn. We'll reach a familiar setup: pawns on e4,d4,f4, knights to c3 and f3 and bishop to d3. We fight the Pirc and Modern in the same way. }
5... e5
{ Black needs some foothold in the centre. This move is the secondary idea of Black's previous move. }
6. Nf3
{ We complete our central setup. Black has the basic choice between capturing on d4 and opening the game or keeping the pawn on e5 and holding the centre. Black's best way of employing the second strategy is the bishop development to g4. }
6... exd4 { Black gives up the centre to attack the e-pawn later. } 7. Nxd4 g6
{ This makes the most sense. The bishop will be actively placed on the long diagonal, putting some pressure on our centre. Black's d-pawn looks weak but can't be attacked easily, as we have pieces on d3 and d4. As we will see, the d-pawn is a minor worry for Black - their real problem lies elsewhere. }
8. O-O Bg7
{ The move  8...Qb6  is best answered with  9.Be2  , when  9...Bg7  puts more pressure on our centre. Black now threatens ...Nxe4 - what to do? The best solution is  10.Be3!  , when  10...Qxb2  11.Qd2  is already winning for White.  11...Qb4  12.e5!  dxe5  13.fxe5  Nd5  14.Nxd5  Qxd2  15.Nc7+  wins the house, while  11...O-O  12.a3!  is powerful, taking away key squares. Black can't avoid material losses. }
9. Kh1
{ A good prophylactic move after f4 is on the board. You can't play with Queen checks and pins in the air all of the time. }
9... O-O 10. f5
{ This is the most popular move here, and it seems to be strong indeed! White aims for Qe1-h4 and a caveman-style attack. Those caveman clubs might be crude, but they hurt a lot!   A sample line to illustrate is:  10...Nbd7  11.Qe1  Nc5  12.Qh4  Qb4  13.Nf3  Nxd3  14.cxd3  Nd7  15.Bh6  ,  when White was much better in a game between the GMs Dominguez Perez and Arencibia. Grandmasters rarely dare to play this line with Black, which is considered too risky. }
*

