5... Be7
{ The question mark is a bit harsh, but this move is a mistake. Black usually answers the slower 5.Bc4 with 5...Be7, but routine moves don't cut it against our line. It is simply too slow. }
6. g4 { Here we go. } 6... h6
{ This is played most of the time. Black's alternatives, like  6...O-O  7.g5  Nh5  8.Be3  or the similar @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppnbppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP1P1/2N2N2/PPP2P1P/R1BQKBR1 b Qkq g3 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6  7.g5  Nh5  8.Be3  don't convince, either. }
7. h4
{ An important move and a key difference to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBR1 b Qkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6  6.g4  h6  , when  7.Be3!  is correct. in this line  7.h4?!  is worse due to  7...exd4  8.Qxd4  Qb6!  , which shows the difference to the version here. }
7... exd4
{ Black has no good defence here. After  7...c6  8.g5  hxg5  9.hxg5  Nh7  10.Be3  , we reach all that you can hope for. We'll castle queenside quickly and have already won the kingside battle. }
8. Qxd4
{ Here, the queen capture is already deadly, more or less. we threaten g4-g5, when Black's g7-pawn is under fire. There is no good defence for Black anymore. }
8... Ne5
{ A desperate measure. We'll have a look at an excellent tactical resource now. }
9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qxe5 { A tasty centre pawn! Can Black regain the pawn on g4? }
10... Bxg4 { Taking with the knight will be met with the same tactic. } 11.
Rxg4 Nxg4 12. Qxg7
{ We attack the rook and the knight, winning material.It is surprising to see how quickly Black's position deteriorates after 5...Be7 ... And it is a very commonly seen response! }
