1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6
{ We'll focus on this move, as others are either transposing to a different chapter or are too obscure to warrant detailed coverage.   Here are two possible ways to transpose:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  leads to a Modern Defence.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e5  3.Nf3  leads to the old Philidor move order. Instead, taking on e5 and trading queens is also somewhat better for White  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8+  @@EndBracket@@, but I prefer to transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  , giving White good chances for an advantage. }
3. Nc3
{ After 3.Nc3, we arrive at the crossroads of the chapter. We will examine 3...c6, 3...Nbd7 and 3...e5, which is the most popular of the three.  Black may also play 3...g6 for the Pirc, which we cover in a dedicated chapter. }
3... e5
{ This is Black's best move after  3...g6  . Black's idea is a transposition to a Closed Philidor formation after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  , an invitation I am happy to accept. }
4. Nf3
{ A natural development move and the most challenging, I think. White has some alternatives here, one being  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.Bc4  , going for the queen trade. I analyzed this line for a bit and concluded that White has some chances for an advantage. Two key lines are  6...Be6?!  7.Bxe6  fxe6  8.Nh3  is nice for White, intending Nh3-f2-d3, with some pressure on e5.  6...Ke8  is better, but  7.f4  gives White some initiative.My main objection to the trade on e5 is that Black wanted this game style, and I'd like to play more aggressively against players who chose a rather defensive setup.Right after the first edition's release in 2018, I found the idea  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Rg1  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@, posing Black far greater problems. It also has a large surprise value. Still, if you like endgames or want a quieter game for some specific reason, 4.dxe5 is a good line. It is analyzed in Yuriy Krykun's Lifetime Repertoire, Part 1, if you like more information. }
4... Nbd7
{ That's Black's main idea, but there are two possible transpositions to other chapters.   A.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  leads to the Ruy Lopez Steinitz, a welcome line for us.   B.  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  is analyzed in the chapter on Open games sidelines via the more common move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  looks @@StartBracket@@at least@@EndBracket@@ slightly better for White. }
5. Rg1
{ Wait... what? Yes, I recommend playing this quirky move! I know it looks completely crazy at first, but hear me out. It makes a lot of sense once you have looked a bit deeper.   Before we do that, I want to reflect on my old recommendation from the first edition, the classical continuation of  5.Bc4  ,  followed by O-O. Is there anything wrong with it? Not from a quality perspective, as the move still promises an opening advantage. I noticed, however, that students had problems with the myriad of possible move orders that may happen. Black has various pawn formations, and things can get rather sophisticated sometimes.When I discovered the  5.Rg1  variation in 2018/2019, while studying Richard Rapport's games, I knew I had a cool alternative on my hands. Some years later, the idea has caught on but is still not well-known to players on the Black side.Let's discuss what we accomplish with the early rook move. The immediate intention is clear: we want to play g2-g4 next, gaining ground on the kingside. The move g4 has more than one point. The first one is the position of Black's knights. Our opponent must worry about g4-g5, as the f6-knight has no natural flight square. They certainly don't want to retreat to g8, and jumping to the edge of the board to h5 does not look ideal. The current theoretical status suggests that Black should play a quick ...h6 to secure the knight for the moment. This is not an easy decision for Black: once the pawn is on h6, Black can't ever castle kingside.Let's discuss a secondary and less obvious idea of playing g4. Once the pawn is on g4, protected by the rook, we can comfortably develop our bishop to e3, without getting annoyed by ...Ng4. This often allows a quick queenside castling.I want to add one important point: we have a good grip on the centre. The famous 'rule' is that an action on the flank should be met with a central counterblow. Black has no good way of doing that. Taking on d4 rather helps us, as you will see.Let's have a look at Black's options. Our choice is a fresh idea and often will hit Black by surprise. If you look at online games or games below master level, Black is usually much worse quickly, and they don't know or find the best defences. Surprise value goes a long way!   A.  5...h5?!  is a dubious move but still frequently seen. Black stops our g4 idea but weakens the g5-square too much.   B.  5...Be7?  is very popular online and below master level. After  6.g4  , White is much better, as we will see. The bishop move is a bit too slow.   C.  5...exd4?!  6.Nxd4  is excellent for White, as the d7-knight is passive in this structure.   D.  5...g6  is a popular move. Black prepares ...Bg7 and covers the h5-square, which becomes relevant after  6.g4  Bg7  7.g5  Nh5  when the knight is protected. Still, we are better due to the offside piece.   E.  5...c6  6.g4  h6  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ currently seems to be Black's best bet. This position may also arise via  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBR1 b Qkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...h6  6.g4  c6  ,  a less common move order.We'll examine these options in dedicated trainable lines. }
5... g6
{ Black prepares the fianchetto and makes the h5-square a safer spot for their knight. }
6. g4
{ According to our plan, of course.   Here White has an interesting alternative worth mentioning. It is possible to delay g4 and start with  6.Be3  , which may lead to slightly different positions after  6...Bg7  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.g4  , followed by Qd2 and O-O-O.  I prefer playing 6.g4 immediately, as it is easier to remember and just as good. }
6... Bg7 7. g5 { 'Off to the rim, please!' } 7... Nh5
{ Now it's easy to describe the nature of White's advantage: the knight on the rim is dim. Our next step is completing queenside castling. }
8. Be3 { Playing Be3, Qd2 and O-O-O is very natural and strong. } 8... O-O 9.
Qd2 c6
{ Black needs some hope for counterplay and usually tries this idea, preparing ...b5. The timing of this move is difficult for Black, though. More about that in a moment. }
10. O-O-O
{ We have completed the next step and castled queenside. Black's defensive task is not easy now. In practice, they often go wrong quickly. Here are some examples of how the game could continue.   A.  10...b5??  is very common, particularly in online games.  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Qd6  wins on the spot, as Black loses c6, and everything falls apart.   B.  10...Qa5?!  11.Kb1  b5  12.a3  shows a good setup for us. We are safe on the queenside, and Black has difficulty developing a plan.  12...a6  13.dxe5  dxe5?  14.Nd5!  shows an important tactical point of playing Kb1 - we avoid the capture on d2 with a check.   C.  10...Re8  A quieter move like this might be best. We have a choice between maintaining the tension, for instance, with  11.Kb1  , or  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Bh3  , which illustrates an additional idea at our disposal. After  12...Qe7  13.Qd6  we keep some advantage in the endgame, as our pieces are more active. They also have to watch out for the e5-pawn, which will often need protection by a piece, as ...f6 is more difficult to play with a pawn on g5. }
*

