1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6
{ We'll focus on this move, as others are either transposing to a different chapter or are too obscure to warrant detailed coverage.   Here are two possible ways to transpose:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  leads to a Modern Defence.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e5  3.Nf3  leads to the old Philidor move order. Instead, taking on e5 and trading queens is also somewhat better for White  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8+  @@EndBracket@@, but I prefer to transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  , giving White good chances for an advantage. }
3. Nc3
