[White "G1) 1.e4 Sidelines – Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "1.e4 Sidelines – Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello and welcome to the final part of the course.  Every opening course has its 'Others' or 'Odds and Ends' part, and this is the one for the Second Edition of Keep It Simple: 1.e4. There is little left to cover. We have two chapters in this part.  Let's have a look and discuss the contents.  A. Alekhine's Defense @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Nf6  . White has a wide choice of answers to this provocative opening. I recommend  2.e5  Nd5  3.d4  d6  4.c4  Nb6  5.exd6  , the Exchange Variantion. It gives White an advantage without being overly theoretical. If you studied the first edition of the course, you might remember that I had already recommended this line five years ago. It is still an entirely rewritten chapter, as I changed my suggestions right after Black recaptures on move five. The new approach is simpler to learn and gives White excellent chances.  B. 1.e4 Others. The final chapter covers two replies,  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@Nimzovich Defense@@EndBracket@@ and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  @@StartBracket@@Owen's Defense@@EndBracket@@. Against the Nimzovich, I suggest @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , allowing Black to transpose into 1.e4 e5 territory by playing  2...e5  . We'll discuss what happens if they avoid this transposition. Black has some options, ranging from overly aggressive and bad to sane, but at best, slightly worse for Black. The Owen's neglects central control and if better for White. We can occupy the center and get a substantial advantage.  I decided to leave out rarer lines; you'll do fine by following general opening principles. This chapter uses the same lines as the first edition of Keep It Simple 1.e4, but they have been overhauled and simplified. Rare lines should not require much study time.  That's the overview of the final part of the course. Let's examine how to tackle these rare lines now! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "G2) 1.e4 Sidelines – Alekhine's Defense"]
[Black "Alekhine's Defense 1...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ Black opts for the Alekhine's Defense, a provocative opening. They attack our pawn and want us to expand in the center. Black hopes that we overextend and our center will be the subject to a counterattack. }
2. e5
{ We don't mind being provoked. Gaining space with tempo is something we are happy to do. }
2... Nd5
{ The only good move and almost exclusively played at this point.   Very understandable, as  2...Ne4?  3.d3  Nc5  4.d4  Ne6  7.f4  looks horrible, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/4P3/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Ng8  can be answered with normal development. A continuation like  3.d4  d6  4.Nf3  will do, for example. }
3. d4 d6
{ Black starts their counterattack against our center.   Black has no good alternative to this move, but I recently became aware of the following line:  3...b5?  4.Bxb5  c5  , called the O'Sullivan gambit. Black's trap is  5.dxc5??  Qa5+  , when it's time for 'Oh no, my bishop!'. Yes, you guessed it: I saw this trap in an Eric Rosen video!  So don't fall into this trap, but play a different fifth move, for example, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/8/1BpnP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq c6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Be2  @@StartBracket@@there are many more that are just as good@@EndBracket@@  and keep the extra pawn. }
4. c4
{ Here  4.Nf3  is a different main line, but I am sticking with my recommendation from the first edition. }
4... Nb6
{ After 4...Nb6 White has the choice between my recommendation, 5.exd6, and the sharp Four Pawns Attack 5.f4, which is nowadays considered a critical try against the Alekhine. I had already covered 5.exd6 in the first edition and was seriously considering if switching to the Four Pawns is an option.  I decided against it, ultimately. The practical issue in the Four Pawns is that Black has many dubious systems, but you need to know what to do against them. Lots of lines are very sharp, and general considerations are not enough. Objectively speaking, the Four Pawns looks like a great line, but it is tough to simplify for the context of this course.  What's more, my recommendation 5.exd6 looks in excellent shape, too. White has pressure in all lines without taking any risks. }
5. exd6
{ The Exchange Variation of the Alekhine is our repertoire choice. It still puts considerable pressure on Black without being overly theoretical. Now Black has a fundamental choice between recapturing with either c- or e-pawn. The consensus is that taking with the e-pawn is solid for Black but relatively passive. The other option is sharper but was always considered a riskier choice.  Now, while I am sticking with the choice of 5.exd6, I am changing my recommendation against both recaptures. The reason is pretty compelling: there is a much simpler approach/setup that works well in both cases and is far less prone to possible move order mishaps. The setup I am suggesting consists of Nf3, Be2, O-O and Nc3, a very natural formation.  In the 5...cxd6 line, you need to play a quick h3, while after 5...exd6, this move is not strictly necessary but still useful and should be included. Does the order of the moves matter? You are not in danger if you play a somewhat imprecise order, but my conclusion is that the following order works well after BOTH recaptures:  Play Nf3 @@StartBracket@@we are not worried about ...Bg4 early on@@EndBracket@@,Play h3 @@StartBracket@@we need this move exactly now in the 5...cxd6 line, more on that later@@EndBracket@@,Play Be2,Play Nc3,Play O-O.  You can switch Be2 and Nc3; it won't make a difference. Let's examine some details now. }
5... exd6
{ The solid, conservative move. The symmetrical structure should be slightly better for White, as we have more space and active pieces. A way to view this position type is to call it a Petroff/Russian Defence structure with the black knight slightly offside, on b6. }
6. Nf3
{ The start of our setup involving Nf3, h3, Be2, Nc3 and O-O. I suggest playing the moves in exactly this order, as it works well here AND in the 5...cxd6 variation.  However, I want to mention that after the symmetrical recapture, the move order plays less of a role. Sticking to one order in both cases helps with memorization, though.   After  6.Nf3  , Black's main choice is between the main move  6...Be7  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/1n1p4/8/2PP4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , which tries to exploit our early knight move with a pin. It turns out that we are more than happy to see 6...Bg4, because White seems to be much better. Let's examine. }
6... Bg4
{ Black goes for the pin, which looks tempting. The move enjoys popularity, but it looks like we are much better with aggressive play. Our concept is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/1n1P4/8/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd6  6.Nf3  Bg4  , when we immediately attack the bishop with  7.h3  , too. }
7. h3 Bh5
{ Black maintains the pin, an understandable decision.   A position like after  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Nc6  9.Be3  Be7  10.Nc3  O-O  11.h4  @@StartBracket@@stopping ...Bg5@@EndBracket@@ plays itself for White. We have the long-term asset of the bishop pair and can start an attack on the kingside after O-O-O. We usually castle kingside in the Alekhine, but we can be more ambitious against the premature ...Bg4. }
8. Nc3
{ There is nothing wrong about playing our standard setup with 8.Be2, O-O, etc., here. It's just that we have an even stronger option. By playing Nc3 and Be3 first, we preserve the option of playing g4! at the right moment. Let's have a look at how this works. }
8... Be7 9. Be3 O-O
{ The alternative  9...Nc6  10.g4!  Bg6  11.h4  h5  12.g5  may lead to the same position. Black is in terrible shape here. }
10. g4 { Here we go! } 10... Bg6 11. h4
{ What now? Our simple threat is h4-h5, winning the bishop! } 11... f5
{ Black does not have a satisfactory reply - all moves lead to an awful position. I chose 11...f5 as the main move, as it was played by the strongest player who had the unfortunate task of trying to find a defense.   The alternatives are not better:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/ppp1bppp/1n1p2b1/8/2PP2PP/2N1BN2/PP3P2/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...h5  12.Ng5  quickly opens files on the kingside.  B. @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/ppp1bppp/1n1p2b1/8/2PP2PP/2N1BN2/PP3P2/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...h6  12.h5  Bh7  13.g5  hxg5  14.h6  also quickly tears down Black's king shelter. }
12. h5 Be8 13. gxf5 { Black's kingside is falling apart. } 13... Rxf5 14. h6
{ Playing 14.h6 is better than  14.Bd3  Rxh5  , which is still promising, but unnecessary.   White has a decisive attack, for example, after @@StartFEN@@rn1qb1k1/ppp1b1pp/1n1p3P/5r2/2PP4/2N1BN2/PP3P2/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...g6  15.Bd3  Rf8  16.c5  , when checks on the a2-g8 diagonal are looming. }
