8... Nc6
{ I will use this move order to illustrate the ...Nc6-based setups. We will usually reach the position after  8...Nc6  9.Nc3  Bf6  10.O-O  Bf5  11.Bf4  , but Black may play these moves in different orders, for example, starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/1n1p4/8/2PP4/5N1P/PP2BPP1/RNBQK2R b KQ - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bf5  and the other moves later. }
9. Nc3 Bf5 { Or  9...Bf6  10.O-O  Bf5  , leading to the same position. } 10.
O-O Bf6
{ Now we have reached an instructive moment. A key idea for Black is the following:  11.Be3?!  d5!  12.c5  Nc4  , when our bishop and b2-pawn are attacked. We want to play in a way that makes Black's idea impossible or at least less attractive. }
11. Bf4
{ I like this move a lot. Black can't play  11...d5  now, as  12.c5  is powerful. After  12...Nc4  White has more than one strong reply. The immediate  13.Bxc7  is possible, winning a clean pawn after  13...Nxb2  14.Qb3  Qxc7  15.Nxd5  Qd8  16.Nxf6+  Qxf6  17.Qxb2  , but @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n2b2/2Pp1b2/2nP1B2/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.b3  or the less intuitive comp suggestion @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n2b2/2Pp1b2/2nP1B2/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Re1  is even stronger.  The key point is that we don't want to allow ...Nc4 to happen with a tempo on Be3. Playing the bishop to the more active f4-square is better, avoiding this scenario. }
11... Re8
{ Black's usual choice, seeing that 12...d5 is dubious. The position we have now on the board can also be reached by 8...Bf5, 8...Re8 etc. - for both sides, it is more of a 'setup' than move sequences. }
12. Qd2
{ We connect our rooks, a logical next step. A problem for Black is that they soon run out of little improvement moves. Black is sitting on their three ranks and has no active plan.   12...d5?  fails to  13.c5  Nc4  14.Bxc4  dxc4  15.Nb5  Rc8  16.d5  , crashing through in the center.   Black has to sit and wait. We should further improve our position and then see how to continue. Here's a sample line to illustrate:  12...h6  13.Rfe1  Qd7  14.Rad1  a6  15.b3  We have lots of time to get everything nicely organized. Have you wondered why our rook went to d1? That is not only a useful precaution, leaving the diagonal, but it can have a direct idea.  After  15...Bh7  , a further waiting move, we have the cunning idea  16.Qc1!  , when all of a sudden the move c4-c5! is a threat.  We should treat these positions with White's space advantage with patience. We want to expand and push the opponent back step by step. Often, they don't have the patience to sit tight and lash out - and we are well set to punish unwarranted activity. }
