4. c4
{ Here  4.Nf3  is a different main line, but I am sticking with my recommendation from the first edition. }
4... Nb6
{ After 4...Nb6 White has the choice between my recommendation, 5.exd6, and the sharp Four Pawns Attack 5.f4, which is nowadays considered a critical try against the Alekhine. I had already covered 5.exd6 in the first edition and was seriously considering if switching to the Four Pawns is an option.  I decided against it, ultimately. The practical issue in the Four Pawns is that Black has many dubious systems, but you need to know what to do against them. Lots of lines are very sharp, and general considerations are not enough. Objectively speaking, the Four Pawns looks like a great line, but it is tough to simplify for the context of this course.  What's more, my recommendation 5.exd6 looks in excellent shape, too. White has pressure in all lines without taking any risks. }
5. exd6
{ The Exchange Variation of the Alekhine is our repertoire choice. It still puts considerable pressure on Black without being overly theoretical. Now Black has a fundamental choice between recapturing with either c- or e-pawn. The consensus is that taking with the e-pawn is solid for Black but relatively passive. The other option is sharper but was always considered a riskier choice.  Now, while I am sticking with the choice of 5.exd6, I am changing my recommendation against both recaptures. The reason is pretty compelling: there is a much simpler approach/setup that works well in both cases and is far less prone to possible move order mishaps. The setup I am suggesting consists of Nf3, Be2, O-O and Nc3, a very natural formation.  In the 5...cxd6 line, you need to play a quick h3, while after 5...exd6, this move is not strictly necessary but still useful and should be included. Does the order of the moves matter? You are not in danger if you play a somewhat imprecise order, but my conclusion is that the following order works well after BOTH recaptures:  Play Nf3 @@StartBracket@@we are not worried about ...Bg4 early on@@EndBracket@@,Play h3 @@StartBracket@@we need this move exactly now in the 5...cxd6 line, more on that later@@EndBracket@@,Play Be2,Play Nc3,Play O-O.  You can switch Be2 and Nc3; it won't make a difference. Let's examine some details now. }
5... cxd6
{ Black goes for the non-symmetrical, more enterprising capture. Black now enjoys two center pawns; their dream scenario is mobilising the e- and f-pawn in the long run. This is usually prepared with the kingside fianchetto, followed by ...Nc6 and ...e5. As mentioned: that is Black's dream. With precise play, this won't materialise in an acceptable form for Black, if at all. }
6. Nf3
{ This is a change from my first edition choice, the Voronezh Variation @@StartBracket@@based on Nc3, Be3, Rc1@@EndBracket@@.   Now I found that the simpler plan started with  6.Nf3  is just as good. It has the bonus of being essentially the same approach as against 5...exd6, which is a welcome simplification, too.   After  6.Nf3  , Black's most popular reply is  6...g6  , which fits well with their intention to play a later ...e5 pawn push.  We don't have to worry about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/1n1p4/8/2PP4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , but I will check the move. }
6... Bg4
{ The conceptual problem of this move will become clearer after our reply, the simple  7.h3  . Let's consider it again after this move is on the board. }
7. h3
{ 'What's are you doing on g4, buddy?'   The capture gives us a nice advantage based on the bishop pair and space. OK, but what about the retreat? We'll check both options now. }
7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3
{ Thanks a lot for the bishop pair. On top of everything, we also attack the b7-pawn. }
8... Nc6
{ This looks relatively best. Black develops with an attack on the d-pawn.   The move  8...d5  is great for White after  9.c5  when the depressing  9...Nc8  is forced. }
9. d5 Ne5
{ Black has two knights in play, but it's a short-lived activity. Where should we move our queen now? }
10. Qb3
{ This move looks easier to play than  10.Qd1  , which is strong, too. } 10...
Rc8
{ Black attacks our c-pawn again, trying to use the better development.   After  10...g6  , we'd continue  11.Be2  Bg7  12.O-O  O-O  and now  13.Na3  leads to a type of position that we'll also reach via 10...Rc8 - hang on. }
11. Na3
{ I suggest this move for practical purposes.   Stockfish correctly claims that  11.a4!?  or @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/pp2pppp/1n1p4/3Pn3/2P5/1Q5P/PP3PP1/RNB1KB1R w KQk - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Be2!?  are possible, even sacrificing the c4-pawn. But there is no need for fancy play.  If we keep the c-pawn, our strategic advantages will be significant. We have much more space, the bishop pair, and Black's knights are not stable in the long run.  We'll continue with Be2, O-O and Be3 next, completing development and increasing the pressure on Black's queenside. }
