6. Nf3
{ This is a change from my first edition choice, the Voronezh Variation @@StartBracket@@based on Nc3, Be3, Rc1@@EndBracket@@.   Now I found that the simpler plan started with  6.Nf3  is just as good. It has the bonus of being essentially the same approach as against 5...exd6, which is a welcome simplification, too.   After  6.Nf3  , Black's most popular reply is  6...g6  , which fits well with their intention to play a later ...e5 pawn push.  We don't have to worry about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/1n1p4/8/2PP4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  , but I will check the move. }
6... g6 7. h3
{ A crucial move order finesse!   We want to prepare kingside castling with  7.Be2  , but now  7...Bg4  comes at a better moment for Black than on the previous move.  It looks more powerful to stop ...Bg4 and ask Black about a good square for the c8-bishop. }
7... Bg7 { Black continues as planned: complete the fianchetto and castle. } 8.
Be2 { You may also play  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Be2  , leading to the same position. }
8... O-O
{ Now, Black is closer to achieving the ...e5 break after having castled. We need to show some precision with the move order now. }
9. Nc3
{ This move is a bit more precise than  9.O-O  , because after  9...e5  , we would like to play  10.Bg5  f6  11.Be3  , which can be met with  11...e4  now!   This is the reason why 9.Nc3 is more precise: we cover e4, so the pawn advance is stopped.   After  9.Nc3  , we'll examine the mentioned  9...e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/8/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  , delaying a possible central strike. }
9... e5 { The move that Black wants to play, but it does not work out well. }
10. Bg5
{ A very annoying move for Black. The queen has no good squares to go to, and trading bishops with  10...Bf6  would weaken the dark squares. That only leaves  10...f6  . }
10... f6 11. Be3
{ We have provoked the undesirable move of the f-pawn and happily redeploy the bishop. Now I don't see a satisfactory way for Black to play.  Our main idea is the sequence dxe5, ...dxe5, and then c5! which pushes Black's knight back and opens the squares c4 and d5 for us. Ideas like Nc3-b5-d6 are looming, as well. }
11... Nc6
{ Black plays this move most of the time. We can briefly check two alternatives:  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp4bp/1n1p1pp1/4p3/2PP4/2N1BN1P/PP2BPP1/R2QK2R b KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...f5?  does not work at all due to  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.c5  N6d7  15.Bc4+  , when Ng5 and Nb5 ideas are deadly.   B. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp4bp/1n1p1pp1/4p3/2PP4/2N1BN1P/PP2BPP1/R2QK2R b KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Be6  is a better try, but we are much better in various ways, too.  12.Qb3  , intending a4-a5, looks fine, but you can make an argument for @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp4bp/1n1pbpp1/4p3/2PP4/2N1BN1P/PP2BPP1/R2QK2R w KQ - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.d5  Bf7  13.h4  , as well. Our central control gives us plenty of options on the flank. }
12. dxe5 dxe5
{ The other recapture,  12...fxe5  , would leave the d-pawn and all central squares eternally weak. Well, maybe not eternally, as the d-pawn will probably not live to see the end of the game. }
13. c5 { Our key idea is clearing the way for our pieces. } 13... Nd7 14. O-O
{ We can stop here, concluding that 9...e5?! is very dubious, at best.   Black is in severe trouble here, as lines like @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n2bp/2n2pp1/2P1p3/8/2N1BN1P/PP2BPP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...f5  15.Ng5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n2bp/2n2pp1/2P1p3/8/2N1BN1P/PP2BPP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Kh8  15.Qa4  f5  16.Rad1  suggest. }
