{ Now, Black is closer to achieving the ...e5 break after having castled. We need to show some precision with the move order now. }
9. Nc3
{ This move is a bit more precise than  9.O-O  , because after  9...e5  , we would like to play  10.Bg5  f6  11.Be3  , which can be met with  11...e4  now!   This is the reason why 9.Nc3 is more precise: we cover e4, so the pawn advance is stopped.   After  9.Nc3  , we'll examine the mentioned  9...e5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/8/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  , delaying a possible central strike. }
9... Nc6
{ Black does not commit the e-pawn yet and focuses on development.   The move  9...Bf5  follows a similar idea, and after  10.O-O  Nc6  might easily lead to the same line we will examine now. }
10. O-O
{ Completing our setup. Now Black's best move is 10...Bf5, it seems. The alternatives don't convince me at all:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/1nnp2p1/8/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 6 10@@EndFEN@@  10...e5?  is met with the typical  10...e5  11.Bg5  f6  12.Be3  , when Black has tons of weaknesses. After  12...f5  13.dxe5  dxe5  the move  14.Qb3  is nice, threatening c4-c5+ and clearing d1 for a rook. Black can't play this ambitiously and create so many weaknesses.   B. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/1nnp2p1/8/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 6 10@@EndFEN@@  10...d5?  is met by  11.c5  Nc4  12.b3  , when the knight only has the sad square a5 available. White is much better here, of course. }
10... Bf5
{ A healthy development move, but we still have excellent chances after it.  White has tried many moves with some success, but I want to suggest the top engine recommendation, which is strong and extremely tough for Black to play against. }
11. d5 Na5
{ That is the critical move.   After  11...Ne5  12.Nxe5  Bxe5  13.Bd2  Rc8  14.b3  we stabilize the pawn chain and have a large strategic advantage. Next, we aim to exchange dark-squared bishops with Be3/Qd2 and then Bd4. Then we can double rooks on the e-file to pile up on Black's backward e7-pawn.  It is comparable to positions from the Maroczy Bind when White plays Nd5, and the knight gets captured. White takes with the e-pawn, and the same structure is reached. In the chapter on the Moscow Variation of the Sicilian, we frequently reach the Maroczy Bind and discuss these themes more.  Now, after 11...Na5, the issue is simple: Black attacks the c-pawn twice, and we have no way to save it. The big point is that we can sacrifice it for excellent play. }
12. Nd4
{ We force Black to take the pawn now. Otherwise, we'd play b3 and secure the chain. After  12...Bd7  13.b3  , for example, the a5-knight is stranded, and Black is in awful shape. They have to grab the c-pawn. }
12... Naxc4
{ Taking with the offside knight is much more logical than  12...Nbxc4  . In this case, Black might end up with these pieces trapped at the edge of the board:   A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/3p2p1/n2P1b2/2nN4/2N4P/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  13.b3  Nb6  14.Nxf5  Bxc3  15.Nh6+  Kh8  16.Bd2  Bxd2  17.Qxd2  shows how the knight might be trapped!  B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/3p2p1/n2P1b2/2nN4/2N4P/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  13.b3  Nb6  14.Nxf5  gxf5  15.Qd3  e6  16.Bd2  , we have a great position, based on Black's terrible structure and badly placed pieces. }
13. a4 { The threat is a4-a5 now, winning one of the unlucky knights. } 13...
a5
{ Probably best, as the alternatives look even worse:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/3P1b2/P1nN4/2N4P/1P2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - a3 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rc8  15.a5  Nd7  16.a6  opens up the square c6 for our knight.   B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/3P1b2/P1nN4/2N4P/1P2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - a3 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Na5  14.Nxf5  gxf5  15.Bd3  e6  16.Re1  gives White great play, too. We have excellent attacking chances on the kingside, with Qh5 ideas on the agenda. }
14. Nxf5
{ We take the bishop and worsen Black's pawn structure. Our compensation for the pawn lies in Black's weak light squares, which will often be the color complex we will play on. }
14... gxf5
{ Now White has a choice of strong moves. I'll suggest the one I think is easier to handle. }
15. Bd3
{ Stockfish claims that the more sophisticated  15.Re1  is even better, but I am happy with this more straightforward idea. We attack the f-pawn and force Black to make a decision:  A. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1p2ppbp/1n1p4/p2P1p2/P1n5/2NB3P/1P3PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Qd7  16.Qh5  or @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p1qppbp/1n1p4/p2P1p2/P1n5/2NB3P/1P3PP1/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Ne2  give us a strong attack on the kingside.  B. @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1p2ppbp/1n1p4/p2P1p2/P1n5/2NB3P/1P3PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...e6  16.Bxc4  wins back the pawn with a comfortable advantage after  16...Nxc4  17.Qe2  Ne5  18.dxe6  fxe6  19.f4  Nc6  20.Qxe6+  , when the light squares remain weak.  The conclusion is: after 5...cxd6, the game is non-symmetrical and dynamic. I don't see a way for Black to get close to equality against our setup. Active ideas based on ...e5 fail, and the main line leads to a position with Black being on the defensive, as we have just examined. }
