[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "G3) 1.e4 Sidelines – 1...b6 & 1...Nc6"]
[Black "1.e4 Sidelines – 1...b6 & 1...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ Welcome to the final chapter of this course. The final chapter is usually about the 'Odds & Ends', the rare lines your opponent may play once in a blue moon. What do we have to check?  A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  , the Owen's Defense. It gives White too much leeway in the center but has some tricky lines worth knowing.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nc6  , the Nimzowitsch Defense. This opening is slightly underestimated in my mind. It's nothing to worry about, but it's not a terrible choice for Black. Magnus Carlsen has used it as a surprise weapon, for example.  I don't think it is worth studying any concrete lines against even rarer moves. If Black plays something else, they'll violate one or more opening principles and you should answer keeping two key points in mind:Play according to opening principles: occupy the center, develop pieces, get castled.Don't feel too provoked by wacky opening moves. Keep cool and stick to common-sense moves that keep your position harmonious.  If it looks very odd, it's likely awful. Enjoy the game, but keep the first two points in mind! }
