[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "G3) 1.e4 Sidelines – 1...b6 & 1...Nc6"]
[Black "1...b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ This is called Owen's Defence. The queenside fianchetto 1...b6 is quite playable against 1.c4 and 1.Nf3 but dubious against 1.d4 and 1.e4. Black does not get enough active play against the strong center that White will build. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ 3.Nc3  wouldn't be terrible, but flexibility with the c-pawn is an important asset for White. In some cases, c2-c3 lends important protection to the center, similar to our setups in other openings @@StartBracket@@French, Ruy Lopez@@EndBracket@@.  Now we will check two options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppppp/1p6/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5??  is a known mistake met with a fun refutation.  B. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppppp/1p6/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  is Black's main line, in most cases playing for ...d5 soon. Black also has the idea to play for a Hippo formation with ...g6, which we will examine via the move order  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppppp/1p6/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.Nf3  g6  , but they certainly could start with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppppp/1p6/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  right away when  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.c4  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppp1p/1p4p1/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Bg7  5.Nf3  is likely to transpose. }
3... f5
{ This loses, but you sometimes meet it in blitz games. It's rare, but the refutation is fun to study. }
4. exf5
{ It turns out that we can call Black's bluff and allow the capture on g2. }
4... Bxg2 5. Qh5+ g6 6. fxg6 Bg7
{ Black's only move, because  6...Nf6?  7.gxh7+!  Nxh5  8.Bg6#  leads to a cute mate. }
7. gxh7+ Kf8
{ Black is hoping for  8.hxg8=Q+  Kxg8  9.Qg4  Bxh1  , which might be better for White, but is very murky.  Instead, we have moves that win convincingly. }
8. Nf3 { I think this is the simplest to learn, based on the following line. }
8... Nf6
{ Black's best try.   After  8...Bxh1  9.Ne5  Qe8  10.hxg8Q+  Rxg8  11.Qf5+  Bf6  12.Bh6+  Rg7  13.Bxg7+  Kxg7  14.Qh7+  Kf8  15.Ng6+  , we win the house. }
9. Qg6
{ We attack the g2-bishop and force a decision. Black can take the rook or knight now - neither capture saves the day. }
9... Bxf3
{ The other capture is even worse:  9...Bxh1  10.Bh6  Rxh7  11.Ng5  is immediately resignable. }
10. Rg1 Rxh7 11. Qg3
{ This is the key move that decides the game. We attack Black's rook, the sole defender of the g7-bishop. It's all falling apart now. }
11... Be4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. Qf3+
{ And it's over. After @@StartFEN@@rn1q1k2/p1ppp1br/1p6/8/3Pn3/5Q2/PPP2P1P/RNB1K1R1 b Q - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nf6  , we have  14.Qxa8  , while @@StartFEN@@rn1q1k2/p1ppp1br/1p6/8/3Pn3/5Q2/PPP2P1P/RNB1K1R1 b Q - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Kg8  14.Qxe4  gives us a winning attack with an extra pawn to boot. }
