[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "G3) 1.e4 Sidelines – 1...b6 & 1...Nc6"]
[Black "1...b6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ This is called Owen's Defence. The queenside fianchetto 1...b6 is quite playable against 1.c4 and 1.Nf3 but dubious against 1.d4 and 1.e4. Black does not get enough active play against the strong center that White will build. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ 3.Nc3  wouldn't be terrible, but flexibility with the c-pawn is an important asset for White. In some cases, c2-c3 lends important protection to the center, similar to our setups in other openings @@StartBracket@@French, Ruy Lopez@@EndBracket@@.  Now we will check two options for Black:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppppp/1p6/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5??  is a known mistake met with a fun refutation.  B. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppppp/1p6/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  is Black's main line, in most cases playing for ...d5 soon. Black also has the idea to play for a Hippo formation with ...g6, which we will examine via the move order  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppppp/1p6/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.Nf3  g6  , but they certainly could start with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppppp/1p6/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  right away when  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.c4  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpppp1p/1p4p1/8/3PP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Bg7  5.Nf3  is likely to transpose. }
3... e6 4. Nf3
{ After our natural move, Black has a choice between several unconvincing options:  A. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpp1ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d5  is strongly answered by  5.exd5  , which opens the game favourably.  B. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpp1ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  attacks our d-pawn, but we even have two good replies.  C. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpp1ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...g6  aims for a Hippo formation, but  5.O-O  Bg7  6.c4!  is a powerful response. }
4... d5
{ Black may play this here or after some preparatory moves. It is important to understand that playing e4-e5 will always be somewhat better for White as this is an excellent version of the French with a strange bishop on b7.  In some cases, however, we have even better options than advancing the e-pawn, exploiting Black's bad development. }
5. exd5
{ White is also better after  5.e5  , but taking on d5 is an attempt to get Black into immediate complications while they are underdeveloped. }
5... Qxd5
{ Black has some alternatives, but they're nothing special:   A.  5...exd5?!  looks terrible, blocking in the bishop on b7.   B.  5...Bxd5  will likely lead to a transposition after  6.O-O  Nf6  7.c4  Bb7  when we reach the same position as after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbp2ppp/1p2p3/3P4/3P4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qxd5  6.c4  Qd8  7.O-O  Nf6  , which we will examine now. }
6. c4
{ This move looks best, but nothing is wrong about  6.O-O  or  6.Nc3  , either. }
6... Qd8
{ Going back home is Black's best move, as  6...Qh5?!  7.Be2  leaves the queen in an insecure spot. Black is also vulnerable to Nc3-b5 attacks, as the queen can't help defending the queenside. }
7. O-O { Or  7.Nc3  first, followed by O-O, will lead to the same position. }
7... Nf6 8. Nc3 Bd6
{ This looks more interesting than  8...Be7  , when we'll be better with simple centralization, for example, using a setup based on Re1, Qe2 and Rad1, as indicated in the first edition of KIS 1.e4. }
9. Bg5
{ After Black has already played ...Bd6, this pin gets more attractive. Breaking it with ...Be7 would require the bishop to move again. }
9... O-O
{ After  9...Nbd7  the knight jump  10.Nb5  looks good to me. We will get the bishop pair as  10...Be7?  11.Bf4  is quite embarrassing for Black. }
10. Ne5
{ I like this knight jump, increasing the pressure. Now Black needs to tread carefully.   One attractive line runs @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pbp2ppp/1p1bpn2/4N1B1/2PP4/2NB4/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 8 10@@EndFEN@@  10...c5?  11.f4!  cxd4  12.Ne4  , which gives us a string attack that can quickly turn decisive.  12...Be7  13.Nxf6+  Bxf6  14.Qh5  g6  15.Qh4  is already crushing.  The engines recommend  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pbp2ppp/1p1bpn2/4N1B1/2PP4/2NB4/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 8 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Be7  , but the plan  11.Bc2  , intending Qd3, looks attractive for White.  We can be happy about this opening result, for sure. }
