[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "G3) 1.e4 Sidelines – 1...b6 & 1...Nc6"]
[Black "1...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzowitsch Defense. It is not that bad if used as a transpositional tool to reach 1.e4 e5 positions - the independent lines are not that reliable for Black or just downright bad. }
2. Nf3
{ White has two main options: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , which is my suggestion.  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  d5  3.e5  Bf5  White enjoys some advantage, but it's a slightly odd position and not so easy to play. Black might know it a lot better than we do, so going for a different solution makes sense.  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  is my choice, when Black's objectively best move is  2...e5  , transposing to the Open Games.  In the current chapter, we need to check Black's other options:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...f5?  is the Colorado Gambit. It is, unsurprisingly, bad for Black, but it is good to know why.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5?  is a bad version of a Scandi. The early ...Nc6 does not harmonize with the queen sortie, as we will see.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  is Black's best move if they want to avoid the transposition to the Open Games @@StartBracket@@1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@. This is how the World Champion played in some of his games. }
2... d5 { Scandi style play - it is very questionable though. } 3. exd5 Qxd5 4.
Nc3 Qa5
{ Our early knight move to f3 allowed  4...Qh5  , a move that is impossible in the standard Scandinavian. To my surprise, I found thousands of online blitz games with it. It has a huge drawback... after  5.Nb5!  Black has no good way to cover c7. They have to play the embarrassing  5...Kd8  , giving us some hope for a quick win. }
5. Bb5
{ This is important to remember. The pin is annoying, and the black queen is deprived of some squares on the 5th rank. }
5... Bd7
{ This looks like the relatively best defence, but Black is in serious trouble in any case. }
6. d4
{ We want to continue with ideas like Bd2&a4, targeting Black's unlucky queen. }
6... a6
{ After  6...O-O-O  7.Bd2  Black's queen is running short of squares.  The move 6...a6 prompts a bishop move so that the queen gains more squares on the fifth rank. }
7. Bxc6
{ The other bishop moves are strong too, but this is a simpler way to an advantage. Against rare lines, simple recipes are very sensible. If you learn some complex refutation, you will likely forget it when that rare line pops up after a long time. }
7... Bxc6 8. O-O Qh5
{ After  8...O-O-O  9.Ne5  Be8  10.Qf3  White is much better, too. A fun idea is  10...Nf6  11.b4!  , using the fact that  11...Qxb4??  12.Rb1  is possible.  The move 8...Qh5 can be refuted, but only with one particular sequence of moves. }
9. d5
{ A strong move - if you know what happens after Black's most testing reply. }
9... O-O-O
{ This is not an easy position to play if you don't know or find the next move. White to play and win! }
10. Qd4
{ This is amazingly strong. We threaten Qa7!, which is crushing after  10...Bxd5  11.Nxd5  Qxd5  12.Qa7  , for example.  Black has no defence now, as after @@StartFEN@@2kr1bnr/1pp1pppp/p1b5/3P3q/3Q4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Kb8  11.Ne5  Be8  12.Be3  b6  13.a4  we rapidly get into 'Mate in X' territory. }
