[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "G3) 1.e4 Sidelines – 1...b6 & 1...Nc6"]
[Black "1...Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzowitsch Defense. It is not that bad if used as a transpositional tool to reach 1.e4 e5 positions - the independent lines are not that reliable for Black or just downright bad. }
2. Nf3
{ White has two main options: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , which is my suggestion.  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  d5  3.e5  Bf5  White enjoys some advantage, but it's a slightly odd position and not so easy to play. Black might know it a lot better than we do, so going for a different solution makes sense.  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  is my choice, when Black's objectively best move is  2...e5  , transposing to the Open Games.  In the current chapter, we need to check Black's other options:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...f5?  is the Colorado Gambit. It is, unsurprisingly, bad for Black, but it is good to know why.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5?  is a bad version of a Scandi. The early ...Nc6 does not harmonize with the queen sortie, as we will see.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  is Black's best move if they want to avoid the transposition to the Open Games @@StartBracket@@1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@. This is how the World Champion played in some of his games. }
2... f5
{ The Colorado Gambit. It's incorrect, but it definitely has some trick and trolling potential.  White has more than one way to obtain a large advantage, though. The main question is what is the most economical way to deal with it. You'll rarely face it, so a practical weapon is called for.  I suggested the best line by engine standards in the first edition, but it is quite long and complicated. For the second edition, I switch to a more practical approach, which still is much better for White. }
3. exf5 d5
{ Black wants to get the pawn back. Instead, we are not worried about that and focus on controlling the key central squares. }
4. Bb5
{ We develop, pin the knight and increase control of e5.   The alternative move order  4.d4  Bxf5  5.Bb5  is also possible, of course. }
4... Bxf5 5. d4
{ I think this move is a bit more practical than my previous suggestion of  5.Ne5  , which is stronger if you rely on engine evaluation only. I'll still mention the key lines because maybe you are a perfectionist and want to see them. After  5...Qd6  6.d4  Nf6  7.O-O  Nd7  8.Bf4  Ndxe5  9.Bxe5  Qg6  a critical position is reached. Now  10.Qf3  and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/ppp1p1pp/2n3q1/1B1pBb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c4  lead to a large advantage, but it's still quite murky. }
5... e6
{ Black usually plays this move to enable a development based on ...Bd6 and ...Nge7, which lends more cover to e5 and c6.   After  5...Nf6  we can simply develop with  6.O-O  , when  6...e6?!  7.Ne5  shows the problem: how does Black cover c6? We have many weaknesses to play against in the long run @@StartBracket@@e5-square, e6-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Ne5 Ne7
{ Black could also play  6...Qd6  , but it's much worse compared to @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp1p1pp/2n5/1B1p1b2/8/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Ne5  Qd6  , as the e6-pawn obstructs the queen on the sixth rank. We are much better with many replies, but I suggest  @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/ppp3pp/2nqp3/1B1pNb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nc3  , intending Bf4 next. The immediate  @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/ppp3pp/2nqp3/1B1pNb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bf4  Qb4+  is unnecessarily complicated. }
7. Nc3
{ A simple development move on the surface. It sets a cunning trap, though. What about 7...a6 now? }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ We keep the pin and hope for  8...b5?  , falling into the trap I mentioned. }
8... b5
{ This fails, but it is a very tempting move. Black can play something else, but I don't see how they untangle their position. We'll castle kingside and play Bg5 to pin the other knight, too. }
9. Nxb5 { This knight sacrifice is crushing. } 9... axb5 10. Bxb5
{ 'Pin And Win'... couldn't resist this one here! } 10... Qd6
{ Black covers the knight and threatens ...Qb4+ now. } 11. c3
{ Not the only win, but it's very telling that a slow move is enough. Black is completely busted now, as they can't move any minor piece. We have Bf4 or Bg5 ideas and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/2p1n1pp/2nqp3/1B1pNb2/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ra5  12.Qe2  Rxb5  13.Qxb5  does not help. }
