1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzowitsch Defense. It is not that bad if used as a transpositional tool to reach 1.e4 e5 positions - the independent lines are not that reliable for Black or just downright bad. }
2. Nf3
{ White has two main options: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , which is my suggestion.  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  d5  3.e5  Bf5  White enjoys some advantage, but it's a slightly odd position and not so easy to play. Black might know it a lot better than we do, so going for a different solution makes sense.  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  is my choice, when Black's objectively best move is  2...e5  , transposing to the Open Games.  In the current chapter, we need to check Black's other options:  A. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...f5?  is the Colorado Gambit. It is, unsurprisingly, bad for Black, but it is good to know why.  B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5?  is a bad version of a Scandi. The early ...Nc6 does not harmonize with the queen sortie, as we will see.   C. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/2n5/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  is Black's best move if they want to avoid the transposition to the Open Games @@StartBracket@@1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@. This is how the World Champion played in some of his games. }
2... d6
{ The best of the independent lines. We will get a small advantage, but Black's position is playable and not as well-explored by the opening theory. }
3. d4
{ Now  3...Nf6  looks best for Black.   They sometimes play  3...e5  , which we can answer effectively with  4.Bb5  , transposing to a Ruy Lopez Steinitz. }
3... Nf6
{ Very natural and the best move, attacking the e-pawn.   In the first edition of KIS 1.e4, I also analyzed  3...Bg4  in some detail. The objectively best answer is  4.d5  when  4...Ne5  can be met with the excellent  5.Nxe5!!  , a queen sacrifice that is essentially winning for White.  But this line has a problem: it will appear on the board once in a blue moon, and you need to be super precise to make the sacrifice work. It would need several trainables to get fully covered, and that's not an economical way to approach rare sidelines. Therefore I have decided to skip it in the second edition.   Still, I'd like to show the main path of it here:  3...Bg4  4.d5  Ne5  5.Nxe5  Bxd1  6.Bb5+  c6  7.dxc6  Qa5+  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp2pppp/2Pp4/1B2N3/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBbK2R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a6  8.c7+  is easy@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp2pppp/2Pp4/qB2N3/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBbK2R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nc3  O-O-O  @@StartBracket@@here @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp2pppp/2Pp4/qB2N3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BbK2R b KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a6  9.b4!!  is one of those points you need to know. Otherwise, you are a queen down!!@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2kr1bnr/pp2pppp/2Pp4/qB2N3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BbK2R w KQ - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc4  Qc7  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@2kr1bnr/pp2pppp/2Pp4/qB6/2N1P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BbK2R b KQ - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qb4  10.a3  is another long line that leads to a winning attack@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2kr1bnr/ppq1pppp/2Pp4/1B6/2N1P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BbK2R w KQ - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nd5  Qb8  11.c7  Qa8  and now  12.Bd2!  is the clearest finish. You see that these lines are great, but the practical problem is clear, I think.  If you want to learn more about this sacrifice, it's a good idea to explore it on your own, maybe with the help of a training partner or/and the computer.   So what to do after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp1pppp/2np4/8/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg4  , then? You can still play the queen sac line, but if you feel unconfident about it, just a normal move like  4.Nc3  will do. Black's likely reply is  4...Nf6  when we reach @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp1pppp/2np4/8/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  Bg4  , as analyzed in the next variation. }
4. Nc3
{ After  4.Nc3  Black mostly plays the moves  4...Bg4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp1pppp/2np1n2/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...g6  , which was Magnus Carlsen's choice in some games. Against both, I have recommended Bb5 in the first edition, and I still like this pragmatic solution.   If Black plays @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp1pppp/2np1n2/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e5  here, the reply  5.Bb5  again transposes to a nice Ruy Lopez line. }
4... g6
{ Black is aiming for a mix of the Nimzovich and Pirc Defence. Our Anti-Pirc Repertoire is based on the Austrian Attack with f2-f4, so we can't just play as we do against the Pirc. }
5. Bb5
{ I am suggesting the same approach as after 4...Bg4, playing for the weakened queenside. White has some good alternatives here, though. A more aggressive option is  5.Be3  ,  intending Qd2 and queenside castling.The whole 4...g6-line is not theoretically well-explored, so you have many options to choose from without worrying that your opponent might know tons more. Just play according to your taste. }
5... a6
{ Black can't play  5...Bd7  , due to  6.e5  , when Black's knight has no good square to go to. }
6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. O-O
{ And I prefer White here. Black's pawn structure is not great, and the bishop pair is not effective now. White would like to trade the g7 bishop here, so Be3 or Bf4/Qd2 is a natural follow-up. The move h3 is also useful for preparing these ideas and controlling the g4-square. }
